<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, My 10.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INTELLIGENCE (Washington) _ From the grainy airborne
reconnaissance photographs of downtown Belgrade that NATO military
planners use to identify bombing targets, the Chinese Embassy and a
headquarters for a Yugoslav arms agency nearby situated nearby look
very similar: same size, shape and height. But at street level,
there is no mistaking the embassy's marble structure with blue
mirrored glass, flying the distinctive Chinese flag, from the
Yugoslav military's white office building across the other side of
a major thoroughfare, Lenjinov Bulevar. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-ASSESS (Beijing) _ Through their extended campaign
to portray the United States and NATO as evil aggressors in
Yugoslavia, and now their endorsement of mass demonstrations,
China's leaders may have unleashed forces that will come back to
haunt them. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBIA (Podujevo, Serbia) _ Three months ago, Milos Savic
was frantic. He had been stopped at a checkpoint by the Kosovo
Liberation Army close to this northern Kosovo city and dragged out
of his car at gunpoint. The fear took him over, he said, and he
lost nearly 40 pounds. Today, Savic says he's feeling much better,
even as NATO airplanes bomb in the hills to the west. The KLA
checkpoints that began less then a mile from the city center are
gone, pushed back by the Serb offensive. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA-LEADER (Tirana, Albania) _ Hundreds of thousands of
uprooted ethnic Albanians are huddled in woods and fields inside
Kosovo under the protection of Kosovo Liberation Army fighters,
Hashim Thaci, prime minister of the rebel provisional government
said in a telephone interview Sunday from inside the embattled
province. `'The food supply is running very low, the medical care
is minimal and hygenic conditions are very bad,'' Thaci said. ``We
have the first signs of epidemics of various diseases among the
children.'' By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-FAMILY (New York) _ After six terrifying weeks spent
fleeing war at home in Kosovo, Sytkije Deva and her family had
finally arrived at Kennedy International Airport late Saturday
night. When it came time to leave, Mrs. Deva, 67, looking frail and
bewildered, asked her sister Lili Erbeli whether they were going to
a refugee camp next. Mrs. Erbeli took her eldest sister's hand and
broke the good news in rapid-fire Albanian. ``You're coming home
with me,'' she said. Then Mrs. Erbeli, 55, and her husband, Rex,
59, brought home to their 3-bedroom duplex 14 of their Kosovo kin _
undoubtedly among the world's luckiest exiles of war. By Somini
Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-U.S.-CHINA-SPYING (Washington) _ A 1997 case involving
a Taiwanese-American scientist working on a classified Pentagon
project demonstrates that the U.S. government knew that China
successfully engaged in espionage during President Clinton's second
term. By Jeff Gerth and James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION (Soweto) _ In a country with a jobless rate
that may be as high as 40 percent and a crime rate that includes
140 murders or attempted murders a day, unemployment and safety are
the issues that top the agenda for most South Africans. But with
only four weeks to go before this country's second post apartheid
elections, corruption is emerging as a key issue too. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-ISRAELI-EMBASSY (Bueno Aires) _ In a new twist in the
investigation of the 1992 bombing of the Israeli embassy that left
29 people dead, a tape recording of a police radio call has
suddenly emerged suggesting that officials purposely removed guards
from the facility three minutes before the blast. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-BASS-FISHING (Verplanck, N.Y.) _ The Hudson River, which for
years was a forgotten waterway between more popular fishing grounds
on the Atlantic Coast and the Great Lakes, has become one of the
hottest spots for striped-bass fishing in the country. By Andrew C.
Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-PRESCRIPTIONS _ Prescription drugs were not much of an
issue when Medicare was created in 1965, and thus not included as a
benefit. But 30 years later medicine has been transformed by
expensive new drugs to treat the ills of old age, leaving millions
of the elderly struggling to pay the bill, and creating a struggle
on Capitol Hill over coverage for outpatient drugs. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CIVIL-RIGHTS _ In a sign of the ways that both Congress
and the leading civil rights groups have changed, the big civil
rights battles now are not about affirmative action or school
choice, but about access to bankruptcy courts and bank loans. By
Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-VIOLENCE-CONFERENCE _ In a search for a meaningful public
response to yet another outbreak of schoolhouse violence, President
Clinton will convene a White House meeting on Monday to address the
causes of violence by teenagers. But behind the White House summit
is the president's fabled political realism and a desire not to
alienate two powerful groups with broad political influence and
very deep pockets: the NRA and Hollywood. By John M. Broder and
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-LOST-JOBS (LOS ANGELES) _ Seamstresses, steel workers
and electronics assemblers have all lost jobs as manufacturing
moved from the United States to countries where costs were lower.
Now complaints about similar job losses are coming from workers in
a quintessentially American industry: Hollywood's film and
television studios. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-TV-ANALYSIS (Undated) _ Has Bill Gates become the
Captain Ahab of the information age? Gates' white whale remains an
elusive digital set-top cable box that his company, Microsoft
Corp., is hoping will re-create the personal computer industry by
blending the PC, the Internet and the television set into a
leviathan living-room entertainment and information machine. By
John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-CEO (San Jose, Calif.) _ Meg Whitman, chief executive of
the Internet auction company E-Bay, is one of the new generation of
Internet executives who is bringing conventional corporate bona
fides and consumer product-style marketing to the Web. In the
process, executives like Ms. Whitman are changing the way Web
companies are run _ even as they are developing a new management
style suited to this emergent medium. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HDTV-SALES (Washington) _ In an effort to jump-start the
nation's sluggish transition to digital television, Mitsubishi
Electric Corp., a major maker of television sets, has agreed to
underwrite CBS' costs to broadcast most of the network's prime-time
schedule in high definition beginning next fall. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-MEDIA (Undated) _ In the last three years,
start-up technology companies have pushed forward with plans to
make electronic books as ubiquitous as mass market paperbacks. But
the culture of technology has collided with the slower-moving book
industry, which is engaged in a tense, early clash over how to
divide up the spoils of an infant business that is still difficult
to picture in scope and potential. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV:; Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Free PC, a hatchling from the Idealab
technology incubator in Pasadena, Calif., announced earlier this
year that it would give away PCs and network access to 10,000
households between April and June. To be considered, applicants
agreed to accept continuous on-screen advertising. By Denise
Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Shares in National
Semiconductor Corp. evidently got a lot more attractive last week,
after the company announced it was quitting the personal computer
microprocessor business. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   CHIAT-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Jay Chiat, who had been chairman and
chief executive at Chiat/Day, the agency known for campaigns for
advertisers like Apple Computer, Energizer and Nissan, is seeking a
shop to handle the account of Screaming Media, a New York company
in which he holds a minority stake and is temporarily acting as
chief executive. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTING-GOODS-INTERNET (Undated) _ Some of the nation's biggest
sporting goods retailers are banding together to back a single
company that will run Internet stores for all of them. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE-INTERNET (Undated) _ US West Corp. intends to announce
Monday that it will introduce a new phone developed by Alcatel of
France that includes a color screen, pop-out keyboard and one-touch
access to the World Wide Web. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Shares in National
Semiconductor Corp. evidently got a lot more attractive last week,
after the company announced it was quitting the personal computer
microprocessor business. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ Claritin is one of the most popular
prescription allergy treatments on the market, with $1.9 billion in
national sales for its maker, Schering-Plough, last year. Because
of its patent protection, Schering-Plough enjoys a monopoly on
crucial chemical compounds in Claritin. The weekly patents column.
By Teresa Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   TVHITS-PRODUCER-MEDIA (Undated) _ Brad Gray, the chairman of
Brillstein-Gray Entertainment, has a track record that includes the
television programs ``The Sopranos'' as well as ``Just Shoot Me''
and ``News Radio,'' both on NBC. His company also produces ``The
Steve Harvey Show,'' on Time Warner Inc.'s WB and ``Politically
Incorrect'' for ABC, and it was the production company that created
the groundbreaking series ``The Larry Sanders Show'' for HBO. By
Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ADVICE-POPSONG-MEDIA (Undated) _ Never before has such mileage
been milked from 675 words. The Chicago Tribune columnist Mary
Schmich's column on June 1, 1997, dispensing life advice in a mock
graduation speech, has gone on to become a mass E-mail message, a
novelty book, and, now, a hit pop song. By Sreenath Sreenivasan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-IMAGE-TV (Hollywood) _ The small-screen perspective on Los
Angeles, focusing on the banal, the superficial and the glitzy, has
been beamed out in dozens of television shows over the decades,
reflecting an image of Los Angeles that has acquired the undeniable
patina of truth for many viewers. But the city's image, like
television, is changing. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-ART-LAWSUIT (Paris) _ Embarrassed by persistent rumors that
it collaborated with the Nazi occupiers of wartime France, the
Wildenstein family, the powerful French-Jewish dynasty of
international art dealers, has brought a lawsuit seeking $1 million
in damages against an American writer who repeated some of these
allegations in a recent book. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   PROULOUX-ON-WRITING (Undated) _ A whole set of metaphoric
shovels is part of my tool collection, and for me the research that
underlies the writing is the best part of the scribbling game. The
American Letters series. By Annie Prouloux.
</P>
<P>
   ELEMENTALS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``How do you decide when to
stop looking at something?'' This is the riddle that haunts the
protagonist of ``Crocodile Tears,'' the fine opening story of A.S.
Byatt's kaleidoscopic new collection, ``Elementals.'' By Hilma
Wolitzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire criticizes the
Justice Department for its failures in investigating Chinese spying
against this country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The choice of Don Zimmer _ in his
crimped and cranky condition _ to be the temporary replacement for
Joe Torre as manager of the Yankees should raise a question that is
disturbingly decades-old: To what lengths will a professional
sports team go before it turns to a minority aspirant, if only to
fill in? By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-BERKOW-COLUMN (New York) _ Ricky Ledee, who was something of
a World Series hero and seemed ready to blossom, instead is off to
a terrible start. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-LEFTY-RELIEVERS (Undated) _ Tony Fossas is a left-handed
relief pitcher and, though he is 41 years old, rarely throws above
86 miles per hour and has been with seven major and minor league
teams in the last two years, he is a precious commodity in a
baseball world where lefty relievers are so scarce that even
recycled veterans are valuable. Why are lefties so precious? Mostly
because they are so difficult to find. By Jack Curry. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Miami) _ On the Knicks-Heat series. By
William Rhoden.
</P>
