<HEADER>
A0445 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHASE-COVERAGE-2Takes     05-10 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-COVERAGE-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S TV STOPS EVERYTHING TO COVER FREEWAY FUGITIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A horrific tornado hit Oklahoma, a deranged
motorist slammed into a day-care center, bombs fell on Belgrade,
but in Los Angeles the big story of the day, live on television,
was another freeway car chase.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, on this particular day, it was a slow-speed pursuit of
a lumbering, renegade motor home that news helicopters beamed to
millions of homes across Southern California for more than three
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a journalist, the chase wasn't a real significant story,''
said Jeff Wald, news director for KTLA-TV, the WB affiliate. ``But
our industry is viewer-driven, and every time there's a chase,
people tune in. It's all about what our viewers want.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Los Angeles, home of the televised car chase, a
cultural event that unfailingly draws crowds around TVs, as
everyone waits for a crash or _ even better _ a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings are the name of the game in the entertainment capital of
the world. And nothing gets viewer numbers quite like a freeway
chase.
</P>
<P>
   Police say freeway chases are on the rise, in great part because
these live broadcasts encourage people to run from officers to get
on television.
</P>
<P>
   Behavioral experts say this growing appetite for chases reflects
humanity's worst side, as viewers turn off sitcoms and soap operas
in the hopes of seeing a real-life drama unfold right before their
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these pursuits come on, people say, `Oh gosh, not another
one,' but then they will sit there and watch for two to three
hours,'' said Dr. Bruce Gross, a criminal behavior expert at the
University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a morbid curiosity to see how they end _ if they have
to kill the guy or someone gets hurt or a major situation arises.
That's just the way society is, and it can be a real problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the man in the motor home pointed a handgun at
police and died in a barrage of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   KTLA and other stations had already dropped live coverage when
the chase became a standoff, Wald said. But ground crews kept the
tapes rolling, capturing the bloodshed for the morning news.
</P>
<P>
   It was the ultimate payoff for those who had watched.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, about 1.2 million viewers tuned to KTLA alone for the
drama, as compared to the average 700,000 that normally watch
during that period, Wald said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say TV performs a public disservice by airing the
chases. The ``glorification'' of police pursuits could even
encourage some to run, Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is contempt for police or a person is trying to make
some kind of statement by tying up the roadways and the airwaves,
then televised pursuits could encourage that activity,'' Gross
said.
</P>
<P>
   TV stations only once _ and only briefly _ reconsidered their
aggressive drive to broadcast all chases to the very end.
</P>
<P>
   A distraught Long Beach, Calif., man shot himself in the head
April 30, 1998, as a million horrified television viewers
witnessed, including children who tuned in for afternoon cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Jones, 40, had stopped his pickup truck on an overpass
between the Harbor and Century freeways, then he unfurled a banner
and set himself, his dog and the truck on fire. He bolted out of
the burning truck and removed his flaming trousers.
</P>
<P>
   Then he shot himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   The shock and outrage by the on-air death provoked criticism
from many viewers and prompted TV stations to use a time delay for
broadcasting chases so they wouldn't get caught airing another
death.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted only a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewers are driven by the thought that something bad will
happen _ that there will be a bloody payoff for watching _ and the
stations take advantage of that for ratings,'' said Cynthia
Rawitch, chairwoman of the journalism department at California
State University, Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV stations do not do a public service broadcasting these
chases, like they claim,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Behavior specialist David W. Stewart at USC blames the media for
creating an appetite for pursuits, but he said the attraction will
decline over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people in Los Angeles are awfully bored, and there's a
certain level of excitement created by pursuits because we want to
see how they end,'' Stewart said. ``But the recent excitement has
been created by the media. Car chases have been around as long as
there have been cars.''
</P>
<P>
   At a local Fry's Electronics store, when a chase flashes on the
wall of televisions for sale, the result is predictable: a crowd
quickly gathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a natural reaction. People will stop and watch,''
said salesman Rene Suguitan.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bustos, 33, said he watches chases for excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happening live and you want to see what happens,'' said
Bustos. ``It shows you how crazy some people can be, and how the
cops deal with it. It's kind of cool.''
</P>
<P>
   (second take to follow)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0447 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHASE-COVERAGE-2nd-ta     05-10 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-COVERAGE-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: kind of cool.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remembered chase of all time, ironically, is
known for its slow speed _ O.J. Simpson's snail-paced return to his
Brentwood home in June 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Simpson chase cemented televised police chases
as the new pop drama and became as much a part of Los Angeles
culture as In-N-Out Burgers.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a new phenomenon, however.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, the first ``telecopter'' hit the skies to take
weather shots, and soon after they were capturing crime scenes and
chases.
</P>
<P>
   The Rodney King beating and the Los Angeles riots further fed
broadcasters' obsession with live shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual for a reporter to be standing in an empty
parking lot at 11 p.m. doing a live report where something happened
15 hours earlier,'' said Rick Marks, a CSUN journalism professor
who spent 23 years as a news producer with NBC and its Los Angeles
affiliate, KNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all consultant-driven. There's an idea that ratings will
jump if you can trick viewers into thinking that something is
happening live.''
</P>
<P>
   Wald defends the coverage of pursuits as a public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ultimate hope as a journalist is to show our viewers that
the bad guys don't get away, so there's no rational sense to run,''
Wald said. ``We want to deter people from getting involved in
them.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the chicken-and-egg debate over who has the blood lust,
the media or the viewers, Wald said it's definitely the viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask anyone if they watch public television, and they'll tell
you yes, even though they really don't,'' Wald said. ``Then ask
them if they watch pursuits and they say no way. If they didn't
watch pursuits, we wouldn't have been the No. 1 station covering
the (motor home) chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say the live broadcast of chases is dangerous for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media really needs to cut back on the thirst for this
news,'' said Lt. Anthony Alba, a Los Angeles Police Department
veteran who's been dealing with the media since 1994. ``Stuff like
this creates further issues with youth and cheapens the value of
human life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a voyeuristic society that has a fascination with
danger, and my big fear with them is that something bad will happen
_ people will get killed _ and it will be broadcast live.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the chases embolden people to run from police is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The California Highway Patrol reports their pursuits have gone
up in recent years. Between 1996 and 1997 _ the most recent numbers
available _ the number of chases reported went up about 1.5
percent, CHP spokeswoman Ann Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   For the LAPD, the booming fascination with pursuits comes at a
time when chases have actually declined, a phenomenon attributed to
stricter laws and changes in pursuit policies, which make officers
more selective about whom they chase and why.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, when Los Angeles officers logged 908 pursuits in the
city, there has been about a 40 percent drop in chases, according
to a new study. Only 534 pursuits were logged in 1998, the report
says.
</P>
<P>
   Alba asserts the live broadcasts are dangerous for all involved.
</P>
<P>
   The media reveal police tactics. During a chase, when you have
eight news helicopters in the sky and two police copters, the
potential for disaster rises.
</P>
<P>
   Alba says he's elated that Los Angeles County Supervisor Yvonne
Brathwaite-Burke is opening the debate over whether the media
should be required to use a pool helicopter in covering chases. The
move would significantly reduce the possibility of an air disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad someone else is finally talking about this. I've
wanted it for years,'' Alba said. ``I'm going to feel real sorry
for the first news copter that's involved in an accident. It's
unsafe, and the risk is unnecessary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
