<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WRONG TARGET IN BELGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, May 10:
</P>
<P>
   American officials spent a nervous weekend apologizing to China
for NATO's bombing of its embassy in Belgrade, hoping meanwhile
that the incident would blow over without irreversible damage to
the nascent diplomatic efforts to restore peace in Kosovo. With
luck, it will. With luck, the angry criticism in Moscow and the
United Nations, and the dangerous demonstrations in China, will
recede. But this was a very careless mistake, not only because
several Chinese were killed, but because China _ as a member of the
U.N. Security Council _ is a critical component of any negotiated
solution in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is not reason enough to suspend the air war against
Slobodan Milosevic, which Washington has correctly decided to
continue. Given Chinese and Russian sensitivities, it might be
appropriate to continue the undeclared pause in the bombing of
targets in Belgrade. But this should be a diplomatic gesture rather
than a fundamental change in strategy. The pause could also be used
to review targeting procedures to make sure that a big mistake does
not happen again.
</P>
<P>
   The timing could not have been worse. Last week, Russia agreed
with the United States and its allies on the core principles of a
peace deal, including an international security force in Kosovo to
prevent further ethnic conflict and to assure the safe return of
more than a million displaced Albanian refugees. This was a pivotal
agreement, and marked a significant shift in Moscow's position.
</P>
<P>
   But the allies also agreed that the mandate for such a force
must come from the U.N. Security Council, not only to insure the
force's credibility but also to overcome Serbian and Russian
concerns about the presence of foreign troops on Yugoslav soil.
Russia, though angry at the bombing, is unlikely to veto a Security
Council resolution supporting the force. An angry China might do
so. Officials from the United States and other NATO countries
argued yesterday that since a U.N. resolution on the security force
was some weeks away, the accident need not affect the final vote.
They also argued that if Russia backed a resolution, China would
not stand alone and veto it. But Washington clearly has some
explaining to do to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   It also has some explaining to do to the American public.
According to accounts provided in Washington and at NATO
headquarters in Brussels yesterday, somebody picked the wrong
building. The intended target was the Federal Directorate for
Supply and Procurement, a Yugoslav arms agency. Instead, the bomb
hit the embassy. NATO officials have pointed the finger at the CIA,
whose analysts may have used murky reconnaissance photographs or
outdated maps. The site of the embassy building is well known in
Belgrade. The directorate is housed in a white office building. The
embassy, several hundred yards away, is a marble structure with
blue mirrored glass and flies the Chinese flag.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement yesterday, Defense Secretary William Cohen
conceded that there had been a targeting error and acknowledged
that the military's ``extensive process in place used to select and
validate targets'' had not caught the original error. He also
called the mistake ``an anomaly that is unlikely to happen again.''
These are soothing words, but not entirely reassuring given the
fact that ever since NATO's strikes began six weeks ago, allied
officials have relied primarily on laser- and satellite-guided
weapons. Such weapons presuppose reliable targeting information on
the ground, and Cohen owes the public a fuller explanation of why
it was not provided in this case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
