<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/09/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. -- May 9, 1999 --
ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-MEDIA-2, 5-09 -- Martin Eberhard, the chief
executive of Nuvomedia of Mountain View, Calif., says authors'
royalties ``will improve with lower costs.'' Eberhard contends that
the costs of publishing an electronic version are lower than
conventional formats and so authors can improve their shares.
(Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 9, 1999 -- ELECTRONIC-BOOKS-MEDIA-1,
5-09 -- Chuck Verrill, a literary agent with Darhansoff &AMP; Verrill,
wants publishers to allow writers to revise contracts once the
economic impact of electronic books is clearer. ``We want to see
the market grow, but we want to make sure the terms are fair,'' he
says. (Philip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 9, 1999 -- REFUGEES-FAMILY-4, 5-09
--Njeldez Deva, 35, and her son, Adhe, in the safety of their
relatives home in Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn, after six terrifying
weeks fleeing war back in Kosovo. The family in Kosovo, had hidden
at home for eight days, leaving only when a neighbor, a Serb,
offered to help them get away. If they did not leave, the neighbor
told them, they would be killed. Hours later, with a few bags
packed with food and clothes for the children, cash and jewelry,
they left. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- May 9, 1999 -- REFUGEES-FAMILY-3, 5-09 --
Lili Erbeli, 55, waiting for the arrival of her sister's family
from Skopje, Macedonia, at Kennedy Airport Saturday night. When the
NATO bombings began seven weeks ago, the Erbelis, like scores of
Kosovars in New York, were on the phone nearly every day with
family in Kosovo, hearing about death and destruction. Now, after
their arrival, Lili Erbeli, eyes brimming, took her eldest sister's
hand and broke the good news in Albanian. ``You're coming home with
me,'' she said. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 9, 1999 -- REFUGEES-FAMILY-2, 5-09 -- At
a hangar set up as a welcoming hall, eight-year-old Brianna Dhuki,
left, and 12-year-old Argjent Erbeli draped in American and
Albanian flags, wait at Kennedy Airport late Saturday night for
their relatives to arrive from Macedonia. Their relatives were
among 102 refugees who arrived from Skopje. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 9, 1999 -- REFUGEES-FAMILY-1, 5-09 --
With a feast at their home in Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn, Lili and
Rex Erbeli welcomed 14 relatives who had fled the fighting in
Kosovo. The refugees were among 102 who arrived at Kennedy Airport
Saturday night, from Skopje, Macedonia. The extraordinary occasion
was marked by a relatively quiet meal. Although dinner was served
in shifts, Lili and Rex Erbeli seemed unfazed about making do with
an extra 14 people. ``You help them now or never,'' she said.
(James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MOSCOW -- May 9, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RUSSIA-VETS, 5-09 --
Aleksei Vasilenko, 72, a former infantryman, gathered with tens of
thousands in Moscow on Sunday for Victory Day, the national holiday
marking the Allied triumph over Germany. Vasilenko, who entered
World War II as a 16-year-old Cossack cavalryman, believes that
``Russians don't trust Americans.'' At a Communist Party rally
downtown, a crowd waved placards bearing the face of President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia and cheered the slogan
``Solidarity With Yugoslavia.'' (Gleb Kosorukov/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PAINESVILLE, Ohio. -- May 9, 1999 -- BIKER-FEST, 5-09 --
After riding in on matching blue Harley-Davidsons, Dennis Slother
and Gretchen Bryan were married by a leather-clad minister at this
year's ``Louie Run.'' Michael Warren, one of the ``Louie Run''
originals, at right, looked on. The Louie Run is more than an
occasion for bikers to air out their leather chaps. The event is
also a serious fund-raiser for a number of causes that the bikers
hold dear. Last year, Louie Run Inc., a nonprofit charitable
organization, gave away more than $24,000. (Barney Taxel/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MARTINSBURG, W.Va. -- May 9, 1999 --
MEDICARE-PRESCRIPTIONS, 5-09 -- Dorothy Baker, 82, left, and Edith
Dennison, 82, at the Berkeley Senior Center in Martinsburg, bemoan
the cost of medicines. More than a third of the 39 million people
on Medicare have no coverage for prescription drugs they use
outside hospitals, and many others with some form of private
coverage have substantial out-of-pocket costs. ``My medicine bill
was almost $200 last month,'' says Ms. Dennison. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) STENKOVEC, Macedonia -- May 9, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-FLIGHT-FLOAT-2, 5-09 -- Refugees at the Stenkovec
camp having ID photos taken on Sunday for their flights to Spain,
while hundreds of other refugees at the camp spent the day looking
for their names on a list of people chosen for flights to other
countries. Thousands of ethnic Albanians are taken daily by bus to
Skopje airport for flights to countries that have agreed to accept
them. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) STENKOVEC, Macedonia -- May 9, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-FLIGHT-FLOAT-1, 5-09 -- Refugees at the Stenkovec
camp in Macedonia looked for their names Sunday on a list of people
chosen for flights to other countries. Thousands of ethnic
Albanians are taken daily by bus to Skopje airport for flights to
countries that have agreed to accept them. (Tyler Hicks/New York
Times Photo
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 9, 1999 -- GUNS-MCCARTHY, 5-09 -- Rep.
Carolyn McCarthy, 55, D-N.Y. , represents a certain grisly
expertise on the subject of gun deaths, as the widow of a gunshot
victim. Ms. McCarthy is a politician humbled by the way things work
here, but one who personalizes the continuing gun deaths to keep
her edge. ``I'm here two and a half years and that means I've lost
close to 13,000 kids,'' she says of the 5,000 American minors who
are shot to death annually. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PODUJEVO, Yugoslavia -- May 9, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SERBIA,
5-09 -- Milos Savic, the civil defense officer in Podujevo, has
recovered from his overwhelming fear after a run-in with Kosovo
Liberation Army rebels, who have since been forced out of his town.
``Of course the Serbs would defend Kosovo, which belongs to them,''
he says. ``It is our house, and the Albanians were welcome to live
there, too. But it is not their house, and we are not going to give
it away.'' (Steven Erlanger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- May 9, 1999 -- EBAY-CEO-2, 5-09 -- Meg
Whitman, 42, chief executive officer of Ebay, is one of the new
generation of Internet executives who is bringing conventional
corporate bona fides and consumer product-style marketing to the
Web. With no technology background to speak of, Ms. Whitman leaves
the heavy lifting to the tech experts. But what she does seem to
have are many of the skills that may be necessary if Ebay is to
prove itself more than a hot stock or consumer fad. (George
Frey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- May 9, 1999 -- EBAY-CEO-1, 5-09 -- Meg
Whitman, 42, chief executive officer of Ebay, with Matthew Bannick,
left, the vice president for customer support, and Lynn Hrdin, the
director of customer support, reads an account of Ebay in a local
newspaper during a trip to Utah. Since Ebay's $735 million offering
last September, the company's market capitalization has blossomed
to $22.1 billion -- the stock price skyrocketing 1,019 percent.
(George Frey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
