<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SENATE CONFRONTS GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, May 10:
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Senate will address an issue that has been part
of living-room conversations all across America for the last two
weeks. The issue is gun control, specifically a set of common-sense
measures to keep guns away from children and criminals. The
Democratic sponsors of the package _ basically a scaled-down
version of President Clinton's proposal two weeks ago _ hope that
their colleagues will treat the issue with the same gravity that
Americans have ever since the Columbine High School massacre.
</P>
<P>
   From that tragedy has sprung an urgent need and a rare
opportunity for progress on a problem that Congress usually tries
to duck. The measures will be introduced as amendments to a
still-evolving juvenile crime bill. They will leave those senators
who found excuses not to act after last spring's rash of school
shootings with no place to hide. How these lawmakers vote will tell
whether they care more about protecting children's safety or their
own cozy relationship with the gun lobby. For senators with spine,
the votes will not be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Parroting the line of the National Rifle Association, some
senators argue that the nation does not need new laws, only
rigorous enforcement of existing laws. Enforcement is not the
issue. The issue is the dangerous loopholes that were carved into
those laws because the NRA insisted on them. Among the loopholes
are those that exempt gun shows and the Internet from the
regulations that govern the sale of firearms in stores. The new
amendments would close them.
</P>
<P>
   Other proposals would reinstitute the three-day waiting period
for handgun purchases that expired on Nov. 30, ban juvenile
possession of assault weapons, impose criminal penalties on adult
gun owners whose children gain access to those weapons and injure
themselves or others, and raise the age limit for handgun
possession from 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the package is too modest. To increase its chances
of passage, the Democrats left out a provision that would limit
individual gun purchases to one per month. Such a provision would
curb gun traffickers who buy weapons in bulk in states with weak
laws and sell them in states with strong laws. Nor does the package
address the urgent need for a national gun licensing and
registration system _ a need dramatized by the fact that federal,
state and local law-enforcement officials needed two weeks to track
the guns used in the Littleton, Colo., shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, one of the NRA's best
friends, should set aside his normal inclinations and permit a full
debate on each proposal. The country deserves this debate, and the
timing is right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
