r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-10 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECT MOTHER'S DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ If Mama said there'd be days like these, she said it
softly, to herself.
</P>
<P>
   Even Annette Fisher, watching from a floor-level seat at the
Forum on Sunday, must have found this one hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Her son, little Derek Fisher, isn't supposed to win playoff
games for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal is. Kobe Bryant is. Glen Rice is.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is there to throw them the ball with the clock running
down and the game on the line. Assuming he's !ital!in!off! the game
at the time _ an unsafe assumption for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So what developed in Game 1 of the Lakers' first-round NBA
playoff series against the Houston Rockets?
</P>
<P>
   Happy Mother's Day!
</P>
<P>
   Shaq didn't make a basket in the final 4 minutes, 5 seconds, and
missed three of his last four free throws. Rice didn't make a
basket in the final 11:47 _ and heaved up an air ball with the
Lakers trailing by two in the last minute. Bryant didn't make a
basket in the final quarter _ though those were his free throws
that put the Lakers ahead to stay with 5.3 seconds on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fisher was all over the floor _ literally _ and the
hero of the Lakers' dramatic, 101-100 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The unsung hero, if you didn't count the two dozen reporters
around him afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Who'd have believed it?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the fan who came up to Fisher in the Hallmark store where
he bought his Mother's Day card and congratulated him on his recent
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost a bet because of you,'' the man said. ``I bet the guys
you weren't NBA material.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Fisher said Sunday, ``was one of the best and worst
things anybody's said to me.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mom in town from Little Rock _ toting the camera Derek gave
her for Mother's Day _ Fisher showed what tough material he's made
of.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with 20 points, establishing a playoff career high
and matching the regular-season high he set in a March victory at
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   That included a 3-pointer from the top of the circle with 4:32
to go, taking back the lead; two free throws with 3:02 to go,
breaking a tie; and two free throws with 1:17 to go, breaking a
tie.
</P>
<P>
   But the points weren't the point. The Lakers don't go to Fisher
for scoring. They pay big money to guys who are supposed to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, the third-year point guard from Arkansas Little Rock,
made the difference with hustling defense, and, for once, other
Lakers seemed to follow his example.
</P>
<P>
   The play of the game _ of Fisher's career _ came with the clock
on single digits and the Rockets leading 100-99. Houston's Scottie
Pippen dribbled near half-court. Bryant poked it away. Fisher saw
the loose ball and did what he always does.
</P>
<P>
   He dived. A full belly flop.
</P>
<P>
   He grabbed the ball with both hands and immediately signaled
``timeout'' with 7.6 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe that I could get there and actually control
it and call timeout,'' Fisher said. ``At that point I knew we were
going to win the basketball game. That kind of thing just doesn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   After the timeout, Bryant faked Sam Mack into a blocking foul
and made both free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Then O'Neal made the other defensive play of the afternoon,
blocking Cuttino Mobley's driving layup as the buzzer sounded. Fans
clambered over press row _ I'm expecting some soreness in the
morning _ to slap palms with Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   See, defense can be cool.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, 24, has always wanted to believe that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like that's my responsibility,'' he said of setting the
example. ``Tonight, everybody will be talking about my scoring 20
points. But when I see I made a play that changed the game on the
defensive end, that's what tells me I played a heck of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher did his job. The rest of the Lakers responded. They
didn't play a great defensive game _ the Rockets made 52.1 percent
of their shots and Charles Barkley went around them like
driving-school pylons _ but they played hard after watching
executive vice president Jerry West rip them in an NBC interview
for failing to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lifted the team,'' Rice said of Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher hit the hard floor so many times, it was enough to make a
mother cover her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't get into the shower and it starts stinging,'' he
said of the floor burns, ``I don't feel right.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher stung, then dressed, then cut out of the locker room,
otherwise the interviews might have gone on all night.
</P>
<P>
   He and Annette had dinner plans. Perfect end to an unbelievable
day. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
