</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUFF'S TROOPS WERE READY 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Reality bites.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of cruising past the Buffalo Sabres was always a
fantasy. Losing Game 2 at home is reality. And it's just as well
that the more impressionable of the bandwagon fans the Bruins have
picked up in the past two weeks understand that particular reality,
however distasteful it may be.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of simple mathematics and playoff experience tells
you the Bruins are now in trouble after dropping a 3-1 decision to
the Sabres at the FleetCenter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of puts us in the driver's seat,'' observed Michael
Peca, whose first-period goal was a huge determining factor in
deciding the outcome. ``We are tied and going back home. This
should really energize our crowd. Our building should be extremely
loud. The 82-game schedule drains the players, so why should the
fans be any different? They'll be ready, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no surprise out there on the FleetCenter ice. Coach
Lindy Ruff's wish was the Buffalo players' command. The spin coming
out of the Sabres' locker room following Thursday night's Game 1
was that the nine-day interval between the four-game conquest of
the Ottawa Senators and the beginning of this series was not
beneficial. By the time Buffalo got back into its rhythm at the
tail end of the second period of Game 1, the prize stallion long
since had fled the barn. The Buffalo belief was that period three
was far more indicative of their expertise, and that everyone in
Boston would be made aware of that fact in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the score was a manageable 1-0 after the end of
the first 20 minutes Sunday, there was no doubt whose game was
being played. The 17-5 shots on goal disparity was a pretty good
barometer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our first period was fabulous,'' maintained Ruff.
``We opened up the gates and kept coming. We could have come out of
there with three or four goals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw everything at us in the first period, probably
things we hadn't seen before,'' concurred Bruins mentor Pat Burns.
``Everything was black sweaters, bodies flying.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a nice little Bruins ride since the Game 4 equalizer
in the Carolina series. That started a four-game winning streak,
during which time believers started to believe even more and all
sorts of converts partook of the baptismal waters. People were
starting to think that Bobby, Espo, and Cheesie were back.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa.
</P>
<P>
   Things remain good. The future is bright. But in the very
graphic here and now, the reality is that the Bruins are up against
a very formidable opponent. Buffalo is a very solid team that is
more dangerous than just about any team in the league if allowed to
secure a two-goal lead during the course of any given game. And why
is that? Is that what you're asking?
</P>
<P>
   Duh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty comforting just to know he's back there, no matter
what the score,'' says Curtis Brown, who scored Buffalo's second
goal during a five-on-three situation at 5:57 of the second period.
``If I had to bet on it, I'd say we have more peace of mind out
there with him than anyone else has with their goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He,'' of course, is All-Universe goaltender Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say we relax if we're up two goals,'' adds Peca, ``but
if you get down to us by two goals you really have to battle. It's
got to be pretty discouraging knowing you've got to score three
goals against the best goaltender in the world. That's why it's so
important for us to get the early lead.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Now It Can Be Told Dept., the Sabres are free to admit
that nine days is just too damn long to go without playing a
serious hockey game at this stage of the season. Winning Game 1 in
this building against a feeling-its-oats Boston team might not have
been a feat comparable to the Miracle of the Loaves and Fishes, but
it would have been a phenomenal achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the layoff hurt us,'' says Brown.
``The coaches did a good job trying to prepare us, but it felt like
we had been off for two months. It was like a brand new season.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was more acutely aware of the dynamics of the situation
than Burns, who would have been justified in starting his postgame
remarks with an emphatic ``I told ya' so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted it more,'' he said. ``They did not want to be in a
situation where they'd be on the outside looking in. It was exactly
what I expected. They are a pressure team, so you have to do things
quick. We weren't quick enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the Bruins weren't anything enough for the first
54 minutes, or until Don Sweeney blasted one past Mr. Hasek from
the circle to the Dominator's right to make it 2-1. ``There were
two guys on one side,'' analyzed Ruff. ``That was about the only
time we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the crowd was in it, and things got very tense when Joe
Juneau was sent off at 17:16 for a high-sticking infraction against
Darren Van Impe. This, of course, is when you need some big-time
penalty-killing and some big-time goalkeeping, and that is exactly
what Buffalo got. The Bruins did not score, and Dixon Ward put them
out of their misery with an empty-netter at 19:23.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, you had one very concerned coach (guess who)
and one very relieved coach. Ruff was talking about a team that had
finished checks and had killed off a five-on-three penalty for a
minute and 47 seconds and that had come into Boston under a tough
circumstance and had come away with the opening series split every
reasonable playoff veteran _ be it player, coach, owner, GM, or fan
_ wants when the other guy has the home-ice advantage. The Sabres
left on such a high no one even bothered to mention that they are
operating without 40-goal scorer Miroslav Satan (foot injury).
</P>
<P>
   It's great to have people psyched and interested in the Bruins,
but part of a fan's responsibility is to know what is and isn't
realistic. Reality really does bite sometimes, and the reality here
is that this will be a very, very difficult series to win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
