u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-B     05-10 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' SLOW STARTS MUST STOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Over the course of an 82-game National Hockey League
regular season, what happened to the Bruins Sunday would not have
been out of the ordinary. In fact, it happens way too often for
various reasons _ too many teams, too many games, too many miles,
just simply too much hockey compressed into too little time to make
it possible, even fair, to expect a top performance every night.
</P>
<P>
   But the playoffs, now that's a different issue. Clunkers aren't
supposed to be accepted fare. When a team has everything to play
for (i.e. a viable shot at playing into June), then every second of
the clock is supposed to represent opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   When opportunity came knocking Sunday, the Bruins got knocked to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible,'' summarized Jason Allison, among the
collection of key Boston forwards who weren't into it from the
start and who, therefore, were quickly out of it. ``I was terrible.
And a lot of other guys weren't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   When the puck was dropped, the home team, in the black trunks,
moved to the center of the ring looking almost lovestruck. You
never know, it could have been the Mother's Day factor, too many
nice thoughts running through their noggins.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the other team in the black trunks, the Sabres, came
out with their legs firing and didn't allow the Bruins the least
bit of playmaking room. It was downright nasty. They kept breaking
over the blue line with speed and passion, in fierce pursuit of the
puck, denying, almost daring the Bruins to touch it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down low, they kept cycling and cycling,'' said Boston
netminder Byron Dafoe. ``It was like a feeding frenzy at times.''
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the wrong time for Boston to play bait. If not for
Dafoe, who had a handful of excellent saves in the first period, it
could have been 6-0 after 20 minutes. Instead the score read 1-0.
More poignant was the shot count, which had the Sabres holding a
lopsided 17-5 advantage. The Bruins barely could get out of their
own way, never mind head-man the puck or move to the other end of
the ice and set up around Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made no secret of the fact that we wanted to start the game
the way we finished Game 1,'' said Sabres captain Michael Peca,
whose squad played very strong second and third periods in the
opener. ``We wanted that start.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind his own bench, there wasn't much Bruins coach Pat Burns
could do. Under assaults like these, teams typically can chip the
puck out and relieve the pressure, at least momentarily, by forcing
the play into the neutral zone. Icing the puck is another option,
though not as good, because it results in a faceoff in the
defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth was, the Bruins were so out of it they couldn't
get possession to make the chip or wing it down the ice. In Round
1, faced with a similarly tenacious Carolina attack, they
consistently moved out from under the barrage and eventually made
headway toward the other end of the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Not here. Boston's forwards were helpless in assisting the
defense down low. Their defensemen, now looking tired after eight
postseason games, were suffocating in the blanket of black Buffalo
sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   What was Burns telling them?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say it here,'' Burns said in his postgame news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he preached the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get your head out of a certain area,'' he told them. ``Because
they're coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison had a pair of shots in the first period and he was the
only Boston forward to put anything on Hasek. Defensemen Kyle
McLaren and Ray Bourque combined for the other three. It wasn't
until the middle period, when the Sabres' aggressiveness turned
chippy and led to penalties, that the Bruins began to shape a game
with the puck. But they still weren't coming with the kind of speed
and muscle it would take to win a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to go out and get right back at it,'' said the
Sabres' Dixon Ward. ``We got in there with (Wayne) Primeau, (Erik)
Rasmussen, and (Michal) Grosek, and when they cycle it, it's hard
to defend. It wears 'em out. We dominated that first period.''
</P>
<P>
   The series now moves to Buffalo and the Bruins desperately need
their key forwards to reestablish their games. If the likes of
Allison, Joe Thornton, Dmitri Khristich (one shot, 20-plus
minutes), Sergei Samsonov (no shots, 11-plus minutes), Anson Carter
(one shot, nearly 23 minutes) and Steve Heinze (one shot, nearly 18
minutes) again show up with a game that looks a lot more
mid-February than early May, then it will spell trouble with a
capital golf Tee.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Carolina, folks. The Bruins fell into a 2-1 series
deficit with the 'Canes and quickly figured out that they could
thwart the Carolina attack by denying them the dump to the corner
and the passing lane from behind the net. Once finding that key,
they unlocked the series in three straight games.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot more to the Buffalo offensive game, with or
without top goal-scorer Miroslav Satan. For five of the six periods
in this series, they've shown they can keep the pressure up, keep
the Bruins backpedaling. The only way for the Bruins to stop that
now is, first and foremost, be ready off the hop. They don't have
the speed or muscle to match the Sabre attack, but if they can cope
with the pressure and win some room at the other end of the ice,
they at least have the chance of forcing some shots on Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not what we had in mind,'' said Dafoe, reflecting on the start
that quickly developed into a downward spiral. ``We just couldn't
get it down there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
