<HEADLINE>
RED SOX UNTOUCHED BY ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANGELS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mo Vaughn is in the rear-view mirror, Tom Gordon is on
the horizon, and Tim Wakefield is volunteering for double duty for
the suddenly solvent Red Sox, winners of four in a row after
dispatching Anaheim's crippled Angels, 4-2, before a modest
Mother's Day gathering of 23,710 on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, now two games over .500 (16-14) after falling two games
under the break-even point, completed a three-game sweep of the
Angels behind the pitching of Mark Portugal and relief help from
Jim Corsi and Wakefield, who registered his second save in four
days and is thinking of applying for dual citizenship, as both a
starter and reliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to,'' said Wakefield, who is still scheduled to start
Tuesday night against the Seattle Mariners but would like to
continue his gigs out of the bullpen. ``It depends how I feel
between starts, but I could go down there and throw a couple of
innings.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a plausible scenario, given the protected species status of
Gordon, who is due to be activated from the disabled list Monday
but will be handled carefully until he proves his right elbow is
sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting thought,'' said pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan. ``I think he has the capability of doing it, because he
throws strikes. I don't think you'd have to worry about that
ninth-inning walk syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to throw every day and the more he throws it, the
more consistent he gets with it. I think his background as an
everyday player (Wakefield originally was a first baseman) helps
him a lot, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to take care of Flash (Gordon), too. We don't want
to pitch him too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield came out of the pen for the third time in four games
and worked a scoreless ninth after Corsi, who has been battered of
late, retired Troy Glaus on a pop fly with Garret Anderson on
second and two out in the eighth. ``It was just one out, but you've
got to crawl before you can walk,'' Corsi said.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's aura is considerably brighter when he works 7 2/3
strong innings, as he did Sunday, than when he is cashiered early,
which was the case in last Monday's infamous 12-11 loss to the A's,
in which the Sox couldn't hold a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro (Martinez) just pitched fantastic on Friday and (Juan)
Pena threw a great game (Saturday), so you see guys do that kind of
job you try to match up with what they did,'' Portugal said.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old righthander gave up a run on a two-out double by
Todd Greene and a single by Orlando Palmeiro in the second and
another run in the fifth on Darin Erstad's triple and a double by
Dave Silvestri, but allowed just two other runners as far as second
base and did not walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal also did his part in adding to a lost weekend for
Vaughn, who managed to sneak in at least one visit on his gimpy
left ankle to the Foxy Lady but went 0 for 3 with two strikeouts
Sunday, giving him a final tally of one hit and six strikeouts (two
in each game) in 11 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a guy in here who was not happy to see Mo again,''
Portugal said, ``but when the umpire says play ball, you've got to
play nine innings. I've got friends all over the league. We should
know how to get him out, we've seen him hit enough. We would know
what his weaknesses are, and we were fortunate to exploit a couple
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was such a nonfactor this weekend that Sox general
manager Dan Duquette cheerfully emerged Sunday from two days of
near-seclusion to make a pass through the press-box area.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, meanwhile, waved off all reporters Sunday, except for a
prolonged heart-to-heart chat with Steve Burton of Channel 4.
``He's just shooting the breeze with him,'' said Angels vice
president Tim Mead. ``They're good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's old friends in Red Sox polyester, meanwhile, roughed up
Lynn's Ken Hill for four runs on seven hits and four walks in 3 2/3
innings. Nomar Garciaparra hit his second home run in five games in
the second, Troy O'Leary singled home John Valentin in the third,
and Damon Buford tripled home the third run and scored the last on
Jose Offerman's sacrifice fly in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin had six hits over the weekend, Garciaparra and Buford
extended their hitting streaks to 12 and 10 games, respectively,
and rookie Trot Nixon had his first three-hit game of the season as
the Sox outscored the Angels, 16-3, in the three-game set.
</P>
<P>
   The four-game winning streak is only the second time since they
opened the season with five wins in a row that the Sox have won
even back-to-back games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to get something strung together,'' said
Mike Stanley, who did not start but pinch hit and replaced Brian
Daubach at first. ``It's been a season where we've been playing
some very good baseball and some very bad baseball. Obviously, if
we want to stay near or at the top, we've got to play consistent
baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
