<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0484 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS     05-10 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS LOSE THEIR EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's official: The Bruins and Sabres hate each other.
</P>
<P>
   After their victory in Game 1, Boston's players said it was too
soon for there to be too much vitriol, too early for any bad blood,
too little familiarity for it to breed contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. That all changed Sunday at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Things got down and dirty in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference
semifinal series and it resulted in a 3-1 Sabres victory, tying the
series, as the venue shifts to Buffalo for Games 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   There was something for everyone _ nasty hitting, coaches
playing the ``psych out the referees'' game, a total of 16 power
plays. In the end, the beginning proved the Bruins' demise. They
came out flat, fell behind, and then mounted a comeback that fell
short.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted it more, they were hungrier, they knew it was a
situation where they didn't want to be on the outside looking in
and they really came after us,'' said Boston coach Pat Burns. ``We
expected that, I expected that from them. They've done that all
year long. There's a lot of character in that room.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Bruins were too fancy, too tentative, too
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw everything at us in the first period that we had
probably never seen before,'' said Burns. ``Everything was black
sweaters and bodies flying.''
</P>
<P>
   After Game 1, Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said he felt Burns's
antics on the bench helped work the referees into getting more
calls. Sunday, Burns said Ruff was working the officials in his own
way with those comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the referees even got intimidated there,'' he said.
``It was a good call by Lindy, getting that in the papers and
getting them to read that. Our bench got hell from the drop of the
puck. We didn't do nothing yet. Our trainer apparently was talking
too loud.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres were so much the better team in the opening 20
minutes, it wasn't even funny. They outshot the Bruins, 17-5, with
three of Boston's bids coming from the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the game in the first period,'' said right wing Rob
DiMaio. ``I just don't think we were prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Peca put the Sabres ahead, 1-0, with a goal less than
two minutes in. Curtis Brown centered the puck and it glanced off
the stick of goalie Byron Dafoe and bounced right to Peca. He fired
it from the slot, beating Dafoe to the far side at 1:51.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obviously not a satisfying start for us,'' said Dafoe.
``We were not happy coming into this dressing room after the first
period. Playoff hockey, we can't allow that, especially against a
team like that. Getting down a goal early, it makes the hill that
much higher to climb, especially with Dominik (Hasek) in net. We
had to play catchup the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' fortunes worsened in the second with the club
finding itself in penalty trouble. It cost them dearly. Ken
Belanger was called for roughing, Tim Taylor joined him in the box
for cross-checking, and the Sabres had a two-man advantage, their
second of the game, this time for 57 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Alexei Zhitnik, at the right point, dished a pass down for Brown
along the right goal line. Brown put it right between Dafoe's pads
from a tough angle and the Sabres led, 2-0, at 5:57.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cheating a little bit,'' said Dafoe. ``I was spread out
because I was expecting passes. When he walked, I took the bottom
away but he put it over my stick and through my legs. He had to
beat me with a pretty good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' best opportunity for offense came late in the second
when captain Ray Bourque drew consecutive penalties on Buffalo,
giving Boston a two-man advantage for 1:42. At 16:54, Peca drilled
Bourque at the blue line and was called for roughing. Only 18
seconds later, Zhitnik ran Bourque from behind and slammed him into
the Boston bench. He was called for boarding. Boston simply
couldn't get anything past Hasek, who wasn't overly taxed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Bruins' best bids was by Dmitri Khristich, who had
the puck on his forehand, low in the slot. But with Hasek down on
all fours in the crease, Khristich couldn't get the shot up and it
went right into Hasek's crest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were way too soft, the passes were soft,'' said Burns.
``They're a pressure team so you've got to do things quick. We
weren't doing them quick enough. The (five on three) was too
diagrammed instead of being simple and basic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins finally cashed in at 14:03 of the third, by far their
best period, when Don Sweeney tallied a power-play goal to pull
them to within 2-1. Too little, too late. Dixon Ward's empty-net
goal with 36.2 seconds remaining closed the door for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought hard in the third period and made it close,'' said
Dafoe. ``We put a good effort in, but if you go back to the first
period, that kind of says the reason why we had to come back like
we did. We have to play with a little more emotion, with a little
more of a hate factor. This is a war now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
