<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCIOWA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWANS WONDER WHEN, OR IF, THEY'LL SEE CANDIDATE JOHN MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Burnside likes what she's heard so far about Sen.
John McCain. For one thing, she says, the Arizona Republican scored
``brownie points'' by leading the national debate on war in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But Burnside lives in Iowa, a state that places a special,
homespun emphasis on seeing their presidential candidates in the
flesh, not just in the news media.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, Burnside, of the small community of Storm Lake,
hasn't seen much of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has the rest of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's only a name in a newspaper rather than a physical body,''
said Burnside, 65, a Buena Vista County supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think he'll come here?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain actually has been to Iowa a few times, but has no formal
organization there yet. By comparison, he already has campaign
staff in New Hampshire and even South Carolina, on which he says
he's placing a ``high priority.'' McCain's relative inattention to
their state has Iowans wondering whether he plans to compete in the
2000 caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   McCain ``hasn't been here very much,'' said Hugh Winebrenner,
professor of public administration at Drake University in Des
Moines. ``He obviously is not making a concerted effort. The people
who are making a concerted effort are organized to varying
degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowans have been guessing about McCain's approach, or
non-approach, ever since his campaign released an itinerary for a
planned April announcement tour that was later scrapped because of
the war in Yugoslavia. The tour was to have included stops in the
key presidential primary states of New Hampshire, South Carolina,
Arizona and California.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa was conspicuous by its absence. To traditionalists,
McCain's schedule was akin to touring Arizona and skipping the
Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Iowa regards itself as a bellwether of presidential
politics. Its neighborly caucuses _ which are, in effect, precinct
meetings held in all of the state's 99 counties _ have long been
regarded as key, early indicators of candidates' strength. The GOP
caucuses are scheduled for Feb. 7.
</P>
<P>
   McCain insists he's not ignoring Iowa. His campaign staff is
careful not to slight the state, whose residents can be sensitive
to the possibility that the caucuses' importance may be slipping as
other states, such as Arizona, hold their primaries earlier and
earlier. Arizona's GOP primary is scheduled for Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't read too much into the announcement tour,'' said
campaign spokesman Howard Opinsky. ``It's awfully early to be
drawing conclusions about strategy when we don't even know exactly
what the primary schedule will be yet.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire's date, for example, is not yet set.
</P>
<P>
   Wondering about his intentions, the ``Des Moines Register,''
Iowa's largest newspaper, recently asked McCain about them point
blank at an editorial board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   His response: ``I've been here a lot in past years. I will be
here a lot, and I take it very, very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, McCain's tentative May schedule on his campaign
Web site (www.mccainforpresident.org) suggests other priorities:
planned trips to New Hampshire, South Carolina, Arizona and
California. No Iowa visits listed.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons McCain may want to avoid building high
expectations in Iowa by investing lots of time there.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa is ``labor-intensive,'' that is, it requires candidates to
build statewide organizations capable of turning their supporters
out to caucuses on a winter's night. For that reason, the caucuses
are a reflection not just of the polls, but of the candidate's
ability to organize.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a commitment of a person by a handshake, you'll
usually follow that up with a vote at the polls,'' Burnside said.
</P>
<P>
   In organization, McCain starts at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our former governor of 16 years (Terry Branstad) is working
for Lamar Alexander, and he (Alexander) was here quite a bit last
time (1996), so people remember him because they have have met him
and because he came into the small communities,'' Burnside said.
``Pat Buchanan has been here, New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith has been
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, whom McCain acknowledges as the
front-runner for the nomination, hasn't been to Iowa yet for the
campaign. But Bush already has locked up the endorsement of all
four Republican Iowa congressmen, each of whom avoided endorsements
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates _ Dan Quayle, Gary Bauer and Buchanan _ are
likely to benefit from the heavy religious conservatives
participation in the caucuses. In 1996, 31 percent of likely GOP
participants identified themselves as fundamentalist or born-again
Christians, according to a ``Register'' poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to voting in the caucuses, the people who are
going to be out and participating do tend to be a bit more hawkish,
but they also tend to be much more conservative, and that's what
hurts McCain, I think,'' said Arthur Miller, a University of Iowa
political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   McCain mostly earns high marks from the Christian Coalition and
other religious conservative groups for his votes on their
centerpiece issues, such as abortion. But he also has alienated
many conservatives in the party.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in urging reform of the campaign finance system in
the last few years, McCain ``was way out ahead of his party, and
maybe he was at a position that was closer to what the public in
general would want, but not necessarily what Republican activists
would want,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Take ethanol. McCain says he won't waffle on his opposition to
the federal subsidy for the fuel blend, even though it could cost
him Iowa votes. Ethanol is made partly with corn.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ethanol stand puts him at odds with virtually everyone in
the state,'' Winebrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is not going to change his message to go to
different places, and in Iowa he's going to talk about the same
things he's talking about in New Hampshire, the same things he's
talking about in South Carolina,'' Opinsky said. ``And that incudes
being against ethanol. And if that means that is going to cost him
there, then that that's the way it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a final reason McCain may choose not to emphasize an
Iowa campaign. It may simply be that Iowa, long treated by
candidates as the first meaningful contest of the season, may not
be so pivotal any longer. McCain has been paying a lot of attention
to California, whose primary is March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have big states that follow so closely behind Iowa,
such as California,'' Winebrenner said. ``In the past, it's been
dangerous to try to skip Iowa, but it might be that this is the
year to try it again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
