r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     05-10 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ'S SWAT SAVES LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Poor Cuttino Mobley never saw it coming. He could
only hear it when it was already too late. (begin ital)THWACK!(end
ital) Buzzer. Ball game.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, all 7 feet, 2 inches and 330 pounds of him,
snuck up from behind, and, with one mighty swing of his tree-trunk
arm, swatted away Mobley's potential game-winning layup Sunday. And
with that singular, powerful motion, O'Neal lifted the Lakers to a
101-100 victory and 1-0 advantage in their first-round playoff
series with the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The poor Forum press table didn't see it coming either. As the
ball shot harmlessly into the hardwood at the final buzzer, O'Neal
kept going, slamming into the rickety table from one side, while
fans poured out of the baseline stands from the other side,
engaging in a spontaneous frenzy of fist pumps and hand slaps and
congratulatory screams.
</P>
<P>
   It was the swat heard 'round the world. And the Lakers enjoyed
every deafening millisecond of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely phenomenal,'' coach Kurt Rambis said of the play.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no man of O'Neal's mass should be able to stay
step for step with a 190-pound point guard driving to the hoop.
This one does.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone that's 7-foot-2 and over 300 pounds to have the
grace that he does... it's just amazing that a man that big can be
that graceful,'' Rambis said. ``You see him on tape or on
television, you'd swear he's only 6-9.''
</P>
<P>
   Phenomenal, too, that the Lakers _ worst in the league in
defense just weeks ago _ took the lead in this best-of-five series
on a defensive stop.
</P>
<P>
   But then that seemed appropriate on a day the Lakers won the
unconventional way.
</P>
<P>
   They did it with clutch defense down the stretch from O'Neal and
Derek Fisher. They did it by coming from behind after blowing a
double-digit lead. They did it despite a quiet scoring day from
foul-troubled Kobe Bryant (5 of 9, 17 points). And they did it with
a 20-point explosion from Fisher, the point guard known more for
his dives on loose balls than his scoring savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the way we're playing,'' O'Neal said. ``If we can
play like that, then the sky's the limit for this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if they continue to get the offensive bursts from
Glen Rice to complement O'Neal's inside game. O'Neal started slowly
but scored 27. Rice, guarded by all-world defensive stopper Scottie
Pippen, scored 29 _ including 14 in the second quarter, when the
Lakers took an 11-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   But on defense, the Lakers showed occasional glimpses of their
recent past, surrendering 52 percent shooting to Houston and
watching Charles Barkley (25 points) and Hakeem Olajuwon (22) have
their way in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mack came off the bench to score 11 points in the fourth
quarter, as the Rockets overcame a nine-point deficit and made it a
tight game for the final 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And then it all came down to a rookie, the ball in his hands
with five seconds left, about to steal Game 1 and the home-court
advantage from the Lakers. Mobley lost Fisher on a screen, leaving
O'Neal to make the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq's 7-4. He was right on my back, so I wasn't really
worried about him,'' Mobley said. ``But he made a good play.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, chided often for his defense, had to gloat a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumor is, I'm not a good pick-and-roll defender,'' he said
wryly, while admitting to being ``a bit matadorish on defense'' at
times.
</P>
<P>
   It just made his redemption that much sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I know how to play defense,'' he said. ``I knew he was
left-handed. I kind of let him pass me and I just came from the
back. As soon as he put it out, I just went out there and got it.''
</P>
<P>
   It capped a series of game-turning plays in the closing seconds.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers down 97-96, Fisher knocked the ball away from
Mobley, then pounced on it, drawing a foul from Mobley. Fisher went
to the line and hit both free throws to retake the lead with 1:17
left.
</P>
<P>
   The next error, and the last one, was Pippen's. Working the ball
against Bryant, he slipped, Bryant poked the ball and Fisher
pounced on it. That possession change led to a pair of go-ahead
free throws from Bryant with 5.3 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was up to O'Neal's big right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' Fisher said. ``Shaq always tells us, if we
get hit by a screen, just stay with his (man) and he'll take ours.
Sometimes I don't listen to him because I'm always thinking I gotta
keep up with my guy. But the thing we've really improved on
recently as we've started to play better is trusting in one
another, believing in whether a guy is gonna make the shot or make
the defensive stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Or one big swat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
