A0494 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GUMBEL-SFCHRON &LR;      05-10 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GUMBEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS TO PUT GUMBEL ON DISPLAY IN MORNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS has a history of loud explosions in the morning, and right
now disaster seems to be smeared all over Bryant Gumbel's puss.
</P>
<P>
   So CBS' plans to reconstitute ``This Morning'' as a vehicle for
its $5 million amateur golfer already sound like a Gumbel fumble.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference in New York last week, CBS said it will
sink $20 million into a street-side studio in the General Motors
Building to put the morning program's famous anchor on public
display.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the new show is named in the fall _ ``Yesterday'' comes
to mind, in honor of Gumbel's past success on NBC's ``Today'' _
it's still another variation of the ``CBS Morning News'' or ``This
Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   And what a legacy. No network over the decades has programmed
itself more winningly than CBS. Yet the morning franchise dug
itself into third place back in TV's Paleozoic period, and it
hasn't budged.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where Walter Cronkite _ Walter Cronkite! _ clowned with
a puppet lion.
</P>
<P>
   Where Sally Quinn foundered in ignorance of such TV fundamentals
as camera cues.
</P>
<P>
   Where Phyllis George thought that it would be just swell if a
rape victim allowed herself to be hugged by the man who raped her.
</P>
<P>
   Where Kathleen Sullivan decided that CBS stood for ``Cheap
Broadcasting System.''
</P>
<P>
   Where chatty Mariette Hartley was so unstoppable that she kept
talking even after her clip-on microphone fell off.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, it's usually been where one of two things happens:
Your career dies right in front of you, or you pack and change
networks.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS position is understandable. It's paying Gumbel $5
million a year for his prime-time newsmagazine, for all his
prime-time specials and for the astute ideas he's bringing to CBS'
Eyemark syndication arm.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Public Eye'' flopped, you might have missed the prime-time
specials and those exciting syndication prospects haven't
materialized. Gumbel has been a man at leisure for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is eager to get its expensive acquisition back into harness.
All the better that it'll be in his old morning time period.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Friedman, once Gumbel's executive producer at ``Today''
and now a CBS station executive in New York, will pitch in. The
network has to figure that Gumbel can regain a morning audience.
Anyway, what's to lose? It can still keep the spiffy new studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Been there, done that _ that's no longer my arena,'' Gumbel
said in 1997, when asked if he'd anchor a morning show on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's the one who ought to be wary. Even a man of his
generous self-esteem must know that if he fails here, the dominoes
will topple all the way back to his ``Today'' credits. His critics
will say it was Katie Couric all along, and not he, who took
``Today'' to the top.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's press conference, Gumbel, 50, said his paid
absence from television hadn't been onerous at all. He added that
he felt no guilt about accepting his CBS paychecks, ``and I don't
think people upstairs at CBS think I should feel guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the suits at CBS have been gnashing their teeth over
Gumbel's blithe idleness and his apparent preference for golf links
over TV studios. And they have been wondering, disparagingly,
whether any competitive fire still burned in Gumbel's belly.
</P>
<P>
   Morning news viewers are notoriously stubborn about changing
channels. Right now, the weirdly formatted ``This Morning'' has
half the viewers of ``Today'' and about three-quarters the ``Good
Morning America'' audience. So maybe ``GMA'' can be challenged and
eventually caught. That would more than validate CBS' investment in
Gumbel.
</P>
<P>
   But broadcasting history suggests that the Gumbel program will
join the list of kaffeeklatsch casualties at CBS. Then his CBS
contract will expire, the network won't offer a new deal, and
Gumbel can resume his sporadic slide into comfortable retirement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
