<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION PREVAILED WITHOUT ZENGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Revolution's first look at life without Walter
Zenga was unpleasant. They lost nine successive games in 1997, then
failed dismally after he retired last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Zenga's return as player-coach has brought the team a style
of play and bolstered confidence. Zenga has not worked miracles,
but the Revolution's propensity to defend has given them a point of
reference and provided a third-place standing in the Eastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Their most recent experience without Zenga was the final 23
minutes of Saturday night's game against the Miami Fusion. Zenga
departed with a right groin strain and is questionable for the
team's visit to Columbus Saturday. The Revolution, though,
performed well enough to play to a 0-0 tie in regulation, and won
the shootout, 3-2, as reserve goalkeeper Jeff Causey remained
poised and stymied some dangerous assaults.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga's status will be determined later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter will basically take the next two days off from
training,'' Revolution spokesman Derek Aframe said Sunday. ``The
groin bothered him when we played Kansas City (April 3), then he
took two days off and was fine. This is a little worse, but Walter
should be available for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Causey's performance came at a critical time. Last season, the
Revolution had 10 points through seven games but did not earn
another point until July. Now they have 7 points in seven games and
are facing matches at Columbus, Los Angeles, and the MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   They could remain in contention in the Eastern Conference or
face a crisis similar to those of the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga's setback fits in with the theme for the season, as Imad
Baba (groin) and John Harkes (sprained right knee) have yet to
play, and Richard Goulooze (calf), Paul Keegan (sprained right
knee), and Ivan McKinley (suspension) were out against Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Goulooze and Harkes, former teammates at Derby County in
England, are expected to return against Columbus. The Revolution
should improve as injuries heal, but there is no guarantee others
will not be injured.
</P>
<P>
   Among Zenga's objectives this season was to improve the
Revolution's depth, but there are questions about whether it has
been improved enough. Several reserves have been used and others
have played out of position in recent games, and the Revolution
have held together but shown little improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have earned only 1 point in four home games. But
they have lost only once in regulation time this season and have
outscored road opponents, 5-3. They must now step up their
offensive production or at least become less predictable in the
transition to attack.
</P>
<P>
   The defense solidified against Miami as Brian Dunseth performed
much better in an inside position and Mike Burns brought stability
to the right side, though he seemed unable to overlap into attack.
Kris Kelderman has been ineffective at defensive midfield in the
last two games and Jair appears out of position on the wing. Edwin
Gorter and Joe-Max Moore played some effective combinations late in
the game, but Moore and Giovanni Savarese are not receiving many
scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Columbus-Revolution game will be the first at the
22,000-seat Crew Stadium, the first major US stadium built
primarily for soccer since the 1920s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-VAUGHN-BOS     05-10 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 VAUGHN, BAT SILENT
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BOSTON _ Move on, Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   That was the advice Anaheim hitting instructor Rod Carew gave
the struggling Angels slugger and former Red Sox star Sunday. Carew
encouraged Vaughn to put the 1-for-11 weekend at Fenway Park behind
him. Ditto the ovations and the jeers from the fans, and the
pressure of wanting to do well in his first return to Fenway in a
visitor's uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Carew also reminded Vaughn to exercise his right to remain
silent. ``I went in (the trainer's room) and asked him, `Do you
feel you have to talk to these guys out here?' '' Carew said,
``because I think mentally it's tough right now. I hope the guys
understand. Give him the time to chill out a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `You don't have to talk to those guys out there.
If you want to, you can, but you don't have to. Give yourself a
little breathing room.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn heeded Carew's advice. When reporters assembled before
his locker following the Angels' 4-2 loss to the Red Sox, he said
he did not want talk, got up, said, ``See you all later,'' and
retreated to the trainer's room. He stared out at reporters
repeatedly from the trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, Angels vice president for communications Tim Mead
informed reporters that Vaughn would not be not fielding questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to get his thoughts and everything back together,''
said Carew, who added that Vaughn's left ankle, injured in the
Angels' first game of the season, probably still is bothering him.
Sunday, Vaughn went 0 for 3, striking out swinging in the fifth and
eighth innings. He reached after being hit by a pitch, but the only
time his bat made contact with the ball was in the first inning,
when he lined to right fielder Trot Nixon. He is now 1 for his last
17 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Vaughn stepped to the plate Sunday he was showered
with a mixture of cheers and boos, the same greeting heard
throughout the three-game series. Each time he struck out, there
were nothing but cheers. There also were cheers when Red Sox first
baseman Brian Daubach hit a hard drive Vaughn's way and he reached
forward to snare the ball but had it roll past him.
</P>
<P>
   When he took the base after being hit by a pitch, Vaughn was
booed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the ankle injury) is still there,'' said Carew. ``But
he knows he came here to play and not stay on the bench. He knows
we have some key guys injured and the load is on him, and he's
going to go out there and carry the load.''
</P>
<P>
   Carew said that's all the more reason for Vaughn to move forward
and put the weekend behind him. Anaheim begins a three-game series
in New York Tuesday. ``I knew this was going to be a tough series
for him coming back here being under the light and everybody
looking and wondering what is going to happen,'' said Carew. ``It
grinds on you mentally, but he's going to be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following the game, about 25 fans gathered outside
the Angels clubhouse, chanting, ``We love Mo.'' Vaughn waved to the
fans before heading into the clubhouse. Then, just before leaving
the park at 5:40 p.m., Vaughn greeted several fans huddled in front
of his limousine and signed a few baseballs and photos. Then he
departed.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins declined to say how much Vaughn's
homecoming affected the slugger. ``Only Mo can answer that,'' he
said. ``I certainly can't sit there and say that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys know him, those who have been around him more than
me, and I don't think I've been around a stronger human being
mentally. I'm sure he dealt with it in his own way. I know one
thing: He wanted to hit better than he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
