<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-PITCHING-B     05-10 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WHOLE STAFF IS PITCHING IN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-PITCHING-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Whatever it takes to win. You'll be hearing that phrase
a lot around the Red Sox' clubhouse from now on. And maybe it's not
a bad idea for the Fenway Faithful to adopt that philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly was a recurring theme Sunday after a three-game
sweep of Mo Vaughn and the Anaheim Angels. The celebration in the
clubhouse seemed a bit greater than what might have been expected
after four victories in a row. There seemed to be unanimous joy
that the sum of the parts equals the whole once again, especially
regarding the pitching. When the Red Sox come together as a team,
they have their best chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Sox limped home from a 2-5 road trip that left them
with a 12-13 record, the picture looked bleak. Tom ``Flash'' Gordon
was on the disabled list and soon was joined by Bret Saberhagen.
Facing the Texas Rangers and the Angels seemed an invitation to
disaster. But the Sox won four of the five and may be an even
better team because of the adversity of the last week or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a ballclub of unselfish players,'' said knuckleballer
Tim Wakefield, who came out of the bullpen for Boston Sunday and
recorded his second save. ``Whatever it takes to win that day.
That's (manager) Jimy Williams's philosophy, and a lot of us are
happy to be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week in Oakland, the team was hitting and the pitching
wasn't there. It's just a matter of getting the hitting untracked,
the pitching untracked, and the defense. It takes all three to win
ballgames, and it seems like we've got that under control.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston had no trouble scoring runs against Minnesota and
Oakland, but lost five of seven. Against Texas and Anaheim, a
return to the early-season excellence of the starting pitching was
needed. That is exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Rapp didn't last beyond a third of a inning and Boston lost
to the Rangers Wednesday, 8-3. Saberhagen went three innings
Thursday, but when he went down, the Sox still managed a 3-2
victory because of the relief work of Derek Lowe, Rheal Cormier,
and Wakefield. Then came a couple of strong starting performances
by Pedro Martinez and Juan Pena, who simply overwhelmed the Angels.
By the time Mark Portugal finished off Anaheim in Sunday's 4-2
victory, there was a sigh of relief everywhere. And it felt good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen over the course of a 162-game season,'' said
Williams. ``When things go wrong, the players straighten it out. A
lot of different people are contributing. One by one, they all have
their moments in the limelight where they can contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were losing before, we hit the ball well and scored a
lot of runs. Today, we had some opportunities and we made the most
of them. I believe in our pitchers. I believe in those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   When John Wasdin pitched 6 2/3 strong innings of relief
Wednesday, it gave a great break to the bullpen. The Sox were then
able to use Pena in a starting role Saturday, and his six innings
of strong work were the key to a 6-1 victory. Again, the bullpen
was needed only sparingly, and Sunday's 7 2/3 innings by Portugal
seemed to line things up very nicely.
</P>
<P>
   The starters are set up and the bullpen is rested for three
games against Seattle. Look for Gordon to be declared ready for
duty soon, although when and how much is still undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get Flash back tomorrow, everybody will be in their
regular roles in the bullpen,'' said pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
``Everyone should fit into their proper time frame of the game and
can expect to pitch in that time frame. We can come at you pretty
good with the right-left game and the mixing and matching pretty
good. It gives the skipper some leeway in what he can do out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox will carry 12 pitchers, to provide insurance in case
Gordon has any trouble and/or Saberhagen responds slowly to
treatment while on the disabled list. Williams has touted all along
the benefits of having Wasdin, who has started, around for bullpen
duty. Pena has pitched only as a starter. It makes a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good going into the game (Wednesday),'' said Wasdin.
``I've been starting, but I also feel I can help out the bullpen. I
have confidence in my ability. There are a lot of different
situations that can arise. I've been lucky to have every role there
is. It's made me a little bit better, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   At his recent rate, Wakefield could become a 30-30 man. That's
30 starts and 30 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'll see that happen,'' the knuckleballer
said. ``But I'm willing to go out there (in relief) between starts
every time if I feel well physically. If I threw a complete game of
125 pitches, I don't think I'd be out there. With Sabes going on
the DL, it makes it more of a challenge for me to go down there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
