<HEADLINE>
BUFORD EARNING HIS STRIPES 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BUFORD-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Damon Buford sent a Kenny Hill fastball into the
gap in right-center for an RBI triple in the fourth inning of
Sunday's 4-2 victory over the Angels at Fenway Park, it was just
the first half of his personal 1-2 punch that helped KO the
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Buford's hit drove home run No. 3 for the streaking Red Sox, and
he came home shortly thereafter on Jose Offerman's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Oriole, Met, and Ranger _ who extended his
hitting streak to 10 games (14 for 41, .341) _ wasn't done
bedeviling the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Just after taking the field for the fifth inning, center fielder
Buford ran down a Jeff Huson drive, making a graceful sliding stab
in left-center.
</P>
<P>
   He nearly duplicated the feat when the very next batter, Darin
Erstad, hit a line drive to just about the same spot, but this one
bounded past the diving Buford, with Erstad winding up on third.
</P>
<P>
   A platoon player last season, when Darren Bragg would face
righthanded pitching and Buford would take on the lefties, Buford
has seen more playing time this year because of the slow starts at
the plate by Trot Nixon and Darren Lewis, plus Lewis's three-game
suspension after his altercation with Indians pitcher Jaret Wright.
</P>
<P>
   He has responded with a .310 average, hitting above .300 against
both righthanders and lefthanders.
</P>
<P>
   An Orioles 10th-round draft pick in 1990 and the son of former
major leaguer Don Buford, who is Baltimore's assistant director of
player development, Buford said after Sunday's 1-for-4 performance
that he wasn't even aware of his hitting streak, and he downplayed
his offensive and defensive heroics. ``It was a good all around
game for the whole team,'' said Buford. ``We got good pitching and
defense and timely hitting, so it was a good win.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his highlight-film catch ``was tougher than normal
because of the day game and the conditions. There were a lot of
white shirts in the stands and the ball was kind of dying away from
me, but I saw Troy (O'Leary) behind me and so I took a chance and
dove for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't as fortunate with Erstad. ``It was almost the same
play, but Erstad hit his a little bit harder and it was sinking a
little bit more,'' he said. ``But I'll tell you what: I'd try it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   When he came to the plate in the fourth, Scott Hatteberg was on
first base via a leadoff walk. ``It was one of those times in the
game when Kenny was struggling to throw strikes,'' said Buford. ``I
just took advantage of the situation. We kind of let him off the
hook earlier in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Buford was reluctant to make any prediction based on his or
his team's recent progress. ``We've still got a whole season ahead
of us,'' he said. ``So it's not something you want to talk about
too much. I come to the ballpark every day, do my workouts, and
stay ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's my time to play, I go out and play hard and leave it
out there. But it's too early to talk about the team or myself
turning any corners.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has managed to turn a couple of heads in the Red Sox
clubhouse _ those of manager Jimy Williams and hitting coach Jim
Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played like this since he's been here and he's been
playing more against righthanders,'' said Williams. ``He's just a
good player.''
</P>
<P>
   And, added Rice, he's a player who has made some positive
changes since coming to the Red Sox. ``He's made the change from
being strictly a pull hitter,'' said Rice. ``He's learned to hit
the ball where it's pitched, and he has power to the opposite
(right) side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's capable of being successful that way.''
</P>
<P>
   After his blast off righthander Hill Sunday, you wouldn't get an
argument on that from the Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
