<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIES WILL BE PUNISHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There is a fine line between vigilance and vigilantism,
and the Buffalo Sabres either straddled it or strangled it Sunday,
depending on one's viewpoint _ assuming one wasn't viewing the
point through swollen black eyes, as many of the combatants were.
</P>
<P>
   The result was indisputable: The Sabres throttled the Bruins,
3-1, at the FleetCenter and evened this best-of-seven Eastern
Conference semifinal scrum at 1-1. But whether they achieved this
through robust clutch-and-grab hockey or borderline assault and
battery is a matter of testimony. The Bruins weren't angels,
either, as goalie Byron Dafoe observed once he got out from under
siege.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some cheap shots on both sides,'' he said. ``The hate
factor is a part of it. We have to hate them. They're the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   If the case goes to trial, there probably will be four major
items of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A: At 15:39 of the first period, Bruins defenseman Kyle
McLaren left the ice, his right eye looking like the Red River,
after Sabres forward Vaclav Varada swatted him with his stick.
Referee Kerry Fraser was a witness, though he made no call.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw everything at us in the first period,'' said Bruins
coach Pat Burns. ``I think they intimidated the referees, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit B: At 8:54 of the second period, Bruins forward P.J.
Axelsson staggered to the bench, his left knee wobbling like
Jell-O, after Buffalo defenseman Alexei Zhitnik delivered a
knee-on-knee hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to take the body,'' said Zhitnik. ``He never moved
away. I don't know what happened after that.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was that Buffalo captain Michael Peca, another
master of sub rosa work, was penalized for holding on the other
side of the ice as Zhitnik escaped scot-free.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit C: At 17:12 of the second came the main event. Repeat
offender Zhitnik dropped Bourque from behind at the Buffalo blue
line, less than three minutes after he'd been sent off for charging
the Boston captain.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque crumpled to the ice, Zhitnik was called for boarding,
and McLaren began a long-distance exchange of pleasantries as
Fraser restrained Zhitnik while ushering him off to serve his
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a dirty hit on Ray,'' said Burns. ``That's what I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque became well acquainted with such attention while serving
as the Sabres' favorite fodder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I turned my back,'' said Bourque, ``they'd be
coming. There were some cheap shots there, but it's a long
series.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the biggest part of our hockey team,'' said teammate Rob
DiMaio. ``They know that and came after him. Everyone here has to
respond to that, but respond in the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhitnik, by now well versed in the art of proclaiming innocence,
felt the response was excessive. At least for the second
transgression.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first hit was dirty,'' he said. ``I got him from behind.
The second hit, he didn't see me, then went down like I hit him
real hard. I wasn't hitting him from behind. I pulled up. He didn't
say anything, but when I looked at him, he was smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, he was alone in that regard because the crowd was
screaming for bloodlust and McLaren was eager to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He yapped a little bit and I yapped a little bit,'' said
Zhitnik, smiling ever so benignly. ``As the referee skated me off,
he said he thought it was a questionable penalty, but it wasn't his
call.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit D: At 5:01 of the third period, McLaren took a couple of
jabs at the puck after Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek covered it with
his glove. Hasek took issue and took off after McLaren. His five
teammates on the ice beat him to it, forming a posse and menacingly
skating McLaren into a corner; the Bruins defenseman was fortunate
Hasek, trailing the parade, didn't have a rope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who it was, but he hit me twice with his stick,''
said Hasek. ``I was upset no penalty was called. A couple of times
before that, they had pushed at the puck after the whistle. I was
pretty upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The aggrieved parties had better get used to it, because
administering and absorbing punishment seems to be the cost of
doing business in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any game now is going to go from physical to hostile,'' said
Peca. ``In a seven-game series, you're going to see it. It's
nothing personal. It's going to get even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the Bruins had better bring plenty of sutures and
ice packs to Buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0108EDT &QL; 
