<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-REACTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE TEAMS DEVELOPING HATRED? CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Kyle McLaren says he won't forget the hit Alexei
Zhitnik threw on his captain.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns called it ``a dirty hit.''
</P>
<P>
   And Byron Dafoe says it's something ``we'll remember heading
into Game 3'' in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   War hasn't been declared yet, but it became obvious Sunday at
the FleetCenter that these teams don't like each other and things
should get very interesting when this Eastern Conference semifinal
series between the Bruins and the Sabres resumes Wednesday tied at
a game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 3-1 Buffalo win was physical to be sure, and among the
star attractions were Zhitnik, who rang up 10 hits, and McLaren,
who had four, and took exception to the Zhitnik check on captain
Ray Bourque in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   It came at 17:12 in front of the Bruins bench and after Bourque
was hit, he went down in a heap and was slow getting to his feet.
Zhitnik was sent off for boarding, giving the Bruins a
five-on-three power play.
</P>
<P>
   McLaren was so incensed that he followed Zhitnik to the penalty
box, where he got into a shouting and finger-pointing match with
the Buffalo defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I said to him is stuff I probably can't repeat on the air
right now,'' said McLaren in his postgame interview with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hitting) is part of the game, but that hit was uncalled for.
It was kind of from behind and you just don't do that to guys like
Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, he's one of our best players and they're
going to hit him every chance they get. But don't hit him that way.
I was fortunate enough to be on the ice and get my words in there.
I'm not going to take a cheap shot at (Zhitnik) or what not, but .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   That incident was just one of three McLaren found himself in the
center of during the game.
</P>
<P>
   At 15:35 of the first period, he took a high stick from Vaclav
Varada to the corner of right eye. The play happened directly in
front of referee Kerry Fraser, who let it go. As play continued and
McLaren retreated to the bench, blood flowing from the gash, Burns
was ripping into Fraser. McLaren later returned sporting six
stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at 5:01 of the third period, McLaren bore in on Buffalo
goalie Dominik Hasek, and poked at the puck that, McLaren says,
``was just sitting there.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Jay McKee, who, along with every Buffalo player on
the ice, including Hasek, went after McLaren in the corner. In
effect, just as he was telling Zhitnik earlier not to mess with
Bourque, they were telling him not to mess with Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puck was sitting there and the referee thought he had it,
but it was on the other side of his blocker,'' said McLaren. ``I
saw that and went in there after it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I did it after the whistle or before the
whistle, but the puck's there and I'm trying to put it in the net
and try and get this team going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't consider our team real chippy. I think we play hard
and play clean. It gets a little chippy out there every once in a
while and we have to stand up for ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we knew right from the start of this series that it
was going to be physical. But sticks are coming up and hits are
coming from behind and those are the things we have to respond to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray's a big guy and can stand up for himself, but when a hit's
uncalled for, well, we'll take care of each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the type of hits that aren't forgotten. They better
not be. I know I'm not going to forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   War hasn't been declared yet, but it certainly doesn't sound
like peace is at hand, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0109EDT &QL; 
