<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LOOKING BACK FOR NBA'S WELTS SINCE SONICS TITLE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If humiliation wasn't sufficient, let's add historic
irony.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' absence from the playoffs comes at the 20-year
anniversary of the biggest deal in modern local sports, a peak
never reached again:
</P>
<P>
   An undisputed national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' 1979 NBA title remains alone in the Puget Sound
sports pantheon, made even more lonely by this season's hoop
travails in which one of the championship-team members, Wally
Walker, is now held in contempt, if not custody, for failing to
return the lost glory.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonic president's plight is further evidence for the wisdom
in the axiom that you can't go home again.
</P>
<P>
   Another figure from that championship season has made the point,
too. Rick Welts was the club's public-relations man, who that
summer demonstrated an exquisite sense of timing by leaving the
Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   He never looked back, just up, and over the past two decades
became one of the most influential executives in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Now the sense of timing prevails again. As the NBA attempts to
recover from its recent self-slaughtering, Welts, whose 17 years in
the NBA front office made him the No. 3 power broker after David
Stern and Russ Granik, is moving on to head up something called Fox
Sports Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The operation is in its infancy, but since his new boss is
Rupert Murdoch, the most powerful man in sports, odds are decent
that Welts in five to 10 years will be astride a sports-business
colossus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see the headline now: `Ex-Sonic ball boy makes good,'''
Welts said, laughing over the phone from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Welts joins the Fox empire July 1 in Los Angeles, where he has
been assured an office next to the studio where TV's ``Ally
McBeal'' is filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Having seen the program, this is not inspiring news. But Welts,
the NBA's executive vice president and chief marketing officer, is
recently familiar with lame show business, having been in full
cringe for a year as the NBA crashed and burned.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the personal side, it was the most difficult year we've
ever been through,'' he said. ``You couldn't tell what the next
one, two or three years of your life would be like. That takes a
toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we had a real resolve that if we get it right, we'll have
an extended period of growth. If we got it wrong, it will take a
long time to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA did get it right. The league crushed the union and the
agents, winning a hard salary cap and a rookie salary scale. The
tradeoff was a horrible half-season of hoops _ a deal owners would
make 10 times out of 10.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a human cost _ disillusionment and anger permeated
an enterprise once cited as an ideal operation for its turnaround
into America's trendiest sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of residual damage,'' he said. ``It's like any
other consumer-product business _ it can take years and years to
come back. But we tried to learn from other sports about how to
recover, and we've been pleasantly surprised the league came back
as quickly as it did.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatively minor drops in ratings and attendance signaled
again the gullibility of the American sports market as well as the
NBA's resilience _ partly due to the work of Welts, who was the
primary guy behind the NBA's marketing shrewdness.
</P>
<P>
   The Sporting News' annual ranking of the 100 most powerful
people in sports put Welts 77th, the only Seattle native on the
list besides Bill Gates (27) and Paul Allen (45). There is no
question about the top guy on the list _ Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with his network's bold acquisition of NFL telecasts,
Murdoch's sports and TV empire is growing exponentially. Welts'
boss, Chase Carey, is Murdoch's right-hand man and sixth on the
power-broker list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brands, logos and personalities he (Welts) helped create
and nurture have become universally known and respected,'' Carey
said. ``The events he pioneered, including the NBA All-Star
weekend, have become models for the sporting world.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that the selling of the NBA's stars was cited
as the biggest problem in preventing a reasonable settlement,
because the players were convinced they were bigger than the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Frankenstein's basketball monster was then. The now in
Welts' life is overseeing Fox's non-TV interests in pro sports: the
Dodgers, the new Staples Center home for the Lakers and Clippers,
ownership shares in New York's Knicks, Rangers and Madison Square
Garden, plus hunting for fresh Murdoch meat.
</P>
<P>
   He'll conduct the fight in Los Angeles, the epicenter of a
corporate sports brawl between Fox and Disney, owners of the
Anaheim Angeles and NHL Mighty Ducks as well as ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   According to Tim Leiweke, president of the NHL Kings and the
Staples Center, ``What Rick has to do is figure out how to make
sense of all the pieces that Fox has _ and that's all Fox has now,
pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Welts, 46, loves a jigsaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could design a job not knowing whether it exists, this is
it,'' he said. ``Murdoch is one of the biggest TV players in the
world, and he knows that two things are guaranteed to bring viewers
to TV _ movies and sports. It's tried and true.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Sonics employee for a decade, it's good to see the gig can
ultimately get something more than a good booing.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
