<HEADER>
A0502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROW-EASTERNSPRINTS-BO     05-10 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROW-EASTERN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRINCETON PROVES A TIGER 
</HEADLINE>
 SPRINTS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ The Princeton Tigers grabbed the field by its
tail Sunday in the 54th edition of the Eastern Sprints on Lake
Quinsigamond.
</P>
<P>
   The heavyweights, defending national champions who finished
third here last year, covered a 2,000-meter course in 5:42.10 to
beat Brown (5:46.99) by a length. Following were Penn (5:48.91),
Wisconsin (5:49.26), Harvard (5:50.28), and Northeastern (5:54.88).
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton lightweights, defending Eastern Sprints and
national champions and headed to Henley in July, posted a 5:50.40
to beat sixth-seeded Columbia (5:52.12) by a half-length.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Harvard (5:52.83), Rutgers (5:54.46), Yale
(5:55.53), and Georgetown (6:03.1).
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton heavyweights rowed their typical race, putting on
bursts at the 1,000- and 1,500-meter marks to get ahead and stay
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The race was all even after 500 meters. It was Princeton, Brown,
Wisconsin, and Penn after 1,000 meters, and then the Tigers took
off as if shot from a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton coach Curtis Jordan said, ``We're not a fast-mover at
the start of any race. So we put in a game plan before the season
started and we stuck with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed close at the start of our race, make strong moves
after 500 and 1,000 meters, then got ahead and stayed ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was worried that all the crews got off to such a fast
start.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bothered me, because I was worrying about having enough
energy towards the end of the race,'' he said. ``My guys certainly
did. We rowed a perfect race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton heavyweights will not go to Henley because some
oarsmen have duties with national teams and some will go to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stay together until the IRAs, then disband,'' Jordan
said. ``It has been a fun season. We have five new oarsmen this
year, and they all did well.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeton lightweight coach Jim Murtaugh said, ``It was a great
race. We have everyone back from last year except two oarsmen and
we had a great season. We weren't top-seeded here but we had to
earn this championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Princeton had won all its regular-season races by open water and
that streak ended because of gallant efforts by Columbia and
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some great crews around this season and you can't take
anything for granted,'' said Murtaugh. ``We had to make a total
team effort and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard freshman heavyweights were 8-0 entering Sunday's
race and won by a half-length over Brown _ 5:55.20 to 5:57.88.
</P>
<P>
   First-year Harvard coach Bill Manning, a 1986 Holy Cross grad,
said, ``We're relatively small, averaging 6 feet 2 1/2 inches and
180 pounds, but we have quality people.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard was pushed by Brown and Princeton at the start, then by
Brown alone over the last 500 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel relaxed until there were 15 strokes to go,''
said Manning. ``Then I knew we had it. We rowed well from start to
finish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
