<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSERO'S 7-INNING EFFORT GOES FOR NAUGHT AGAINST YANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With his starters averaging 52/3 innings per outing
and his bullpen depleted and ragged, Mariners manager Lou Piniella
sat in his office Sunday and said, hopefully, ``I'd like to see
Fassero go seven innings today. Seven or eight. Then give the ball
to Mesa.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's got just what Piniella ordered _ sort of. Jeff Fassero,
their No. 1 starter, worked seven innings, then gave way to closer
Jose Mesa. It was the longest outing by a Mariner starter in more
than a week, but all it got the M's was a 6-1 loss to the New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero (1-4) was starting on three days' rest as the Mariners
began their plan to go with a four-man rotation for the next month.
He allowed five runs on seven hits and six walks in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter touched him for a two-run homer in the first, and
after three innings the Yankees were ahead, 4-0. At that point,
Fassero took a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about mechanics so much,'' Fassero said.
``After three innings, I said, `(Forget) mechanics, just throw the
ball over the plate.' Danny (Wilson) said my sinker started moving
a lot more, my fastball in was driven in, my slider and forkball
were a lot sharper. I'm just going to go off the last four innings
and see if that gets me going.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero's next start will be on the usual four days' rest, and
with an off-day every week for the next six weeks, the Mariners
will need him to start on three days' rest only twice.
</P>
<P>
   Their other starters, Jamie Moyer, Freddy Garcia and Mac Suzuki,
also will have just two starts on three days' rest. Piniella said
he will arrange the rotation so left-handers and right-handers
alternate.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Brett Hinchliffe, who will be recalled from Class
AAA Tacoma Monday, figures to work in long relief after making a
spot start Monday night in Boston. The Mariners likely will send
down a reliever to make room for Hinchliffe, leaving them with a
six-man bullpen to back up the four-man staff.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero's counterpart Sunday Mike Stanton, made his first major
league start after 552 relief appearances because scheduled starter
Ramiro Mendoza was sick. Stanton broke the old record of 443
appearances before starting for the first time, set by San
Francisco's Gary Lavelle in the 1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   It was unorthodox, but the strategy worked. Stanton pitched four
strong innings, though Wilson's third-inning double dashed hopes of
another Beanie Baby Day-perfect game at Yankee Stadium, which David
Wells did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton's shutout, however, remained intact when home plate
umpire John Hirschbeck called Wilson out at home after two-out
single by Brian Hunter. Replays clearly showed Wilson slid around
Jorge Posada, slapping home plate before Posada tagged him. Wilson
slammed his helmet to the ground after being called out. Third base
coach Steve Smith was ejected in the argument that followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was safe,'' Wilson said. ``(Hirschbeck) thought I
slid past it and was tagged before my hand got there.''
</P>
<P>
   Things got so desperate for the Mariners, Piniella came out
after the sixth inning and told Hirschbeck he believed the Yankees'
Jason Grimsley was doctoring the ball. Piniella said he noticed
Posada had flipped third-out strikeouts into the stands in the
fifth and sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grimsley was doing something to the ball,'' Piniella said.
``The last two innings he pitched, he wasn't. But the first two, he
was. His pitching coach, (Mel) Stottlemyre, can teach a sinker, but
not that kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said Hirschbeck told him, ``Boy, if someone had that
type of sink on the ball, he could win 20 games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out the last two innings and mixed his pitches,''
Piniella said. ``He still pitched well, but not with the movement
he had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley, a journeyman who has enjoyed a renaissance with New
York, struck out five and allowed one run to move his record to
4-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I throw the ball, and the ball sinks,'' said Grimsley, who
said Hirschbeck never talked to him. ``It's always sunk. I've just
never been able to throw it over the plate. I take (the Mariners'
suspicions) more or less as a compliment, because that tells me my
ball is moving more or less the way I want it to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
