<HEADER>
A0507 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-10 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ When you are bigger than life like Shaquille
O'Neal, it only makes sense that soon you begin to believe anything
is possible.
</P>
<P>
   And soon, like in the heart-gripping seconds it takes a
320-pound, 7-1 monster player like you to chase down Cuttino
Mobley, it becomes apparent that almost anything is.
</P>
<P>
   You can do it all, and you know it. You revel in the monster
image and expectations of being the scariest, most dominant big man
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   You call the energy drinks you down before every game ``diesel
fuel.'' You chest-bump teammate Ruben Patterson during pre-game
introductions, and he crumbles to the ground like a rag doll,
laughing at your strength.
</P>
<P>
   You embrace the aura that surrounds you _ the beautiful people
telling you how great you are; the blaring songs singing your name;
the record producers, movie executives and stars from here to Jack
Nicholson parading in front of you asking for autographs and
handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a unique player,'' O'Neal said. ``I know I do unique
things.''
</P>
<P>
   You love the way greatness fits you and how you are feared on a
basketball court. You are a phenomenon. You are the Diesel. Shaq
Daddy. Superman.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, anything seems possible.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Game 1 of this Rockets-Lakers playoff series
Sunday showed us everything we need to know about this remarkable
player.
</P>
<P>
   It's scary how he can win a game almost by himself. It's equally
scary how he can nearly lose it by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate missing free throws,'' O'Neal said. ``I felt bad about
how I shot them today.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal proved to be everything Hollywood loves to love in the
Lakers' 101-100 win at the Great Western Forum. He was huge inside,
offensively and defensively, constantly making plays that boggle
the mind.
</P>
<P>
   But he also again showed the tragic flaw in his game _ a 5-of-14
touch that is to free-throw shooting what Kazaam was to cinema.
</P>
<P>
   One moment, O'Neal was running a fast break like Magic Johnson
and finishing it with an alley-oop pass to Kobe Bryant. He was
spinning on the Rockets' Hakeem Olajuwon for a huge dunk and
lofting a soft one-hander over Charles Barkley in the waning
moments of this tough game.
</P>
<P>
   But he also was clanging a pair of misses from the free-throw
line with 3:38 remaining, keeping the game tied as the crowd
groaned.
</P>
<P>
   With 28 seconds left, he was hitting only one of two from the
line, keeping the Rockets up 100-99 and causing Lakers coach Kurt
Rambis to run his fingers through his hair in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   But then, there he was making the game-saving play after Bryant
hit a pair of go-ahead free throws with five seconds left. O'Neal
sealed the Lakers' victory when he perfectly defended the Rockets'
last-gasp pick-and-roll play, forced Mobley into an awkward
baseline shot and blocked it into the seats as the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   He screamed and hugged four of his teammates at once. Shaq
Daddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phenomenal,'' Rambis said of his superstar.
</P>
<P>
   And phenomenal he was, at least in the images that will linger
in Lakers minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq has been ridiculed and criticized a lot for not defending
that play,'' Lakers guard Derek Fisher said of the game-winner.
``Lo and behold, they run a pick-and-roll in the last seconds, and
Shaq wins it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Neal, mumbling into the cameras: ``I've got so many great
highlights I don't know if I've ever blocked a shot (for the win)
before. But I admit I've been a matador before on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Lo and behold, it's the Lakers up 1-0 going into Tuesday night
at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaq nearly lost this one, too. And that's why so long as
O'Neal is on the floor, anything remains possible in this series.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was concerned about O'Neal's numerous misses
from the line, Rambis scowled. He paused, shrugged and then
announced, ``Yeah, we're not going to play him next game.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course O'Neal will play. He'll dominate. He'll clang free
throws and get hacked and chopped on. That's why anything remains
possible.
</P>
<P>
   That's why in every close game that ensues in this series,
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich will continue to substitute Antoine
Carr and Stanley Roberts like hired guns in the critical moments,
with O'Neal in their sights.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal will be fouled, fouled often and fouled on every critical
possession. Then he'll step up to the line for those flat free
throws of his and hope they don't bounce off iron so many times the
Rockets couldn't help but win.
</P>
<P>
   He truly is bigger than life. He swings big and misses big.
Anything remains possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0508 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-LAKERS-HN     05-10 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Rockets had done everything they were
supposed to. They had run down the to-do list as if completing
Sunday errands. Charles Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon took turns
dominating. The rookies stepped up. They had the lead and the
basketball and a few more seconds to burn.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All that was left to check off was the last line: Don't fall
down in the last eight seconds. The Rockets did not hit the wall
with the game on the line. They ran into the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen crashed with 7.6 seconds left, handing the Lakers
the ball and a last chance to steal the win. Sam Mack then fell
into a two-guard pileup with Kobe Bryant, giving the Lakers the
free throws that became a 101-100 win to begin their Western
Conference first-round playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't steal one,'' Pippen said. ``We gave the game
away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets' last chance was snuffed out at the buzzer when
Cuttino Mobley dashed around an Olajuwon pick, flying past guard
Derek Fisher. But with Mobley leaning back to arch his shot over
Robert Horry, Shaquille O'Neal closed from behind to smash the ball
into the crowd, joining it to shout and high-five with the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what they were trying to do,'' O'Neal said. ``I told
Fish to just stay with him and I would take care of the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Rockets having blown the road win that could have given
them early control of the best-of-five series, it was not the last
big shot they lamented. It was the one that got away, and the one
the Lakers never had to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we gave this game away,'' Barkley said. ``That's a
no-brainer. We got the lead and the ball, and you turn it over.
That's frustrating. We just turned the ball over. I'm not going to
blame anybody. You can't turn the ball over like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he were willing to point a finger, it would have had to
go across the locker room to his friend who could not get Barkley
the ball in the last seconds. Barkley had scored 12 of his 25
points in the fourth quarter, toying with J.R. Reid until he fouled
out and manhandling Horry.
</P>
<P>
   The only break in Barkley's dominance was when he used it to
attract double teams to pass outside to the Rockets shooters who
had reversed a horrible first half to carry the team back from an
11-point halftime deficit to control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But after O'Neal made one free throw with 28.4 seconds left,
pulling the Lakers within one, Pippen found himself with the ball
with the shot clock running out. Barkley was on the block with
Horry on his back. Mack was on the wing. Pippen tried the first
steps of a drive but dribbled his legs out from under him. As he
smacked the court, the ball squirted to Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was tripped,'' Pippen said. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mack was sure about the next play. With only a few seconds
to shoot, the Lakers went to Bryant, who shook his hips and headed
for the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any contact,'' Mack said. ``He tripped over his
own foot. He tripped. I felt him falling. He reached out a little
to try to catch himself. I tried to get out of the way. I didn't
want any contact. He fell over me.''
</P>
<P>
   Official Ted Bernhardt hesitated, then called a foul on Mack.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant tagged the move ``the Philly Shake.'' But if naming his
moves or getting the ball on the last possession when three
starters had outscored him did not indicate Bryant's growing star
power, getting the call might have.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what that was, don't you?'' Pippen said. ``That was a
Michael Jordan call.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen did not blame the refs or his turnover as much as he
pointed to mistakes and to a Barkley decision. Pippen's was not the
only late turnover. With the Rockets holding a 97-96 lead, Mobley
looked for Mack on the basic Barkley post-up play. Mack had said
that if Glen Rice overplayed him, he would curl to the baseline,
instead of out on top. But Mobley did not get the message, looked
for Mack in the usual spot and let the ball slip away with 1:17
left.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher grabbed the ball, was fouled and made both free throws
for a 98-97 LA lead. Lakers coach Kurt Rambis moved Reid off
Barkley to Olajuwon, who immediately planted Reid with a spin move,
fouling him out and giving the Rockets a 100-98 lead with 1:03
left.
</P>
<P>
   Rice (29 points) airballed a wide-open 3. But when Olajuwon
missed an 18-footer from the baseline, O'Neal grabbed the rebound
and Barkley fouled to put O'Neal on the line.
</P>
<P>
   A notoriously dreadful free-throw shooter, O'Neal had made 54
percent this season, finishing well from the line. But when Barkley
hacked him, O'Neal had made just four of 13, his five second-half
misses helping the Rockets' comeback.
</P>
<P>
   With 28.4 seconds left, O'Neal missed his first. And though he
made the second, the Rockets had the lead and 28 seconds to hold
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we wanted to do,'' Barkley said. ``Every time Shaq
got the ball, we were going to foul him, and that gave us a big
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pippen chastised Barkley for fouling too soon, and for that
matter, for fouling him at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think the foul we gave Shaq at 28 seconds, when we
were up two points, was a very smart move,'' Pippen said. ``We
should have made them come down and have to work to score, at least
take the time off the clock. That was our biggest enemy right then,
to take some time off the clock. They got to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up two points, and we just allowed them to (cut the lead
in half) and they get the ball back because we now have to do
something on the other end. We gave them the opportunity, and he
put us in a position where we had to score. We just put our back to
the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Down one game in the series, the Rockets are not there yet. But
they can see that wall closing in as clearly as the floor had in
the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some mistakes were very costly,'' Olajuwon said. ``We cannot
afford those kind of mistakes. It was a golden opportunity. This
was a great opportunity, and we lost it. We gave it away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
