<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0510 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     05-10 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARKLEY HOLDS HIS TONGUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ When the subject happens to be the Los Angeles
Lakers, Charles Barkley is the anti-hype.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the NBA has chided the team itself and those who are
fascinated by the vogue, photogenic Lakers their fans, the media,
themselves more often than Sir Charles. To do anything else would
be uncivilized.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday afternoon, Charles was forced to hold his tongue, not
because the Lakers impressed him thoroughly or because he is ready
to annoint Kobe Bryant as the NBA's new king, but because his
Houston Rockets hand-delivered the mother of all Mother's Day
gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had the ball, a two-point lead and less than a
minute on the clock in the first game of the best-of-five
first-round playoff series, and somehow managed to lose. Their
final 30 seconds featured an airball, two stumbles, a touch foul
and the debut of new Lakers point guard Shaquille O'Neal, and it
was all bad for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The 101-100 Lakers win won't go in anyone's scrapbook but will
count for the Lakers as they aspire to higher NBA playoff ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was obviously a gift,'' said Barkley, irked yet calm in
the Rockets' dressing room. ``It is very disappointing to give them
this game. Three turnovers in the last 90 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very tough game to lose. We played what I thought was
pretty much a perfect game until then. Our game plan was good. We
wanted to foul Shaq and make him shoot free throws, and we did
(Shaq was 5 for 14 from the line). They didn't limit me much today
(25 points, 10 rebounds). They don't match up well against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But all that counts is that they won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were content to take it. Their post-mortem didn't
talk about who gave them a gift as much as how well they handled
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see what it takes to win, and that's on the defensive
end,'' said guard Derek Fisher, who had the presence to dive for a
Scotty Pippen turnover with seven seconds left and call timeout
while prone. ``If we can continue to do that, we'll win, and it
won't matter whether it's by one point or 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. The Lakers may go on to close out the NBA's oldest team
and Charles' mouth in the process, but their effort didn't win many
new admirers or scare any future opponent. Their flaws as a team
were still littered all over the Forum Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, for example, scored 29 points, but none of them came
in the game's final 10 minutes. It was his air ball from the top of
the key that gave the Rockets the ball to go with their lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won despite not scoring a field goal in the last four
minutes. Their last nine points came from the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   They tossed a half-dozen defenders at Barkley J.R. Reid, Robert
Horry, Rick Fox, Sean Rooks, Shaq and even Kobe on some switches
and no one came close to stopping the 36-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers won because because Pippen stumbled and lost
possession driving on Bryant, and Fisher recovered; because Sam
Mack stumbled guarding Kobe and drew a foul as Kobe drove over him;
and because Shaq, moving better than a 325-pounder should be
allowed, shadowed guard Cuttino Mobley off a pick on the game's
final play and stuffed his baseline attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was phenomenal,'' said coach Kurt Rambis. ``They were
going to pick-and-roll, and Shaq did a great job helping out those
hung up on the pick. He just followed the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the truncated season began, Barkley looked at NBC's
schedule and howled at the number of exposures the Lakers were
getting. Charles has nothing against any one in L.A., but he voiced
the obvious point that a team should have won something to become
the chosen one.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was giving the Lakers the title, Barkley said then,
even though they're not even the best team in their conference. A
few days after the Rice-for-Eddie (Jones) and Elden (Campbell)
trade, Barkley lit into the Lakers again, saying a team with an
erratic defense had just traded away its best defensive player and
their only big forward.
</P>
<P>
   At least in this series, the Lakers miss Campbell (not to
mention Dennis Rodman), who was always big enough to guard guys
like Barkley. Their defense of late has been better than it was
most of April, but they still miss Jones' ability to harass
shooters. Mack made all three of his 3-point shots in the second
half Sunday, allowing the Rockets to overcome an 11-point halftime
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the Lakers have accomplished lately is suspicious.
They closed the season with four wins, but two of those came
against non-playoff teams and two against a Portland team that
peaked in March. They were 2-5 in the seven games before that, with
both wins over non-playoff teams and three losses by 22 points or
more.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Sunday's game, to be followed by game two
Tuesday. ``This loss won't take a thing out of us because we're a
veteran team,'' said Barkley. ``This was obviously disappointing,
but I've been through worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Charles and the Rockets have perhaps the oddest streak
in the league working against them. They have now lost 14 straight
games that were televised by NBC, a streak that goes back to
February of 1998 and includes eight games this season.
</P>
<P>
   This may have an impact on Barkley's post-NBA sportscasting
career. For now, it's merely a streak he would like to break so he
can revive his monologue about the Lakers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
