<HEADER>
A0511 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREST-FUNDS-SPI &LR;      05-10 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREST-FUNDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK GIFT WILL HELP GROUP BUY, PROTECT WILDERNESS AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Environmentalists working to purchase and preserve a
wilderness area in north-central Washington will announce on Monday
a multimillion-dollar gift in stock that, along with grass-roots
fund raising, puts them halfway to their goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Loomis Forest Fund, launched to protect 25,000 acres of
rugged and pristine state-owned land near the Canadian border, aims
to raise $13 million by July 1 to purchase the forest and protect
it from planned logging.
</P>
<P>
   The Loomis Forest, a largely roadless area in northern Okanogan
County, is a popular recreation area that is host to numerous
wildlife species, including grizzly bear and the largest U.S.
population of Canada lynx in the lower 48 states.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Munson, campaign director for the Loomis Forest Fund, said
he and others will announce on Monday that an anonymous donor has
contributed to the effort by donating stock worth millions. They
won't reveal the company, except to say it's local, or the current
stock price because it could identify the donor, who wishes to
remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, but also kind of ulcer-generating because the
stock fluctuates so wildly,'' said Mitch Friedman, executive
director of the Northwest Ecosystem Alliance and one of the leaders
in the drive to protect Loomis Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said the plan is to sell the stock as soon as it makes
sense to do so to help pay for the land acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had more than 3,000 donors, so it's not just Microsoft
millionaires we're talking about,'' added Munson. He said donations
vary in amount, but the average per donor has been about $950.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this really shows is that when it comes to protecting our
wilderness, people really reach deep,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group also is looking to the Washington Legislature to reach
deep during this upcoming special session to help make the land
transfer happen. Advocates of the sale, which include state Public
Lands Commissioner Jennifer Belcher, say the state will recoup more
money from the transfer of ownership than from selling logging
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly the best use of this land,'' Friedman said.
The state has already agreed to the sale if the money can be raised
by the July deadline, he noted, but he wants the Legislature to
pitch in because this constitutes a public benefit on a number of
fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, a former tree-sitting and occasionally incarcerated
member of the radical group Earth First!, is now executive director
of Northwest Ecosystem Alliance and one of the prime movers behind
this market-based approach to saving wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   It's a switch in tactics for folks like Friedman, whose
organization earlier filed a series of lawsuits aimed at preventing
the state from allowing logging. The lawsuits argued this would
further threaten the local population of Canada lynx, which the
federal government last year proposed to list as a threatened
species.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase proposed by the Loomis Forest Fund would not hurt
the state's Common School Construction Trust, which uses the sale
of logging rights on state land to finance public school buildings.
Friedman and Munson have agreed to give the trust money to buy
timberland of comparable value and they contend the sale will
provide the school fund with more money than it would get from
logging the Loomis Forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason it hasn't been logged yet,'' Munson said. The
two largely roadless parcels they aim to protect are
higher-elevation forest land with skinny lodgepole pine trees of
the kind typically used for chipping into pulp, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing the Loomis fund purchase, Munson said, would preserve
wilderness, and the state would retain the right to allow
recreational use as well as grazing.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said ranchers had threatened to sue to block the deal
if they were not allowed grazing rights.
</P>
<P>
   He said it's in the Legislature's interest to help pay for the
transfer as well because the school construction fund will get more
bang for the buck than if it simply went for logging. Friedman said
an independent appraisal estimated the school fund would receive
about $6 million if it sold logging rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We propose to get them twice that much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Friedman first proposed private purchases aimed at
protectingpublic timberlands, environmental allies were dubious if
not downright critical. Some felt he had abandoned his principles
and perhaps his common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think so,'' Friedman said. ``It's about trying do
whatever might work, about thinking outside the box.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he hopes the Legislature _ despite an extremely short
special session beginning a week from Monday _ can also think
outside the box and help fund a land transfer that protects both
the budgetary bottom line and the state's natural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the Loomis Forest Fund, call
206-264-0477 or visit the campaign Web page at www.loomisfund.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
