<HEADER>
A0718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN12-COX     05-10 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Poison in our land
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An admired movie actor, aging but still a commanding presence,
addresses the annual meeting of the National Poison Association, of
which he is president:
</P>
<P>
   Fellow NPA members, it is a pleasure to be with such righteous
and patriotic Americans, a wholesome change from the time that I
have to spend with the whiners of this country just to defend our
basic right to own the poisons of our individual choice.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, the threats to that right have been growing. We
have a president who believes some poisons should be outlawed. He
wrongly argues that the inevitable fatality and fast action of some
of the newer ones somehow make them fundamentally different from
the old poisons. And he would have the government regulate even the
poisons that can take hours to work and for which antidotes are
available in most communities.
</P>
<P>
   Special-interest organizations are misrepresenting poisons and
defaming the good people who account for the overwhelming majority
of poison owners.
</P>
<P>
   These organizations say that the easy availability of poisons is
the cause of poison deaths and illnesses. We are, all of us,
saddened by such tragedies, but it would be wrong to penalize the
law-abiding majority of poison owners for the misuse that a
criminal few make of a substance that, after all, can commit no
crimes on its own.
</P>
<P>
   We of the NPA have long worked with law enforcement officials to
fight criminal poisonings. We support mandatory and longer prison
terms for persons who use poison in a crime. We spend more money
than any other organization teaching children to respect poisons
and we conduct workshops that show children how to use poisons
safely. The NPA is proud of its Poison Buddies program _ you've
seen its lovable mascot, Vinnie Vulture _ which brings parents and
children together for fun outings at our Responsible Poisoning
Camps.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, if poisons are outlawed, only criminals will have
poisons. Tax-paying homeowners would be left defenseless against an
array of predators. These days, it's a woods out there! And the
surest way to stop the next young lady who thinks she's Lucrezia
Borgia is to remind her that the next guy she meets might be
packing poison himself. More poisonings are prevented by poison
than are committed with it.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in this vast room is appalled at the recent situation
in Smalltown, Iowa, where a man slipped strychnine into the water
system. Our hearts go out to the families. Some now call for
controlling strychnine, but the fault for this horrible crime lies
elsewhere. Smalltown, with a single guard at the reservoir, was
clearly negligent in its public safety duty, and the perpetrator of
this heinous act had been watching too much television. It is our
godless culture that really is poisoning us.
</P>
<P>
   I am pleased to accept a second term as your president. I will
not _ I will not! _ let the Smalltown tragedy lead to the
confiscation of your poisons or to requirements for safety caps.
Let me leave you with this _ and let us all say in unison: Poisons
don't kill people. Poisoners kill people.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
