<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, May 16)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending May 1, at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE PILOT'S WIFE, by Anita Shreve. (Back Bay/Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) After learning that a plane flown by her husband
</P>
<P>
   has exploded, a woman tries to unravel the secret life
</P>
<P>
   he led.
</P>
<P>
   2. HOMEPORT, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.) An art
</P>
<P>
   expert's troubles, personal and professional, lead
</P>
<P>
   her to seek help from a seductive art thief.
</P>
<P>
   3. YOU BELONG TO ME, by Mary Higgins Clark. (Pocket,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A radio talk-show host attempts to expose a
</P>
<P>
   killer who targets lonely women.
</P>
<P>
   4. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE READER, by Bernhard Schlink. (Vintage, $11.)
</P>
<P>
   A German high school student falls in love with a
</P>
<P>
   former Auschwitz employee.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``N'' IS FOR NOOSE, by Sue Grafton. (Fawcett, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Kinsey Millhone investigates the sudden, strange death
</P>
<P>
   of a cop in a California town.
</P>
<P>
   7. I KNOW THIS MUCH IS TRUE, by Wally Lamb. (Regan Books/
</P>
<P>
   Harper Perennial, $16.) A troubled man must care for his
</P>
<P>
   schizophrenic twin brother.
</P>
<P>
   8. LEGACY OF SILENCE, by Belva Plain. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Her past haunts a woman who fled to America at the
</P>
<P>
   beginning of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   9. COAST ROAD, by Barbara Delinsky. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A California architect puts his life on hold when his
</P>
<P>
   former wife falls into a coma.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE ELEVENTH COMMANDMENT, by Jeffrey Archer.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Paperbacks, $7.99.) A CIA officer must contend
</P>
<P>
   with a new enemy, the director of central intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   11. DIVINE SECRETS OF THE YA-YA SISTERHOOD,
</P>
<P>
   by Rebecca Wells. (Harper Perennial, $13.50.) Three
</P>
<P>
   generations of Southern women.
</P>
<P>
   12. THE STREET LAWYER, by John Grisham. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A young lawyer discovers his
</P>
<P>
   prestigious firm's dirty secret.
</P>
<P>
   13. WHERE THE HEART IS, by Billie Letts. (Warner, $12.)
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant teenager finds help and caring in a small
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma town.
</P>
<P>
   14. A WIDOW FOR ONE YEAR, by John Irving. (Ballantine,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) Three looks at the complex emotional life of a
</P>
<P>
   writer and single mother.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) NOW YOU SEE HER, by Linda Howard. (Pocket, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young painter takes a strange turn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. REAL BOYS, by William Pollack. (Owl/Holt,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) A clinical psychologist discusses the
</P>
<P>
   emotional development of boys.
</P>
<P>
   3. OUR DUMB CENTURY, edited by Scott Dikkers. (Three
</P>
<P>
   Rivers, $15.) Newspaper headlines making fun of great
</P>
<P>
   events of the past century.
</P>
<P>
   4. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages.
</P>
<P>
   5. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) Life in the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   6. OCTOBER SKY, by Homer H. Hickam Jr. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) A memoir of Coalwood, W.Va., where the author
</P>
<P>
   learned to build rockets.
</P>
<P>
   7. ARE YOU SOMEBODY? by Nuala O'Faolain.
</P>
<P>
   (Owl/Holt, $11.95.) The memoir of a Dublin journalist.
</P>
<P>
   8. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of the
</P>
<P>
   nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   9.(x) ADVENTURES OF A PSYCHIC, by Sylvia Browne and
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette May. (Hay House, $12.95.) A psychic tells
</P>
<P>
   her life story.
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) TALKING TO HEAVEN, by James Van Praagh.
</P>
<P>
   (Signet, $6.99.) A ``world-famous medium'' discusses
</P>
<P>
   communication with the other side. (b)
</P>
<P>
   11. FALLING LEAVES, by Adeline Yen Mah. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) From a cruel childhood in China to life as a
</P>
<P>
   California physician: an autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   13. TENDER AT THE BONE, by Ruth Reichl. (Broadway,
</P>
<P>
   $13.) A memoir by the former restaurant critic for The
</P>
<P>
   New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday,
$7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE COLOR OF WATER, by James McBride.
</P>
<P>
   (Riverhead, $12.) A black writer remembers growing
</P>
<P>
   up with his white mother in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) ALL OVER BUT THE SHOUTIN', by Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   (Vintage, $14.) From poor white in Alabama to
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning reporter: a memoir.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION, by
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Atkins. (Avon, $14 and $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ways to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. PROTEIN POWER, by Michael R. Eades and Mary
</P>
<P>
   Dan Eades. (Bantam, $6.50.) Two physicians offer a
</P>
<P>
   protein-rich, low-carbohydrate plan for losing weight.
</P>
<P>
   3. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE MOTHER'S SOUL, compiled by Jack
</P>
<P>
   Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen, Jennifer Read Hawthorne and
</P>
<P>
   Marci Shimoff. (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspiration. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. DON'T SWEAT THE SMALL STUFF ... AND IT'S ALL SMALL STUFF,
</P>
<P>
   by Richard Carlson. (Hyperion, $10.95.) How to enjoy life more.
(b)
</P>
