<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0739 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-R     05-10 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KOSOVO-MONTENEGRO-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING THE PRESS FOR PROTECTION IN MONTENEGRO 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Montenegro _ As soon as foreign reporters enter
Yugoslavia by one of the only routes still open _ into the
country's junior republic, Montenegro, by way of Albania _ a small
squad of heavily armed police officers is there waiting for them.
</P>
<P>
   The police immediately take the reporters into custody, but not
to kick them out of Yugoslavia. Rather they are there to escort
them safely into Montenegro's capital, Podgorica, where they are
invited to work in a modern press center complete with
long-distance telephone lines, fax machines, Internet connections
and access to top government officials.
</P>
<P>
   That special treatment is a far cry from the way most Western
correspondents were rounded up and forced out of Belgrade early in
the NATO bombing campaign. The reason for this hospitality is
simple: The tiny republic of Montenegro, only the size of
Connecticut, is in big trouble. Its new Western-leaning government
has pulled out of the federation with Serbia in all but name and
has refused to accept the declaration of war passed in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independent foreign press is the last bastion in the
defense of Montenegro, along with our police units,'' said Abaz
Beli Dzafic, deputy secretary of Montenegro's Ministry of
Information. The ministry runs the press center in Podgorica and
coordinates a police team that provides escorts and occasionally
rescues journalists caught in roadblocks set up by the Yugoslav
Army, which has confiscated equipment from foreign reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav army positions in Montenegro have been bombed anyway.
NATO jets have damaged the airport in Podgorica as well as a bridge
on the border, causing a number of civilian deaths. The mayhem gave
the army and a segment of the political opposition _ which is
aligned with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic _ fuel with
which to attack the government of Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   The government says it is helping foreign journalists (more than
500 have received press credentials from the Ministry of
Information since the conflict began) to prevent the
state-controlled Serbian media from presenting the only images of
what is actually happening here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine what would happen if NATO had no information
from Montenegro and it notices some anti-aircraft fire coming from
the ground,'' said Deputy Prime Minister Dragisa Burzen. ``Instead
of understanding it was just an attempt by the army to incite
trouble, NATO might believe that the government is no longer in
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps uniquely in the Balkans, Montenegro has a tradition of
independent journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is horrible because we've got that constant
feeling that the army can grab you any time you go out on the
street,'' said Milka Tadic, the managing editor of The Monitor, a
weekly newspaper with a circulation of 10,000. The government has
provided protection for Monitor employees and has pledged to
support their efforts to continue publishing, even though many of
the paper's articles are also critical of the current government.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they have a reason to protect us,'' Ms. Tadic said. ``We
can say much more about what is going on in Serbia than the
state-owned media. We are openly writing about ethnic cleansing in
Kosovo and about the moves by the army of occupation here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
