w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETER-PAUL-AND-MARY-S     05-10 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETER-PAUL-AND-MARY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLK HEROES: PETER, PAUL AND MARY TUNE UP FOR THE NEXT MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of folk singers Peter Yarrow, Paul Stookey
and Mary Travers. 
 By BONNIE SIEGLER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's been almost four decades since three folk singers combined
talents for a concert at Greenwich Village's Bitter End coffee
house, and Peter, Paul and Mary are still going strong.
 &HT;    Their latest album, ``Songs of Conscience and Concern'' (Warner
Bros.), is their 21st, a collection of old songs focusing on the
political and social themes for which they are best known. But
instead of a ``greatest hits'' album, they have chosen to sing
lesser-known songs that they feel deserved a wider audience, and
one new song, ``Don't Laugh at Me,'' whose message seems especially
appropriate in the wake of the tragedy in Littleton, Colo.
 &HT;    ``All of our music has a certain ethical bottom line,'' says
Mary Travers, now 59 and a grandmother. ``The sense of human
dignity in this song, reminding people that we are all entitled to
a certain level of respect, is what drew us to it.''
 &HT;    Peter, Paul and Mary _ the other two-thirds are Peter Yarrow and
Noel ``Paul'' Stookey _ do sing a lot of their old hits in concert,
but even there they try to make at least a third of their songs new
material, in deference to audiences which includes decades-long
fans and newcomers alike.
 &HT;    ``When we first began singing, we were singing to people our age
and younger,'' Travers says by telephone from her Connecticut home.
``They grew up and became mommies, daddies and grandparents.''
 &HT;    After all these years, and despite the $30,000 to $50,000 that
they reportedly command per concert, Travers says the songs
themselves are still the group's purpose.
 &HT;    ``It was to sing these songs, to be able to put your passion
where your mouth was,'' she says. ``I did, and I'm still doing
it.''
 &HT;    She'll admit that the trio has sung such hits as ``Puff The
Magic Dragon'' and ``Blowin' In The Wind'' ``trillions of times''
since they first sang them in 1962, but insists that there's
nothing wrong with that. ``Blowin' in the Wind'' still resonates
for her as much as it ever did.
 &HT;    ``It's still an immensely powerful song,'' the folksinger says.
``All I have to do is remind myself what's happening with the
Serbs. Fundamentally, it's dealing with classical issues _ we're
always going to have to talk about human rights, and each
generation fights the good fight. The fight never ends.''
 &HT;    Speaking by telephone from his Manhattan apartment, Yarrow
seconds the motion.
 &HT;    ``There's a phrase in Yiddish that says `Tikkun olam,''' he
says, ``which means you don't ascribe to yourself the task of
saving the world, but you cannot shrink from doing your part. That
characterizes our sense of commitment.
 &HT;    ``As an artist, I feel a sense of completion when I speak to
somebody whose life has been affected by our music or folk music in
general,'' Yarrow says. ``Once a young man said to me that he sang
`The Great Mandala,' that I wrote, to a judge when he was to be
sentenced.''
 &HT;    He cites ``Blowin' In The Wind'' or ``Where Have All The Flowers
Gone,''' which they sang at the legendary 1965 civil-rights march
in Selma, Ala., as among the group's most powerful songs.
 &HT;    ``But our songs are no longer songs per se,'' he adds. ``They
are symbols of hopes and dreams, written in blood and pain. What
identifies Peter, Paul and Mary up to this point is we have been
together longer than any other performing act that has achieved
this recognition.''
 &HT;    During the 1960s, for a relatively brief period, the three were
major pop stars. Today their records sell steadily, but they are
most active as live performers, outside the mainstream of the music
industry where stars such as Celine Dion, Lauryn Hill and Marilyn
Manson rule. Which, Travers says, is fine.
 &HT;    ``Folk music survives without the commercial machinery,'' she
says. ``It's more a grassroots thing. People want moments of lapsed
cynicism, they want moments when they feel a sense of community.
It's a specific well that people can go back to.''
 &HT;    Nonetheless, she says, she pays attention to the stars of today,
and sees folk influences all over the charts.
 &HT;    ``Rap music is nothing new,'' she says with a laugh. ``We call
it, in folk music, `the talking blues.' It's been around for over
150 years _ Woody Guthrie wrote a wonderful rap song about unions
decades ago.
 &HT;    ``There are a ton of young singers who have borrowed from folk _
Sheryl Crow, Alanis Morissette _ and I like to listen to them,
along with my opera music.''
 &HT;    Yarrow won't condemn today's music either, though he admits to
some reservations about what he hears on the radio.
 &HT;    ``I see rap music as very narcissistic, negative and
inflammatory,'' he says. ``That frequently comes from manipulators,
like a street version of Jerry Springer, but uglier. Some rap music
is a cry from a disenfranchised population.
 &HT;    ``But I can't make a categorical decision on rap either,'' he
adds. ``There have been very stylish folk songs written, too, just
to make money. Art is always something to be evaluated one person
at a time.''
 &HT;    Calling from his Maine farm, Stookey notes that the social and
political climate has changed around the trio.
 &HT;    ``We live in more pragmatic times than when we originally
recorded those '60s songs,'' he says. ``But many of the dreamers of
the '60s have been elected to governmental office or taken on
leadership in their communities.''
 &HT;    It was Stookey who was the impetus behind the group's breakup in
1970.
 &HT;    ``Yes, I wanted to explore more of my spiritual side,'' says
Stookey, who has been an evangelical Christian since 1969, an
outlook reflected in his post-breakup music, most notably the
popular ``Wedding Song.''
 &HT;    After the split, Travers continued to record, as well as
producing, writing and starring in a BBC television series. Yarrow
devoted his energies to political activism _ ``it's what keeps my
motor running and keeps me young,'' he says.
 &HT;    None was as successful solo, but Travers says the time apart
from each other was important nonetheless.
 &HT;    ``We needed that time,'' she says, ``because we were just tired.
We were doing 190 concerts a year.''
 &HT;    ``We were only human and, as so, we have human foibles,'' Yarrow
adds. ``But if the people only wanted to hear our old songs, we
would have stayed broken up.''
 &HT;    The three reunited in 1978 for an anti-nuclear benefit that
Yarrow helped organize at the Hollywood Bowl. And, while each
remains active in his or her individual concerns, they've been
working together periodically ever since.
 &HT;    ``We hadn't sung together in six years or so,'' Travers recalls.
``We realized that we'd missed each other, personally and
musically, and wanted to work together again. Simply put, when we
hit the stage, we seek the best of each other.''
 c.1999 Bonnie Siegler  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Bonnie Siegler is a Playa del Rey, Calif.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
