<HEADER>
A0766 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IAN-MCDIARMID-IN-STAR     05-10 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IAN-MCDIARMID-IN-STAR-WARS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' 
</HEADLINE>
 
 THE EMPEROR STRIKES BACK: IAN McDIARMID RETURNS TO THE WORLD OF (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Ian McDiarmid in a scene from ``Star
Wars: The Phantom Menace.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Pop quiz: Who are the three actors who play the same characters
in ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace'' that they did in the original
``Star Wars'' trilogy?
 &HT;    Anthony Daniels as C-3PO, of course. And Kenny Baker as R2D2,
that makes two. And then there's ... well, there's ... hmmm.
 &HT;    Time's up _ the third would be Ian McDiarmid, the veteran
Scottish actor and staple of the London stage who portrayed the
ghostly, enigmatic and aged Emperor Palpatine in ``Return of the
Jedi'' (1983). He'll reprise the role in George Lucas' ``Phantom
Menace'' when the film opens nationwide on May 19.
 &HT;    Though a repentant Darth Vader heaved the Emperor into the
cosmic void in ``Jedi,'' ``The Phantom Menace'' unfolds nearly 40
years before that event, setting the stage for the 50-something
McDiarmid's return engagement.
 &HT;    The actor had heard via the ``Star Wars'' grapevine that
Palpatine might be involved in the prequel, but only after months
of rumors were those reports confirmed.
 &HT;    ``George Lucas called,'' McDiarmid says, chatting over a bottle
of sparkling water at the bar of the Almeida Theatre, the
prestigious London theater for which he serves as co-artistic
director. ``I hadn't seen George in 15 years, but he asked me to
meet him at a hotel.
 &HT;    ``We got together,'' he continues, ``and I recall that he said,
`Would you like a drink?' I ordered a water, and then he said, `Do
you know anybody who might want to play the Emperor?' And I said,
`Funny you should ask.'
 &HT;    ``He said, `Well, great. Welcome back, if that's what you'd like
to do.'
 &HT;    ``That's how George is,'' McDiarmid says with a chuckle. ``He
gets an idea about something or somebody and follows it through.''
 &HT;    In the $115 million epic, McDiarmid plays the pivotal role of
Senator Palpatine, the principal representative of Queen Amidala
(Natalie Portman), the teen-age ruler of the beleaguered planet
Naboo.
 &HT;    Anyone who remembers Palpatine from ``Return of the Jedi'' won't
have much trouble figuring out that he's up to no good.
 &HT;    ``Palpatine is a politician, and that alone should tell you
volumes about him,'' McDiarmid says with a laugh, stroking his
salt-and-pepper goatee and looking less than evil in jeans and a
black-and-green plaid shirt.
 &HT;    ``I could stop right there, but will say that he's doing the
best he can for his queen and his planet,'' he adds. ``Like all
politicians, however, he is not entirely unaffected by matters of
self-interest.
 &HT;    ``Now, there I shall stop.''
 &HT;    McDiarmid, who is single and lives in the Notting Hill section
of London, knew many of his fellow actors prior to filming. Liam
Neeson (Qui-Gon Jinn) had starred as Oscar Wilde in the Almeida
production of ``The Judas Kiss,'' while Ewan McGregor (Obi-Wan
Kenobi) is the nephew of McDiarmid's old friend Denis Lawson, who
played the small role of pilot Wedge Antilles in the first three
``Star Wars'' adventures. Frank Oz (Yoda) directed McDiarmid in the
comedy ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels'' (1988).
 &HT;    He hadn't previously known Portman, with whom he shares most of
his scenes.
 &HT;    ``Poor Natalie had to deal with a lot,'' he says
sympathetically. ``She's got wonderful makeup and wonderful
costumes, many of them, but some of the costumes were very heavy.
And the headdresses were extremely heavy.
 &HT;    ``The headdresses were often very high up and revolved
backward,'' he says, ``but Natalie came through it wonderfully
well. She's a real professional, and at such a young age.''
 &HT;    ``Phantom Menace'' was an incredibly elaborate film to make,
with lavish sets, intricate costumes and literally thousands of
special effects that would be added digitally after the actors'
work was done.
 &HT;    Even after the shoot, McDiarmid wasn't done. For more than a
year afterward _ and as little as two months before the film's
release _ McDiarmid was still re-recording dialogue and even
shooting new scenes.
 &HT;    But McDiarmid says that Lucas kept everything on an even keel.
 &HT;    ``He's pretty much the same on the set as he is off it,'' the
actor says. ``He's relaxed, friendly and a bit shy. I liked that. I
like George.
 &HT;    ``He made it seem, despite the enormous size of the whole thing,
that we were a small group doing a movie,'' McDiarmid adds, ``and I
think that's how he's always worked. Terms like `blockbuster' and
`multibillion' are obviously there, but they're never present when
you're filming a scene.
 &HT;    ``You do feel that you're doing your job while surrounded by a
group of people who really know what they're doing, and that it's a
group led by a man who's on top of every detail,'' he says.
``George is, literally, physically and in every other way, in
charge.
 &HT;    ``There are no suits, there's no studio pressure _ there's just
George, and that allowed us to concentrate on the essence of the
film.''
 &HT;    Between stints McDiarmid found time to act in a BBC adaptation
of ``Great Expectations'' and in the upcoming feature film ``Sleepy
Hollow,'' directed by Tim Burton and starring Johnny Depp,
Christina Ricci and Christopher Walken. He also shepherded the
Almeida's revival of ``Plenty,'' which features Cate Blanchett and
opened on the West End in late April.
 &HT;    While he appreciates the opportunities and paydays that
television and film present _ his screen credits include
``Dragonslayer'' (1981), ``Gorky Park'' (1983) and ``Restoration''
(1995) _ theater is the medium closest to McDiarmid's heart. He's
starred in ``The Doctor's Dilemma,'' ``Volpone'' and ``Tartuffe,''
and for the Almeida he has directed ``Scenes from an Execution''
and an opera, ``Siren Song,'' among others.
 &HT;    ``I've been with the Almeida for 10 years,'' says McDiarmid, who
in October will star as Barabas in the company's production of
``The Jew of Malta.'' ``We've basically decided on plays, contacted
the artists and, by and large, they've said, `Count me in.'
 &HT;    ``We've been lucky,'' he says. ``We've expanded beyond our
little 300-seat theater here and are producing shows at other
theaters in London and around the world, including on Broadway.
 &HT;    ``We needed to scare ourselves, to refresh ourselves,'' he
concludes. ``And taking our work to more places and to more people
accomplishes that.''
 &HT;    McDiarmid's work will take a quantum leap with the release of
``Phantom Menace.'' Millions upon millions of people worldwide will
see him in action, and he'll be far more recognizable than he was
in ``Return of the Jedi.'' Even McDiarmid can only speculate about
the consequences.
 &HT;    ``On `Jedi' I had the anonymity of the makeup, and that's not
the case here,'' says the actor, who expects to appear in the
second and third episodes, though he hasn't officially signed to do
so. ``Whatever happens, I will just go on being me.
 &HT;    ``I'm not moving, I'll still run the Almeida and I really doubt
that anything will change too dramatically,'' he says. ``I like to
use the tube and to stop and shop, and I hope that doesn't
change.''
 &HT;    McDiarmid takes a final sip of water.
 &HT;    ``Come back to me in six months, when the film has been released
just about everywhere,'' he says. ``Then I'll tell you how things
are going.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
