<SLUG> BC-CHER-IN-TEA-WITH-MUSSOLINI-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHER AND CHER ALIKE: SHE'S BACK, ON SCREEN AND ON CD 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Cher in a scene from ``Tea With
Mussolini.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In Hollywood there are comebacks and then there are comebacks
... and then there's Cher.
 &HT;    In salvaging her career after the end of Sonny and Cher's 15
minutes of fame in the 1970s, in reinventing herself as a solo
singer and an Oscar-winning actress, the former Cherilyn Sarkisian
LaPierre had already earned a spot in the Comeback Hall of Fame.
 &HT;    But by the mid-1990s, as she moved into her 50s, the clock
seemed to have struck midnight once again. Her records weren't
selling, the long-delayed release of ``Faithful'' (1996) more or
less torpedoed her movie career and a series of infomercials had
made her into a late-night-television punchline.
 &HT;    There might not be anywhere to go but up, but no one was
expecting to hear much more from Cher.
 &HT;    Fast-forward: It's 1999, and on the eve of her 53rd birthday
Cher has a smash album with ``Believe,'' a multimillion selling
single of the same name _ No. 1 in 23 countries around the world _
and a hot-ticket summer concert tour. And she's receiving great
notices for her role in Franco Zeffirelli's ``Tea With Mussolini,''
opening nationwide throughout May and June.
 &HT;    ``See what happens when I take a big rest?'' she jokes. ``I'm
like John Travolta _ I come back big.''
 &HT;    In person she hides behind her dark, mile-long hair like some
kind of shield. Her voice is sweet and low, with a warm laugh and a
motherly nature that peppers her conversation with frequent
``honeys'' and ``sweeties.''
 &HT;    She's glamorous but approachable. Her fans regularly come up and
greet her by her first name _ not that they have a lot of choice _
and start conversations. The most common question, she says, is
``Where have you been for so long?''
 &HT;    It's a good question.
 &HT;    ``I designed houses, and what else did I do?'' she says
thoughtfully. ``I started a catalog company. I did some
infomercials, which I do regret.''
 &HT;    She pauses.
 &HT;    ``I just did stuff.''
 &HT;    She's still doing stuff _ it's just higher-profile stuff,
including her return to the big screen as American adventuress Elsa
Morganthal in ``Tea With Mussolini.''
 &HT;    Based on Zeffirelli's own childhood, the $14 million film
centers on a young boy raised in 1930s Italy by three eccentric
Englishwomen (Judi Dench, Joan Plowright and Maggie Smith). Elsa is
a former Ziegfeld dancer who deals in modern art and dallies in
free love.
 &HT;    ``I think of her like spice,'' the actress says. ``She yells and
screams and flirts. And then she leaves and changes and improves
herself.''
 &HT;    It's an offbeat, interesting role for a woman who won an Oscar
as Best Actress for ``Moonstruck'' (1987), but of late has had
difficulty finding parts that intrigued her, in large part because
of her age.
 &HT;    ``The last few years, I've realized that there aren't many movie
roles for me out there,'' she says matter-of-factly. ``I don't care
how good you look. Jack Nicholson now plays opposite Helen Hunt.
It's not like anyone wanted to cast me with Brad Pitt.
 &HT;    ``That's the way it is in Hollywood,'' she says with a shrug.
``If I've learned one thing over the years, it's that you can't
argue with the way things are. You can just do what you can do to
change your little spot.''
 &HT;    And often there is little that can be done. Since 1985, Cher has
suffered from the Epstein-Barr virus, a cause of infectious
mononucleosis and other energy-draining diseases.
 &HT;    ``There were times I was so sick that I thought I was going to
die,'' she says.
 &HT;    Then she laughs, as if to dispel any hint of despair.
 &HT;    ``Look, I've been working since I was 16 years old, and that's a
long time,'' she says. ``It's just tiring to be in the public eye
for that long. That's why I wanted to take off for awhile _ I need
a break from being Cher.''
 &HT;    She laughs again.
 &HT;    ``You know, it's a busy job being Cher,'' she jokes. ``Sometimes
it's even a pain in the a-- being her.''
 &HT;    Holistic herbal remedies, acupuncture and oxygen therapy have
helped her recover, she believes. Her youthful appearance is also
in part attributable to plastic surgery, which has generated rumors
of everything from cheek and eye work to reports that she has had
two ribs removed and her belly button reshaped.
 &HT;    ``It's no one's business,'' she says.
 &HT;    In the past she's admitted to having had her nose, breasts and
teeth reworked, but she won't comment on anything more. Well,
except those stories about her famous cheekbones.
 &HT;    ``I've had the same cheekbones since birth,'' she says firmly.
 &HT;    When she thinks about it, Cher adds, the tabloid fascination
with gossip and rumormongering infuriates her.
 &HT;    ``I think Hollywood is a much meaner-spirited place now than
when I started,'' she says. ``People are always looking for the
dirt.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to see pictures of Hugh Grant inside his bedroom
window or Liz Hurley with no makeup on,'' she adds angrily. ``I
don't want to say, `Oh God, she doesn't look good today.' It's
trash information. I don't need to bother my brain with it.''
 &HT;    For her own part, she insists that it doesn't matter. Even the
media coverage of her eulogy to her late ex-husband Sonny Bono
didn't faze her, she says.
 &HT;    ``I've never cared what they said about me,'' she says flatly.
 &HT;    On the other hand, there are benefits to being Cher,
opportunities which she's only too happy to take advantage of.
 &HT;    Most people celebrate reaching the half-century mark with a cake
and maybe a few presents. Cher's 50th birthday involved helicopter
landings, boats and a French chateau.
 &HT;    ``I was staying with a friend of mine on his boat in Cannes,''
she recalls. ``On my birthday, a friend of mine who has a chateau
gave this huge party and all these people were brought in.''
 &HT;    ``Brought in,'' of course, means flown in specially for the
occasion.
 &HT;    ``On helicopters,'' she says, laughing at the lavishness of it
all. ``It was the most jet-setty I ever get. I mean, I wanted to
stay home on my birthday, but there I was watching all these
helicopters landing on the lawn, and I thought, `This is so totally
cool.'
 &HT;    ``I thought, `If this is as bad as it gets at 50, it's not so
bad!'''
 &HT;    And actually, it's gotten better since then. The record, the hit
single, the tour and now the movie have all added up to a midlife
renaissance for Hollywood's comeback queen.
 &HT;    It's even brought her a new generation of fans, she reports _ no
surprise to one of the most fan-friendly stars around.
 &HT;    ``It seems to me that I give good vibes and I get them back,''
she says. ``People kind of instinctively think they like me. That's
the best part of being Cher.''
 &HT;    Of course, those fans are sometimes surprised that the person
they meet isn't the feather-encrusted, rhinestone-studded glamor
queen they've seen on the Oscars, the talk shows or the concert
stage.
 &HT;    ``I think people would be surprised to know that I'm very soft
in a certain way,'' she says. ``It's just that you can't be too
soft and survive in my world.
 &HT;    ``If you were too soft, you would just be crying all the time.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
