<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCY-LAWLESS-IN-XENA-WARRIOR-PRINCESS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WALK ON THE LAWLESS SIDE: A CHAT WITH THE STAR OF `XENA: WARRIOR
PRINCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Lucy Lawless in a scene from ``Xena:
Warrior Princess.'' 
 By MICHAEL LOGAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Appearances, as anyone who's ever ridden into an apparently
peaceful village sometime in the mist-shrouded past can attest, can
be deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Xena: Warrior Princess'' and its star, Lucy Lawless, who
has emerged as an unlikely feminist icon.
</P>
<P>
   Lawless has created one of the most imposing, strikingly
original looks in television history. You know the getup _ swinging
sword, leather toga, sexy breastplate and those butt-kicking,
high-heeled boots that send her already considerable height _
5-foot-10-inches _ into the Amazonian ozone. And then there's the
formidable, deeply bronzed bod and that impossibly thick mane of
Cher hair.
</P>
<P>
   But look beneath the surface, and you're in for a surprise.
Minus wig and warrior wardrobe, La Lawless is jaw-droppingly
delicate. She is slender, even slight, and when not covered in
head-to-toe Xena makeup she has a porcelain-white complexion even a
china doll might envy.
</P>
<P>
   The New Zealand-born cult heroine is also remarkably
down-to-earth, chummy and vulnerable _ like someone who could be
your next-door neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I am somebody's next-door neighbor,'' Lawless says over a
light lunch of pita bread, Middle Eastern dips and Diet Coke. ``We
all live next door to somebody. Being normal is no big deal where I
come from _ it's just not in our national character to get carried
away with ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get out of line in New Zealand, we're only too ready to
say, `Who the hell do you think you are?'''
</P>
<P>
   It took several seasons of ``Xena'' for Lawless to get
comfortable with her status as a female role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it felt like a burden, like a yoke I couldn't carry,
and I shunned it,'' she says. ``During our first season Ms.
magazine put me on its cover _ at the very time I was trapped in
the horror of being a role model. It was very disconcerting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But eventually I came to see it can be really pleasant, that
people aren't expecting more of me _ just that I be human.''
</P>
<P>
   Her own heroines, she adds, don't wear steel and leather.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm tempted to think of myself as successful, I think of
our housekeeper,'' the 31-year-old says. ``She's from El Salvador,
where her father was kidnapped and there were attempted kidnappings
of others in her family. She has endured so much pain, so much
hell, and yet she has still discovered the secret of joy _ her cup
is always half full.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at her and think, `Wow, now you are a truly successful
human being.'''
</P>
<P>
   If the actress is thinking more about home and family than she
used to, that's understandable. Lawless and her husband of one
year, ``Xena'' executive producer Rob Tapert, are expecting a baby
in October. But don't panic, fans _ a ``Xena'' spokesperson says
the pregnancy will be hidden ``creatively'' and won't affect
production in any way.
</P>
<P>
   The actress also has a 10-year-old daughter, Daisy, from her
marriage to computer expert Garth Lawless, whom she divorced three
years ago. Because ``Xena'' often takes her to the wilds of New
Zealand, Daisy lives with her father during the week and spends
weekends and school vacations with her mom and Tapert in their Los
Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The juggling isn't easy, but we make the best of it,'' Lawless
says. ``Garth is a hands-on, excellent father. We have a very
cooperative relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress intends to pursue movie work when ``Xena''
eventually ends its run, but insists that having a good marriage
and a large family matters more to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to choose, I'd go for family over Oscars any day,''
she says. ``If I didn't, I'd kick myself when I'm 80.''
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't always seen things that way, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an early age, I was very aware of my mortality and felt
pressured to do-do-do, achieve-achieve-achieve,'' she recalls. ``As
a Catholic kid, I was obsessed with the last part of `Hail, Mary' _
you know, `Holy Mary, Mother of God, pray for us sinners now and at
the hour of our death, Amen.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `Our death? What do you mean, death?' When you're
6, that's a hell of a concept. So I was always in a terrible
hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point came in 1996, when she fell off a horse while
performing a stunt for ``The Tonight Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I broke my pelvis in four places,'' Lawless recalls. ``The
best thing that came of that physical breakdown was that it made me
stop and put my fears in order. It made me realize what's really
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Another crisis overtook her last year, during an arduous,
six-episode ``Xena'' arc that was shot during bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in snow and rain and cold for months,'' she recalls,
``and I started to have what is called a neural association, where
you associate work with physical discomfort. My nonstop thought
that whole time was `I am in pain!'
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not bear to get up one more morning and put on that
yucky brown makeup one more time,'' she says. ``It got to the point
where I could not even speak about work at home or I would cringe _
which is a real problem when you're married to the producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``So then, by association, home became a bad thing. I was a
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Xena was rescued by ... Leeza Gibbons?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a really low point one morning, just mindlessly
flipping channels, when a Leeza infomercial caught my eye,''
Lawless says. ``I thought, `Hmm, what's Leeza have to tell me
today?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, she was selling tapes by (motivational guru) Tony
Robbins and I went `Oh, hell, why not? I've got to do something to
pull myself out of this.' So I swallowed my pride and bought some
self-help tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   To her surprise and delight, they worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I nipped it in the bud,'' Lawless says, ``before I lost
everything, including the respect of my colleagues and possibly my
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the secret was coming to terms with her own success, she
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tempting when you're in my position, with people tying
your bootlaces and holding an umbrella over your head when it's
hot, to think you are special,'' the actress explains. ``You can
start believing your own publicity and thinking you have feelings
other people can't possibly understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come to see that practicing appreciation and gratitude is
the way to health and happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   She's particularly appreciative of the unlikely circumstances
which brought her together with the American-born Tapert, who also
produces ``Hercules: The Legendary Journeys,'' the show that
introduced Xena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role landed in my lap because no American actress would
take it,'' Lawless says. ``Nobody wanted to miss the Hollywood
pilot season and go to an unknown, funny country to act on an
unproven show _ because at that point `Hercules' wasn't yet a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result,'' she concludes, ``I got two things I didn't
expect _ the role of a lifetime and a husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawless admits that her new mother-in-law wasn't expecting
someone like her, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always used to say to Rob, `Now, why don't you bring home
a nice girl like that Morgan Fairchild?'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Michael Logan is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Xena: Warrior Princess,''
consult the Universal Studios Website at www.universalstudios.com.
And don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0865 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-EUROPE-JOBLESS-REVI     05-10 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-EUROPE-JOBLESS-REVIEW-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 UNDATED: Wolfers said.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Europe, many displaced workers stay out of work longer, and
bad things happen when a large group of people stay out of the work
force for a long time. Lawrence Katz, a labor economist at Harvard,
says that reducing the stigma attached to joblessness has profound
effects on the labor market. In Sweden, which combined extremely
low joblessness with extremely generous welfare programs, someone
who got laid off used to be ashamed to admit it to his or her
neighbors. Now, with a new generation of workers less imbued with
that work ethic, much of that shame has evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   There are other negative effects as well. Workers who don't get
rehired fast also lose skills and, more importantly, connections.
Since most hiring is by word of mouth, people who don't know others
with jobs find it hard to get one themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The flaws of the welfare state are compounded by other forms of
government intervention, says Alan B. Krueger, an economist at
Princeton University. One important reason American workers get
hired at such surprising rates is that it's much easier to start
new businesses in the United States. In Austria, Krueger says,
someone who wants to open a pharmacy must get permission from the
other drugstores in town.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, it boils down to social choices. ``One
can say the Europeans have made a political decision that they are
unwilling to tolerate as much income inequality as in the United
States,'' Katz said. ``But equity comes at the cost of job
creation.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today, men in their prime working years are not faring much
worse in Europe or Japan than in the United States. But in America,
which excels at absorbing new workers, other groups like the young,
immigrants and women are faring much better. Now the U.S. economy
is absorbing workers with the least education and the fewest
skills, including ones who have been out of the work force for
years and written off as lost causes.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, choices made decades ago are preventing a similar
expansion in the work force. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
