<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0785 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-ANIMAL-CRUELTY-REVI     05-10 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ANIMAL-CRUELTY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAPSTICK ABUSE OF ANIMALS IN MOVIES: WHY IS IT ON THE RISE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the film ``There's Something About Mary,'' a small dog flies
out a window. In ``As Good as It Gets,'' a pooch is crammed down a
trash chute. In ``EdTV,'' a love scene culminates in Matthew
McConaughey falling on a cat. In ``Men in Black,'' an alien pug
confesses after it is mercilessly shaken. Even the preview for
``Idle Hands'' shows a cat being swung around by its tail.
</P>
<P>
   For cats, dogs and other animals, life in the movies is
beginning to appear less than glamorous. Indeed, at this historical
juncture of political correctness and feeling the pain of others,
pretending to hurt animals has become an intentional laugh-getter
in movies, television and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The ad campaign of Cyberian Outpost, an online shopping site,
features gerbils being fired from an artillery cannon into a wall.
(They were actually plastic.)
</P>
<P>
   The question arises, as President Clinton prepares to meet
Monday with experts on youth violence in the wake of the Colorado
killings, how positive an influence is all this animal abuse?
</P>
<P>
   Not very, worries Dr. Pamela Sicher, president of the Children's
Mental Health Alliance Foundation. ``Is this something that
desensitizes us to the meaning of hurting living things?'' she
said. ``At what point in children's lives can they actually discern
the meaning in this?''
</P>
<P>
   The animal bashing comes at a time when other movies like
``Babe'' depict other fauna in a sympathetic, if not adorable
manner that even the most ardent animal-rights activists applaud.
Virtually all the cinematic atrocities are, of course, staged.
Animal abuse is now a felony in 23 states. Advances in robotics and
computer imaging have made it possible to simulate just about
anything. Since 1980, after a horse was killed by a dynamite
explosion in ``Heaven's Gate,'' the Screen Actors Guild contract
has required that the American Humane Association vet any scripts
involving animals. Representatives visit film sets to insure that
even rats and spiders are not mistreated. A recent New Yorker
cartoon was on the mark: It showed a studio honcho proclaiming,
``OK. Just make sure no animals are harmed in the exploding-donkey
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   But why are there exploding donkey scenes? Mainly, it seems,
because people laugh at silly humor, and animal predicaments,
particularly painful ones, are part of that time-honored genre. Dr.
Alan Manevitz, a family psychiatrist at New York Presbyterian
Hospital, suggests that the apparent abuse represents a regression
to cartoon humor of yore. Three Stooges-style slapstick, which
relies on a dose of sadism, is no longer ``politically correct with
people,'' he says. Since people know the animals are not being hurt
_ and most filmmakers run an official disclaimer from the American
Humane Association in their credits _ animal slapstick is in.
</P>
<P>
   While the humane association ignores the film content, other
groups have focused on the message. The Ark Trust, which monitors
entertainment and media for their depictions of animals, will today
televise its Genesis Awards. Among the honorees is an episode of
``Spin City,'' in which Michael J. Fox's character refuses to kill
a fawn. It is also handing out less laudatory ``Foe-Paw'' awards,
one of which will go to Outpost for its glib depiction of gerbils.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Wyler, president of the trust, said such scenes are no
laughing matter. ``They sort of give legitimacy to the acts,'' Ms.
Wyler said. ``It's a potential source of destructive ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights activists are fond of pointing to a study by the
Federal Bureau of Investigation that links many serial killers to
animal abuse. As a youth, Jeffrey L. Dahmer stole his neighbor's
pets and practiced taxidermy on them, keeping skulls in his yard.
Albert DeSalvo, the ``Boston Strangler,'' trapped dogs and cats in
orange crates and shot arrows through the boxes. Before Russell
Eugene Weston Jr. was charged with killing two policemen in the
U.S. Capitol last year, he reportedly shot 16 of his grandmother's
cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every one of these kids who ends up shooting up the
school yard has a history of animal abuse,'' said Kenneth Shapiro,
executive director of Psychologists for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals.
</P>
<P>
   The link between pretend violence on the screen and real
behavior is fuzzier. But if Manevitz is right that the appeal of
the humor is a throwback to cartoons, there seem to be grounds for
worry: A study by George Gerbner at the University of
Pennsylvania's Annenberg School for Communication found that cruel
images of animals outnumbered positive ones 12 to 1 in Saturday
morning cartoons. As to the question whether watching a violent act
has a cathartic effect on viewers _ or is more likely to spur them
to imitate it _ research has pointed toward imitation, Shapiro
said.
</P>
<P>
   And younger children surely see the famous scene in Mel Brooks'
``Blazing Saddles,'' where Alex Karras knocks out a horse with a
single punch, differently than most adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you trivialize the meaning of hurting living things, you're
doing something to the pathways by which children develop
appropriate restraints and constraints on their behavior,'' said
Sicher. ``You want them to be horrified by cruelty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
