 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2541 - May 10, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. UNDER THE GUN High-profile gun incidents - from the attempted
assassinations of President Ronald Reagan and Pope John Paul II to
school shootings such as those in Jonesboro, Arkansas and
Littleton, Colorado - provide fuel for the political debate. But
now the gun industry is sweating a new development. Frustrated by
35,000 gun-related deaths per year, gun-control proponents and
mayors from around the United States opened a potent new front :
the courts. By James Bandler. From The Boston Globe Magazine.
Full-length (4,700 words) + edited article available.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
WHEN CHILDREN KILL In the wake of the shootings at Columbine High
School in the United States, psychiatrists say it is the fragile
children - not the sturdy ones - who are most likely to ``break''
in dramatic ways, according to a growing number of ``psychological
autopsy'' studies of youthful suicides, and from less formal
studies of adolescents who have committed murders. At the same
time, other studies have shown that the turbulence, pathology and
confusion considered ``normal'' in adolescence are, in fact, far
from typical. By Erica Goode. New York Times Science Times. 1,500
words.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE GREAT APE MASSACRE Serving a growing market for ``bush
meat,'' hunters are wiping out chimps and gorillas. Because the DNA
of chimpanzees is 98,5 per cent the same as that of humans, some
animal-rights advocates say that eating them is ``98,5 per cent
cannibalism.'' By Donald G. McNeil Jr. From The New York Times
Magazine. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   4. CHRONOBIOLOGY AND SLEEP Modern man sleeps a fifth less than
he did a century ago and society is paying a high price.
Researchers who study body rhythms are finding that lack of sleep
is linked to disease and depression as well as to a disturbing rise
in transportation and industrial accidents. While few people in a
performance-oriented society seem to find time to sleep more,
partial solutions range from better work scheduling to the
imaginative application of artificial light. By Andreas Weber. From
GEO Magazine. 2,500 words. English translation available.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. WINE MAKING Blended wines, such as those cheerfully thrown
together by Californians, may turn out to be top-notch, but to a
Frenchman they will lack something special - ``terroir.'' This is a
vineyard's particular combination of dirt, rock and exposure to
sunlight that leaves an indelible mark on wine. Something,
naturally, French vintners have always known, but scientists are
just beginning to understand. By Robert Kunzig. 950 words. From
Discover Magazine.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
NOVEL MOLECULE DISCOVERY MIGHT CREATE INSULIN PILL Diabetics may
some day take a rain-forest fungus in a pill to treat their
disease, according to pharmaceutical corporation researchers. By
Dan Vergano. From Medical Tribune News Service. 500 words.
________________________________________________________ 7. FROM
NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain. Embargo : 19h00 BST
Wednesday May 12, 1999.)
</P>
