<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-MOUSE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More than art that works, it's a mouse-terpiece!
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Pity, for a moment, the abuses suffered by your
garden-variety computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Manhandled and squeezed by uncaring palms. Forced to run laps
around the mouse pad or crawl with exacting precision on an Excel
spreadsheet. Retrieved with a pull of the tail when it is
accidentally shooed off the desk by a clumsy hand. Often forced to
live a bland white-beige existence.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Miller, a University of Texas graduate and former Power
Computing Corp. salesman, is doing something about the unjust life
of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   He and his partner Reid Dickson founded Custom Mouse Co., a
small operation they run from Miller's apartment. There, they make
mice with personality _ custom-designed mechanisms with color, odd
shapes and designs.
</P>
<P>
   Custom Mouse Co. has its roots in Dickson's garage, where the
two first took apart broken mice and experimented with black
leather, and later, paints and silk-screen logos. But not just any
paints _ specialty painting and silk-screen companies that work
with Custom Mouse do a three-layer paint job on the mice that
yields what you'd find on a Lexus or a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a colorful collection of mice that look ready for
the race track.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Dickson buy mice from a supplier, then take custom
orders from companies, hoping that instead of the usual coffee mug
or key chain, companies in today's computer age will give away mice
with their company logos as promotions.
</P>
<P>
   In bulk, the mice run about $36 a piece _ about three times the
cost of a typical bargain-basement mouse. Custom Mouse has only
worked with a few clients so far, including Falcon Imaging
Solutions, but Miller hopes the company will make a splash this
year at a trade expo for the promotion industry in August.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful mice may become a booming industry _ the popularity of
Apple Computer's iMac proved there's a market for more colorful
computer goods. Miller said the small variety of computer colors in
the PC world led to his partner's idea for the company. He claims
he hasn't heard of any other company doing similar work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
