<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0865 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN11-C     05-10 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K COMMENTARY: Work and leisure intermingling
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the school year winding down and the temperatures
warming up, millions of Americans are pulling out the travel
brochures to plan their summer vacation. In droves, we'll be
heading for beaches, mountains and amusement parks for a little
relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   But the simple act of relaxing is getting more complicated as
the lines blur between work and leisure. With cellular phones,
laptop computers and beepers bringing us updates from the office, a
vacation day at the beach has become less of, well, a day at the
beach. At the same time, leisure is creeping into our jobs, with
business conventions often turning into enjoyable outings and
baseball games serving as ``networking'' time with clients.
</P>
<P>
   With the distinctions between work and fun getting less clear,
sociologists, economists and other workplace observers are arguing
about the future of leisure. Some think Americans will work longer
hours in the next century, while others say we are entering a
golden age of relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   In general, this past century has brought us more fun and less
drudgery. In 1900, workers typically toiled 10 hours a day, six
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Leisure took a leap forward in 1938 when Congress passed the
Fair Labor and Standards Act to set 40 hours as the legal workweek.
Two-week vacations became common in the post-World War II era.
</P>
<P>
   Today, slightly more than two-thirds of U.S. workers put in 40
hours or more on the job each week. In other words, for the great
majority of us, the workweek is no shorter than it was 60 years
ago. With all of the increases in productivity since then, why
haven't we gained more leisure time?
</P>
<P>
   Some economists say the workweek has not shrunk because most
Americans prefer to increase their buying power rather than expand
their relaxation time. Indeed, union leaders typically find that
workers would much rather fight for higher wages than demand
shorter hours. By sticking to a 40-hour week, we have pushed our
affluence to record heights, with home ownership rates at the
highest level in history and the average new home size growing to
twice what it was in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it time to say enough already? The majority of us have
enough income for basics, such as food, clothing, shelter and
transportation; aren't we ready to spend more time enjoying life?
</P>
<P>
   Some sociologists argue that we already are doing just that,
even though it appears we are ``working'' long hours. For example,
we may still be sitting at our desks for 40 hours, but we are
spending much of that time making personal phone calls, playing
computer games and surfing the Internet. Web site operators say the
peak surfing time is between 11 a.m. and 2 p.m. because so many
workers are entertaining themselves online.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of lunch-hour fun, more and more workers are
finding that the food in the cafeteria is _ dare we say it _ good.
Many employers are making sure their workers' breaks are filled
with Dove Bars and Starbucks coffee. Going to work in a suburban
office park can mean outdoor tables and an in-house gym.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, millions of Americans are not enjoying themselves as
they mine coal, clean toilets or pour asphalt. For them, work
remains nothing but work. But for the majority, the hours spent on
the job are getting more enjoyable because of changes that involve
air conditioning, computers and lunchroom microwave ovens.
</P>
<P>
   The issue in the new century may not be whether we will have
more leisure time or more work, but whether we will be able to tell
the difference.
</P>
<P>
   This is a weekly report by Atlanta Constitution editorial writer
Marilyn Geewax on issues raised by the coming of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
