<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0867 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIFI11-COX     05-10 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIFI11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surveying sound systems
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sound reproduction for popular enjoyment has come a long way
since World War II, especially for people who can remember the
1940s along with 78 rpm records, record players and the tinny,
sometimes muddy, sounds that came from a single speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Today the options are numerous, from the head-rattling bass
systems youths install in cars to ``Star Wars'' banks of speakers
in family rooms. And the choices of musical sources now include
records, tapes, video cable, videotapes, satellite and DVD, the
latest technology for sharp video and digital-quality music.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only yesterday that the ideal for serious music
listeners was ``concert hall sound,'' or sound roughly equivalent
to what you might hear in an auditorium or theater.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, we hear things never heard in concert halls _
sound bombardment from all directions, straight from the movie
theater courtesy of George Lucas and his inventive colleagues. And
the sound sources that get amplified range from records to tapes to
cable to the last word in DVD, a digital brew of pictures and
startling audio.
</P>
<P>
   The simulation of movie theater sound, sometimes called surround
sound, has become practically the heart of the audio business these
days, with aural thrill seekers shelling out up to $10,000 and more
for powerful equipment.
</P>
<P>
   If you can bear the thought of not being on the frontier,
however, experts like Tim Hurd of HiFi Buys in Atlanta, say you can
get good sound for considerably less, perhaps in the neighborhood
of $1,000 _ assuming you are starting from ground zero. A key is
that advanced electronics now allow for entertaining sound
production from smaller packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are quality speakers in a compact system that would be
goo for people getting their start in modern sound,'' Hurd said.
</P>
<P>
   Most people don't start from the beginning, however. Nearly all
music fans have at least a pair of quality speakers that are
capable of decent high- and mid-range sound reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   In launching my personal venture into surround sound, I was able
to start with a couple of DCM TimeWindow floor speakers that I've
had for nearly 20 years but still give good wide-range performance.
</P>
<P>
   The other components needed, in addition to the speakers,
include a well-engineered receiver such as a Kenwood Dolby Digital
model, available for about $400. A receiver is a combination tuner,
usually AM and FM, as well as an amplifier to drive the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolby Digital is a special kind of amplifier, produced by
various companies including Sony, Denon, Yamaha and others. What
makes it special is that it takes clear, accurate digital programs
from sources such as CD, certain tapes, cable or others, then
splits them into six distinct signals for the individual speakers
so the final combination of sounds envelopes the listener.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with video by way of tape or DVD, the sound can cause
the listener to ``hear'' a helicopter circling, or a twig crack
behind you, doing it so realistically that sometimes you can't help
but turn and look.
</P>
<P>
   It is a technology that can augment the action of certain movies
or give an aura of realism to programmatic music.
</P>
<P>
   DVDs or digital versatile (or ``video'' depending on who is
defining) discs provide pictures twice as clear as VHS tapes, with
CD-quality sound. This technology is so popular that stores have
trouble keeping up with demand, even at $300 and more per machine.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sophisticated receiver, with the power to
assign sounds to individual speakers, the equipment package also
must include the right speakers. The ideal system consists of two
main speakers capable of good mid-tones and highly directional high
notes, as well as a front-center speaker to fill in and two rear
speakers also capable of a range of sounds.
</P>
<P>
   A package of speakers that fit into a system in the $1,000 range
could include Mirage AVS-200 speakers and a Mirage AVS-100 center
speaker, all designed to carry out special, complementary
assignments in the Dolby system. The small size of these speakers,
about 7 inches by 5 inches and 4 inches deep, makes them easy to
place around a modest-sized room.
</P>
<P>
   And a special feature of the modern sound system in the
surround-sound format is the sixth speaker, called a subwoofer,
that specializes in the bass or lowest sounds. While the other
speakers are powered by the receiver or main amplifier, the
subwoofer typically has its own amplifier and separate power
source. It picks up the bass signal from the receiver but draws its
power from its own electrical outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bass signals consume high amounts of power, sometimes
as much as 80 percent of the power output of the receiver, the use
of a subwoofer contributes to better overall sound by relieving the
receiver of the power-consuming bass chore. Freed of that workload,
the receiver is able to devote its full power to the production of
quality mid-tones and high notes. In the sound system for $1,000,
the subwoofer has only an 8-inch speaker but also includes a
100-watt amplifier.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bass sound is nondirectional, subwoofers can be placed
virtually anywhere in the listening room. But the bigger the room,
the more bass response that is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to augment this sound in a larger room is simply to
purchase a larger subwoofer,'' said Hurd of HiFi Buys.
</P>
<P>
   For listeners willing to forgo the surround sound, for a price
within the $1,000 or so range, the floor-standing speakers by
makers like Klipsch can produce very lifelike sounds that harken
back to the concert hall ideal favored by many fans of classical
music.
</P>
<P>
   Popular pairs of Klipsch speakers, with their distinctive horn
designs, are available from $650 to $1,500. Boston Acoustics,
Mirage and others produce their own floor speakers in roughly the
same price range, including some higher. Surround sound or not,
however, the only true test of personal satisfaction is to hear the
ensembles of speakers, so a visit to the dealer is highly
recommended. It's a very pleasurable assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
