<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NETWATCHER: NPR missing boat on online shopping
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memo to National Public Radio: Want to raise money? Think about
online shopping.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, NPR ``Weekend Edition'' anchor Scott Simon read
aloud from a children's book called ``Polka Bats and Octopus
Slacks'' by Calef Brown. Many listeners were charmed by the offbeat
nonsense poems and logged on to Amazon.com to order one or more
copies of the book for the little ones in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But as it happened, Amazon underestimated just how many people
listen to NPR. There was a sudden flurry of requests for what was a
relatively obscure children's book. My friend Janet, who wanted
three copies, received a note from Amazon, sadly informing her
there was a ``surprise sellout.'' This is not an isolated case.
Another friend tried to order a CD featured on NPR, only to be told
of a similar ``sudden sellout.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprise? Oh please. Let's think about this for a minute, shall
we?
</P>
<P>
   It would seem to me that if you are Amazon.com and have
experienced several ``surprise sellouts,'' this might be something
you would want to look into. You might find out either from your
own internal reconnaissance or from readers like the one from
Youngstown, Ohio, who posted a note on the ``Polka Bats'' page
telling fellow book lovers that the reason the book was sold out
was because it had been featured on NPR.
</P>
<P>
   NPR is woefully underrepresented on the Web. I recently spent
two or three weeks searching on and off for a book I heard featured
on ``Weekend Edition.'' This was particularly rough since I could
remember only one word of the title.
</P>
<P>
   I finally found the book by searching through a long list of NPR
programs and trying to remember exactly which Saturday it was that
I heard the review. Clearly, there has to be a better way to
capture folks like Janet and myself, who are referred to in the
retail industry as ``motivated buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Major media organizations like CNN and even online-only
publications like Salon have deals with Barnes &AMP; Noble. Visitors to
each site are directed to Barnes &AMP; Noble to purchase books and
music featured on the sites. NPR has something of a relationship
with Borders online and offline bookstores to sell feature books
and CDs mentioned on its programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the list of books in Borders' ``Heard on NPR'' Web page is
painfully short, doesn't tell you much about the books and does not
include the beloved ``Polka Bats'' book.
</P>
<P>
   National Public Radio, home to such popular programs as ``All
Things Considered,'' ``Fresh Air,'' ``Car Talk'' and ``Prairie Home
Companion,'' boasts an upscale, literate and educated audience.
These are the same people analysts say are most likely to have
computer access and engage in online shopping. Pointing people to a
Web site where they can buy these books, CDs and other NPR-related
items seems like a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of NPR's subject matter and its upscale,
computer-savvy audience is an e-commerce bonanza waiting to happen.
Borders.com, which seems to have some relationship with NPR, should
work to get more and more featured materials on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   For an online bookseller running a distant third to Amazon and
Barnes &AMP; Noble, Borders.com has a great opportunity to drive
traffic, build out its brand and establish itself as the
``do-gooder'' shopping site that supports the noble cause of
National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the subject of underwriting. Anyone who has
had their favorite NPR programs interrupted by the sounds of
ringing phones and pleas for pledges knows that NPR is
listener-supported radio. There is no advertising. So maybe instead
of interrupting my drive-time commute to ask for a donation, why
not encourage me to go to a Web site and buy something?
</P>
<P>
   All or part of the proceeds could go to NPR. If these sudden
sellouts of books and CDs mentioned on NPR say anything about NPR
listeners, it says this is an audience that uses the Internet to
buy books and music. NPR's television counterpart, the Public
Broadcasting Service, has its own online store at shop.pbs.org. All
proceeds from books and videos sold on the site go to support
public television. Why not shop.npr.org?
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is simple: Organizations that need money a lot
less than NPR are using online shopping to increase brand
awareness, drive traffic and make money. NPR listeners will spend
the time and the money online purchasing books, CDs and other
materials mentioned on its programs. If there's any organization
that needs to get deeply into electronic commerce, it's National
Public Radio. And if there's anybody who needs to be thinking about
funding NPR, it would be the online book and music retailers who
are, or could be, supported in part by NPR listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
