<HEADER>
A0873 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOGAME-VIOLENCE11-     05-10 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAME-VIOLENCE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gallaga: It's not the games kids play, but how
 &HT;    By Omar Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A few nights ago, I went to Blazer Laser Tag,
cashed a few dollars and began pumping quarters into an arcade
shooting game. The premise is surviving a haunted funhouse _ you
shoot monsters, ghosts and zombies with a shotgun that you hold in
your hands. When you run out of bullets, you reload by pumping the
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   I played for about 20 minutes, losing myself in a noisy, bloody
fantasy. I shot zombies' heads off, blew away flying insects and
tore through the flesh of relentless ghouls. When it was over, my
finger exhausted from firing several thousand rounds of imaginary
ammunition, I put the gun back _ not because the thrill was gone,
but because I'd run out of quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my enthusiasm for game technology _ I'm quick to buy a
new graphics card or invest in more computer memory to play the
latest titles _ I've found myself for the first time ever agreeing
with parents and industry critics.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the games are too violent.
</P>
<P>
   A new University of Texas study, however, shows that while some
video games may make kids more aggressive, it may not be due to
their violent content.
</P>
<P>
   I've been thinking a lot of about video game violence lately,
not just as a reporter covering the criticism of the game industry
that followed the Columbine High School shootings, but as a
longtime gamer who grew up on Asteroids and Missile Command.
</P>
<P>
   I've watched with a mixture of horror and fascination as the
games I play have grown more extreme in their presentation _ as
graphics and sound have improved, the games have become more
involving experiences. The blocky graphics of one of the first
shoot-out games, The Castle of Dr. Wolfenstein, have given way to
the bloody, nightmare corridors of Requiem: Avenging Angel. In that
game, bloody, naked torsos jut out from the walls of an imaginary
hell, screams echoing through the computer's speakers.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair to the game industry, the research that's been done
so far suggests that games themselves are no more responsible for
Columbine than the Beatles were responsible for Charles Manson's
killings.
</P>
<P>
   And hard-core gamers are notoriously protective of their world,
a secret land of cheat codes, garish game magazines and fickle
tastes. Gamers will defend Quake and Duke Nuke 'Em, pointing out
that they've never killed anyone _ millions of other players
haven't gone on similar rampages.
</P>
<P>
   Video games, whether gamers like it or not, are part of today's
culture. Game magazines feature slick promos for how extreme and
twisted a game can be. Mortal Kombat's success had less to do with
great game play than its ``Can you top this?'' presentation of
fatalities. Death, in the world of many games, is not only
necessary _ it's cool.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a different idea: What if the level of violence in
video games doesn't matter at all in nurturing aggressiveness in
children?
</P>
<P>
   That's what a new study by a UT doctoral candidate suggests. A
dissertation by Michael Brooks with help from a colleague, Chuck
McVey, suggests that frustration _ how difficult a game is _
contributes more to a child player's aggressiveness than the
violent content in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the effects of frequent video violence game play
over a long period of time, but in the short term, we found that
frustration was significantly correlated with negative emotions in
general,'' Brooks said. ``The kids who played and got frustrated
got irritable and upset.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the study indicates, a particularly rough game of
Tetris might make your child more upset than blasting aliens with a
chain gun in Quake II.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' study of 120 sixth- and seventh-grade students also
suggests that to kids, most video games are less realistic than TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``By saying video games themselves contribute significantly to
aggressive behavior oversimplifies a very complex phenomenon,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   More research is still being done _ UT's Center for Research on
the Influences of Television on Children will release the results
of a study on games later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Brooks and his counterparts at the UT center agree:
Parents need to be vigilant about what their kids are up to. That
goes beyond buying games based simply on ratings. That goes beyond
getting rid of the games that merely sound bad or look dangerous.
Understanding the games kids play is key to understanding what, if
any, effect violent video game have on kids. Parents should pick up
a game pad and find out for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Gamers are vigilant about defending their turf, but I've never
known one to refuse some multiplayer gaming with mom or dad.
</P>
<P>
   Gallaga writes for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
