<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0882 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-MOUSE11-COX     05-10 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-MOUSE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More than art that works, it's a mouse-terpiece!
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Pity, for a moment, the abuses suffered by your
garden-variety computer mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Manhandled and squeezed by uncaring palms. Forced to run laps
around the mouse pad or crawl with exacting precision on an Excel
spreadsheet. Retrieved with a pull of the tail when it is
accidentally shooed off the desk by a clumsy hand. Often forced to
live a bland white-beige existence.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Miller, a University of Texas graduate and former Power
Computing Corp. salesman, is doing something about the unjust life
of the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   He and his partner Reid Dickson founded Custom Mouse Co., a
small operation they run from Miller's apartment. There, they make
mice with personality _ custom-designed mechanisms with color, odd
shapes and designs.
</P>
<P>
   Custom Mouse Co. has its roots in Dickson's garage, where the
two first took apart broken mice and experimented with black
leather, and later, paints and silk-screen logos. But not just any
paints _ specialty painting and silk-screen companies that work
with Custom Mouse do a three-layer paint job on the mice that
yields what you'd find on a Lexus or a BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a colorful collection of mice that look ready for
the race track.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Dickson buy mice from a supplier, then take custom
orders from companies, hoping that instead of the usual coffee mug
or key chain, companies in today's computer age will give away mice
with their company logos as promotions.
</P>
<P>
   In bulk, the mice run about $36 a piece _ about three times the
cost of a typical bargain-basement mouse. Custom Mouse has only
worked with a few clients so far, including Falcon Imaging
Solutions, but Miller hopes the company will make a splash this
year at a trade expo for the promotion industry in August.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful mice may become a booming industry _ the popularity of
Apple Computer's iMac proved there's a market for more colorful
computer goods. Miller said the small variety of computer colors in
the PC world led to his partner's idea for the company. He claims
he hasn't heard of any other company doing similar work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0883 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIFI11-COX     05-10 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIFI11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surveying sound systems
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sound reproduction for popular enjoyment has come a long way
since World War II, especially for people who can remember the
1940s along with 78 rpm records, record players and the tinny,
sometimes muddy, sounds that came from a single speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Today the options are numerous, from the head-rattling bass
systems youths install in cars to ``Star Wars'' banks of speakers
in family rooms. And the choices of musical sources now include
records, tapes, video cable, videotapes, satellite and DVD, the
latest technology for sharp video and digital-quality music.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like only yesterday that the ideal for serious music
listeners was ``concert hall sound,'' or sound roughly equivalent
to what you might hear in an auditorium or theater.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, we hear things never heard in concert halls _
sound bombardment from all directions, straight from the movie
theater courtesy of George Lucas and his inventive colleagues. And
the sound sources that get amplified range from records to tapes to
cable to the last word in DVD, a digital brew of pictures and
startling audio.
</P>
<P>
   The simulation of movie theater sound, sometimes called surround
sound, has become practically the heart of the audio business these
days, with aural thrill seekers shelling out up to $10,000 and more
for powerful equipment.
</P>
<P>
   If you can bear the thought of not being on the frontier,
however, experts like Tim Hurd of HiFi Buys in Atlanta, say you can
get good sound for considerably less, perhaps in the neighborhood
of $1,000 _ assuming you are starting from ground zero. A key is
that advanced electronics now allow for entertaining sound
production from smaller packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are quality speakers in a compact system that would be
good for people getting their start in modern sound,'' Hurd said.
</P>
<P>
   Most people don't start from the beginning, however. Nearly all
music fans have at least a pair of quality speakers that are
capable of decent high- and mid-range sound reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   In launching my personal venture into surround sound, I was able
to start with a couple of DCM TimeWindow floor speakers that I've
had for nearly 20 years but still give good wide-range performance.
</P>
<P>
   The other components needed, in addition to the speakers,
include a well-engineered receiver such as a Kenwood Dolby Digital
model, available for about $400. A receiver is a combination tuner,
usually AM and FM, as well as an amplifier to drive the speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolby Digital is a special kind of amplifier, produced by
various companies including Sony, Denon, Yamaha and others. What
makes it special is that it takes clear, accurate digital programs
from sources such as CD, certain tapes, cable or others, then
splits them into six distinct signals for the individual speakers
so the final combination of sounds envelopes the listener.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with video by way of tape or DVD, the sound can cause
the listener to ``hear'' a helicopter circling, or a twig crack
behind you, doing it so realistically that sometimes you can't help
but turn and look.
</P>
<P>
   It is a technology that can augment the action of certain movies
or give an aura of realism to programmatic music.
</P>
<P>
   DVDs or digital versatile (or ``video'' depending on who is
defining) discs provide pictures twice as clear as VHS tapes, with
CD-quality sound. This technology is so popular that stores have
trouble keeping up with demand, even at $300 and more per machine.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sophisticated receiver, with the power to
assign sounds to individual speakers, the equipment package also
must include the right speakers. The ideal system consists of two
main speakers capable of good mid-tones and highly directional high
notes, as well as a front-center speaker to fill in and two rear
speakers also capable of a range of sounds.
</P>
<P>
   A package of speakers that fit into a system in the $1,000 range
could include Mirage AVS-200 speakers and a Mirage AVS-100 center
speaker, all designed to carry out special, complementary
assignments in the Dolby system. The small size of these speakers,
about 7 inches by 5 inches and 4 inches deep, makes them easy to
place around a modest-sized room.
</P>
<P>
   And a special feature of the modern sound system in the
surround-sound format is the sixth speaker, called a subwoofer,
that specializes in the bass or lowest sounds. While the other
speakers are powered by the receiver or main amplifier, the
subwoofer typically has its own amplifier and separate power
source. It picks up the bass signal from the receiver but draws its
power from its own electrical outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bass signals consume high amounts of power, sometimes
as much as 80 percent of the power output of the receiver, the use
of a subwoofer contributes to better overall sound by relieving the
receiver of the power-consuming bass chore. Freed of that workload,
the receiver is able to devote its full power to the production of
quality mid-tones and high notes. In the sound system for $1,000,
the subwoofer has only an 8-inch speaker but also includes a
100-watt amplifier.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bass sound is nondirectional, subwoofers can be placed
virtually anywhere in the listening room. But the bigger the room,
the more bass response that is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to augment this sound in a larger room is simply to
purchase a larger subwoofer,'' said Hurd of HiFi Buys.
</P>
<P>
   For listeners willing to forgo the surround sound, for a price
within the $1,000 or so range, the floor-standing speakers by
makers like Klipsch can produce very lifelike sounds that harken
back to the concert hall ideal favored by many fans of classical
music.
</P>
<P>
   Popular pairs of Klipsch speakers, with their distinctive horn
designs, are available from $650 to $1,500. Boston Acoustics,
Mirage and others produce their own floor speakers in roughly the
same price range, including some higher. Surround sound or not,
however, the only true test of personal satisfaction is to hear the
ensembles of speakers, so a visit to the dealer is highly
recommended. It's a very pleasurable assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0884 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN11-     05-10 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Fight for communications dollars is on
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T buys control of MediaOne, promises to provide competitive
local phone service. MediaOne, with access to the deep pockets of
AT&AMP;T, suddenly takes on the phone company to get Internet service
customers. Microsoft, yes Microsoft, a new player in
communications, steps in with software to push more entertainment
and information through your video cable.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sight to delight the eyes of federal Judge Harold Greene.
He's the bold Washington jurist who put muscle in the plan 15 years
ago to break up the monopoly of Ma Bell and usher in the era of
free-for-all competition in communications.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened since then, partly because of the new
atmosphere, has been the growth of wireless telephone
communication, lively rate competition in long-distance phone
service and the emergence of the Internet, the hottest advance in
communications history.
</P>
<P>
   But old Judge Greene, casting a sharp legal eye on this scene,
might very well see some reason for concern.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, AT&AMP;T, right before our eyes, is regaining much of
the shape and configuration that alarmed regulators and federal
trustbusters a generation ago. Moreover, we have the element of
Microsoft, already on trial on charges of being anticompetitive in
the way it uses its software dominance to squeeze out rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In a $5 billion deal with AT&AMP;T, Microsoft signed agreements that
may lead to AT&AMP;T adopting set-top boxes engineered by Microsoft,
blending Windows and WebTV technology to provide TV sets that also
act like computers.
</P>
<P>
   What Microsoft may hope to gain from its $5 billion investment
in AT&AMP;T is nothing less than a running start in the race to
dominate the cable box business. That would open a whole new
frontier for the company that already dominates computer operating
systems.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, as it has done for a long time, said last week it hopes to
use its telephone expertise and new cable properties to develop
one-stop communications services for consumers. These services
could include cable television, high-speed Internet connections and
an array of telephone services.
</P>
<P>
   With its power potentially to reach 60 percent of the national
market, more than any other single-stop provider of communications
services, AT&AMP;T raises a threat of industry domination once again,
in the eyes of consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, AT&AMP;T argues that it can bring competition, for the
first time ever, in the local phone market and thus give consumers
a leg up on monthly communications costs.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the cable technology AT&AMP;T is hoping to provide may
put an end to the need to maintain separate phone lines for
conversations and for computers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, industry people concede that AT&AMP;T can provide the cable
business, for the first time, real expertise in telephone
technology, thus unifying the media for the benefit of all
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   However, some consumer advocates, like Mark Cooper of the
Consumer Federation of America, say the individual consumer could
lose in the huge bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Said Cooper:
</P>
<P>
   ``The costs (of the AT&AMP;T acquisition of MediaOne) are humongous
in terms of the anticompetitive effects on cable and broadband
services, and the benefits of local phone competition are
minuscule.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the AT&AMP;T words about competition are mere buzzwords will
be debated for some time among regulators, local and federal, in
the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, local phone companies like BellSouth will be fighting
the proposed merger on one front, and at the same time redoubling
efforts to upgrade their own systems to provide comprehensive
one-stop services of their own. That's a do-or-die mission for
them.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months both the local phone companies and AT&AMP;T
will be relying, to some degree, on their brand names to persuade
the public to look their way for a successful single retail
communications window.
</P>
<P>
   Each needs to be wary. It has been nearly a generation since
AT&AMP;T was truly Ma Bell, the trusted one-stop phone company. For
many young consumers AT&AMP;T may be just another phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Though BellSouth can take some pride in the local reputation for
reliability of its phone systems, the public must get used to the
idea of the phone company as provider of cablelike TV and Internet
service.
</P>
<P>
   We, as consumers, have a big task ahead in sorting through the
blizzard of ``nice deals'' that will be fired our way from a
platoon of bidders for our communications dollars.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be dull, this new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
