<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Palm V sticks with basic design, improves screen and software
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's expensive at $430, but the Palm V represents a big
improvement over earlier models of this hand-held computer.
</P>
<P>
   For Mac users, what's most important is that manufacturer 3Com
has finally got the PalmPilot's backup and synchronizing software
right for their platform.
</P>
<P>
   The company has successfully converted Apple Computer's old
Organizer software into a new release called MacPac 2.0. It's a
reliable and sophisticated personal information manager.
</P>
<P>
   But MacPac is no longer the only choice. Several other personal
information managers, such as Consultant and BrainForest, are also
offering versions for the Mac PalmPilot. That makes the PalmPilot
the only hand-held alternative for Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   Software is just the beginning of the improvements for Palm V.
There's nothing radically new about this latest model, which is
good news. The company has wisely decided to stick with the basic
design. What it has done is tweak the original design in important
new ways.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the screen. One of the big problems with
earlier PalmPilots was that the screen was hard to see in dim or
direct light.
</P>
<P>
   With the Palm V, you can see the screen in almost any lighting.
Images are sharp and clear. There's a backlighting button included
with the Palm V, but you almost never need it.
</P>
<P>
   Another big change with the Palm V is that it doesn't use
batteries. Instead, you recharge it from a cradle that plugs into
the back of your Mac. It is from this cradle that you also back up
your calendar, to-do list, notes and contact list into the
Organizer software.
</P>
<P>
   One charge lasts days, if not weeks, depending on how often you
use the Palm V.
</P>
<P>
   But enough of these technical improvements. What really grabs
people about the Palm V is its looks. This PalmPilot sports a
wafer-thin, silvery body that fits snugly into any palm or pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In this design, 3Com has stolen a page from Steve Jobs' playbook
at Apple and discovered that style in designing computers is
important.
</P>
<P>
   Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
