<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECHNOBUDDY: Use your computer to take a shortcut to shortwave
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There seems to be a Bulgarian in my PC.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he's sitting next to a German woman singing opera, who
is not far from a pompous-sounding British guy reading the news.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, I turned my PC into a shortwave radio. I did
not need the eye of a newt (newts across the nation should be
grateful for that), nor was it necessary to whisper the secret
words (you won't see them here; they wouldn't be secret anymore if
I told you).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, for $300 I added on a computerized shortwave radio. For
the money, you get a radio that performs just about as well as the
fancy $2,000 shortwave transceiver I use in my ham radio hobby. The
radio doesn't look like much _ it's small (about the size of a
brick) and doesn't have dials or knobs. That's where the computer
comes in.
</P>
<P>
   You hook up the radio to the computer (using a serial cable),
load in some software that comes with the radio and _ all of a
sudden _ you have a working shortwave. You use your mouse to tune
the radio, clicking on an on-screen control panel. That's part of
the reason you get so much radio for so little money _ the computer
does a lot of the work.
</P>
<P>
   The radio is made by a relatively small company called Ten-Tec
that's located in Sevierville, Tenn. (You can read about it on the
Web, or even order a radio, by going to www.tentec.com.) The fact
that the radio is made in the United States is a big deal, at least
to me. Shortwave radios _ like almost any other electronic gadget
you can name _ just aren't made here anymore for the most part.
Most of the big names _ Kenwood, Yaesu, Sony, Icom, among others _
are made in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   I was halfway afraid when the folks at Ten-Tec offered to send
me one of the radios to try. I like the idea of American-made
radios (and cars and steel and almost anything else you can name),
but if the radio had been really lousy I would have had to let you
know. But I didn't need to worry. Not only is the radio about the
size of a brick, it works and feels as sturdy as one.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the big deal about a shortwave radio that plugs into a
PC? After all, you can buy shortwave radios that don't plug into a
PC all day long. That's precisely the point ... you can buy them
all day long but, mostly, people don't buy shortwave radios. It's
seen as a hobby that is old-fashioned and sort of geeky, the very
same way that computers were seen when I started messing with them.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays, computers are trendy and seen as a lot of fun. So
I am hoping that some of you find this great hobby of shortwave
listening through the back door. Maybe because the Ten-Tec radio
(it's called the RX-320 PC radio) works with a computer, some of
you will give it a try. Then, once you have it, maybe you'll pretty
much forget about the computer for a while and get lost _ in a good
way _ searching the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   The night I tried the radio, I listened to an American fighter
plane communicate with his controllers, two ham radio operators
talking about cornbread and bird dogs, a really intelligent
commentary on the troubles in Kosovo from the BBC (arguably the
best radio news service in the world), and some opera from Germany.
Compare that to what you can find on your local cable television
lineup at any given time of the evening and _ unless you actually
like programs designed for dull normal people _ you'll see why I
think shortwave radio is a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   I've spent a lot of time bragging on the Ten-Tec radio, and
everything I've said is true. But don't get hung up on that
particular radio if it is too pricey for you or if you'd rather
have a radio that you can take camping. You can find less-expensive
models from companies such as Grundig, Sony and Radio Shack, and
any of them can literally transport you to new places.
</P>
<P>
   Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. His web page
is www.mindspring.com/(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
