<HEADER>
A0890 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-COLUMN11-COX     05-10 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wonders of technology leave a user wondering
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A woman called last week to ask for help in solving what at
first seemed a simple problem, but when I finally understood it, it
could almost be called Catch-22 1/2, or ``You can't get there from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   All this nice person wants to do is get a new computer and
transfer her text files from her old one to her new one. Well, of
course, all of us seventh-level cognoscenti know there are many
ways to do that.
</P>
<P>
   You can do it, if all else fails, with floppy disks. You can do
it with Zip disks, which is what my caller would really like to do.
You can do it via modem. You can do it by simply hooking up the two
computers with a cable.
</P>
<P>
   But my caller can't do it in any of these ways. While she wasn't
looking, the technology race not only passed her but it lapped her.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't grasp the depth of the problem until a young man who is
trying to help her called me. She is running an 80286 computer
(that's a true antique). But that's only part of the problem and in
fact not the biggest part. The biggest part is that it's a really
early 80286 with 360K floppy drives (those are the big 5 1/4-inch
disks that you seldom see any more).
</P>
<P>
   So she can't transfer her files on floppies. Well, how about
transmitting them over the telephone?
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't have a modem, but I expect she'd be happy to buy
one. The problem is that I can't think of a single modem
manufacturer that puts its software on 360K disks any more.
</P>
<P>
   That's the rub. It's not merely a matter of not being able to
get files out. There's no feasible way that her helper or I could
think of to get software onto her computer. She's running an old
version of DOS, 3.2 I think.
</P>
<P>
   This is the worst case of technology lag I've encountered, and
the bitter part of it is that this person can't really be faulted
for not keeping up with the Gateses. All she wants to do with her
computer is write. She's not interested in computers per se; she's
interested only in what they can do for her in this particular
area.
</P>
<P>
   As many of us have already discovered, simple word processing is
possibly the easiest task there is for a computer. It doesn't
require any particular speed. Anyone, certainly, working with a
word processor will notice the difference between writing on an
80286 and writing on a Pentium II though.
</P>
<P>
   However, the difference is chiefly in how quickly the program
loads. Somewhere between the 80386 and the 80486, computers reached
a sort of equilibrium with word processing. Other than the speed of
loading, I can't see that Microsoft Word works one bit faster on my
400-MHz computer than it did on my 200-MHz machine.
</P>
<P>
   It was only when she began to think about storage issues and the
possibility of adding a Zip drive that my caller began to explore
the idea of upgrading her computer.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I could ultimately suggest to her assistant was
to seek out a data recovery company, but that might be
prohibitively expensive.
</P>
<P>
   If there is anyone out there who has a solution, let me know
about it, and I'll put you in touch with this lady and her stranded
files.
</P>
<P>
   Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
