 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Tuesday, May 11, 1999 are moving today
to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN - Marilyn Geewax's weekly column looking at
issues raised by the coming of 2000. (Geewax, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN - GIBSONBURG, Ohio - The other day I'm reading a
story about a pushcart peddler to my eighth-graders. The setting is
New York, and in an effort to bring the Big Apple down to
understandable size for a group of youngsters growing up in a farm
community of 2,000, I ask if anyone has ever been to New York City.
it's the first in a series of wrong questions to ask. (Schuett, Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KABAT-COLUMN - WACO, Texas - Why buy a new house afterall? A
house is like a member of the family. You tend to overlook the good
points and too quickly fixate on the bad. At least you know what
the problems are and you're used to dealing with them. Sometimes
you don't realize what you have under your own roof until you start
looking under others. (Kabat, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN - DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. - Scanners have helped
dumb-down already tedious work. We work faster and dumber all the
time. Moving from self-serve gasoline, to the ATM, to self-serve
grocery scanning, I'd hardly talk to anybody anymore. I see this as
a bad thing. People live too much in their own little cocoons.
Everyone should once in awhile have to speak with a few people not
of their choosing. If we don't, we forget that everyone isn't just
like us. (Lane, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
</P>
