<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: There's no place like home
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ We undertook a little exercise in futility a few
weeks ago. Befelled by temporary insanity, we suddenly believed it
would be a good idea _ although we have three sons to put through
college in the next decade _ to buy a new house.
</P>
<P>
   Many people look toward downsizing when children begin to leave
home. Not us. We were operating under the better-late-than-never
premise.
</P>
<P>
   So, we began the search. I pored over real estate listings,
shying away from the ones that didn't include a price. I
optimistically circled in red ink the 4br, 3ba, private master, 2
liv. area listings and tried not to gulp too loudly at the
six-figure prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never get what they ask for,'' I assured my husband,
casting myself as the real estate expert. ``We can probably offer
tons less than that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure we can,'' he replied, ``and they'll laugh hysterically.''
</P>
<P>
   Wet blanket.
</P>
<P>
   I began driving the long way home, looping through neighborhoods
on my ``wouldn't-it-be-nice'' list. When I scoped out a few
possibilities, I'd show them to my husband. He never saw the same
possibilities I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that a lovely back yard?'' I'd exude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd take three days to mow it,'' came the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But look at the gable windows on the second story,'' I'd
counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gonna climb a ladder to wash them?''
</P>
<P>
   I went back to looking by myself.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, I fall in love with just about every house I
see. I step across the threshold and I'm imagining our sons' brides
walking down the staircase on their wedding days, picturing
grandchildren playing in front of the hearth, planning the
wallpaper I'll use in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   My husband steps across the threshold and notices the rotting
floorboard, the water stain on the ceiling, the lack of storm
windows, the slight crack in the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   We don't look for houses often because it really isn't a
pleasant way for us to spend time together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing,'' my husband intoned soberly one evening
during our search, ``is that we have no guarantee we could sell
this house.''
</P>
<P>
   We both cast an appraising eye about our domain. It does have a
nice, homey, lived-in feel about it: stained carpets, banged-up
interior doors, besmudged walls and the faint, lingering odor of
dirty shinguards and wet dogs.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, there's brand-new central heat and air. After
years of sweating through summers and freezing in winter, it's
wonderful. There's a newly shingled roof with a new skylight. We
have repainted almost every room in the house at least once. We
have replaced some of the carpets, if not all (who ever goes in
those back rooms anyway?).
</P>
<P>
   As my husband and I mentally assessed the pros and cons of our
house, we looked at each other with a dawning awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' I said, ``I could paint the laundry room and make
some new curtains. It would really brighten that room up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we could buy a few more lamps for this room,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Faster than you can say ``amortization schedule,'' we decided to
put our house-hunting on hold. We still have a master bath the size
of a postage stamp and no shower in the front bathroom. We still
have a cracked back patio and more weeds than grass in the yard.
But it fits us well. Let's face it _ we're crabgrass kind of
people.
</P>
<P>
   A house is like a member of the family. You tend to overlook the
good points and too quickly fixate on the bad. At least you know
what the problems are and you're used to dealing with them.
Sometimes you don't realize what you have under your own roof until
you start looking under others.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, is that a new water stain?
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
