</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: 25 years of swipe and beep
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The routine of my first job was as strange
and antique to my children as if I were a powder monkey,
blacksmith's apprentice or loblolly boy.
</P>
<P>
   I worked a cash register.
</P>
<P>
   It had big, round, chrome-edged mechanical keys. A bell that
jingled when the cash drawer flew open. I computed the change in my
head. A distant epoch, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The device that changed this work was the bar-code scanner, an
invention that celebrates its 25th anniversary this month.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to remember the pre-bar-code world. It was a long time
ago in a supermarket far, far away. Back when the phrase ``paper or
plastic?'' didn't automatically mean grocery bags. An age when they
stamped prices right on the merchandise. When shoppers could look
at a clearly marked price that would never change between shelf and
checkout line. A time when a clerk could not silence a long line of
whining customers by shouting the simple phrase: ``the system's
down!'' An age without the things that make modern life so
convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Let history record that everything changed May 5, 1974. That's
when NCR rolled out the first bar-code scanner at a supermarket
industry trade show. The next month, June 26, at Marsh Supermarket
in Troy, Ohio, a 10-pack of Wrigley's Juicy Fruit gum was waved
over glass to become the first product scanned in a supermarket. I
wonder if there will be a costumed re-enactment.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1980s, the things were so commonplace that President Bush
looked bizarrely out of it when he gee-whizzed at the sight of this
newfangled contraption. Had this man never been on a fact-finding
tour of a Mini Mart?
</P>
<P>
   But any technological miracle comes with side-effects. This
one's no exception. Bar-code scanners helped move lines so fast
that clerks no longer needed to look up from their processing to
say ``hello.'' We went from chatting behind the counter to
repetitive stress injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The art of mentally calculating change also began dying out.
Scanners and computers figure the amounts and clerks merely shove
change at you without comment. They don't know if it's right. You
don't know if it's right. You both look numbly at the readout
screen and figure it knows best.
</P>
<P>
   All this makes for a more boring world on both sides of the
counter.
</P>
<P>
   Scanner jockeys are deprived of the simple tactile pleasures of
the old cash registers. Of feeling springs and gears resist your
fingers as you bring the keys down with both hands. Cashiers work
to a rhythm of a monotone beep. Sweep and beep as each code is
noted by laser beam. No friendly little jingle of a bell.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic cash boxes often have no place to tape kids'
pictures, sales-tax conversion charts written in ballpoint or a
scornfully displayed bad check.
</P>
<P>
   Scanners have helped dumb-down already tedious work.
</P>
<P>
   In our post-literate society, some fast-food chains have cash
registers with pictures on the buttons. That way the help doesn't
need the ability to read words or even numbers printed on keys.
</P>
<P>
   We work faster and dumber all the time.
</P>
<P>
   So much faster and dumber, that some supermarket chains are
experimenting with self-service scanners. That way I, the customer,
can experience the pleasure of telling myself that even though the
marked price is wrong and there's nothing I can do about it because
I just work here. I can crush the bread and break the eggs myself,
just like a pro.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from self-serve gasoline, to the ATM, to self-serve
grocery scanning, I'd hardly talk to anybody anymore. Except my
kids, and they're teen-agers, so a lot of what they say isn't
helpful.
</P>
<P>
   I see this as a bad thing. People live too much in their own
little cocoons. Everyone should once in a while have to speak with
a few people not of their choosing. If we don't, we forget that
everyone isn't just like us.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, bagging groceries is too much like work. And what will
those kids do for summer jobs if I take their job? They will go the
way of gas pumpers, newsboys and milkmen.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to do things for myself, I like to think I'm
standing up for the humble bag boy. This is not laziness _ there's
a principle involved. If it doesn't stop here, what could the next
25 years of bar codes bring?
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
