<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The meaning of hats
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The other day I'm reading a story about a
pushcart peddler to my eighth-graders. The setting is New York, and
in an effort to bring the Big Apple down to understandable size for
a group of youngsters growing up in a farm community of 2,000, I
ask if anyone has ever been to New York City. I'm thinking a
first-person, hometown association might make the barely believable
at least imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan raises his hand and tells us he'd ALMOST been there
once but his grandma had changed her mind and taken him to
Cleveland instead. ``Is that close enough?'' he wonders.
</P>
<P>
   When the story follows our character down into the subway, I ask
someone to describe how a subway works. Benjy volunteers. ``It's a
place where you buy sandwiches on long buns. There's one in
Woodville.'' As proof, he begins reciting the menu from memory.
</P>
<P>
   Ted insists a subway is a hole in the ground with buses in it
where people go to get mugged. They argue.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, I encourage a little controlled controversy in the
classroom as a stimulus to higher thought, but a heated discussion
over whether or not someone was selling salami sandwiches from a
bus in a hole in the ground is leading nowhere. I intervene and do
my best to describe a subway system, how one looks (but not how it
smells), and why such an operation is necessary in metropolitan
areas where everybody who lives north works south, and vice versa.
We move on.
</P>
<P>
   A few chapters later, the main character is dressing for church
and, in her haste, accidentally jabs herself with a hatpin. Angie
interrupts. ``What's a hatpin?'' I launch into a thumbnail sketch
of the design and function of a hatpin. From the sea of blank
expressions facing me, it's evident that my explanation needs to be
more basic _ starting with, What's a hat?
</P>
<P>
   ``This story we're reading,'' I begin, ``takes place in 1942.
People dressed differently back then and folks wore hats everywhere
_ to work, to church, shopping, even to the movies.'' A quip about
ladies with hats big enough to block out John Wayne AND his horse
is declared a dud. Quickly, the kids size up my lecture as little
more than another installment of grown-up baloney. Fearlessly, I
slog on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picture a time,'' I suggest, ``when young men didn't have to
walk around holding up their pants with both hands because they'd
bought Hoss Cartwright-size britches to hang on their Mr.
Peepers-size bodies.'' That comment, of course, falls flat on its
antiquated backside. They've never heard of either character, and
as Roger reminds me, only dorks wear pants that don't leave half of
their butts and all of their dignity hanging out.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it really matters to me that these kids understand
about hats. ``Hats did more than keep people's heads warm,'' I
begin again. ``They were used as a sign of respect. Gentlemen
always removed their hats in elevators, in deference to the ladies.
And when the American flag passed in a parade, men placed them over
their hearts in a display of patriotism.' No one is particularly
impressed, but Angie says she's seen her grandfather do that at the
Firemen's convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can anyone tell me why hats are not allowed in our school
building?'' I ask. Benjy says it's just another way of bossing kids
around. I correct him: ``Because it's considered bad manners to
wear hats indoors. It signifies a lack of respect for authority,
each other, and maybe even motherhood and apple pie.'' Not a
chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of hopelessly outdating myself I explain that
baseball caps used to be worn only by kids who played baseball, and
any guy who wore one turned backwards was immediately branded a
rowdy who rode a bicycle with no fenders and smelled like an
ashtray. My audience finds this impossible to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   In a last-ditch effort to explain the importance of hats in
history, I relate the story of my mother's Easter hat _ the black
straw shaped like an old stovepipe. ``It was so silly looking that
it cracked up half the Sunday morning congregation AND Lillie Mae
Cosens, my mother's best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho hum.
</P>
<P>
   Give it up, I tell myself. Quit while you're behind. So much for
hatpins and respect, and back to the streets of New York.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 W.
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431, or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
