<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0911 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-FEATURE-COX     05-10 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEWS FOR KIDS
 &HT;    Kids struggling with weight can fall into eating disorders
 &HT;    By Mary Beth Bishop
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you imagine not eating anything all day long except for a
handful of gummy bears and an apple?
</P>
<P>
   That's the way Jordana Wolff, who's now 23, used to eat. Her
hips and breasts began developing sooner than her friends', making
her feel like she was much larger than they were.In fourth and
fifth grade, she started to diet. She continued to lose weight in
high school.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of feeling better as she grew thinner, her body was
worn out and malnourished. She had to take naps after school to
make it through the day. ``I had to give my body a rest. I couldn't
take it,'' she said. Once, at a sleepover when she was a teenager,
she blacked out in a kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   She didn't get back on a healthy diet until she was a college
student and went to a psychiatrist for help.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff is not alone in her struggle with food. At least 8 million
people in the United States suffer from serious eating disorders,
according to the National Association of Anorexia Nervosa and
Associated Disorders (ANAD).
</P>
<P>
   Most of those people were teenagers when they first got sick.
Ten percent began having serious problems when they were 10 or
younger, the group says.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of girls look in the mirror and see themselves as fat when
they're not really overweight at all. When Wolff was hurting her
body so badly in high school, she only wore about a size 8. If
you're a girl in middle school and think you weigh too much,
remember that gaining weight in your hips, thighs and breasts is a
normal part of getting older.
</P>
<P>
   And what about guys? They don't go through the same kinds of
changes and don't get eating disorders as often as girls. But it
can happen to boys, and more of them are starting to acknowledge
the problem, says Dina Zeckhausen, a psychologist who specializes
in eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   There are different types of eating disorders:
</P>
<P>
   Anorexia nervosa is when a person eats very little food and
becomes dangerously thin.
</P>
<P>
   Bulimia nervosa is when someone eats large amounts of food but
then vomits or takes pills to keep weight off.
</P>
<P>
   Binge eating is when a person overeats for a period of time but
then diets or doesn't eat at all.
</P>
<P>
   Skipping meals every day just until you drop some weight may
seem harmless, but that's how lots of kids get on the road to
serious eating disorders. Too much dieting can keep important parts
of your body _ like your heart and kidneys _ from working the way
they should. It can also keep your body from developing the way it
should.
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFO
</P>
<P>
   If you or someone you know has an eating disorder, you can get
help from the National Association of Anorexia Nervosa and
Associated Disorders at 847-831-3438.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
