<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0912 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH-COX     05-10 0249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Runs with NFK-FEATURE and NFK-CHECKITOUT
 &HT;    News for Kids
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   Refugee baby born in U.S.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need water or a microwave oven to create an instant
American _ you just need to be born in the United States. Last
week, a couple became the first Kosovar refugees to have a baby in
the States. The father said he was glad his 7-pound, 8-ounce boy is
a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The couple fled their home in Kosovo and spent many weeks in a
crowded refugee camp in Macedonia. They were among the first
Kosovar refugees to arrive in the States.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor who delivered the baby said the mother had much nicer
conditions here to give birth than in the refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes strike U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Many U.S. cities got lucky last week as storms passed through
without causing much damage. Tornadoes born from the same storm
systems killed more than 50 people and injured about 1,000 in
states across the West and South. More than 35 tornadoes were seen
in Oklahoma, four struck Kansas and one hit Texas.
</P>
<P>
   High winds, heavy rain and hail struck Atlanta on Thursday.
About 13,000 homes were left without power. Tornadoes form when
warm, moist air fills the lower atmosphere and the temperature of
the air above drops rapidly. For Georgia and surrounding states,
tornado season usually lasts from March until May.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
