<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNNY STUFF GETS BIGGER, CLEARER IN HDTV PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On a Burbank sound stage, a crew of actors and
support personnel work their way through the pratfalls of a
standard television sitcom. But on second glance, this sitcom shoot
isn't so standard after all.
</P>
<P>
   Over to one side, the highly stressed director is one of the
hottest young talents in the TV business, studying a four-way
monitor that for once can't tell him everything the cameras see.
</P>
<P>
   In a little jerry-rigged island of electronics at the back of
the sound stage, people crowd around some very expensive TVs,
watching the action unwind on a wide-screen set with an
extraordinary picture.
</P>
<P>
   After days of experimenting, the actors' makeup has been applied
with excruciating care. And the sets have become something to worry
about, because even little flaws have to be covered up.
</P>
<P>
   And the studio cameras being used to shoot all this, something's
different about those, too. Instead of the massive, studio-quality
behemoths commonly used on such shoots, these are tiny, weighing
all of 25 pounds, and bolted to rolling tripod mounts that seem
oddly out of proportion to the relatively tiny machinery they bear.
</P>
<P>
   It's those cameras that change everything. They're
high-definition digital cameras, being used recently to shoot a
spec sitcom called ``Sam 'n' Ella's.'' No one's bought the show
yet, but its producers think it won't take long to find willing
customers, on three continents.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we decided to do it in high-definition, we were
approached by a couple of people (interested in buying the show),''
said producer Mark Baker. ``Europe and Japan are begging for
(high-definition) content. So we're trying to sell it
internationally, because that's where the markets are.''
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated one-tenth of 1 percent of American households
currently owning high-definition television sets, there aren't a
lot of U.S. viewers just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to design a show over who's going to view it first,''
said scriptwriter Scott Morgan. ``That's probably going to be the
Japanese and British, which is why the teleplay is heavy on
physical comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last Saturday, all TV stations in the nation's Top 10
markets finally were required to begin broadcasting a separate HD
signal (though most of the big stations around the country actually
started sometime around last Nov. 1's ``voluntary'' start-up
target).
</P>
<P>
   And only on Monday did a major network program, ``The Tonight
Show,'' begin regular high-definition broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the people behind ``Sam 'n' Ella's'' think they'll
find buyers here, too. As with Europe and Japan, stations will soon
enough be crying for high-definition content like what the company
is making. That said, the production wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   The show's producers were able to attract director Josh Baerwald
(cousin of musician David Baerwald), a protege of ``Cheers''
co-creator James Burrows.
</P>
<P>
   Baerwald is one of the hotter young TV directors of the moment
but was willing to work on a spec show because of the chance to
learn how to deal with HD, he said. There are definite differences
from the kind of television he was suckled on.
</P>
<P>
   With the much wider screen, Baerwald had to frame shots
differently, which was good, he said. The wide screen, with an
aspect ratio similar to movies in a theater, allows both the action
and its comedic reaction to play out in the same shot, in a natural
way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think comedy is played in twos instead of singles,''
Baerwald said. ``The high-definition screen is giving much more of
a range of line of sight.''
</P>
<P>
   But he struggled with a four-way monitor _ designed to show what
all running cameras are seeing simultaneously during a scene _ that
wasn't high-definition itself.
</P>
<P>
   Baerwald couldn't see the entire frame of each shot, requiring
constant consultations with director of photography Tom Feldman
about what worked and what didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of tough issues for producers,'' said Feldman.
``The level of perfection is way higher than on regular NTSC
(standard television) shoots.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the cameras' extremely high resolution meant
Baerwald and Feldman had to keep an eagle eye on screen details
they normally wouldn't much worry about in the run-and-gun world of
television comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see so much on HDTV,'' Baerwald said. ``We're shooting
through a net (over the camera lens). Without the net, at 20 feet
the camera can see the pores in an actress's face.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
