<HEADLINE>
TRAIL LEADS TO PARADISE IN NORTHERN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA, Calif. _ A beam of sunlight bore a hole through the
redwood canopy and poured across 60-foot Silver Falls, the light
refracting in the water crystals like miniature prisms.
</P>
<P>
   Deep in the Santa Cruz Mountains behind us was Berry Creek
Falls, a 70-foot free-fall framed perfectly in a redwood canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Up ahead was Golden Falls, a long, meandering series of cascades
that looks like a water slide as clear water passes over gold
sandstone.
</P>
<P>
   And here among the three crown jewels of waterfalls was Silver
Falls, where the trail passes so close to its brink you can reach
out and dip your fingers in the water as it passes.
</P>
<P>
   These gems unfold on the Skyline-to-Sea Trail, the No. 1 hiking
and camping trip in the San Francisco Bay area and the best place
to enjoy the coronation of spring.
</P>
<P>
   The hike starts on the Skyline Ridge above Saratoga, with the
trail head at an elevation of 3,000 feet, then is routed west over
China Grade, down through Big Basin Redwoods State Park and all the
way to the ocean at the Rancho del Oso Nature and History Center.
The hike covers 34 miles, including a 2-mile up-and-down to see the
waterfalls, and is downhill for most of the route, making it the
easiest three-day backpack in California.
</P>
<P>
   There are panoramic views, giant old-growth redwoods, pristine
streams in remote canyons, gorgeous wildflower blooms, honey-combed
sandstone rock formations _ with clean and sheltered campsites to
spend each night.
</P>
<P>
   The mass of civilization is just 15 miles from the trail head,
but it doesn't take long to feel as if you have launched into a
different orbit from the rest of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   My comrades for the trip were Rambob Stienstra, my brother and
wilderness explorer, and Michael Furniss, one of the preeminent
soil scientists in the nation. We have joined together for many
expeditions, including the John Muir Trail, much of the Pacific
Crest Trail, hunting for Bigfoot and mountain climbing.
</P>
<P>
   We left a shuttle car at the end of the trail, making it a
one-way hike. We planned for three days on the trail, with hiking
days of 9.6 miles, 9.5 miles and 15 miles, and two trail camps on
the way.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-morning, we were at the trail head at Castle Rock State
Park, just south of the junction of Highway 9 and Highway 35 on
Skyline Ridge. We hoisted up our packs, tightened the belts, joined
in a high five and a shout: ``Down!''
</P>
<P>
   Down? It seems every trip we've ever made goes up. In fact, 99
of 100 hikes in California go up, but the Skyline-to-Sea is the
exception.
</P>
<P>
   And down it goes, from the first few steps. Within minutes, you
drop down into a lush riparian woodland, a canyon filled with bay
and towering black oaks and live oaks, many coated with moss.
</P>
<P>
   After so much rain this winter, there is a green freshness to
everything. The headwaters of Kings Creek form at the canyon
bottom, at first a trickle of droplets, but soon a pretty brook.
</P>
<P>
   In little over a half-mile, the surprises start. That brook
drops over the side of a cliff, creating the first waterfall of the
trip. It is a broken free fall, the water hitting a crag about
halfway down. An observation deck seems to jut out over open space,
set just above and to the side of the waterfall rim.
</P>
<P>
   The sound of the crashing water is as refreshing as a shower.
</P>
<P>
   ``It already seems like we're a million miles away from all the
people,'' Furniss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ocean seems a million miles away, too,'' Rambob said.
</P>
<P>
   The trail then cuts a lateral route across an open rock facing.
On clear days, the reward is a series of sweeping views to the
southwest, across a sea of conifers to Big Basin, the Pacific Coast
and Monterey Bay. On foggy days, the layer of stratus looks like a
pearl sea, with mountain tops poking through like tiny islands. On
rainy days, mist rises from the tree tops.
</P>
<P>
   But Castle Rock State Park is best known for its sandstone rock
formations. Many of these massive rocks are honeycombed like Swiss
cheese, a unique process where soft material has been eroded away
over eons. The most dramatic are Castle Rock itself and Goat Rock,
a popular rock-climbing site for technical climbers.
</P>
<P>
   The trail passes the base of Goat Rock, where a permanent
climbing cable has been affixed; for day hikers, the top of Goat
Rock with its lookout of Monterey Bay makes an idyllic picnic site.
There was not another soul on the trail. We had this world to
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   From here, the trail goes down past the Castle Rock Trail Camp
(2.8 miles in), through Loughry Woods, then down past Travertine
Springs and the headwaters of the San Lorenzo River.
</P>
<P>
   The forest is second-growth here but has filled in well after
being cut 100 years ago, with a lush understory.
</P>
<P>
   On many hikes there is a sameness for miles, but Skyline-to-Sea
changes with every curve and ravine. The trail is cut so it is
routed in and out of canyons, around shoulders and ridges, heading
down to Waterman Gap Trail Camp (9.6 miles in).
</P>
<P>
   Every 10 minutes you get something different, from oak woodlands
to conifer forests, from cool, deep canyons with streams to hot,
open faces with long-distance views.
</P>
<P>
   Waterman Gap is the first-night destination for most hikers.
</P>
<P>
   We settled in, setting up bivvies and tents, cooking on a
backpack stove, marveling at the day's surprises.
</P>
<P>
   That night, I slept about seven hours. Only problem was it came
in about 20 installments. That can happen on the first camp-out of
the year. By summer camp-outs, I'll be sleeping better than on a
bed.
</P>
<P>
   After camp breakfast, soup and oatmeal, we set out on the second
leg of our hike, a 9.5-mile tromp to Big Basin Redwoods State Park.
</P>
<P>
   The trail leaves the oak woodlands and enters second-growth
redwood forest, and _ for the first time since the trail head _
heads up in a gentle incline to China Grade. It felt good to get
into a rhythmic climb, but it was over after 15 or 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it seemed the entire world was at our feet. China Grade
is the rim of Big Basin, and below were miles of tree tops, many of
them giant redwoods, 300 to 2,000 years old. Looking west, we could
see Waddell Creek Canyon, and beyond, the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   We instinctively gathered in a circle for another high five, and
shouted ``Down!''
</P>
<P>
   And down we went again, grinning all the way. Within minutes, we
were crossing a series of huge sandstone plates that looked like
glacial-carved granite in Yosemite. Except this rock isn't slippery
like granite, and in many spots is like walking on sandpaper.
</P>
<P>
   Every step came with a view as we crossed through oak and
manzanita, the trail's edge sprinkled with wildflowers. After
topping a narrow ridge, the trail is routed down steeply into the
redwoods, and it seemed again we had discovered a world few enter.
</P>
<P>
   The route passes in and out of ravines filled with redwoods and
an understory of sorrel, bracken ferns and blooming trillium, with
creeks and streams flowing clear and pristine. The dirt trail was
sprinkled with brown redwood needles, soft and forgiving to feet
only now beginning to toughen up to trail life.
</P>
<P>
   The air was cool, and along shaded creeks we often stopped just
to watch the water go by.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while out in the woods, you understand that the
landscape is alive, and the streams are its blood,'' said Furniss,
a scientist who specializes in the protection of small streams.
</P>
<P>
   As we neared headquarters along Opal Creek, the redwoods started
getting bigger _ some 300 feet tall, and 40 to 50 feet around.
</P>
<P>
   We camped among the big trees that night and, after dinner, as
the temperature dropped to the 30s, built a campfire. The
flickering orange glow cast shadows off the trunks and limbs of the
giant trees, and we wondered about all that had passed here over
the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   As I drifted off to sleep, I thought of William Waddell, the
logger who cut down some of the biggest redwoods here in the 1800s,
and how he was killed by a grizzly bear near the creek that is now
named for him. The grizzlies have been gone for most of this
century, but the big trees remain. The proximity of such an awesome
old-growth grove to San Francisco inspired Big Basin's creation as
the first state park in California.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day was warm, and by mid-morning the first blooms of
spring were opening to the sun _ wild iris, trillium, miner's
lettuce and morning glorys.
</P>
<P>
   From the forest floor near park headquarters, the trail rises
for 20 minutes, a steady grade, and tops the Big Basin Rim at 1,200
feet. The trail then descends 600 feet, over 4 miles, to the
waterfalls.
</P>
<P>
   You round a bend and suddenly glimpse filtered silver through
tree limbs. You head on and there it is: Berry Creek Falls. There
are two perfect viewing areas, one where the entire canyon is
framed, the other an observation deck at the base of the falls.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 20 waterfalls in the Bay region, this is the classic, a
70-foot free fall, with moss oozing water at its edges, surrounded
by redwoods, sword ferns and sorrel. The air tastes sweet and
fresh, full of life.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking upstream, you come upon Silver Falls, and then just
above, Golden Falls. You can spend hours here, having a picnic,
taking pictures, tromping up and down the canyon, absorbing the
energy.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun passed overhead, the light changed, and with it the
character of the waterfalls seemed to change as well. It was like
watching the face of a person you care about _ in the shade, cold
and pensive; in refracted sun, wondrous and mysterious; in direct
light, effervescent and electrifying.
</P>
<P>
   From the falls, it's an easy jaunt to trail's end, hiking along
Waddell Creek. We found 20 species of wildflowers, including the
most extensive blooms of Forget-Me-Nots I've ever seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
