<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-FOUNDATION-TEX     05-10 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-FOUNDATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS PATRONS, ORGANIZATIONS CREATING OWN GRANT PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The arts community, stung by cutbacks in federal
arts programs and the virtual elimination of grants to individual
artists, is stepping into the breach with a grants program of its
own.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a group of arts patrons and 22 arts organizations are
to announce the formation of the Creative Capital Foundation,
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement is scheduled for a cocktail party Tuesday
evening in the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts near the
SoHo section of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The new nonprofit organization, initially financed with $5
million, plans to distribute $1 million a year to 50-60 artists in
the performing and visual arts. And, unlike grants from the
National Endowment for the Arts, grants by the new foundation to
controversial artists should pose no problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a gap in the funding of artists wanting to do new
forms of art and who weren't going to be picked up by the
entertainment community or the mainstream art world,'' said
Archibald Gillies, board chairman of the new foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look at art that's interesting, innovative, even
experimental and that challenges convention,'' said Gillies, who is
also president of the Andy Warhol foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the patrons of the Creative Capital Foundation is
filmmaker Richard Linklater of Austin, who will serve as a board
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its time has definitely come,'' he said. ``It's not a lot of
money, but for artists a lot of time that's the first validation.''
</P>
<P>
   Linklater received a $2,600 grant from the NEA for one of his
first films, ``Slacker,'' a 1991 cult hit about the zany aspects of
Austin. He went on to make more films and create a nonprofit fund
for Texas filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The move to form the Creative Capital Foundation, and its focus
on controversial projects, was sparked by opposition to the NEA
from conservative members of Congress, particularly House Majority
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, offended that controversial artists such as Robert
Mapplethorpe and Andres Serrano had benefited from NEA funding,
engineered a 40 percent cut in the agency's funding and termination
of most individual grants in the agency's budget for fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Told of the plans to create private-sector funding through the
new foundation, Armey press secretary Michele Davis said: ``This is
what we've been saying all along. Government has no business
deciding what is and what is not art.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives have consistently maintained that the private
sector should pay for the arts. Some NEA supporters worry that the
new foundation could be used against the agency just as it is
rebuilding its support in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   NEA chairman William J. Ivey, who has held the job less than a
year, is asking Congress for a big increase in his budget _ from
$98 million in the current budget to $150 million for fiscal 2000,
which begins Oct. 1. He is also talking about reinstituting grants
to individual artists _ a program that distributed about $10
million a year at its peak _ in several years.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey said he welcomes the new foundation but does not think it
will impede his quest for more federal dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything the NEA does is part of arts funding in the U.S.,''
Ivey said. ``Never are we the entire support system. The private
sector needs to play a role, but the NEA provides a sense of public
investment, permanence and continuity that only a federal agency
can bring to arts funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Art gallery owner Ronald Feldman, who is on the board of the new
foundation, said: ``Even with NEA funds going to individual
artists, this would still be needed. It is in no way intended to
replace the NEA.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, federal dollars have also brought controversy.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the NEA funded a touring exhibition of the
work of photographer Mapplethorpe, which included homoerotic
photographs, and another exhibition that included a Serrano
photograph that showed a crucifix in a vial of the artist's urine.
</P>
<P>
   And would Mapplethorpe and Serrano receive funding from the
Creative Capital Foundation?
</P>
<P>
   ``Would we shy away from that work? No,'' said Ruby Lerner,
executive director of the new foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner acknowledged that ``there is no question that the NEA
shutting down support for most artists was the framework for the
new foundation.'' She added that the foundation plans a new
approach to arts funding to generate continued support for artists.
</P>
<P>
   The new foundation will get an agreed-upon percentage of each
artist's work once the project starts to generate revenue. The idea
behind the ``revolving fund'' is to return money to the foundation
for the next batch of artists.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's offices will be in the same building as the
Andy Warhol foundation, and Feldman, who represented Warhol, thinks
it appropriate that the new foundation will be linked with the
avant-garde.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have loved it,'' Feldman said, referring to Warhol,
who died in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
