A0982 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      05-10 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Tuesday,
May 11 . If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   SCATTER: The Housing Authority of Kansas City will build nearly
300 scattered site units throughout the city in the next 18 months.
In doing so, the authority is following a national trend of moving
from concentrated projects to duplexes and other small
developments. The move has generated concerns among neighorhood
leaders on both sides of the river. They see the developments
lowering home prices and hurting neighborhoods. But today's
scattered site housing is not your cement block project of the post
World War II era. We visited one woman who lives in a new Northland
duplex with a two-car garage. She says her home has given her
stability and chances for a better future. Ruth Igoe. 45. Photos,
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   EVOLUTION: Tomorrow the Kansas Board of Education will begin
discussing proposed new science standards for public school
education and testing that call evolution a benchmark of science.
An alternate proposal, by a state board member, would change the
definition of science and list evolution as well as creationism as
theories. The alternate proposal was written mostly by people from
the Creation Science Association for Mid-America, who asked the
board member to propose it. Kate Beem. 30.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN: When Park College awards its first three master's degrees
in business administration next weekend, it will be to three women.
At many college commencement ceremonies across the country this
year, women will outnumber men, a trend that has strengthened
during the 1990s. Men's share of bachelor's degrees declined from
81 percent in 1900 to just 45 percent today. In Missouri and
Kansas, those percentages are slightly lower. Some people celebrate
women's success at earning college degrees as revenge for years of
exclusion from higher education. But others bemoan the trend,
saying men are losing out in a changing world that often requires a
college diploma for good careers. Lynn Franey. 45. Photos and
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH (with WOMEN): An especially worrisome aspect of this trend
is the dearth of black men in higher education. Women earn about 64
percent of all college degrees awarded to African-American
students. Franey. 20. Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA (Tentative): A couple from Kansas City is in China _ site
of anti-American and anti-NATO demonstrations _ trying to adopt a
baby and is staying not far from the American consulate. Bill
Graham. 20.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE: A new program to help Missourians save money for college
with significant state and federal tax breaks was to be unveiled
Monday at Penn Valley Community College. Lynn Franey. 12-15 inches.
</P>
<P>
   CALL _ Kansas City has become a call center hub for thousands of
employees and big companies ranging from Gateway to ATT. By Diane
Stafford. Graphic and Photo
</P>
<P>
   BAKE _ Interstate Bakeries didn't do everything it was supposed
to do when it acquired Continental Grain, Dept. of Justice says.
Jennifer Mann
</P>
<P>
   STOVER _ Those candy guys are buying another confectioner, this
one with about 200 stores. Steve Everly
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
