<HEADER>
A0989 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIDGE-BATTLE-HNS &LR;      05-10 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-BATTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE, NAVY SPAR OVER ROUTE OF NEW BAY BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ State transportation officials knew three
years ago there would be problems getting permission from the U.S.
Navy to build a new San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge, but it forged
ahead anyway and eventually spent $40 million for planning.
</P>
<P>
   Now a deadlock between the California Department of
Transportation and the Navy is the only thing holding up the $1.5
billion bridge, which is being financed by a 1998 toll increase of
$1 on all spans in the San Francisco Bay area, except for the
Golden Gate Bridge. The new bridge would be one of the largest
building projects in Caltrans' history.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers on where Caltrans wants to position the new
span between Oakland and Yerba Buena Island.
</P>
<P>
   State engineers and a regional commission want to build to the
north of the current bridge. But Mayor Willie Brown and the Navy
say the span should be built to the south, to protect potential
development and historic buildings on Treasure Island that adjoins
Yerba Buena.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge, which was built in 1936 and has a main span that is
2,310 feet long, joins the east and west sides of the Bay. The two
links connecting Alameda County to the east and San Francisco to
the west meet at Yerba Buena.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans has tremendous power to take land it needs for building
freeways and bridges, but it has no control over the Navy. Caltrans
is up against another behemoth it can't control.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that they don't hear the word `no' very
often,'' said Jeff Young, a spokesman for the Navy, ``and I think
they kind of just proceeded. And now they've run into federal
property.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Caltrans hasn't worked with the Navy about getting
a drilling permit and putting heavy construction equipment on
Treasure and Yerba Buena islands. Caltrans has put together a file
with 74 letters and memos between the two agencies dating to July
6, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, when it became clear Caltrans wanted to build a
new bridge instead of retrofitting the old one, environmental
officials for the transportation department sent a letter
requesting access to Navy property.
</P>
<P>
   Six days later, on March 10, 1997, the Navy replied with a
detailed letter saying the request was premature.
</P>
<P>
   The service said it appeared the plans would put Navy housing in
jeopardy, make too much noise and bother movie sound studios on
Treasure Island, and make it generally difficult for people to live
and work on the island.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Navy said Caltrans was ignoring its pleas to
improve dangerous ramps to and from the island that were built in
the 1930s, and Caltrans hadn't resolved who would clean up lead
contamination under the Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Navy desires to facilitate the seismic improvements
to this vital Bay area transportation artery,'' Navy manager Kenn
Y. Parsons wrote, ``we also feel that we need to understand the
environmental and economic impacts. ... As now structured, there
are too many unknowns and issues still undecided.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy contends the transportation department spent the next
three years meeting, writing memos and sending letters, but never
really fixing any of its concerns and always feeling it had a right
to the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think the level of communication would be greater
than that, given that a state agency does not have the power of
eminent domain over federal property,'' Young said. ``We're not
asking anyone to come to us with hat in hand. We're just saying the
communication could be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans now claims that if the Navy gets its way on a more
southern route for the bridge, the $40 million the state spent on
planning the northern route will have gone to waste.
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy says Caltrans knew that money was at risk,
especially since it failed to get formal permission to drill on
Treasure Island before it went ahead with its plans.
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans blames the Navy entirely for the delay, saying it sent
maps of where it needed to work and held numerous phone conferences
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   According to a memorandum from a July 1997 phone conversation, a
Caltrans official told the Navy it ``will not destroy historic
property on'' Yerba Buena Island, although the northern route could
``possibly go over or come close to the Nimitz House.''
</P>
<P>
   Caltrans officials also told Navy officials the new ramps the
service wanted were not part of the plan. Caltrans had no answers
about construction noise levels, except to say that pile drivers
would be needed. It told the Navy it would pay fair market value
for the use of Navy land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is, they've known for three years that
a replacement bridge was an option,'' Caltrans spokesman Jim Drago
said, ``and they knew that if there was a northern alignment that
it would affect their property. And they, to this date, have not
allowed us to go in there and do the necessary drilling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the east side of the San Francisco Bay, Alameda County
Supervisor Mary King supports the current plan and thinks Brown is
using the Navy to protect development interests on the island.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Navy, like Caltrans, should think more about the
safety of bridge commuters than the shrubbery and historic
buildings it owns on the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy is the federal government. It belongs to the
people,'' King said, ``and this is a health and safety issue for
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, supports the state agency's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This problem can easily be solved by the Navy doing the right
thing and allowing Caltrans to proceed,'' said Michael Bustamante,
the governor's spokesman. ``This has been under consideration for
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
