suffered a second crash this week, resulting in NATO's first two
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the darkest assessment of NATO's progress was offered by
the outgoing chairman of the alliance's Military Committee, General
Klaus Naumann, a German, on May 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly and honestly, we did not succeed in our initial
attempt to coerce Milosevic through air strikes to accept our
demands, nor did we succeed in preventing Yugoslavia from pursuing
a campaign of ethnic separation and expulsion,'' he conceded.
</P>
<P>
   NATO might have fared better, he suggested, if it had dropped
even more bombs even sooner, and been less constrained by the need
to avoid hitting civilians, churches and mosques.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, there was still a ``real chance we can make it'' and
prevail in Kosovo through air power alone, the general thought. But
it was also possible, he admitted, that Milosevic might succeed in
his plan to deport the entire ethnic-Albanian population. &QL; 
