<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' CARTER HAS ALWAY BEEN A GOAL-GETTER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ He had wasted enough of his life. Frivolity was no
longer a luxury. It was time to get serious, to settle upon a
career, to map out a path to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   He sat down with his mother for a heart-to-heart talk. He was
going to attend college in the States, he told her. He'd done
exhaustive research at the local library and determined that the
educational system south of the border was superior to Canada's. He
would get his US degree, he explained, and proceed to medical
school. He was going to be a doctor. An orthopedic surgeon. It was
settled.
</P>
<P>
   He was 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   All right, so a young child's ambitions rarely work out exactly
as planned. That doesn't mean they have to be abandoned. Just
refined a little.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of becoming a US physician would be prohibitive, he
eventually told his mother. He didn't want to saddle his parents
with such a crushing expense. But this game she hadn't wanted him
to play, this ice hockey, could be more than just winter fun. It
was a means with potential. Some US colleges _ top-flight US
colleges _ awarded scholarships to young men with skating and
studying skills, he'd discovered. And he had both. So this was to
be his pathway. Hockey would pay his way to college _ a Central
Collegiate Hockey Association college, he specified, so he would be
close enough to home that his parents could watch him play. That
would set the stage for his career in orthopedics.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and one other thing. He would be deferring medical school
for a while. Until he was through playing in the National Hockey
League.
</P>
<P>
   Now this was a mature life plan, with all the particulars filled
in.
</P>
<P>
   He was 14 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Anson Carter's parents laugh about it now as they sit in the
living room of their tidy two-story brick house in the middle-class
Scarborough section of this city. Sure enough, their boy attended a
fine US college, Michigan State _ a CCHA school, of course. Sure
enough, a hockey scholarship paid for his studies. And sure enough,
he's playing in the NHL. There he is right in front of them on the
television, brought to them courtesy of the small satellite dish
atop their roof, playing left wing for the Bruins in the opener of
their Eastern Conference semifinal against the Buffalo Sabres, a
surprising advancement he helped Boston achieve with a pair of
vital goals against the Carolina Hurricanes in the first round,
when he showed flashes of becoming an emerging star.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he still has a couple of courses to go for his degree,''
points out his mother, Valma. ``So he's done two of the three
things he said he would.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, considering the grandiose nature of his prepubescent and
adolescent predictions, that's a remarkable percentage. Who would
have believed it?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not his parents, Horace and Valma. ``We used to laugh
at that so much,'' says his mother, recalling those career
objectives that seemed to be more delirium than design. ``We
thought it was a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they should have known better. ``I had a pretty good
grasp of things at the time,'' says Carter. ``I knew exactly where
I wanted to be, what I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, from the time he was 4 years old, when he vainly tried
to persuade his parents to let him play ice hockey, Anson Carter
was not one to kid about such things.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Anson, he can be so serious,'' says Valma. ``Sometimes
he's boring.''
</P>
<P>
   His parents never will face such accusations. Horace and Valma
Carter, who emigrated from their native Barbados some 30 years ago,
are people of accomplishment who don't take themselves too
seriously. They laugh easily, downplay their roles in Anson's
development, and are just as proud of their daughter Michelle, 27,
who works in human resources at a telecommunications company, and
son David, 19, a student at St. Clair College, as they are of their
25-year-old hockey star.
</P>
<P>
   Horace and Valma were teachers in Barbados who switched careers
after arriving in Canada. Horace, 58, became an assessor with
Revenue Canada, from which he retired eight years ago. Valma, 55,
still works in communications for the Ministry of Transportation.
But there is no doubt about their priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Barbados,'' says Valma, ``a lot of emphasis is placed on
education. If the educational standards are being met, then fine if
you want to do sports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hockey was a bonus,'' says Horace.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, hockey was out of the question when Anson initially
approached his parents for permission to play. He spent much of his
free time with the older kids in the neighborhood playing street
hockey, and as would prove to be the case in all sports he tried,
he mastered the game immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anson was the type of kid who was always ahead of the class,''
says Valma. ``He was very gifted in everything _ school,
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   And to his way of thinking, if he could handle the game on
macadam, why not on ice?
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main reasons I wanted to play ice hockey was that
I'd take a lot heat from my friends,'' says Carter. ``I'd make a
move on them in street hockey and they'd jab me: `You couldn't do
that on the ice.' It drove me to prove people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Anson could skate. Just not well. He would join
Michelle, a relatively accomplished skater, on the ponds, ``and he
was kind of shaky,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But he was persistent, too. For four years, he kept at his
parents. ``He persevered and persevered,'' says Valma, meaning he
pestered them to distraction.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't use grades as a reason to deny him. Earning
straight A's from the start, he passed a test at age 7 to attend a
school for gifted students, but his parents wouldn't allow the move
when he pleaded in tears that he didn't want to leave his friends.
His second-grade teacher's alternative, that he skip a grade, was
rejected for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the teacher always had to find extra work for him,'' says
Valma. ``The regular work was never enough for him. It was that way
all through public school.''
</P>
<P>
   Anson acknowledges this, but don't be deceived, he warns. He was
serious but not a nerd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get in trouble with teachers and at recess because I was
confident and wanted to express myself,'' he says. ``I had a lot of
focus in some areas, but in others, you could look at me and say,
`That kid has no direction.' I'd pick my spots.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them was hockey. But he still made no headway at home,
though he was undeterred. Even when he became an instant star in
baseball as a pitcher and shortstop, his appeals to get a crack at
the rink continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd say, `Baseball is a US sport; I won't be good enough to
play in college there,' '' recalls Valma. ``I don't know why, but
he was a man on a mission to play hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he found an opening when he was 8 and his parents
decided to let Michelle give soccer a try. If she could play the
sport she wanted, he argued, why couldn't he? ``Leverage,'' he
calls it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leverage?'' says Valma, exploding in laughter as she is
advised of this. ``That sounds like Anson.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. While his parents weren't sold on his skating, they
gave him permission to join the local youth league. As a show of
good faith, his father created a rink at home, flooding the
backyard during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   And opening the floodgates.
</P>
<P>
   As calculated as his career course seems, happenstance may have
been the key ingredient. Almost by accident, Brian Ballantine
became his first hockey coach, ``and without Brian,'' says Horace,
``I don't think the rest of it would have happened. No matter who
his coach has been since, Anson always says, `Brian laid the
groundwork.' We were just lucky, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is mutual. ``When you coach 25 years and get a kid
like Anson,'' says Ballantine, a full-time Seattle Mariners scout
and former major junior goaltender, ``you're lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine is sitting in the lobby of Commander Park Arena, a
two-rink facility set in the back of an industrial development a
few blocks from the Carter home. He recalls how he inadvertently
discovered Carter while coaching the Agincourt Lions, an all-star
team of 8-year-olds that is part of the 540-player Scarborough
Hockey Association.
</P>
<P>
   His roster was full and Anson had been late signing up,
Ballantine remembers, but it turned out one of the Lions lived
outside the district, rendering him ineligible. After two or three
weeks of watching Carter play in-house games, he gave him the
roster spot, despite a familiar misgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a poor skater,'' says Ballantine. ``I mean, he couldn't
skate that first year; they were a size too big. But he was big and
aggressive, good with the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter worked diligently on his shortcomings his first year,
participating in power-skating drills and going out on his own to a
pond in a neighborhood construction area.
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine liked that work ethic. And something else. The
newcomer seemed to instantly absorb whatever he was taught.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you did it in practice,'' says Ballantine, ``he'd do it in
the next game. And he wouldn't forget. He'd do it again later in
the season.''
</P>
<P>
   He never was a strong skater during his five years with
Ballantine. He certainly didn't have the flash of the left wing on
the line he centered, Adrian Sciarra, whose father, Pat, sponsored
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That drove me, too,'' says Carter. ``He was a year younger,
and he was so impressive with all those flashy moves. I said, `He's
a year younger. I think I'm a pretty good player, too. I should be
able to do that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He never did, not in his five years with Ballantine. But his
other assets were undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of that first year,'' says Sciarra, now an area
manager for a window cleaning company, ``he was obviously the best
player in the league. And by the time he was 12, it was obvious he
was going to go a lot further than we were.''
</P>
<P>
   Because somehow he just kept emerging as the star. When he was
10, he was named MVP of an international tournament in Boston, his
first exposure to checking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
