<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SLOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO STILL STUCK IN THE SLOW LANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Sun Tzu were still around, he would not look
kindly on the NATO air war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the nature of an army to stress speed,'' the Chinese
strategist wrote more than 2,000 years ago in his seminal text,
``The Art of War.'' The point of speed is to get to the battlefield
first, then to shock, disorient, demoralize, and ultimately defeat
the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after six weeks of dropping bombs, NATO's Operation Allied
Force has proved most notable for how slowly it got under way.
Diplomatic efforts, stepped up the past several days, may soon end
the war, but not before Slobodan Milosevic has accomplished his
main objective of ``cleansing'' Kosovo of its ethnic Albanians, a
process that NATO's bombing, for all its ferocity, did nothing to
stop or deter.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Could NATO forces have arrived in time at least
to have impeded the slaughter?
</P>
<P>
   In part, the dragged-out pace of the operation might be
attributed to the nature of alliance warfare, in which each of 19
democratically elected governments has a say over what targets can
be hit and whether certain options _ like sending in ground troops
_ can be contemplated, much less put in motion.
</P>
<P>
   However, military specialists say the sluggishness is also a
result of the structure of the US armed forces _ a cumbersome,
four-headed bureaucracy (Army, Navy, Air Force, Marines) that,
nearly a decade after the collapse of the Soviet Union, remains
tied to its Cold War moorings.
</P>
<P>
   Through the 40 years of East-West confrontation, US war planners
built massive forces of heavy armor, deployed them in fixed
positions (mainly in Germany and Korea), and trained the troops, by
and large, for one kind of contest.
</P>
<P>
   In the post-Cold War era, however, Presidents Bush and Clinton
have mobilized troops for dozens of crises, near and far. This
calls out for a force more agile, more easily transported, and more
flexibly trained.
</P>
<P>
   Military commanders have started to make adjustments of just
this sort. However, the efforts either have been half-hearted or
too recent to have any effect on the current conflict.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Army has initiated a concept called ``Force
XXI'' that aims to replace old-fashioned divisions, each of which
has about 20,000 soldiers, with Strike Forces, units of 3,000 to
5,000 troops tailored to specific missions and organized for rapid
deployment anywhere. However, the first experimental Strike Force
will not be ready for action until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't completed all the analytical work in terms of war
games . . . models and simulations,'' General John N. Abrams,
commander of the Army's Training and Doctrine Command, said in a
news release last month announcing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has been working on similarly scaled-down units,
called Airborne Expeditionary Forces. Organizational charts show 10
of these units, each composed of 150 aircraft, mixed and matched to
perform specific missions. While the Air Force concept has moved
farther along than the Army's, officials say it still is more
theoretical than real.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, when a president wants to dispatch troops, military
commanders have to dip into the large divisions, usually into
several at once, and to pull out the elements needed.
</P>
<P>
   This is one reason it took three weeks for 24 Apache
tank-hunting helicopters to arrive in Albania. Some of these were
taken from Army divisions in Germany, others from the United
States. M-1 Abrams tanks and M-2 Bradley fighting vehicles, sent to
protect the helicopters, were taken from other units. Some supplies
and support gear, as well as the trucks and jeeps to carry them,
came from still different units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting all these things together isn't as easy as it might
seem,'' said Frances Lussier, a military analyst at the Rand
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one-third of US troops are based overseas at any one
time, down from one-half 10 years ago, and regulations make it hard
to send more. Many soldiers are exempt from being sent abroad, such
as those who have served there in the past year or whose terms in
the military expire within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   So when the officer in charge of an Apache task force calls up a
commander and asks for M-1 tank crews, it might take a while to
find some who can go.
</P>
<P>
   Lussier calculated that it would take two or three months to
send 100,000 troops to Yugoslavia. ``At least a month of that,''
she said, would be the time it takes to assemble the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Once the commanders figure out who is going, they and their
weapons and logistical supplies are sent on special airlift cargo
planes and sealift ships. Ships carry a lot, but move slowly.
Planes are fast, but can't carry much. (The largest cargo-transport
planes, the C-5 and C-17, can carry only one or two tanks each and
nothing more.)
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the Pentagon has spent a lot of money on
airlifts and sealifts. Even as the number of US combat troops has
declined by a third, the number of cargo planes and ships has
risen.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration plans to spend $20 billion on the
lifts during the next four years. With operations and maintenance
costs, that balloons to $54 billion by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   This new emphasis on cargo transport grew out of the 1991
Persian Gulf War, when it took seven months to move enough troops
and weapons into the region to drive Iraq's army out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a ``rapid deployment force,'' initiated under the
Carter administration, was greatly expanded at an air base on the
Indian Ocean island of Diego Garcia and on three of the first
prepositioned ships. The Rapid Deployment Force evolved into the US
Central Command, which is geared to defend the Persian Gulf just as
NATO defended Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, an armored brigade today can be moved into Kuwait
within four days, one-fifth the time it took at the start of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   In parts of the world where ports and airfields are scarce,
however, these efforts only go so far. Another reason the Apaches
took so long to arrive in Albania was that Tirana Airport was in no
condition to receive them. The field where they were eventually
headed, near the Kosovo border, was in sorrier shape. Army
engineers had to get to the scene first to do renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all these new efforts, some officers say only a
wholesale restructuring would allow the military to move quickly
enough to deal with some crises.
</P>
<P>
   Army Colonel Douglas A. Macgregor, author of the 1997 book
``Breaking the Phalanx,'' is one of the most influential of these
new military thinkers. He proposes breaking the Army's 10 divisions
into 25 or 30 combat groups. Each would be tailored to certain
missions and would stay together and train together for those
missions. He calls the group a ``smarter, smaller, faster and more
technologically advanced warfighting organization.''
</P>
<P>
   These Combat Groups are similar to the Strike Forces of the
Army's Force XXI concept, except that Macgregor recommends joint
groups, with elements from the Army, Air Force, Navy, and Marines,
working together under one command as if the separate services did
not exist.
</P>
<P>
   In the upper echelons of the military, this notion is nothing
less than revolutionary. Except for the Air Force's airlift and
Navy's sealift, whose very existence is wrapped up in carrying Army
equipment, the services always have loathed cooperating with one
another in doctrine, weapons, or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Macgregor writes that unless they start cooperating and stop
buying redundant weapons systems, his strategy _ which requires
spending a lot more money on certain kinds of weapons and new
technologies _ would be too expensive even by hawkish standards.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy also requires some new weapons, most notably the
Armored Gun System, a tank that is much smaller, lighter, and
better-suited to cargo planes than the M-1. The Pentagon canceled
the gun system three years ago just as production was to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Macgregor _ who quotes Sun Tzu a great deal in his book _ now
runs the Joint Operations Center at NATO headquarters in Brussels
and serves as a chief aide to General Wesley K. Clark, the
commanding officer of Operation Allied Force.
</P>
<P>
   One Pentagon analyst who knows Macgregor's work said, ``He must
be having a very frustrating war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
