<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-ART     05-10 1723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-CARTER-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 TORONTO: ... to checking.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I told him that if he hit first, they wouldn't be so eager to
hit him,'' says Ballantine. ``As the tournament went along, he was
almost giving them the puck so he could check them.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 12, the Lions had become the Toronto Arrows,
a Double A youth team in the tougher Metro Toronto Hockey League.
They finished a surprising second that season, and Carter was one
of the leading scorers. By then, Ballantine was ready to send him
along to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was head and shoulders our best player by the time he
left,'' says the coach. But even then, his career ceiling seemed
limited. ``I thought he might go as far as major junior,'' says
Ballantine.
</P>
<P>
   His next year, with the Triple A Toronto Red Wings, proved a
revelation on two fronts for Carter. For one, he finally started to
get the hang of this skating thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was far from the best player on the team,'' he recalls.
``But I finished second in a skating drill one day and I thought,
`I'm not such a bad skater.' That's when it really dawned on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The other new experience was far uglier. For the first time,
Carter encountered racism. Not in Scarborough, where the fact that
he was one of a handful of black players was never an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always kid him,'' says Valma, ``that all his friends are
white.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a Christmas tournament in Guelph, an opponent from the
Detroit Little Caesars began taunting him with racial epithets.
Carter's response: ``Don't just talk, you wimp. Show it on the
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And Anson just dominated him in the game,'' says Valma. ``That
shut him up.''
</P>
<P>
   In college, there would be two more incidents. A Michigan player
directed racial slurs at him in one game, and one night while he
was indulging a longtime passion, surfing the Internet, a Michigan
student sent him an e-mail that said, ``Go back to your project.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter did not initially realize this was a slur; he didn't know
what a project was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither did I,'' said Valma. ``When Anson found out, he said,
`I'm going to send him back an e-mail telling him I'm not from a
project.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Valma persuaded him that he should not dignify the message with
a response.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put it behind you,'' she told him. ``That's how
you've been raised _ you take people for how they are, not for how
they look.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter says he has encountered no such hostility since, though
he was warned to beware when he came to Boston in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at it with an open mind,'' he says of the city. ``And
the people here have been wonderful. But I'm not so naive as to
think it doesn't go on. I'm a black athlete. I don't live in a
bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he joined the elite Tier II, Junior A Wexford Raiders at
17, Carter's NHL vision was still somewhat hazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just another way I could use to get a scholarship,'' he
said. ``But really, I was just having so much fun playing the game.
I'd hang out with my teammates off the ice. They were my best
friends. I loved going to tournaments where we could fool around,
almost get thrown out of hotels. I lived for the tournaments. I'd
circle the dates on the calendar.''
</P>
<P>
   But under coach Stan Butler, Carter and his parents came to the
realization that those early pipedreams were eminently reachable.
``I thought I had a good shot at the NHL,'' says Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, a Scarborough teacher-coach at the time who had seen
Carter star against his junior high teams in basketball and track
but was aware only of his raw athletic talent in hockey, was
convinced after one game in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Wexford, which was on its way to the Metro Junior Hockey League
title, was locked in a 3-3 tie against the mediocre Weston Dukes
with 10 seconds left. Butler still has the videotape of the game,
which was shown on cable. It shows Carter taking the puck at his
blue line, racing up the ice _ and being stopped by the Dukes
goalie's glove stab with two seconds left. Game? Not quite. The
puck slipped out of the glove, and with a lightning reach, Carter
poked it in with a half-second left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a basketball player following up his shot,'' says Butler
reverently. ``When I saw that play, I said, `This kid is for real.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his athleticism, the play reinforced Carter's development
into a legitimate skating force. When Butler got his first close
look at him on blades, he nicknamed Carter Dancin' Anson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the way he skated,'' says Butler. ``It was like he
was dancing on skates. He kind of ran on the ice, almost like a
sprinter that put skates on his feet. But he was such a good
athlete that I knew if he worked on his technique, he could be a
good skater. His athletic skills and intelligence and coachability
made up for that.''
</P>
<P>
   During the year he played at decaying Scarborough Gardens Arena,
which Brad Park's father helped build and was on the other side of
town from Carter's home, Butler put him through an array of drills.
His specialty was called the Snake, a series of zigzag maneuvers
that emphasized cutting back and forth on the edges, not going full
speed ahead on the blades. By the end of the season, Carter was a
polished skater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credit goes to him,'' says Butler. ``I had no doubts he
could make it to the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two avenues he could take. One was the traditional
Canadian route of playing major junior hockey. The other was via
college in the United States. The latter was Butler's calling card
_ 69 of his players earned college scholarships in five years, a
major reason Valma and Horace allowed their son to play for him.
</P>
<P>
   But they left the choice to Anson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played that summer against some Ontario Hockey League guys,
potential first- and second-round draft choices,'' says Carter.
``Granted, summer hockey is different, but I knew I could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he rejected the junior option, typically after thorough
research. There were two deciding factors.
</P>
<P>
   At 140 pounds, he didn't think he could endure the rigors of the
OHL schedule. ``I wanted to use the next four years to build myself
up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And he'd seen too many major junior players end their careers at
that level with nothing to show for it, including a degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``He determined that the educational opportunities weren't as
good in the OHL,'' says Valma. ``He'd see their players interviewed
on TV and say, `Look at that. They can't even speak the language.'
''
</P>
<P>
   ``The OHL was geared too much to hockey,'' says Carter.
``College offered a balance.''
</P>
<P>
   He found it in East Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State coach Ron Mason eagerly welcomed Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had really good skills,'' says Mason. ``I liked the way he
handled himself on the ice. And I loved the kid as a person, just
the way he came across. But you never know with any recruit how
hard he'll work, how much time he'll put in.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Mason didn't know how Carter would deal with a
demoralizing development from the previous summer. Eligible for the
NHL draft, he was selected by the Quebec Nordiques in the 10th
round, the 220th pick overall. That was a bit of a comedown for a
kid who fancied himself a premier prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was devastated,'' says Butler. But the snub did provide him
with a familiar objective. ``I wanted to prove them wrong,'' says
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   So he virtually took up residence in the weight room, bulking up
to his present 185 pounds. He got stronger on skates, tougher in
battling for the puck. He became a four-time All-American and
helped Canada win the 1994 world junior championship. After
expressing his doubts about going to the team tryouts and being
reassured by Butler that he belonged, he wound up on the first line
by the end of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anson developed,'' says Mason, ``as much as or more than any
player I'd ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   But his crusade on the ice did result in a change of plans.
Eventually, the classroom demands of medicine, especially the
chemistry load, proved a deterrent to pursuing world-class hockey.
So Carter switched his major to sociology, and while he intends to
pursue his degree, he doubts orthopedics are in his future. Other
things have come up.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't come to terms with Colorado, nee Quebec, and he
didn't get much of a look from Washington, which had acquired him
from the Rockies. But once he was obtained by Boston along with
Jason Allison and Jim Carey in the blockbuster that sent Rick
Tocchet, Bill Ranford, and Adam Oates to the Capitals on March 1,
1997, he began to find an NHL home.
</P>
<P>
   ``As limited as the chances were in Washington,'' says Carter,
``Boston gave me every opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Sinden, the Bruins' president and general manager, was
only too happy to oblige after hearing scout Gerry Cheevers tout
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got size, speed, good balance, doesn't get knocked off
the puck, and he's a fast, strong skater,'' says Sinden, unaware of
the dedication that went into that last attribute. ``He's a good
scorer and he's going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   He already is. Despite missing 27 games because of a holdout and
an ankle injury, Carter scored 24 goals this season. In the
playoffs, he truly has begun to flourish, as evidenced by his
double-overtime goal that beat Carolina in Game 5 of Round 1 and
his insurance goal in the clincher two nights later.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he hits the net,'' says Sinden, ``then the mind gets going,
it tells you you can do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Carter has been telling himself regarding one
subject or another for more than 20 years. True, his sole focus now
is hockey and he figures that after his playing career, he'll
pursue business, perhaps in music or entertainment, rather than
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't regret it,'' he says. ``I'm thrilled the way
things turned out. I set goals early and achieved most of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he'll redirect one of them. In the meantime, he
remains devoted to his family, splitting his summers between
California and his basement bedroom in Scarborough. He e-mails
Michelle constantly. And after every game, he telephones his
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the phone rings at 1 in the morning,'' says Valma, ``we
just say, `It's got to be Anson.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the hour, Mom and Dad answer the phone. They've
learned to pay attention when the kid speaks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
