<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-VOLCANO-BOS &LR;      05-10 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-VOLCANO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS WARILY EYE EXPLOSIVE NEIGHBOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO XALITZINTLA, Mexico _ From the concrete front step of
the tiny corner store he has run for 30 years, Fausto Soto has a
clear view of the towering mountain that he considers both a friend
and a potential killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afraid?'' asked Soto, 66, as his tired eyes took in the
18,000-foot peak, its shape an almost perfect cone. ``I only fear
an act of God, and if that happpens, then it happens. But I would
lose everything if that volcano erupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Most days, the first piece of news that people in this remote
hamlet get has something to do with their unstable, snow-capped
neighbor named Popocatepetl. It has been five years since the
volcano, known to all as Popo, awoke from a 75-year slumber. And
while it hasn't yet produced a major eruption _ the last one was
nearly 280 years ago _ it frequently coughs up rocks and sulfuric
ash and spreads panic as far away as Mexico City, about 40 miles to
the west. Some believe the worst is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volcano has its ups and downs,'' said Cervando de la Cruz,
a volcanologist at the Geophysics Institute at Mexico's National
Autonomous University. ``In November and December last year, the
activity increased. Lately, it's been quieter, but that's not to
say that the activity is lower.''
</P>
<P>
   The volcano poses a direct threat to a half-million residents
who live in its shadow, but de la Cruz said that even in a large
eruption, nearby major cities like the capital and Puebla probably
would escape with nothing worse than showers of ash. They are far
enough away not to be imperiled by lava or mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   On its crankiest days, the volcano, whose wide skirt touches the
states of Puebla, Morelos, and Mexico, can produce as much as
800,000 tons of sulfur dioxide and set off up to 200 microtremors,
according to the National Disaster Prevention Center.
</P>
<P>
   And if one unpredictable peak wasn't enough, another volcano in
the Pacific coast state of Colima last year began belching its own
noxious mix of steam and gas.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the daily updates for the communities closest to Popo are
as simple as a flag on the roof of a local municipal building. A
green flag means all is quiet. A red one means danger and is
usually accompanied by orders from government officials to head for
safer ground.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the flags are yellow, a sign that Popo is not an
immediate threat, but the possibility of a destructive explosion
exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there probably will be another eruption, but I don't
think any of us will be around to see it,'' said Juan Merino de los
Santos, a farmer wearing a straw hat. He was sworn in last month as
the mayor of Santiago Xalitzintla, whose town square is only 10
miles from Popo's crater. ``The only alarm we have is the church
bell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Government disaster officials have had mixed results in
developing evacuation and contingency plans in case Popo blows.
Each of the surrounding villages is marked with rectangular
green-and-white signs and an arrow directing people where to go
should lava or mudslides begin to flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have exercises and everyone knows we're supposed to go to
the next hill,'' Merino said. ``And we can only take what we can
carry.''
</P>
<P>
   But a poll last year by Mexico's Civil Protection Agency found
that 40 percent of the residents of the 12 highest-risk communities
were not familiar with evacuation routes.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency workers say designing an effective contingency plan
has been complicated by a lack of money, the remoteness of some
communities, and the challenges of training mostly poor and
uneducated residents. But perhaps the biggest challenge has been
trying to put a scientific, modern-day face on a mountain that most
people in this area worship like a god, or talk to like a loyal
companion. Many here still make regular pilgrimages to the mountain
to deliver gifts ranging from bottles of tequila to pairs of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mount Fuji in Imperial Japan, or Vesuvius in Roman-era
Italy, Popocatepetl is as much about legend and history as it is
geology. Poems, stories, and songs have been written about the
Aztec warrior who was returning from battle at last to see his
love, Iztaccihuatl.
</P>
<P>
   Before he arrived, Popo's enemies told her that he'd been killed
fighting. Distraught and unconsolable, Iztaccihuatl died from
sadness. When he learned of her death, the warrior laid Izta's body
on one mountain range, while he knelt at her side.
</P>
<P>
   In the Aztec language of Nauhuatl, Popocatepetl means ``smoking
mountain,'' and Iztaccihuatl means ``mountain of the white woman.''
The two are depicted _ as humans and mountains _ in Mexican
paintings and calendars.
</P>
<P>
   Another tale, told mostly by locals, is that the volcano is a
kind and poor man named Don Gregorio Chino, who was looking over
his wife, Dona Rosa, while she slept. But she never woke up and he
stayed with her until they turned into mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are more than volcanoes,'' said Homero Aridjis,
president of PEN, an international writers group, who is a renowned
poet and has written extensively on the two peaks. ``They've always
been seen as a romantic, mythic couple, and they've always been
present in Mexico's story.''
</P>
<P>
   It was through the gap between the mountains that the Spanish
conquistador Hernan Cortes and his troops passed on their way to
the Aztec city of Tenochtitlan, known today as Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Aridjis and others also believe that the recent volcanic
rumblings are sending an end-of-millennium message. Popo began
erupting in 1994, the year that Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo
took office and devalued the peso in an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The country's capital, Mexico City, was once the center of Aztec
culture, with a clear view of the mountains. Today it is a densely
populated metropolis of 20 million, plagued by poverty, government
corruption, crime, and choking air pollution. Only on a rare clear
day can the mountains be seen at all from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent deforestation around Popo by paper companies has
increased the chances of deadly mudslides if an eruption occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message to the people today is that Mexico is
deteriorating and it's being sacrificed,'' Aridjis said.
</P>
<P>
   But poets aren't the only ones fixated on the volcano.
Government geologists use satellites, video cameras, and radars to
monitor its activity. There are 14 seismic monitoring stations
around the mountain and five prisms to monitor the crater.
Recently, NASA officials were called in to help.
</P>
<P>
   Volcanologists say Popo's most violent eruption happened 23,000
years ago, with a force equal to that of the Mount St. Helens blast
in Washington in 1980. Popo's last eruption with possible victims
was in 1720, according to the Disaster Prevention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Even the thought of a major eruption has been enough to scare
away some Santiago Xalitzintla families. Since Popo started moving
again five years ago, Merino estimates that the population has
fallen from about 9,000 to 6,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Juan Jimenez Castro, a 44-year-old part-time farmer who
still remembers the childhood hikes he took up the mountain with
his father, says the shakes and smoke don't scare him anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens so much now, we get used to it,'' Jimenez said.
``We can't live in fear. We just keep telling ourselves, `There
goes the Big Chief again.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
