</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WAR WAS DESTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid a sudden, confusing war, an editorial in The Boston Globe
on June 18, 1898, noted the noisy swapping of plumage among hawks
and doves of the time, much like the cacophony in today's political
aviary:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, by the irony of fate, a war which the Democrats forced
upon the Republicans has in its progress compelled the two parties
to make an exchange of positions, the radicals of two months ago
becoming the conservatives today, while the conservatives then are
the radicals now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meanwhile, the American people as a whole are astraddle the
fence of doubt, whittling the stick of silent reflection. In other
and plainer words, for once they are stumped! Even Boston, which is
the greatest compounder of solutions for all problems that vex the
minds alike of the finite and the infinite, discovered when its
wisdom was assembled in Faneuil Hall on Wednesday that there was no
complete solvent ready made for this most novel and unforeseen
occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe referrred to the Anti-Imperialist League's first
meeting, in Faneuil Hall, on June 15, four months after the USS
Maine exploded in Havana harbor. Presiding was George Boutwell,
former US senator and former secretary of the treasury. Notables
from the Boston bar and the Harvard faculty sought to halt the war
fever sweeping America.
</P>
<P>
   The league's principles, opposing American annexation of former
Spanish colonies, attracted former president Grover Cleveland;
philosopher William James; novelists William Dean Howells and Mark
Twain; and, in an unlikely pairing, labor leader Samuel Gompers and
industrialist Andrew Carnegie, who sent Gompers a telegram saying,
``Let us stand together to save the Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuba and Puerto Rico were close to America, but the Philippines,
distant and exotic, seemed a greater prize. The Anti-Imperialists,
wrote Barbara W. Tuchman in ``The Proud Tower,'' ``were attempting
to hold their country back from plucking the archipelago in the
Pacific, which seemed to glow with the fatal evil of the apple in
the Garden of Eden.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Finley Peter Dunne's fictional bartender, ``Mr.
Dooley,'' chided his customer, Mr. Hennessy, who said, ``I'd hist a
flag over th' Phlippeens, an' I'd take in th' whole lot iv thim.''
</P>
<P>
   ``An' yet,'' said Mr. Dooley, ``tis not more thin two months
since ye larned whether they were islands or canned goods.''
</P>
<P>
   The war began at the urging of ``the yellow press'' and the
recitation of Spanish atrocities, real and imagined, filled
American newspapers. American naval and military might crushed
Spain's empire in a few months. President McKinley, reluctant at
first, said acquiring new colonies, including Hawaii, ``is Manifest
Destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, the Globe addressed ``the inner circles of the
professed advocates of peace'' and concluded: ``The one and only
way to secure a speedy and honorable peace lies through a vigorous
prosecution of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State John Hay called it ``a splendid little war,''
but every war has unintended consequences. In the Philippines, US
troops took three years to suppress rebels led by Emilio Aguinaldo,
who believed that the Americans came to liberate, not conquer,
those whom the new military governor, William Howard Taft, called
our ``little brown brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, the mood was expansionist, even imperial. Today,
humanitarian motives ignite the explosives of war and reverberate
with similar instincts of self-admiration. The Boston Globe was the
first newspaper to syndicate Chicago's Dunne, whose ``Mr. Dooley''
predicted quick victory in Cuba: ``Morro Castle'll cave in, and th'
air 'll be full iv Spanish whiskers. A long blow, a sthrong blow,
an' a blow all together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a gr-reat people,'' said Mr. Hennessy, earnestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ar-re,'' said Mr. Dooley. ``We ar-re that. An' the best iv
it is, we know we ar-re.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
