u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-10 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEEHAN'S MISSION IS HONEST POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ At the last count, there were 191 members of the
House of Representatives all committed on paper to forcing campaign
finance reform legislation onto the floor for that simple act the
moneyed interests fear most _ a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the cause, every one is a Democrat (not
counting Vermont independent Bernie Sanders), which means that once
again where a major issue is concerned, one key to the outcome will
be how certain kinds of Democrats and certain kinds of Republicans
deal with each other. And in this case, that means the largest
share of the work across the aisle will have to be done by
Representative Marty Meehan of Massachusetts, Democratic chief
sponsor of reform and ally of the Republican chief sponsor, Chris
Shays of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   It is tough, grinding work, building a case for a member of the
other party to take a position against his leadership on an issue
that concerns the very business of getting elected. In this
situation, Meehan needs to find 26 GOP members.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Meehan is likely to find the GOP allies his
cause requires _ either for a petition forcing a vote or for
persuading the GOP leadership to allow one, rather than be forced
to. One reason he's likely to be successful is that he's been
successful before (last year 61 Republicans in the House made the
Shays-Meehan legislation legitimately bipartisan).
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, as campaign finance reform was beginning to
come to a head in the House last week, Meehan at last got off his
duff and quietly announced _ via a letter sent to every household
in his district _ that he is in fact running for a fifth term next
year.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal under normal circumstances, except that Meehan is
the only Democrat trapped by a pledge made years earlier in support
of the moribund term-limits movement. For a spell early in his
career here, he did talk some of the talk and walked some of the
walk, though he has never resembled the fanatics who came along two
years later as part of Newt Gingrich's revolution-that-wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, what he has done as a congressman belies his earlier
stance and underlines the overriding need for veterans here in an
era when problem-solving has eclipsed crusading as the major job
requirement. Seniority per se is not the point; mere length of
service doesn't count for much anymore, but what does is the
ability to work across the aisle at a time when no matter which
party is in the majority, its margin is not going to be large
enough to govern without the other party's help and therefore input
on major issues.
</P>
<P>
   That's true about all the big entitlement programs from Social
Security to Medicare; it's true about regulating HMOs; it's true
about the next step in the tobacco wars; and it has always been
true about campaign finance reform in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, in fact, was a part of the realistic efforts to effect
change from almost the beginning. After Bill Clinton's election in
1992, the stalemate on this issue was framed not just by
conservative intransigence on behalf of the big-money status quo
but also by liberal Democratic proposals to regulate federal
elections in excruciating detail and to introduce public financing.
The only hope for bipartisanship was to focus on eliminating the
most egregious abuses _ above all, the unregulated cash called soft
money and the phony ``issue'' ads that special interests finance.
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas remain at the core of the Shays-Meehan legislation
in the House and of the counterpart being pushed in the Senate by
Republican John McCain of Arizona and Democrat Russ Feingold of
Wisconsin. The Republicans Meehan will recruit to help put the heat
on Speaker Denny Hestert to schedule a vote can trust him to keep
the Democrats' end of the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   When Meehan ran in '92, it was the time not only of Bill
Clinton's moderating influence on the Democratic Party, but of Ross
Perot's healthy bucket of cold water on traditional politics.
Before Perot undercut his own movement via personal antics, it had
made several major contributions to the political atmosphere with
its emphasis on sane budget policy, problem-solving, and clean
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Term limits were in the mix back then, but over time that hot
button's temperature has cooled, for all the right reasons. Ability
is what counts, which is why decisions by people like Meehan to
stick around will be welcomed far more than condemned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
