<SLUG> BC-HOOKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING FOR RETIREMENT AND KIDS' EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both 43 and we plan on retiring at age 58.
We also intend to help our daughters, aged 10 and 5, with their
college expenses. Currently my wife and her employer contribute
$7,000 a year to a 401(k) account which now amounts to $135,000. It
is invested in these Vanguard funds: 10 percent each in a money
market fund and an investment contract, 20 percent each in Index
500, Windsor II, and International Growth. I am a teacher, and at
retirement I will receive benefits representing 70 to 80 percent of
my average salary for my final three years. I also contribute
$1,100 a year to a 403(b) account, which now stands at $46,000. Of
this, $35,000 is in Fidelity Growth and Income fund and $5,500 each
is in Fidelity Equity Income I and Fidelity Equity Income II. All
of my current contributions go into the Growth and Income fund. We
also contribute $350 quarterly to our older daughter's college fund
and $250 quarterly to our younger daughters fund. Both accounts are
in Fidelity Growth and Income, and each stands at $6,500. Finally,
the older child has $9,000 invested in Janus fund. Do you feel we
have allocated the money correctly? I attach a list of the options
for my wife's 401(k). We are considering increasing my wife's
contribution to the 401(k). Should we contribute more to the
children's funds instead?
</P>
<P>
   K.K., East Longmeadow, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, it seems to me that you have established very little
real diversification, even though you're using a number of funds.
With the exception of your international fund and the two
fixed-income funds, virtually all of your savings are focused on
large-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   I would make two suggestions for your 401(k). The first is to
swap one of the three large-cap funds (Index 500, Windsor II and
U.S. Growth) for Vanguard Explorer fund, which holds a small-cap
portfolio. Second, I suggest you rethink the 20 percent of the
401(k) portfolio which is split between the money market and
savings trust accounts. If you insist on having a conservative base
for the portfolio, I would suggest that money go into Vanguard
Wellington, where roughly a third of the portfolio is invested in
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   You don't spell out the options that are available within your
husband's 403(b) program, but I'd seek similar diversification
there _ an ideal makeup might be 50 or 60 percent large cap
(represented by the three funds he now owns) and the balance
divided equally among a mid-cap, a small-cap, and international,
and (in a perfect world) a health care sector fund.
</P>
<P>
   My tally shows that with your ongoing contributions, your 401(k)
program will grow to $717,410 in the course of 14 years, a tally
which presumes average annual portfolio growth of 10 percent. Under
the same assumptions and with ongoing contributions at the same
level, your husband's 403(b) account would reach $206,857 in the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this, combined with your husband's pension, is likely to
be sufficient for your retirement is a determination you'll have to
make for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   As for the children's accounts, you've probably worked these
calculations out before, since the answers show you'd have fairly
similar amounts saved for each child by age 17.
</P>
<P>
   Again assuming average 10 percent returns, the 10-year-old would
have $44,091 in the combined Fidelity and Janus accounts at age 17,
while the five-year-old's account would grow to $42,757 by the time
she is 17. Whether this is enough depends on two factors _ one is
whether the children attend public or private schools, and the
other is what you mean by the word ``help.'' The current edition of
``Paying for College Without Going Broke'' by Kalman A. Chaney and
Geoff Martz projects average college costs in the year 2006 at
$11,591 for a public school and $29,808 for a public school. For
the younger child, presumed to be ready for college in the year
2011, the projected bill would be $14,793 for a public college and
$38,043 for the average private school.
</P>
<P>
   So if by helping you basically mean paying the bill, you'll
probably need to save a lot more for both if they go to private
schools; if they will likely go to public schools, you'll need to
save a little more for the older child and quite a bit more for the
younger.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, I hope you have been maintaining these educational
accounts in your own name; the accumulation of significant assets
in the student's name sharply reduces her prospects of winning
financial aid packages. If you have been saving in the children's
names, I suggest you immediate stop contributing to the accounts
and put all further savings in your own names.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You frequently refer to Vanguard's and Fidelity's funds, but
I rarely see references to those of the Janus fund family. I check
in the (papers periodically, and I find Janus funds seem to do as
well or better than the funds at Fidelity. What am I missing? My
wife has about $100,000 to invest. We have a number of other
investments in various categories as well. as well. What do you
suggest?
</P>
<P>
   B.M., San Diego &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You aren't missing anything. Janus is a fine fund family, and
if I write about it less than its larger peers, it's simply because
many of my correspondents have established relationships with the
bigger companies. If I were to select an all-purpose portfolio
among Janus' funds (there is, of course, no such thing) I'd put 50
percent in either Janus fund or Janus Growth and Income, 20 percent
in Janus Overseas, 15 percent in Janus Venture, and 15 percent in
Janus Balanced. All of these funds get four- or five-star ratings
from Morningstar Mutual Funds, with the exception of Janus Venture,
whose three-star rating reflects the generally dismal small-cap
growth sector in recent years, rather than a poor performance
relative to its peers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
