<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRASS-ROOTS IDEA YIELDS SCHOLARSHIPS FOR STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How many times a month or a week do you feel
your heart sink at the hopelessness of it all? Need. Pain.
Inequity. Everywhere. Where do you start? What can one person do?
Especially if a person is not Bill Gates?
</P>
<P>
   Henry Safrit, a San Francisco endocrinologist, has an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago _ before they could think about it too long _ he
convinced four of his friends to engage in some radical but
practical philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Each pledged $500 a year for four years and turned the money
into a $10,000, four-year college scholarship to be awarded to a
senior at a public high school in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The following year Safrit button-holed more friends, and five
more $10,000 scholarships were awarded. The year after that, there
was enough money for nine. This year, after reviewing more than 100
applications, the advisory board for the Meritus College Fund will
present a dozen $10,000 scholarships to financially needy students
in San Francisco public high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's philanthropy at an affordable level,'' said Carl Berry,
whose wife is one of the original Safrit Five. ``And the best part
is, you get involved with the life of your scholar. It can be
anything from having them to dinner to providing summer employment.
But it's much more than writing a check.''
</P>
<P>
   Nestor Navidad, a San Francisco State University sophomore, is
representative of the Meritus winners. His mother, a 34-year-old
Salvadoran immigrant, supports her two children by baby-sitting and
house cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Navidad's energy and 3.5 grade point average convinced his
teachers and a counselor at Galileo High to urge him to check out
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wasn't sure I would make it because of all the money you
have to pay,'' he said. ``My mom can't possibly pay for college for
my sister and me.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many academic awards and scholarships, Meritus is not a
one-shot deal. It's $2,500 a year for four years, so long as
students keep their grades healthy. The kids get every cent that is
given because all administrative costs are donated.
</P>
<P>
   Safrit, a native of North Carolina native and a graduate of Duke
University, had grown frustrated over the years with
bureaucracy-heavy endowment giving ``where they take the interest
out each year and a little of the money trickles down to the
scholar.'' After several years on the board of a youth center, he
thought: ``Why not figure out a way to help needy kids who want
help?''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Berry's wife, Linden, then a counselor at Washington High
School, helped find the student pool that produced the first
winner. Now scholars from all San Francisco high schools can apply.
</P>
<P>
   To give the group tax-exempt status _ yes, donations are tax
deductible _ a lawyer did the legal work pro bono. There is a
four-person interview panel.
</P>
<P>
   Safrit's home doubles as the fund's business office. Scholar-
winners help out with paper work and the Wells Fargo bank has
kicked in $5,000 this year for administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, everyone involved is a middle-class working Joe
who has an interest in education and wants to make a difference,''
Carl Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing proprietary about what we do,'' Berry said.
``Anybody who wants to get five people together _ or however they
configure it _ is welcome to join us. We'd like to raise more money
and have more kids apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, unlike most other scholarships, Meritus is looking not
for the students with perfect 4.0 grade averages, but for those
with 3.5s or even 3.2s _ children who show promise and a
willingness to work. Reflecting the population of San Francisco's
public schools, most of the scholars are minority students, and
many are the first members of their family to attend college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are mesmerizing,'' Safrit said. ``They're so much fun
to be with. Most of them have had so little in their lives _ many
of them are from immigrant families _ yet, in spite of all these
roadblocks, they overcome them. We (the donors) probably get more
joy out of it than the students do.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For information about Meritus, call 415-922-7630.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
