<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEELE CASE UNDERSCORES TRUE STARR MOTIVE: VENGEANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The mistrial in the Julie Hiatt Steele case underscores the
misguided motives behind Kenneth W. Starr's investigation of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel indicted Steele because she did not
cooperate with him during his $40 million failed quest to ``get
Clinton.'' She was the first and only person in the White House sex
scandal to be indicted by Starr. And now a deadlocked jury has
refused to back up his charges in a case that never should have
been brought.
</P>
<P>
   According to Starr and his colleagues, Steele was indicted for
lying and obstructing Starr's investigation of Clinton when she
refused to corroborate Kathleen Willey's charge that Clinton made
unwanted sexual advances to her, including groping and kissing her.
</P>
<P>
   As the story goes, Willey told Steele of the president's
behavior. Willey also told her story to Newsweek, and the magazine
in turn called Steele to corroborate the story, which she did. But
Steele later called Newsweek and asked that it not publish the
story because Willey had asked her to lie to the reporter. She said
Willey's account of Clinton's unwanted advances was not true after
all.
</P>
<P>
   With Steele recanting her story to Newsweek, Starr was left
without a corroborating witness to Willey's story, which she
broadcast in her appearance on CBS-TV's ``60 Minutes.'' Shortly
after that, Willey's credibility began to crumble when stories
about earlier lies and her continued efforts to be close to Clinton
were published.
</P>
<P>
   Even in cross-examination at the Steele trial, Willey, with the
facts confronting her, was forced to acknowledge discrepancies
between the statements she gave to Paula Jones's lawyers in Jones's
lawsuit against Clinton, and the statements she later gave to
Starr's investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In her 1998 deposition in the Jones case, Willey couldn't
remember where the president groped her or put his hands, or even
if he kissed her. According to one report, Willey said ``I don't
recall'' 63 times during the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, she seemed to remember in detail everything about
the event, including where the president put his hands and that he
kissed her. One of those accounts had to be untruthful.
</P>
<P>
   Insteading of indicting Willey for lying, and even after it was
clear she lied about her relationship to another man, Starr gave
her further immunity. Even Linda Tripp reportedly gave a different
version of what Willey told her about the events and what Willey
had told prosecutors. That means either Tripp or Willey had to be
lying, but neither was indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Steele, however, was indicted, and the only reason apparent is
that she ruined Starr's chances of making Willey's charge of
unwanted sexual advances stick against the president. Thus, his
desire to ``get Steele'' by indicting her for obstructing justice
and lying to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration of a mistrial helps to demonstrate that Starr's
indictment of Steele is simply another example of his blatant abuse
of the power of his office.
</P>
<P>
   With the impeachment trial over, with a federal judge making a
final statement by holding Clinton in contempt for lying during the
Paula Jones case, and with the news media now focused on Kosovo and
Belgrade, the Steele case appears to have been not only unnecessary
but also a complete waste of taxpayer money _ yet on Friday,
Starr's prosecutors said they were weighing whether to seek a
retrial. Then again, a prudent use of taxpayer money was never high
on Starr's agenda; getting Clinton, by almost any means, was.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Starr must be seen as the big loser in this case. As
for Steele, it may be some consolation to her that she will come
out of this looking a lot better in the public eye than Starr, who
will now look only worse.
</P>
<P>
   And if any legislator had any doubt as to whether the
independent counsel law should end, never to rise again, all he or
she has to do is to review the Steele case and see all the
vindictiveness, mean-spiritedness, and abuse that Starr has heaped
upon her simply because she would not do his bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's reputation will be permanently tarnished; he walks away
with guilt, or should, knowing that he destroyed or harmed the
lives of many people who got in his way during his relentless
pursuit of the president.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to think that someday Steele and other victims
of Starr's investigation might finally see him come to justice. But
for it to be truly appropriate justice, one of his victims would
have to exercise the same vindictive power over him that he has
wielded over them. And to find one who could be just like Starr
would be virtually impossible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
