<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AMA-IMAGE-BOS &LR;      05-10 1833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AMA-IMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMA IN DANGER OF VANISHING FROM THE SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When thousands of doctors converge here in June for
the American Medical Association's annual meeting, it will likely
be the most harmonious gathering of its kind in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Not because the AMA has won over its critics. There are more of
them than ever and they're madder than ever _ over everything from
the firing of Dr. George Lundberg, the AMA journal's top editor _
to a series of more recent troubles and firings. But that anger has
made many simply give up on the AMA, canceling plans to attend the
annual meeting, or, if they go, deciding it will be futile to raise
a challenge. All of which threatens the once-omnipotent doctors'
lobby with irrelevancy, the one fate it fears more than its current
controversies.
</P>
<P>
   And unless it can somehow reinvigorate itself, it'll be more
than doctors who have lost a voice. At a time when health care is
resurfacing as perhaps the most contentious issue in the country,
patients, too, will be without a potentially potent advocate
against limits imposed by managed care, Medicare cuts, and other
moves to retrenchment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who would be willing to criticize and stand up are just
drifting away. Doctors are saying this whole thing is just
irrelevant,'' worries Dr. Raymond Scalettar, a former AMA chairman
who has led reformers in unsuccessful bids to overhaul the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to Europe instead of to the annual meeting. It's the
first meeting I'll miss in 25 years . . . but it's the only message
I can send.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Delbanco, a Harvard Medical School professor who edits a
monthly column in the Journal of the American Medical Association,
is sounding a similar alarm: ``One would hope that a loud voice
from the doctor would represent the public interest rather than
purely self interests. I have so little faith in the AMA being that
way with its current configuration that I'm embarrassed by their
pretending to speak for doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Randolph Smoak, the current AMA chairman, is much more
upbeat. ``I believe our organization is working well,'' he says.
``Like any others, there always will be a few little glitches, but
you have to look at how strong we are. We have a wonderful
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the media tends to concentrate on the negative and I
think that is unfortunate, in my view. I hate to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult not to zero in on the negative given what's been
happening recently at the nation's biggest organization of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Start with membership numbers. The AMA today represents about 35
percent of America's physicians _ down from 90 percent in the 1950s
and 50 percent in 1975. The erosion has continued, albeit more
slowly, over the last five years, and there is speculation that
when the newest numbers are out they will show a further decline,
probably inspired by the firing of Lundberg as editor of the
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors around the country, especially younger ones, simply
don't think the AMA is relevant to their practices or their
patients, and they don't want to spend the $400 or so a year it
costs to be a member. Others are joining societies representing
their speciality, say dermatology, and feel that such groups offer
more than the AMA in scientific and political guidance.
</P>
<P>
   What the specialized groups don't offer is a broad-based
direction for the nation on such pressing issues as insuring the 44
million Americans without health coverage, restructuring Medicare,
and ensuring that managed care doesn't ride roughshod over
patients. These are the sorts of practical and ethical challenges
that a general medical society like the AMA historically has
addressed here, although it generally has seemed more concerned
with the interests of doctors than patients. And they're the sorts
of broad-based challenges that medical societies still devote major
attention to in other Western nations.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last several years, however, the AMA has had to focus a
disproportionate amount of energy on internal controversies,
leaving its senior staff with less time and fewer resources to
devote to broader social issues.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the deal, unveiled in 1997, in which the AMA
would have received millions of dollars for endorsing humidifiers,
blood-pressure monitors, and other products made by Sunbeam Corp.
The plan was dropped after AMA members questioned the ethics of the
agreement, but the executive vice president had to resign, Sunbeam
sued and settled for nearly $10 million, and a recent independent
report accused AMA trustees of failing to properly police the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the firing, in January, of JAMA editor Lundberg,
who over 17 years had built the journal into one of the world's
most respected medical publications. The AMA said Lundberg had
stepped over the line by running an article that touched on
presidential sex and impeachment politics, but critics around the
world accused the association of improperly interfering in
editorial decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been other, quieter problems. Like the summary
dismissal, a day before Lundberg, of the AMA's top mental-health
specialist for allegedly inciting trouble by questioning a staff
reorganization. ``The only thing I had incited people to do was
talk to one another,'' responds the ousted Dr. Larry S. Goldman,
who is back teaching at the University of Chicago and says the AMA
has tried to keep him from communicating with former colleagues by
screening out his e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   The man behind the firings was Dr. E. Ratcliffe Anderson Jr., a
retired Air Force general brought in as executive vice president to
help restore the AMA's frayed image in the wake of the Sunbeam
fiasco. Instead he has created new waves of controversy. And last
month new doubts about his leadership were raised when a Missouri
court ruled it had been illegal for Anderson, in his former post as
head of a Kansas City hospital, to try and fire the chief of
radiology who'd been critical of him.
</P>
<P>
   While rumors contine to swirl that Anderson's job is in
jeopardy, AMA insiders insist that he actually is consolidating
control, and that the AMA board backed his firing of Lundberg and
other controversial moves. Anderson declined repeated requests for
interviews and has shunned the press since the Lundberg firing. But
Smoak, the AMA board chairman, says that ``since Dr. Anderson came
on board last summer we have been on course and our vision
certainly has been strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there have been several things that had to take
place that not always were pleasant and there were issues that
needed to be addressed and he addressed them properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say recent developments reflect a disturbing pattern _ of
Anderson using military-like discipline to purge the AMA of
critics, of the AMA board failing to anticipate or know how to
extricate itself from controversies that have plagued it, and of
the organization becoming so mired in internal machinations that it
has lost its impact on wider health issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pattern of disrepect, if you will, for due process,''
says Dr. Robert Kaiser, a gastroenterologist from a suburb near
here who tried unsuccessfully to get the Illinois State Medical
Society to take action on the Sunbeam and Lundberg cases.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jerome P. Kassirer, editor-in-chief of the New England
Journal of Medicine, also is distressed, by the firings as well as
the AMA's seeming move to the ideological right as evidenced by its
backing of a proposed ban on ``partial-birth'' abortions. ``I think
it has lost enormous ground,'' Kassirer argues. ``Though it says it
speaks for American medicine, it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Many at AMA headquarters share those concerns, but are taking a
wait and see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   They're waiting most especially for the blue-ribbon panel of
independent doctors that the AMA has named to select a new JAMA
editor and to set up new rules to ensure the journal's
independence. While panel members decline to discuss their work
publicly, privately they say they're hopeful Anderson and the AMA
board will give JAMA the assurances it needs _ and if not, the
panel will abandon its search.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bracken, head of epidemiology at the Yale School of
Medicine, also is in what he calls ``a state of watchfulness'' over
the search for an editor and a wall of separation between the AMA
and JAMA. If such a separation is not assured, he adds, scientists
may stop submitting research papers to JAMA.
</P>
<P>
   While the search process proceeds, JAMA staff say they are
putting out the best publication they can. ``We're not standing
still, ringing our hands,'' says Phil Fontanarosa, the interim
coeditor. ``We're launching new initiatives, moving ahead with new
projects.''
</P>
<P>
   The JAMA search also could influence how much contention there
is when 4,500 or so doctors convene here for next month's AMA
annual meeting, which starts June 20. Some, like Kaiser, are almost
certain to mount a challenge, and at least one reformer will take
on a board-supported candidate for the vice speaker's post.
Delegates also will confront the cotentious issue of whether the
AMA should form a union-like collective bargaining unit.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Webster of Wisconsin, an AMA delegate and former
president of the American Academy of Dermatology, is hopeful the
AMA can emerge from its June meeting ready to tackle the
considerable challenges facing it. ``Am I optimistic?'' he asks.
``It's going to be a tough job, but if the AMA should fold we would
have to have another AMA-type organization to represent physicians
and the professional and ethical aspects of medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more doubtful that the association can turn things
around. ``I haven't tossed in the sponge on the need for organized
medicine one bit, but what I have decided is that unless there's
some miracle turnaround in the AMA House of Delegates or board,
then an alternative to the AMA has to evolve,'' says Dr. Jerald
Schenken, who served on the board from 1985 to 1994, tried
unsuccessfully to get the executive vice president's job in 1989,
and has long been a leader among would-be reformers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are beginning to give up on the AMA all over the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the opposite is happening in Britain, where ``the British
Medical Association is in the forefront of arguing against nuclear
war and smoking, and for seat belts and human rights,'' says Dr.
Richard Smith, editor of the British Medical Journal, which has the
same relationship to the BMA that JAMA does to the AMA. ``And more
than 80 percent of doctors here belong to the BMA, which is the
highest it has ever been. That's partly because it negotiates terms
and conditions for doctors in the National Health Service, but also
because it does a very good job positioning itself alongside
patients.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
