<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTY IS ONLY PEOPLE DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Teeth are important,'' Burt Bacharach tells People magazine.
This carries a lot of weight, coming as it does from one of the 50
Most Beautiful People in the World.
</P>
<P>
   It's that time of year again. A taste for the absurd draws me,
year after year, to the magazine's Beautiful People issue. Burt
Bacharach? But who am I to doubt the testimony of Angie Dickinson,
his ex-wife twice removed, who tells People, ``Not only is he
devastating-looking but he has this gentility about him, with lots
of strength but also a softness, like a prizefighter carrying
flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, readers can count on this issue of People to be
irresistibly ridiculous. It starts with the premise. The 50 Most
Beautiful People in the World? Says who? That's one of the reasons
people buy this issue, the editors note, to see how People's
choices compare to their own.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the editors seem to have taken particular pains to
diversify, and by so doing to challenge readers to expand their
personal definitions of what constitutes beauty. Along with
Michelle Pfeiffer, Joseph Fiennes, Ben Affleck, et al., the crop
includes Sudanese model Alek Wek, 63-year-old actress Gena
Rowlands, plus-size rapper/actress Queen Latifah, 70-year-old
composer Bacharach, and a number of other beauties of various
races, ethnic backgrounds, ages, sizes. This is commendable, I
guess, but it doesn't make the premise any less absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the emphasis on diversity hasn't changed People's
peculiar editorial approach to its Beautiful People. This year's
emphasis is on personal grooming. What do Beautiful People do to
stay beautiful? Teeth are important, as Bacharach points out.
Melina Kanakaredes, star of the television drama ``Providence,''
concurs, confessing she never goes anywhere without her Braun
electric toothbrush. ``My parents were always saying, `Cavities!
Cavities!' Now I have a mouthful of them,'' she tells People
ruefully.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these revelations are delivered in an almost nannyish
tone, as if People's editors are bent not just on revealing the
beauty secrets of the fabulous 50 but on exhorting readers to
improve their own grooming habits, perhaps even by purchasing some
of the products conveniently advertised in its pages. So brush your
teeth. And do something about your hair. ``For guys, your hair is
your feature,'' says ``well-chiseled'' sculptor Toland Grinnell.
Skin, though, is most crucial, or ``skin is in,'' as People puts
it.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we learn that actor Rick Schroder of ``NYPD Blue''
cultivates his ``sun-cured skin,'' naughtily ignoring his wife's
sensible suggestion that he apply sunscreen. ``I'm going to look
like Robert Redford when I'm 40, very weathered and leathery,'' he
tells People hopefully. But, he adds, ``I think I need to start
adding some moisturizer, because my skin gets really dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Moisturizer looms large in these pages, which must please some
of People's bigger advertisers, such as Pond's and Revlon. Actress
Jennifer Lopez is ``never without moisturizer'' and switches brands
every few months because ``I feel my skin gets tired of just one.''
ITN news anchor Daljit Dhaliwal keeps a supply of Elizabeth Arden's
Eight-Hour Cream handy at all times.
</P>
<P>
   No reader can know for sure why some celebrities fail to make
the Beautiful People list. Maybe it all comes down to who has the
most aggressive publicity agent. I wonder if certain obvious
candidates were crossed off because they failed to meet People's
grooming standards. Julia Roberts, for example. But for those
much-publicized, and much-photographed, hairy armpits she might
have knocked Pfeiffer off the magazine's cover. Or maybe she
doesn't use enough moisturizer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
