<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BAR-CODES-BOS &LR;      05-10 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BAR-CODES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BAR CODE, AT 25 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago this June 26, an Ohio supermarket
executive named Clyde Dawson whisked a 67-cent ten-pack of
Wrigley's Juicy Fruit over a strange new contraption and officially
launched a now ubiquitous piece of technology, the supermarket
checkout scanner.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Dawson's successful test at the Marsh Supermarket in
Troy, Ohio, more than 27,000 US supermarkets have installed
scanners. The concept of scannable bar codes has boomed beyond
grocery stores to find uses in everything from processing mail and
medical samples to managing car-parts inventories and airline
baggage.
</P>
<P>
   The basic idea behind supermarket scanners is that most of the
tens of thousands of items for sale are identified by a unique
12-digit number. That number in turn is represented by a series of
lines and spaces of varying widths (30 lines and 29 spaces, as a
matter of fact, whatever the number).
</P>
<P>
   When a low-powered laser light is shone on the bar code, more
reflects back from the gaps than the lines, telling a reader inside
the machine what the product is. (Most shades of red cannot be used
anywhere in a bar code because lasers cannot see them.) The
supermarket's computer then reports the current price and deducts
the item from recorded inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Reading a bar code from the way it reflects light is a tricky
enough thing to do anyway. So scanners compensate by taking a vast
number of readings _ usually thousands per second.
</P>
<P>
   The typical supermarket scanner sends out a pattern of laser
light reflected off several mirrors by a spinning mirror.
Reflections are focused by a reading lens, then the machine
determines which images it sees are valid codes.
</P>
<P>
   Most supermarket bar codes consist of 12 numbers. The first
digit corresponds to a class of goods _ including 0, 6 or 7 for
general groceries, 2 for produce and meat, 5 for coupons, and 3 for
drugs and pharmacy goods.
</P>
<P>
   The next five digits are the manufacturer's code, and the next
five are specific to the item. Take a 10-ounce box of regular
Cheerios, 0 16000 66510 1: 16000 is General Mills's number and
66510 corresponds to that size and type of Cheerios. Other sized
boxes, frosted and honey nut have their own 5-digit reference.
</P>
<P>
   The 12th digit of a UPC code is called a ``modulo check digit.''
Odd and even numbers in the first 11 digits are multiplied and
added through a surprisingly complicated equation to yield a 12th
number, the check digit.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is unlikely that the hairs on a checkout
person's wrist would somehow correspond to the UPC number.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what a scanner does, in fact, involves ``filtering out
noise'' to determine what things it sees are really bar codes, says
Craig Maddox, product line director for bar code scanners with NCR
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of codes mounted on round cans or lumpy surfaces,
machines will take multiple readings from different directions,
then combine them to see what the code would look like if perfectly
flat.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers on the right side of the label are also represented in
mirror image from numbers on the left side, so if the machine reads
a can of corn upside down, it can figure out where the code begins
and ends.
</P>
<P>
   And some can even read ripped or damaged codes: When President
George Bush was caught in 1992 expressing seemingly
out-of-touch-with-reality amazement at the workings of a bar code
scanner, he was actually at an industry convention observing a
machine able to read a UPC code ripped into seven pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller products like cigarettes and baby food jars carry
seven-digit numbers. Through a technique called ``zero
suppression,'' 0s are omitted but in such a way the machine can
determine where they would fall in the underlying 12-digit code.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1970s, most scanners failed to read codes as often
as three times out of 10, Maddox said. The main reason was badly
printed UPC labels, aggravated by limited ability programmed in to
the machine to make sense of blurred labels.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Maddox said, the typical scanner gets 99 out of 100 items
on the first pass, reflecting tougher standards for producing UPC
labels and more intelligent code reading programs.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to develop something like the UPC system date back to
the late 1940s, including a failed system that used bullseye-like
patterns. A key 1969 grocery-industry summit led in March 1973 to
agreement on the linear bar code system.
</P>
<P>
   A Dayton, Ohio, organization called the Uniform Code Council
oversees issuing code numbers. It has signed up an estimated
210,000 manufacturers, and it costs a minimum of $350 to get a UPC
code.
</P>
<P>
   Because like phone numbers in area codes the supply of 1
trillion possible UPC numbers is nearing practical exhaustion, the
council has urged retailers to prepare for 13-digit UPC numbers
beginning in 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
