<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-STONES-ART-BOS &LR;      05-10 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-STONES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S A HONKY TONK FARMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ The last time Chuck Leavell appeared in
public, he was banging out ``Sympathy for the Devil'' on the
keyboards as Mick Jagger and the Rolling Stones preened before
20,000 screaming fans in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But when the ``No Security'' tour ended last month, the Georgia
piano player didn't follow his bandmates off to jet-set vacations.
Instead, he traded in the glitz for tweed, and went to the
ivy-decked halls of Yale University to lecture on conserving
American forests.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary meeting of the worlds of rock 'n roll and
elite academics, Leavell came to America's oldest forestry school
last Monday to tell the story of his award-winning tree farm where
men named Baby Joe and Bimbo work the land and where the
conservation ethic comes from a deep Southern sense of place and
family.
</P>
<P>
   Leavell's appearance turned staid college professors into
autograph hounds, and prompted organizers from the Yale Forest
Forum to sneak in a baby grand piano in hopes that he would play.
(He did.)
</P>
<P>
   Leavell, in turn, was touched that Yale would want to hear his
story. A musician who has performed for tens of thousands with
entertainers from Eric Clapton to the Allman Brothers to the
Stones, Leavell seemed awestruck by his audience of 150.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a high school dropout to be invited to Yale to talk about
anything, it's quite an honor. I'll cherish it for the rest of my
life,'' said Leavell, with a Yale School of Forestry and
Environmental Studies pin on his lapel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Leavell had a message beyond celebrity. Unlike other
rockers-turned-environmentalists such as Don Henley and Sting,
Leavell gets his hands dirty managing the environment, spending
long days on the tractor at his 1,900-acre farm, Charlane.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Leavell spoke for an often-overlooked group in the
environmental debate, private individuals who own much of the
American landscape. He called for conservation, to be sure, but he
also warned against laws that tie the hands of owners, preventing
them from logging or hunting on their land.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the 47-year-old self-described ``rock 'n roll tree
farmer'' is an enigma, living two lives that seem incompatible. On
the farm outside of Macon that he owns with his wife Rose Lane,
Leavell is up by 6 a.m., preparing for the day's chores. On tour
with the Stones, 6 a.m. is more likely to be bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   But Leavell, a dapper, gray-bearded man who speaks in a gentle
drawl, has no problem moving from one job to the other, eagerly
heading for the woods whenever he gets home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are 180 degrees apart as far as lifestyles, but I find
the farm really provides a psychological balance . . . It allows
you to get perspective on what is really important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Leavell talks about managing the land in much the same
way that he talks about the blues music he grew up with in rural
Alabama. Both are inheritances that need to be passed down to the
next generation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's the other members of the Rolling Stones who have a hard
time understanding Leavell's farm life. Sure, drummer Charlie Watts
has a horse farm, but he doesn't actually ride the horses. And
Jagger once complained that publicity for Leavell's tree farm
diverts attention from concert ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scratch their heads a lot about it. They're amused about
it, but they know I'm sincere,'' said Leavell, who has tried in
vain to get fellow Stones to visit his tree farm since he began
touring with the band in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Leavell is good at growing pine trees, and
protecting nature as well. He and his wife have set aside 20 acres
of nature trails, they invite school groups to tour the land, and
they leave aside portions of the property for duck, quail, and
other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition, Leavell has twice been named Georgia Tree Farmer
of the Year, and he is currently up for regional tree farmer of the
year. Now, along with University of Georgia officials, he is
writing a book on the history of forest management.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Leavell is not a typical celebrity environmentalist,
appearing at benefits for the rainforests and the like. Leavell
says society must balance the need to preserve trees with
humanity's voracious appetite for wood products from his own piano
to the morning newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ecologists' view that you should never cut a tree, never
dig a hole, never kill a thing . . . That's not reality,'' said
Leavell.
</P>
<P>
   Leavell knew almost nothing about forests until 1981 when his
wife inherited a run down cattle and vegetable farm from her
grandmother. The farm had been in the family since the 1920s, but
it carried a large tax liability, and he was too busy touring to
pay the tab by tending a conventional farm.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of keeping the farm together, Leavell tried
tree-farming, which required less day to day management. In 1982,
he took a correspondence course in tree farming through the Georgia
Extension Service, and Leavell's second career began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were touring with the Fabulous Thunderbirds and I'm sitting
in the back of the bus doing my homework: trees, trees, trees,''
recalled Leavell.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Leavell's accomplishments as a tree farmer, he was
stunned when Yale forestry graduate student Alex Finkral e-mailed
him with an invitation to speak at Yale. The Yale Forest Forum,
after all, is a place where distinguished scientists and
policymakers, such as the head of the US Forest Service, hold forth
on important subjects such as forest ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe that I'm at Yale University,'' said Leavell,
beaming from behind the podium. ``I feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the audience gamely tried to stick to the subject of
Leavell's talk _ even asking about his hardwood management strategy
_ questions eventually turned to the Rolling Stones, and Leavell
confessed that he is awestruck, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mick Jagger is the most amazing front man in rock 'n roll,''
said Leavell. ``I'm up there playing and I can't keep my eyes off
Mick because he is so entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   As for lead guitar player Keith Richards, known for his hard
partying, Leavell called him a masterful musician though ``some
people may wonder why he's still walking the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Leavell finished his talk, followed by a rollicking
version of ``Route 66'' on the baby grand, forest management had
given way to standing ovations and celebrity worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a crack up. All the professors are asking for
autographs,'' laughed professor Lynne Bennett, clutching the
promotional poster Leavell signed for her.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Leavell's message of balance in the woods wasn't lost in
the hoopla. ``What he is doing is so monumentally important, not
just maintaining the property . . . but building on it in a
creative way,'' said Yale lecturer and Stones fan Paul Draghi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
