</P>
<P>
   CHINA-Y2K (Beijing) _ China is just now waking up to the idea
that on Jan. 1, 2000, some of its computers may think it is Jan. 1,
1900. Experts in China warn that the country could suffer
everything from severe disruptions in power and water to lesser but
still expensive glitches in and transportation. And China's woes
could spill over to Hong Kong, where banks, brokerages, and
shipping companies with close ties to the mainland are worried
about lost cargo and missing payments. Yet so little is known about
the nature of the problem here that the experts are often reduced
to a digital-age version of reading tea leaves. By Mark Landler.
</P>
