<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: &LR;  The following is the budget for the New
Scientist for material available the week of Mon., May 10 and
anytime thereafter. This material is free for use for New York
Times News Service clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HACKERS HAVE FIELD DAY WITH FREE WEB MAIL &LR;  _ Free Web-based
e-mail services are vulnerable to hackers, according to findings by
an Internet security consultancy in Maryland. They found that the
three biggest Web-based e-mail services failed to provide a basic
security feature that helps keep hackers out. By Duncan
Graham-Rowe. 400 words. (slugged:
BC-HACKERS-ON-THE-WEB-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SNORING KILLS &LR;  _ Studies in Sweden and Australian show that
women who snore when they are pregnant may be at risk of developing
dangerously high blood pressure. Around 10 percent of pregnant
women suffer from pre-eclampsia, where high blood pressure can lead
to injury or even death in the mother and the fetus. By Nell Boyce.
400 words. (slugged: BC-SNORING KILLS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BACTERIA THAT GORGE ON ROTTING WASTE CAN BREAK DOWN DDT &LR;  _
Chicken manure, old newspapers or straw can be used to clean up
land contaminated with dangerous chlorinated pesticides such as
DDT, Canadian scientists say. They used soil bacteria that feed on
rotting waste to break down hazardous substances to less toxic
byproducts. By Matt Walker. 600 words. (slugged: BC-GREEDY
BUGS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW ALERTING SYSTEM FOR TSUNAMIS &LR;  _ Japan should soon be able
to get advance warning of tsunamis, the giant waves that create
havoc when they hit the coast. A new alerting system uses Global
Positioning System navigation satellites to monitor the vertical
motion of a buoy moored out in the ocean. By Peter Hadfield. 400
words. (slugged: BC-TSUNAMI-ALERT-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
