<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIETY-HUMILIATION-B     05-10 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIETY-HUMILIATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CORROSIVE EFFECTS OF HUMILIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Humiliation is the feeling that, it seems, is the most difficult
to talk about. It is familiar to every second-grader who got no
valentines, to every youngster chosen last in a pick-up game, to
every person ostracized by the in crowd. It is also visited on
those oppressed and persecuted by force, from the victims of
colonialism to the women raped as part their expulsion from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the wake of the tragedy in Littleton, it is a feeling
very much on the minds _ if not the lips _ of those who have
suffered through it, or witnessed its searing force.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its cousins _ embarrassment and guilt _ humiliation is an
emotion that often does not erode with time. It can linger a
lifetime. It can also build.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Campbell was 5 when her North Charleston, S.C.,
kindergarten teacher wrote on her face with an indelible blue
marker, ``Where are my glasses?''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the kids teased her; the bus driver on the way home said
`What happened to you?','' recalled Teresa Campbell, Nina's mother.
``She was in tears when she got off the bus and when she got to my
door she was devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   The words were visible for two weeks. Now, three years later and
after a successful lawsuit against the school district, Nina still
suffers the sting of that humiliation, her mother said. Adding to
her confusion: The woman who wrote on Nina's face was nominated
this year as teacher of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Humiliation _ being stripped of one's dignity _ does something
to the psyche that other emotions, such as shame, cannot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You live with shame, you may feel badly about yourself, but
you try to restore your own self-regard, and within a few days, it
washes away,'' says Dr. Lloyd Sederer, medical director and
executive vice president of McLean Hospital in Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Humiliation is shame squared.''
</P>
<P>
   One hallmark of humiliation is the difficulty we have talking
about it, or sometimes even acknowledging it. We can talk about the
embarrassing time we tripped, or didn't zip our pants. We can
acknowledge guilt by confessing it, apologizing, and moving on. In
fact, June Tangney, a professor of psychology at George Mason
University who specializes in the psychology of shame and guilt,
says feeling and expressing guilt is a sign of an empathetic
person. ``It is related to positive aspects of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But not so with humiliation, which is something people have
great difficulty in expressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never confess to anyone the things that humiliated us;
they are the things you don't reveal to anyone,'' says William Ian
Miller, a professor at the University of Michigan Law School and
author of ``Humiliation: And Other Essays on Honor, Social
Discomfort, and Violence.''
</P>
<P>
   We are most likely to be humiliated during adolescence and as we
grow old because both are periods when our sense of self and our
capabilities often collide.
</P>
<P>
   In old age, as the mind or body can no longer do what one
expects it to do, the result is something much deeper than
embarrassment. In adolescence, there is great importance in how
others perceive you, in the regard you are afforded. Insults,
ostracism, both can weigh heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value that (lies) in the formation of identity of
adolescents is critical,'' says Sederer. And adolescents most
frequently measure themselves against their parents, which makes it
even harder to turn to those parents for support in difficult
times.
</P>
<P>
   While no one knows what drove Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold to
murder 12 of their fellow Columbine High School students, a
teacher, and then take their own lives last month, several students
of the clique to which the 17- and 18-year-olds belonged have
detailed a litany of abuse that some members of the so-called
Trenchcoat Mafia suffered at the hands of the more popular,
powerful jocks. There were constant taunts, they say, ranging from
``dirtbag'' to ``faggot,'' physical abuse such as being slammed up
against lockers, pelted with rocks and sodas, and forced to bus the
jocks' trays in the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Ethicist Sissela Bok, a distinguished fellow at the Center for
Population and Development Studies at Harvard University and author
of ``Mayhem: Violence As Public Entertainment,'' cautions that it
is impossible to pinpoint one source for the motivation of the
killers, but says that humiliation plays an important role in many
murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people to be able to cross the line and kill another human
being, several things have to happen,'' Bok says. ``First of all,
they have to have the feeling that this is authorized, as in war
where it is ordered, or they belong to a group or a cult that
regards it as all right. A big difference is also if they can talk
themselves into thinking `Those people are humiliating me.' . . .
We know that almost all serial killers were tremendously abused as
children, and humiliation is one part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Can anything good ever come of feeling humiliated? There are
those who say yes. ``To be able to harness the energy that is
unleashed in people who have been humiliated, and use it in a
productive way, can make someone go a long way,'' says Rev. Richard
E. Spalding, co-pastor of the Church of the Covenant, in Boston's
Back Bay, whose recent sermon dealt with Columbine and humiliation.
``Look at Nelson Mandela. Apartheid was an ironclad system of
humiliation which required the degradation of people and he was
able to harness the energy out of that for change without rancor.''
</P>
<P>
   Humiliation can also galvanize a nation. Jesse Jackson's 1988
campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination in large part
relied on the theme of ``I am somebody,'' his longtime clarion call
to the young, the dispossessed, the humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more and more courts around the nation are including
humiliation as part of their sentencing. Drunk drivers are forced
to put warning stickers on the bumpers of their cars; men arrested
for soliciting prostitutes have their pictures published in local
papers; and pedophiles have warning signs placed on their lawns.
</P>
<P>
   There is no data, however, to indicate that humiliating an
offender is anything more than a quick fix of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you shame an offender, as opposed to encourage them to
grapple with the bad effects of their behavior, it does not
encourage people to take responsibility, but elicits increased
anger and rage,'' says George Mason's Tangney,. ``Research shows
this is a misguided approach.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one federal judge agreed, striking down as
unconstitutional New York City's celebrated and storied ``perp
walk,'' where those arrested are paraded in front of the media. The
case was brought by a doorman who was arrested for theft, paraded
before cameras, lost his job, and later was acquitted of the
charges. His trial for damages is scheduled to begin next week in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways to overcome humiliation, some more successful
than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of diminishing the pain, if you can find islands of
dignity in this ocean of humiliation, it helps,'' says Sederer, the
McLean physician. ``As you build up the islands, and the mass is
greater, you may be on land more often than drowning in the ocean.
But does the water ever go away? Not in cases where the humiliation
is profound and overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to accomplish this, he says, is to work to spare others
the same experience you have suffered. That gives someone purpose,
which gives dignity.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the advice that Jesus gave his disciples _
turn the other cheek _ to, as Rev. Spalding put it, ``cultivate an
inner landscape that makes it possible not to return evil for
evil.'' And in some ways, that can be an antidote to humiliation,
specialists say. The act of choosing not to do something, in this
case to offer the other cheek, can help restore honor that was
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most frequently employed method and least likely to
succeed against humiliation is denial, or its flip-side, limitless
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever one thinks of President Clinton, his ability to
continue to do his job while the impeachment effort (and all its
sordid manifestations and revelations) took front and center in the
nation's consciousness for more than a year was nothing short of
remarkable. ``How could anyone go through that and not be
humiliated?'' Miller asks. ``Clinton is one of those people with an
infinite reservoir of self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   Humor, too, is a powerful defense against humiliation. Certainly
professional comedians like Rodney Dangerfield and filmmaker Woody
Allen have made careers out of appearing as failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using humor is a complex move,'' says Miller. ``By making that
claim, it preempts anyone from humiliating you. There is the
refined sense that the smarter people are the ones who see their
own flaws. People understand that as a threat, and know the barrels
could be turned on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sederer says that by exposing your own humiliation through humor
you are controlling it and the ``trauma is often digested.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dangerfield says his motives are much more simple. Asked why
he developed his ``no respect'' shtick, he responds: ``When `The
Godfather' came out, it was filled with respect: `You got to show
me respect.' `You got to show her respect because she is with me.'
All I heard was `respect' `respect' `respect.' I thought there
might be a cute thing there if I turned it around.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I wrote one joke: `I played hide and seek and they wouldn't
look for me. I tell ya, I get no respect.' I tried it out, and it
worked, and I wrote thousands of `no respect' jokes. I thought
people might identify with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if they don't want to talk about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
