<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOILING PROPERTIES OF WATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why, when a metal spoon, cold or hot, is dipped into a
recently boiled cup of coffee, does the coffee start boiling again
for a moment?
</P>
<P>
   M.H.N.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Bring a cup of water to a boil, then let it set until it
stops boiling. Drop in a tea bag, and the water starts boiling
again briefly. The water should be cooler at that time. What's
going on here?
</P>
<P>
   J.R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a perfect example of the first law of thermodynamics:
nature conserves energy. Put another way, nature is efficient. It
will always use as little energy as possible, and use whatever help
it can get to do the work required.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, water can get superheated, which is hotter than
212 degrees Fahrenheit without boiling, supercooled, which is
colder than 32 degrees F without freezing, or supersaturated, which
is greater than 100 percent humidity without changing from vapor to
liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Converting matter from a solid to a liquid or from a liquid to a
gas, called a phase change, takes work. It requires energy to
rearrange the molecules. The part of that change that requires the
most energy, the part nature least likes to do, is getting the
phase transition started.
</P>
<P>
   Water is a great example. It takes a certain amount of energy to
heat water. But it takes extra energy to make the jump from one
state to another. To change water from liquid to gas requires extra
energy to get the first little bubbles going. Think of it like
pushing a car that's standing still. It takes more pushing to get
it moving, then less to keep it moving.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows that water boils at 212 degrees Fahrenheit, and
freezes at 32 degrees F, right? WRONG. Those temperatures create
energy states that are just enough to get a phase change started if
efficient nature has some help. (That's where your spoon and tea
bag come in. More on that in a moment.)
</P>
<P>
   Without help, something to provide a little extra energy, the
water can get much hotter, or colder, and remain liquid. According
to Jeff Tester, Director of MIT's Energy Lab, the world record
temperature for superheated water before it boils is 535 degrees
Fahrenheit. The world record for supercooled water is 36 below
before it freezes (Both are under normal sea level atmospheric
pressure.)
</P>
<P>
   Superheating, supercooling, or supersaturation can happen when
the water molecules are very still, and very pure, without other
molecules around them. Under those conditions, nature has to do all
the work to get the phase transition started. It's like just one
person pushing the car to get it rolling.
</P>
<P>
   But nature tries to conserve energy. It will look for any help
it can get, just like we look for partners to help push the car to
get it moving. It finds that help in tiny impurities in the water,
or imperfections in the surface of whatever's holding the water,
even in just the movement of the water itself. All those things
jostle the H20 molecules just enough to release some of their
stored energy. That jump-starts the process to get the boiling
going at or near 212, and the freezing going at or near 32.
</P>
<P>
   Did you ever hear that water vapor in the air needs a speck of
dust or something to use as a nucleus around which to condense into
a raindrop? That's an example of supersaturation. The air can be at
100 percent humidity, completely water vapor, but not have liquid
rain, because it's supersaturated. The speck of dust, or wind that
bumps water molecules into each other, is enough to jostle some
stored energy out of those molecules and get the phase transition
from vapor to liquid started.
</P>
<P>
   You can see superheated water by watching a pan of water start
to boil. The bubbles start at the bottom of the pan. In part that's
because that's where the water gets hottest first. But it's also
because of microscopic imperfections in the surface of the pan.
Just before they boil, the water molecules are superheated, hotter
than 212. Those imperfections in the pan disturb the water
molecules in those spots, tapping their stored energy, helping
nature create bubbles there first.
</P>
<P>
   Now we finally get to your spoon and tea bag. The cup of water
or coffee that just stopped boiling is probably still superheated,
a few degrees hotter than 212. Ready to boil again, with a little
help. Jiggle the water molecules with your spoon, or throw in a tea
bag,and you've released some stored energy from the water
molecules, enough to get the boiling going again momentarily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
