</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-POWER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US UNEASY AS UNRIVALED POWER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States is in an uncomfortable place in
the world this spring, not only because it is the planet's only
superpower, not only because there are rogue nations around the
globe brandishing terrifying arsenals, not only because
humanitarian crises beg for its attention and intervention, not
only because the world waits for its leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the United States is in an uncomfortable position
because the nation _ so powerful, so prosperous, so secure _ is so
unsure about how to use its power outside its own borders. Even
with the emergence of a framework for settling the Kosovo crisis,
the question is still unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to decide this, and probably soon,'' says Michael
Klare, a military specialist at Hampshire College.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Republicans and Democrats agree, we haven't decided.
We haven't even decided that we have to decide.
</P>
<P>
   For a whole decade, since the collapse of the communist bloc in
1989, the United States has stood alone at the apex of world
influence, occupying a position of power that, in this century, the
British, Germans, and Soviets all aspired to _ but never achieved.
And for much of that decade the debate over how to wield American
power _ a subject that dominated American civic life in the
Eisenhower and Kennedy years _ was little more than a theoretical
curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   It was conducted in graduate seminars and at resort conference
centers, but not on the campaign trail, not in the chambers of
Congress, not in coffee shops or Little League bleachers, and not
in the most rarefied reaches of the White House, State Department,
and Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish there were a prescription for this,'' says Brent L.
Scowcroft, the national security adviser to President George Bush,
``but there isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, of all the hard questions in Washington today _ how to
fix Social Security, whether to tinker with Medicare, when to raise
the minimum wage _ this may be the hardest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, answering that question would not have been
hard,'' says Francis M. Bator, a Harvard University professor of
political economy who was deputy national security adviser to
President Lyndon B. Johnson. ``There is no good general doctrine
with any bite that would help a president make these kinds of
decisions. Anyone who will lay one out to you is a bit of a fool.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a conundrum of consequence not only for the United States
but also for the world; a nation that spends more on defense than
the next 10 countries combined has the ability to impose its will
on the world if it wishes, to direct the attention of the world to
international crises if it likes, to mobilize world opinion if it
desires.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the failure to address this question is visible in the
large issues prompted by the Kosovo crisis, such as how to decide
whether to intervene in problems around the world. But it is also
evident in the smaller issues, such as how to prevail once American
interests are identified and American forces are engaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a conflict, you want your enemy to be dead sure
of your objectives and completely unclear on your tactics,'' says
Richard Armitage, a defense official and foreign-policy negotiator
in the Reagan and Bush administrations. ``Right now the enemy is
unclear on the objectives, but they are dead sure of our tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Stirred by the war in Yugoslavia, the unease with which
Americans watch the hopelessness of the ever-growing group of
refugees, the open-ended nature of the NATO military operation, and
the dwindling hopes for a swift solution to the problem, these
important questions are finally beginning to bubble to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``A democracy goes to war very sloppily, with all sorts of
different perspectives, depending much on the course of events,
depending in part on the security interests involved,'' says Morton
Abromowitz, senior fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, top diplomatic thinkers say, the United
States should not plunge into military action without a consensus
on what American national interests are, how much sacrifice in
blood and treasure the nation is willing to make, how much
political support there is for intervention, and how much loss
public opinion will bear.
</P>
<P>
   But first a superpower like the United States must sort through
all the issues competing for its attention, establish its
priorities, and weigh them against its national interests.
</P>
<P>
   Though American policymakers have been chary of defining US
national interests, there is little disagreement that the United
States certainly has a stake in maintaining stable relations with
major powers, such as China and Russia; and probably has a stake in
addressing any aggression taken by rogue countries that can do a
lot of damage to the nation's geopolitical and economic security,
such as North Korea and Iraq; and might have a stake in events with
humanitarian consequences.
</P>
<P>
   It is the latter that is problematical and is causing problems
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a country with values and TV sets, and we look at what
goes on in these places, we don't like it, and we want to stop
it,'' says Robert Zoellick, who was undersecretary of state in the
Bush administration. ``The difficulty is deciding how much we want
to pay in terms of lives and money to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the crisis in Kosovo is so unsettling to American
policy makers. The human suffering is as obvious as it is
unbearable. It occurs in an area that may be of little consequence
to the United States but is nonetheless consequential to its
neighbors, including Greece, Turkey, Hungary, and Romania _ all
nations with longtime ties to the United States, emotional if not
political, and all nations whose stability is essential to the
overall stability of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people over there are suffering like hell, but lots of
people are suffering in the world,'' says James E. Auer, a
political scientist at Vanderbilt University. ``The president
apparently thought you could kind of get involved. You can't kind
of get involved. Vietnam should have told us that: You either
fight, or you do not fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Many times, the United States has decided not to fight.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s alone, deadly civil wars have raged throughout the
world, including two in the Horn of Africa, Sudan and Somalia; two
in central Africa, Rwanda and Burundi; two on the west coast of
Africa, Angola and Liberia; and two in Eurasia, Yugoslavia and
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Besides an intervention in Haiti, close to American shores and
American hearts, and a brief and uncomfortable foray into Somalia,
the United States has decided to intervene only in the former
Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. Five years later, US
forces remain in Haiti; four years later, in Bosnia. All signs
point to an eventual long-term US presence, probably a peacekeeping
role, in Kosovo once a peace agreement is reached and ratified.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda, where at least a half-million people perished, has
provoked guilt in the American conscience, and Clinton went so far
as to apologize to the Rwandan people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1100 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-POWER-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-BO     05-10 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-POWER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (w and i coding)  
 WASHINGTON: ... Rwandan people.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The question is where you can make a positive difference,''
says Michael E. O'Hanlon, a fellow in foreign-policy studies at the
Brookings Institution, the Washington think tank. ``You can
eliminate a few easily; it would have been insanity to risk a
wide-scale war by getting involved in something so important to the
Russians as Chechnya. In some of these civil wars, you couldn't
even figure out what to do once you intervened.''
</P>
<P>
   These problems seldom affected earlier generations of Americans.
Presidents George Washington and Thomas Jefferson warned Americans
to avoid entangling alliances. Both warned Americans to remain free
of foreign disputes, a notion that was brought home to Jefferson in
the breach as he was dragged deeper into the Napoleonic wars that
engulfed the continent of Europe in the first decade of the 19th
century.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, however, Americans tended to their own knitting. The
United States stayed out of the Crimean War, resisted entry into
World War I until the last year of combat, was essentially a
bystander during the Spanish Civil War, and desperately tried to
avoid World War II. The United States joined the latter conflict
more than two years after it began, and then only when it became
impossible to stay out _ even though humanitarian factors not
unlike those in Yugoslavia might have provided an adequate reason
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed when the war ended, leaving Germany and Japan
all but destroyed as world military powers, the British Empire
fatally weakened, and China in turmoil. More important still, the
end of the war also left the Soviet Union empowered by its
territorial grabs in Eastern Europe and its expansionist ideology
and the United States strengthened by the economic leaps that
wartime mobilization brought to the only major combatant whose home
territory escaped damage.
</P>
<P>
   Then, despite a small remnant of isolationism, the United States
swiftly acquired a broad international role, with broad
international responsibilities. The globe was convulsed in an
ideological struggle, with capitalism and the United States
battling communism and the Soviet Union (and, after 1949, China).
Small wars were fought for big stakes in Korea, Vietnam, Central
America, the Caribbean, and central Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But the end of the Cold War in 1989 brought an end to these
regional brush fires stoked by global ideology. It ended the
artificial stability imposed on regional and ethnic warriors by the
two superpowers. It also ended the ease with which, for a brief
window in our national history, the United States decided whether
to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've historically had this problem, but it's even worse now
because of the deep ambivalence in Washington over whether the
United States should use the power it has, a power that is
indisputably the greatest power in the world,'' says Klare, the
Hampshire College specialist in military affairs. ``American
leaders, both Democrats and Republicans, are having trouble making
those decisions _ and are even having trouble deciding what is an
American interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Bator, the former Johnson adviser, believes Kosovo may offer
some hints about how to think about these questions. ``Foreign
policy has to deal with trying to use whatever influence we have to
create an environment where the United States can continue to
thrive as a disorganized, messy, decentralized, open society,'' he
says. ``That is the fundamental national interest. So this is more
than a humanitarian question. We have a stake in a decent world
order, just as the rich man with a big house on the hill has a
stake in the surrounding countryside being pretty peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   But determining American interests is only the beginning, most
specialists agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a problem that's getting worse, you look at the
tools you have, all the way from diplomacy to the use of force,''
says Scowcroft, the Bush-era national security adviser. ``If it
comes to the possibility of force, you need to figure out whether
it will do the job. But you have to ask: How much will it take? How
much will it cost? And can you sustain the support of the American
people for doing it?
</P>
<P>
   ``And if the answers all are `yes,' he continues, ``you still
have to ask whether you can get the Americans out when it's over.
There aren't many places where the answers to all those things are
`yes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Political leaders of both parties agree that President Clinton
has offered a rationale for US intervention in Kosovo, but no road
map for deciding whether to intervene elsewhere. Indeed, most of
his comments have been very narrowly drawn.
</P>
<P>
   To the convention of the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees on March 23, he said: ``So what do we learn
from Bosnia? We learned that if you don't stand up to brutality and
the killing of innocent people, you invite the people who do it to
do more of it. We learned that firmness can save lives and stop
armies.''
</P>
<P>
   To the American Society of Newspaper Editors on April 15 he
expanded his explanation somewhat: ``We are in Kosovo because we
care about saving lives and we care about the character of the
multiethnic post-Cold-War world. We don't want young democracies
that have made the right choices to be overwhelmed by the flight of
refugees and the victories of ethnic hatred. We don't want to see
Europe re-fight with tanks and artillery the same battles they
fought centuries ago with axes and arrows. And because stability in
Europe is important to our own security, we want to build a Europe
that is peaceful, undivided, and free, a Europe where young
Americans do not have to fight and die again to deal with the
consequences of other people's madness and greed.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now Americans are fighting but not dying in Eastern
European combat, conducting an antiseptic air war that offers
Americans limited exposure to risk but also offers NATO limited
potential for success. The reason is admirable but constricting:
Clinton and his advisers will brook no large-scale American
casualties, a strategy that is derided by some of his critics but
is supported by decades of poll data.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively low number of civilian deaths seems to have kept
American concerns to a minimum over the broader costs of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, neither the president nor the Republicans who are
eager to succeed him have engaged in a larger debate over why, and
how, the United States might get involved in world problems in this
difficult new era of American leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two questions,'' says Senator John F. Kerry, the
Massachusetts Democrat who sits on the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee. ``How should we decide? And how have we decided? At the
very least, we need very large interests at stake and a significant
amount of diplomatic effort that is finally exhausted, along with
defining the effort and educating the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the moment, we haven't gone to war,'' Kerry adds. ``That's
the anomaly. The country in no way feels it is at war, and there's
no impact here, other than budgetary, that might suggest we are at
war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1101 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SOAPS-BOS &LR;      05-10 1786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOAPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE SOAPS DEAD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sorry, 19-time nominee Susan Lucci. ``The Daytime Emmy Awards''
airs on May 21, and the favored candidate for best soap-opera
actress is Kim Zimmer from ``Guiding Light.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer, already a three-time winner, performed a beloved soap
trick last year when she played two identical characters at once.
But don't think Zimmer's double duty was for some ordinary
evil-twin plot, or for the sort of multiple-personality psychodrama
that has kept five-time winner Erika Slezak of ``One Life to Life''
busy and dizzy for decades. Zimmer became both feisty Springfield
resident Reva Shayne and a new gal in town by the name of Cleva,
who was Reva's . . . clone! Yes, thanks to the scientific ambition
of daytime TV writers, clone Cleva looked precisely like Reva right
down to the DNA _ except, of course, for that telling scar on her
arm. How can Academy voters resist those teary scenes of Cleva
dying in Reva's embrace?
</P>
<P>
   Soap operas sure aren't what they used to be. With overall soap
ratings declining about 25 percent in the 1990s, the classic
daytime genre has spent the last few years going through a peculiar
identity crisis that has reached beyond cloning to include Satanic
possession, angelic visitation, alien romance, and, thanks to some
cursed jewels, mummification. From the popular ``The Young and the
Restless'' to the struggling ``Sunset Beach,'' many of the 11 soaps
now on the air are toying with ways to attract and keep the
shrinking audience of 18-to-34-year-old women, TV viewers who spend
their nights watching ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and ``The
X-Files.'' While soap honchos are honoring soap conventions _ there
are still plenty of love triangles, clingy ex-wives, and
kidnappings _ they're also working to move an old-fashioned genre
into the future, beckoning to viewers whose tastes range from MTV
to ``The Jerry Springer Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Two recent events reveal a soap world in the throes of change.
</P>
<P>
   --The biggest lather has been over the cancellation of ``Another
World,'' a 35-year-old warhorse that will offer up its final visit
to Bay City on June 25. On top in the mid-1970s, ``Another World''
has slipped to the bottom tier of the ratings, beating only ``Port
Charles'' and ``Sunset Beach.'' It generally wins less than half as
many viewers as the highly rated ``The Young and the Restless,''
which pulls in about 6 million daily _ itself not a high number
compared with ``General Hospital'' during its early-1980s heyday
(about 10 million). NBC has killed the show to make room for
``Passions,'' a new soap that NBC exec Jerry Petry has been quoted
as calling ``fresh, hip, and targeted to appeal to a younger
demo.'' Press leaks about ``Passions'' indicate a juicy paranormal
story line.
</P>
<P>
   --ABC and Disney announced the creation of a 24-hour soap cable
channel, to debut in January. The as-yet-unnamed channel will
re-air the ABC soap lineup in prime time on the same day of its
afternoon airing. While this move threatens to lower the daytime
ratings of ABC affiliates, it could regenerate interest in soaps by
making them more readily available to 9-to-5 workers who don't like
to tape. It won't be much of a leap from ``Dawson's Creek'' to
``General Hospital.'' As network TV in general loses ratings ground
to cable options, this move could put the soap back on people's
screens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Soaps scooped
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How has TV's quintessential form become its most forgotten and
endangered one? The short answer is that TV and real life have
scooped the soap opera. All the defining qualities of soaps can now
be found elsewhere, on nighttime TV from ``ER'' to ``Ally McBeal,''
on tabloid talk shows and tabloid news shows, and even in the Starr
Report, whose finely detailed approach to the Lewinsky-Clinton
affair almost matched the soap opera's ability to mimic real time.
The qualities that once made soap operas unique _ the continuing
story lines, the garish romantic liaisons, the catfighting and
backbiting and murder trials _ have filtered into other areas of
American culture.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious blow to the soaps has been nighttime's
obsession with ongoing plots. Ever since they were invented to hawk
detergent to housewives on the radio and then on TV, daytime soaps
have relied on the lure of story, on the hypnotic power of endless
narratives. By offering a keyhole view of other people's lives,
soaps became _ to the joy of companies like Procter &AMP; Gamble _
addictive. They were the original ``appointment television,'' long
before NBC solidified the concept with its ``must see'' campaign.
Loyal soap viewers are famous for scheduling their days around
visits with their TV ``family.'' An Internet tour of ``Another
World'' sites reveals a community of fans who are devastated and
angry that their story is ending, and there are even mentions of
boycotting NBC during sweeps month and ``Passions'' when it
premieres on July 5.
</P>
<P>
   The soap magazines _ including Soap Opera Digest, Soap Opera
Update, and Soap Opera Weekly _ do acknowledge the weekly nighttime
series that are overtly soapy, including ``Party of Five,''
``Beverly Hills 90210,'' ``Felicity,'' ``Dawson's Creek,'' and
``Melrose Place.'' But they don't cover those nighttime series that
aren't soaps but that are quite soaplike, including ``Providence,''
``ER,'' ``Ally McBeal,'' and ``The Practice.'' Even today's sitcoms
have narrative arcs, most of them involving attractions between
central characters like Ross and Rachel or Monica and Chandler on
``Friends,'' or Maya and Elliott on ``Just Shoot Me,'' or Dana and
Casey on ``Sports Night.'' Last year's heavy-breathing death of
Jimmy Smits's character on ``NYPD Blue'' was elongated and
melodramatic enough to make even the most conventional daytime soap
green with envy.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid talk and news shows, too, have stolen the soaps'
thunder. They've grabbed viewers by zeroing in on the sorts of
lurid tales that were once exclusive to soap operas _ domestic
distortions like adultery and incest and ``women who love men who
love other women who love other men.'' A recent Springer episode,
for instance, featured a screamfest called ``Attack of the
Homewreckers'' that made years of classic soap vixenhood look
boring. The tab shows are upping the ante on the soaps' ability to
exploit viewers' fantasies and fears. Both the denizens of
Springer-land and the residents of Llanview and Port Charles have
bizarre problems we don't want, from evil twins to artificial
insemination by the wrong sperm. But they also represent our secret
longings unleashed, ranging from extramarital sex and financial
greed to conniving and backstabbing.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just tab TV that's competing with soaps. The
tabloiding of American culture in general seems to hand us a glitzy
new national soap opera every week. These scandalous dramas
penetrate newspapers and magazines as well as TV, and they've
become the hot ``water cooler'' topics. The most obvious one is the
Clinton-Lewinsky affair, but the decade's lineup of public soaps
ranges from the trashy violence of Amy Fisher and Joey Buttafuoco
and Lorena and John Wayne Bobbitt to the celebrity indiscretions of
Woody Allen and Mia Farrow and Michael Jackson. Even tragedies like
the murders of Ron Goldman, Nicole Simpson, and JonBenet Ramsey and
the death of Princess Diana have become our ``stories,'' some of
them rich in the kind of murder subplots and secondary characters
(Kato Kaelin) and moving eulogies (Earl Spencer) and hair changes
(Linda Tripp) that soaps have thrived on. Next to these real-life
soaps, Lucky's ``death'' on ``General Hospital'' (like his mother,
father, and grandmother before him, Lucky's not really dead) seems
less operatic.
</P>
<P>
   It was a telling moment when ``Sunset Beach'' recently tried to
steal some ratings with a guest visit from tabloid overlord Jerry
Springer. And it wasn't entirely absurd when a rumor in the soap
world had ``Sunset Beach,'' which is produced by Aaron Spelling,
negotiating with an up-and-coming celebrity named Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The young and the rest
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As they make a home for themselves in this new landscape, many
of the soap operas are trying to ``youthify,'' like so many other
mediums. That has certainly happened at the movies, where the
country's huge teenage population has created a boom in
teen-oriented fare, most recently with ``Varsity Blues,'' ``She's
All That,'' and ``The Matrix.'' Prime-time TV is also famous for
downplaying older-skewing shows like ``Touched by an Angel'' in
order to lavish promotion on the likes of ``Ally McBeal'' and
``Friends,'' whose young demographic makes advertisers drool.
</P>
<P>
   Soaps, like teen movies and WB series, have soundtracks with
songs by youth-market artists like the Goo Goo Dolls (``One Life to
Live'') and Monica (``As the World Turns'' and ``Guiding Light'').
The stately, adult-sounding series titles like ``As the World
Turns'' are being replaced with steamier titles that connote more
explicit, up-to-date story lines like those of ``Passions.'' And
younger characters have gained more air time on some shows, as
long-lost siblings and children turn up out of the blue. Actor Jay
Hammer claims that he was fired from his 14-year-long role as
Fletcher Reade on ``Guiding Light'' in 1998 because of his age and
the emphasis on younger, hunkier (and less expensive) actors.
(Hammer returned to the show in March, with a short-term contract.)
</P>
<P>
   With the coming of ``Passions,'' the writing is on the wall.
When NBC decided to premiere the new series, it was clear that one
of the network's other soaps would have to be cut. But while
``Sunset Beach'' is the lowest-rated soap, the network chose to
pull the plug on the older ``Another World'' and give ``Sunset'' a
six-month extension. Partly, that was because NBC wants
``Passions'' to follow ``Days of Our Lives'' in the schedule, but
in Daily Variety, NBC entertainment president Scott Sassa also
pointed to the youth market: ` ``Sunset Beach' seemed to have more
momentum with younger viewers, so we went with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the soaps will continue to ply their fantasies. But the
fantasies may become more fantastic, the pretty people may become
prettier, and the shiny hair may become shinier. There will always
be enough illness and murder and amnesia and facial disfigurement
to keep a fictional town in melodramatic heaven and hell. But
behind that finely plucked eyebrow that arches ever so slightly
before the scene fades to commercial, you may find yourself
wondering if someone has neatly implanted a computer microchip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MESSINA-2TAKES-     05-10 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MESSINA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JO DEE MESSINA IS DOING ALRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Jo Dee Messina is singing. This is something she does
well, and often, in front of thousands of people at sprawling
venues. Today, however, she is performing an impromptu concert for
an audience of two, sprawled in the back of a limousine in tight
black jeans, tall black boots, and a little white T-shirt. We are
stuck in traffic _ the country star, a management rep, and the
reporter _ en route to a radio station, and Messina is caterwauling
an improvisational tribute to the T. She croons about the Green
Line and the Red Line, then segues into a riff about the fabulous
new lipstick color she's found. Messina pulls down the visor and
applies a fresh coat. It's pale brown, a muted complement to her
cascade of red locks. ``Maybe I'll wear this tonight. I just
might,'' she says, inspecting her glossy mouth in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorful she is. Messina, a Massachusetts native, Nashville
transplant, and chart-topping darling of country music, was in town
to perform at last month's Kahlua Boston Music Awards at the
Orpheum Theatre. Although she didn't know it yet _ ``I'm gonna be
the Susan Lucci of these awards,'' Messina kept muttering
throughout the day _ she would pick up three awards, including one
for best act of the year. That's no small feat for a country singer
in a rock town. But Messina is no stranger to beating the odds.
</P>
<P>
   The last three years have been a bizarre roller-coaster ride for
Messina, beginning with her self-titled debut album in 1996 that
produced two Top 10 country hits: ``Heads Carolina, Tails
California'' and ``You're Not in Kansas Anymore.'' While the
singles sailed to the top of the charts, the album didn't. The
third single stiffed. Recording a follow-up album turned out to be
a nightmare. Everything from song selection to recording sessions
stalled repeatedly, ultimately delaying the release of ``I'm
Alright'' for more than a year. Messina's debts mounted. Christmas
of 1997, she didn't turn on the holiday lights in order to save on
her electric bill. Her accountants and attorneys advised her to
file for bankruptcy. Messina couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us forever to make that second record, and then we'd
been off the radio for about a year, and I pretty much lost
everything I owned,'' Messina states succinctly, over lunch at the
Omni Parker House, before heading to the radio station. She's
supremely composed, verging on sedate, and not at all the outgoing
firebrand one expects from reading articles written about her. It's
the combined effects of a red-eye from Nashville and her pre-6 p.m.
personality, Messina explains, venturing a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so bad she couldn't make her house or car payments,
Messina recounts between bites of salad. But quitting _ that's what
bankruptcy court would have meant to her _ wasn't an option. By
early 1998, the papers were drawn up and ready to sign. ``I just
refused. The label'' _ Nashville-based Curb Records _ ``covered
some of my bills, and a trucking company came in from out of the
blue and asked me to be their spokesperson and that gave me enough
money to float for a few months,'' she says. ``The next thing I
knew, the first single from `I'm Alright' came out, and now here I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Where she is now is making history, as the first female country
artist ever to have three consecutive, multi-week No. 1 hits on
Billboard's Hot Country Singles charts. ``I'm Alright'' was finally
released in March of last year, and it has catapulted 28-year-old
Messina into the upper echelons of the country music elite. The
title track, ``Bye Bye,'' and ``Stand Beside Me'' have all reached
the top of the charts. On April 28, ``I'm Alright,'' which is
currently No. 8 on Billboard's Country Album charts, was certified
platinum, signifying sales of more than 1 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Messina won Best New Female Vocalist at the
Academy of Country Music Awards; she received a standing ovation
from industry folks who well know how hard she's fought. Speaking
by cell phone from the press area backstage at LA's Universal
Amphitheatre, a teary, elated Messina said, ``My head is still
spinning. It's been a long road, and I've been praying so hard. I
feel so, so lucky.'' With hardly a moment to catch her breath,
Messina will hit the road with George Strait.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, when we finally arrive at WKLB (99.5) that
afternoon, Messina is treated like royalty. Although management is
beginning to sweat as the split-second-timed schedule for the day
unravels at the first stop, Messina is emerging from the cloud of
fatigue that has kept her mood and manner low-key so far.
Computerized screens in the main lobby of the Greater Boston Radio
Group flash her picture and a personalized welcome message. Radio
staff and unidentified hangers-on seem to crawl from the woodwork
to greet her. There's a big white cake with her name on it in the
sound booth, and much photo snapping and autograph signing. Messina
squeals her delight off and on the air, her famous effervescence
bubbling up to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Messina's 20 minutes on the radio are filled with big raspy
laughs and spontaneous, gleeful hand clapping. She cackles
hysterically over the fact that the jewel box for her latest
single, ``Lesson in Leaving,'' got her name wrong, and coyly looses
bits of juicy Jo Dee gossip. Randy Travis was her first country
crush. She's dating a guy in Nashville _ no, he's not in the
business. For her acting debut on ``Nash Bridges,'' Messina
declined the first role they offered her _ a pistol-wielding mama,
as she describes it _ because she didn't feel right playing such a
harsh character. She wound up playing a country singer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A country singer, after all, is the only thing Jo Dee Messina
has ever really wanted to be. She took to the stage at the tender
age of 13, singing in various local bands with the remarkable
support of her mother, Mary, who was then raising Jo Dee and her
three older siblings as a single parent. Mary would chaperone her
youngest daughter in the nightclubs until 1 a.m. and then rise at 5
to go to work at Raytheon. ``My mom worked and then put herself
through school and she still loved us like we were the prince and
princesses of her life,'' Messina recalls, leaning in close, her
gratitude and admiration fierce. ``And we were.''
</P>
<P>
   When she turned 16, Messina formed the Jo Dee Messina Band _ ``I
already had a following, and we wanted people to connect my name
with the new band'' _ with her brother on drums and a sister on
bass. Their sets were packed with Reba McIntyre and Juice Newton
tunes, Lorrie Morgan and Patsy Cline music. Aside from the
occasional Bob Seger rocker, it was country music through and
through. Ginny Rogers, music director at WKLB, was the midday host
on WBOS in the mid-'80s, when it was a country station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to introduce the Jo Dee Messina Band at club nights
back then,'' Rogers recalls. ``You could just tell she was one of
the few that had a real chance at making it.'' Today, Rogers says,
``Jo Dee is definitely on her way to becoming a superstar act. She
has the talent and the personality, and with this album she has the
momentum to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Messina remembers the early years with a mixture of fondness and
exasperation. ``We used to play JR's Place in Beverly, Sacco's in
Watertown, the Adelphia in Dorchester. I remember performing at a
place in Lawrence for a guy that was screaming at himself and a
woman that was dancing with a Miss Piggy doll,'' she recounts,
shaking her head. ``That was it, and we played for five hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the rigors of club life and unabashedly driven,
Messina at age 19 struck out for Nashville in 1989 to try her luck
in the country music capital. ``When I packed up and left, people
said `Oh, Nashville, they won't have anything to do with you.'
Because I was a Northerner. `We'll see you in six months,' they
said. But once I got down there no one even asked where I was from.
It wasn't an issue. It's always been about the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years, countless temp jobs, and one failed record contract
later, then-fledgling producer Byron Gallimore walked into her
life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
