<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-FATHER-BOS &LR;      05-10 1280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDAN QUINN CELEBRATES HIS FAMILY STORY IN `THIS IS MY FATHER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would become Aidan Quinn's latest film began as a story
told by a mother to her sons, a tale from the old country about
love, a widow, a curse, and a coffin laid at the widow's gate. That
yarn, from their mother's native Ireland, involved the brothers'
grandfather, one of the pallbearers who placed that coffin down on
ground forever damned.
</P>
<P>
   When Quinn's brother Paul traveled to Ireland to flesh out the
story, he found very little information. Undeterred, he took the
threads of his mother's story and wove them into ``This Is My
Father,'' a film written and directed by Paul, and starring Aidan.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Ireland, and told mostly in flashbacks, it's a story of
love lost and love found, the latter between a middle-aged Chicago
schoolteacher (played by James Caan) and the father he never knew
(Quinn).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's primarily a love story, but it's informed by the search
for family, and the search for your roots. It all really goes back
to `Roots' and (Alex) Haley, and Frank McCourt with `Angela's
Ashes.' It's out of that same tradition,'' says Quinn. ``James
Caan's character needs to know who his ancestors were, who his
father was, who his family is, hoping that will make him better
understand who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening Friday, the film also stars Moya Farrelly, Gina Moxley,
Jacob Tierney, and Colm Meaney.
</P>
<P>
   This film about family marks the first time Quinn has worked
with his younger brother, Paul, and his older brother, Declan, an
award-winning cinematographer who has shot such films as ``Leaving
Las Vegas,'' ``One True Thing,'' and ``Vanya on 42nd Street.'' All
three brothers also served as executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as though we don't irritate each other, as all
siblings do,'' Quinn said. ``But we are really good friends, and we
share a sense of humor, and a lot of other sensibilities. Plus,
there really wasn't a lot of time for petty squabbles; we were
working way too hard. We had a gargantuan thing in front of us that
we wanted to accomplish, and a small budget, and a small amount of
time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers also share an intense love of Ireland, where much
of the film was shot. Making the film there was easier than getting
the details on the true story that inspired it. Quinn said his
brother Paul ``met a stone wall of silence, with people telling
him, `Don't be bringin' that up, leave the dead good enough buried,
leave the dead where they belong.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So he just made it up,'' he said, ``and wrote this
staggeringly beautiful script.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Quinn's third film set in Ireland _ the other two are
``The Playboys'' and ``Michael Collins.'' Unlike that latter film,
and others such as ``In the Name of the Father,'' ``Some Mother's
Son,'' and ``The Boxer,'' ``This Is My Father'' has nothing to do
with the Irish Republican Army or ``the Troubles'' in Northern
Ireland. For Quinn, it was important to show another side of his
ancestral homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRA and the Troubles have very little to do with most
people's daily lives in Ireland. It's not a huge subject matter,''
he said. ``This story had nothing to do with that, and it wouldn't
have been appropriate to include it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An occasional home
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though born and raised in Chicago, Quinn is fiercely protective
of Ireland, where he has lived for several periods throughout his
life. His family returned there twice during his childhood, and
Quinn also spent summers there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we moved there as kids, people would say, `Be safe, don't
get shot.' People had no idea that the violence rate was so
incredibly low. There are no guns, except from the IRA and a few
criminals,'' he said. ``But growing up, we had no access to guns.
There might be huge horrible fights, and maybe knives, but Chicago
was way more scary than anything there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love being back there, I love working there, I love
reconnecting there,'' he said. ``Being back there I feel very
comfortable. I love the sense of humor. And I love the Guinness _
it tastes better there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his love of the Emerald Isle, Quinn said, he and his
brothers did not want to ``look through a glass at the Irish
romantically'' because ``that's not the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish are bitter, jealous, spiteful _ and I'm talking
about myself, I'm talking about our character. We are famous back
stabbers,'' he said. ``But we're also incredibly joyful,
courageous, generous, emotional _ we cry at the drop of a hat.
We're very conservative people, and yet we love wildness above all
things. It's a real paradox, a sort of schizophrenic identity, and
I think it's from trying to hang on to the Celtic stuff amongst
being conquered.''
</P>
<P>
   As passionate as he is about Ireland, Quinn displayed equal
fervor in discussing his career. After his debut in 1984's
``Reckless,'' he gained notice in the landmark 1985 television film
``An Early Frost,'' the first Hollywood production to deal with
AIDS. Quinn played a young gay man faced with revealing his
sexuality to his family after he became sick. Then, he costarred as
Rosanna Arquette's boyfriend in the sleeper hit ``Desperately
Seeking Susan,'' which also starred Madonna. Some predicted Quinn,
with his soulful blue eyes and dark Irish good looks, would be a
major star.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't happened. He was upstaged by Brad Pitt's hair in
``Legends of the Fall.'' He gave solid performances in ``Avalon''
and ``The Playboys,'' but they withered at the box office. There
have been out-and-out flops like the recent ``In Dreams,'' although
he was fortunate enough to be have been bludgeoned to death about
halfway through the film.
</P>
<P>
   While his pal and ``Michael Collins'' costar Liam Neeson will
soon be seen in ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,''
Quinn has never broken out as an A-list star, the kind who gets the
scripts without fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lack of risk taking
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say there's probably no less imaginative group of
men running companies than those running movie companies,'' he
said. ``They've made this decision that there's these 10 or 12
people they can cast in a movie, and you can't cast anyone else.
There's so little risk taking they shoot themselves in the foot
because people get bored. And when these movies bomb, then they get
desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the Four Seasons Hotel, Quinn, 40, sounded more like
a cranky critic than an actor who just completed the big Hollywood
film ``50 Violins,'' starring Meryl Streep, and has worked with
such acclaimed directors as Barry Levinson, Hector Babenco, and
Neil Jordan. Still, in an industry where most are too afraid to
even think critical thoughts, let alone utter one, Quinn's honesty
was surprising and refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People meet me on the streets and say, `Why aren't you doing
more stuff or better stuff?' '' Quinn said. `` `The Assignment' (a
twisty, little-seen 1997 thriller) and `This Is My Father' are the
two best roles I've had in maybe 10 years. It's a little
disconcerting. I'll do a decent role, a supporting role, which I
don't mind doing so long as with the next role I'm challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   In producing, Quinn said, he can create the ``great roles''
Hollywood seems to deny him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (producing) was inevitable because of the frustration
from the lack of challenging roles one gets offered through the
Hollywood studio system,'' he said. ``A lot of my friends are
realizing you have to produce or create your own work. It's a
really good trend, born of frustration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
