</P>
<P>
   Breathing problems that cause snoring may be a risk factor, Karl
Franklin of Ume University in Sweden told a meeting of the American
Lung Association in San Diego last week. He and his colleagues
discovered this when they gave questionnaires to 502 pregnant
women.
</P>
<P>
   While only 4 percent reported frequent snoring before pregnancy,
23 percent snored by the end of their pregnancies. Around 10
percent of the snoring women had pre-eclampsia, while only 4
percent of nonsnorers developed the condition. All patients with
pre-eclampsia started snoring before any hint of pre-eclampsia such
as blurred vision appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Similar findings came from Natalie Edwards and her colleagues at
the University of Sydney. They looked at 32 women with severe
pre-eclampsia and 40 with normal pregnancies and found that all the
women with pre-eclampsia were snorers. Women with the highest
degree of airway obstruction during sleep also had the highest
blood pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian researchers found that they could prevent both
the snoring and the high blood pressure by giving women breathing
masks attached to a machine that kept their airways open while they
were asleep. ``All of the obstetricians were impressed that we
could control this so effectively,'' Edwards says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is very intriguing,'' says James Van Hook at the
University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston. ``This may be an
important phenomenon that causes their condition to get worse.'' He
hopes to collaborate on larger clinical trials of the breathing
masks. &QL;   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly
science and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
