<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !!! &LR;  ``Dry Cleaning'' In this lethal French comedy, a bisexual
interloper moves in on a bored couple running a dry-cleaning shop,
only to discover that he's not as tough and they're not as timid as
he had supposed. Subtle performances and invigorating risk-taking
by the actors, especially Miou-Miou as the emergent adventuress and
Charles Berling as the seemingly prissy spot remover. (French with
subtitles) (Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FL)  &UR; !!!! &LR;  ``Election'' The sharpest and darkest comedy of the new
year so far is set in a high school where a ruthless little
overachiever (Reese Witherspoon) hits back hard at an earnest but
unequipped civics teacher (Matthew Broderick), who talks a popular
jock into running against her for student council president. A
worthy follow-up to Alexander Payne's debut film, the abortion
satire ``Citizen Ruth.'' (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  ``The Empty Mirror'' What's empty here is this film's lame
fantasy that imagines Hitler's last hours in his bunker as a
rantfest that tells us nothing we didn't already know. Despite a
brave performance by Norman Rodway, the fictionalized film is blown
off the screen by actual newsreel footage, Eva Braun's home movies,
and Leni Riefenstahl's documentary, ``The Triumph of the Will.''
(Unrated) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 ``Lovers of the Arctic Circle'' A wildly romantic yet
intricately patterned love story with a philosophical dimension.
The movie asks whether it's fate or chance that forges a bond
between a schoolboy and schoolgirl that persists for 25 years
despite a lot of missed connections. Few films make the connection
between love and geography _ including the geography of the human
heart _ that gifted Spanish filmmaker Julio Medem does here.
(Spanish with subtitles) (R) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(FR)  &UR; !! &LR;  ``The Mummy'' Better they should have stuck with the
rotting-gauze look of the Boris Karloff original, rather than make
a whizbang computer-generated successor that's more campy and funny
than scary and moody. The been-there-done-that flavor extends to
Brendan Fraser's desert swashbuckler, too. He seems haunted more by
Indiana Jones than by the mummy. (PG-13) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !! &LR;  1/2 ``SLC Punk!'' It's life amongst the glorious ruins, early
in the Reagan era, for a couple of semi-righteous, semi-messed-up
punk-rock pals in Salt Lake City. Director James Merendino has an
eye for detail, nuance, and irony _ this doesn't feel like one of
those groaner youth movies made by ``adults.'' On the other hand,
the plot mostly consists of posturing, partying, and fighting, so a
certain tedium sets in, too. But the soundtrack rocks, the kids'
issues seem as big as they feel at that age, and the writers avoid
cheap moralizing. (R) (Jim Sullivan) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! &LR;  1/2 ``The Winslow Boy'' David Mamet, known for his American
lowlifes, triumphantly breaks out of writer's typecasting with this
sterling adaptation of Terence Rattigan's Edwardian period piece of
a play. There's a somber atmosphere, sustained tension, and a
screenful of rich performances in this intimate drama about a boy
whose respectable middle-class family risks everything to clear him
of a charge of petty theft. (G) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
