<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL SESSION A POLITICAL GAMBLE FOR BUSH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One of the Texas governor's strongest weapons in
a relatively weak arsenal is the power to call special sessions of
the Legislature and set their agendas. So it is not much of a
surprise that rumors of an extra session have been flying
throughout the Capitol as legislators continue to resist Gov.
George W. Bush's tax cut priorities.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to try to predict how all the speculation will
play out. But Bush, who has never called a special session, surely
is aware that this same weapon, if not handled with great care, may
end up shooting him in the foot _ or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Taking liberties with the legendary former University of Texas
football coach Darrell Royal's famous quote about his aversion to
the passing game: A lot of things can happen to a governor during a
special session, and many of them are bad.
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-Bush years, special sessions were almost as frequent
as the rumors. The governor's three predecessors faced serious
budgetary problems that required several tax increases and often
sparked intense fights between Democrats and growing numbers of
Republican lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's situation is markedly different. He is trying to cut
taxes during a time of budgetary surplus, and, of course, he may be
running for president. And those two factors are not unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed tax cuts totaling about $2.6 billion,
including $2 billion in school tax relief. But many lawmakers,
Republicans as well as Democrats, are insisting that most of that
money be spent on public education, particularly raises for Texas'
underpaid teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The governor isn't saying whether he would call legislators back
for another session this summer if they fail to provide what he
would consider sufficient tax relief before the regular session
ends on Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   But he may be tempted to do so, partly to counter criticism that
his leadership has faltered this year and partly to add to his
anti-tax credentials, which were left open to potential attack
after the 1997 session.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature cut school property taxes by $1 billion two
years ago at Bush's bidding. But the governor may be vulnerable on
the tax issue because he also proposed a controversial sales tax
increase and a new business tax as part of an unsuccessful tax
trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   Should Bush choose to delay or interrupt his national
campaigning this summer to call a special session, he could luck
out and convince lawmakers to cut taxes enough for him to declare
victory. Those prospects would be enhanced if Comptroller Carole
Keeton Rylander, a fellow Republican, were to find some additional
state money and increase the revenue projection that determines how
large a budget or how deep a tax cut lawmakers can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Previous comptrollers have produced rosier-than-anticipated
revenue updates to bail previous governors and Legislatures out of
late-session budgetary jams, but, so far, Rylander isn't making any
promises, at least publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Without Rylander's help, the bottom-line budget numbers won't
change. And without better numbers, Bush may be no more persuasive
with lawmakers in a 30-day special session than he has been during
the 140-day regular session.
</P>
<P>
   Partisanship also could become a greater factor during a hot,
summer session. With Democrats holding a majority of the House and
15 of the Senate's 31 votes, Bush will need their help, and they
may not be willing to boost the governor's political aspirations at
the expense of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The governor would have a few hammers to use during a special
session. If an extra session were held in June, he could threaten
uncooperative lawmakers with vetoes of still-unsigned bills that
they passed during the special session. And he could try to woo
some tax-cut votes by promising legislators to add their pet bills
_ those they didn't get passed during the regular session _ to the
special session's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Although a special session could project Bush as a leader
determined to force lawmakers to do his bidding, it also could help
the governor fall flat on his face in full view of the national
media, a decidedly unflattering position for someone who would be
president.
</P>
<P>
   The special session speculation will continue and may soon be
broadened to include the bill requiring parents to be notified
before their minor daughters can have abortions. That measure,
which also could be of huge political importance to Bush in
Republican presidential primaries, hasn't emerged from the
legislative mine field yet, and time is ticking away.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the issue, though, a special session for a governor is
at best a calculated risk. At worst, it can be an irresponsible
roll of the dice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
