<HEADLINE>
LACK OF CREWS, SUPPLIES MAY SLOW REBUILDING IN OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ Like many of his fellow residents near Sunrise
Drive and Northwest 21st Street, a quiet neighborhood that no
longer exists, Jody Alexander sifted through the debris where his
house once stood, searching for any personal belongings that would
make it easier for his family to start life over again.
</P>
<P>
   This neighborhood of working-class people was leveled by the
tornado that struck May 3. By midweek, homeowners were marking
their turf, spray-painting their addresses and the names of their
insurance company on their driveways or the walls of their homes,
if any remained. A few had even planted American flags in the
rubble, giving the quiet streets the look of a battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who is 28 and delivers vending machines for
Coca-Cola, isn't as fortunate as many of his neighbors. He doesn't
have homeowner's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let my homeowner's lapse, and I don't really know why,''
Alexander said. ``We were saving money to go on vacation, and I was
thinking that when we got back, I'd get insurance again.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been eight days since the killer tornadoes struck, and
for those left homeless, everyday life is temporarily on hold. As
the massive cleanup begins in earnest, even those with insurance
may find that going home will take longer than they expect.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's mayor, Glenn Lewis, estimated that rebuilding could take
from six months to a year. Almost a quarter of the 15,000 houses in
the town were destroyed. Hundreds more were damaged but are
habitable, according to local police.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor's prediction may be optimistic. The irony is that
a strong economy and a construction boom have created a shortage of
building materials and construction crews throughout the country.
Supply cannot meet demand, and that is driving up prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sheetrock shortage and brick shortage,'' said L.O.
Harrington, a home builder and insurance agent in Moore. ``It's
frustrating, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shock is just hitting. Builders won't be able to get
subcontractors to rebuild homes because these people can make more
money repairing homes than working on new ones. I'm not sure what
the bigger problem is,'' Harrington said, ``a lack of materials or
workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hap Lowry of Trinity Brick, an Oklahoma City distributor, said
that the tunnel kilns that produce brick are running at full
capacity 24 hours a day, 365 days a year. ``They can produce only
so many bricks a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also wondering whether they're going to make it a priority
for people who lost their homes to get brick first or for those who
are having homes built and have been waiting for two or three
months,'' Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Feuerborn, co-owner of Blanchard Building Supplies in
Blanchard, said he has been without a ready supply of drywall since
November, and must special order it for customers.
</P>
<P>
   He said insulation, lumber and roofing material are also in
short supply. Also, spring is the builders' busiest season, when
most of the new housing construction starts.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that some of the tornado victims will purchase
new homes that were built on speculation in the Oklahoma City area.
But that may require moving to another part of the region, which
some may be unwilling to do.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Farney, a spokeswoman for the Oklahoma City mayor's
office, said there is concern that a shortage of materials and
workers will enable unscrupulous contractors to victimize impatient
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we are handing out packets to people at our
shelters and command centers,'' Farney said. ``We're telling them
to get three estimates and references, even from builders or
subcontractors from out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that homeowners have to be particularly cautious when
hiring someone to do roofing repairs because Oklahoma doesn't
license roofers.
</P>
<P>
   In Moore, a bedroom community of 50,000 south of Oklahoma City,
many of the survivors of last week's tornadoes are still too busy
salvaging keepsakes and remnants of their belongings to pay
attention to such issues.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
