<HEADLINE>
LEONARD NIMOY STARS IN ``STAR TREK: INSURRECTION'' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES: ``Star Trek: Insurrection'' _ Maybe the title is
meant to suggest the feelings expressed by the William
Shatner-Leonard Nimoy crew when confronted with the script of this
``Star Trek'' drek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, UConn!'' _ The official 1999 NCAA basketball championship
video is out, for less than $20. Condensed to 50 minutes, the CBS
Video production includes highlights from the tournament as well as
the thrilling final game against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK SET: It took a director of Stanley Kubrick's stature to
unite three competing companies _ Warner Home Video, MGM Home
Entertainment, and Columbia TriStar Home Video. On June 29, just
two weeks before Kubrick's final feature, ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
opens, they are releasing ``The Stanley Kubrick Collection'' on
both VHS and DVD. The set includes ``2001: A Space Odyssey,''
``Paths of Glory,'' and ``The Killing'' from MGM; ``Lolita,'' ``A
Clockwork Orange,'' ``Barry Lyndon,'' ``The Shining,'' and ``Full
Metal Jacket'' from Warner; and ``Dr. Strangelove'' from Columbia
Tristar. The set will sell for $124.92 on VHS and $149.92 on DVD.
Individual titles will sell for $19.98 on VHS and $24.98 on DVD
(except for ``Barry Lyndon,'' a double cassette, for $24.98 in
either format).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMING ATTRACTIONS: May 18: ``The Impostors,'' ``Batman Beyond:
The Movie,'' ``Bent,'' ``Holy Man,'' ``In Dreams,'' ``Memorial
Day,'' ``My Sweet Suicide,'' ``Rowing With the Wind,'' ``Shadow of
Doubt.'' May 25: ``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``Gloria,'' ``Alice in
Wonderland,'' ``Horatio Hornblower,'' ``The Aviator's Wife,'' ``The
Marquise of O,'' ``Forbidden Fruit,'' ``Wrestlemania XV,''
``Hellcab.'' June 1: ``Berenstain Bears'' (three new episodes),
``The Base,'' ``Gunshy.'' June 8: ``From the Earth to the Moon,''
``Treehouse Hostage,'' ``Psycho'' (remake), ``Gods and Monsters,''
``Before Stonewall,'' ``After Stonewall,'' ``Last Rites.'' June 15:
``Little Voice,'' ``The World Within,'' ``Enemy of the State,''
``The Faculty,'' ``Facade,'' ``The Patriot.'' June 22: ``Waking Ned
Devine,'' ``Patch Adams,'' ``A Simple Plan,'' ``Rushmore,''
``Wishful Thinking,'' ``Sweethearts,'' ``The Life of Birds,''
``Storm of the Century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1122 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORNADOES-REBUILD-2nd     05-10 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADOES-REBUILD-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
MOORE, Okla.: to such issues. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pamela Hester, who is 26 and has three young children, is more
concerned about safety. She told her husband, Shelby, that she will
no longer live in Oklahoma without a storm shelter. All that
remains of their rented home is a 4-by-5-foot closet in the master
bedroom, where the family hid as the tornado roared over them.
</P>
<P>
   It was just last October when a much smaller twister cut a swath
a mile south of last week's trail of destruction. That storm
damaged 150 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Watson, 74, has no intention of leaving. ``I've lived all
my life in Oklahoma, and we learn to get along with this,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After a 15-year absence, his neighbor Sheila Meadows was
welcomed home to her native Oklahoma by October's tornado. Her
husband is in the Army, stationed in Kansas. She and her three
children survived last week's tornado in their storm shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my three children and my dog,'' she said. ``I'll
rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the street from where Jody Alexander lived, Shelly Haygood
and her teen-age daughter LaShell were sifting through the ruins of
their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years ago, I had a house burn to the ground and lost
everything,'' said Haygood, 37 and a single mom. ``I learned that
things can be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't thought about whether she will risk losing a third
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much to do. I've got to hold the mail; I've got to
look to rent something,'' she said. ``But it will be fine. Things
will work out. And I imagine that when all is said and done, I'll
have a good cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools in Moore opened again Monday. Some of the tornado
survivors have already returned to work. But employers are flexible
and giving their workers an opportunity to recover from the trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander has been given a month off with pay by Coca-Cola,
which has also offered free counseling for his family. South Winds,
a nearby apartment complex, has given him an apartment rent-free
for the first three months.
</P>
<P>
   He is married and has three stepchildren. They were looking
forward to the vacation planned for June in Red River, N.M.,
celebrating his first wedding anniversary. He said it would
probably have been the last he and his wife, Donette, could afford
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Alexander tried to be optimistic. One of his relatives is
a bricklayer who promised to help him rebuild his house if he
decides to stay at 2200 Sunrise Drive. He is counting on assistance
from the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   His mom drove 100 miles to bring a new set of dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And look at this,'' Alexander said, holding up a small plastic
bag filled with loose change that was buried in the debris. ``I've
got it made.''
</P>
<P>
   At a command center at First Baptist Church in Moore, insurance
companies such as Allstate, Farmers and State Farm had catastrophe
crews on site, parked in huge trailers. They sent claims adjusters
like commando units into the tornado-ravaged neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already writing checks for $5,000 for living expenses,''
said Raleigh Floyd, a spokesperson for Allstate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where we earn our keep,'' said Kitty Miller of
Farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers cleared some debris, although the real cleanup will
begin within three weeks under the direction of FEMA.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Moore Police Department said that some of
the debris will be sent to a landfill in Oklahoma City. Some will
have to be burned because there isn't enough room in the Moore
landfill.
</P>
<P>
   As the rebuilding process begins in the weeks ahead, there are
models for these Oklahoma communities to study. This year marked
the 20th anniversary of a tornado that swept through Wichita Falls,
Texas, killing 45 and causing $800 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Harper, an architect considered an expert on disaster
recovery, helped formulate the rebuilding plans in Wichita Falls. A
year after ``Terrible Tuesday,'' 85 percent of residential
dwellings in that city had been rebuilt or were in the process of
being rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Harper also worked hand-in-hand with his alma mater, Texas Tech,
to create in-house storm shelters, steel reinforced rooms or
closets that are likely to become increasingly popular.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Pamela Hester will live in a house with one. Communities
can be rebuilt, but memories of the tornadoes will last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born here and raised here,'' Hester said, ``but now I'll
be horrified whenever I hear storms come.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
