<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TRUFFAUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING TRUFFAUT'S TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Francois Truffaut is hot. The Brattle Theatre in Cambridge,
Mass. begins a major retrospective of 10 films and two short
subjects, with all-new 35mm prints, on Thursday. Truffaut's entire
oeuvre is being repackaged and remastered for DVD by Fox Lorber.
Knopf just published a thorough, if somewhat dry, Truffaut
biography by Antoine De Baecque and Serge Toubiana.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there was no one like Truffaut,'' says Jeanne Moreau,
who starred in several Truffaut films, including ``Jules and Jim''
and ``The Bride Wore Black,'' by telephone from her suite at a New
York hotel. ``When I first thought of watching so many of
Francois's films again, I was sad. When you love a person, and that
person is gone, it is sad. But it is also wonderful that we have so
many of his marvelous films. For those films to all be seen again .
. . we are privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   Francois Truffaut made meaningful films when films had meaning.
He didn't make them for money; he made them for himself and an
audience that believed in film as a redemptive art form. Back when
the success of a film was judged on theme, character, story, and
style and not simply on the weekend box office receipts, Truffaut
flourished. Until he died _ of a brain tumor, at the age of 52, in
1984 _ he gave serious filmgoers funny, complex, entertaining
films.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Truffaut's success was that he lived a life
outside film. Many directors go directly from film school into the
industry without having tasted life. By the time Truffaut picked up
a camera, he had been disowned by his parents, served a couple of
jail terms, and deserted the French Army. He was broke. During his
incarceration, he had struck up a correspondence and friendship
with novelist Jean Genet and persuaded critic Andre Bazin to be a
character witness during one of Genet's trials. He had lied,
cheated, and stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Francois lived life. He brought his life . . . in some ways a
very difficult life, to his films,'' says Moreau, who was one of
the producers and stars of ``Jules and Jim.''
</P>
<P>
   Life was tough for Truffaut right from the start. Francois
Roland was born out of wedlock to Janine de Monferrand, his Roman
Catholic mother, on Feb. 6, 1932. He was immediately placed with a
nurse and, according to ``Truffaut: A Biography,'' his mother
basically ignored him during his first three years. When his mother
married Roland Truffaut, her new husband gave the little boy his
surname _ but little else. His adoptive father never told him the
truth about their relationship, and his mother treated him as an
afterthought. Francois became a street kid. He acted up in school,
stole items from stores, lied about his attendance, and became a
juvenile delinquent.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The 400 Blows,'' when Truffaut's alter ego Antoine Doinel
(Jean-Pierre Leaud) must come up with an excuse for playing hooky,
he tells his teacher, ``It's my mother, sir . . . she died.''
</P>
<P>
   While only a card-carrying psychobabblist would believe that his
early life was the primary factor leading to Truffaut's lifelong
feelings of alienation, it does present a legitimate starting point
for a brief consideration of his memorable career.
</P>
<P>
   He often sought refuge from both his uncaring parents, truant
officers, and the local police in the cinemas of Paris. There he
found anonymity. Darkness. Escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``These early experiences of watching films on the sly, as a
clandestine activity, became, for Truffaut, a defining condition of
cinema,'' write de Baecque and Toubiana. ``From then on, love of
cinema represented a pocket of resistance in the culture of the
period _ a parallel society, forming a counterculture network,
cultivating a taste for secrecy and contraband, and gradually
taking the shape of an intimate diary, shared with faithful
initiates.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as a kid in his late teens, Francois Truffaut began seeing
things in cinematic terms. Describing his first trip to a film
festival in Biarritz, he wrote ``The beach is straight out of Jean
Vigo, with framings straight out of (Henry) Hathaway, a depth of
field out of (Orson) Welles, and perspectives out of Fritz Lang.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening credit sequence in ``The 400 Blows'' (1958),
Truffaut's first feature, is a series of images of the neighborhood
around the Eiffel Tower shot at a long angle looking upward _
always keeping the Eiffel Tower near the center of the frame. It's
from the child's perspective. And, no matter how Truffaut matured
and how many awards he won or how he was lionized, he never lost
that unique perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Through Doinel, the filmmaker transformed the notion of children
in film from stereotypes to complex little beings. In each of the
Doinel films, beginning with ``The 400 Blows'' and ending with
``Love on the Run,'' Truffaut explored childhood seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``In dealing with life, Antoine Doinel always reacts
emotionally, not intellectually,'' Truffaut said in a 1979
interview to promote the final Doinel film, ``Love on the Run''
(1978). ``We all know well that life doesn't build up to something
glorious or exalted. He's the opposite of an exceptional character,
of a hero, but what distinguishes him from average people is that
he never gets into average situations. He's either profoundly
disappointed and desperate to the point at which we fear the worst,
or he's in a state of total ecstasy and enthusiasm.'' In other
words, still a child.
</P>
<P>
   Even in some of his other films, particularly ``Jules and Jim''
(1961), he uses a childlike perspective. As Truffaut pointed out in
an interview published shortly before his death, ``Jeanne Moreau's
Catherine was the ideal woman seen by a child. A sort of fairy
tale.''
</P>
<P>
   Truffaut always seemed to be searching for two elements that he
believed were missing from his life: a happy childhood and a
permanent love.
</P>
<P>
   As Truffaut got older, his attention turned to passion _
particularly, sexual passion. In ``Two English Girls,'' ``The Story
of Adele H.,'' ``The Green Room,'' and ``The Woman Next Door,'' he
explored the dilemmas and enigmas of romance. Men adoring women,
and women rejecting men, formed the backbone of his career's
mid-life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several of Francois's movies I'm not particularly
fond of,'' says Moreau. ``I never liked `The Man Who Loved Women.'
I thought it was silly. And Francois was not a silly man. He loved
women but in a very deep, rich sense. He also loved paradox. That
is not his best work. And he would not want me to say
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was one particularly revealing remark in ``The Man Who
Loved Women,'' when the title character explains that he likes to
read because it helped him forget a mother who ``could stand me
only if I was silent.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of these Truffaut films have been available only on
VHS during the past 15 years, the current revival and release of
his films on the DVD format allow a new generation to experience
his marvelous artistry. Watching several Truffaut films on DVD, you
can't help thinking of how the filmmaker might have used the
technical capacity of the disc to enrich the experience. What would
it be worth to watch ``Jules and Jim'' while listening to Truffaut
illuminate the film on a separate track? Because of his
encyclopedic knowledge of the cinema and his ability to articulate
his reasons for particular shots or cuts, it would be unrivaled.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Louis Malle, Truffaut's colleague, said, ``Francois
was a very hard worker. He had a desire to work beyond any of us.
And he only liked looking back in his films.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's our chance to do the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
