<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CHICKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIXIE CHICKS ARE COOKIN' WITH COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dixie Chicks. What could evoke the Deep South more than that
name? Yet, here's the honest truth: Two of the three Dixie Chicks
have Yankee roots and are classically trained, while the other
attended Berklee College of Music. These are no ordinary Chicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are actually Yankees and I was born in
(Massachusetts),'' says Emily Erwin, 26, whose fellow band members
include older sister Martie Seidel, 29, and lead singer Natalie
Maines, 24, the Berklee connection.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that's where the surprising background ends.
</P>
<P>
   The Dixie Chicks, who are touring with George Strait, Jo Dee
Messina, and other festival acts, grew up mostly in Texas. Erwin
and Seidel lived in Dallas, where they studied the Suzuki method
and classical music in high school, and Maines in Lubbock (home of
Buddy Holly and Waylon Jennings), where her dad was famed pedal
steel guitarist Lloyd Maines.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another truth: No country group has been hotter this
year than the Chicks, whose album ``Wide Open Spaces'' sold 5
million copies and landed on the Top 10 pop charts as well as
country. Last week, the Chicks won in three categories at the
Academy of Country Music Awards in Los Angeles: best group, best
new group, and Album of the Year. That follows the Chicks' Grammy
win for best country album, beating out heavily favored discs by
Shania Twain and Garth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was truly shocking,'' Erwin says of the Grammy win. ``But
it helped us gain a lot of credibility outside of country music,
too. And that's kind of cool.''
</P>
<P>
   While some of their fashion statements are acutely modern (and
have enabled them to grace many hip magazine covers), their music
is country, with influences dating back to bluegrass and to
storytelling influences from Emmylou Harris and Dolly Parton (both
are idols of Erwin's). Such devotion to tradition no doubt inspired
many Grammy voters to choose the Chicks over the more amorphous,
pop-lusting likes of Twain and Faith Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicks are definitely not trying to follow the Twain and
Hill crossover path. While their album includes songs by Bonnie
Raitt and J. D. Souther, it resonates with timeless country vocal
harmonies and rootsy instrumental breaks on guitar, dobro, banjo
(by Erwin), and fiddle (Seidel).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not consciously trying to go pop,'' says Erwin. ``A
great example is when VH1 called our record label and said they'd
love to run the song `Wide Open Spaces,' but would need to take the
fiddle and pedal steel out. We thought, `Whoa, the fiddle is Martie
and that's taking out one-third of the Dixie Chicks. And the steel
player is Natalie's dad and the steel really makes that song. So,
no, we're not going to change our music to fit your format.' As
much as we'd like to be played on VH1, we're not going to mold
ourselves around that. We know what our strengths are _ and we want
to play country music.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dixie Chicks play it extremely well. On their hit single ``I
Can Love You Better'' (a punchy, cocky tune about making a
boyfriend forget a past love) and on ``There's Your Trouble''
(which won another Grammy for best country vocal performance by a
duo or group), the Chicks exude a contagious energy.
</P>
<P>
   It's also amazing to realize that the album that's caused all
the fuss, ``Wide Open Spaces,'' is really their fourth album.
Before that, the Chicks languished in obscurity _ many people would
be surprised to know, for example, that they've played at Johnny
D's in Somerville four times without much fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville-based Chicks started in 1989, when Erwin was only
16. She and her sister had another lead singer at the time and were
obsessed with frilly gingham dresses on stage and a more
bluegrass-based sound that sailed past the ears of most Nashville
executives.
</P>
<P>
   But when Maines signed up a few years ago, the fashion statement
changed and the music toughened into bolder country-rock. ``When
Natalie joined, she said, `I dig your music, but I'm not wearing
stupid clothes.' I totally understood,'' says Erwin. ``At the time,
the cowgirl thing was really a gimmick. I mean, as far as being who
you are, I'm not a cowgirl. . . . So we kind of re-created
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicks now favor more sexy, modern outfits, though short of
the risque level of Shania Twain. ``We don't play the sexy card
that Shania does, but we do enjoy glamor,'' says Erwin. ``I mean,
be serious about your music and know what you want to do but have
fun with it, too. It is not worth doing if you take yourself too
seriously. And part of it is that we're just girly girls who love
putting on makeup and getting pretty clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   New singer Maines also steered the group toward a more
contemporary musical direction. She suggested recording Bonnie
Raitt's ``Give It Up or Let Me Go'' on the latest album. And the
group also added more guitar, which pleased radio programmers who
crave snappy guitar hooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned guitar out of necessity because banjo wasn't going
on some of the country stuff that we wanted to approach,'' says
Erwin, whose specialty had been the five-string. ``So I wanted to
learn the guitar, and the dobro went along with that. It's all a
matter of expanding and experimenting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where Martie and I came from bluegrass, Natalie came from more
Texas country and blues,'' adds Erwin. ``And it was really a group
effort in choosing the songs. Natalie is the huge Bonnie Raitt fan,
and she also brought in the Dobie Gray hit, `Loving Arms.' And
Martie and I wrote one based on our parents' divorce, the `You Were
Mine' song. And the other ones we just picked up from other
songwriters. We loved Radney Foster's `Riding,' so we pursued him
to give us some songs and luckly found one that we really liked. I
think we looked under stones that other country artists don't look
under. They look for maybe what is a country song, as opposed to
what is a great song that you can turn into a country song.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, the Dixie Chicks will play some Lilith Fair dates
this summer (``We want to bring country to that audience''), as
well as more shows as part of George Strait's stadium tour. At this
point, the Chicks are big enough to headline on their own, but
they're choosing to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to go out and headline with just one album of
material with this lineup,'' Erwin says. ``People who are
headlining have hours of hits. And though we've been lucky with how
many Top Five singles we've had off this album, it doesn't make for
a two-hour show. But the George Strait tour is a perfect
opportunity to get in front of an average of 50,000 people a night
and turn them on to our music, so next year we can hopefully get
those same people back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's great to just play one hour a night and go
knock 'em dead and then hang out with all the other artists the
rest of the day. You're not having to worry about the catering, the
promotion, and everything else. It's somebody else's problem and
somebody else's headache. I love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
