<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIFE' MISSES THE HEART OF THE ASSEMBLY LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LIFE ON THE LINE 
One Woman's Tale of Work, Sweat, and Survival 
By Solange De Santis 
Doubleday, 272 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the end of another long night, the close of another long
week on the assembly line, a group of auto-plant workers
interrupted their grueling 5 p.m. to 1 a.m. shift with an impromptu
water-balloon fight. After monotonous hours of installing van
windows, the laughter and watery explosions were a welcome respite.
</P>
<P>
   Among the workers was Solange De Santis, Sally to her fellow
shoprats. She participated in the game, but also viewed it all
``from a vantage point far away, an out-of-coveralls experience.
The worker jams in another window, fits another liner to the frame.
The reporter, a visitor on this blue-collar planet thinks, Yes,
this is perfect. This is why I am here. This will make a terrific
story.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``terrific story'' to which De Santis refers is her own, and
that's the nagging problem with her book, ``Life on the Line.'' In
1991, De Santis, then a reporter at the Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail, took
a leave from journalism for a job at General Motors' Scarborough
Van Plant in Ontario. The plant was slated to close in 18 months,
and while that would seem the most compelling story _ a close-up
look at the 2,700 workers erased by corporate downsizing _ it
wasn't the one that really interested De Santis.
</P>
<P>
   The book's subtitle says it all: ``One Woman's Tale of Work,
Sweat, and Survival.'' This is De Santis's story of how a woman
ensconced in the white-collar world decided to play ``Norma Rae''
for a while. She would enter the auto plant not as a seasoned, Ivy
League-educated journalist, but as ``Sal,'' a woman with a sketchy
work history eager to earn a steady wage. It's all very
well-intentioned, but the book fails to rise much above a vanity
project.
</P>
<P>
   For De Santis, working in the plant was a walk on the wild side.
Always, she had known a life of comfort: raised in New York,
daughter of a trade-organization executive and a fashion writer.
Even before she graduated from Columbia University, she had her
first journalism job at NBC Radio. Jobs at Reuters, the Associated
Press, and the Palm Beach Post would follow until, nearing 40, De
Santis began to have her doubts about strolling ``the plush carpet
life had woven for me without stepping off and walking barefoot on
the gravel.''
</P>
<P>
   So when she hears of the imminent closing of a GM plant in
suburban Toronto, De Santis moved to swap ``the genteel world of
desks, air-conditioning, computers, telephones, and Post-it notes''
for the mind- and muscle-numbing grind of the assembly line.
``Working at the van plant would be a character test: my Everest,
my Zen monastery,'' she writes, admitting ``My interest wasn't
political in nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Slipping into her $16-an-hour job in fiberglass insulation, De
Santis finds the work tough and tedious. The insulation is hard to
handle; the fibers sting her hands and are easily inhaled. Still,
she enjoys her new identity as Sally because ``it sounded jaunty.
Rosie the Riveter, meet Sally the Autoworker.''
</P>
<P>
   But everything at the plant isn't as free and easy, and De
Santis's recollections of her co-workers' off-the-line hardships
are the book's highlight. Men and women would anesthesize
themselves nightly with drugs or with beers at Gene's, a favorite
watering hole. On any given night, half its customers were wearing
GM overalls, and, to De Santis, the place seemed like ``the
cafeteria with a liquor license and slightly better food.''
</P>
<P>
   She finds workers with dreams beyond the factory walls,
including her supervisor Lance, a high-school graduate who aspires
to attend an Ivy League school and move up the GM management
ladder. De Santis already has that degree, which she comes to
appreciate as she realizes it's something most of her co-workers
will never achieve.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time, ``Life on the Line'' plays like a hardscrabble
version of ``The Wizard of Oz,'' with De Santis as Dorothy,
recognizing again and again that there's no place like home. At
least, that's the prevalent feeling when she isn't making the
assembly line sound like one of those roughing-it-for-a-week
Outward Bound courses.
</P>
<P>
   This subject was better covered in Ben Hamper's ``Rivethead:
Tales from the Assembly Line,'' a humorous, heartbreaking memoir of
his years as a worker at GM's ill-fated Flint, Mich., factory. De
Santis, who's now a Wall Street Journal reporter, means well _ but
she's never more than a stranger in a strange land. Swayed by her
own gee-whiz bravado, she misses the heart of those who truly live
their lives on the line, if only because she could always walk away
_ and, unlike most of her co-workers, walk away to something far
better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
