<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1133 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MESSINA-2NDTAKE     05-10 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MESSINA-2ND </SLUG>
 TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... into her life.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I first heard Jo in this family-style dinner club an hour and
a half outside of Nashville,'' recalls Gallimore, whose roster of
heavyweight artists includes Tim McGraw, Faith Hill, Brooks and
Dunn, and Randy Travis. ``I guess it was around 1991. I'm telling
you, she was as good that night as she is today. She stole those
people's hearts. I called her two days later and asked her to come
in for a meeting. The first thing she said was `I don't have any
money.' And I said, `I don't want any money. I just want to work
with you.' I guess she'd heard so many tales about being taken
advantage of in Nashville that it took her a while to trust me. So
we cut some sides, and Tim pretty well flipped over her. When she
signed to Curb, he wanted to help out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallimore and McGraw co-produced both of Messina's albums, which
Gallimore accurately describes as unique. ``She has a fire in her
voice that transmits on tape,'' he says. ``Her energy level is off
the map. It's just the way she is. She's a survivor, and she's done
it with raw talent.''
</P>
<P>
   A &AMP; R executive Phil Gernhard, who signed Jo Dee to Curb in 1995
before taking a year off, is more circumspect about her troubled
start. ``I never would have put that record out,'' Gernhard says.
``She didn't know who she was yet as a recording artist. A lot of
those tracks were experiments. But Tim was involved, and he's an
impetuous boy.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Messina had begun work on ``I'm Alright,'' she'd had
more touring and recording experience, and Gernhard was back at
Curb. ``As soon as we started, it was like `Wow, she's found
herself.' She had matured, she had a firm grasp on her music.'' In
his estimation, Messina's next album _ though technically her third
_ will function as the crucial sophomore effort, because it will be
the one to follow her breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easy part is over,'' he says. ``The struggling isn't the
hard part, even though you were starving. The hard part is now,
when it gets serious. It's a business with responsibilities. It's a
pressure cooker, and this is when a lot of people get thrown.
That's why you see artists, talented artists, come and go. But Jo
Dee could run for president and win if she wanted to. She's got the
drive and determination. Jo Dee's future is up to Jo Dee.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surviving has become second nature to Messina, but not
necessarily in the way one would imagine. During the limo ride from
WKLB to the Orpheum for sound check, Messina is glued to her cell
phone. The vivacious showperson who wowed fans in radioland is once
again quiet, curled in the corner of the car, deep in discussion
with a business associate about the merits of a concert offer. The
pay is good, but evidently the venue is questionable. ``Think
career, not money,'' Messina instructs at the end of the call,
despite the fact that she's not yet out of the red.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lessons she learned from the tumult of achieving sudden
success, then losing it all, and now rebuilding her life and career
have underlined Messina's abiding faith _ in both her spiritual and
professional path. ``When I was away from radio for a year or so, I
really relied on God, on him delivering my true friends, and
delivering a smile on days when I couldn't make myself smile,'' she
says, her gaze as steadfast as her belief. ``I've learned how rare
it is to have a career in this business. I've learned about the
folks who have tried and tried and still can't get it done and
there is no obvious reason. So you don't compromise, even if it
kills you. And it has killed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bigger than the blow to her pocketbook was the blow to her sense
of humanity _ naive though it may have been. Her memories of
growing up in Holliston are idyllic. ``We had mom-and-pop pizza
places. We had Fiske's, which is like a general store,'' she
recalls, her eyes glowing. ``It had rows and rows of candy in the
buckets, you know, and you'd go in and get a lollipop, or a piece
of gum, or licorice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up next to the Aldermans my whole life. They were the
greatest people on the face of this earth. And I thought everyone
in the world was like the Aldermans. I thought everyone was that
honest, that trustworthy, that considerate, that kind, that loyal,
that caring, that real. In Nashville, I realized that everyone is
not like the Aldermans. When I stopped getting airplay on the
radio, my phone stopped ringing. No one would return my calls.
People I thought were my friends. And I was devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a silver lining to her travails, it's a pointed, and
poignant, appreciation for what she has. The deed to a modest
three-bedroom house 20 miles east of Nashville. The means to buy a
station wagon for her mother, who now lives near Messina in
Tennessee. (So, by the way, does Sean Alderman, her former
neighbor, whom she hired to work for her.) A joy in singing that's
so great she can't find the words to describe it. The knowledge
that ``all these things that I have in my life, all the success, is
blessing,'' Messina says, clear-eyed and quiet, and you know she
means it. ``It's like the song, `I'm Alright.' I'm here, I'm living
life. I'm not rich. I'm not poor. I've got my health. I'm in the
game. I guess I'm doing OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
