<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1138 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARIN-HOUSING-HNS &LR;      05-10 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARIN-HOUSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AFFORDABLE HOUSING' CREATES STIR IN EXCLUSIVE TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT REYES STATION, Calif. _ The working-class families,
ranchers and wealthy professionals who live among the coastal
hamlets of western Marin County differ in many ways, but they share
an attitude: They don't like outsiders telling them what to do.
</P>
<P>
   So Tuesday night they will crowd into the biggest building in
the area, the Red Barn, to settle by secret ballot one of the most
divisive issues that has engaged the community in recent years:
Should affordable housing be built in Point Reyes Station for the
people who work in this hub of western Marin County but cannot
afford to live here?
</P>
<P>
   For renter Oscar Gamez, assistant manager at Toby's Feed Barn,
the answer is clear. ``We need it,'' he said. ``I'm the only one
working at Toby's who lives here. I'd like to stay here if I can.
This is our one chance to own a house.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jeanette Pontacq, an organic flower grower and retired chief
executive of a large San Francisco travel agency, the correct
decision is equally clear: thumbs down. ``It's like a Trojan horse
has come into West Marin,'' she said. ``This is basically an urban
solution to a rural problem.''
</P>
<P>
   There are only 362 residences in picturesque Point Reyes
Station, population 900. It's a small town and proud of it. An
electric cow moo can be heard daily all over town at noon and 6
o'clock, giving folks the time. The local weekly newspaper, the
Point Reyes Light, has won a Pulitzer Prize. And its main street is
home to some of the best bars (The Western) and restaurants
(Tomales Bay Foods, Station House) in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Rentals here are hard to find, and home prices range from
$270,000 to $900,000 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, EAH of San Rafael, the second largest nonprofit housing
developer in the San Francisco Bay area, wants to build 49 units _
all but five to be sold at below-market rates _ on a 19-acre horse
pasture in the northeast corner of Point Reyes Station. Combined
with a senior housing complex already approved, the projects would
expand the local housing stock by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This area, just north of San Francisco, has never faced such
rapid growth before, but residents are tackling the issue in their
time-tested, albeit idiosyncratic way _ they're talking it out,
trying to reach community consensus.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a community decision,'' said Lamar Turner,
the project manager for EAH. ``We've never done anything like this
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Literally.
</P>
<P>
   If the town hall voters don't support the project, EAH will walk
away. If they do, the company will proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The project abuts West Marin School and is contiguous to the
town itself. As planned, the development would include 26 rental
units, 10 cottages, eight live-work units and five lots to be sold
at market rate. EAH would use the federal low-income housing tax
credit to subsidize the rental units. As for the rest, ``We will
make them as affordable as we can,'' Turner said. ``We will
certainly ask for and pursue subsidies.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 months of planning, EAH has yet to apply to the Marin
County Planning Commission, the Coastal Commission and other
agencies for zoning changes and other permits necessary for the
project. Instead, working with a 13-member steering committee
selected by local organizations, it has tried to incorporate
community concerns raised at a dozen forums. If Tuesday night's
vote falls below 60 percent approval, EAH's board of directors is
expected to drop the project.
</P>
<P>
   Few here debate the need for more affordable housing, but
opponents such as Pontacq do debate whether this rural community
should encourage a development of this size.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to set a huge precedent for more development, and
people are going to be sorry later,'' Pontacq said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   George Stamoulis, a Point Reyes Station resident who works in
San Francisco, agreed: ``It's a gigantic, quantum leap. It's like
dumping 30,000 houses in San Francisco overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet others say the housing shortage has grown so severe it's
altering the very nature of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our workers go through the torments of the damned to get
housing out here,'' said Dave Mitchell, editor and publisher of the
Point Reyes Light. ``We have dishwashers out here who have to
commute almost an hour from Petaluma. ... We recently went to hire
a reporter and got about 50 letters of application, including two
or three top-notch people. When they found out the housing
situation here, they all backed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Existing zoning would allow up to 30 homes on the site, 19 fewer
than EAH proposes. Elizabeth Ptak, executive director of the Marin
Agricultural Land Trust, said she believed the project was in-fill,
not sprawl, and would fit nicely into the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``This process is quite unique _ a real attempt to deal with two
imperatives, a growing population and the impact on the beauty. ...
It's balancing the aesthetics of a small-town atmosphere against
the social need,'' Ptak said. The 19-acre horse pasture, which is
zoned residential, ``is destined to be developed, and if it's not
used for this purpose, it will very likely be developed with very
expensive homes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
