<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; TUESDAY &LR; , May 11.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports of The Times column:
Amid speculation about who will take over the Jets, Leon Hess, the
oil executive and owner of the Jets, is buried today. By Dave
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN (Miami) _ Sports of The Times column on the
Knicks. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-HEAT (Miami) _ The eighth-seeded Knicks, who had a
surprisingly easy 20-point victory in Game 1, face the host Heat in
Game 2 tonight. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   LACROSSE-DEATH (Farmingville, N.Y.) _ It was a freak accident,
so rare that doctors say young athletes have a greater chance of
being killed in their parents' car on the way to Little League or
lacrosse than by being hit in the chest by a ball, which can
disrupt their heartbeat. But today the parents of Eric Sopracasa
bury their son, who died on Wednesday after being hit in the chest
by a lacrosse ball during practice. By Tarik El-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox
News Service, Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
</TEXT>
