<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with BRUINS-CARTER and SCI-LEAVELL are being
transmitted to NYT Photo Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SLOW (Washington) _ After nearly six weeks of dropping
bombs, NATO's Operation Allied Force has proved most notable for
how slowly it has gotten under way. By Fred Kaplan. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-VOLCANO (Santiago Xalitzintla, Mexico) _ Every day the
first piece of news for residents east of Mexico City involves
their snow-capped neighbor: What did Popocatepetl do the night
before? Life under the volcano. By Richard Chacon. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-JOURNAL (Moscow) _ Like most Russian veterans, Anatoly
Vershinkin condemns US involvement in NATO strikes against
Yugoslavia. By David Filipov.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   US-POWER (Washington) _ The United States _ so powerful, so
prosperous, so secure _ is so unsure about how to use its power
outside its own borders. By David M. Shribman. (2 takes) (w and i
coding)
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Washington) _ Ability is what counts, which is
why decisions by people like Rep. Martin Meehan to stick around
will be welcomed far more than condemned. By Thomas Oliphant. (w
and k coding.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DOLE (Salisbury, N.C.) The formative years of Elizabeth
Dole _ the story of a woman who both fulfilled and then challenged
the expectations of her Southern family with her ambitions. By Mary
Leonard (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY (Crystal City, Mo.) _ Bill Bradley is showing
signs of being able to hit the long outside shot in his pursuit of
Al Gore. By Michael Kranish. 1700 words.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIETY-HUMILIATION (Undated) _ Humiliation is the emotion
that's the most difficult to talk about. And, after Littleton, it
very much on everyone's minds. By Matthew Brelis. 1690 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MCNAMARA-COLUMN (Undated) _ It is a measure of how much we need
one another in trying times that 94 percent of Columbine High's
students returned to class. It is a measure of how little we learn
from one another that some students had been asked to stay away. By
Eileen McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ After the trial of Julie Hart Steele,
there should be no doubt about Kenneth Starr's motives in his
investigation of President Clinton. By Robert A. Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   JACOBY-COLUMN (Undated) -- About those 400,000 deaths from
smoking ... By Jeff Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN-COLUMN (Undated) -- When war was destiny. By Martin F.
Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH/SCIENCE (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AMA-IMAGE (Chicago) _ The nation's biggest medical group is
moving from controversy to the one fate it fears more: irrelevancy.
Membership continues to plummet and its critics are simply giving
up. By Larry Tye. 1900 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STONES (New Haven, Conn.) _ When the Rolling Stones' tour
ended, the jet-setting band scattered. Keyboardist and musical
director Chuck Leavell went to Yale to give a speech on conserving
American forests. By Scott Allen. 1200 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BAR-CODE (Undated) _ Twenty-five years ago an Ohio
supermarket executive whisked a 67-cent ten-pack of Wrigley's Juicy
Fruit over a strange contraption and launched the supermarket
checkout scanner. By Peter Howe. 850 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUESTIONS (Undated) _ What makes a cup of water ``boil
again''? By David Ropeik.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLE &LR;   &UR; (l) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-COLUMN (Undated) _ It's that time of year again, the time
for absurd news. By Diane White.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-SOAPS (Undated) -- They used to be TV's outpost for love, sex
and revenge. Now daytime soaps are on a decline as prime-time shows
take up the themes and talk shows the outragious behavior. By
Matthew Gilbert 1850 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-LIFE (Undated) _ Solange De Santis's story of how a woman
ensconced in the white-collar world decided to play ``Norma Rae''
for a while. By Renee Graham.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-TIPS (Undated) _ What's hot on the just-published list.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MESSINA (Boston) _ JoDee Messina, one of the country's
rising stars, returns home and reminisces. By Joan Anderman. (2
takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CHICKS (Undated) _ Dixie Chicks, also on the George Strait
bill, are up and coming country stars. By Steve Morse. 1240 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-FATHER (Undated) _ What would become Aidan Quinn's latest
film began as a story told by a mother to her sons, a tale from the
old country about love, a widow, a curse, and a coffin laid at the
widow's gate. By Renee Graham. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-TRUFFAUT (Undated) _ Francois Truffaut is hot. Why?
``Because there was no one like Truffaut,'' says Jeanne Moreau, who
starred in several Truffaut films. By Michael Blowen. 1350 words.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-GUIDE (Undated) _ Globe critics review current movies.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-VIDEOS (Undated) _ Good and bad in video films. By Globe
staff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FINANCE-HOOKER (Undated) _ Saving for retirement and kids'
education. By Kenneth Hooker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HKN-BRUINS-CARTER (Toronto) _ Bruins forward Anson Carter has
set -- and met -- high standards for himself at every level of
hockey. By Bob Duffy. (2 takes) PHOTO
</P>
