<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Tuesday, May 11.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-ART-THEFTS (Paris) _ Arts Abroad: French chateaux and
manor houses being looted of art objects. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TONYS (New York) _ A reporter's notebook on the aftermath of the
Tony nominations. By Robin Pogrebin.
</P>
<P>
   WHITNEY-AUCTION (New York) _ The Whitney collection is auctioned
at Sotheby's, as the auction season gets under way. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``England, England,'' by Julian
Barnes (Knopf). Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CASSATT-REVIEW (Undated) _ On HBO's the Artists' Specials,
``Mary Cassatt: American Impressionist.'' Reviewed by Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WAR-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``Frontline: Give War a
Chance.'' By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston
Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle,
The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
