<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-FREIER-0511-CO     05-10 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-FREIER-0511-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'FREIERS' ARE SUCKERS, LOATHED IN ISRAELI POLITICS
 &HT;    425&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ To many Israelis, Prime Minister Benjamin ``Bibi''
Netanyahu is stubborn, brazen, and maybe a little loose with the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   That's why they like him.
</P>
<P>
   After all, you can call the controversial leader a lot of names,
but he's no ``freier.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronounced ``frier,'' it means ``sucker'' or ``pushover'' and
the word has become a hot button in the approach to Monday's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Just as no American candidate wants to be seen as a liar, no
Israeli pol can afford to be taken for a ``freier'' -- not in the
tough neighborhood of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bibi is never going to be a freier in anything,'' says
28-year-old Kobi Agami, a Netanyahu supporter who sells pastries in
the Mehaneh Yehuda produce and meat market. ``Especially not with
the Arabs. He's not going to give and give.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, when it comes to politics, Agami adds, ``You can't
trust anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is popular in the crowded stalls of the market, where
the noisy haggling is nearly an art-form and ``freiers'' get swept
aside like yesterday's corn husks.
</P>
<P>
   In everyday Israel, you're a ``freier'' if you wait in line
instead of cutting in, if you actually stop smoking in a no-smoking
area, or if you compromise easily on anything from a parking space
to politics. While Americans might consider it a virtue to be
laid-back, in Israel that's considered foolish complacency.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly derived from Yiddish, antipathy to the ``freier'' may
have started as the tiny country won its toe-hold along the
Mediterranean, battling great odds and in defiance of its Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a deep cultural phenomenon in Israel,'' says Israeli
sociologist Hanna Herzog at Tel Aviv University.
</P>
<P>
   Its daily manifestations can enrage foreigners -- naive
Americans are seen as mega-freiers. But, Herzog said, the concept
helped Israelis shed the stereotype of dependence and weakness that
stigmatized Jews in European ghettos.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, parliamentary candidate Tommy Lapid, an overbearing
talk show personality, has built a political movement by playing
the ``freier'' card.
</P>
<P>
   Lapid's Change Party is running a rant against ultra-Orthodox
Jews, who he makes out to be freeloaders Israel can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello to you, Freier,'' begins a Change Party pamphlet.
</P>
<P>
   The flier asks non-religious Israelis why they serve in the army
while ultra-Orthodox Jews get military exemptions and why they pay
taxes that support religious people who don't work. ``Why?'' the
pamphlet asks, ``Because you're a freier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It works,'' Lapid says. ``There is nothing that people in
Israel hate more than being taken as a sucker.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins.)
</P>
<P>
   Once a political oddity, polls now show Lapid's campaign may win
six seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, fighting for second term, frequently taps into
Israel's fear of ``freiers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not freiers,'' Netanyahu told high-schoolers in April,
explaining his reluctance to give the Palestinians land under the
Oslo peace process.
</P>
<P>
   While Netanyahu's opponents accuse him of being sneaky, some
consider that a quality in facing Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
who Israelis see as an untrustworthy terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Netanyahu) may not be the guy you would buy a used car from,
but the perception is that he will use these shrewd skills in the
(peace) negotiations,'' said Ephraim Yuchtman Ya'ar, an Israeli
sociologist.
</P>
<P>
   But, Netanyahu may find he can only go so far with an image as a
master manipulator.
</P>
<P>
   Some new anti-Netanyahu banners are cropping up around the
capital: ``Only a freier would vote for Netanyahu twice.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
