<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1271 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     05-10 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSE JACKSON: A LONE RANGER OF RESCUE AND DIPLOMACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson is one of a kind.
</P>
<P>
   It's useless to compare him with anyone else. He's different. He
follows his own drummer and has abounding self-confidence and a
clear concept of mission. Jackson is an intuitive advocate,
champion of the underdog, promoter of equality, defender of
justice. When he perceives a wrong, he wants to right it. He makes
waves, and they splash on people.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse thinks he can talk, or shame, the meanest men on earth
into doing something decent. Surprisingly often, he can. Sometimes
a hard-bitten foreign dictator or profit-driven corporate head is
persuaded by Jackson to perform a simple humanitarian act for a
reason that others may suspect as self-serving. But it's hard to
quarrel with the obvious, simple results of the good deed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jackson and a broad-based committee of American
clergy prevailed upon Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
release the three U.S. servicemen he'd been holding as prisoners of
war. Some people bridled at Jackson's brand of personal diplomacy.
Some accused him of interfering with President Clinton's conduct of
foreign policy. Maybe he was, although it's hard to see how.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has suggested that America would be better off with Steve
Gonzales, Chris Stone and Andy Ramirez still in that Serbian
prison.
</P>
<P>
   No president likes to be upstaged, particularly in foreign
affairs. Not even by a friend. Some claiming to know Clinton's mind
say he was ticked off when former President Jimmy Carter, in a
similar mission of personal diplomacy, opened up a dialogue with
North Korean leaders after four decades of bristling armaments and
military threats.
</P>
<P>
   All I know of that episode is that Carter had kept Clinton
informed of his effort and thought he had a clear understanding of
the president's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   There was an obvious misunderstanding, however, in Carter's
journey to Haiti later that year where he and Gen. Colin Powell
persuaded the reigning military junta to stand aside and let the
elected president resume office. A disagreement on how to handle
the negotiations, after they were well under way, almost resulted
in a major international embarrassment. While Carter appealed to
reason, Clinton threatened force.
</P>
<P>
   Save for a successful last-ditch plea by Carter, a
presidentially ordered bombing raid would have rained terror down
on the pitifully poor Caribbean capital just at the moment that the
armed usurpers were agreeing to relinquish power. That
miscalculation could have been a tragedy of monstrous proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Any president needs support and cooperation from the nation if
he is to conduct foreign policy successfully. No American should
set out to embarrass or undermine him. Even so, there are times
when private, unofficial, ``back-channel'' diplomatic probes are
not only useful but necessary. When bilateral
government-to-government communications formally break down,
presidents must rely on informal emissaries as long as there is any
hope for a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon Johnson and Richard Nixon both employed a variety of
go-betweens in a vain effort to communicate with Ho Chi Minh and
his successors in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   Two American businessmen doing business in the Soviet Union _
Armand Hammer and Dwayne Andreas _ reported regularly to Ronald
Reagan after talks with top Soviet officialdom through the 1980s.
Several times I filled a similar role in Latin America for
President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's initiatives are different from these in that he is
pursuing an agenda of his own making, not necessarily the
president's. Not that the chief executive could disapprove of the
humanitarian results. But he couldn't be seen or suspected as
bargaining for them.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jackson talked Syria's hard-line leader, Hafez Assad, into
freeing a downed U.S. Navy pilot named Lt. Robert Goodman in 1984,
he has been the agent of rescue for hundreds of mostly humble
citizens held in military and political prisons. He talked Fidel
Castro into freeing 48 prisoners, Americans and Cubans, and
persuaded Saddam Hussein to release 500 foreign nationals being
held in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The charismatic clergyman's self-initiated forays into
negotiations have not been confined to international diplomacy. Far
more numerous, though less well-known, are times when he's
prevailed upon private business interests to dignify underpaid,
low-skilled workers with an overdue raise, to desegregate theaters
and restaurants, to open stores or extend credit in disadvantaged
neighborhoods, or to end racially discriminatory hiring practices.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse is a preacher with a worldwide parish. He refuses to be
confined. Twice he tried for the Democratic presidential
nomination, probably without expecting to win it. It gave him a
pulpit to say things he wanted to be said.
</P>
<P>
   Gifted with multiple talents, Jackson flirted briefly as a youth
with professional baseball and declined a University of Illinois
football scholarship when told that no black could go out for
quarterback. Trained as a clergyman, he now performs as a
television talk-show host. He speaks at times with a poetic cadence
and may be the best wordsmith and phrasemaker in national political
life today.
</P>
<P>
   A decade and more ago, when I was fighting the battles of
Congress, Jesse would call me occasionally with an original slogan
or pithy phrase he thought I might use to advantage. ``My
brother,'' he'd begin, ``let me tell you what you need to be
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson won't ever be president, and he is just too
independent for the average president to feel wholly comfortable
with Jesse in his Cabinet. But don't try to tell the families of
those he's rescued from captivity that he is anything short of a
fine American and a positive force for good.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright/Ntcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
