<HEADER>
A1272 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWNSIZING-HOUSES-TEX     05-10 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNSIZING-HOUSES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CASE FOR DOWNSIZING TODAY'S PALATIAL HOUSES
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanied by BC-DOWNSIZING-FEATURES) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Architect Sarah Susanka proposes a local heresy. She says small
houses are better houses. This is not in keeping with the
prevailing Texas style, but maybe it should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all searching for home, but we are trying to find it by
building more rooms and more space,'' Susanka says. ``A house is so
much more than its size and volume, neither of which has anything
to do with comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Can it be that three living areas plus an office and a home
theater don't buy happiness, even at today's low interest rates?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so, for many building professionals and homeowners
are responding to Susanka's call for smaller, well-built houses.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, she spoke at the American Institute of Architects'
national convention in Dallas. It was her second podium moment of
the week; she was one of the few speakers who were invited to bat
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Susanka told the assembled throng of conservatively well-dressed
people the words they long to hear but scarcely believe: It's
possible to have a healthy business devoted to designing
residences. Her talk was titled ``Practicing Residential
Architecture: Insights From a Firm That's Made It Work.''
</P>
<P>
   Susanka is motivational. She advises people who want to spend
more than $250,000 to hire an architect. She advises architects who
want more residential projects to ``get over the hump of fear and
go after this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Susanka and her partners in the Minneapolis-based firm
Mulfinger, Susanka, Mahady &AMP; Partners do ``two to three hundred
projects a year with a staff of 40 _ all are residential or
remodeling jobs,'' she said in a recent phone interview. It's
enough work to keep them happily afloat and noticed.
</P>
<P>
   They were chosen to design the 1999 Life magazine Dream House.
The results of their efforts are in the May issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the 1999 house, we wanted an architect that is
well-respected but not untouchable, that you don't need to be a
millionaire to hire to design your house,'' says Jenny Allen,
Life's Dream House project writer. ``The firm relates to how
families live today and is smart about eliminating spaces that
don't serve us well.''
</P>
<P>
   Susanka, 42, catapulted her business into the spotlight last
fall with the publication of ``The Not So Big House: A Blueprint
for the Way We Really Live'' (Taunton Press, $30). Her philosophy
is that we need homes that are compatible with our lives. They
should serve our spiritual needs and material requirements.
</P>
<P>
   We need our kitchens and family rooms, where the family and
guests tend to congregate. We need our bedrooms at bedtime. What we
don't need is spaciousness, Susanka says. ``While you might be able
to afford a 6,000-square-foot house, you may find that building a
3,000-square-foot house that fits your lifestyle actually gives you
more space to live in.''
</P>
<P>
   People buy large houses out of a sense of entitlement, she says.
``We're very afraid of someone putting us in a small house. The
fear is `I'm not going to have enough.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in a nutshell, we're so driven by expedience and
splendid isolation that we lose what is most important, that which
gives our lives meaning, which is connections and relationships.
This is inadvertent, not intentional. We don't have enough things
at the core when we have this bigness.''
</P>
<P>
   When Susanka talks small, people respond in a big way. Her book
was the No. 1 bestseller on home design last year. She gets massive
amounts of e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   To answer frequently asked questions, she has set up a Web site,
www.notsobighouse.com. It functions as a place where architects can
add their names and individual manifestoes.
</P>
<P>
   Aledo-based architect Richard Wintersole believes his work
probably ought to be there. ``I'm doing a 950-square-foot house
right now in Burleson. That's as not-so-big as I've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wintersole had heard about Susanka's list of architects. So have
many others. The word on her is spreading publicly and through the
underground gossip conduits. Her attention has been so diverted by
the overwhelmingly positive reaction to her book, she is going to
leave the architectural firm _ it's amicable, she says _ and devote
her time to the greater interest in the not-so-big house.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
