<HEADER>
A1273 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWNSIZING-FEATURES-T     05-10 0210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNSIZING-FEATURES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 FEATURES THAT DISTINGUISH A NOT-SO-BIG HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies BC-DOWNSIZING-HOUSES) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. The formal and informal spaces are the same.
</P>
<P>
   2. Built-ins and cabinetry serve as furniture but are a natural
extension of the house.
</P>
<P>
   3. Alcoves and window seats offer homey sheltered spaces that
are connected to the room but allow for multiple activities.
</P>
<P>
   4. By raising or lowering the ceiling, spaces are enlivened and
individually defined.
</P>
<P>
   5. Because houses are filled with noise, it is good to offer a
secluded room that is acoustically isolated.
</P>
<P>
   6. A home office should be tailored to the at-home working
needs.
</P>
<P>
   7. Lights should be installed that can transfigure space.
</P>
<P>
   8. There should be a welcoming entrance for both guests and the
people who live in the house. Slipping in through the garage and
laundry room is not a positive way to enter your home.
</P>
<P>
   9. Diagonal views are manipulated to make rooms seem larger.
</P>
<P>
   10. Houses will feel bigger and more comfortable if there are
outdoor connections such as screened porches.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
