<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV16-NY     05-10 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENDERESE: LOOKING FOR A MASTERFUL WEBMISTRESS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, May 16.)  
 (Eds., items in boldface should be set in italics.)  
(js) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hypersensitivity to sexism in language can pull the punch out of
a good sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In ``All Too Human,'' his revealing and riveting White House
memoirs, George Stephanopoulos tells of his attempt to soften a
line that Dick Morris wrote for the 1996 Clinton State of the Union
address.
</P>
<P>
   The line that stole the Republicans' clothes was ``The era of
big government is over.'' A poll presumably taken by Morris showed
those words approved by 80 percent of Americans. But Stephanopoulos
thought that such a potently illiberal line, unqualified, would
make President Clinton a prisoner of conservative oratory. He and
Michael Waldman, a White House speech writer, wanted to balance it
with ``but the era of every man for himself must never begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrote the memoirist: ``Morris, surprisingly, didn't object; but
our political-correctness police did. ... They argued that `every
man for himself' was a sexist insult, and they appealed directly to
the president.'' Clinton neutered the sentence: ``But we cannot go
back to the time when our citizens were left to fend for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the same,'' noted Stephanopoulos correctly. `In a
political speech, it takes a cliche to counter a cliche.''
</P>
<P>
   In wiping away the undoubted masculine tilt to a thousand years
of English, and in attempting to imbue our language with gender
equality, are we going too far too fast? Contrariwise, in making
our language reflect a belated sense of fairness, should we tell
tradition-bound male chauvinists, ``Sorry, buddy, but you can't
make an omelet without breaking eggs''? (Or contra-contrariwise,
should we use an egg metaphor at all in this discussion?)
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the advocates of linguistic sex neutrality have
indisputable logic on their side. If women are going to be firemen,
policemen and mailmen, then we're better off with  &UR; firefighter &LR; ,
 &UR; police officer &LR;  and  &UR; mail carrier &LR; . If the boss of your company is
a woman, you can't call her a  &UR; businessman &LR; ; she's an  &UR; executive &LR; ,
and if she's tall and runs a small business, get a hyphen to help
you out: she's a  &UR; tall small-business executive &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, some have sought to unsex a word but found
resistance:  &UR; chairman &LR;  went through  &UR; chairperson &LR; , which sounded
labored, to  &UR; chair &LR; , which sounded four-legged, and then to
 &UR; chairwoman &LR; , which sounded too much like  &UR; charwoman &LR; . Accordingly,
some presiding women, in a display of security, preferred to go
back to  &UR; chairman &LR; . A more satisfying solution was found to
 &UR; congressman &LR; / &UR; congresswoman &LR; / &UR; congressperson &LR; : we now give all
members of the House of Representatives the neutered title
 &UR; representative &LR; ,  &UR; rep &LR; . for short.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Humankind &LR;  has triumphed over  &UR; mankind &LR;  among the many to whom
the male does not automatically embrace the female. Thus has the
 &UR; century of the common man &LR;  become the  &UR; time of the average
person &LR; , or the  &UR; era of ordinary people &LR; . Somehow  &UR; century of the
common man &LR;  has more of a ring to it; unsexing has its drawbacks.
(The replacement of the verb  &UR; man &LR;  with  &UR; staff &LR;  suggests the order
`` &UR; Staff &LR;  the lifeboats!'' and might encourage anti-P.C. types to
go down with the ship.)
</P>
<P>
   Some gender-diktats make it; some don't. At some colleges,
 &UR; freshmen &LR;  were supposed to be called  &UR; first-year &LR;  students; that
struck most frosh as a little stiff, but &UR; freshman week &LR;  was
replaced in many places by  &UR; orientation week &LR; . ( &UR; First-year &LR;  Asian
students did not object.)
</P>
<P>
   I have long enjoyed the search for female equivalents to other
masculine words:  &UR; avuncular &LR; , for example, meaning ``genial,
kindly, familial,'' is rooted in the Latin for ``maternal uncle.''
The Nonsexist Word Finder, a sternly prescriptive dictionary of
gender-free usage, by Rosalie Maggio, directs readers to avoid the
word. OK; why can't we have a new adjective that calls up the
qualities of an aunt? (I took a crack at this coinage years ago,
rejecting the hesitant  &UR; tantitive &LR;  for the smiling  &UR; amital &LR; , based
on the Latin for ``father's sister.'' It went nowhere.)
</P>
<P>
   Finding the appropriate feminine alternative to masculine words
is not easy. How about  &UR; womanizer &LR; ? For a promiscuous female,
 &UR; loose woman &LR;  sounds dated and  &UR; slut &LR; , overly harsh;  &UR; temptress &LR; 
and  &UR; seductress &LR;  deal with technique rather than state. My
preference is  &UR; philanderer &LR; ; although based on ``love of man,'' it
imputes enjoyment of playing around to both sexes, on the analogy
of  &UR; representative &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Pronouns need special handling. By constantly personifying nouns
like judge, author, critic and executive with  &UR; he &LR; , notes the
National Council of Teachers of English, we subtly condition
ourselves against thinking of women in those roles. One way to
avoid that is to recast into the plural: ``Give each student  &UR; his &LR; 
paper as soon as  &UR; he &LR;  is finished'' can be desexed with ``Give
students  &UR; their &LR;  papers as soon as  &UR; they &LR;  are finished.'' In the
same way, ``The average judge is worried about  &UR; his &LR;  opinion being
overturned on appeal'' can be fixed as ``Most judges are worried
about  &UR; their &LR; , etc.'' When desperate, fall back on the
space-consuming  &UR; his or her &LR; . (Why don't we use  &UR; her or his &LR; ?
Relax; it's because the  &UR; s &LR;  elides more easily than the  &UR; r &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, one of the hottest new words in the computer world is
resolutely sexist.  &UR; Webmaster &LR;  is ``one who designs, develops,
markets and/or maintains one or more sites on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bill Cullifer, executive director of the World
Organization of Webmasters (WOW) in Fulsom, Calif., ``the word
originally came from  &UR; postmaster &LR; . The early Webmasters were those
academics who routed electronic stuff.'' ( &UR; Stuff &LR;  is a big word
among  &UR; Webmasters &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   But  &UR; master &LR; , from the Latin  &UR; magister &LR; , ``chief,'' has always
been associated with males, especially controlling, dominant,
insensitive fellows. Its female counterpart is  &UR; mistress &LR; ,
sometimes pronounced ``gerfren.'' Many of WOW's 7,000 members are
women; what to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``At the World Wide Web conference in Australia,'' Cullifer
says, ``some guy asked why we didn't use more inclusive language. A
female Webmaster got up and said, `If you don't like it _ too bad.'
'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
