<SLUG> BC-CRAFTS-DUCTTAPE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO KNEW DUCT TAPE COULD MAKE SUCH COOL CRAFTS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was bound to happen _ eventually someone would envision the
possibilities of craft projects made entirely of duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   The world can thank Joe Wilson, 37, Canadian comic and resident
of Guelph, Ontario. ``It was a long winter, and I don't play
hockey,'' he says by way of explanation, or apology, for inventing
the duct-tape apron, tool belt, baseball cap, cellular phone holder
and bachelor's toilet-roll cover, among other clever projects.
</P>
<P>
   These are the things that MADE IT into the book. Wilson's
not-so-famous duct-tape quotes were cut:
</P>
<P>
   ``Veni, vidi, ducti'' (I came, I saw, I taped.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Carpe ducti'' (Seize the tape.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Tape it so, No. 1'' _ Capt. Jean-Luc Picard
</P>
<P>
   He's still chapped about that, though his book is full of
duct-tape minutiae such as the chapter titled ``The Role of the
Roll: A Ripping History.''
</P>
<P>
   Invented by the military during WWII to keep ammunition boxes
dry, it was a khaki-colored cloth mesh tape with a rubber-based
waterproof adhesive. It was christened gun tape. Once in the field,
soldiers found innumerable uses for the almost indestructible
product.
</P>
<P>
   The postwar desire for central air-conditioning demanded the
color change to gray to match sheet-metal ducts, and it became
known as duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   In his book's FAQ section, Wilson explains the difference in
duct tape prices. ``If you rip off a piece of tape and look at it
closely, you can actually count the number of threads. These
threads are called the `scrim.' The more threads per inch, the
stronger the tape. The stronger the tape, the more costly it is to
produce. `Military tape' has a 40-pound rip strength. Less
expensive tapes have only a 20-pound rip strength. Generally, the
more you spend on tape, the less tape you have to use.''
</P>
<P>
   The glory of the book is the projects. Most of them are
fashioned by using three basic duct-tape techniques: sheets, strips
and loops.
</P>
<P>
   The waterproof-flakproof apron uses both sheets and strips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Materials needed:
</P>
<P>
   Duct tape
</P>
<P>
   1. Create one sheet, 26x32 inches. (Sheets are made by
overlapping layers of duct tape, working both the back and front
sides to create a double-sided, thick sheet of duct fabric.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Create three big strips: one 26 inches long for the neck
strap, one 24 inches long and one 13 inches long; these will form
the belt.
</P>
<P>
   3. Positioning your sheet vertically, mark off and cut a 7-inch
square from each side of the top of the sheet. You can attach these
squares as pockets on the front of your apron. The top of your
apron will now measure 12 inches.
</P>
<P>
   4. Attach your 26-inch strip at each corner of the 12-inch bib.
Tape the ends of the strip down firmly on the back of the apron
using about 2 inches of tape for each end. This is the neck strap.
</P>
<P>
   5. Take the 24- and 13-inch strips and attach them to the side
corners, 24-inches from the bottom. This is your belt.
</P>
<P>
   According to Wilson ``Yes, the apron is waterproof. And yes,
real men do dishes. The `flakproof' part works like this: If you
put on the apron and do the dishes, you're going to get a whole lot
less flak. Peace in our time. Once again, duct tape has a strategic
military use.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
