A1276 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PREGNANCY-ADVICE-TEX     05-10 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREGNANCY-ADVICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR USES SCRIPTURE AND PERSONAL EXPERIENCE TO ENCOURAGE PREGNANT
WOMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHLAKE, Texas _ As far as Jessica Lee Kelly is concerned,
it's God _ not the devil _ who is in the details.
</P>
<P>
   And even though, for a pregnant woman, the details are sometimes
nagging, God is still in the mix, she says.
</P>
<P>
   It's just hard to believe that notion at times _ such as when
the mother-to-be finds herself pulled over by the side of the road
in rush-hour traffic waiting for morning sickness to pass.
</P>
<P>
   But in her new book, ``Pregnancy: The Miracle Journey,'' Kelly
offers what she says is a reminder to pregnant women that God will
be there through nine months of great changes, small worries and
the birth of a child.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Please give me a parking place up close,' '' quips Kelly,
34, of Southlake north of Fort Worth. ``People don't know they can
pray for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration for writing the book came from Kelly's personal
pregnancy experience and her search for material that would
spiritually prepare her for the change in her life and body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for guidance on how to start preparing to be a
mother,'' Kelly said. ``I was trying to get it from books or
girlfriends. I couldn't find the book that would give me a
spiritual guide.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, which combines Scripture with practical advice and
space for journal writing, was released last month by Herald Press
and will be available at local bookstores, on the Internet from
Amazon.com and through the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some other (books), but I think this is a unique
package in which she puts in an opportunity for journaling and
meditation and keeping track of the pregnancy,'' said David Garber,
senior editor of the book.
</P>
<P>
   For Michelle Carlstedt, a cousin of Kelly's who used the book
while pregnant with her daughter, Brooke, now 12 weeks old, the
book offered an opportunity to document her pregnancy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you are pregnant, instead of thinking all the
time about how you feel and how you can't do this, that or the
other thing, the Scriptures reminded me that it is a child and how
lucky I was that I was pregnant,'' Carlstedt said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the book is broken into three parts _ or
trimesters. Within that framework, Kelly devised monthly and weekly
subsections.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the weeks start with a personal anecdote from one of
Kelly's friends. For example, in the 29th week a friend offered
this advice:
</P>
<P>
   ``As the mother of six children, I can tell you: Change is
certain, laundry is constant, all things will pass, and stretch
marks will fade.''
</P>
<P>
   The anecdotes are followed by Kelly's observations, personal
experience and practical advice. For that 29th week, the topic was
stretch marks and vanity.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, there is also a workbook-type page with a line of
Scripture for each day. On day five of week 29, for instance, a
passage from Proverbs states: ``Charm is deceitful, and beauty is
vain, but a woman who fears the Lord is to be praised.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it was just so encouraging,'' said Grapevine resident
Suzette Evans-Roach, who tested the book for Kelly during her
pregnancy. ``It was a real good guidance to journaling while you
are pregnant to help you in prayers for the baby and yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration for the book came from a need Kelly said she felt
during her first pregnancy. When Kelly was pregnant with her first
son, Colton, now 5, her husband, Mike, a pilot, was away for long
periods of time. And because her mother had died of cancer when
Kelly was 16, she had to look to others for help and advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think that what happened is I didn't have a lot of people
to talk to,'' Kelly said. ``... I just felt, `How in the world am I
going to do this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly kept a journal of the experience, marking down changes in
her life and body. She fit in the writing as best she could,
balancing her job as a J.C. Penney fashion buyer with a first
trimester that required her to drive around with a supply of
air-sickness bags her husband supplied.
</P>
<P>
   But the physical side of pregnancy wasn't Kelly's only concern.
She also worried about how well she would handle motherhood. So she
decided she needed to address these matters from a Christian
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see shortcomings in yourself until you are going to
be fully responsible for another one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During her second pregnancy, with her son Clay, now 3, Kelly
said she kept a more detailed journal with the purpose of
eventually writing the book.
</P>
<P>
   With her own experience documented, Kelly looked to friends and
relatives for anecdotes and advice. She also spent six months
searching the Bible for Scripture passages that would speak to
pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   ``God wants us to be encouraged,'' said Kelly, who shopped for a
publisher until Herald Press, part of Mennonite Publishing House in
Scottdale, Pa., agreed to take the book in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Kelly said she hopes the book will remind women to
be thankful, even as they struggle with the challenges of
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have morning sickness or just feel miserable, but we
have a choice about our spiritual attitude,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
