<HEADLINE>
BRANDWISE WILL LAUNCH COMPARISON SHOPPING WEB SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ brandwise, LLC announced that it will launch its
comparison shopping Web site, brandwise.com, in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   brandwise.com will offer the results of product testing by the
Good Housekeeping Institute, a unit of The Hearst Corporation.
Other participants include the Whirlpool Corporation and The Boston
Consulting Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``brandwise.com represents the next step in the evolution of
e-commerce,'' says Kathy Misunas, CEO of brandwise, LLC. ``Our
objective is to empower consumers with an unprecedented level of
content, including in-depth product descriptions, advice, extensive
customer support, and a wide variety of community features, backed
by some of the most credible product testing techniques in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Product categories will initially include major appliances, and
will be expanded to include consumer electronics, lawn and garden,
small household appliances and power tools.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth A. Bronfin, deputy group head and senior vice president
of Hearst New Media and Technology, said Hearst was the largest
equity partner in brandwise.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only will consumers have comprehensive information and
customized comparisons for products that have been through the
rigorous testing process guided by the Good Housekeeping Institute,
but brandwise.com will be an open, unbiased site, so that any
retailer, distributor or manufacturer in the product category has
the ability to participate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Hake, senior executive vice president and chief financial
officer of Whirlpool Corporation, said brandwise.com would
``empower the consumer to make more informed buying decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
