<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GROUP-MARATHON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-DISTANCE RUNNER NO LONGER LONELY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif., Ga., Ohio)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By KIMBERLY STEVENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lydia Siegel ran the Boston marathon last month and
credits some of her success to the group she meets on Tuesday
evenings in Central Park. ``It's a lot easier in the freezing rain
to meet up with a group,'' said Ms. Siegel, a 27-year-old research
assistant at Mount Sinai Medical Center. ``When people have similar
goals, it makes it much more fun, and easier to train.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the growing numbers of people running in groups, it
looks as if the loneliness of the long distance runner may be a
thing of the past. Group marathon training is expanding across the
country and running groups, health clubs, coaches and personal
trainers are becoming instrumental in providing safe and successful
venues for long distance training.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Lamppa, of the U.S.A. Track and Field Road Running
Information Center, a database for running statistics in Santa
Barbara, Calif., says the nation is in the midst of a second
running boom, which he describes as more of a participation boom
than the first, in the late 70s and early 80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of marathon runners now are less competitive,
their focus on health and fitness,'' he said. ``Part of the growth
can be attributed to the group mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamppa said nearly every one of the nation's 250 marathons has a
training group affiliated with it. ``Marathons become social
institutions in every city, and people want to be a part of it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the success of groups like Team in Training, begun by the
Leukemia Society of America with 57 chapters nationwide, and the
Galloway program, based in Atlanta, offshoots and similar programs
have popped up all over. Health clubs have caught on to the trend,
possibly as a way to lure runners back into the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Crunch in New York City has implemented a program called ``You
Can Run a Marathon,'' which offers an educational seminar series
and organized running groups.
</P>
<P>
   And the group mentality may be a key reason why marathon running
has become increasingly popular. According to a spokeswoman for the
New York City Marathon, there were a record-breaking 13,254 runners
who waited in line for a number on April 25 to participate in the
race next November, although only 7,500 numbers were given out.
</P>
<P>
   Last year only 9,871 waited in line for the 7,500 numbers. Later
this month Cincinnati will host its first marathon, The Flying Pig
Marathon, and 7,500 have signed up _ a startling number for a
first-time marathon, Lamppa said.
</P>
<P>
   The marathon training season is beginning now, and Jeff
Galloway, an Olympic runner and author of two books, including
``Marathon'' (1996, Phidipoides Publishing), will travel to 50
cities nationally to lecture to marathon training groups. ``The
most noticeable difference I see in running today compared to
running in the late 70s is that people are running together,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Keohane, who runs his own marathon training group in New
York City, said he is amazed at how drastically the marathon
training scene has changed. ``Running has become an incredibly
popular social outlet,'' he said. What he refers to as the ``middle
of the pack,'' he added, is growing rapidly because of this
mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the folks that are responsible for the boom in small
national races,'' he said. ``They all travel together and run
together and really support one another.''
</P>
<P>
   And the increasing proportion of women who are interested in
marathon running may contribute to the numbers of organized running
groups that are popping up nationally. Amby Burfoot, editor of
Runners World magazine, attests to the social running phenomenon
and recognizes the role of women. ``Women statistically are better
joiners and tend to be part of groups more often than men,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Keller, 32, a graphic designer who lives in San Francisco
couldn't imagine what it would be like running a marathon alone.
``The desire to share the experience, from beginning to end is
powerful,'' she said. ``It just feels natural to be with others
along the way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
