<HEADER>
A1297 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BEETLES-FIRE-ART-     05-10 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BEETLES-FIRE-ART-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE TRAIL OF FIRE-DETECTING BEETLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During a forest fire, most insects and animals flee
in all directions _ flying, running, crawling and using every
possible means to avoid the deadly flames. But there are
exceptions, like some jewel beetles.
</P>
<P>
   These insects are fire seekers. Fire in the woods, particularly
if certain tree species are burning, draws them from miles away. So
intense is their interest that firefighters are sometimes hampered
by swarms of the flying beetles, which swirl around in a
distracting mass or latch onto the humans with their powerful
mandibles.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly strange conduct of these fire beetles, as they are
sometimes called, is not an exercise in self-destruction but an
example of evolutionary behavior aimed at perpetuating their
species, scientists say. And some scientists believe people can
capitalize on their behavior and the body parts they use to detect
fire or sense chemicals in the environment.
</P>
<P>
   In their fire-seeking frenzy, flying into flames or crawling
along still-smoldering trees, the beetles may be trying to beat
competitors to weakened or dying trees so that they are the first
to plant their eggs into them, researchers believe. To do that,
though, the beetles must be able to find burning trees and get to
them quickly. While it has been known for decades that these
insects have infrared detectors that allow them to sense the heat
of fires, new research by German scientists indicates they also
possess highly sensitive detectors in their antennas that allow
them to sense minute amounts of volatile substances in smoke from
burning wood.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stefan Schuetz of the Justus Liebig University in Giessen,
Germany, and colleagues say this highly sensitive smoke detection,
coupled with their heat sensors, appears to be part of a system
that allows the beetles to sense fires and home in on them from
distances of more than 30 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a complex interplay with the infrared system that we
do not fully understand,'' Schuetz said, ``but we think detecting
the smoke may be an early indication to the beetle that there is a
fire in the area.'' The beetles are often found in hilly places
where there may not be the clear line of sight to a fire that is
needed by their heat detectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that if they detect the odor of a fire they fly up
and look around,'' Schuetz said. The insects may also follow a
wispy trail of smoke until their infrared detectors locate the
blaze and guide them to it, he added.
</P>
<P>
   E. Richard Hoebeke, a beetle expert in the entomology department
at Cornell University said the German work was ``new and exciting''
but also showed how much people had to learn about insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did these beetles develop their ability to lay eggs this
way?'' Hoebeke asked. ``Think about how little we know of insects
with incredibly sensitive and complex sensory mechanisms.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daniel Young, director of the insect research collection at
the University of Wisconsin's entomology department, said many
beetle species found in the United States and Canada exhibited
fire-seeking behavior, looking for stressed or dying trees in which
to plant their eggs, so their larvae could develop in or under the
bark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trees that are healthy have chemicals, such as pitch, to
attack a parasite and the strength to resist invasion,'' Young
said. ``Those that are weakened, dying or dead are more acceptable
hosts for insect pests.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these invading insects prefer certain trees for food or
egg-laying, experts said, and attack only that species or closely
related species.
</P>
<P>
   Jewel beetles belong to a family of insects called Buprestidae,
hard-shelled creatures named for their shiny, metallic &UR; - &LR; looking
shells, often dabbed with bright colors or spots. The fire beetle
studied by the German researchers, a species called Melanophila
acuminata, with a less dazzling charcoal color is common in
temperate zones of the Northern Hemisphere, including large areas
of Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William G. Evans, an entomologist who studied the insects 30
years ago as a professor at the University of Alberta in Edmonton,
Canada, said he was gratified that scientists were continuing to
study the beetles, but not too surprised by their findings. ``All
insects have olfactory organs in their antennas,'' he said, ``and
you would almost expect the beetles to detect smoke.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In earlier research, Evans discovered that Melanophila acuminata
had a pair of thoracic pit organs that were sensitive infrared
receptors, guiding the insect to fires.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the German team involved in the antenna work, Helmut
Schmitz and Horst Bleckmann of Friedrich Wilhelm Rhineland
University in Bonn, Germany, have continued work on the heat
receptors.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said the theory that smoke activated the beetles' hunt for
a fire was plausible, but that locating burning trees was primarily
the function of the infrared detectors.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published in March in the British journal Nature,
Schuetz and his colleagues said they removed antennas from the
beetles, dipped them in an electricity-conducting liquid that
contained nutrients and connected them to instruments that measured
electrical changes in the fluid. The antennas were exposed to
volatile chemicals from smoldering pieces of wood and the reactions
generated by thousands of sensory hairs on the antennas were
measured by electrical changes.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the antennas were particularly
sensitive to phenolic compounds found in wood smoke, and that the
reaction was pronounced for a species of pine tree, Pinus
sylvestris, it particularly favored. The antennas detected
combustion derivatives in concentrations as low as a few parts per
billion, the researchers reported. They estimated that this
sensitivity would allow a beetle to detect the smoldering bark of a
single pine tree in light wind from a distance of more than half a
mile.
</P>
<P>
   Similar tests on the antennas of three other beetles, including
two that attack weakened trees, showed much lower sensitivity to
combustion compounds, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   Most forest fires occur in the autumn, Schuetz said, and this is
when the beetles lay most of their eggs. The eggs require a cooling
period to hatch, which they do after the winter frost, and the
larvae develop in the spring. Another curiosity about the beetle's
reproductive cycle is that only 65 percent of the eggs hatch, he
said, and the other third lie dormant for a year. Of these
remaining eggs, two-thirds hatch the following year, and the rest
stay inactive for yet another year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beetles need forest fires to propagate, and this appears
to be a protective mechanism to keep the species going through
years when there are no fires,'' Schuetz said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said that understanding how the beetles detected
fires could have practical applications, particularly in developing
new types of fire alarms and early warning detectors for forest
fires. Schuetz said his group was working with his university's
physics institute on a bio-sensor for fire warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Current fire alarms that look at carbon dioxide levels or
combustion volatiles can be fooled by automobile fumes and other
gases, he said, and the group is trying to develop a hybrid system
using electronics and biological sensors to detect specific
by-products of smoldering fires. They are testing a prototype
bio-sensor that uses transistorized components and actual beetle
antennas, he said, and are trying to isolate and identify the
proteins in the insect antennas that react to smoke so that they
can be used in more advanced devices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
