<HEADLINE>
FAITH SURVIVES THE RUIN OF OKLAHOMA STORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT FLORES  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWEST CITY, Okla. _ The sanctuary was shattered, but the
spirit remained intact.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Sooner Baptist Church gathered in an outdoor worship
service on Mother's Day to reinforce their faith and to demonstrate
their unfettered resolve on the first Sunday after a series of
killer tornadoes pummeled the Oklahoma City and surrounding
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important to remind ourselves that our church is
not the building, that the church is the people,'' the Rev. John
Coker said moments before he conducted a service for about 150
parishioners in the small, tight-knit congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The services were held in the parking lot because a twister
demolished the 51-year-old church. A heap of pulverized bricks,
splintered wood and mangled steel was the backdrop for the prayers.
</P>
<P>
   A wooden cross that used to hang above the church organ was
propped up with several bricks on top of the rubble, and an
American flag and another bearing a cross flapped in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   A telling banner was fastened to the remnants of a church wall:
``The God of heaven shall prosper us, therefore we, his servants,
will arise and build. _ Nehemiah 2:20.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen recovered church pews and dozens of assorted
folding chairs provided most of the seating for the congregation.
Several children sat on blankets that had been spread across the
paved lot.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the congregation in its service were 55 uniformed
members of a crisis response team known as ALERT, a Christian-based
organization of young volunteers who help with disaster clean-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the church is the people, then we've not lost a thing,''
Coker said, motioning toward the congregation. He noted that
despite the destructive force of the tornado that struck this
community east of Oklahoma City on May 3, none of the congregation
members was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the death toll in the Oklahoma City area was more than
40, Coker said he was amazed thousands of lives were spared. The
twisters had sliced across the city in some of its most heavily
populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   Among those escaping unscathed were five members of one family
who had sought refuge in the church nursery after they saw the
approaching storm. Although the tornado demolished the church, the
family members were unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Coker said that harrowing episode was a testament that God was
watching over his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to remind us that whenever God is involved with
his people, his people are going to be OK,'' Coker said. ``He's
protected us and He'll also help us rebuild this thing _ and build
it back a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   The pastor praised members of his congregation, a handful of
whom lost their homes to tornadoes. Many members had lived for
years in the neighborhood's modest homes a short distance from
Tinker Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   ``These folks are stable and have a strong faith. They are not
high-strung and reactive,'' Coker said. ``A lot of them are from
the generation that went through the Great Depression and World War
II _ they have a character about them that knows how to handle
adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the congregation echoed that resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important for us to be here today. You need to be
together when something like this happens,'' said Charles Guidry, a
member of the congregation. ``We are very small, but we are very
devoted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
