<SLUG> BC-TORNADOES-WICHITAFALLS-1000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WICHITA FALLS RELIVES TRAUMA AFTER TORNADOES IN OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By D'ANN MABRAY SHIPPY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The stillness inside Fay and Lee Hogle's
bathroom was eerie. No movement. No sound.
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit, hammering the house. The roof was torn from the
walls, and seconds later, dropped back into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall what I heard before the silence. That puzzles
me,'' said Fay Hogle, 84. ``My husband said it sounded like a
train.''
</P>
<P>
   It was ``Terrible Tuesday,'' April 10, 1979, in Wichita Falls.
The day a mammoth tornado cut an 8-mile-long swath through the
city, killing 45 people, injuring 1,702 and leaving 20,000
homeless. It was strikingly similar to the tornadoes that
demolished parts of Oklahoma City and nearby towns last week,
killing more than 40 people, flattening houses and shredding the
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The images make Fay Hogle's heart ache.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cry with them. Just seeing it, I relived it. You can't help
it, and that's been 20 years ago. ... I don't care to talk about
it,'' she said, taken aback by unexpected tears. ``Isn't that odd?
I thought I was over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wichita Falls has rebuilt its neighborhoods, shops and municipal
buildings, and survivors' physical scars have healed. But even for
those such as the Hogles, who said their experience was less
traumatic than that of many of their neighbors, Terrible Tuesday
left an indelible mark.
</P>
<P>
   How survivors of trauma _ from violent crime to tornadoes _ cope
and rebuild their lives varies from person to person, experience to
experience, said Mary Grace, a senior research associate in the
psychiatry department at the University of Cincinnati and a
founding member of the International Society of Traumatic Stress
Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Some appear unaffected, others experience long-term numbness and
avoidance _ subtle indications of post-traumatic stress disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Most fall somewhere in the middle. These are the people who
initially experience nightmares or are overly vigilant, for
example, checking the sky regularly after surviving a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   That will happen to the Oklahoma tornado victims, said Jeremiah
Davidson, 29, a survivor of the Wichita Falls tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's far from over for them. I can tell you right now that
they'll be watching the skies, and every time a storm blows up,
they'll be nervous. They've got a right to be,'' Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   But in time they, like the Wichita Falls tornado survivors, will
``re-establish their psychological equilibrium,'' Grace said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say there won't be lingering effects,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wichita Falls tornado survivor Lori McConnell, 24, knows about
lingering effects.
</P>
<P>
   The 1979 tornado hit at dusk, just after her mother, Cathy
Grimes, finished her afternoon paper route. After spotting the
black funnel cloud, Grimes grabbed 4-year-old Lori and Lori's
18-month-old sister, Lacy, put them inside her Ford Pinto, and
headed for her husband's office.
</P>
<P>
   They never made it.
</P>
<P>
   As debris blew by, Grimes pulled the car over and ran with the
girls into a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom was holding Lacy under her, and she had a hold of my
wrist. My feet were off the ground,'' McConnell said. ``Then I
guess her adrenalin just kicked in, and she yanked me under her
until the storm had passed.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, McConnell said she prepared for future tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I packed up all my prized possessions _ my Nancy Drew books
and a letter from my Grandma. And whenever the (warning) sirens
would go off, I grabbed them and ran to my neighbor's cellar,''
McConnell said. ``It really had an effect on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, McConnell said she makes sure to place her children in
day-care centers that have a storm shelter or a basement.
</P>
<P>
   The lingering effects on longtime Wichita Falls resident L.E.
Williamson are even more conspicuous.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, 76, keeps 25 one-gallon milk jugs full of fresh
water, as well as a kit with two oil lamps, a battery-powered
radio, a flashlight and candles. And during tornado season, he
makes certain that his automobiles have a full tank of gas, which
was a rare commodity for days after Terrible Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He also always pays attention to the birds, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Comanche Indian told me once that if you can look outside
and not see any birds, to get worried,'' Williamson said. ``You'll
notice that after a tornado, you don't see any dead birds around.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Holster was a 17-year-old high school senior working at
Kmart when the Wichita Falls tornado hit. The store was only
partially damaged, but her family's house was destroyed. They
survived because they got inside a cellar, but they had to use the
weight of their bodies to keep the door shut against the powerful
winds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and my daughter think I'm crazy, but because of
that, I had a lock put on the inside of a closet inside our
house,'' Holster said. ``And when bad weather starts brewing, I put
my jewelry in a Baggie and grab my purse and go inside.''
</P>
<P>
   But because everyone responds differently to trauma, there are
some who purport to be unfazed by calamity.
</P>
<P>
   And that's OK, Grace said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a reasonable response,'' Grace said. ``There might be
some people whose defenses have them bounce right back and say,
`Everything is fine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Grace knows about trauma's long-term effects. Until 1991, she
and a team of psychiatric professionals studied the survivors of a
1972 dam break that killed 165 people in a small community in West
Virginia. Without warning, water swept through the narrow valley,
pulling babies from their parents' arms and drowning skilled
swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   She has made 30 trips to the area, and she said her findings
show that most people improve, especially children.
</P>
<P>
   The key to recovery? Talking _ with family, friends, neighbors,
clergy, hairdressers, Grace said.
</P>
<P>
   Wichita Falls residents have done a lot of that over the years.
Everyone has a story to tell, and they do. They have seen the black
clouds. They have walked neighborhoods that have no recognizable
landmarks, forcing them to count streets to find any remnant of
their houses. They have mourned the loss of human life, and still
do.
</P>
<P>
   And they say it has made them stronger. The Oklahoma tornado
victims will be stronger for it, too, Holster said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wichita Falls can relate. We know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
