<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEDY-BUGS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACTERIA THAT GORGE ON ROTTING WASTE CAN BREAK DOWN DDT  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MAY 10, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By MATT WALKER  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicken and cow manure, old newspapers, straw and wood chips can
be used to clean up land contaminated with dangerous chlorinated
