<HEADER>
A1315 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-TRIP-COX     05-10 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-TRIP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volunteers recall despair in Albanian refugee camps
 &HT;    By Robert Sims
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tears come to Norman Goldblum's eyes when
recounting what he witnessed last week in one Ethnic Albanian
refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tents that they are living in are absolutely horrible,''
the Palm Beach resident said. ``It might be sufficient for the
summer, but when the winter comes, I don't know what's going to
happen. And even when the conflict is over, they don't have homes
to return to. It's heart-wrenching to see the woman with their
babies. No one knows where the men are. I'm in tears just thinking
about it now. I think about it and I break up.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldblum and Mark Levy, both vice presidents of Jewish
Federation of Palm Beach County, returned Friday from a five-day
mercy mission to the Balkans coordinated by the United Jewish
Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The mission required Goldblum and Levy to accompany 20 tons of
provisions from Israel to the refugee camp in the Albanian capital
of Tirana. Goldblum flew to the Balkans not expecting a sightseeing
tour, but he did not anticipate walking out of the refugee camp
`emotionally shook up.'
</P>
<P>
   Housed at a summer swimming resort, the refugee camp serves as
home to 5,000 ethnic Albanians forced to leave Kosovo by the
Serbian authorities. Refugees live nine to a tent, receive their
daily rations of water by the bucket, bath or shower once a week
and crowd bulletins boards hoping for news about missing loved
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Levy said, this is `one of the better-conditioned
camps,' dubbed by relief workers as the `Hilton' of refugee camps.
The refugees looked clean and dignified, Levy said, but they still
need more food, water and clothing. Relief workers forbid Goldblum
and Levy from handing out provisions on their own _ not even so
much as a candy bar _ fearing refugees would mob them.
</P>
<P>
   Provisions distributed included food, clothing and medicine. The
United Jewish Appeal, which serves as conduit for overseas funding
for Jewish Federations nationwide, has so far distributed 120 tons
of provisions to the camps and airlifted 100-plus ethnic Albanian
refugees to Israel. Relief has come from the Jewish Federation, the
Jewish Agency for Israel (JAFI) and the American Jewish Joint
Distribution Committee (JDC). The JDC has already raised $2.25
million in relief for the estimated 370,000 Ethnic Albanian
refugees in addition to the $1.25 million raised by Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Besides distributing food and clothes, Goldblum and Levy heard
stories about how armed Serbians excavated Albanian towns in a
matter of minutes. The Serbians detained men to execute or to use
as slave labor, refugees speculated.
</P>
<P>
   `One adorable little girl followed me around the camp,' said
Levy, a Palm Beach native who now lives in West Palm Beach. ``I
asked what happened to her. Through a translator, she told me that
her mother, father and brother were dead. I could not bring myself
to ask what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldblum believes the past will take care of itself, so he
restricted himself to questioning the refugees about how to
alleviate their suffering. Aside from provisions, the refugees need
permanent housing if they are to survive the blistering summer heat
and the bone-chilling winter cold.
</P>
<P>
   The men said the refugees told them that their lives are in
limbo. They want to return to Kosovo if and when the conflict ends,
even though they fear Serbian forces destroyed their homes. Yet
they do not want to live under the rule of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just don't know what's going to happen. They're in a
state of mental shock,'' Goldblum said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Levy heard the same from Yugoslavian Jews airlifted to Israel
during this and previous United Jewish Appeal relief missions. This
struck a cord in Levy. In the early 1990s, Levy visited refugees
who fled Ethiopia for Israel. The Ethiopian refugees, Levy said,
were ``looking forward to a new life in Israel. (The Yugoslavian
Jews) do not know what the future holds and they want to return to
their homeland.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldblum and Levy returned to Israel with 30-plus young
Yugoslavian Jewish evacuees from Belgrave. The Yugoslavian Jews _
mainly women, children and the elderly _ fled to Budapest in
Hungary when NATO began bombing Belgrave. None had lost their homes
at the time they left Belgrade, but they did not feel safe in the
city. They were airlifted from a hotel used as shelter for
Yugoslavian Jews to a kibbutz north of Tel Aviv. Goldblum said they
have six weeks to decide whether they want to become Israeli
citizens or return home to Belgrade when the NATO bombing ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're Jewish,'' Levy said, ``but they don't really know
about Israel. They think Israel's a dangerous place to live
(because of tensions between Jews and Arabs). I talked to one woman
who said she could not walk down the streets of Belgrade alone at
night. I said to her that Israel is so safe that she can walks the
streets alone at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Ethnic Albania refugees, Goldblum said, the
Yugoslavian Jews do not understand why NATO targeted Belgrade for
bombing. Levy said the Yugoslavian Jews' opinions on the Kosovo
crisis has been colored by propaganda spread by the Milosevic
regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they really understand the full force of what's
going on, from the bombing to the genocide,' Goldblum said. ``They
hear what we say, but they don't seem to listen or have mixed
emotions about what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't remember World War II and they don't remember what
happened to the Jews. I was told that in Albania, during World War
II, no Jewish family was turned over to the Germans. Albania
protected the Jews. That's why they feel so close to Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims writes for the Palm Beach Daily News in West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
