A1316 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINESE-EMBASSY-COX     05-10 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-EMBASSY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida woman almost caught in student protests in China
 &HT;    By Jan Sjostromm
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tanya Brooks expected her spur-of-the-moment
trip to China to be a memorable experience.
</P>
<P>
   She never thought she would end up on the fringe of the biggest
protest to shake Beijing since the Tiananmen Square pro-democracy
demonstrations 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was shopping in a Beijing market across the street from
the United States embassy Saturday (May 8) when she saw busloads of
students pull up to the embassy. Brooks was alone. She had walked
to the market from her hotel, a few blocks away from the embassy.
She did not realize that anything was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market was boarding up quickly,'' said Brooks, who
returned to Palm Beach early Monday morning. ``They didn't speak
English, so there was no one who could tell me why they were doing
it. If I had known, I would have been nervous. I was strolling
casually.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks did not find out about the protest until after she
returned to her hotel and switched on Cable News Network. ``I was
horrified,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 27 people in Brooks' tour group was harmed by
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of rock-throwing protesters converged on the U.S.
embassy, pinning the American ambassador and other officials inside
the building, after NATO planes bombed the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia Saturday. NATO officials say the bombing was
accidental. Demonstrations continued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators also attacked the British and Albanian embassies
Sunday and held protests in other Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
   The United States State Department issued a warning Sunday
urging Americans to defer travel to China. American citizens in the
country ``should remain in or close to their homes or hotels,'' the
advisory said.
</P>
<P>
   The warning referred to ``ongoing large-scale demonstrations,
incidents of harassment of private Americans and damage to U.S.
businesses'' in China.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Rudensky, a spokeswoman for State Department's Bureau of
Consular Affairs, said there have been no reports of injuries to
American tourists in China, although isolated incidents of
harassment have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Rudensky advised travelers to check for updates from the
American embassy before leaving for China.
</P>
<P>
   Information is available at the state department's Web site at
www.state.gov or by calling 202-647-5225.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks had planned to go to the Chinese opera Saturday night.
She intended to go alone, because no one else in her group wanted
to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a driver there to take me,'' she said. ``The tour
leader said `I don't recommend you go but it's your choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks and the other members of her tour group did not leave
their hotel on their last night in China. ``I wasn't as worried
about my own safety as I was about the possibility that I could
start a serious incident for the American government if something
happened to me,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said she had enjoyed her seven days in Beijing until the
demonstrations broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fabulous,'' she said. ``I was going to go home raving
about how wonderful it was.'' When Brooks awoke Sunday morning, she
found a notice from the United States embassy that had been slipped
under her door. The notice advised travelers to use caution, but it
did tell them to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
   Later that same day, Brooks boarded the bus for the airport.
``Getting to the airport was a mess,'' she said. ``It was a mob
scene.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane was delayed for an hour past its scheduled departure
time, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Kerr, director of marketing for Pacific Delight Tours, the
company that handled Brooks' trip, said such delays are common in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traffic in Beijing is very heavy,'' Kerr said. Major
flights out of Beijing like the one Brooks took are often delayed
to accommodate connecting flights, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Pacific Delight Tours, the largest American
tour operator to China, has not canceled any of its tours to China.
</P>
<P>
   As for Brooks, she advises against traveling to China any time
soon. ``It was so dangerous, and there was no protection,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
