<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1324 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT &LR;      05-10 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VITAL-SIGNS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCHANGES: FOR CHILDREN, A DIRECT LINE TO THE DOCTOR  
 SAFETY: A CRUCIAL MOVE TO PREVENT DROWNINGS  
 THERAPIES: ON THE COUCH ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you get the blood out of someone while it is still blue? Do
cats and dogs get sick from second-hand smoke?
</P>
<P>
   These are typical questions from children in two schools in
rural Vermont who were part of a Dartmouth Medical School study
that looked at e-mail communication between children and doctors in
training. The study also examined how children responded to
computer-mediated communication.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty medical students and pediatric residents exchanged more
than 1,400 messages with the children in kindergarten through 12th
grade over a period of two years. The researchers monitored and
analyzed the content of the exchanges in order to establish what
issues were important to children and how well both the young
people and doctors communicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This e-mail interaction was good for the doctors and good for
the students,'' said Amy Bernhardt, director of Health Quest
Initiative, a Dartmouth health education project and the lead
author of the study. ``Kids are often with parents when they go to
the doctor's office and their parents do the talking for them. What
we learned is that children have a lot of questions about their own
health. This set-up enables them to ask their questions for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchanges focused on avoiding tobacco, with most addressing
the health effects of smoking, its social implications and tips on
how to quit. The children also asked about personal health
concerns, among them a request for suggestions about weight-loss
exercises from an 8-year-old girl, Ms. Bernhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arnold Ronning, a pediatric resident and one of the
participants, confirmed the value of the program. ``Many kids get
information in locker rooms and television, and what they're
hearing might not necessarily be accurate,'' he said. ``If kids can
address their health-care questions to their doctors on e-mail as
they occur to them, they may be likely to address issues they
wouldn't address in front of a parent who might be in the doctor's
office with them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   Double Duty for a Lifesaving Move
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, a doctor named Victor Esch was on a beach when he saw a
lifeguard pull an unconscious man from the water. The guard tried
to resuscitate the man, but was unsuccessful and declared him dead.
</P>
<P>
   Esch stepped in and asked if he could try something else. The
lifeguard said yes, and Esch performed the Heimlich maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   With each upward thrust into the man's abdomen, water gushed out
of his mouth, and in moments, the ``dead'' man recovered. A chest
X-ray later showed that his lungs had been filled with water.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the 25th anniversary of the introduction of the
maneuver, its inventor, Dr. Henry Heimlich, worries that the public
knows the Heimlich only to prevent death from choking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety to 93 percent of drowning victims have water in their
lungs,'' he said. ``And the water must be gotten out immediately.''
Besides getting the water out, the Heimlich jump-starts breathing
by pushing up on the diaphragm.
</P>
<P>
   While 200,000 lifeguards are trained each year to use the
Heimlich to save drowning victims, more than 1,000 children die of
drowning every year, mostly in private homes where no lifeguard is
present. They drown in pools, buckets of water and bathtubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can learn the maneuver in one minute,'' Heimlich said.
``If they know it, they will react at home and save these
children.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALISHA BERGER
</P>
<P>
   Maids, Bellhops and Now, a Psychologist
</P>
<P>
   For the anxious, stressed out traveler, the Nob Hill Lambourne,
a hotel in San Francisco that caters to business travelers, offers
an unusual way to decompress: The front desk will arrange for a
session with the hotel's psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, owned by Joie de Vivre Hospitality, started the
service in February 1998. Though only a few guests have taken
advantage of it, the Hotel Acqua, also owned by Joie de Vivre, is
scheduled to open in Mill Valley, Calif., in August, and will offer
therapy sessions as well. Dr. Charmian Anderson, the Lambourne's
in-house psychologist who has a private practice in Mill Valley,
said she pitched the idea to the hotel's parent company thinking
``business people are getting used to services that are speedier
and speedier. Why not `quick' therapy?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anderson says that most sessions take place over the phone,
though she occasionally meets with clients at the hotel. The fee is
$2 a minute, 20 percent of which goes to the hotel. The hotel
offers pamphlets in each room that describe the service.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anderson said most guests arranged for sessions because they
were worried about business concerns, and many called back for
further consultation. She said she recently talked to a chief
executive who had two weeks to raise several million dollars for
his company, and needed a sounding board for his strategy. Once the
man returned home, he arranged for a second phone session.
</P>
<P>
   Another guest was disappointed after a series of job interviews.
She called Dr. Anderson to vent and plan her next career move, but
eventually brought up the unhealthy relationship she was in.
``People start out discussing business, but it often segues into
personal matters,'' Dr. Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that the effectiveness of this type of therapy
depends on the guests' concerns: ``Travelers have unique pressures
because they don't have the safety nets of home,'' said Dr. Joseph
Kobos, director of the counseling service at the University of
Texas Health Science Center in San Antonio. ``Short-term therapy
can be useful for those issues, but you can't help rearrange a
whole life in one session.''
</P>
<P>
   _ KRISTYN KUSEK
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
