<HEADER>
A1353 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARHISTORY-MOVIES-AZ     05-10 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARHISTORY-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE SHADOW OF STAR WARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 ByBOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Before ``Star Wars,'' there were spaceships hanging
from strings in ``Plan 9 From Outer Space.''
</P>
<P>
   When our heroes battled extraterrestrial invaders in ``The
Thing,'' the monster turned out to be nothing more threatening than
Marshal Dillon (James Arness) in a carrot suit.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Star Wars,'' science fiction was sci-fi as far as
Hollywood was concerned; B-movie throwaways for the underside of a
Saturday matinee double bill for kids.
</P>
<P>
   Movies such as ``The Blob,'' ``The Fly'' and ``Neutron vs. the
Maniac.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' changed all that. It blasted science fiction into
the front ranks of Hollywood spectaculars.
</P>
<P>
   George Lucas proved you don't need a Cecil B. DeMille cast of
thousands to produce movie spectacle. All you need is a
behind-the-camera crew of special-effects experts manipulating
expensive computers to generate illusions.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Star Wars'' opened, Hollywood didn't expect it to be a
big hit. The studio released it into relatively few theaters. Fans
soon corrected the misjudgment, however, and Hollywood responded.
If the business understands one thing, it's imitation.
</P>
<P>
   Film producers learned their ``Star Wars'' lessons well: Spend
your time and money on the special effects. Use computers to detail
the images you project on the screen. Create visions of exotic
worlds and fanciful creatures. Give audiences heroes to cheer,
villains to jeer. Always play to the big moments. Never forget your
catch phrases. If you want to advance a mystical philosophy, make
it kid-simple.
</P>
<P>
   And so we got ``Alien'' and ``Terminator'' and ``Independence
Day.'' There were ``Total Recall,'' ``Blade Runner,'' ``The
Abyss,'' ``E.T.'' and remakes of ``The Fly'' and ``The Thing,''
using shape-changing technologies that blew early sci-fi movies
into the dust bin of parody.
</P>
<P>
   But for all Lucas did to change the popular perception of the
genre, he didn't create modern science fiction. Before Lucas, there
were the books, the rich literature of what devotees called SF.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the student of science fiction, there are
virtually no good films that are good science fiction,'' professor
James Gunn of the University of Kansas was quoted in the book
``Anatomy of Wonder.'' ``The problem with the science fiction film
is that it adds nothing to science fiction except concretene ss of
image _ and this may be more of a drawback than an asset.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the professor getting at?
</P>
<P>
   All the odd-looking creatures and exotic battle gear of Lucas'
galaxy are wallpaper for a kid's playroom. SF is challenging and
disturbing. ``Star Wars'' is cute and clever.
</P>
<P>
   SF books expand the realm of the imagination. Movies such as
``Star Wars'' contract the imagination by reducing limitless
speculations of alternative realities to a costume melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   Movie SF is not far from where literary SF started 70 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Early science fiction books concentrated on Flash Gordon space
operas, the sword and sorcery fantasies of Robert Howard (Conan''),
and the incredible adventures of H.G. Wells (The Invisible Man) and
Jules Verne (20,000 Leagues Under the Sea'') _ all of which by
today's standards aren't so incredible.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the first wave of experimenters, who opened the
universe of SF for exploration:
</P>
<P>
   _Isaac Asimov, with his ``Foundation Trilogy,'' depicted the
forces and counterforces that shaped a galactic civilization over a
thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   _Robert Heinlien used SF as political allegory, with ``Starship
Troopers'' mimicking the war between communism and militarism, and
``Stranger in a Strange Land'' heralding New Age mysticism.
</P>
<P>
   _Science-based Arthur C. Clarke analyzed the future of
technological civilizations from anthropological and religious
slants. &QL; 
GROWING UP  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These writers and others opened the gates, and bursting through
came new SF authors, including Frederik Pohl, Robert Silverberg,
William Tenn and Harlan Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '60s and '70s, science fiction literature grew up.
New writers were attracted to the genre. They advanced themes from
monsters into manifold manifestations of stretched, and often
warped, mentality. They wrote about exploration of the universe,
planet colonization, time travel, what-if variations on terrestrial
history, alternative intelligence, extraterrestrial religions, the
distant future and the far past.
</P>
<P>
   This new generation of SF writers used all the psychological and
artistic strategies of mainstream fiction writers without the
limitations of realistic fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Slow to react, critics continued to dismiss SF as kids' stuff.
Readers knew better. They weren't dismissing the new writers. They
were reading them, taking trips through vast realms of the
unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   SF offered new views on politics, racism, the ecology,
sexuality, mysticism, technology, the future. It broke the barriers
of thought that often constrain mainstream fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Women authors, such as Anne McCaffrey and Ursula K. Le Guin,
started writing feminist SF, offering the one thing SF fans were
most open to: new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   As computers took over more aspects of our lives, William Gibson
and other wired novelists wrote about the realms of artificial
intelligence for the digitally adept.
</P>
<P>
   Then just as the literature of SF was gaining mainstream
acceptance, ``Star Wars'' came along and redefined SF as a toy of
pop culture. After ``Star Wars,'' SF no longer meant books; it
meant kids' movies with great special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Fans, including people who had never read an SF book, came to
see ``Star Wars'' multiple times. That was great news for SF. It
was also bad news. Just as the literature was growing up, the
movies took it back down to Saturday matinee level _ just better
Saturday matinees. ``Star Wars'' was a B-movie made with A-money
technology. &QL; 
INTO THE NURSERY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As John Brosnan wrote in his book, ``The Primal Screen,'' ``With
one bound Lucas had taken SF cinema out of the hands of adults and
into the nursery, where it has tended to remain ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' explored no new territory (except in the visual
effects sense). Many other SF stories had already mapped the vistas
that ``Star Wars'' was to claim for its own.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the ``Star Wars'' look comes from the illustrations of
SF magazines. Many of its ideas about empires and space travel can
be traced to other writers. The Force is a loosely digested mix of
New Age mysticism and fairy tale myths.
</P>
<P>
   But so what? It's just a movie, and nothing digests other
people's ideas like Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bob Shaw's ``Night Walk'' (1967) and James Blish's
``Bridge'' (1952) were among the many early SF books that involved
interstellar travel. Themes of galactic conquest, empire and revolt
were explored in Jerry Pournelle's ``A Spaceship for the King''
(1971) and Jack Vance's ``The Five Gold Bands'' (1950).
</P>
<P>
   Mystical ideas such as the Force of the Jedi Knights can be
found in books like Roger Zelazny's ``Lord of Light'' (1967) and
Frank Herbert's ``Dune'' (1963).
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in ``Star Wars'' is new. But its old ideas are put
together on the screen in dazzling fashion. Lucas didn't get there
first, but he did get there with the most. Whatever claims SF
writers have to the gold of imagination, George Lucas owns the
bank. ``Star Wars'' gave SF its biggest shot of popularity, driving
masses to the pedantic fandom of TV's ``Star Trek'' and ``The
X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Star Wars'' is basically a kids' movie, many people
think it's nothing but mindless entertainment, deserving no further
analysis. That never stops the analysts, who can find significance
in anything.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously, ``Star Wars'' extends our obsessions with the
inevitable triumph of machines over human abilities. All the humans
and humanlike aliens in ``Star Wars'' are dwarfed by the machines
they battle, particularly the Death Star.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Darth Vader so threatening is his mechanical
qualities. He is a man with no face, transformed into a
half-machine exultant to be less, or more, than human. The
laugh-reflex robots, R2D2 and C3PO, are Lucas' comic way of
diminishing the threat of the machines for kids in his audience.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have also read religious allegories into the saga: Yoda
as a Buddha figure; Luke as Christ being tempted by the devil of
the dark force in the wilderness, the Satanic Darth Vader; or Luke
as Adam forced out of the garden of Eden by the lure of forbidden
knowledge.  &QL; 
LUKE'S SWORD  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Per Schelde, linguistic anthropologist. He analyzes
``Star Wars'' in his book ``Androids, Humanoids and Other Science
Fiction Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's virtually impossible to imagine the hero (Luke) without
his laser sword,'' Schelde writes.
</P>
<P>
   Most fans and kids who have played Jedi knight would agree
happily with that estimate. Then, the anthropologist lowers the
boom.
</P>
<P>
   Schelde analyzes Skywalker and his lightsaber and other
weapon-draped superheroes, this way: ``The protagonists do not have
personalities in the traditional sense. They have weapons. Put
bluntly, guns are penis-extensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Schelde pictures Luke before he learns to use his laser sword as
a teenager ``waiting for life to begin. Before (he) can become
fully adult (Luke and other science fiction heroes) have to learn
to be men, to control their penises; Luke has to learn to master
his laser sword.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever fun or insights can be had analyzing the hidden
meanings of ``Star Wars,'' Hollywood analyzed it in a different
way: The vast fortune it brought in came from the special effects,
not from the story.
</P>
<P>
   By Hollywood reasoning, SF means SFX. The plot is of little
importance, as long as the movie's special effects are spectacular
and the big moments bring the kids back through the box office
again.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the literature of SF continues to
challenge our minds by exploring alternate worlds, dimensions and
mental capacities that completely transcend anything attempted on
film.
</P>
<P>
   It's waiting out there for you whenever you're through seeing
the movie. All you have to do is open a book.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Fenster can be reached at bob.fenster(at)pni.com via e-mail.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
