<HEADER>
A1356 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SAUNDERS-HOSPICE-     05-10 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SAUNDERS-HOSPICE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTING ON A LIFE OF TREATING THE DYING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dame Cicely Saunders is considered by many to be the world's
foremost expert in the care of the dying. In 1967, she opened St.
Christopher's Hospice in London, the first research and teaching
hospice. Her vision of a place where people could die with dignity,
surrounded by family and treated by specialists in end-of-life
care, spread around the world and helped spawn a new medical
discipline, palliative care. Dr. Saunders, now 80, still goes to
work every day and lives around the corner from the hospice that
she founded. She was in New York recently to deliver a lecture at
Mount Sinai Medical Center. In an interview, she spoke about her
life and her philosophy of death.
</P>
<P>
   Q. For the last 50 years you've been involved in caring for the
dying. Tell me about your life before that.
</P>
<P>
   A. I had a fairly easy upbringing, with money at home and
boarding school, and I went up to Oxford University in 1938 to read
philosophy, politics and economics. When the war came, that didn't
seem to be the right thing to be doing, so I left university and
went to train as a nurse. For the first time in my life, I thought
I was really in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did you come up with the idea for hospice?
</P>
<P>
   A. I went back to university for a year, which enabled me to
qualify as a medical social worker. I got into St. Thomas' Hospital
in 1947 and there, in the first ward I took over, I met a Polish
Jew from Warsaw, who got out before the Resistance. He was 40, and
had inoperable cancer, and because he had no family, I knew he had
run into trouble. And so I kept in touch with him, and when he
collapsed and was admitted to another hospital, I followed him
there and was virtually his only visitor for the two months that he
was dying. We talked together about somewhere that would be more
suitable for him than the very busy surgical ward where he was. We
wanted a place not just for better symptom control, but for trying
to find out, in a way, who he was.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So your vision was to build a place for the dying. How did
you begin making plans?
</P>
<P>
   A. I went to one of the few early homes for the dying in London
as a volunteer nurse in the evenings, once or twice a week. It was
there that I saw the regular giving of oral morphine to prevent
pain, rather than waiting for patients to have pain first, so that
they would have to earn their morphine. This was so impressively
better than anything I had seen.
</P>
<P>
   Q. You became a doctor. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A. I was working for a very interesting thoracic surgeon, and I
said to him, ``I really have got to go back and nurse somehow. I've
got to get to people who are dying.'' And he then said, ``Go read
medicine. It's the doctors who desert the dying. And there is so
much more to be learned about pain, and you will only be frustrated
if you don't do it properly.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. How old were you then?
</P>
<P>
   A. I was 33.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Were you thinking about hospice during your training?
</P>
<P>
   A. By this time, I was determined to do some research in pain. I
got entrance to St. Joseph's Hospice, which was run by the Sisters
of Charity in the East End of London. When I turned up and said,
``I've got a research fellowship to look at the management of
terminal pain,'' the reverend mother replied, ``Well, I haven't any
money, but I have patients in need of a doctor.'' They were giving
drugs on demand, like everybody else was, or an hour before
visitors came. I was given these poor patients, and I simply took
the drugs that they were already taking and put them onto a regular
schedule. That was like waving a wand over the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What did you learn from those early patients?
</P>
<P>
   A. I said to a patient, a lady called Mrs. Hinson, ``tell me
about your pain,'' and without any more prompting, she just said,
``Well, doctor, it began in my back but now it seems that all of me
is wrong.'' She described her symptoms, and then said, ``I could
have cried for the pills and the injections, but I knew that I
mustn't. Nobody seemed to understand how I felt, and it seemed as
if the world was against me, and my husband and son were marvelous
but they were having to stay off work and lose their money, and
it's wonderful to just feel safe again.'' So she has described what
I started talking about as total pain.
</P>
<P>
   Q. We're having a debate in this country over assisted suicide.
What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   A. What I have learned over all these years, especially of what
people can do at the end of their lives if they have good care,
makes me very wary of a quick way out. I think it denigrates people
into just being an incurable illness, and I think it is socially,
really very dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What about Kevorkian?
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I think it's bizarre, isn't it? What he has been doing
is not looking at the whole patient. He's a pathologist. He's not a
skillful physician who can offer alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What can people accomplish as they are dying?
</P>
<P>
   A. Reconciliation in families. A search for your own important
values. A setting of real priorities. My husband, who died in his
90s, sat back at the end of his life and said, ``I'm completely
happy. I have done what I had to in my life, and now I am ready to
die.'' That's a very fortunate position. But some people may look
back at a life that they think is one of failure. Still, it is
possible to meet them at that point and say to them, ``You matter
because you are you.'' You could give a person that sort of
recognition, so that they could come to the end of their life
saying, ``Well, I'm me. And it's all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. We talk about a good death. What is it?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think with a sense of fulfillment and a readiness to let
go. As far as my husband was concerned, it was a belief, as Monty
Python said, ``And now for something completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you thought about how you want to die?
</P>
<P>
   A. Everybody else says they want to die suddenly, but I say I'd
like to die of cancer, because it gives me time to say I'm sorry,
and thank you, and goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are you well?
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm very arthritic. I've got a hiatus hernia. I'm waiting to
have my next knee done. Considering all that's the matter with me,
I'm fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
