<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1359 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CULTURE-COMMENT-AZ     05-10 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CULTURE-COMMENT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS CULTURE DOES NOT HAVE AN `OFF' SWITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH LAFAVE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - (begin ital) ``If you don't like what you see on
television, you can turn it off.'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   We've all heard this in one form or another. ``If you don't like
(insert anything), you can turn it off.'' If you don't like certain
language, or violence, or innuendo, you don't have to view it.
</P>
<P>
   What's true for the rectangular luminescences in our living
rooms is a microcosm of the bigger scene. If you dislike certain
trends in music or movies or lifestyle or belief patterns, you
don't have to engage them. You have a free choice to accept
anything, or reject anything. Such is the blessing of a free
society.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of things, this is obviously true. Yes, I can turn
off a television. I can even throw one out. I can also live as I
wish (more or less), practice my beliefs as I desire (within
limits) and accept or reject any ideas, trends, entertainments or
artistic endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   But _ and this is the thing usually forgotten _ (begin ital) I
cannot choose to live in a culture that is free of the elements I
reject. (end ital) I cannot choose the field of choices from which
I select what I deem right, beautiful, appropriate. And it is
precisely this field of choices that sets the context for my
personal decisions. Inevitably it limits them. Unless I live as a
hermit, I must deal with elements I might prefer to reject
outright. I have no choice. Neither do you.
</P>
<P>
   You can't turn off the Big TV _ the culture at large, with its
specific do's and don'ts. A culture is no more than this: a field
of choices, of lifestyle choices, belief choices, arts and
entertainment choices. These choices can be narrow, they can be
wide. But they are never unlimited. They cannot be. Choice is
always contextual, always somehow limited.
</P>
<P>
   A pizza delivery man once roared up to my house with rap music
going full-blast that including the f-word. I could not choose to
have him not blare it. I might ask him to turn it off or even
complain to the store owner, but I was powerless to control the
exposure at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   I would prefer to live in a culture free of that sort of easy
pseudo-sophistication, that smug atmosphere in which the mere
employment of a simple curse word is taken as a symbol of freedom
and hipness. However, short of moving to a remote place in, say,
Alaska, I cannot make that choice, anymore than someone living in
the 1950s could have chosen to live in a culture that encouraged
the license to which I object. Everybody is stuck with the culture
at hand, and with the field of choices it offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turn off the television'' is particularly insulting when
applied to parents, as it often is, usually by non-parents. In our
house, the grown-ups battled for a long time to keep the young ones
from saying ``butt.'' That wasn't a word we found appropriate;
``behind'' was encouraged in its place. You can disagree with the
choice, but it was our choice, and that is the point: our choice
didn't matter. ``Butt'' is in all the television shows and movies,
and even if our kids didn't see those shows and movies, they have
dozens of friends at two schools, and ``butt'' _ whether we like it
or not _ is generally acceptable among them. It sneaked in through
peer groups, along with a couple other choice words that were never
heard in our house, either on TV or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Even flipping the channels is a dangerous business. Unless it is
done swiftly, and preferably with the mute button on, a parent can
easily find himself having to explain oral sex, adultery, abortion
and child molestation _ and that's just from a chance encounter
with the nightly news. &QL; 
SOLUTIONS TO TV
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps eliminating television entirely is an option, although
it would take enormous effort, energy and ingenuity to come up with
ample replacements in society as now constructed. It would also be
necessary to turn off a few kids at school whose parents don't turn
off the TV. Showing only select videotapes is a possibility,
although it would mean staying up at night pre-screening everything
for content. (As guides, ratings are a big joke.)
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the most horrific elements can be kept at bay. The
kids don't have to see Jerry Springer. But even that will
eventually become a losing battle. As children grow into teens,
some among their peers will happen to see Springer and his ilk _ no
parent can monitor a teenager 24 hours a day _ and these few will
report to the others about the woman who took 300 lovers in 24
hours or the man who slept with his wife's entire family. The
culture cannot be turned off.
</P>
<P>
   But it can be changed. Cultures are always changing, in little
ways and big. People have their effect on the big picture. Voices
can be raised in objection to explicitly sexual television content.
Protests can be lodged against violence-laden song lyrics. Critical
eyes and ears can be turned to dislodging bad art posing as free
expression.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes necessary to add a disclaimer: I am not advocating
government censorship. We have become accustomed to thinking that,
because a person dislikes X, he then thinks it should be against
the law. There are plenty of legal things I dislike, but I do not
wish them legislated against. There are also many illegal things I
dislike that I would like to see legalized. It is the role of
culture, not government, to determine the choices we have. It is
culture that must be influenced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
POLITICS OF HYPOCRISY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I can already hear somebody mumbling about ``cultural
censorship.'' To protest any expression of any kind is to engage in
de facto censorship, some people say.
</P>
<P>
   This is hypocrisy in full swing, for there is always cultural
censorship. Always. Any culture allows some forms of expression and
restricts and punishes others. Try, for example, to tell certain
jokes. Tell a joke offensive to anyone but rednecks and
Republicans, and you could be out of a job. Write a script that
glorifies smoking or presents politically incorrect content and it
won't get produced. There is acceptable expression and unacceptable
expression in baby boomer America just as there is acceptable and
unacceptable expression in every conceivable society. That's
cultural censorship. Wherever there are people, it will exist. The
only thing that changes is what is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like what's currently acceptable, if you object to
the cultural context you're stuck with, you have the right to
attempt to change it through art, through protest, through
educational reform. ``Turning off the television'' is not only not
enough, it simply isn't possible. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kenneth LaFave can be reached can be e-mailed at
ken.lafave(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
