<HEADER>
A1385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MORNING-TALK-NYTR &LR;      05-10 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MORNING-TALK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAKE UP TO A NEW MORNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAY HANDELMAN   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   And you thought the late-night TV talk show war between Jay Leno
and David Letterman was fascinating. Take a look at the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The network battle is beginning to bubble like an old-fashioned
percolator. In what may be one of the last great TV battlegrounds,
with the potential for real audience growth, ABC and CBS finally
are taking aim at NBC's ``Today,'' the perennial ratings leader.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, CBS surprised no one when it announced that Bryant
Gumbel, who had struck out with his prime-time news magazine,
``Public Eye,'' will become host of a revamped ``CBS This Morning''
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   It was a logical choice because Gumbel was the king of morning
television during most of his 15 years at the helm of ``Today,''
which he left two years ago to join CBS. He was expected to become
a prime-time magnet for viewers because of his live interview
skills. He has a reported $5 million-a-year contract, but he hasn't
been seen since ``Public Eye'' was canceled earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   In January, ABC called out its own big guns to give a new boost
to its failing ``Good Morning, America.'' Diane Sawyer and Charles
Gibson, both busy on the prime-time ``20/20,'' were brought in to
bring some short-term consistency to the show that hadn't worked
well since Joan Lunden left and Gibson was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer and Gibson have helped raise the ratings and profile for
the former No. 1 morning show, and network observers say their
``temporary'' status may turn out to be a longer-term pairing.
</P>
<P>
   Both ABC and CBS also are building new studios to give their
viewers the same kind of ``window on the world'' that they get on
the ``Today'' show. A studio with a view of New York City streets
reportedly was one of Gumbel's conditions for agreeing to return to
the morning beat on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   CBS still has to name a new co-anchor for Gumbel, and ABC may
still be searching for permanent hosts for GMA.
</P>
<P>
   But will any of it matter? ``Today'' continues to just glide
over the competition primarily because of the family atmosphere it
has created with co-hosts Katie Couric and Matt Lauer, news reader
Ann Curry, and jovial weatherman Al Roker.
</P>
<P>
   When they're together, everything seems to flow smoothly, and
even the occasional forays into the crowd gathered outside the
studio near Rockefeller Center seem genuine rather than forced.
</P>
<P>
   That's the real challenge facing ABC and CBS: To find hosts who
can gel and provide the kind of tone that will help viewers wake up
and get ready for work or school each day.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel will bring some sort of following to the CBS show, which
likely will get a new name. But how will he get along with the
anchor hired to join him? Don't expect to see Deborah Norville's
name among the possibilities after their short-lived pairing on
``Today'' when she replaced Jane Pauley.
</P>
<P>
   During the announcement last week, Gumbel dismissed any notion
that he failed in prime time and that his new assignment is
something of a comedown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view it like somebody who was a Broadway star and then went
and did a movie. And the movie wasn't a big box-office smash and so
they decide to go back to Broadway. Does that make them a bomb? I
don't think so,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbel has formidable skills. He is a strong interviewer, who
will ask tough questions without appearing offensive, and who takes
the news seriously. But it will take more than interviews to turn
the CBS morning show into something more than the also-ran it has
been for years.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
