<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1404 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MUSIC-SCIENCE-2TA     05-10 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MUSIC-SCIENCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERSTRINGS AND THE NEANDERTHAL PHILHARMONIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mich.)   (af)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The discovery of animal bones with holes drilled at regular
intervals has encouraged paleoanthropologists to believe that
Neanderthals were playing music on crude flutes 43,000 years ago.
True or not, musical instruments have an ancient lineage firmly
based on physics and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   In the 5th century B.C., both Pythagoras of Samos (the one who
discovered the theorem about right triangles) and Chinese
bronzesmiths who cast musical bells hit upon systematic scales of
notes defined by mathematical relationships. Music seems almost as
old as human history.
</P>
<P>
   But connections between music and science are subtle and
uncertain, and all too often we are asked to accept on faith the
supposed links between the concert hall and the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   A seemingly endless debate persists between those who regard
music as a branch of physics and those who see it as the artistic
product of inspired but inexplicable minds. The latest attempt to
bridge the chasm between these divergent perspectives was offered
in New York last week at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum by the
Emerson String Quartet and a Columbia University physics professor,
Dr. Brian Greene, whose words-and-music performance was not exactly
a recital and not exactly a lecture; it was something like what
people in the 1960s called a ``happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The five black-clad performers sought to demonstrate an
underlying kinship between some seminal ideas of physics and music;
Greene's depiction of Newton's clockwork universe, for instance,
was followed by two elegantly structured Bach fugues. A simplified
introduction to the modern theory of superstrings preceded some
hard-to-get-to 12-tone works by Anton Webern and Alban Berg.
</P>
<P>
   Superstring theory is an attempt to bring into consonance two
bodies of thought central to modern physics: relativity, which
helps to explain cosmic-scale interactions, and quantum mechanics,
which describes the domain of the ultra-small.
</P>
<P>
   Both theories are wonderfully successful within their own
domains, but have yet to be united as a single coherent description
of the universe _ unless, perhaps, the superstrings theory turns
out to be correct.
</P>
<P>
   That theory (or rather, the five versions of it grouped together
as components of a larger theory) depend on mathematical
correspondences between 10 different dimensions of reality _ as
mind-boggling an idea as any in science. It is easy enough to
envision a three-dimensional cube, but when even one more spatial
dimension is added, as in a four-dimensional tesseract or
``hypercube,'' visualization becomes impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the acceptance of a 10-dimensional description of reality
requires an act of faith in the mathematics involved. Many
physicists would like to become believers, if only because
superstrings would solve many problems, including the mystery of
how gravity is related to the other forces of nature.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an analogous act of faith is required to fully accept
the atonal and 12-tone music of Arnold Schoenberg and his
followers, some of which was played at the Guggenheim event.
</P>
<P>
   But acts of faith in both music and mathematics are hard for
ordinary people to swallow. A much more accessible connection
between music and science lies in the fact that music and science
often seem to cohabit creative minds. Among the thinkers who
noticed this was Gottfried Wilhelm von Leibniz, who invented
calculus independently of Newton. He wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Music is the hidden mathematical endeavor of a soul
unconscious it is calculating.''
</P>
<P>
   A conspicuous example of the admixture of science and music was
Alexander Borodin, a distinguished Russian chemist and physician,
who in his spare time wrote the opera ``Prince Igor,'' three
symphonies and some other immortal orchestral and chamber works.
</P>
<P>
   He is less well known for having pioneered a field of
carbon-fluorine chemistry that ultimately led to nonstick cookware
and freon refrigerants; unknowingly, the composer helped to found a
branch of chemistry that has unfortunately led to depletion of the
global ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If there is a connection between Borodin's wild sonorities and
his sober chemistry, it is obscure.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John F. Putz, a mathematician at Alma College in Michigan,
thought he perceived mathematical influences in the music of
Mozart. Some of his evidence came from a search of Mozart piano
music for a mathematical proportion called the ``golden ratio'' _ a
number known to mathematicians, architects and others since ancient
times.
</P>
<P>
   The golden ratio, which defines many patterns in nature
(including the spiral patterns at the centers of daisies) can be
calculated by dividing up a straight line into two unequal
segments. If this is done in such a way that the ratio of the whole
line to its larger segment is the same as the ratio of the larger
segment to the smaller segment, the resulting ratio works out to
about 1.61803 to 1: a value known as the ``golden ratio.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article in Mathematics Magazine, Putz wrote that the
golden ratio defines proportions in architecture that many people
find pleasing, so he looked for this ratio in paired sections of a
Mozart sonata. Each of the three movements of Mozart's Sonata No. 1
in C major was divided by the composer into two parts, with a short
``exposition'' at the beginning followed by a longer
``recapitulation and development.''
</P>
<P>
   Putz found a very close agreement with the golden ratio in the
lengths of the two sections of each of the first two movements of
the sonata, but not in the third movement. ``We must remember that
these sonatas are the work of a genius,'' Putz wrote, ``and one who
loved to play with numbers. Mozart may have known of the golden
ratio and used it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added an acknowledgment that it was probably Mozart's
inspired mind and not any mathematical calculation that produced
the music.
</P>
<P>
   Many have applied mathematical relationships to musical
composition. Among the most influential of the mathematical
composers was Joseph Schillinger, whose system of composition found
its way into movie sound tracks, synthesizer music and many other
musical forms. Schillinger's most famous student was George
Gershwin, and even Albert Einstein thought highly of Schillinger's
system.
</P>
<P>
   Some physicists, like Dr. Richard F. Voss of IBM, have asserted
that music has a strong ``fractal'' element; that is, it contains
rhythmic and melodic structures that sound the same at all size
scales. (Fractal geometry, which supposedly describes the
``self-similarity'' of mountain ranges or shore lines as viewed
from any distance, is a part of chaos theory.)
</P>
<P>
   But the question of whether music and physics can be illuminated
in terms of each other remains open. It is entertaining to hear the
views of physicists about the ultimate realities of existence. It
is also entertaining to listen to great music. But it remains to be
proved that these two fields of creative endeavor are causally
linked.
</P>
<P>
   In his essay ``The Joy of Music,'' the composer Leonard
Bernstein wrote: ``We bumble. We imitate scientific method in our
attempts to explain magic phenomena by fact, forces, mass, energy
...
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way one can really say anything about music is to
write music.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
