<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARGUIDE-MOVIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCI-FI, BEFORE AND AFTER GEORGE LUCAS  
 (ADV: WITH STARHISTORY-MOVIES) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Early sci-fi meant B-movies, Saturday matinees such as
``It Came From Outer Space,'' ``Plan 9 From Outer Space,'' ``Attack
of the 50-Foot Woman,'' ``Cat Women of the Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Star Wars'' wasn't the first great science fiction movie.
Here are 10 winners that brought worlds of SF to the screen before
Wookiees were a gleam in George Lucas' eye:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' (1968): A spectacular foray into
adult science fiction, as director Stanley Kubrick turns an Arthur
C. Clarke story into a sobering examination of space exploration
and man's relations with the technology he creates but cannot
master.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Invasion of the Body Snatchers'' (1956): Science fiction as
allegory, with this creepy tale of plant invaders that turn humans
into mindless, conformist pod people who apparently are still with
us. Brilliantly remade by director Phillip Kaufman in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Night of the Living Dead'' (1968): You have to watch this
horror movie about an uprising of the dead all alone at 3 a.m. with
the back door unlocked. Then see how long you can leave it
unlocked. The sequel, ``Dawn of the Dead,'' is more ironic and
comic but still a strong follow-up that will change the way you
look at shopping malls forever.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Village of the Damned'' (1960): Creepy tale of an English
village where all the women, impregnated by an alien force, give
birth to platinum blonde babies whose eyes glow and whose minds are
otherworldly. Remade with less impact and success in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``A Clockwork Orange'' (1971): Stanley Kubrick at his best
again, directing Anthony Burgess' novel about violent misfits of a
futuristic society into a premonition of today's outbreaks of urban
nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Barbarella'' (1968): A young, highly aerobic Jane Fonda
plays an intergalactic sex kitten in this funny, visually
imaginative version of a French comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``The Day the Earth Stood Still'' (1951): Best of the early
B's, this extraterrestrial encounter actually has a message, as an
alien arrives on Earth with a warning.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``The 5,000 Fingers of Dr. T.'' (1953): Imaginative musical
fantasy for kids and parents about a boy trapped in the bizarre
world of a piano dictator. Dr. Seuss wrote the script, so you know
it's packed with off-beat treats.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Planet of the Apes'' (1968): Our sense of the order of
things is turned inside out when a spaceship crashes on a planet
run by intelligent apes. Followed by sequels of varying quality.
</P>
<P>
   10. ``A Boy and His Dog'' (1975): A young Don Johnson stars in
this adaptation of the Harlan Ellison story about a boy trying to
survive a post-apocalyptic world with the aid of his psychic dog. &QL; 
AFTER `STAR WARS' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The post-``Star Wars'' era is filled with great SF movies. We'll
assume you've seen the big hits that came out since ``Star Wars''
was released in 1977: ``Terminator'' and ``T2,'' ``Alien'' and
``Aliens'' (``Alien 3'' and ``4'' optional), ``Total Recall,''
``Blade Runner,'' ``The Abyss`` (the studio's cut, not the
director's), ``E.T.,'' ``Honey, I Shrunk the Kids,'' ``Back to the
Future'' (``Part 2'' and ``3'' questionable), ``Twelve Monkeys,''
``The Fly'' (David Cronenberg's 1986 version, not the 1958
original).
</P>
<P>
   We hope you lucked out of seeing some of the big-budget bombs
that didn't learn the ``Star Wars'' lessons: ``Dune,'' ``Sphere,''
``Event Horizon.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are five imaginative works of science fiction that you
might have missed over the past 22 years:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``The Brother From Another Plane''t: John Sayles typically
makes clever dramas about real people caught in real-life
situations, films such as ``Lone Star'' and ``Return of the
Secaucus Seven.'' But Sayles doing science fiction?
</P>
<P>
   His tale of a mute, Black-skinned alien who crash-lands in
Harlem and comes to terms with our planet's possibly unique brand
of racism demonstrates how flexible science fiction is and what
clever use a smart director can make of camera tricks without a big
budget.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Earth Girls Are Easy'': SF comedy about alien men who come
to our planet looking for dates and find two Valley girls (Geena
Davis and Julie Brown), who take them out of this world again.
</P>
<P>
   Science fiction doesn't often get funny, but it does here.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``The Incredible Shrinking Woman'': Cult satire starring Lily
Tomlin as the woman who shrinks in her kitchen. The film's art
design took SF in a new direction, finding fantasy without ever
leaving home.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``The Man Who Fell to Earth'': Eerie tale of a corporate
executive (played by rocker David Bowie), who is actually an alien
on an earthly mission.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``It Came From Hollywood'': Hilarious collection that samples
the worst of early sci-fi movies, with funny commentary from a
variety of comedy stars. &QL; 
BEST BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The alternative universes of science fiction are waiting for you
behind a thousand covers. The books suggested are just a starter's
list:
</P>
<P>
   Isacc Asimov's ``The End of Eternity,'' Arthur C. Clarke's ``The
Fountains of Paradise,'' Samuel R. Delany's ``The Einstein
Intersection.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip K. Dick's ``Eye in the Sky,'' Thomas Disch's ``Camp
Concentration,'' Harlan Ellison's ``The Beast That Shouted Love at
the Heart of theWorld,'' Philip Jose Farmer's ``Jesus on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Heinlein's ``The Door Into Summer,'' Damon Knight's ``Far
Out,'' Ursula K. Le Guin's ``The Left Hand of Darkness,'' Fritz
Leiber's ``A Specter Is Haunting Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne McCaffrey's ``The Ship Who Sang,'' Barry Malzberg's
``Galaxies,'' Larry Niven's ``Neutron Star,'' Joanna Russ' ``The
Female Man,'' Margaret St. Clair's ``The Dolphins of Altair.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Sheckley's ``Immortality, Inc.,'' Robert Silverberg's
``Tower ofGlass,'' Clifford Simak's ``Time Is the Simplest Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Sturgeon's ``More Than Human,'' William Tenn's ``Of All
Possible Worlds,'' Kate Wilhelm's ``Juniper Time,'' Roger Zelazny's
``The Dream Master.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
