<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODBYE, STARR 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Also filed in ``w'' category)  
 (For New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Go away, Ken Starr.
</P>
<P>
   At last, you are finished. Kaput. You are morally, politically,
psychologically and legally bankrupt. The country wants to be rid
of you.
</P>
<P>
   If you had any sense, you would resign right away. But then you
don't have much sense, do you?
</P>
<P>
   We are fed up with your vindictiveness, your lack of judgment,
your partisan prejudices, your self-righteous rampage. You have
ruined not only your own reputation but the once-revered concept
that an outside independent counsel would be more honest than the
Justice Department in probing charges of wrongdoing in the
executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness, in the end you were simply incompetent. You
couldn't hook the Big Fish in the White House and you couldn't send
the smallest fish of all to jail, either.
</P>
<P>
   You spent more than $40 million of taxpayers' money to get 12
guilty pleas from relatively unimportant officials, three
convictions in Arkansas, three partial acquittals and two
mistrials. Except for former Associate Attorney General Webster
Hubbell's tax evasion conviction and the endless aggravation and
legal fees imposed on people close to the White House, you were no
match for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   You got House Republicans to impeach Clinton with your
overheated report elevating his personal misbehavior into high
crimes. But you couldn't get the Senate to convict him. He's
battered but still standing.
</P>
<P>
   You flaunted your partisan bias. You kept mum about the fact
White House aide Vincent Foster was a suicide long after you
reached that conclusion and well after the 1996 election, allowing
conservative conspiracy nuts to indulge in wild speculation about a
murder orchestrated by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   You have not found grounds to indict either the president or
first lady on Whitewater or any other supposed financial misdoings,
yet you have refused to clear them.
</P>
<P>
   After Susan McDougal served her 18-month civil jail sentence for
refusing to cooperate with your grand jury probe of Clinton's
financial activities, you demanded she go to jail again for
criminal contempt and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   A wise Arkansas jury said phooey, this is too much, acquitted
her on obstruction and deadlocked on other contempt counts.
</P>
<P>
   You had great legal power and you abused it _ and your arrogant
trampling of witnesses' civil rights was a far more dangerous
threat to our democratic system than the sins of a flawed president
lying about a pitiful affair with a silly intern.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting that you got your fatal comeuppance last week in a
Virginia courtroom where you sent six prosecutors _ count `em, six
_ to persuade what you thought would be a friendly, conservative,
anti-Clinton jury to ruin a woman who frustrated you.
</P>
<P>
   The mistrial of your absurd obstruction of justice suit against
Julie Hiatt Steele was a ``so what?'' case that ended correctly,
with the charges neither proven nor unproven. No rational
prosecutor would have brought such a minor case.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Willey, who had claimed that President Clinton groped
her, said she promptly told Steele about it; Steele disagreed,
saying Willey didn't make the claim until years later. There was no
conclusive evidence to convince the jury, or Starr, which one was
lying.
</P>
<P>
   Starr chose to believe Willey because her unquestioned testimony
could have added another count to his impeachment charges against
Clinton, who denied her accusations. But Steele's contradictory
version undercut Willey and bolstered Clinton's denial.
</P>
<P>
   When Willey admitted under defense questioning to prior lies
about other sexual adventures, she seemed far less credible than
she had in a ``60 Minutes'' interview recounting Clinton's supposed
assault.
</P>
<P>
   Juror interviews afterward indicated that some didn't much care
for her. Steele's lawyers cleverly left it at that, keeping their
client off the stand and free of potentially embarrassing questions
about her own life.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the whole episode was centered on a minor event
that did or did not happen. This is not of the magnitude of
presidential wrongdoing and corruption that the taxpayers thought
Starr had been hired to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Steele was the only person in the Monica Lewinsky saga who Starr
legally threatened with up to 20 years in prison. He gave Monica
herself immunity for cooperating with him and not only once but
twice he gave immunity to Willey, who had also initially lied to
prosecutors. Starr's office kept Willey's immunity secret until
legally forced to reveal it to Steele's defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in a CNN interview why the women, all of whom had
credibility problems, were treated so differently, former Starr
prosecutor Robert Bittman indicated that a crucial difference was
whether they cooperated with Starr and company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people come to Jesus,'' Bittman said, adding that Steele
had been given the opportunity to ``come to the truth'' (as seen by
the prosecutors) but had not done so.
</P>
<P>
   Her crime, like McDougal's, is basically that she did not fry
Clinton for Starr, as he wanted her to.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's vengeful approach to McDougal and Steele was so
transparent that both women were able to use it effectively as a
partial courtroom defense. Yet he's no sadder or wiser.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of immediately bowing to reality, his office said he
would think awhile about whether to re-try them. He may legally do
a rerun in both cases. But he won't if he still has some shred of
sanity left.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, Ken Starr. It's been bad to know you.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
