<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, May 11, 1999x, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A winter storm warning was posted for the mountains of western
Montana Monday morning as a low pressure system several thousand
feet aloft, marked by a pocket of very cold air, drifted overhead.
Tuesday, as the cold low moves east-northeast, the atmosphere will
destabilize over eastern and central Wyoming, paving the way for
scattered showers and thunderstorms. Showers and storms will
migrate east over the high plains of western South Dakota and
western Nebraska later Tuesday afternoon and evening. Farther east,
scattered showers and thunderstorms will develop over the upper
Middle West over the upper Mississippi Valley and western Great
Lakes. A few will be heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will erupt from Kansas to central
Texas as moist air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico is
lifted ahead of a cool front associated with the cold upper-level
low pressure system over the northern Rockies. The availability of
low-level moisture will be high over Texas and southern Oklahoma,
but relatively weak winds between 10,000 and 20,000 feet will limit
the risk of severe weather. Nonetheless, downpours and gusty winds
will accompany some of these storms.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms will bubble up Tuesday
afternoon across parts of the southern Appalachians and Tennessee
Valley. Isolated thunderstorms will form along the sea-breeze
fronts just inland from FloridaUs Gulf and Atlantic Coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered showers will escort a rather modest Pacific
disturbance into western Washington and western Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Legacy of Storms
</P>
<P>
   Hours after a cluster of thunderstorms dies, the legacy of
rain-cooled air left in its wake can spark new storms. The line
between the area of rain-cooled air and warmer air to the south,
which is often a breeding site for new storms, is called an outflow
boundary. When increasingly warm, humid air from the south impinges
on this boundary, it is forced to rise over cooler air, setting the
stage for new storms to develop. Monday morning, an outflow
boundary left in the wake of a cluster of thunderstorms over Texas
sparked afternoon thunderstorms that reached severe levels in some
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
