<SLUG> BC-JAMESON-INNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shareholders give go-ahead to Jameson, Signature merger
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based Jameson Inns said Monday its merger with
Signature Inns has been approved by shareholders of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, valued at $120 million, increases the number of rooms
for Jameson by 73 percent. It also increases the number of states
in which Jameson operates or has properties under development from
eight to 13. By the end of the year, the combined company will have
8,000 rooms in operation.
</P>
<P>
   This is Jameson's first acquisition. Previous growth has been
achieved through the building of new properties. There is no
specific plan for additional acquisitions at this time, according
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Strategically and financially, the deal with Signature is a good
fit, said Craig R. Kitchin, president and chief financial officer
of the 11-year-old company. Neither company has franchised units.
</P>
<P>
   ``They own their own brand and so do we,'' he said. ``It's
important for us to be able to control all aspects of hotel
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, holders of outstanding Signature common
stock will receive one-half share of Jameson common stock and a
cash payment of $1.22 in exchange for each share of Signature
common stock. A dividend of 28 cents per share was paid to holders
of Signature common stock.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchin said the brands will retain their separate identities,
but will be operated by Jameson.
</P>
<P>
   Jameson has 85 inns, primarily in the Southeast, including
Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, North Carolina, South Carolina and
Tennessee. The company currently has 17 new inns under development,
and will be building in Florida and Virginia this year. Signature
has 25 inns, largely in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   David Tannehill, an analyst with Morgan Keegan &AMP; Co. in Memphis,
estimates the merger will add to Jameson's earnings from operations
by 20 cents to 35 cents per share on an annualized basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good transaction for Jameson,'' Tannehill said. ``The
Signature portfolio has been a stagnant group of properties in the
Midwest, and Jameson has been more growth-oriented and expanding
their brand throughout the Southeast.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, he said, will be integrating the two operations
and growing the Signature brand, which does not have strong
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Signature has about 650 employees and Jameson 1,800. No layoffs
or closings are planned, said a Jameson spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments, Jameson recently announced it had opened
a state-of-the-art training facility adjacent to its home office in
suburban Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Jameson University will offer three programs and ongoing
training via video conferencing to all of the inns throughout the
Southeast. New managers will be required to complete the four-week
curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT THE COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   J a m e s o n I n n s
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   No. hotels: 85, primarily in the Southeast
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy rate: 61.7 percent
</P>
<P>
   Average daily rate: $50.60
</P>
<P>
   S i g n a t u r e I n n s
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters: Indianapolis, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   No. of hotels: 25, primarily in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy rate: 62 percent
</P>
<P>
   Average daily rate: $60.40
</P>
<P>
   Shelia M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
