<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Menacing reviews for `Phantom'
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reviews of the new ``Star Wars'' movie are in, and, in the words
of Han Solo, we have a bad feeling about this. ``Episode I: The
Phantom Menace'' is panned by the major magazines, with reactions
ranging from the gentle reprimand to the slam.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in Time ($3.50), Richard Corliss calls it the ``Phantom
Movie,'' high on special effects and low on character. Director
George Lucas ``was more interested in the aliens than the humans
and in the art direction than the direction of actors.'' Corliss
acknowledges that the movie may be a victim of its own
unprecedented hype, which rivaled that of the run-up of ``Gone With
the Wind,'' but adds that the final two parts of the new trilogy
could redeem this bad start. ``Hype, after all, is just moviespeak
for hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek's ($3.50) David Ansen is more blunt: ``The movie is a
disappointment. A big one.'' Despite some marvelous set pieces,
including Anakin Skywalker's zippy Podracer contest, ``Phantom''
fails to hint how this likable tot will morph into big bad Darth
Vader. This Ansen calls ``a rudimentary failure of storytelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas is given high marks for incorporating digital effects into
the live-action flow, but, writes Ansen, ``All the state-of-the-art
technology in the world is no help to an actor saddled with Lucas's
tinny dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Other publications have also weighed in on ``Phantom,''
including a rasher of newspapers that broke the gentleman's
agreement not to review advanced screenings until opening day, May
19. The daily Variety reports on the displeasure at 20th Century
Fox, while also letting on that the film is a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the 25 years since its creation, the Durham, N.C.-based
Southern Exposure ($5) has maintained a contrary voice, championing
a man-the-barricades style in the heart of the conservative South.
Published by the Institute for Southern Studies, the bimonthly
celebrates its first quarter century by visiting 25 key leaders in
the South, including former Georgia state legislator Julian Bond,
who says, ``I could defeat Jesse Helms. Easily. It just takes
organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The good empire: In the New Yorker ($3), Oliver Morton
re-reads the father of galactic empires, Isaac Asimov, whose
``Foundation'' series was everything ``Star Wars'' isn't. `` `Star
Wars' is about speed, faith and fairy tales, and the `Foundation'
is about size, science and history.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mona's mysteries: Smithsonian ($4) deconstructs the most
famous painting in the world. Apparently there is no evidence that
Lisa, the wife of Florentine official Francesco del Giocondo,
actually posed for the famed Mona Lisa, but absent that provenance
the Smithsonian examines layers of outrageous explanations for the
notorious half-smile, including theories that the model suffered
from a stroke, had mercury-blackened teeth and was a beardless
Leonardo da Vinci himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blowing bubbles: Investors in booming Internet stocks may take
an interest in the story of the South Sea Co., a notorious
speculative bubble that burst in 1720. Writing in Harvard Magazine
($4.95), Christopher Reed draws on manuscripts from the
university's Kress Library to describe how South Sea stock jumped
from 128 pounds on Jan. 1, 1720, to nine times that value in June.
Secured with scant evidence of underlying value (sound familiar?),
the South Sea edifice came crashing down by September.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Who's hot? Atlanta star Monica is first up among the 21
hottest stars under 21 in Teen People ($2.99), followed by Britney
Spears.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Milosevic and the Serbs:
</P>
<P>
   The New Republic's ($3.50) Stacey Sullivan says the lack of
resistance from Serb civilians to the Serb campaign of terror
against ethnic Albanians amounts to what seems like approval; that
the rank and file Serbs are in fact Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic's ``willing executioners.''
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
