A1459 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BOBSLED-COX     05-10 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BOBSLED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No icy track needed for U.S. Bobsled Team tryouts
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The U.S. Bobsled Team is conducting tryouts for the
2002 Olympic team Saturday in Marietta, Ga., with no fee and no ice
_ and no bobsleds.
</P>
<P>
   By taking a simple four-item test that looks like it belongs in
a physical education class, candidates can tell if they have the
speed and explosiveness to be good push athletes. Herschel Walker
took a similar test before making the 1992 Olympic team, although
his scores were not among the highest.
</P>
<P>
   The events _ vertical jump, five consecutive hops, 30-meter
sprint and 60-meter sprint _ are given point values like those in a
decathlon. The men and women scoring highest in tryouts across the
country will be invited to a training camp this summer in Lake
Placid, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Mike Dionne, one of six Georgians to make the 1998
Olympic team, got started five years ago. Dionne, who is helping
coordinate the event at Life University's track facility, read a
newspaper article about tryouts in North Carolina, where he lived
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went just for fun and had no intention of making the team,''
said Dionne. ``Four years later, I'm going to the Olympics in
Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nagano Olympics turned into an ordeal for Dionne, who tested
positive for a banned stimulant that he had taken inadvertently. He
was allowed to stay in Nagano but could not compete.
</P>
<P>
   Dionne said he and Olympic officials have ``put it behind us,''
but he also said, ``For the rest of my life, I will think what they
did was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not have to give up his Olympic clothing, but the U.S.
Olympic Committee denied his request for an Olympic ring.
</P>
<P>
   Dionne said he went through some depression after Nagano but
bounced back when the 1998-99 season began. Now a driver, he was
sent to Europe to train.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the pressure of having to race,'' he said. ``We
could take our time and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Dionne and Garrett Hines, another '98 Olympian, are the only two
Georgians who have committed to training for Salt Lake City. U.S.
Bobsled relies on national tryouts to add depth to its program. The
men's team is still looking for its first Olympic medal, and
women's bobsled is hoping to attain Olympic status for the 2002
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women 18-35 years old are eligible for the tryouts. They
need only running shoes; sprint spikes are recommended.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of a top score, consider Dionne's results _
vertical jump, 35.5 inches; five consecutive hops, 15.7 meters;
30-meter sprint, 3.67 seconds; and 60 sprint, 6.67 seconds.
Walker's scores for the same events were 30.5 inches, 15.25 meters,
3.70 seconds and 6.67 seconds. The average for top women is 22
inches, 10.8 meters, 4.25 seconds and 7.65 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In the sprints, the timing eye is 1 meter after the start, which
takes place from a small platform.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 people attended a recent tryout in Springfield, Mass.,
and five were invited to the training camp. Athletes _ including
those not invited _ must pay their own way to Lake Placid. However,
if they pass additional tests, their room and board will be free.
Contenders also must run a 100 sprint and throw a 16-pound shot put
with both hands from a crouch position.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic training center in Lake Placid has wheeled sleds, so
athletes can practice loading, but they won't see ice until October
when they travel to Park City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Dionne said that's when some potential Olympians get derailed.
``A lot of guys do (the tryouts), go to Lake Placid for summer
camp, then get on the ice in October and say, `Whoa, this isn't for
me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. BOBSLED TEAM TRYOUTS
</P>
<P>
   _ When; where: 9 a.m. Saturday; Life University track facility,
Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who: Men and women from ages 18 through 35.
</P>
<P>
   _ What to bring: Running shoes, with sprint spikes recommended.
</P>
<P>
   _ What you'll do: Four-event test consists of vertical jump,
five consecutive hops, 30-meter sprint, 60 sprint.
</P>
<P>
   _ To register: Call 1-800-Bobsled, ext. 103 or 108.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
