<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BIRD LIFTS OFF 
AQUATIC ELEPHANTS 
HOW BATS FIND FLOWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To become airborne, a plane must reach a critical speed as it
rolls down the runway. Below this limit _ 150 mph, say, for a jet
under certain conditions _ the plane stays on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   If, as some paleontologists believe, the earliest birds learned
to fly by flapping their wings while running (as opposed to
climbing trees and gliding down from them), then they had to
achieve a certain takeoff velocity as well. For the earliest known
bird, archaeopteryx, which lived about 140 million years ago, this
has always presented a problem. Its estimated running speed of
about 2 meters per second (about 4.5 miles an hour) is far slower
than the velocity needed to get off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   But a new aerodynamic analysis of archaeopteryx, by researchers
from the San Diego and Los Angeles County natural history museums,
shows how the bird could have closed this velocity gap.
</P>
<P>
   According to this analysis, published in the current issue of
Nature, the bird's flapping wings generate both lift and thrust.
The thrust adds to the propulsive force generated by the bird's
hind limbs, while the lift helps remove some of the body weight
from the hind limbs, allowing the bird's speed to increase even
more. The researchers calculated that within three seconds of
beginning its run, archaeopteryx could achieve a speed of about 8
meters per second, enough to become airborne.
</P>
<P>
   Elephants' Swim Trunks
</P>
<P>
   If the earliest birds were out flapping their wings, the
ancestors of elephants, it seems, were lolling about in the water.
</P>
<P>
   There is much information, both from fossils and molecular
analysis, to suggest that elephants and sea cows share a common
ancestor, one that was aquatic. Now, a rare chance to examine an
embryo and early fetuses of the African elephant has uncovered
further evidence that elephants had a marine past.
</P>
<P>
   The seven specimens, which were collected from elephants killed
as part of an effort to reduce herds in a South African national
park, ranged from 58 days to 166 days (an elephant pregnancy
usually lasts about 660 days). They were examined by Australian
researchers, who described their work in The Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The most important finding noted by the researchers was the
presence in the developing kidneys of funnel-shaped ducts called
nephrostomes. These are a characteristic of freshwater fish and
frogs, but have never been found in other mammals (other than
egg-layers like the platypus).
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also suggest that the elephant's trunk, which
was evident even in the earliest fetuses studied, might have
evolved as an adaptation to an aquatic environment. Proto-elephants
may have used it as a snorkel, much as modern elephants do when
they swim in deep water.
</P>
<P>
   A Bat's Favorite Flower
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to fathom how a pollinating insect or bird could be
attracted to a flower by its appearance. But hundreds of species of
plants are pollinated by bats, which are sightless. So how does a
bat, with only a sonarlike ability to navigate, find its favorite
flower?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in one case at least, is that it gets help from the
flower itself. Two German scientists, writing in Nature, have
described a type of tropical vine whose flowers include a petal,
called a vexillum, that rises up when the flower matures. This
petal, which is concave, acts like an acoustical mirror, serving to
efficiently reflect a bat's echolocating signals back to it.
</P>
<P>
   The vexillum has a structure that allows it to send back strong
signals, even if the source of the signal is off to one side. So a
passing bat, sending out a stream of acoustic signals, will receive
a series of strong return signals from the same point, allowing it
to determine the flower's location.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
