<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE TRAVEL NET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no strain to arrange a demanding excursion on the Web. Just
go to your search engine and type in a key word like ``kayak'' or
``climb'' and follow the trail. When I typed ``backpacking'' into
Yahoo's travel subsection, 16 sites were listed, ``kayak'' brought
seven, and ``climb'' 171. There are scores of such sites, and
following are examples of what you'll find. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLANNING A HIKE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.nehikingholidays.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New England Hiking Holidays offers trips along trails of a range
of difficulty; at night, you relax in an inn. Despite the service's
name, the hikes are not limited to New England. There are also
offerings in the American South, Southwest, Hawaii, Canada and
Europe. The site is clean and easy to navigate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the treks offered this year are a five-day $1,065 hike
($1,125 in fall) in the White Mountains of New Hampshire, where
Clare and Kurt Grabher, who operate New England Hiking Holidays,
live; five days in the Shenandoahs, also $1,065, and a week on the
southwest coast of Ireland (Counties Clare and Kerry), at $1,935.
The prices are complete, including lodging and food, taxes and
tips, although you do have to get to the place on your own. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hiking day begins at around 9 a.m. with a trip either on
foot or by van to the start of the trail, and ends back in the inn
in mid to late afternoon. Lunch is taken on the trail at a
picturesque spot, if one is available, or in a pub or roadside inn.
There are two guides with the group to accommodate both people who
want to stroll and those who want a strenuous hike. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RIVER ADVENTURES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.riversearch.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 whitewater outfitters from 10 countries are
gathered together on Riversearch. Canoeists, rafters and kayakers
point to an area on a list, click and view a map on screen; listed
alongside are the names of Riversearch members who operate on that
river. Most of the rivers are in North America, but a few others
are in Costa Rica, Peru, Ecuador, Chile, South Africa, Australia,
Fiji and China.
</P>
<P>
   I clicked on the Great Bend of the Yangtze River and was
connected to an outfitter, Earth River in upstate New York, that
features two weeks on the Yangtze for $3,600. Whatever you click
on, you ultimately find yourself at the outfitter's Web sites, some
neat and some not so, with a range of offerings there. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BACKPACKING
</P>
<P>
   www.geocities.com/TheTropics/8168/travel.html &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to commercial sites, you can find home pages with
personal comments on the kind of activity you're researching by
using the same method: type in the search term and hope for the
best. I lucked into the Worldly Backpacking Page, a free home page
on the Geocities service, where the proprietor, identified only as
Eric, gives details and snapshots of his own travels, offers
numerous tips, and includes links to such related sites as youth
hostels and places to make reservations.
</P>
<P>
   For novice backpackers there's a checklist of how to prepare for
the first trip, as if you wouldn't have thought to check your
finances or make an itinerary, and guides to costs. A main point of
backpacking is that it is an inexpensive way to travel. How
inexpensive? ``I figure that it'll cost about $650 to $950 for
every two weeks that you travel in Europe,'' Eric says, adding that
the United States should be ``much cheaper'' and Asia _ well, it's
a big place and he doesn't much get into it.
</P>
<P>
   Geocities, like other services, lets individuals construct their
own home pages, in all their amateurish glory, for no charge,
although you do have to put up with an advertisement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
