<HEADER>
A1463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUMMEL-COX     05-10 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUMMEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small town mourns passing of beloved doctor
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLQUITT, Ga. _ One told of how Dr. Peggy Rummel would drop
anything she was doing to help a child in need. Another recalled
how she would volunteer for any civic cause without being asked.
Still another remembered how she would treat anyone who needed
care, occsionally accepting eggs and chickens as payment for her
services _ ``and sometimes hogs, if she had to.''
</P>
<P>
   One by one Monday, her friends and neighbors stood inside the
sunlit sanctuary of the Colquitt United Methodist Church to relate
the many ways that Rummel, who died Friday of liver cancer at age
43, had enriched this small southwestern Georgia community.
</P>
<P>
   And almost to a person, they said they never expected to meet
her likes again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peggy was the most giving person I've ever seen,'' said John
Lane, Rummel's accountant, who described the bartering she had
resorted to as one of Colquitt's four physicians. ``She's
irreplaceable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rummel's good deeds, from taking in foster children to fighting
for the local hospital's survival, came to light after she received
national and international publicity for her unusual search for a
replacement. She was so determined that her work treating the poor
and delivering babies at the Miller County Hospital continue after
her death, she posted a letter on the Internet pleading for another
physician to take over her practice.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, just three days before she died, she met the new
physician, Dr. Ifekan-Shango Simon of Columbus, Ga., who will move
to Colquitt next month. His wife gave birth over the weekend, and
he did not attend the Monday service.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much has been written about this fine lady,'' the Rev. Eric
Sizemore, pastor of Colquitt United Methodist, told the 120
mourners who attended Monday's memorial. ``There's been a lot of
hype. But I haven't heard anything that wasn't true.''
</P>
<P>
   Mourners did more than extol Rummel's accomplishments, though.
They also reveled in what Sizemore called her ``droll, warped sense
of humor.'' He told of times when she would subtly deflate pompous
speakers at public meetings, and another friend, India Taylor,
recalled a patient who complained about hospital food: ``Oh,''
Rummel responded, ``what is the burnt offering for the evening?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're supposed to feel sad today, and a part of me
does,'' Sizemore said. ``But I praise God for her life.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that, even in death, Rummel would continue her
``noble work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be heaven to Peggy,'' he said, ``if she had to sit
around on a cloud and pluck on a harp.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Judd writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
