<SLUG> BC-SCI-TUNA-RISK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS DEBATE SAFETY OF CANNED TUNA FOR THE VERY YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By NANCY BETH JACKSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Based on a sampling of mercury levels in canned tuna, a
coalition of environmental and health care groups has written a
report urging pregnant women to avoid the fish entirely and advised
mothers of preschoolers to serve up no more than one tuna salad
sandwich a week.
</P>
<P>
   Although federal guidelines were used to gauge risk, the Food
and Drug Administration questioned the report's findings, calling
them very suggestive, very preliminary and highly uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Tuna fish has too much mercury to be eaten regularly by pregnant
women and young children, said Charlotte Brody, a registered nurse
who is one of the coordinators of Health Care Without Harm, which
worked with the Environmental Working Group in preparing the
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't mean to suggest all people should stop eating
tuna,'' Ms. Brody said. ``Our concern is what mercury can do to the
development of the fetus and young children.''
</P>
<P>
   The group bought 27 samples of chunk light canned tuna and
frozen fish sticks and shrimp at grocery stores in San Francisco,
Chicago and Washington, and had mercury content analyzed by an
independent laboratory. The average level of methyl mercury _
mercury as it accumulates in fish tissue _ in the tuna was 0.09
parts per million or just under the 0.1 ppm limit the FDA set for
human consumption in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The report claims that a 4-year-old eating one 6-ounce can of
chunk light tuna a week over several months could suffer subtle but
permanent brain and nervous system damage. A pregnant woman,
particularly in the first trimester, could expose her fetus to an
unsafe dose of the metal by eating a half can of chunk light a day,
the report also said. Todd Mettenbach, an analyst with the working
group and a principal author of the study, said that ``the science
around mercury levels is absolutely murky,'' but added, that
because of ``the history of mercury and what we are learning from
lead, it doesn't pay to take chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry
recognizes an increased risk of methyl mercury exposure for
developing fetuses and children under 4, but the FDA has set no
risk levels specific to women and children. The agency does advise
pregnant women and those of childbearing age to eat shark and
swordfish no more than once a month. Everyone else is advised to
eat no more than 6 ounces of these fish per week.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bolger, a toxicologist and chief of the FDA contaminants
branch, said that ``during prenatal life, humans are susceptible to
the toxic effects of high methyl mercury exposure levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is not clear,'' he added, ``is the effect, if any, on
fetuses at much lower levels _ those that approach current exposure
levels through normal fish consumption.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolger pointed out that federal guidelines are screening values
rather than absolutes and have come under reconsideration following
studies completed since the FDA and Environmental Protection Agency
set risk standards. He cited a University of Rochester study,
reported in the Journal of the American Medical Association last
year, which found that children in the Seycelles, where residents
have mercury levels about 10 times higher than in the United States
were ``without any detectable adverse influence of mercury.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also urges reductions in mercury pollution in the air
to help decrease mercury levels in fish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
