<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1469 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-VOICE11-COX     05-10 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-VOICE11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computerized voice causes stir on airwaves
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you tuned into Atlanta radio last week to hear
updates on the severe weather, you probably noticed a strange sound
coming from your speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Several stations, including news/talk giant WSB (750 AM),
new-rock station 99X and lite-rock station Peach 94.9, had
programming interrupted by the beep-beep-beep from the National
Weather Service (not so unusual). But the tornado warning that
followed perhaps can be best described as otherworldly _ a freaky
echo resembling the voice of the ``Lost in Space'' robot speaking
in Hindi.
</P>
<P>
   No, interplanetary invaders have not landed at Weather Service
headquarters in Peachtree City (GA.). The sound is part of the
agency's new NOA Weather Radio 2000 system. And the mystery voice
isn't human, it's computer-generated.
</P>
<P>
   The NWS has been using the system since February to provide
weather warnings to North Georgia, replacing human announcers. Some
stations, such as WSB (the official station of the Emergency
Activation System), have opted to use the NWS voice even though it
has prompted calls from baffled listeners. Others, such as WGST,
have chosen to remain with live announcers because management
considers the computer voice ``emotionless and antiseptic,'' says
program director Ken Charles.
</P>
<P>
   John Talbert, WSB director of technical operations, concedes
that not everyone in the industry favors the new sound and that
``the issue is a big topic of debate among broadcasters'' all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's a little awkward, but we feel it's important to get
the information on the air immediately,'' Talbert says. ``In
minutes, you can have a tremendous amount of damage to lives and
property. I say if there's a way to lessen that amount of time,
let's do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new system may let the agency get warnings out as much as
``two to three minutes sooner'' than the old method, says NWS
science operations officer Gary Beeley. But it also has caused a
bit of a stir among listeners apparently confused by the aesthetics
of what they are hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks we've hired a foreign worker to come over and
do a radio broadcast,'' says Frank Taylor, NWS data acquisition
program manager. And apparently no one can quite decided the
nationality of the new voice. ``It runs the gamut, from Middle
Eastern to Indian to Scandinavian to Korean to Mexican.''
</P>
<P>
   According to WSB's Talbert, the computer voice sounds the way it
does because of the technology required to create the words.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason they had to go with this is because the vocabulary
required (for weather reports) is phenomenal,'' he says. ``It has
to be able to deliver the names of every creek, river, stream,
adjoining waterway and wide spot in the road. So it takes the text
and sounds out the words phonetically unlike, say, a short
computer-generated phone message.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said even he was a little surprised when he first heard
the computer system ``talk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't what I expected, and it took a little getting used
to,'' he said. ``I come from a background where broadcasting has
always been done by humans, and this is definitely a change. But
what's amazing to me is that kids who tour our building don't think
it's a big deal. It's others who are having a hard time with it.''
</P>
<P>
   99X program director Leslie Fram says her young-end listeners
all seem to know the voice is a computer: ``No one thought it was
weird at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of weather alerts, Atlantans can hear the voice give
updates around the clock over weather radios at 162.55 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor says NWS staffers haven't yet come up with a nickname for
their new office mate. ``We're open for suggestions.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
