<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1470 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SPY-SAFEHOUSE-ART     05-10 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPY-SAFEHOUSE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BOOKS REVIVE OLD TALK OF SPIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(The Science Times) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tantalizing clue to the atom spies of a half-century ago
centers on Santa Fe, N.M., just down the road from Los Alamos,
where thousands of scientists and other experts worked on the bomb,
Washington's great wartime secret, sheltered by the tall pines and
deep canyons of the New Mexican wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   New research suggests that among the adobe walls and Indian
curios of the Santa Fe plaza was a drugstore whose spare rooms
served as a safe house, just as a Stalin-era spy chief has
suggested. In this refuge, Los Alamos experts are said to have
given Moscow the intellectual heart of the bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no doubts about it,'' said Jerrold Schecter, a former
Moscow bureau chief for Time magazine who has written one book on
the espionage and is working on another. He and rival investigators
say new signs, including New Mexican records, support the existence
of the safe house, no trace of which remains today.
</P>
<P>
   The atomic betrayals of the 1940s have grown steadily in
estimated number and import over the decades to the point that
today a small army of scholars is working hard at tracking and
unmasking spies. A rush of recent books list new cover names, point
to suspects long dead and _ in one case based on circumstantial
evidence _ confront a living scientist with accusations of
espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The digging has nothing to do with current fears of Chinese
spying at Los Alamos but shows how suspicions can linger for
decades and how damage assessments can grow over time.
</P>
<P>
   The most damning evidence comes from the federal government
itself. In recent years it has declassified more than 3,000
messages between Moscow and its spies in the 1940s that code
breakers were able to partly decipher. The unveiled discourse,
code-named Venona, led to the recent exposing of Theodore Hall, a
former Los Alamos physicist, and has raised questions about many of
Moscow's other scientific informants identified only by cover
names.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they are spies,'' said Robert Louis Benson, a Venona
expert at the National Security Agency, a federal espionage group,
because the messages spell out such things as the passing of atom
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, Stalin knew more about the bomb than Truman
did when the president in 1945 told the Soviet leader that the
United States had developed a new weapon of unusual destructive
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Soviets got an immense amount of information'' from known
spies and received more from ones now being uncovered, said Dr.
Gregg Herken, a historian at the Smithsonian Institution who is at
work on a book about atom scientists and espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Motives in the spying, scholars say, included not only
ideological sympathy for Moscow, but a desire to foster a balance
of terror so Washington would be unable to wage unilateral atomic
war, which some experts feared before the Cold War's deadlock took
hold.
</P>
<P>
   The drama began in earnest when Los Alamos (``the poplars'') was
founded in 1943 at what had been a rustic boy's school in the New
Mexican mountains. Its charismatic leader was J. Robert
Oppenheimer, a thin, pipe-smoking physicist with a fondness for the
Bhagavad Gita, the sacred Hindu text. ``I have become Death,
destroyer of worlds,'' he said, when a blinding flash revealed that
the first test of the weapon, on July 16, 1945, had been a success.
</P>
<P>
   Historians have long known that Klaus Fuchs, a top physicist,
betrayed the effort, as did David Greenglass, a machinist.
</P>
<P>
   But the Soviet collapse in 1991 brought new revelations. Russian
scientists said Moscow's first atom bomb, detonated in 1949, was an
exact copy of the main Los Alamos one, which was made of plutonium,
its core smaller than a softball. Russians making the assertions in
1992 and 1993 included Yuli Khariton, scientific head of the Soviet
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Western experts viewed the claim as credible since scientists
are normally reluctant to share credit.
</P>
<P>
   So too, Russian intelligence officers alleged, often anonymously
or in disputed accounts, that as many as a dozen Soviet spies stole
atom secrets. One such account was ``Special Tasks'' (Little,
Brown, 1994), by Schecter, his wife, Leona, and Pavel Sudoplatov, a
Stalin-era spy chief.
</P>
<P>
   The Sudoplatov book contended that several top scientists,
including Oppenheimer and Neils Bohr, had aided the Soviet cause.
Many scholars ridiculed these sweeping assertions. But some
elements, like the safe house in a drugstore owned by a Soviet
agent who traveled frequently to Mexico, have recently gained
credibility among atom historians and investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Bradbury, who lives in Santa Fe and works with the
Smithsonian Institution's national associates program, researched
city records and interviewed old-timers, finding a site that
matched the book's descriptions. ``It fits very nicely,'' she said.
``If true, it speaks volumes about the depths of the Russian roots
into the project. It's pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   New discoveries about what went on in the back of that
drugstore, and who visited, historians say, may eventually
materialize from the mountains of accumulating Russian and American
data. That goes especially for the Venona interceptions, which were
made public in 1995, 1996 and 1997 and to date have been only
partly analyzed publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The decryptions have already unmasked Hall, whose activities are
recounted in ``Bombshell'' (Random House, 1997), by Joseph Albright
and Marcia Kunstel. Hall, an American physicist who now lives in
Britain, was never prosecuted, despite overwhelming evidence of his
spying as ``Mlad,'' or youngster, his Soviet cover name, given when
he was 19.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Hall told the authors of ``Bombshell'' that while at
Los Alamos he regarded an American monopoly on nuclear arms as
dangerous. While he has never outright admitted to spying, he told
the authors, ``In essence, from the perspective of my 71 years, I
still think that brash youth had the right end of the stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars now believe that in treason, if not idealism, Hall may
have had up to a dozen peers, matching early Russian assertions.
</P>
<P>
   John Earl Haynes of the Library of Congress and Harvey Klehr of
Emory University lay out some of the new evidence in ``Venona,'' a
book on the decryptions published Monday by Yale University Press.
They say still undiscovered atom spies had cover names like Erie,
Huron, Pers, Quantum and Volok.
</P>
<P>
   Quantum, who disgorged secrets as early as 1943, delivered both
bomb descriptions and documents, ``Venona'' says. And he demanded
payment, unlike Hall. Among Quantum's revelations was a process of
gaseous diffusion being developed to separate uranium 238 from
uranium 235, the key isotope needed for a type of bomb fuel
different from plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   Pers, Russian for Persian, was a spy who emerged in 1944 cables,
including a lengthy one on the kind secrets he turned over to
Moscow. ``Unfortunately,'' the authors of ``Venona'' say, ``only a
few parts of the report were deciphered.''
</P>
<P>
   Huron, the authors say, was a spy in 1944 and 1945 and may have
been Bruno Pontecorvo, a physicist who defected to the Soviet Union
in 1950 and died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Espionage saved the USSR great expense and industrial
investment,'' the ``Venona'' authors conclude, enabling the
Russians to build a successful bomb ``years before they otherwise
would have.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yet another book, ``Haunted Wood'' (Random House, 1999),
combines the Venona decryptions with materials from Russian spy
archives. Its authors are Allen Weinstein of the Center for
Democracy, in Washington, and Alexander Vassiliev, a former KGB
agent who now lives in Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Among its revelations is a 1944 Russian report asserting that
Oppenheimer, code-named Chester, was a secret member of the
American Communist Party, and that the party was ordered to cease
relations ``to avoid compromising him'' at Los Alamos. But the
authors found no evidence that the long-dead scientist was a spy,
nor were they able to corroborate the claim of secret party
membership.
</P>
<P>
   Still another book and investigation have provoked a furor in
atomic circles with accusations against a living scientist who held
central roles at Los Alamos and was a student of Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by the Sudoplatov book, Jeremy Stone, president of the
Federation of American Scientists, a private group in Washington
that advocates arms control, in 1994 began looking into accusations
of spying because his group had been founded by atomic scientists.
He drew on Russian clues, including what was said to be a
transcript from the recruitment interview of a spy code-named
Perseus (today thought to be Pers, a composite of several spies or
pure disinformation).
</P>
<P>
   In it, Perseus expressed concern about the dangers of nuclear
holocaust and said that American physicists had been ``cheated'' by
their military leaders into being afraid that Nazi Germany would
get the atomic bomb first. Stone, who was well acquainted with
living atom veterans, thought he heard in such phrases the voice of
his old friend Dr. Philip Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   A physicist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
public-television eminence, Scientific American book reviewer and
disarmament statesman, Morrison, 83, is one of the nation's most
distinguished astrophysicists. As a young man in the 1930s,
however, he was a member of the American Communist Party, like many
intellectuals of the day. Morrison received his Ph.D. from the
University of California at Berkeley in 1940 under Oppenheimer's
supervision.
</P>
<P>
   During the wartime effort at Los Alamos, Morrison was in charge,
among other things, of delivering the plutonium core of the first
atom bomb to a test site in the New Mexican desert. More
importantly, he had helped evaluate German intelligence for the
project's military overseer, Gen. Leslie Groves, and so, in Stone's
view, would have known that the Germans were getting nowhere with
their bomb effort.
</P>
<P>
   While making no direct accusations, Stone, in a series of
increasingly elaborate meetings, talked with Morrison of growing
atomic investigations and the possibility of getting congressional
immunity from prosecution for old spies who agreed to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Referring only to a ``Dr. X,'' Stone describes these encounters
in a chapter of his new memoir, ``Every Man Should Try: Adventures
of a Public Interest Activist,'' published April 20 by Public
Affairs. After initially refusing to confirm the scientist's
identity, which historians had quickly guessed and discussed
widely, Stone eventually named his suspect in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The book portrays the meetings as becoming highly charged, the
suspect ``visibly frightened,'' his knees knocking together, and
Morrison's wife becoming agitated. Eventually, Stone detailed the
circumstantial case in a letter to Morrison, which prompted a flat
denial and abruptly ended the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with The New York Times, Morrison strongly denied
any spying and likened Stone's accusations to those of the McCarthy
era, full of innuendo but nothing more. He denounced the assertions
as ``outrageously unfair and false'' and ``devoid of any objective
tests.''
</P>
<P>
   His innocence, he wrote, can be shown by a willingness to reply
to any specific accusations and by the fact that for a half-century
federal law-enforcement officials had never made a single claim of
any wrongdoing or breach of trust. ``It all depends on how I
trembled,'' Morrison said dismissively of the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   As for Perseus' feeling that Los Alamos scientists had been
tricked into working against a Nazi bomb, Morrison said he was one
of the last federal analysts to feel the Germans were far behind.
In the summer of 1944, he said, he would scan his shortwave for
British broadcasts, fearful that ``London would disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Morrison said she never believed her husband was a spy,
contrary to the book's implications. ``I've had every reason to
believe otherwise,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Priscilla McMillan, an atom historian at Harvard University and
the secretary of the Federation of American Scientists, Stone's
group, echoed the outrage of many scholars in saying the assertions
were without merit. ``It's a smear in search of a crime, a criminal
and some evidence,'' she said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Stone argues that a congressional hearing and
immunity could help cut through the fog of suspicion that swirls
around many atomic scientists, alive and dead. Giving Dr. X
immunity, he says, would allow history to ``ascertain, among other
things, his motives and whatever else he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholars say the hunt for atom spies, a half-century after the
fact, is unlikely to cool and may heat up as new evidence is
weighed, including that of a Soviet safe house hidden in the midst
of Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know from Venona, which we can trust, that they are out
there,'' Gregg Herken of the Smithsonian Institution said of atom
spies.
</P>
<P>
   A problem for scholars, he added, is the issue of legal
liability and living suspects who might sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like the truth to come out,'' he said, ``but I don't
want to libel anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-NORTH-KOREANS-A     05-10 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-NORTH-KOREANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE AND MORE, JAPAN'S KOREAN MINORITY CHOOSING ASSIMILATION OVER
NATIONALISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ On the walls of the classrooms are stern portraits of
North Korea's late ``Great Leader'' and his son the ``Dear
Leader,'' and a huge banner on the gymnasium declares, ``Great
Leader Marshal Kim Il Sung Is With Us Forever.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is obvious that this high school is in Tokyo, not North
Korea, when a cluster of giggly teeny-boppers bounce up and test
their English by asking about something really important to
16-year-old hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you like the Backstreet Boys?'' asked Yun Mi Hyang, a
junior at the Korean High School in Tokyo, and she and her friends
paused breathlessly. ``You know, the Backstreet Boys. Kevin! Nick!
Brian! Oh, they are so great! The best American band. I love their
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Yun and the other students at the Korean High School come
across, in short, as the world's funkiest Stalinists. But the 137
North Korea-backed schools in Japan _ partly financed by North
Korea and run by North Koreans who are long-term residents of Japan
_ are caught in a growing crisis, for it is becoming ever more
difficult to balance loyalties to Great Leaders and to the
Backstreet Boys.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the 650,000 ethnic Koreans in Japan _ by far
Japan's largest minority _ seem to be at a crossroads and
increasingly to be choosing the Japanese path rather than the
Korean path. After half a century in which the Korean population in
Japan bridled and fought constantly with its hosts, it is becoming
more subdued, and every year more than 10,000 Koreans are taking
Japanese citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intermarriage is increasing, and taking of Japanese
nationality is increasing,'' Ku Dae Sok, the principal of the
Korean High School, said glumly as he sat in a spacious office with
memorabilia of Kim Il Sung scattered on the shelves. ``So I think
the trend for Koreans here is headed downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's Koreans in Japan are mostly the grandchildren of those
who were brought here to work as manual laborers when Korea was a
Japanese colony early in this century.
</P>
<P>
   Most were from what is now South Korea, but in the postwar era
many were contemptuous of the American-backed government in the
South. Many Koreans felt that the true nationalistic credentials
belonged to Kim Il Sung, who fought Japanese troops during World
War II and who established a fervently nationalistic government in
the North.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot was that most of Japan's Koreans initially inclined
toward the North, not so much because of its Communist political
system as because of patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   Japan discriminated harshly against the Koreans, even after the
war, and that cemented the nationalistic tendencies of the Korean
minority. The discrimination continues today, for Japan's Education
Ministry, which has traditionally been as prone to hard-line
ideologies as North Korea itself, bars graduates of Korean schools
from even applying to enter Japan's prestigious national
universities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the broader reason for the crisis in the Korean schools has
to do with changes among the Koreans themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original purpose of the schools was to prepare Koreans so
that they could go back to their homeland,'' said So Chung On, an
official of the pro-North Korean Chosun Soren organization in
Japan. ``But now young people have no intention of going back to
their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking account of that reality, our organization has been
trying to modify the contents of the education,'' So added. One
result is that the North Korean schools in Japan now study much
less politics and ideology, and the curriculum is fairly similar to
that of Japanese schools, except that classes are all conducted in
the Korean language.
</P>
<P>
   This flexibility in the curriculum has helped preserve the
support of some Korean parents, but even so, attendance of Korean
schools has fallen to 17,000 today, compared with 35,000 in 1967.
That reflects a significant waning of support for North Korea in
recent years among Japan's Korean population.
</P>
<P>
   Korean families in Japan used to send $100 million or more each
year in hard currency to North Korea, but now the aid has fallen to
a small fraction of that. One reason is the current recession in
Japan, but more important is that some Koreans in Japan look to
North Korea and now see not inspiration, but rather something
closer to embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, as South Korea has prospered and democratized and
emerged from beneath the American thumb, it has steadily gained
support. Now more Koreans in Japan are aligned with South Korea
than with the North.
</P>
<P>
   The South does not run full-fledged schools in Japan, so parents
usually send their children to Japanese schools and then sometimes
to Korean-language classes on the side.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps the North Koreans going, it seems, is not ideology or
politics, but nationalism and loyalty, for many still believe that
North Korea is far more authentically Korean than the South, which
they see as run by American quislings. Moreover, most Korean
families in Japan chose their sides a generation or two ago, and
switching camps now would be an unimaginable betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are people proud of their mothers only in good times and then
ashamed of their mothers when they run into troubles?'' asked Shin
Te Jyun, the president of the student body at the Korean High
School. ``No, of course not. We feel the same love for our mothers
in bad times as in good. And it's the same with our motherland.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greater challenge to the Korean schools is not that
pro-North Koreans will defect to the South, but rather that they
will join the flood of Koreans signing up for Japanese nationality.
Most Korean families in Japan now speak Japanese at home, and the
surge of naturalizations alarms many Korean stalwarts who see it as
a kind of cultural suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never think of becoming a Japanese citizen, because we
were colonized by Japan,'' said Sok Kyong Suk, a teacher at the
school. ``To become Japanese would be a humiliation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
