<HEADER>
A1480 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX     05-10 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARRAL-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PARENTS DOING A TOUGH JOB AS WELL AS POSSIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL K. HARRAL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cries are predictable.
</P>
<P>
   After any tragedy involving children, but especially in the
aftermath of a shooting death, everyone wants to know why the
parents didn't do something to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   If only parents would take responsibility, people say.
</P>
<P>
   Let's stipulate that some parents _ perhaps many, maybe even
most _ aren't as involved with their children as they should be.
</P>
<P>
   What we overlook in our passion in the aftermath of something
like the Littleton, Colo., school shooting is that almost all
teen-agers are reasonably law-abiding.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``reasonably'' because I'm not sure all that much has
changed since I was in school four decades ago and we were known to
cut a corner or two when we thought we could get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   But my friends and I, like almost all of today's kids, sort of
knew when and where to stop. So far as I know, none of us wound up
in prison, although a few of us wound up dead in automobile
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The operative words above were ``when we thought we could get
away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not much got past the adults in my hometown. OK, so it was a
tiny town in the Panhandle of Texas, and that's a lot different,
you say, from city life in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone has a neighborhood of some sort.
</P>
<P>
   I can show you places in my current hometown that would scare
Mr. Rogers silly. But the people who live there are doing the best
they can to get along and to see that life is a little better for
their kids than it is for them. Nobody wakes up in the morning and
wonders: ``What can I do today to destroy my children's lives?''
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult realization for parents is that at some
point, they will not be in control of their teen-agers' lives. And
that is the time to look to other adults _ and sometimes to other
teen-agers _ for help.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what your kid is doing, someone somewhere knows about
it. But they may not be telling you what they see. You have to
invite and welcome that kind of information.
</P>
<P>
   It is time for us to get nosy again.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ There is no such thing as a right to privacy for children
living under your roof. Check their rooms frequently. If they've
left a shotgun barrel out on the chest of drawers, or if they've
got a tote sack of fertilizer in the corner, you might want to ask
questions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Learn how to check the history file on the computer to see
where they've been on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's a big sacrifice, but listen to your kids' music. If you
don't approve of it, seize the CDs or tapes. (See the first point
above.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Talk to them about the TV programs they watch and the video
games they play. Children do not need TV sets in their rooms. If
you don't like the games, take them up. (See the first point
above.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Know who your children's friends are. This is more difficult
than it might seem, because no one seems to have last names
anymore, but you can figure it out if you try. Insist that the
friends come into the house before your child can leave with them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Once you know who the friends are, find out the names of the
friends' parents and get to know them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get the parents together and take these vows: (1) Be
tattletales. (2) Don't get angry when another parent tells you
something you don't want to hear about your child. (Just say thanks
and investigate yourself.) (3) Set your standards of taste and
behavior high, and raise them when your child has friends over. (4)
When Johnny says that Raul's mother has invited him over to spend
the night, call and check. (See the first point above.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Know how much money your children have, and where they got it.
When they come home with money or objects that they didn't leave
home with, ask them where they got the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remember your own adolescence and keep that in mind.
Teen-agers are naturally sneaky, and the point is to be not their
friend but their parents. Usually you can do both, but if you
can't, best that you pick ``parent.'' They'll thank you later after
the hormones die down.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't be too quick to side with your child against the school
_ or any authority. (Just say thanks and do your own
investigation.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Know the warning signs. If a child who has been making good
grades suddenly slips, get worried. If children change the way they
dress, abruptly switch friends (especially to a more suspect
group), suddenly start sleeping more, gain or lose a noticeable
amount of weight or start wearing perfume or aftershave heavy
enough to mask a smell, get suspicious. It might just be that they
are teen-agers. Or it might mean that they have started on a
dangerous path. (See the first point above.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Cut a deal with your kids that they can always blame you when
they don't want to do something or when they want to come home
rather than stay out with their friends.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't assume that your child can't get into trouble. There's a
period during the teen years when the peer group is much more
influential than parents.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that even the teen-agers who walk the dark side
usually make it through.
</P>
<P>
   But do you want to leave that to chance?
</P>
<P>
   (Paul K. Harral is vice president and editorial director for the
Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His e-mail address is
harral(at)star-telegram.com. You may telephone him at (817)
390-7836 or write him at P.O. Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
