<HEADER>
A1481 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-ACLU-PA     05-10 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-ACLU-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PA. ACLU FLOODED WITH STUDENT COMPLAINTS FOLLOWING COLORADO
INCIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 10 -- Pennsylvania teens have flooded the state
American Civil Liberties Union chapter with complaints of being
punished for violent writings and wearing black.
</P>
<P>
   Following the shooting rampage last month at a Colorado high
school, ACLU chapters around the nation are reporting an onslaught
of student or parent complaints similar to the 20 received by the
Pennsylvania office.
</P>
<P>
   One 14-year-old Harrisburg teen, who wrote in his journal for
English class that if he had a gun he would kill another person at
school, was suspended for 10 days and charged by police with
terrorist threats, ACLU officials said. Harrisburg school officials
did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid didn't have a gun, didn't have access to a gun and was
giving a response elicited by school officials in a class
assignment,'' said Stefan Presser, legal director for
Pennsylvania's ACLU. ``Does that mean nothing should be done? No.
But perhaps recommending the kid for counseling would have been a
better choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Presser said the other calls have come from around the state
alleging similar incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have gotten dramatically more calls on this than anything
in a very long while,'' Presser said. ``That's a shame because we
want kids who need help to come to us as school officials and
adults. We don't want them to feel like their rights are being
violated.''
</P>
<P>
   National ACLU officials say the well-meaning attempts of
teachers or principals to preserve safety may be violating
students' rights. ACLU chapters send letters to school officials
describing the complaint, refer students to lawyers or help on
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Presser said one Pennsylvania teen, who listed names of
classmates on a piece of paper titled ``Hit List,'' was suspended
and charged by police with making terrorist threats.
</P>
<P>
   Another Pennsylvania teen got suspended after saying in class
that she could understand how someone who is teased continually
could lose control, Presser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true the Colorado kids should have sought help or been
given help,'' Presser said. ``But educators here are in a
democracy. They have the difficult job of having to balance the
need to spot troubled behavior but preserve the rights of teens
expressing themselves. Just because someone dresses a certain way
or writes a certain way doesn't mean they will be violent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1486 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-10 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT: `CASES EMBARRASSING TO JUSTICE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If we needed more proof that the U.S. civil justice system is
out of control, we got it Friday when a jury in Michigan slapped a
TV talk show with $25 million in damages because a former guest on
the show killed another former guest.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse. The lawyer who represented the dead
guest's relatives had asked for more than $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you love it when jurors show restraint?
</P>
<P>
   The defendant in the case was ``The Jenny Jones Show,'' which
stars the onetime stand-up comic Jenny Jones. Do you suppose that
it ever occurred to Jones when she was firing off one-liners on
``Star Search'' oh so many years ago that one day she would be held
responsible for a murder she had nothing to do with?
</P>
<P>
   It probably didn't occur to Jones that such a thing could happen
until the jury's verdict was announced and she saw the smile on the
face of attorney Geoffrey Fieger, who represented the family of the
deceased talk-show guest.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Geoffrey Fieger. He's that shining light of
lawyerdom who parlayed his longtime representation of ``Dr.
Death,'' Jack Kevorkian, into a campaign for governor of Michigan.
Fortunately, Fieger wasn't elected. If he had been, the people who
voted against him might have been shopping for a hotshot attorney
to file a lawsuit against the people who voted for him.
</P>
<P>
   If there were an Obnoxious Lawyer Hall of Fame _ and we need
one, don't you think? _ Fieger would be a charter member. He argued
his case against Jenny Jones not just in the courtroom but on the
TV interview circuit, and his arguments left me no choice but to
side with his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Which I was inclined to do anyway. Not because I like Jones, who
is plenty obnoxious in her own right, or because I like her TV
show. There is nothing to like about her TV show.
</P>
<P>
   I favored the defendant in this lawsuit because I believe that
such lawsuits are outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   The whole deal started, most people know, when Jones decided to
do a program dealing with ``secret crushes.'' One of the crushees
was a heterosexual male named Jonathan Schmitz; the person who had
the crush on Schmitz was a gay man, Scott Amedure.
</P>
<P>
   According to news reports, Schmitz went to Amedure's mobile home
three days after the show was taped _ it was never broadcast _ and
shot Amedure to death with a shotgun. Schmitz was later convicted
of murder, but the conviction was overturned on appeal; he will be
retried.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what happened between the TV taping and the shooting is
not entirely clear. The Associated Press reported that lawyers
representing the show, which is owned by the Warner Bros.
entertainment conglomerate, said the killing might have been
related to a sexual encounter between Amedure and Schmitz. Fieger
insisted that no such encounter occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Fieger argued that Schmitz was mentally unstable, that he didn't
know that the secret admirer he would confront on the show was a
man, that the humiliation he suffered on the program drove him to
murder _ and that the folks who put on ``The Jenny Jones Show''
should have foreseen all this and never let it happen.
</P>
<P>
   A judge once advised me to never criticize a jury's verdict, but
I can't help it: If the jurors in the Jones case bought that batch
of baloney from Fieger _ and they obviously did _ they're dumb
enough to be guests on Jerry Springer's show.
</P>
<P>
   The simple reality here is that two adults agreed to appear on a
TV program that is well-known for its demeaning and embarrassing
content. If one of them later regretted his decision to participate
and for reasons known only to him committed a criminal act of
murder, well, that's a matter for the criminal courts to handle _
and they are in the process of handling it.
</P>
<P>
   It was tragic and horribly unfair that Scott Amedure became a
murder victim. But it is preposterous for his survivors to blame a
TV show for something that happened days after the show was taped.
</P>
<P>
   No one is to blame but Jonathan Schmitz.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Schmitz doesn't have $25 million. Warner Bros. does.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
