<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENGLAND-BOOK-REVIEW-N     05-10 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENGLAND-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ENGLAND, ENGLAND': ENGLAND AS THEME PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two Englands in Julian Barnes' latest work of fiction:
Old England, which is more or less the England we know today but
divested of all its most famous historical landmarks; and England,
England, a snazzy new theme park offering upscale tourists the
quintessence of England (from the White Cliffs of Dover to Big Ben,
from Jane Austen to Queen Victoria, from Diana's grave to Harrods)
within easy sightseeing distance, a virtual, Disneyesque England,
``more convenient, cleaner, friendlier and more efficient'' than
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   There are also two novels in Barnes' book ``England, England.''
The first is a wickedly funny satire that sends up greedy
developers, pompous intellectuals and conniving business tycoons;
the second is a wistful, philosophical portrait of a woman trying
to make sense of her life. The two novels are intercut clumsily
with each other to examine familiar themes concerning the
unreliability of memory and the elusiveness of the past _ themes
that have run through Barnes' work from ``Flaubert's Parrot''
(1985) to ``A History of the World in 10 1/2 Chapters'' (1989) and
``Cross Channel'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   The character who connects the two novels in ``England,
England'' is Martha Cochrane, another of Barnes' stubbornly
independent women, a searcher looking for her real self. Martha, we
learn, grew up in the English countryside, where she learned
English history by memorizing important events and dates. She was a
child when her father left home and never came back. He told her
years later that he had left her mother for another woman and
thought ``a clean break was fairer all round.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha grew up headstrong, clever and outspoken. She graduated
from college with a degree in history and went to work in London.
Now, at 39, she is a consultant to Sir Jack Pitman, a blustering
entrepreneur with an outsize business and an even more outsize ego.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jack likes to compare himself to Beethoven, and he has
decided that it's time for him to come up with his equivalent of
the Ninth Symphony as a capstone to his career. His idea, of
course, is England, England, which he plans to build on the Isle of
Wight. Its current residents, he figures, will be ``grateful future
employees''; its many thatched cottages will make perfect tea
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants are duly called in. A French intellectual declares
that people now ``prefer the replica to the original,'' ``the
reproduction of the work of art to the work of art itself.'' And
one of Sir Jack's chief operatives asserts that tourists want to
``enjoy what they already know,'' that they do not travel to see
anything new but to savor their own preconceptions. Just what do
these potential customers think of when they think of England? A
poll taken by Sir Jack's people reveals that ``the 50 quintessences
of Englishness'' include the royal family, London taxis,
Shakespeare, Stonehenge, bowler hats, cricket, Beefeater and
marmalade.
</P>
<P>
   What Sir Jack's team can't build or re-create on the Isle of
Wight, they cavalierly buy. The king is paid to come live on the
Island for a generous fee, and so is the Manchester United Football
Club. Actors are hired to impersonate Samuel Johnson, Lady Godiva
and Robin Hood, and famous scenes from English history are
re-enacted several times a day. It's not long before the island has
seceded from England and become Sir Jack's own personal fief.
</P>
<P>
   Although Martha and her boyfriend Jack use sexual blackmail to
get Sir Jack to relinquish his control of England, England, the
project still succeeds beyond anyone's wildest dreams. While
England, England grows ever more prosperous, Old England, which had
lost its history and its sense of itself, slides into a decline.
Millions of people leave for sunnier shores, the economy collapses,
and the country retreats into a pastoral, primitive past.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes uses his copious talents as a writer _ his lapidary
prose, his eye for the askew detail, his ear for the
circumlocutions of contemporary speech _ to turn the saga of
England, England into an uproarious farce that mocks both our
postmodernist suspicion of the authentic and our Disney-like
willingness to turn that embrace of the ersatz into a money-making
machine. He examines the arbitrary nature of history writing and
the cyclical nature of history, and he satirizes the ideas that the
English hold about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As for his story of Martha Cochrane's life (from her unhappy
childhood to her involvement with England, England, to her eventual
return to a small English village much like the one she grew up
in), it is sad and often touching _ as effective in evoking the
entire arc of a woman's life as his 1987 novel, ``Staring at the
Sun.'' The problem, however, is that in forcing Martha to inhabit
two novels, one comic and one not, Barnes has given her a split
personality: She behaves like a sharp-tongued boss lady in the
story of England, England and like a melancholy spinster in her own
biography; like a two-dimensional cartoon in the former and like an
old-fashioned, realistic heroine in the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes tries to link his two narratives by suggesting parallels
between a nation's invention of its own mythology and an
individual's invention of a self. He also has Martha say things
like, ``An individual's loss of faith and a nation's loss of faith,
aren't they much the same?'' Such strained efforts, unfortunately,
do not succeed in welding the two narratives in ``England,
England'' into a satisfying whole. The result is two finely turned
tales that add up to a disappointing third.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ENGLAND, ENGLAND'
</P>
<P>
   By Julian Barnes
</P>
<P>
   275 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
