<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA TORNADO OFFERS HINTS OF HOW A KILLER STORM IS BORN 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a classic convergence of tornado-producing forces shaped up
in southern Oklahoma on May 3, funnel-chasing scientists from the
university town of Norman scrambled like jet pilots, heading for
flatbed trucks carrying advanced radar that, they hope, will
eventually help find the key to a tantalizing, frustrating mystery:
How is a tornado born?
</P>
<P>
   The answer lies in the last few minutes of a complex chain of
events that begins when large-scale air masses clash and ends when
a twister rakes the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the process leading up to the critical moment of tornado
genesis is well understood. But unless and until research
meteorologists can solve the puzzle of the last crucial step, they
will be at a loss to predict whether a garden variety tornado is on
the way, or one so puny it will fall apart at the first obstacle it
hits, or a monster like one that struck the outskirts of Oklahoma
City on May 3, demolishing entire neighborhoods and killing dozens
of people.
</P>
<P>
   That tornado appears to have been one of the most powerful ever
observed. Its whirling winds were measured by meteorologists from
the University of Oklahoma at 318 miles an hour, which they believe
to be a record wind speed. More important, they were able to
approach to within about three-quarters of a mile of the big
tornado's center; there, with debris raining down around them, they
believe they captured the twister's birth on radar.
</P>
<P>
   The data will not be fully analyzed for some time, and much more
will be necessary before researchers can draw general conclusions
about tornado birth, life and death. Every tornado is a little
different, and they are all capricious, evanescent and hard to get
a fix on. But in time, the scientists believe, forecasters will be
able to predict not just that a tornado is coming, as they
presently can, but also how strong it will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any skill at that now,'' said Dr. Joshua Wurman,
one of the Oklahoma researchers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the difficulty of trying to pin down the atmospheric
machinations that give birth to a tornado has proved ``just
excruciating,'' said Dr. Roger Wakimoto, a tornado expert who heads
the atmospheric sciences department at the University of California
at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Tornadoes are the product of thunderstorms that blossom when
cold, dry air masses meet warm, moist ones. This takes place along
the jet stream, the high-altitude, west-to-east river of air that
marks the boundary between cold polar air and warm tropical air.
When these air masses meet, warm, moist air near the ground rises,
and, when it meets colder air aloft, the moisture condenses into
rain.
</P>
<P>
   The falling rain drags down air with it, producing powerful
downdrafts. Sometimes, warm, dry air intrudes between the cold air
aloft and the warm, moist air near the ground. As the moist air
near the ground rises, it carries the drier air with it. The drier
air cools faster than the moist air and makes the situation even
more unstable, producing especially violent thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring in Tornado Alley, a swatch of the Great Plains
stretching across Kansas, Oklahoma and northern Texas, those
conditions are often met: The jet stream converges with warm, moist
air from the Gulf of Mexico and warm, dry air from the Mexican
plateau. In fact, ``those three ingredients come together more
frequently in Tornado Alley than anywhere else in the world,'' said
Fred Gadomski, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State University.
More tornadoes develop there than anywhere else on the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The May 3 tornado developed from a variety of thunderstorm
called a supercell, which in turn was produced by just the kind of
convergence of elements described by Gadomski. A supercell is a
big, hulking storm distinguished by the internal presence of a
twisting, tilted updraft whose tilt enables it to avoid getting
tangled up with the storm's downdrafts. This updraft is therefore
more stable and long-lived, enabling the storm itself to live as
long as there is a supply of surface moisture. Supercells can
produce several tornadoes and are the main generator of the most
powerful and long-lasting ones.
</P>
<P>
   But the appearance of thunderstorms only sets the stage for
tornadoes, and only a few storms produce them. Certain conditions
within the storm must be met for a tornado to form. The most
important is wind shear _ cross-cutting winds of differing speeds
or directions. When two layers of wind move in the same direction
at different speeds, the effect is to set air between them
rotating, as when one twirls a pencil between one's palms.
</P>
<P>
   This horizontal roll of rotating air is pushed upward in the
center by the powerful updraft of warm, moist air feeding the
thunderstorm at its base. Eventually, the roll evolves into a
relatively slow-whirling vertical vortex called a mesocyclone. The
vortex then narrows and lengthens; this increases its speed, just
as a skater's whirl intensifies when she pulls her arms in close or
extends them over her head.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery is how that last step happens. It is at this
critical juncture, apparently, that tornadoes somehow become
stronger or weaker. Only a very few reach the status of F4 or F5 on
the Fujita scale of tornado damage _ tornadoes with winds of more
than 206 miles an hour. (F0 and F1, on the other end of the scale,
have winds of 40 to 112 miles an hour; an F3 storm's winds are 158
to 206 miles an hour.)
</P>
<P>
   The chances that an F4 or F5 tornado ``will go over any
individual spot in a person's lifetime is on the order of 1 in 10
million, even in Tornado Alley,'' Gadomski said.
</P>
<P>
   The most destructive and lethal of the Oklahoma tornadoes on May
3 was an F5; such a storm destroys nearly everything in its path.
The May 3 twister was also long-lived, staying on the ground about
four hours. The known record is seven hours; most last only a few
minutes at best.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The big challenge facing researchers is to learn to tell the
difference in tornadoes as far in advance as possible, so that more
precise and timely warnings can be issued. ``Right now,'' Wurman
said, ``we just say there's a tornado coming; we don't know whether
it's an F0 or an F5.''
</P>
<P>
   Improved predictions require better knowledge of the very
fine-scale interplay of temperature, moisture and wind that
converts a mesocyclone into a tornado. Experts like Wurman are
pursuing this knowledge using up-to-date technology to gather
real-world data, which are used to improve theoretical models that
are then expressed mathematically in the computerized models of the
atmosphere on which today's weather forecasters rely.
</P>
<P>
   One theoretical question is whether tornadoes develop from the
top of the thunderstorm down or from the ground up. This bears
importantly on the matter of how a more slowly rotating mesocyclone
increases its spin to tornadic speed. It was long assumed that the
tornado builds from the top down, but Wakimoto says there is ``a
mountain of evidence'' that many build from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   In attempting to answer questions like this, tornado-chasing
researchers have used various technologies. One, called TOTO _ for
Totable Tornado Observatory, not Dorothy's dog from ``The Wizard of
Oz'' _ is an instrument package designed to be placed in a
tornado's path and sucked up by it. Some chasers also deploy squat
packages of sensors called turtles along roads. But tactics like
these, popularized in the movies, have limited utility, since it is
difficult to place the instrument packages properly.
</P>
<P>
   To zero in on tornado genesis, researchers concentrating on
Tornado Alley use two strategies introduced in the past five years,
said Dr. Harold Brooks, a research meteorologist at the National
Severe Storms Laboratory, a federal research installation in
Norman. In one, researchers chase thunderstorms and tornadoes in
fleets of cars and vans packed with instruments that measure things
like temperature, wind, air pressure and atmospheric moisture.
Readings are taken every six seconds in an attempt to build up a
fine-grained picture of tornado development.
</P>
<P>
   Wurman and his colleagues use the second strategy, chasing
storms and tornadoes in two flatbed trucks on which Doppler radars
are mounted. Like conventional radar, the Doppler version can
``see'' fine targets like raindrops and can tell how far away a
mesocyclone or tornado is. But it can also tell whether a tornado
is moving away from or toward the radar station.
</P>
<P>
   Stationary Doppler radar is widely used by weather forecasters.
But because the radar is often many miles away from the storm, its
beam is aimed too high. Doppler on Wheels, as the Norman program is
called, casts its beam into the storm much closer to the ground.
``It allows us to see details in the velocity structure we've never
seen,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Doppler on Wheels also scans the atmosphere eight times faster
than the forecasters' radar, and when two Dopplers focus on the
same storm from different angles, a better picture of the storm's
structure and dynamics emerges.
</P>
<P>
   Wurman and his colleagues are on tornado standby from mid-April
to mid-June. So it was that on May 3, when the classic set of
Tornado Alley conditions materialized over southern Oklahoma, ``we
left the building fast,'' Wurman said.
</P>
<P>
   From 2 p.m. until after midnight, they chased supercell
thunderstorms and tornadoes across the state. They watched the
supercell that spawned the F5 killer that struck Oklahoma City spit
out one tornado after another. In two cases, the researchers
believe, the Dopplers captured tornadoes being formed _ including
the Oklahoma City monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens very quickly,'' said Wurman, with rotating winds
escalating from perhaps 40 or 50 miles an hour to well over 100
miles an hour in two, three or four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's two more puzzle pieces,'' he said of the sightings of
tornado births. ``This will give us some answers.'' But a long road
lies ahead, not least in analyzing the mass of data that the
researchers are gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reeling with the volume of data we've collected,''
Wurman said.
</P>
<P>
   How realistic is it to hope that tornado forecasts can
significantly improve? Predictions will never be perfect, it is
widely agreed. For one thing, the atmosphere has a chaotic, random
streak that frustrates precision and predictability. For another,
the short life of tornadoes inherently limits warning time; just
now it is measured in a few minutes. Some believe it might be able
to improve on that by 15 or 20 minutes. Optimists say an hour might
ultimately be possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the new technology we have,'' Wurman said, ``we are
positioned to make major strides. It really comes down to
persistence in chasing down tornadoes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
