<HEADER>
A1510 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUS-WRECK-HNS &LR;      05-10 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-WRECK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREMENT CENTER CELEBRATES MASS FOR VICTIMS OF BUS CRASH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JERRY URBAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ As authorities Monday continued to investigate the
cause of a bus crash that killed more than 20 people, a Mass was
celebrated for eight of the female victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past 24 hours have been rough ones,'' Monsignor Thomas
Rodi told more than 100 people gathered at the Place Dubourg
Retirement Center in La Place, a community about 30 miles west of
New Orleans. ``Most of us would have liked to wake up thinking this
was a bad dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight women were residents of the retirement center. Two
other female residents remained hospitalized with serious injuries,
caused by the 9 a.m. Sunday wreck on Interstate 610 near Interstate
10 in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The tour bus, operated by Custom Bus Charter Co. of New Orleans,
was taking senior citizens to the Casino Magic casino in Biloxi,
Miss., after leaving La Place.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some confusion over how many people died. On
Sunday, officials said it was 23, but on Monday they said 22
fatalities had been confirmed. The coroner's office said 19 women
and three men died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (the Mass) is a form of pleasure for us,'' said Jessie
Doyle, a resident of the retirement center. ``We're family. We're
all part of a family, very close.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle said the 110 women and nine men who remain at the center
are taking the deaths ``very hard, especially the ones who did not
go on the trip. We had six (residents) cancel because of Mother's
Day. They're feeling such guilt right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at the Mass was Rose Garnett, whose 84-year-old mother,
Florence Mathieu, died.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett said she was concerned about reports that the driver,
46-year-old Frank Bedell, of the bus has had medical problems
recently. ``If they (drivers) are feeling ill ... please don't get
on a highway,'' she said. ``My mama always taught us to be cautious
about driving.''
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans police and the National Transportation Safety Board
continued trying to determine what caused the bus to leave the
freeway and crash into an embankment at a tunnel for golf carts at
the City Park course.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Walker, safety director for the bus company, said the
driver told him the bus swerved when it was cut off by another car.
Police declined to comment about their investigation other than to
encourage potential witnesses to call authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-plus injured people included Bedell, who remained in
``very critical'' condition at Charity Hospital with pelvis and
head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Francis, vice chairman of the NTSB, said during a press
conference Monday that investigators are looking into ``rumors''
that Bedell had kidney dialysis within 24 hours before the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the bus company has said Bedell had an excellent
driving record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask for prayers and sympathy for the families and friends
of the victims and also the La Place and Reserve communities who
have experienced a huge loss,'' said New Orleans Mayor Marc H.
Morial. ``The city is working with NTSB to fully investigate this
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Morial called for all churches and houses of worship throughout
southeast Louisiana to observe a day of prayer and reflection this
Sunday in memory of those who died in the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
