<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-ART-THEFTS-2TA     05-10 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-ART-THEFTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURGLARS MEET THE DEMAND FOR FRENCH ANTIQUES
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Henri-Francois de Breteuil was saddened, though hardly
surprised, when art thieves broke into his family seat, the Chateau
de Breteuil, in January last year. ``It was the fourth time in 10
years,'' the soft-spoken Marquis de Breteuil recalled. ``I was at
home every time. The alarm goes off at 3:30 a.m., you rush out, and
you see a truck leaving the plaza.''
</P>
<P>
   After each burglary, he improved the security system at the
elegant 17th-century castle 20 miles south of Paris. After the last
break-in, he even recovered one object, an ornate gilded
18th-century clock. It brought him little solace. With a spate of
thefts at chateaux and manor houses spreading alarm through
France's landed aristocracy, he can only wonder when he will next
be hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation has become truly dramatic since early 1998,''
said the Marquis, 55, who is also president of La Demeure
Historique, a private association of some 2,500 chateau owners, one
of whom has been robbed no fewer than 13 times. ``The number of
thefts has risen sharply. There has also been a marked escalation
in the quality of the objects taken.''
</P>
<P>
   With 18th- and 19th-century French antiques back in fashion in
wealthy homes around the world, robbing French chateaux has
suddenly become big business.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Gendarmerie, which polices the rural areas
where most chateaux are situated, the number of break-ins more than
doubled last year, rising 115 percent to 1,478, from 688 in 1997.
The Interior Ministry has slightly different figures: 1,266
burglaries of historic domaines in 1998, a rise of 152 percent. But
the agencies agree that thousands of art objects _ in the main,
furniture, antique arms, chandeliers, clocks and bronzes _ have
been stolen. And the crime wave is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Working through La Demeure Historique, chateau owners have
appealed to the Culture Ministry for technical and financial help
in better securing their homes, arguing that art thieves are
plundering France's national patrimony. At the same time the
Gendarmerie has created special investigative police units in badly
affected regions in the hope of breaking up ever more brazen gangs
of castle robbers and traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the mood is one of frustration, it is because both
chateau owners and the police have concluded that their real enemy
is invisible. Burglars, crooked middlemen and unscrupulous dealers
may be the beneficiaries, but the root of the problem is the
surging international demand for French art objects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castles are being targeted more and more because of the
quality of their art objects,'' said Jean-Michel Mimran, head of
France's bureau charged with combating the traffic in stolen art.
``And this seems to be in direct response to the popularity of the
18th- and 19th-century French style. Little of what is stolen stays
in France. What stays here is usually of little interest to serious
antiquarians and collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   Mimran said the United States, Britain, Germany and Japan were
the main markets for French art objects. ``Entire containers arrive
from transit countries, the objects are not identified as stolen,
and no one bothers to verify their origin,'' he said. ``Because the
market cannot meet demand, it often ignores signs of dubious
provenance.'' Some dealers even show photographs of French art
objects. ``In one gallery in Los Angeles, I was told it would take
three or four weeks to deliver some objects,'' Mimran said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, many chateau owners believe that foreign dealers can
``order'' a particular object in a particular castle on behalf of
an individual buyer, although Mimran doubts that the criminal chain
is that efficient. Rather, he said, traffickers respond to demand
for categories of objects. And at the moment French art objects are
in vogue. ``Britain has a very valuable heritage,'' he said, ``but
little is stolen there. Why not? Because there isn't great demand
for the English style.''
</P>
<P>
   Once stolen art objects have been distributed to dealers and
galleries in the United States or other markets, they are difficult
to trace. And once they are in private homes, they generally
disappear forever. Only occasionally are missing items recovered.
For instance, at a ceremony at the U.S. Embassy in Paris on March
22, the U.S. customs commissioner, Raymond Kelly, returned
religious artifacts stolen from a church in northern France and
seized at Newark Airport in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact there are ceremonies each time something is returned
shows just how little is actually caught,'' Mimran said. ``We work
closely with the American authorities, but even when stolen items
are found, the legal obstacles to recovering them are
considerable.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is the 1814 Treaty of Fontainebleau, the
international agreement under which Napoleon abdicated and went
into exile, albeit briefly, on the island of Elba. One example of
the signed document, which was stolen from France's National
Archives in 1988, was consigned for sale at Sotheby's in New York
in 1996. When Sotheby's contacted the French Archives as a possible
purchaser, it learned that the document had been stolen and
withdrew it from sale. Mimran said the man who tried to sell the
treaty had shared a home in Tennessee with the last person known to
have studied it in the National Archives. Nonetheless, France has
still to recover the document.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with thefts from French chateaux, however, is the
sheer volume of the art objects involved. Belgium and the
Netherlands play central roles as transit countries. With most
borders in the European Union now gone, truckloads of stolen goods
can reach, say, Brussels, Belgium, or Amsterdam, Netherlands,
within hours of a theft. (In southern France, some booty is
smuggled into Italy.)
</P>
<P>
   French police investigators say that middlemen based outside
France are the crucial figures in the racket: they have the
distribution contacts in the consumer countries, and they inform
art thieves of what objects are most in demand. Some stolen goods
are put up for sale locally _ the Marquis de Breteuil's stolen
clock, for instance, was recovered in the Netherlands _ but
containerloads of furniture, bronzes, clocks and the like are
shipped to more lucrative markets.
</P>
<P>
   In the hope of cutting the flow of stolen goods out of France,
the Gendarmerie has begun targeting middlemen in this country who
store art objects before they are moved on. Last November, for
instance, 2,000 objects, including 700 clocks, were seized in
hideouts in the Alliers region. Another roundup near Toulouse in
March resulted in 20 arrests and the recovery of a vast array of
goods stolen from chateaux in the region on 95 different occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But Lt. Col. Joel Vaillant, who coordinates the Gendarmerie's
campaign against art theft, remains pessimistic. ``We find less
than 10 percent of what is stolen,'' he said. ``We concentrate on
arresting the receivers of the stolen goods because each receiver
can have several thieves or gangs working for him. If we arrest a
single thief, he's out in no time. But if we can demonstrate that
organized crime is involved, the sanctions are heavier.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
