<HEADER>
A1512 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-ART-THEFTS-ART     05-10 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-ART-THEFTS-ART-2ND </SLUG>
 TAKE-NYT 
PARIS: sanctions are heavier'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What most disturbs chateau owners, however, is the recognition
that security forces are unable or unwilling to do anything to
protect their property. ``Their message is, we know things will be
stolen, but we can help you recover them,'' the Marquis de Breteuil
said glumly. Owners of chateaux that are open to the public, either
as businesses or simply on the annual Heritage Day, feel
particularly vulnerable. Thieves are free to look around for
anything that might be worth returning for.
</P>
<P>
   A few owners prefer to keep out the public, although as a result
they lose certain tax benefits. ``They try to keep a very low
profile,'' said an American woman whose French relatives own two
castles, and who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``They don't want
articles written about them; they don't want photographs published
in fancy magazines.'' Some even avoid taking out insurance on their
valuables, although in this case it is usually to hide their wealth
from the French tax authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Most have opted for tightening their security, though they are
all too aware that art thieves are sophisticated and work so
quickly that they can ignore alarm bells. All too often, they take
their trucks _ pushing them to avoid making noise _ to the doors
and windows of chateaux to load furniture or heavy bronzes. Since
the thieves usually know what they want, they can be in and out
within a few minutes even if alarms sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best solution is to keep the thieves as far away as
possible,'' the Marquis said, ``to have the alarms go off in the
grounds so guardians or families have time to react.''
</P>
<P>
   One way is to install sensors at the entrance to castle grounds;
another is to use large boulders to block smaller paths leading to
the main building. But in estates like the Chateau de Breteuil,
which is surrounded by 200 acres of woodland, it is almost
impossible to keep out strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Marquis, who has recruited a retired general as security
adviser for La Demeure Historique, has recently reinforced the many
full-length windows and doors to his castle. For his most valuable
single object, the Teschen Table, an 18th-century Prussian pedestal
table with a top inlaid with 128 gems and semiprecious stones, he
has built a transparent security box modeled after the case that
protects ``Mona Lisa'' at the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have good security, instead of losing three
clocks, the whole chateau will be emptied,'' the Marquis said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in meetings with members of La Demeure Historique, the
advice from security forces is to anticipate thefts by documenting,
marking and photographing vulnerable items to aid their recovery.
If a theft occurs, information can then be fed into a data bank
operated by Mimran's bureau, which now works in French, English and
Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   The best hope for chateau owners seems to be out of their hands:
that international demand for French art objects will suddenly
slacken. ``It's not impossible,'' Mimran said. ``For years, Italy
was in and France was out. These things come in cycles.
Fortunately, by definition, fashion changes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
