<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0511-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDIFFERENT TO DIPLOMACY: REFUGEES SAY SERB PROMISES ARE HOLLOW
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ As Yugoslav officials announced Monday that
Serb forces would begin a partial withdrawal from Kosovo, thousands
of refugees were completing their own withdrawal _ another forced
march to freedom by hungry and weary ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 refugees crossed into Albania in a three-day period
ending Monday night, fleeing shelling in villages near the western
cities of Pec and Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them brought fresh stories of atrocities by Serb troops
and vowed never to go back to their homes in Kosovo without the
protection of NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of pain they inflicted on my city, the level of
panic they created, is unbelievable,'' said Igjmet Rexhepi, 44, a
lawyer from the city of Mitrovica who fled Monday on foot into
Albania with his wife and three children. He claimed to have
witnessed the deaths of seven people last Friday when Serb
artillery slammed into the village of Zablac, where 5,000 ethnic
Albanians had taken refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees tearfully told of young men being separated from
their groups and taken away, followed by the sound of distant
gunfire. One woman told aid workers that a Serb paramilitary had
pointed his automatic rifle at the head of her baby to force the
family to move on.
</P>
<P>
   The grinding refugee crisis in Albania and Macedonia remains a
world apart from the diplomatic posturing and prospects emerging
from Washington, Belgrade and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Russia and the Group of Seven industrialized nations,
including the United States, reached a broad outline on the
conditions for a peaceful settlement of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Upping the stakes in the diplomatic wrangling, the Yugoslav
government announced that it would pull some Serb forces out of
Kosovo as it declared victory in its efforts to root out the ragtag
Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA.
</P>
<P>
   But the refugees and the international officials struggling to
care for them, view with apprehension the Serb promises as well as
indications that NATO may be accelerating its efforts for a
diplomatic solution by watering down its initial demands of the
Yugoslav regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem isn't coming out. The problem is how do we get
back in? How do we go home? Will Clinton make it possible?'' said
Bekim Krasniqi, 25, a farmer from the Kosovo city of Prizren. He
fled one month ago and keeps a vigil at the Morina border crossing
in northern Albania for other family members he hopes will soon
come out.
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks into the crisis, United Nations officials are still
struggling to cope with refugees coming in waves across the border.
More than 700,000 have left Kosovo - 400,000 of them through the
northern Albanian town of Kukes, where authorities are ill-equipped
to handle the load.
</P>
<P>
   In plans which seem to presume no swift return of the refugees
to their homes, officials are preparing to move large numbers of
the more than 100,000 in and around Kukes to new camps farther
south in Albania. From Macedonia, more and more refugees are being
flown to host countries, including the United States and European
nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply have problems taking care of them here,'' said Ray
Wilkinson, spokesman for UNHCR, the United Nations refugee agency
in Kukes. ``Refugees will be better cared for and protected in
other parts of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign Monday of growing tensions in Macedonia's overcrowded
tent cities, about 2,000 angry Kosovar Albanians protested poor
conditions at the Stenkovec I camp, which houses 23,000 people, and
alleged police harassment _ including the beating of two residents.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters chanted ``NATO, NATO'' in front of a Macedonian
police station, demanding that alliance troops take over the
facility just north of the capital, Skopje.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, UNHCR officials warned that the Macedonian tent
cities were ``on the verge of rioting'' because of overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A nagging concern among aid workers here is that a military
escalation could result should diplomacy falter. That could bring
the war close to the border.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the refugee camps in the Kukes region are within range
of Serb artillery. Authorities here also worry that preparations to
use U.S. Apache attack helicopters to target Serb forces along the
border could provoke Serb retaliation against the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously with the refugees here it makes a more tempting
target,'' Wilkinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer numbers in Kukes has overwhelmed aid agencies. While
NATO has donated trucks to cart the refugees south, only 4,000 to
5,000 are leaving the Kukes area, while thousands more are
arriving. Eight thousand refugees arrived each on Saturday and
Sunday, overflowing transit tents and forcing families with small
children to sleep in the open.
</P>
<P>
   Ilir Olloni, 35, was among the arrivals Monday with his wife
Lumnije and their two-year-old daughter Argyriana. The toddler, as
her parents, had not eaten in four days on the move after Serb
forces drove them from their hiding place in a village near
Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   The walked into Albania with the clothes they wore. The child
was pale and, her mother said, was running a high fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs gave us no time to pack. They told us to move on.
But there was no where to go,'' said Olloni.
</P>
<P>
   The vague language agreed upon last week by Western nations and
Russia could leave open the possibility of a settlement that would
allow some Serb security forces to remain in Kosovo. The document
also did not explicitly state that any peacekeeping force in Kosovo
would be led by NATO, though U.S. officials continue to insist that
it must.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls for the disarming of the KLA, which largely has
been pushed out of Kosovo along with the refugees, and is now
seeking to regroup and train new recruits along the borders of
Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   A KLA military spokesman in Kukes said the movement would never
disarm. ``Each passing day we are getting better organized,'' said
spokesman Shefki Abdullahu. ``We will never give up our arms and we
will fight to the last soldier is dead if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   But a refugee, Deli Qerreti, said only NATO could guarantee a
safe return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we will get back and find our houses burned and our
lands destroyed. But we can rebuild. We want to rebuild. But it
cannot begin unless we are safe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
