<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-COUNTRYMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERN COUNTRYMAN, 81, RETIRED PROFESSOR AT HARVARD LAW SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vern Countryman, a retired professor at Harvard Law School who
was a specialist on commercial and bankruptcy law, died of heart
failure May 2 in Mt. Auburn Hospital in Cambridge, Mass. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professor Countryman reshaped commercial law in a more
complex, humane image,'' Harvard Law professor Elizabeth Warren
said Monday. ``He taught us that commercial law does not consist
merely of dry stuff, of codes and cost curves, but also involves
hard questions about the living, breathing human beings who infuse
the marketplace with opportunity and danger.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Roundup, Mont., Mr. Countryman graduated from the
University of Washington and its law school. He was an attorney for
the National Labor Relations Board in Seattle before becoming a
clerk for Supreme Court Justice William O. Douglas in 1942 and
1943.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he remained close friends with the justice and
wrote three books about him. He was an executor of the justice's
literary estate.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the Army Air Corps during World War II, he was
an assistant attorney general for the State of Washington and an
assistant professor of law at Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   He was a dean of the University of New Mexico School of Law
before joining the faculty at Harvard Law in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The coauthor of the texts ``The Lawyer in Modern Society,''
``Commercial Law,'' and ``Debtors' and Creditors' Rights,'' the
chain-smoking, crew-cut Mr. Countryman was considered a tough
taskmaster in the classroom. ``Stern Vern worked hard and believed
others should work hard,'' said his colleague Andrew Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his writing on bankruptcy law,'' said Kaufman, ``Vern was
for the little guys.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article published in The New York Times in 1982, Mr.
Countryman said, ``There's a great campaign on to convince the
press that the new bankruptcy laws are so enticing that people
can't keep out of the bankruptcy courts. But the real problem is
the economy. People just are getting into trouble, and changing the
bankruptcy laws isn't going to change anything. People don't pay
because they can't pay, and even if you change the law people still
couldn't pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Countryman was a founding trustee of the National Consumer
Law Center, which presents the annual Vern Countryman Award to
recognize attorneys who ``through the practice of consumer law,
have contributed significantly to the rights and welfare of
low-income consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves two daughters, Debra Green of Freestone, Calif. and
Kay Briggs of Lafayette, Calif.; three brothers, Roy of Bozeman,
Mont., Robert of Seattle, and Charles of Yakima, Wash.; and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
