<SLUG> BC-CNN-HILL-HOLLIDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN HIRES HILL HOLLIDAY; FIDELITY HIRES IT SOME HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos was named Monday as
the ad agency of record for CNN, the cable TV news network, but one
of Hill Holliday's top clients, Fidelity Investments, also said it
has hired another agency to join Hill Holliday in advertising its
mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN account, which had previously been handled by CNN's
in-house ad agency, is expected to be worth between $20 million and
$25 million in annual billings, according to Hill Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hill Holliday captured our brand essence in the review
process,'' said CNN vice chairman Steve Korn.
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN is a huge power brand with amazing growth opportunities
ahead,'' said June Blocklin, an executive vice president at Hill
Holliday. ``And it's an extremely exciting win for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Fidelity said it plans to add a new ad agency to a
roster that already includes Hill Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Fidelity's advertising had been shared by Fidelity's
in-house ad department and Hill Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gotham of New York becomes Fidelity's third ad agency,
charged with creating a campaign for Fidelity's retail brokerage
business, which includes on-line trading. Retail brokerage is one
of the fastest growing pieces of Fidelity's business.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, a ``Fidelity.com'' ad campaign was introduced
with the theme, ``Every second counts.''
</P>
<P>
   That campaign was developed jointly by Hill Holliday and
Fidelity's in-house agency. In the future, Gotham is expected to
become the lead agency on that portion of Fidelity's business.
</P>
<P>
   Hill Holliday developed a branding campaign for Fidelity that
stars Peter Lynch, who was once Fidelity's top stock picker. That
campaign will continue under Hill Holliday, a Fidelity spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hill Holliday claims to be unaffected by Fidelity's decision,
though neither Fidelity nor Hill Holliday would disclose how much
Fidelity spends on advertising and how that amount would be divided
up among the various ad agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal has always been to help Fidelity grow their brand and
be profitable as a business,'' said Hill Holliday spokesman Eric
Fehrnstrom. ``We continue to do that as Fidelity's main agency of
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity advertising dollars spent at Hill Holliday and Gotham
ultimately could go to the same place. Both agencies are owned by
the Interpublic Group of Cos., which recently bought Mullen, an
agency based in Wenham.
</P>
<P>
   Hill Holliday, the second largest agency in New England,
reported billings last year of more than $700 million and revenues
of $106 million, a 33 percent increase. Big clients include John
Hancock Financial Services and Dunkin' Donuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
