<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NOMO-RETURN-NYTR &LR;      05-10 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NOMO-RETURN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN TURNS ITS LONELY EYES TO YOU, NOMO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BOB PADECKY   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If it is true an athlete is more interesting
either on his way up or on his way down, then Hideo Nomo is a
five-part television miniseries, a Spielberg movie and a
book-of-the-month club selection. It's not every day people on two
continents intently watch an icon trying to hang onto his dream by
his fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is our Michael Jordan,'' said Kiyoshi Mio, a Japanese
sportswriter based in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, that doesn't even begin to approach the truth.
Michael Jordan never had to suffer the indignity of being released
by two teams within a month of each other, as Nomo experienced this
spring with the New York Mets and Chicago Cubs. Further, Jordan
never had a tryout in his sport and was told he stunk and that he
wasn't wanted, as Nomo was told by the Cleveland Indians a few
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very pleasant to be in major leagues again,'' said Nomo
on Sunday through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   As understatements go, this one carries the subtlety of a brick
falling 10 stories into a greenhouse. Nomo is euphoric,
overwhelmed, numbed, bathe-me-in-lilacs happy. Considering how
universally sour baseball teams are on Nomo _ and the sport is in
the midst of the age of lollipop pitching _ the right-hander has
checked the landscape and lowered his expectations.
</P>
<P>
   This spring Nomo said he signed with the Cubs because he wanted
to go to a World Series contender. Released three weeks later, Nomo
then said he would be happy to sign with anyone. Such finer points
can be made when your earned run average is the size of a large
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Brewers-Giants game Sunday, his first start of the
season, Nomo's ERA is 1.42. He lasted six and one-third innings.
Does this mean the magic is back? Does it mean he has his old
fastball? Does it mean the Brewers uncovered a diamond everyone
else thought was fool's gold?
</P>
<P>
   The answers to those three questions are no, no, no. Sorry to
say, unfortunately.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately because baseball needs Nomo more than Nomo needs
baseball. He is already Japan's Michael Jordan. His name will be
seen forever in the bright lights: the fastest pitcher in
major-league history to reach 500 strikeouts, only the seventh Los
Angeles Dodger to pitch a no-hitter, the proud possessor of
Nomomania, that drop-off-the-table split-finger and a delivery in
which he looks as if he is reaching to take something off the top
shelf of his closet.
</P>
<P>
   With so many faceless pitchers with interchangeable fat ERAs in
the game today, baseball could use Nomo's style, providing he has
the substance to back it up. That's the rub. Sunday, Nomo did show
some flashes, like that diving splitter he threw to Rich Aurilia in
the fifth inning in which the swing from the Giants shortstop
looked more like a tee shot in golf than a swing at a baseball. And
Aurilia is the sixth-best hitter in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not happy,'' Aurilia said.
</P>
<P>
   But more times than not, Nomo did not look like the 1995 NL
Rookie of the Year when he struck out more hitters than any rookie
in Dodger history. He was hittable, but he also was pitching
against the Giants in San Francisco, where he is now 4-0 with a
1.21 career ERA. The first fact was canceled out by the second
fact, one of those immutable laws of the baseball universe and a
development that did not calm the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the people in Japan think he is done,'' Mio said, ``and
we are very worried.''
</P>
<P>
   They think Nomo has lost his crippling fastball. And he has.
They think he has a tough time throwing to the right spot. And he
does. Why, at 30 when he should be entering his prime, has Nomo
suddenly become ordinary? A nation is mystified. How did its
Michael Jordan stop flying?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows,'' Mio said.
</P>
<P>
   So they hang on, just as the man himself does, by their
fingernails, hoping time isn't running out, settling for small
victories. After Nomo finished his postgame press conference, the
man from the Japanese Embassy who acted as his translator stopped
Nomo for his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   Without a smile, Hideo Nomo signed.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
