<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR THE BRUINS TO GET TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Time now for a character check. A huge character
check. The Bruins need more than a good start, more than a better
effort, more than doing all the little things in better and bigger
ways.
</P>
<P>
   What they need now, more than ever, more than anything, is for
one of their big forwards to (itals)arrive(unitals) Wednesday night
when they face the Sabres in Game 3 of their Eastern Conference
semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for someone, like Jason Allison, to arrive the way
Bryan Trottier did for the Islanders in the early '80s.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for someone, like Joe Thornton, to arrive the way Mark
Messier did later in the '80s for the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins are going to live to play another round this
spring, they need big forwards with character, with certifiable
growl, to get them beyond Buffalo. It means taking command. It
means a (itals)coming out,(unitals) of sorts. It means being the
same thing on offense that Ray Bourque and Kyle McLaren are on
defense. It means playing valuable minutes, being asked to score,
and playing with the snarl and determination that Rob DiMaio brings
every shift to the checking line.
</P>
<P>
   It is as simple, yet as difficult, as that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't realize what it takes,'' coach Pat Burns said
Monday, less than 24 hours after watching an intense, almost rabid
Sabre squad shred his Bruins in Game 2, ``if you don't realize what
it means to continue. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Then you don't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Does someone in the Boston lineup get it? We find out Wednesday
night, and we find out Friday night in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Does it all fall on the shoulders of Mssrs. Allison and
Thornton? No. But it's close.
</P>
<P>
   Anson Carter is another prime candidate. Three other forwards
who get bountiful ice time _ Steve Heinze, Sergei Samsonov, and
Dmitri Khristich _ certainly find themselves with the minutes and
the opportunity, but for a variety of reasons they don't fit the
profile. All can be valuable, but none is likely to develop
overnight as the key forward in charge, the man in command of the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Trottier and Messier? Think about it. Trottier was 23 years old
in the spring of '80 when he evolved into the Islanders' key pivot,
his grit a key ingredient in their four consecutive Stanley Cups.
Messier also was 23 in '84 when he took charge of the Oilers'
superb talent _ taking on Trottier nose to nose in the '84 finals,
in fact _ and brought them their first Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who will be 20 in June, is considerably younger and in
only his second NHL season. But Allison will be 24 this month.
Carter will turn 25 next month. Are they too young? We think that
around here because, in part, Bourque is 38 years old, and by
contrast everyone else looks like an outsized kindergartener. But
the truth is, they're here and they're able, and there is no time
like the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are young and they don't realize it, they have to
live it,'' said Burns. ``Some of them are perhaps saying, `I'm
young, I have a chance to do this later in my career.' Don't fool
yourself. Don't fool yourself with that. Because sometimes it can
only come by once, and while it comes by once, try to grab it, try
to jump on the train and don't miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 found the Sabres in full carpe diem mode. They stormed
the Bruins in the first period, dominating them with a fierce
forechecking game that barely allowed the Bruins to touch the puck.
The played, in captain Mike Peca's terms, ``like savage wolves.''
If not for the tidy work of Byron Dafoe in net, the Bruins could
have been trailing by a half-dozen goals after 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo attack dissipated slightly in the second period, but
the statement was made: The Sabres were stronger, faster, and far
feistier. The Bruins weren't pushing back, fighting for space,
displaying the same will to win. Bourque got flattened by a
menacing check from Alexei Zhitnik. That got the Bruins mad, but
even seeing their hallowed captain get pasted wasn't enough for
them to ratchet up their game.
</P>
<P>
   An incensed McLaren stood outside the penalty box and yakked at
Zhitnik. No fight ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zhitnik is not going to fight Kyle McLaren,'' said Burns. ``No
matter what happens, Alec Zhitnik is not going to challenge Kyle
McLaren in a duo. He'll hit Ray Bourque from behind, but he has
nothing to worry about, because nobody is going to get him. Nobody
is going to throw his gloves and go after him, because we stress
discipline and we stress emotion. We stress all these things that
you can't be.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if somebody would do that, he would be considered the most
idiotic person in the world if he did something stupid like that.
He probably would, you know, get torn apart (in the media). That's
the way it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   What would Burns think if someone did go after Zhitnik?
</P>
<P>
   Matter-of-factly, the coach said, ``I would think probably it's
a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   There is virtually no chance that this series will turn into a
donnybrook. Not now, not at 1-1. If the clinching game, be it Game
5, 6, or 7, is clearly determined with, say, 10 minutes to go, then
it could turn very ugly. Zhitnik, guaranteed, would face
retribution. It's a different game today, true, but it's still
hockey, and it's still Bourque, whose career began when pounds of
flesh were still legal tender for paying debts.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what now is about.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the Sabres is taking a carbon copy of Sunday's game plan
and tracing over every X and O. They've got all they need to know.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the Bruins is finding the guy, the big shirt, a forward
who throws his weight around, charges down the middle with elbows
flying, and belts in a goal.
</P>
<P>
   So much to ask. But also obvious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
