<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-WARCRIMES-NY     05-10 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-WARCRIMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KHMER ROUGE'S INTERROGATOR TO BE QUESTIONED BY PROSECUTORS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ The chief interrogator for the Khmer Rouge
has been taken into custody and will soon be questioned by military
prosecutors, a Cambodian government spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The interrogator, Kang Kek Ieu, who is known as Duch, his
revolutionary nickname, was put under protective custody on Sunday
as a possible witness or defendant in the deaths of more than a
million people when the Khmer Rouge held power from 1975 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military court will invite him and ask him some
questions,'' said the spokesman, Om Yentieng. ``It is normal. It is
like a doctor interviewing a patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Duch was the commandant of Tuol Sleng prison in Phnom Penh,
where at least 14,000 people were tortured and killed. He was
discovered last month by foreign journalists, working anonymously
with international aid groups in a remote area of western Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   Duch, 56, told the journalists that he had converted to
Christianity, that he knew he had done wrong and that he was
willing to testify about his own actions and those of other Khmer
Rouge leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually we slit their throats,'' Duch said in a long interview
with Nate Thayer of The Far Eastern Economic Review, which is based
in Hong Kong. ``We killed them like chickens.''
</P>
<P>
   The first case in which he could appear is that of Ta Mok, a
Khmer Rouge military leader who was captured in March and is now
also in custody in Phnom Penh. Ta Mok is awaiting charges involving
the crimes of the 1970s, and it is not clear when his trial might
begin.
</P>
<P>
   A military investigating judge assigned to that case, Gen. Ngin
Sam An, said Duch could be a ``key witness'' in that and other
potential cases. But he said no charges or detention order for Duch
had yet been filed.
</P>
<P>
   In his statements to journalists, Duch also implicated other
Khmer Rouge leaders who have been allowed to surrender and live
peacefully not far from the area where he was working. These
include Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan and Ieng Sary, three of the most
senior architects of the Khmer Rouge rule.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Hun Sen of Cambodia has been carefully
noncommittal about his plans for these men, making strong arguments
against bringing them to trial but at the same time repeating that
they had no guarantee of immunity or personal safety.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen appears to fear losing control of a volatile political
issue that could lead to widespread recriminations and possible
violence. But a diplomat said the unexpected emergence of Duch
could make it harder for the government to avoid bringing these top
leaders to trial.
</P>
<P>
   A broader question is whether any Khmer Rouge trial can be
conducted fairly in Cambodia, where the justice system is widely
viewed as corrupt and unprofessional.
</P>
<P>
   While insisting that any trial be held inside Cambodia _
contrary to advice from the United Nations _ Hun Sen has said he
would accept assistance from foreign experts. The U.N. envoy for
human rights in Cambodia, Thomas Hammarberg, arrived in Phnom Penh
on Monday to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hammarberg said he was open to discussion but that there could
be no half-measures regarding standards of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are flexible on everything except the standards,'' he said.
``The standards must be perfect. They should meet the international
standards of justice and fairness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
