<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1543 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENCE-CULTURE-HNS &LR;      05-10 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-CULTURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS VOLUNTARY RESTRAINTS ON VIOLENCE BY ENTERTAINMENT
INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton urged the nation's entertainment
industry Monday to join a voluntary, grass-roots crusade to protect
children from violence in television programs, movies, music and
video games.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton issued the broad summons to action following more than
four hours of closed-door discussions with nearly 60 entertainment
industry representatives, gun manufacturers, law enforcement
specialists, school officials, religious leaders and members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The president was joined by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton,
Vice President Al Gore and his wife Tipper Gore in outlining steps
designed to prevent any repetition of the school killings that
occurred April 20 in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that there is more for each of us to do at home and at
school, in Hollywood and in the heartland and here in Washington,''
Clinton declared in remarks in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The participants included America Online chief executive Steve
Case; poet Maya Angelou; singer Gloria Estefan; the actor Andrew
Shue, former star of ``Melrose Place''; and executives from
gunmakers Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp., Glock Inc., and O.F. Mossberg &AMP;
Sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot pretend that there is no impact on our culture and
our children that is adverse if there is too much violence coming
out of what they see and experience,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Case added: ``Everybody recognizes that they're part of the
problem. They need to be part of the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House conference followed the premeditated rampage
through Littleton's Columbine High School by two young men who
killed 12 fellow students and a teacher, and wounded more than 30
others before committing suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The killings at Columbine followed several school shootings
since 1997 that have claimed the lives of 29 students and teachers
and wounded more than 75 others.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, credited by the president with proposing the White
House conference, told the participants: ``I hope that everyone _
everyone in America _ will realize that there's a role for each of
us in trying to prevent youth violence.''
</P>
<P>
   The broad call to action included remedial measures throughout
society, from the federal government to the most intimate family
gatherings between parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations included: Greater parental involvement in
the lives of teen-agers; greater efforts to stem domestic violence;
greater investment in pre-school and after-school programs;
stronger ties between religious institutions and citizens' lives;
laws to make it more difficult for underage children to obtain
weapons; voluntary self-restraint by television executives, movie
directors and the music industry; and more teachers and counselors
in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials likened the crusade to earlier
moral-persuasion campaigns aimed at reducing the rate of teen-age
pregnancy and encouraging private industry to hire more than
400,000 welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government plans to create a nonprofit organization
to orchestrate an anti-violence effort that will include public
service advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ordered Surgeon General David Satcher to develop a
report on the causes of violence among young people that will be
delivered to the new organization _ the first such report in more
than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, said his private conversations with Hollywood directors,
producers and executives since the Colorado mass killings appeared
to be yielding results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meetings I've had so far, privately on the phone and in
person with the creative community, tell me that an increasing
number believe they can expunge from their films those elements
which they think are gratuitous _ which is defined as more than
enough,'' Valenti said after the White House conference. ``There's
not a code you can put on that because it has to be done individual
creator by individual creator _ that's as much as you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti cited the ``tenuous links'' between Hollywood
entertainment and the behavior of teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti emphasized that the power of persuasion was all that was
available to reach 500 film production companies, 10,000 screen
directors, 85,000 actors and 27 film distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all going to be volunteer,'' Valenti said. ``You can't
tell a director what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti said he warned Clinton: ``I can't guarantee that after
all the exhortation that there are not going to be movies out there
that you don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Estefan, a recording artist, said consumers can vote against
violence in entertainment with spontaneous boycotts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to buy the music,'' Estefan said. ``That's our
biggest control as consumers _ the money. Don't buy it and it's not
going to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Estefan added that students ``also have to realize their
responsibility in not allowng people that feel like outcasts to
reach out to people that feel alienated that look different.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., praised Clinton for
convening the gathering. Additional summits are needed to ``figure
out what's ailing our society and how we can correct it,'' said
Hastert, who did not take part in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that America Online, the huge Internet services
company, and the video game industry agreed at the meeting to close
a loophole that had allowed children to obtain violent video games
over the Internet that were not available to them in retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   The White House conference opened beneath a cloud of
controversy. The National Rifle Association complained that it was
not invited to the gathering. Wayne LaPierre, the NRA executive
vice president, accused the Clinton administration's inadequate
prosecution of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you start prosecution, you're never going to cut to the
culture of violence,'' LaPierre said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate Gary Bauer decried the
conference for being ``another federal feel-good forum _ lots of
talk and not much action.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by e-mail
at: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
