<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1545 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SUMMIT11-COX     05-10 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SUMMIT11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANTI-VIOLENCE MEETING A 'FOUNDATION' FOR PROGRESS, CLINTON SAYS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A White House ``strategy session'' Monday with
citizens, educators, and leaders of the media and gun industries
created ``a strong foundation (for) a national campaign to prevent
youth violence,'' President Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was exactly the kind of session I had hoped for, where
everyone was talking about the problems and the opportunities,
everyone was talking about what could be done to accept
responsibility,'' said Clinton, who called the closed-door meeting
in response to last month's school shootings in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one was pointing the finger of blame,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president and others among the five dozen participants said
the results will include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A new nonprofit organization to run the national anti-violence
education and advertising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ An update of the 1985 surgeon general's report on violence as
a public health problem.
</P>
<P>
   _ New alliances among organizations represented at the White
House session.
</P>
<P>
   Among participants who stopped on their way out of the White
House to talk to reporters, most said they felt a renewed
confidence in their own organization's approach to dampening
violence by and against teens.
</P>
<P>
   They included members of his administration and Congress,
students active in peer mediation, gun makers and a gun owner,
state and local officials, teachers, doctors, police, a judge,
clergy members, leaders of youth groups and foundations, and
leaders from the motion picture, broadcast television, cable
television, video game, Internet, music and advertising industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was most impressed with the surprising number of
people who said the ultimate burden is on the parents and local
community, and how all the rest of it has to be in support of
them,'' said actor Andrew Shue, whose Do Something Foundation works
to involve children in civic activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prevention, intervention and suppression all had support at
the meeting, which is fine with me, since I support all three,''
said the Rev. Eugene Rivers, a leader in Boston's successful
struggle against murders of young people by young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of thing can't be engineered top down by
government,'' Rivers said. ``It was helpful that the president
created a situation where the issue of the influence of the media
on violence could be discussed in a courteous and candid way, but
the real bottom line was the realization that success depends on
what parents and communities will do.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Case, chairman and chief executive officer of America
Online, the nation's largest Internet provider, said online
officials agreed at the session to work with Doug Lowenstein,
president of the trade group for video game makers, on a joint
approach to giving parents control over their children's access to
violent entertainment. Case and others are working on a new
``click-on'' parental guide for the opening page of portals on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some interested parties, including top officers of the National
Rifle Association, couldn't get invited to the session around a
U-shaped table in the East Room of the White House. At a separate
news conference, the NRA officers criticized most of the
gun-control proposals recently announced by Clinton, and said
stronger enforcement of existing laws would be a more useful
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been the constant message of the NRA to enforce the
laws that are currently on the books,'' said one of the
participants, Minneapolis Mayor Sharon Sayles Belton. ``But I think
most of us think that's only one of the many things that must be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, the American Shooting Sports Council, which
represents more than 350 gun manufacturers and importers, endorsed
some of Clinton's gun-control initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Handgun Control founder Sarah Brady said, ``I want to commend
the gun manufacturers from coming to the table, and opening a
dialogue that's not been present in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the industry leaders, only those from the movie and music
businesses declined to offer specific new efforts to avoid
encouraging violence by or against youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try for my music to be a positive influence,'' said
Cuban-American singer Gloria Estefan. But even music with
``negative'' influences can be useful to parents and society,
Estefan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to listen to our children and listen to
things that attract them, because it shows us what their frame of
mind is like,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, meanwhile, Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., said they would go ahead with their push for
legislation to create a national commission to example the causes
of youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said congressional
Republicans still intend to hold their own hearings around the
country on the same topic.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday is scheduled to begin its debate on the
juvenile justice bill. Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
has agreed to let gun control proponents propose some amendments to
that bill.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
