<HEADLINE>
REPORTER'S NOTEBOOK: SOME SEE DRAMATIC SUBTEXT IN TONY NOMINEES
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some say it signals a backlash against the British.
Others say there was simply a surfeit of good plays this season,
and those are the breaks. Still others are just scratching their
heads about why not one of David Hare's three plays _ ``Amy's
View,'' ``The Blue Room'' or ``Via Dolorosa'' _ was nominated for a
Tony Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work that he brought here this year deserves some
nomination,'' said James Freydberg, a Broadway producer. ``But this
has been a terrific play season, and sometimes wonderful things get
bypassed.''
</P>
<P>
   To Hare, who declined to be interviewed, the announcement of
Tony nominations last week apparently felt like a snub. ``He was
not consolable,'' said Roger Berlind, one of the producers who
brought ``Amy's View'' and ``The Blue Room'' from London. ``It hurt
a lot, and he's had experiences of this nature before.'' (Frank
Rich's negative review of Hare's ``Secret Rapture'' in The New York
Times in 1989 prompted him to threaten never to return to New
York.)
</P>
<P>
   This year's Hare shutout was particularly notable because, it is
generally agreed, Hare has been good for Broadway this season.
``The Blue Room'' proved the hottest ticket in town last fall, if
more for a glimpse of a nude Nicole Kidman than the drama itself,
generating welcome attention to Broadway theater. ``Amy's View,''
which is still running, brought the legendary British actress Judi
Dench back to the New York stage for the first time in 40 years.
And ``Via Dolorosa,'' the one-man play in which Hare appears
himself, was almost universally acclaimed by critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Hare has been a major contributor to the excitement on
Broadway this season,'' said Gerald Schoenfeld, chairman of the
Shubert Organization, co-producer of ``The Blue Room'' and ``Amy's
View.'' ``The idea that one playwright would have three original
plays is something you have to go into the history books to find.''
Schoenfeld called Hare's exclusion ``in league with great
oversights of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether the Tony nominators were sending a message to
British plays _ namely, ``Stay home'' _ Schoenfeld said: ``I would
imagine there are a number of Tony voters and nominators who may
have some predisposition about British theater people coming here.
I don't know of any other discipline where that exists, opera or
music or dance. It does in the theater, and it's an age-old
battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say Hare's exclusion had most to do with the strong season
for straight plays. The nominees for best play include Patrick
Marber's ``Closer,'' Tennessee Williams' ``Not About Nightingales''
and Warren Leight's ``Side Man.'' Marber, by the way, is British.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Hare is certainly one of the most prolific playwrights
on either side of the Atlantic, and it is somewhat surprising that,
given three popular productions, the nominators did not single him
out,'' said Jed Bernstein, executive director of the League of
American Theaters and Producers, which presents the Tony Awards
with the American Theater Wing. ``On the other hand, given the very
strong competition in the play category, it doesn't feel so much a
snub as an embarrassment of good choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Countering this rejection, the New York Drama Critics Circle
voted last week to give a special award to Hare for contributions
to the season. And on Sunday the Drama Desk Awards recognized Hare
for outstanding solo performance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NO FIREWORKS, REALLY
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing the Tony nominations is an annual rite on Broadway.
Because Tony awards can translate into crucial ticket sales _
particularly those for best play or best musical _ the Broadway
equivalent of Kremlinologists spend considerable energy trying to
figure out why the members of the nominating committee vote as they
do.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is made up of 28 people in the theater _ from
scenic designers to choreographers to playwrights _ who cast their
votes on May 2. But despite inevitable efforts to read between the
lines, people connected to ``that meeting'' say it was considerably
less intriguing than many suspect.
</P>
<P>
   There was no discussion of the merits of any production, no
lobbying (in contrast to the jockeying for eligibility in preceding
weeks), no effort at persuasion of any kind, they said. Boring as
it may sound, the members simply cast their sealed ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Because past meetings of the nomination committee were known to
drag on, Tony rules now limit discussion to a maximum of two hours.
</P>
<P>
   This year the committee members agreed at the outset to talk for
only an hour and wound up talking for about 15 minutes, mostly
about procedural questions. Some say several members of the
committee were frustrated by having to nominate four candidates for
best musical in a season widely considered weak in that area.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the meeting the nominators shared their views, as
they do every year, with members of the administration committee,
namely Bernstein of the league, a Broadway trade group; Roy Somlyo,
president of the American Theater Wing, which supports the theater,
and Isabelle Stevenson, chairwoman of the Theater Wing.
</P>
<P>
   Among their suggestions for the future were that the
administration committee find some way to pare the number of
performers eligible in the featured-actor rather than leading-actor
category, given that they had to decide among every cast member in
every play.
</P>
<P>
   They also requested a more realistic connection between actors'
billing and their actual contributions to a production. This year,
for example, Marian Seldes of ``Ring Round the Moon'' was nominated
for best performance by a leading actress, although she is onstage
far less than Elizabeth Franz, of ``Death of a Salesman,'' who was
nominated in the featured actress category, although she was billed
above the title.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Salesman'' successfully sought to move Ms.
Franz from the leading-actress category to the featured category
because of the competition from Ms. Dench and Zoe Wanamaker of
``Electra.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee also suggested that musicals and plays not be
lumped together for scenic design, costumes and lighting.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, which began at 5 p.m., went past 10, mostly because
the nominators had to wait for the accountants to tally each vote.
When there was a tie _ and there were four this year _ the
nominators voted again, with one committee member sitting out each
time to ensure a majority.
</P>
<P>
   THAT LIVELY GHOST
</P>
<P>
   Despite some negative fallout from the resulting nominations,
there were those who celebrated, like the creators of the musical
``Parade,'' which with nine nominations received more than any
other production. The show, which recounted the 1915 lynching of
Leo Frank, a Jewish factory supervisor in Georgia, closed in
February after two months.
</P>
<P>
   Poetic justice? ``I feel terrific about it,'' said Harold
Prince, billed as the show's director and co-conceiver. ``I wish we
were running.''
</P>
<P>
   High-minded talk about artistic excellence notwithstanding, the
Tony Awards are considered a crucial marketing tool. As a result
there is some question as to whether the voters will want to give a
best-musical award to a show not in a position to reap the
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Prince said he hoped the voters considered more than the box
office. ``There has to be some attention paid to the future of
musical form and the next generation of composers and dealing with
unique subjects and not just falling into a pit of
predictability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prince said that if it were not for the financial travails of
Livent Inc., co-producer of ``Parade'' with Lincoln Center Theater,
the show would still be alive. Livent ``defaulted a really
substantial sum _ in not-for-profit theater terms, an enormous
sum,'' Prince said. ``And that's the sum that would have kept the
show running till now and would have paid for advertising.''
</P>
</TEXT>
