<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HMO-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT PUTS MEDICARE-HMO CRISIS IN NEW LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When dozens of health maintenance organizations
abruptly abandoned Medicare last year and left 400,000
beneficiaries scrambling for coverage, the HMOs blamed federal
payment rates.
</P>
<P>
   But a new congressional study found that Medicare reimbursement
was only part of the problem and that competition, profit and
market conditions were significant factors as well.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the review by the General Accounting Office noted
that insurers continue to show strong interest in serving Medicare
beneficiaries via HMOs, signaling that the federal government may
yet be successful in expanding the availability of managed care to
older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is premature to conclude that Medicare Plus Choice must be
radically revised to ensure the success of Medicare managed care,''
said the GAO study, referring to the name Congress gave the HMO
initiative created in 1997. The report suggested that the HMO
crisis of last year mainly reflected a shakeout in the
still-evolving health care market.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't seem like a simple market correction last fall
when HMOs began dropping patients around the country just as the
Health Care Financing Administration was launching its effort to
put more seniors into managed care programs.
</P>
<P>
   All told, 45 health plans dropped their Medicare contracts
outright and 54 others withdrew from selected counties, forcing
400,000 beneficiaries to find a new HMO or go back into traditional
fee-for-service Medicare. About 61,000 consumers had no choice but
to go back to standard Medicare since their counties were left with
no HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Many beneficiaries were not pleased with that prospect since the
HMOs offered extra benefits like prescription drug coverage and
eliminated the need to buy supplemental Medicare insurance. In
short, going back to Medicare meant higher out-of-pocket health
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional offices were deluged with complaints, Florida
officials launched a statewide investigation, and the health
insurers and federal health officials began trading accusations
over who was at fault.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers said federal attempts to cut Medicare spending in
the 1997 balanced budget plan had driven them out; federal health
authorities said the insurers were trying to squeeze out excess
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted with the conflicting claims, Congress asked the GAO
to step in and investigate.
</P>
<P>
   In the resulting report, the GAO investigators said the
situation is not as grim as it first appeared since health insurers
continue to apply for the right to provide managed care. Ten plans
have been approved this year and 30 applications are pending,
including some for areas that do not now have managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If HCFA approves all of the pending plans and service area
expansions, slightly more beneficiaries will have access to a
managed care plan in 1999 than in 1998,'' said the report.
</P>
<P>
   As for the withdrawals, the review said they were due to several
factors, including payment level. While HMOs were more likely to
pull out of counties that had lower payments, they left counties
with high reimbursement rates as well.
</P>
<P>
   GAO investigators said a chief reason insurers pulled back ``may
have been the result of plans deciding that they were unable to
compete effectively in certain areas'' due to an inability to line
up a strong network of doctors, lack of experience in a community
or the presence of a larger competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials took issue with the report, insisting that
low reimbursement rates in some counties _ coupled with new
red-tape requirements instituted by HCFA _ made operating in some
areas impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shakeout thing doesn't fly with me,'' said Chip Kahn,
president of the Health Insurance Association of America. ``In some
cases, I think there just wasn't enough money there.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on past Medicare spending in a community, payment rates to
HMOs fluctuate by county from a low of $380 per enrollee to as high
as $694. HMOs continue to be more heavily concentrated in counties
with the higher rates and presently serve about 6.7 million
beneficiaries nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Federal health officials welcomed the report as vindication.
They argued repeatedly before Congress that the reimbursement
levels were sufficient and that HMOs were trying to shift
responsibility for leaving their customers in the lurch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agree with the report's major findings,'' said Nancy-Ann
Min DeParle, the Medicare chief, in a written statement. ``We are
committed to providing Medicare beneficiaries with the choices
envisioned by the Congress in this important, new program.''
</P>
<P>
   The real test may be yet to come. Insurance companies have until
July 1 to inform Medicare whether they will remain in the HMO
business, a deadline that will make it clear what direction the
managed care push is heading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would still define what happened as a bump in the road,''
said Kahn about last year's pullouts. ``We will know in July or
next year whether the road will get bumpier or whether it was a
one- or two-year phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
