<SLUG> BC-DIET-DRUG-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS WORRY OVER EASY ACCESS TO NEW DIET DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some promoters are already treating it as the next magic potion
for fighting obesity. And though orlistat, a diet pill approved for
sale in this country two weeks ago and marketed under the brand
name Xenical, is available only by prescription, it is being made
easily available. That worries many health specialists, who say the
drug might produce bad reactions or other problems if misused.
</P>
<P>
   A company based in the British Channel Islands called Direct
Response Marketing is selling Xenical over the Internet to just
about anybody who fills out an electronic form. ``This wonder pill
promises to be one of the defining drugs of the '90s along with
Prozac and Viagra,'' the company states on its World Wide Web site.
``Most overweight people harbor a sneaking suspicion that somewhere
there is a product that will solve all their weight-loss problems.
Well, now that product has arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators say that such marketing is legal in most
states if a doctor somewhere signs off on the prescription. They
are worried about such Internet sales pitches but are unsure
exactly what to do about them.
</P>
<P>
   A physician in Los Angeles who had nearly 900 patients on the
wildly popular mix of diet medication known as fen-phen before it
was pulled off the market in 1997 says Xenical may help bring some
of his customers back. The doctor, Ben Krentzman, who himself
weighs 400 pounds, says he believes the drug is harmless and he
sees no need to stick to the regulatory guidelines for who should
take it, though he adds that initially he will do so.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Tison, a psychiatrist in Sacramento, Calif., who devoted
his entire practice to fen-phen, buying it wholesale and dispensing
it to thousands of patients, said he had already written 60
prescriptions for Xenical and could not keep up with the demand.
``My appointment book is pretty full.''
</P>
<P>
   Such signs are pointing to an explosion in popularity like that
last seen in the fen-phen craze of the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The new drug does not work the way fen-phen did. Fen-phen was an
appetite suppressant; Xenical is the first anti-obesity medication
that blocks the body's absorption of dietary fat. And while
fenfluramine and its sister drug dexfenfluramine _ the ``fen'' in
fen-phen _ were recalled after studies showed they might cause
heart-valve defects, no evidence has emerged of dangerous side
effects associated with Xenical.
</P>
<P>
   But fen-phen and Xenical are alike in one crucial way: their
appeal as a potential quick fix for excess fat. More than half of
adult Americans are overweight, and many are desperate to shed
pounds. An estimated six million Americans took fenfluramine or
dexfenfluramine, bringing manufacturers tens of millions in profits
_ and Xenical is looking equally lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate that the market could quickly grow to $3
billion a year, although the drug's limited effectiveness and
unpleasant side effects may make consumers move on to something
else. At least for now, however, ``this has the potential to be a
Viagra-type product in a different field,'' said Ira Loss, an
analyst with HSBC Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as there is a lifelong search for the fountain of
youth,'' he said, ``there is a lifelong search for an easy way to
lose weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some health care professionals and advocates for the
obese worry that many Americans will start popping Xenical without
giving adequate consideration to the costs, benefits and side
effects. ``Misuse will happen for a couple of reasons,'' said Lynn
McAfee, a spokeswoman for the Council on Size and Weight
Discrimination. ``There is just so much money to be made out there
and so much desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   The costs come to about $4 or $5 a day, and insurers are
unlikely to pick up the tab. The benefits are limited; tests showed
patients lost 5 to 10 percent of their weight after taking Xenical
for a year in combination with a reduced-calorie diet.
</P>
<P>
   The most common side effects are bloating, flatulence and oily
stool, diarrhea and fecal incontinence, all of which the
manufacturer says can be minimized by reducing fat intake. But
Xenical also blocks absorption of the fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E
and K, as well as beta-carotene, and so patients must take daily
vitamin supplements.
</P>
<P>
   The Council on Size and Weight Discrimination fears that some
users will not do that, and also worries that people with eating
disorders like bulimia, in which laxatives sometimes are used to
purge food from the system, might be attracted to Xenical.
</P>
<P>
   Health care experts fret about the potential risks of
prescribing the drug with other medications in combinations that
have neither been studied by the manufacturer nor approved by the
Food and Drug Administration. Already, Xenical is being called
xen-phen because some doctors have said they will use it with
phentermine, the still-available half of fen-phen, or with Merida,
a recently approved prescription appetite suppressant.
</P>
<P>
   Creating such drug cocktails could lead to adverse effects. ``I
don't like that, and I wouldn't do it,'' said Dr. Jules Hirsch, an
obesity expert at Rockefeller University in Manhattan who served on
the FDA advisory panel on Xenical. Hirsch said he voted against
approving the drug because of its limited effectiveness. The
public, Hirsch added, should ``remember combinations before that
have been particularly bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman-LaRoche Inc., the pill's manufacturer, says Xenical is
only meant to be used by the most seriously obese people who are
under a doctor's care. The company, based in Nutley, N.J., also
said Xenical should be used only as one component of a complete
weight-loss program. ``What we are providing now is a new tool to
be added to counseling, better nutrition and exercise that we hope
will allow people to better manage their disease for the long
run,'' said Patrick J. Zenner, president and chief executive of
Hoffman-LaRoche, a unit of Swiss-based Roche Holdings Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that many dispensers of the drug are already
treating it as a cure-all. And others say that with no known
serious side effects to the drug, there is little reason to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Take Krentzman, the 400-pound obesity expert who lost most of
his business after the fen-phen fiasco. He recently updated his Web
site to include his price for Xenical, and he says he may
eventually prescribe it to patients who do not fit the guidelines
set by the manufacturer and the FDA. Krentzman also said he was
considering prescribing Xenical in combination with other
medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drug works in the interior of the gut _ it never gets
into the bloodstream _ so what harm can it do to you?'' Krentzman
said. ``If it is none, what's the reason to restrict it?''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty, say health care experts, who note that the effects of
untested drug combinations are often not known until problems arise
later.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
