<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR CAMPAIGN IS SHORT ON LEGALITY, MORALITY, LOGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A compelling letter arrived last week, one not meant
for a journalist's eyes. It was sent by a member of one of our
country's elite military units, who is stationed in the Balkans, to
a relative in Arizona, who passed it on to me.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier believes that our air attack against Serbia is
illegal, immoral and illogical. He didn't know his letter would be
given to a columnist, however, and publicizing it could have the
unhappy consequence of a court-martial.
</P>
<P>
   So I won't quote him. But since my Army service ended three
decades ago, I'll violate no regulations by quoting myself. His
views and mine happen to run parallel.
</P>
<P>
   The war is legally dubious because under international law, one
nation does not have a right to intervene militarily in the
internal affairs of another nation. The United Nations' charter
allows for exceptions, such as responding to crimes against
humanity, but the U.N. wasn't asked to legalize this war. If we're
willing to ignore international law to destroy Serbia, should we
expect other nations to behave differently?
</P>
<P>
   We're on shaky moral ground because most of the people our bombs
have killed or maimed aren't responsible for the crimes in Kosovo
we have sought to prevent.
</P>
<P>
   The moral question is addressed in Christian theology's ``just
war'' theory, developed by St. Augustine in the fifth century and
refined by St. Thomas Aquinas.
</P>
<P>
   The theory says for war to be morally defensible, it must have a
just cause, be declared by a legitimate authority, be a last
resort, have a good intention, allow for the protection of the
innocent and achieve more good than harm.
</P>
<P>
   How many civilians can NATO bombs kill before the attack loses
moral legitimacy? How much ``collateral damage'' can we tolerate in
the name of doing good?
</P>
<P>
   Our war strategy is illogical because the means we've chosen are
poorly suited to achieving our goals.
</P>
<P>
   We've tried to stop highly dispersed paramilitary units in
mountainous terrain with bombs dropped from 15,000 feet, and _
surprise! _ it doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   NATO wants to protect the Kosovars and punish those who violate
their human rights, but the attack has devastated Serbia to the
tune of more than $100 billion while barely affecting the purge of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Because their news media are government-controlled, most Serbs
know little about what their government has directed. They know
only that the Kosovo Liberation Army has waged a terrorism campaign
for years. They believe, and I agree, that some kind of military
response by Belgrade was justified. They've not been told the
response entailed atrocities and the expulsion of 700,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   If the Serbs could learn the truth, they would be less likely to
go along with Slobodan Milosevic. But instead of giving them
information, we've dropped bombs for seven weeks that have turned
them against America rather than their government.
</P>
<P>
   While we have degraded Serbia's ability to make war, we've also
flattened the country's economy and made life much tougher for
civilians. Our bombs have hurt average people more than the masked
murderers in the villages of Kosovo or the ruthless nationalists
ruling in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The argument against sending in ground troops is that it will
risk too many NATO lives. But if the war's ends are just, such
risks are part of the price.
</P>
<P>
   That's easy for me to say; neither I nor anyone in my family
would be putting a life on the line. It's less easy for a soldier
who would stand a good chance of being among the first assigned.
</P>
<P>
   That was the best part of his letter.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote about how much he misses his wife and young son. How he
hopes to teach him how to fly a kite and take apart alarm clocks.
How his heart's desire is to spend a long life with his family and
never see war.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he would rather be sent into Kosovo to try to save lives
than watch the air campaign kill more innocent people and pulverize
their country.
</P>
<P>
   I'm impressed that his military sense of duty doesn't obscure
his moral conscience.
</P>
<P>
   I hope he makes it home safely. His boy is nearly old enough to
fly his first kite. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at steve.wilson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
