<HEADER>
A1565 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIET-DRUG-ART-2NDTAKE     05-10 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIET-DRUG-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: arise later. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In another practice that concerns some of the health care
experts, Direct Response Marketing, which is selling the drug on
the Internet, has few safeguards to verify exactly who its
customers are. The company requires what it calls a medical
consultation, which simply amounts to answering health-related
questions by computer, agreeing to the terms of a disclaimer and
plugging in a credit card number.
</P>
<P>
   One option on the online form, which the company says is
reviewed by its doctors, even allows customers to conceal the use
of the drug from their physicians. They simply click on a box
saying ``I do not want DRM to advise my doctor, and I take full
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Direct Response Marketing, which said it had already received
thousands of orders from customers in the United States, insisted
there was nothing wrong with its marketing tactics or its
customer-screening process. It also said it had turned away some
potential customers because of their responses to its questions.
</P>
<P>
   But just how does the company insure that it is not selling to a
16-year-old or someone with an eating disorder? ``That is something
we have no control over,'' said Tom O'Brien, managing director of
the company, who also said that most teen-agers do not have credit
cards. ``If someone really wants to lie, they can get hold of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the FDA and the Federal Trade Commission acknowledge that
they have been caught off guard by the surge in the sale of
prescription drugs on the Internet _ and cannot even agree which
agency has jurisdiction in regulating the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has sort of taken us to a place and at a pace
that we've got to do some rethinking about the traditional
regulatory models,'' said Rich Cleland, senior staff attorney at
the FTC. The problem is compounded when the seller, the buyer and
the doctor who reviews ``medical consultations'' are in different
states or countries.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line? ``People going on line without a prescription
are taking a gamble,'' said Jeffery Shuren, a medical officer at
the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some physicians and weight-loss companies _
including the Weight Watchers International unit of H.J. Heinz Co.
and Jennie Craig Inc. _ decline to dispense fat-fighting
medications. Even so, the new drug's profit potential is too great
for some chains to ignore altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The Diet Workshop in Boston used to prescribe fen-phen at its
clinics, but said it had discontinued the drug approach. That is
not to say its employees turn away people who want Xenical or other
diet pills. They simply send them to Philemon Marvell, a local
doctor. It so happens that Marvell is one of Diet Workshop's
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is part of Diet Workshop, so he is going to ask those
members to continue the behavior-modification program as well,''
said Jane Shannon, a sales supervisor at the company. Marvell and
other Diet Workshop officials did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   The Council on Size and Weight Discrimination says that
weight-loss clinics should not be associated with diet pills at all
and that doctors who aggressively seek people who want Xenical or
other drugs are exploiting the public. Unfortunately, McAfee, the
council's spokesman, said: ``Xenical is not in Fort Knox with a
fence around it. Any doctor can whip out a prescription pad, write
it and people will buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman-LaRoche, which has 2,000 sales representatives marketing
Xenical to doctors, nutritionists and weight-loss centers, said it
was not promoting the drug as a panacea. ``This is not a magic
bullet,'' Zenner said.
</P>
<P>
   On that point, the company and the Council on Size and Weight
Discrimination agree. And it is all the more reason, McAfee said,
that consumers should not rush to take Xenical.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to consumers,'' she said, ``is if they don't have a
desperate medical need, don't buy a diet drug or a new car in the
first model year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
