<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON MAN BUYS SHOTGUN USED IN O.K. CORRAL BATTLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Houston man purchased Doc Holliday's O.K.
Corral, 10-gauge, sawed-off double barreled shotgun last weekend
for $220,000, thousands more than what was expected.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Peavy, an appraiser with Attorney's Appraisal Associates
in Houston, purchased the shotgun, along with Annie Oakley's Smith
&AMP; Wesson silver engraved pistol for $37,000, U.S. Marshal Heck
Thomas' 1877 .38-caliber Colt Lightning for $42,000, and Thomas'
1877 .38-caliber Colt Sheriff's Model Lightning for $42,000, at the
24th Annual Firearm, Art, Western and Indian Relic Auction in
Pflugerville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every gun was not purchased because it is a gun, but it was
purchased because of its historical value,'' Peavy said.
</P>
<P>
   The shotgun was used by Holliday at the battle in which
Holliday, Wyatt Earp and two of Earp's brothers faced off against
the Ike Clanton gang in 1881 in Tombstone, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Peavy purchased the guns and other artifacts for another Houston
man, who wishes to remain anonymous. The two men plan to open a
museum, though Peavy said he doesn't know when and where the museum
will open.
</P>
<P>
   But Peavy did say the museum would not be for commercial
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a place for the state of Texas,'' he said.
``We started our collection Sunday and will continue shopping.
We're acquiring the very best.''
</P>
<P>
   Peavy said he and his partner plan to shop at more auctions,
hoping to build an admirable collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This won't be just another gun or artifact museum, but a
museum of important identifiable items from famous Indians, lawmen
and outlaws,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Keilman of Tom Keilman &AMP; Son Auctioneers, which conducted
the auction, said the 1,500 items auctioned over a three-day period
brought a little more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The previous owner of the huge collection, David Hall of
Illinois, said he will use the money for his retirement and to buy
more historical artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, an author and historian, recently announced his retirement
and the immediate sale of his old West artifacts after 62 years of
collecting. Keilman said Hall contacted him four months ago, eager
to sell his collection of antique weapons, photographs, law
enforcement badges and historical documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an auction of a lifetime,'' Keilman said. ``We sell
history and we sold a lot of it this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
