<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-DISPUTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SPEAKER'S WASHINGTON KEEPSAKES CAN REMAIN IN TEXAS FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A custody fight over an ancient Grecian urn, which
pitted Congress against a small-town Texas museum, is nearing an
end, and it looks like the urn is staying in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,500-year-old urn, valued at nearly $3 million, is one of
the most notable items in a long list of furniture and other
artifacts that were removed from the Capitol by former House
speakers when Democrats controlled the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Republicans took over in 1995, the House
Administration Committee launched an effort to track down and
reclaim the missing property. The disputed items included former
Speaker Jim Wright's office furnishings, now on display at Texas
Christian University in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wright assured the House that he was willing part with
a couch, a display case, a credenza and a small table, officials at
the Sam Rayburn Library and Museum in Bonham, Texas, in North Texas
contested Congress' claim to the urn and other items in its
collection.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's showcase display includes the original marble
speaker's rostrum, a crystal chandelier from the Capitol and a
fireplace mantel that came to the Capitol from the White House.
Rayburn began shipping the items to Texas a few years before his
retirement in 1961 after nearly two decades in the top House job.
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials contend that the urn was Rayburn's personal
property because it was a gift from the government of Greece. The
former speaker snared the historic rostrum when the chamber was
remodeled during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   In a compromise engineered by Rep. Kay Granger, R-Texas, House
leaders have agreed to let the disputed items stay where they are
as long as they are available for public viewing. Granger convinced
Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois that the public would be better
served by keeping the items on display at various locations around
the country than by returning them to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Hastert, Granger said Rayburn's display is ``very
important for the thousands of families from Texas and around the
United States who come to Bonham to learn about American history.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement would also apply to relics that were removed by
former Speaker Tom Foley, who now serves as ambassador to Japan,
and to the collections of deceased Speakers Thomas P. ``Tip''
O'Neill of Massachusetts, Carl Albert of Oklahoma and John
McCormack of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it's on public display, such as Rayburn's stuff is,
it should work out,'' said John Feehery, Hastert's spokesman.
``We're still working on guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Feehery said House officials hope to come up with a final
agreement this week that would resolve the dispute with the former
speakers and clarify the rules for Hastert and future speakers.
Former Speaker Newt Gingrich, who resigned last year, did not take
his office furniture with him, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   A Wright aide and the director of Rayburn's museum said they
were waiting for official word on the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they'll work it all out,'' museum director H.G.
Dulaney said. ``Surely, after 41 years, they won't be coming down
here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1902EDT &QL; 
