<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DUCHESS JOINS EMERSON AND THOREAU
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The always industrious and always strapped for cash  &UR; Duchess &LR; 
 &UR; of York  &LR; is at work on a novel, which will be published by Simon &AMP;
Schuster, reports the Mirror of London. The Duchess' agent,  &UR; Al
Lowman &LR;  of Authors and Artists group, told the British newspaper
that the writing is ``now in progress'' but the book will be ``very
transcendental.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the literary dictionary on our desk, the
Transcendentalists ``relied on their own intuitions as the only
guide to the comprehension of reality.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with that spirit,  &UR; Queen Elizabeth II  &LR; has had boots
custom-made for her corgis, reports the Sunday Times of London,
because gravel pathways at Buckingham Palace were giving them paw
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, &UR; Prince Charles &LR;  will pay about $80,000 to a former
employee who claimed she was sexually harassed by one of the
prince's aides. The settlement, which will come from the prince's
private money, means that he won't have to testify in court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A CHANGE OF MIND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an interview conducted months ago, but apparently timed for
publication to coincide with the opening of ``Star Wars,''
 &UR; Liam Neeson &LR;  told Redbook magazine he'd had it with making movies.
``I'm getting out,'' he said. ``I'm retiring from movies next year.
Honest to God, I don't want to do it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   By this week, however, Neeson said he didn't mean it. ``It was
something that came up from finishing a long period of work on
stage and on film. ... It's not true. I was just venting a bit of
anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeson had said that ``Film is a director's medium. It has
nothing to do with actors. We are basically puppets, walking
around, hitting marks, saying lines. Producers earn all the money,
and you get the sense that they hate actors.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Perusing the third edition of ``EveryWoman's Health,''
published in 1985, &UR; Shirley Rae Parks  &LR; finds it a book ahead of its
time. A section on sexual fantasies describes the pleasure of
getting exactly what one wants in the fantasy world, ``seducing the
president on the floor of the Oval Room in the White House,'' for
example.
</P>
<P>
   _ Visiting Albania, House Majority Leader  &UR; Richard Armey &LR; ,
R-Texas, requested to hold an American soldier's rifle, reports
Roll Call. ``No, sir,'' said the soldier. Armey asked agin,
several times, but the soldier held fast to his refusal. ``We're
not supposed to let our weapons get very far from us,'' he told the
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seventh graders at East Christian School in Kalamazoo, Mich.,
were asked to write a paper about a role model; send it to the role
model; and ask the role model for a pair of shoes in which the
student could walk. The only two who responded were Supreme Court
Justice  &UR; Sandra Day O'Connor &LR; , who sent a pair, size 8 1/2, and
jazz musician  &UR; Wynton Marsalis &LR; , who sent a pair, size 9.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Wall Street Journal noted that the subject to be discussed
at yesterday's dinner of the charter chapter of the American
Business Women's Association in New York: ``The Art of Business
Dressing: How YOU can look 10 Pounds Thinner!''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Nature Conservancy is selling $31.50 silk ties made by
Mulberry Neckwear in San Rafael and designed to reflect patterns of
nature, as part of an environmental fund-raising project. The ties
will be on sale in the Bay Area at Macy's and Bloomingdale's.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lot 6, an original typed  &UR; Herb Caen  &LR; column from April 1995 _
donated by Caen's assistant,  &UR; Carole Vernier &LR;  _ fetched $900 at
Saturday night's Telegraph Hill Neighborhood Center fund-raising
auction. The auction raised about $80,000 for the social service
agency, good news for the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Up the hill, however, &UR; Mark Bittner &LR; , the wild parrot man who has
to move and abandon his birds in a few weeks, still hasn't found
new digs. Neighbors are concerned enough that they're hoping this
mention might find him a place _ no matter how modest _ to live.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spa Radiance has announced that actress  &UR; Embeth Davidtz &LR; , who
is shooting ``Bicentennial Man'' with &UR; Robin Williams &LR; , stopped by
for a ``state of the art resurfacing skin treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tattoos are the ultimate compliment for a cartoonist.
However, I have mixed feelings when the people showing me their
tattoos have the characters' names misspelled.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt Groening, creator of ``The Simpsons'' and ``Futurama,''
quoted in Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
