<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-NYT &LR;      05-10 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU'S SPENDING PLAN HELPS POLITICS BUT NOT ECONOMICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ One week before the May 17 election, Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu is scoring political points but dismaying budget
officials with new spending plans for roads and Jewish housing in
Arab-dominated eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The announced new spending plans have came as economists here
predicted that slower than expected growth would cut deeply into
tax revenues and further increase both unemployment and the budget
deficit this year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of his finance minister, Netanyahu persuaded
his Cabinet on Sunday to approve a potentially costly program of
$5,000 cash grants for Israeli home-buyers in the state-subsidized
``new neighborhoods'' of annexed East Jerusalem. He also secured
Cabinet support for a $100 million grant to the city government for
``infrastructural improvements'' in eastern Jerusalem over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's opponents in the Labor Party filed a formal
complaint denouncing the Jerusalem spending plans as ``election
bribery'' and noting that there are no surplus funds to pay for the
programs. And Netanyahu's budget advisers were equally outspoken in
their complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Meir Sheetrit, appointed three months ago as the government's
fourth finance minister in two and half years, joined his
ministry's senior civil servants in protesting that the programs
would bloat a deficit that is already exceeding its targeted limit
of 2 percent of gross domestic product. Finance officials, noting
that the plans are not in the recently approved 1999 budget, have
expressed concern about the impact of unfinanced programs on
already skittish local financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   As is usual with closed-door Israeli Cabinet sessions, local
press reports gave blow-by-blow, quote-by-quote accounts of the
acrimonious and theoretically confidential proceedings. Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon and other hard-liners reportedly accused the
budget staff of having ``political motives'' for their objections.
Mayor Ehud Olmert of Jerusalem, a chief beneficiary of the programs
and an expected challenger for the Likud Party leadership should
Netanyahu fail to win re-election, accused finance officials of
``abusing their positions as civil servants.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheetrit said Monday he still opposed the East Jerusalem housing
subsidies, but blasted subordinates for voicing complaints to the
press. ``I confined my objections and my protest to the Cabinet
session,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu told reporters as he left Sunday's meeting, ``Finance
ministers never want to give out money _ that's usual.''
</P>
<P>
   But there may be no money left to give out, economists here
warn. Tax receipts for the year's first quarter were down 7 percent
from last year's revenue, and newly revised forecasts for 1999 have
only made budget officials gloomier.
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth is expected to slow to 1.5 percent, down from an
already anemic 2.2 percent in 1998, according to Bank Hapoalim, a
leading commercial bank. Export income is sinking, with no
offsetting foreign investment, swelling the current account deficit
from $2.3 billion last year to a projected $3 billion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But the most crucial economic number in this campaign is the
unemployment rate. At 8.7 percent, it is already at its highest
level in a generation. And it will rise to 9 percent later this
year, the bank's economic department predicted, regardless of which
party takes power in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our economic forecast for 1999 assumes that it will only be
possible to prevent negative trends from worsening,'' the Bank
Hapoalim report said, so there would be no quick turnaround. The
Labor Party, unsurprisingly disagreeing, promises to embark
immediately on a program to create 300,000 new jobs in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not just the amount of the deficit, but how
they cut the cake,'' said Dov Lautman, the chairman of Delta Galil
Industries and one of Labor's leading business supporters. ``Monies
are going in the wrong direction, in my opinion. They should be
going to job creation, to infrastructure, and education.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, the focus of the Netanyahu government's new
spending plans, unemployment is below the national average,
hovering around 7 percent. The most severe joblessness _ averaging
10 percent and higher _ is found in the new so-called development
towns of the southern and eastern deserts, populated by the recent
Russian immigrants and working-class Sephardic Jews who have been
Likud's core constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Labor strategists hope Netanyahu's emphasis on Jerusalem as
economic duress elsewhere increases will help them make inroads
into those communities. But some experts are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a treasury minister resists the prime minister just a
week before the election, it is an indication of how many problems
Netanyahu has with his own government,'' said Ira Sharkansky, a
Hebrew University specialist in the political economy of Israel.
``But I don't think economic performance is the weakest link in
Likud's world: The poor vote for Likud, and yuppies and big
business leaders vote for Labor. It's a peculiar combination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
