<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; PERSONAL FINANCE BUD &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; TRACKING _  &LR; In school you learned that the whole is equal to the
sum of its parts. The folks on Wall Street insist that sometimes it
can be more than that. That's why a financial instrument called
tracking stock is becoming popular. It is designed to unleash the
market potential of promising subsidiaries whose value might not be
fully reflected in the price of a parent company's stock. It works
much like a spin-off, except that the assets are not actually spun
off. They remain part of the parent company. By Arthur M. Louis
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAILBAG  &LR; _ Arthur Louis' mailbag column on personal finance.
</P>
