<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTER PARTY CANDIDATE REFUSES TO BOW OUT OF PRIME MINISTER'S RACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Yitzhak Mordechai, the Center Party candidate for
prime minister who blazed onto the Israeli political scene, is
fading in the polls but refusing to bow out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Polls that once showed him garnering support from one in five
voters _ high for a first-time candidate _ now give him less than
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The plummet in popularity has put him under pressure to pull out
and throw his political weight behind Ehud Barak, the opposition
Labor Party candidate who is running as the head of a coalition
called One Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But with only eight days left before the elections take place
May 17, Mordechai has said he is in the race for the duration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's staying in the race,'' said Menashe Raz, spokesman for
Mordechai. ``He believes that he has to keep his promise to his
voters and to keep the party together.''
</P>
<P>
   An immensely popular former defense minister sacked by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu last winter, Mordechai's stated goal
when he joined three other disgruntled Likud Party members to form
the Center Party was to bring Netanyahu down.
</P>
<P>
   His election campaign, full of swipes at Netanyahu, was geared
to steal votes away from the prime minister's center-right
constituents. Political pundits predicted early on that he would
eventually pull out of the race and call on his followers to vote
for Barak.
</P>
<P>
   By last week, when polls started showing Mordechai's popularity
had sunk to between 5 and 7 percent, the former military man
stubbornly held on.
</P>
<P>
   An advertisement in Sunday's Hebrew daily Ma'ariv, paid for by
an organization calling itself People Who Care About the Country's
Future, called on Barak and Mordechai to join forces ``for peace,
for economy, for security ... for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Yossi Beilin, a leading Labor Party member, wrote in
a local newspaper that ``it would be much more respectable for
Mordechai to join forces with the camp which will replace Netanyahu
than trying to prove to Netanyahu what a man he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of pulling out, Mordechai has attacked the polls as
``biased.'' His party has dropped the slogan ``Only Mordechai can
beat Bibi big.'' Polls found 71 percent of Israelis had disagreed
with the phrase.
</P>
<P>
   The big question now is whether Mordechai's decision to continue
to run will do more harm than good to Barak's election chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the Mordechai voters are disgruntled Netanyahu
voters,'' said Reuven Hazan, a political analyst at Jerusalem's
Hebrew University. ``If they all go home (to Likud), then by him
pulling out of the race, he'll hurt Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those voters make the leap and vote for Barak, then by
pulling out, he'll hurt Netanyahu,'' Hazan said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls taken last week found the Labor Party candidate leading
Netanyahu by eight percentage points _ 43 percent to 35 percent _
with Mordechai in the race. Without Mordechai, those same polls
showed support for Barak rising to 50 percent _ almost the minimum
needed to prevent a run-off.
</P>
<P>
   If no candidate gets a simple majority of the votes _ 50 percent
plus one vote _ Israel will hold a second round of elections June
1.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's rise in the polls reflects a wide base of support. A
party of religious moderates and one of Jews from Arab countries
have joined his Labor Party, traditionally made up of Ashkenazi
Jewish elites, to form the One Israel ticket. He also has increased
support among new immigrants from the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said Netanyahu has an interest in seeing Mordechai
stay in the race. Already, some of his campaign ads have focused on
calling on Netanyahu voters who have gone over to Mordechai to come
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Netanyahu succeeds in preventing Labor from winning in the
first round, it will energize many of his people,'' said Efraim
Inbar, a political analyst at the Besa Center for Strategic Studies
at Bar Ilan University. ``At least this will give his people a
second chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inbar said Mordechai, a career army officer appointed to all
three Israeli regional commands, may be motivated in part by an
unwillingness to accept defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took on a mission, and he's going on until the end,'' Inbar
said. ``He doesn't want to admit failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, he said, hasn't made it easy for Mordechai to come over
to the Labor camp. Instead, he has humiliated Mordechai by telling
him he has no chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   If Mordechai pulls out now, Center Party members fear the party
will suffer. And many believe that Barak will do better in a second
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is that the party can fall apart if (Mordechai)
pulls out of the race now,'' said Mordechai's spokesman Raz.
``Netanyahu's voters from 1996 who will vote for Mordechai in the
first round will find it easier to vote for Barak on the second
round.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
