u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-SASSER-5     05-10 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-SASSER-572&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING PROTESTS HAVE MADE U.S. AMBASSADOR A PRISONER IN HIS OWN
EMBASSY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-CHINA, KOSOVO-CHINA-TRADE) 
(nk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ For the last three years, Ambassador James Sasser has
toiled to build relations between China and the United States, an
unflagging optimist about the potential for two such different
countries to be friends.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three days, he has been a virtual prisoner in his
embassy office building, surrounded by angry protesters just
outside the gates, many of them hurling rocks, eggs and tomatoes
and calling for vengeance for the NATO bombing early Saturday of
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   When the protesters arrived Saturday afternoon, he was working
in his office. Since then, he has not changed his clothes or
showered. He has been eating freeze-dried military rations and
sleeping without blankets on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I can leave safely,'' he said Monday, in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   And, although Chinese officials have assured him that he and
other foreigners would be safe, he added: ``I'm not sure they fully
appreciate what's happening on the ground in front of our
embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   The low point of the ordeal, he said, came on Sunday morning
when he and other employees began destroying sensitive documents in
preparation for abandoning the building, fearing that raging
protesters were about to overwhelm the double row of police
officers and stream through the gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was pushing the police back _ they looked tired _
and these young police were frantically calling for
reinforcements,'' Sasser said. ``We thought the odds were 50-50
they were coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later he got a call from his wife, who was
similarly stuck a couple of blocks away in the ambassador's
residence, with their 30-year-old son, Gray, and four house guests
from Houston. Protesters who had been throwing rocks from the
residence's distant front gate had discovered that the house was
just feet from an unguarded side wall, and had started lobbing
concrete chunks into the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night protesters threw two gasoline bombs through the
embassy's broken windows, igniting fires that marine guards put out
with extinguishers.
</P>
<P>
   Sasser said he had little success reaching Chinese officials to
complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disturbing thing is that Saturday and Sunday we couldn't
get any high-level Chinese and were just talking to on-duty
officers at the Foreign Ministry,'' he said. ``Finally in utter
frustration I called Li Zhaoxing, the Chinese ambassador to
Washington, and got him out of bed at 3:30 in the morning, to ask
him to help.`
</P>
<P>
   Sasser said the protests at the embassy office building Monday
seemed somewhat less intense, although on occasion rocks and chunks
of concrete poured down like rain.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn Monday Mrs. Sasser escaped from the residence compound,
after someone called from a cell phone to say that the protesters,
who thin out considerably at night, had withdrawn. She grabbed her
dog, Lucky, and his insulin. Then she and the others simply walked
out of the compound to a nearby apartment complex for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sit in the dark and you hear this endless crashing and you
don't know how long it's going to last,'' said Mrs. Sasser. ``We
were scared for our lives, but I was also really hurt since Jim and
I have worked so hard here.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said there was a chance Sasser would be able to leave
the embassy on Tuesday, but for now there are also two political
officers, eight Marines and two security officers there.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The water is working, Sasser said, and so are the electricity
and phone lines, allowing him to maintain contact with Washington.
But, he said, ``we have no blankets, no beds, no pillows, no
showers _ other than that we're doing fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every window on the street side of the building had
been shattered, and shards of glass and chunks of concrete littered
the floors.
</P>
<P>
   The destruction underscores the vulnerability of the embassy, a
hodgepodge of older buildings at two different locations in
Beijing's embassy district; the buildings were bought after the two
countries re-established diplomatic relations in 1979. The office
building where Sasser is trapped is set back only about 20 feet
from the street and was once a Pakistani school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This embassy clearly does not meet the requirements of the
Inman Commission, such as a 100-foot setback,'' Sasser said,
referring to security standards recommended in 1985 by a panel led
by retired Adm. Bobby R. Inman. ``That's why they can get us and
throw in these chunks of concrete and firebombs. So it is hard for
the police to control things.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasser, a former senator, said that he had lobbied congressional
colleagues for money to demolish the buildings and build new ones,
but that the money set aside for this ``got diverted for other
uses'' last year after the American Embassies in Kenya and Tanzania
were bombed.
</P>
<P>
   So Sasser spent Saturday and Sunday nights eating things like
freeze-dried beef stew and sleeping on the floor, to the sound of
breaking glass and chants like ``Hang Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday afternoon, he said, things were looking up, in part
because British diplomats had managed to send sleeping bags into
the compound, presumably by tossing them over the walls that
separate neighboring diplomatic compounds.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For a man who had spent the previous three days as the target of
rocks and tomatoes, Sasser remained remarkably upbeat about China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone through stages on how I feel about all this,'' he
said. ``First there was frustration and anger. But now I realize
that what we're seeing is a venting, and once the emotion is
drained away, the overriding importance of establishing a mature
and stable relationship will re-emerge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
