<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo and reaction to Friday's NATO
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Ledeall: Buffeted by a bombing error
that, from a diplomatic point of view, could hardly have been
worse, the administration had little choice but to insist today
that it was persisting with its dual Kosovo policy of hard bombing
and fast talk. To make the situation even more delicate, the
Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, tried to tantalize the
administration by announcing a partial withdrawal of his military
forces from Kosovo. Other developments. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Chinese officials choreographed
protests against the American Embassy here today, with a relentless
procession of tens of thousands of demonstrators that lasted into
the night. The marchers, who protested the bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade during a NATO raid on Friday, were ushered by
police officers to within 25 feet of the embassy. Many chanted
``Down with American imperialism!'' and sang the Chinese national
anthem. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-SASSER (Beijing) _ A telephone interview with James
Sasser, the trapped U.S. ambassador. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO military commanders seek to refine
their strategy in the Yugoslav campaign. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ In the days just before NATO
mistakenly bombed the Chinese embassy in Belgrade, U.S. officials
already voiced fears that they missed their moment last month to
strike a political deal to get China into the World Trade
Organization. Now the hopes of patching together that deal in the
next few months, the only window when the White House believes it
has a chance of getting through Congress, are quickly fading. By
David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Belgrade) _ The Yugoslav Army announced Monday
that it had completed its operations against the insurgent Kosovo
Liberation Army and had begun a partial withdrawal of military and
police forces from Kosovo. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ A scene story on the services
Monday for the dead Chinese in the Yugoslav capital. By Carlotta
Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (The Hague) _ Yugoslavia takes its case against
NATO to World Court. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Skopje) _ While all of the tributes were
poignant, the letter from the spokesman for the Kosovo Liberation
Army reverberated the most at a grim memorial service held here
today. It praised Fehmi Agani, a 66-year-old moderate Kosovo
Albanian leader killed by Serb police last Thursday, for possessing
a rare ability to reach across political divides and unify. By
David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIEF (Washington) _ Armed with growing reports of
critical food shortages in Kosovo, the U.S. is planning to begin
dropping supplies to the half-million Albanians forced from their
homes and hiding in the hills there with little food or medicine,
the State Department announced Monday. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ The Pentagon maps used by
American intelligence analysts who mistakenly targeted the Chinese
embassy were updated as recently as last year, but were still
inaccurate about the building's location. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
