<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-HATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKER `TAKEN ABACK' BY BRADLEY'S PRESSURE TACTICS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State Sen. Florence Shapiro, one of four
Republican holdouts keeping the hate crimes billed mired in
committee, said Monday she resents pressure tactics by a Democratic
presidential contender to get her to vote for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro of Plano said she got a call last week from Bill
Bradley, a former U.S. senator from New Jersey and the only
announced contender to Vice President Al Gore for the Democratic
nomination to succeed Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taken aback,'' said Shapiro, who has never met Bradley.
``I thought it was a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   After he complimented her on the work she has done in the Texas
Senate, Shapiro said Bradley then told her, ``I know you know how
important the hate crimes legislation is and that you will make the
best decision, and it will be the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hung up the phone and thought, `What in the world could he
have been thinking,''' Shapiro said. ``And that night, of course,
we heard that Clinton was here and that he also was telling Texans
and Texas legislators what he thought that we ought to be doing.
And in putting both of those together, I decided it is politically
expedient for them at this point in time to come out from other
places all over the country and tell Texans what we ought to be
doing. And I quite frankly resent it.''
</P>
<P>
   During a fund-raising rally Friday evening in Austin, Clinton
talked with Francis Renee Mullins, the daughter of Jasper dragging
death victim James Byrd Jr., for whom the proposed legislation is
named.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro accused Clinton and Bradley of getting involved in the
issue because ``it is a political issue that they think they can
get mileage out of.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I care much more for my fellow senators on the floor and their
views,'' Shapiro added. ``I care much more for my fellow House
members and their views than I do Bill Clinton or Bill Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro is one of four Republicans on the seven-member Senate
Criminal Justice Committee, where a bill that would toughen the
state's hate crimes law, is stalled. The others are Sens. Robert
Duncan of Lubbock, Jane Nelson of Flower Mound and Mike Jackson of
Houston. None of the Republicans has thus far agreed to support the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly did not influence me one way or the other,''
Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mark my word,'' Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, said Monday.
``I will get the votes'' to get the bill out of committee. He is
the Senate sponsor for House Bill 938.
</P>
<P>
   As passed by the House, it would enhance penalties for those
convicted of crimes against a person because of the victim's race,
gender, ``sexual preference'' or any of seven other categories of
individuals. It would not, however, increase penalties for those
convicted of murder or capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis refused to say Monday whether he had asked Bradley to call
Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis and other Democrats on the Criminal Justice Committee have
been trying to focus attention on Shapiro and other Republicans who
have supported hate crimes legislation in the past, but will not
this time.
</P>
<P>
   They contend Republicans oppose the inclusion of the ``sexual
preference'' language and because Texas Gov. George W. Bush does
not support the bill. Bush has said he will give serious
consideration to it if it passes the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, however, said her opposition to the bill is not based
on the protection it would afford gays and lesbians but on the
delineation of protected groups.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro was a co-author of the hate crimes bill in 1993. ``I
agreed with it then,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Current law, however, enhances penalties for offenses
``committed because of bias or prejudice,'' but does not specify
groups or individuals that might be subjected to bias or prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is very specific and more narrowly defines those
people that will be protected,'' she said. ``That's where my
problem lies, specifically defining each of those (10 protected)
groups and leaving out other groups as they may occur down the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, whose grandparents and several other relatives died in
concentration camps during the Holocaust, admits she has been
lobbied by Jewish groups that favor the bill, but ``not any more
than any other group.''
</P>
<P>
   She said proponents also have been unable to explain to her how
the proposed change in the hate crimes law would increase the
prosecution of hate crimes laws which is now rare.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
