<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PLO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU CLOSES PLO OFFICES IN JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Israel-Jerusalem)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a political move seen as both desperate and
dangerous, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu ordered
offices in the PLO's Jerusalem headquarters closed Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   With recent polls showing Netanyahu's reelection bid faltering,
the order was seen as part of a campaign strategy to raise the
future of Jerusalem, a powerfully emotional issue for both Israelis
and Palestinians, to the center of debate.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers and campaign rivals say the timing of
Netanyahu's order was clearly politically motivated, coming less
than one week before voters take to the polls for the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is explosive, and virtually certain to erupt in
violence if the Netanyahu government proceeds to use force to shut
down the offices of the building known as Orient House.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a political rally, Netanyahu told reporters Monday
night: ``Israel has full sovereignty over Jerusalem. That is why we
are issuing the orders to close these offices unless the
Palestinians do so themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu says three offices at Orient House are illegal because
they are used by the Palestinian Authority, which under peace deals
has no official standing in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians warn they will respond with violence if Israeli
police try to enter Orient House, focal point of Palestinian
political activity in Jerusalem. They say it is not used by the
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Under Israeli law, the Palestinians would have 24 hours to
appeal the court ruling that gave Netanyahu's government the right
to enact the closure order. But the Palestinians said they would
not file an appeal, rejecting the authority of the Israeli courts
over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday night it remained unclear whether Israeli police
would enforce the order, or some form of compromise would be
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Located in historically Arab East Jerusalem, the entrance to the
sprawling Arab estate made of Jerusalem stone was heavily guarded
by hundreds of young Palestinian men Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers blared a song by Fairuz, the legendary Lebanese singer,
in which the lyrics speak of the Palestinian people's deep love and
willingness to fight for Jerusalem. A Palestinian flag was draped
over building's facade.
</P>
<P>
   Faisal Husseini, a member of the Palestinian National Authority
responsible for Jerusalem affairs and the director of Orient House,
stood at the doorway and said: ``We are not leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem is too sensitive and too holy to become a card in
the Israeli political game,'' added Husseini, a scion of one of the
most influential Palestinian families, which has owned Orient House
for more than 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Netanyahu will resort to anything in politics. But he should
realize, and the world should realize, this is a very explosive
situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shlomo Ben Ami, a parliament member and leader of the rival
Labor Party, said Monday Netanyahu is ``using patriotism and the
charged issue of Jerusalem to conceal his failures in so many other
domains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is in office for nearly three years, but he waits for one
week before the election to do this? Voters will not be fooled by
that,'' Ben Ami added.
</P>
<P>
   Latest opinion polls show Netanyahu trailing Labor challenger
Ehud Barak by some eight percent. Netanyahu supporters are quick to
point to 1996 polls which showed him trailing by a similar margin
just before he won election.
</P>
<P>
   Israel sees Jerusalem as its eternal and indivisible capital.
The Palestinians see East Jerusalem, which was captured by Israel
from Jordan after the 1967 Six Day War, as the site of a future
state. Most of the international community, including the United
States, officially views the status of Jerusalem as undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   The historic 1993 Oslo accords called for Jerusalem and
Palestinian statehood to be among the issues to be negotiated in
the so-called ``final status'' agreements which are already more
than one year behind schedule in the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu threatened to walk away from the peace process if
Arafat made a unilateral move to declare Palestinian statehood, but
has been uninhibited in declaring that the future of Jerusalem is
``not open to debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a recent press conference whether his views on
Jerusalem were not a ``unilateral declaration,'' Netanyahu replied,
``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The status of Jerusalem, as it stands now, remains fully under
Israeli sovereignty,'' he said. ``When we act to ensure our
sovereignty, we are not doing anything to act unilaterally.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement released by the US Embassy said: ``This is an
extremely sensitive situation and both sides have a responsibility
to defuse it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
