<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BSO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA SAYS IT DOESN'T WANT BOSTON SYMPHONY TO PERFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i, a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The China Performing Arts Agency has officially
canceled the Boston Symphony Orchestra's scheduled concerts in
China Wednesday and Thursday. The agency took this action, it said,
in response to ``the barbarous atrocity of NATO'' in the bombing
Saturday of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   A fax received by BSO officials on tour in Japan Sunday stated
that the NATO bombing, which killed three people, ``has evoked the
utmost indignation of the Chinese government and people. As such we
believe the favorable atmosphere for the China tour at the moment
is no longer there, and no longer is it appropriate for the tour to
be conducted as originally scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra will return in two flights from Japan via Detroit
Tuesday. Music director Seiji Ozawa, who was born in China, will
travel to Beijing as scheduled to join his mother Sakora, 91, and
his brother who had already traveled to China; Ozawa still plans to
conduct his scheduled master class and rehearsal of Beethoven's
overture ``Leonore'' No. 3 in the Central Conservatory of Music
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to BSO managing director Mark Volpe, reached in Osaka
Monday, ``Our first information about the bombing in Belgrade was
sketchy, and monitoring the situation was quite difficult because
it was impossible to contact anyone in the American embassy in
Beijing. They were moving everyone out of there except for the
Marine guards.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night the designer Hanae Mori gave a reception for the
BSO and Ozawa in Tokyo, and the reception was attended by the
American ambassador to Japan and several deputies who were able to
supply home phone numbers for US embassy officials in Beijing, who
confirmed that the situation was serious, as did the BSO's contacts
in the US Information Agency. Later in the day, orchestra officials
received notice of the cancellation from the China Performing Arts
Agency, the government promoter.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's concert in Beijing was to be similar to the BSO's
outreach concert in Boston last month and to a program they played
on the Japan tour. The program was to be hosted by the leading
Chinese pop singer, Liu Huan, and attended by Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji and President Jiang Zemin. ``Certainly we are
disappointed,'' Volpe said, ``but we are also relieved that we are
not stepping into a troubled situation.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Ozawa read, ``I was born in China. One of the
proudest moments of my life was the Boston Symphony Orchestra's
trip to China in 1979. I have wanted to return to China with the
BSO for 20 years. I am terribly sad that we are not going back now.
I have decided to honor my commitment to give a master class in
Beijing, but obviously it's not the same without the BSO. I prefer
to think of this as a postponement, not a cancellation.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years have gone into planning the trip to Japan and China
to celebrate Ozawa's 25th anniversary as music director of the BSO.
Changing travel arrangements for the early return of the orchestra,
other people traveling along with the orchestra, and the cargo was
necessarily complicated, but at a post-concert party Sunday night,
orchestra members toasted the emergency skills of their travel
agent, California-based Tim Cole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
