   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RADAR (Undated) _ For two decades the Pentagon has tried
to monopolize a space radar that can expose submerged submarines.
When the radar made its debut in 1978, military officials blocked
public release of satellite photos that showed normally invisible
wakes of speeding craft. Last year, the military had the federal
government set strict limits on the visual powers of proposed
commercial radar satellites, and this year, the Pentagon is
fighting a Canadian plan to launch a radar satellite that would
break the new U.S. rules. By William J. Broad. (Scheduled to move
by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TORNADOES (Undated) _ Most of the process leading up to the
critical moment of tornado genesis is well understood, but unless
and until meteorologists can solve the puzzle of the last crucial
step, they will be at a loss to predict whether a garden variety
tornado is on the way, or one so puny it will fall apart at the
first obstacle it hits _ or a monster like one that struck the
outskirts of Oklahoma City. By William K. Stevens. (The story has
moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,950 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   YOUTH-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Lots of small moments emerged from
President Clinton's three-hour meeting on youth and violence, as
did a pledge by the administration to campaign against violence.
But one immediate result of the talkathon, at which 50 people spoke
and which the press was barred from viewing, was to defuse blame
for the school killings in Littleton, Colo. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
(Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.) 1,200
words.
</P>
