u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS &LR;      05-10 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNS IN CHILDREN'S HANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The massacre in Littleton, Colo., like the other school
shootings before it, resulted from a lethal cocktail of mental
illness, parental neglect, and a culture besotted with violence.
But what makes this scale of carnage possible is the guns. The
nation's attention is riveted on one murderous incident, but 13
children die of gunshot wounds every day, many of them in accidents
when they get their hands on weapons that should be beyond their
reach.
</P>
<P>
   Guns are everywhere in America. After the Oklahoma tornadoes
last week, police hustled to keep ahead of looters in retrieving
hundreds of guns that littered the landsape after being blown out
of homes. Before the Brady Law took effect in 1994, there were more
gun dealers in the country than gas stations. Private collectors
can sell guns without background checks at gun shows or flea
markets or over the Internet. It is illegal for people under 21 to
possess an open beer can but not a loaded handgun. Something is
very wrong with this picture.
</P>
<P>
   The US Senate has a chance this week to close some of the
loopholes that allow teenagers to obtain guns legally. States
cannot do it alone. The crazy quilt of laws in each state makes
them too easy to subvert. There should be national laws to prevent
child access to weapons by requiring owners to use trigger-locking
devices or store weapons in a locked case. Only 16 states,
including Massachusetts, have such laws. Background checks, firearm
permits, or at the very least a waiting period for teenagers
between 18 and 21 should be a national standard. Teenagers in 37
states can buy a gun without so much as counting to ten.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as the National Rifle Association insists, more
should be done to enforce existing laws. But that is not enough.
Responsible gun owners, including leaders of the American Shooting
Sports Council, have split with the NRA to back some of the
common-sense gun controls being proposed this week. Massachusetts
has strong laws, but the children in states without protections are
no less precious; they should not be any less safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
