<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFUSING THE CRISIS WITH CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chinese displays of state-supervised anger against the United
States for the bombing of China's embassy in Belgrade did not
originate in a void. Hard-liners in the United States and China
prepared the way for the current frenzy, with one side stoking
distrust of ``American hegemonism'' and the other indulging in what
Henry Kissinger has called ``a nostalgia for confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a conspiratorialist in the Oliver Stone mold could believe
that Washington wanted to guide three bombs into the Chinese
Embassy in Serbia, thereby validating Beijing's nationalist
propaganda and alienating a government that can veto any Kosovo
peace plan brought to the UN Security Council for approval.
</P>
<P>
   But the China-baiting of some US politicians has played into the
hands of Chinese Communists who want to distract the discontented
masses and legitimize their regime by means of patriotism and
xenophobia. This, after all, is the year of three fateful
anniversaries: the 50th for the Communist takeover, the 40th for
the invasion of Tibet, and the 10th since the Tiananmen bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's state-controlled media hid the truth about Serbia's
brutal uprooting of 1.5 million Albanian Kosovars. Now the
government is hiding news of President Clinton's regrets for the
embassy bombing while stage-managing anti-American protests and
demanding an American apology.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in US-Chinese relations _ a crisis that imperils the
interests of both countries _ has come about not merely because of
a CIA mapping mistake but also because self-serving hard-liners in
both countries have been goading each other into playing with fire.
</P>
<P>
   At one Beijing protest, students from the China Drama Academy
carried a placard depicting President Clinton as a Statue of
Liberty covered in blood and bearing a missile instead of freedom's
torch. To undo the damage of this image, Clinton should amplify his
apologies so that they reach the Chinese public _ the same audience
that responded with friendly enthusiasm during his visit to China
only last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
