<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-USANET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS DEAL REPORTEDLY VIEWED UNFAVORABLY BY HOLDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lycos Inc. executives now doubt shareholders would approve the
Internet company's proposed merger with operations of USA Networks
Inc., say people familiar with the matter, setting the stage for
further negotiations between the two companies if they decide to
abandon their agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The deal's dimming prospects caused shares in Lycos to surge 18
percent Monday, as investors hoped for a sweeter bid or, if Lycos
stays independent, an increase in the company's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of a deal announced in February, approval from a
majority of holders of Lycos' 43 million shares would be needed for
elements of New York-based USA Networks to be combined with Lycos,
one of the largest portals on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was thrown into jeopardy in March after the chief
executive of Lycos' largest shareholder, Andover, Mass. venture
firm CMGI Inc., withdrew his support.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's David Wetherell joined critics who said the agreement
didn't acknowledge the potential value of the portal company. CMGI,
which owns about 20 percent of Lycos, had enough votes to block the
deal, Wetherell said. Meanwhile, Lycos chief executive Bob Davis
vowed to convince enough holders to complete it.
</P>
<P>
   USA Networks head Barry Diller had also remained supportive, and
Lycos was expected to schedule a vote on the deal by early July.
</P>
<P>
   But the company has yet to mail shareholders the statements
needed for such a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Now they may never go out as Lycos executives have concluded the
math is not on their side. About 45 percent of shareholders either
oppose the deal, including CMGI, or aren't likely to vote at all,
said people familiar with the matter. The upshot is that Lycos, of
Waltham, Mass., would have to win 10 out of every 11 votes in the
remaining pool, making victory difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal quotes anonymous sources saying USA
Networks was expected to abandon its bid. Spokespeople for USA
Networks declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   However, USA Networks can't unilaterally walk away from the
deal. The merger agreement between the two companies states that
under current circumstances, either would need to gain the other
company's consent to call off the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming a vote doesn't take place, now the two companies must
bargain over just how USA Networks might withdraw its bid or,
potentially, bring in a new partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see them go alone for the next six to twelve
months,'' said Michael Goldston, principal at Cambridge Equity
Advisors, Nashville Tenn., who holds 40,000 Lycos shares. ``If
somebody looks at buying them six to twelve months from now, I
think the price would be 30 to 40 percent higher,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many leading Internet companies have found marriage
partners lately, an independent Lycos would still have strengths,
said Golston. For one thing, it would be free to continue the
acquisition spree it undertook last year that brought it control of
assets like Wired Ventures. Those new services helped it gain more
viewers in March than arch-rival Yahoo Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Also, certain regulations that have prevented Lycos from
undertaking mergers known as ``pooling-of-interest'' transactions
will lapse in September, making it easier for Lycos to buy other
companies or to sell itself outright.
</P>
<P>
   But the end of the deal with Diller might also strengthen the
hand of CMGI's Wetherell, who has said he might try to bring in
another partner for Lycos. CMGI's stock now trades at more than
twice what it did at the time the deal was announced, making it
easier for CMGI to bid on Lycos outright. A CMGI spokeswoman
declined to comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors still favor the agreement with Diller. CMGI
holder Alex Cheung, of the Monument Internet Fund, in Bethesda,
Md., said he liked the agreement because of the access Lycos would
gain to USA Networks assets like the Home Shopping Network
cable-television system and the Ticketmaster service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in the long-term, probably a combination of Lycos and
USA Networks would be a very potent economic force,'' Cheung said.
``But they have to market the deal to people with a short-term
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   But pessimists like Barry Parr, electronic commerce analyst at
International Data Corp. in Mountain View, Calif., worry a collapse
of the USA/Lycos deal would leave Lycos company in a precarious
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need two things they don't have. One is a media
partner,'' Parr said. ``The other is a consistent, well-known
brand.'' Lycos users are much less loyal than users of the rival
Yahoo Web portal, Parr said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Lycos rose 15 3/4 to close at $105 in Nasdaq trading
Monday. CMGI stock rose 16 11/16 to 237 15/16. USA Networks shares
dipped 1/8 to 35 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe reporter Hiawatha Bray contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
