A1608 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ATLANTA-COX     05-10 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President to visit Atlanta Tuesday
 &HT;    By Carlos Campos
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sonya Jones will welcome President Clinton to her
Atlanta business today in the same way that many Southerners
welcome people _ with some good ol' down-home cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is the owner of a bakery and a restaurant in the Sweet
Auburn Curb Market downtown. She plans on offering the president a
bite of one of her Southern specialities, a sweet potato
cheesecake...''and I want to send him with one back to the White
House,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be visiting with Jones and other vendors at the
city-supported Curb Market to get a closeup of their businesses,
and talk with them about what government and big business can do to
give small entrepenuers a boost.
</P>
<P>
   The brief trip to Atlanta at 2 p.m. today is part of the
unveiling of the Clinton administration's new markets strategy,
designed to encourage growth in underserved communities such as
rural areas, the inner city and Native American reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be calling on local corporations to play a greater
role in helping small businesses grow in those communities. Three
Georgia chief executives, Leo Mullin of Delta Airlines, Duane
Ackerman of BellSouth and Dan Amos of AFLAC in Columbus, Ga., will
attend a roundtable meeting with the president in Washington this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Gold, press secretary for Mayor Bill Campbell, said the
president chose Atlanta from among 10 cities where federal
Empowerment Zones are in place. Campbell will meet Clinton at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just tremendously proud of this opportunity to present
Atlanta to President Clinton and his administration of all that we
have accomplished with the tremendous level of cooperation between
Washington and the Campbell administration,'' Gold said. ``We're
especially pleased with the progress of the Empowerment Zone.
Although it's a work in progress, there are many successes that we
can talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The city chose the curb market for the president to visit
because it illustrates his new markets program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here you have the Curb Market less than a mile away from some
of the cities' most successful businesses, like BellSouth and
Georgia Pacific,'' Gold said. ``The president ... is calling on big
businesses to support the smaller industries and businesses in
their communities so that they too can get a leg up and benefit
from America's robust economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Donegan and others financed Eureka themselves, but said she gets
tax breaks for hiring people because her restaurant is in the
Empowerment Zone.
</P>
<P>
   She said business has been brisk since opening in November.
</P>
<P>
   Donegan said she plans to tell Clinton that government
assistance in urban renewal in areas such as Cabbagetown ``can
definitely happen. I think it's a good role model what we're doing
here. They're definitely they're to help you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what he'll be curious about, to see how things
are going and what other areas we really need more help in,'' Jones
said. ``There are areas that people have overlooked because of
certain locations. I'm very, very excited. I just think it's so
great that he's taking a personal interest in it, to come see
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid, the operations manager of the Kaffee Shoppe, a coffee shop
that also sells deli sandwiches, said she's excited about the
``once in a lifetime'' chance to meet with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to talk to him about more funding for marketing the
(Sweet Auburn Curb) market,'' Reid said. ``It's hard on the small
businesses because media, newspaper and radio ads, is so expensive.
It puts a big dent in the income.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's plane is expected to arrive at Hartsfield
Atlanta International Airport at 1:30 p.m., and depart about 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Campos writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
