<HEADER>
A1609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-PACIFIC-COX     05-10 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-PACIFIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Pacific attempts takeover of Unisource Worldwide
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia-Pacific Corp., moving to shore up its
distribution network for paper products, has launched a $1.49
billion bid for Pennsylvania-based Unisource Worldwide Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Unisource's board of directors said Monday it had authorized
discussions with Georgia-Pacific about the Atlanta-based forest
product company's cash merger proposal, which tops an existing
offer. That $1.3 billion offer from UGI Corp., a Pennsylvania-based
energy company, is still pending, Unisource said.
</P>
<P>
   A. D. ``Pete'' Correll, chairman and chief executive officer of
Georgia-Pacific, said Unisource's paper supplies and distribution
business would ``provide a good strategic fit'' with
Georgia-Pacific Group's paper and tissue businesses.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the merged companies could save money by trimming
overlapping distribution functions. Georgia-Pacific currently
distributes its own building products, but uses other companies to
handle its paper products.
</P>
<P>
   Unisource is rated as the nation's largest distributor of paper
products and janitorial supplies. Based in Berwyn, Pa., with 12,000
employees, Unisource reported net income of $37.7 million and
revenues of $7.4 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific Group, which excludes the company's timber
business, has 45,000 employees and is the second-largest U.S. maker
of building products and paper. The company reported net income of
$98 million and revenue of $13.22 billion for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Georgia-Pacific is doing is recognizing that the
distribution channel is becoming important,'' said Mark W.
Connelly, an analyst with J.P. Morgan Securities. Noting that
Unisource already distributes Georgia-Pacific paper products, he
said the acquisition was a ``logical move'' for the Atlanta-based
company.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific once owned a paper distribution company, Butler
Paper, which it sold in 1993 to Alco Standard Corp. in a
cost-cutting move. Unisource was formed three years later as a
spinoff from Alco.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly said, however, that while an acquisition makes good
strategic sense for Georgia-Pacific by giving it control of
distribution channels, ``it won't do a lot for earnings'' because
of low-margins in that part of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Impact on stock
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Pacific's stock fell nearly 7 percent Monday after
investors weighed the impact of a possible deal on the company's
bottom line. The company's stock, which is up 57 percent since the
beginning of the year, reached an intraday 52-week high of $99.50
before falling sharply to close at $92.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently announced a 2-for-1 stock split, payable
June 3 to shareholders of record May 14.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Monday's announcement, Moody's Investors Service
said it placed $5.5 billion in Georgia-Pacific debt securities
under review for a possible downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia-Pacific has operated with high debt levels since a
large acquisition several years ago. Although debt protection
measurements had begun to improve, this acquisition may reverse
this improvement,'' Moody's said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While an acquisition by G-P would likely improve the company's
credit quality, Moody's believes that the introduction of a new
merger candidate could interrupt the timing and effectiveness of
the company's ongoing operations in Atlanta,'' the service said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger announcement comes two weeks after Georgia-Pacific
Group reported that building products sales generated turnaround
earnings for the first quarter of $99 million. That was sharply up
from $4 million in net income from a year earlier, which included
$12 million for early retirement of debt.
</P>
<P>
   The company is benefiting from a boom in homebuilding. Correll
said in March that Georgia-Pacific was more inclined to expand
building products operations than those that make paper, which have
suffered from declining prices.
</P>
<P>
   Terms for Unisource
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific offered $12 per share in cash, or about $842
million, for Unisource's 70 million shares outstanding. Unisource
said outstanding debt of $440 million plus off-balance sheet debt
of $210 million would boost the value of the transation to $1.49
billion.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Unisource agreed to a merger with UGI that valued
Unisource stock at $11.50 per share. UGI had offered to swap 0.566
shares of UGI common stock for each share of Unisource stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was approved by both companies' boards but adverse
investor reaction sent UGI stock into a tailspin. That offer is now
valued at $10.08 per share, or $705 million, based on UGI's closing
price of 17 13/16 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   UGI, based in King of Prussia, Pa., declined comment Monday.The
company is the largest U.S. propane seller and also operates an
electric and natural gas utility in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
