<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: RHEINGOLD TRIES TO REVIVE VENERABLE NEW YORK
BRAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Striving to put the ``gold'' back in Rheingold, the
top executives in charge of reviving the venerable New York beer
brand are revamping their marketing efforts with an overhaul that
includes a new agency.
</P>
<P>
   Rheingold Brewing Co. has hired DeVito/Verdi in New York, an
agency known for sharply humorous creative work for advertisers
like New York magazine and Office Depot. DeVito/Verdi succeeds
Ferrell Calvillo Communications in New York, which handled the
account during the brand's initial reintroduction last year.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the agency change comes a Web site,
www.rheingoldbeer.com, created by Compelling Content, an Internet
agency in New York, and an increased focus on male beer drinkers
ages 21 to 34. As a result, the ads in year two assume a jocular,
hypermasculine tone to promote Rheingold as the brew ``for the few
real men still left.''
</P>
<P>
   The makeover for the brand _ formally Rheingold Extra Dry Lager
Beer _ is indicative of the competitive nature of the American beer
market as giants like Anheuser-Busch increase market share and
consumers restlessly switch from domestics to imports to microbrews
and back again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rheingold faces significant hurdles to gain awareness,
especially among younger drinkers when competitors like Budweiser,
Heineken, Coors Light and Corona are spending a lot more dollars in
the New York metropolitan area,'' said Benj Steinman, president at
Beer Marketer's Insights in Nanuet, N.Y., a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Rheingold has residual affection from those who
recall drinking the beer from the 1940s through the 1970s. Many
older New Yorkers can still sing the brand's familiar jingle, which
begins: ``My beer is Rheingold, the dry beer. Think of Rheingold
whenever you buy beer.'' But the drinkers born long after Brooklyn
lost the Dodgers are the crucial segment of the market because they
consume the bulk of the beer sold each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building a franchise with younger adult consumers is the
future of the brand,'' said Michael H. Mitaro, president at
Rheingold Brewing in White Plains.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it has been a big surprise to us that the best business
we're doing is in bars where those consumers are in lower Manhattan
neighborhoods like the East Village, West Village and SoHo,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   To capitalize on that, said Walter H. Liebman, the managing
director at Rheingold Brewing, whose family owned the brand until
1963, the ads are being changed to ``make them contemporary to
young adults.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is being done with ``a New York personality,'' he
added, laughing, ``that we're all sort of difficult to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   So radio commercials, heard on WFAN-AM as Rheingold sponsors
coverage of New York Mets games, present barbed parodies. In one
spot, a weakling impresses his girlfriend by bonking a bully with
``a refreshing bottle of Rheingold'' _ empty, of course. In another
spot, after a nurturing, caring man attends to the every need of
his ``poopie,'' an announcer intones: ``If you're repulsed by what
you just heard, then have we got a beer for you. A manly beer.
Rheingold Extra Dry.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials are ``meant to be tongue-in-cheek, said Sal
DeVito, creative director at DeVito/Verdi, ``not meant to be taken
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to get noticed,'' he added. ``If you take it with a
smile, it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Of two other ways Rheingold hopes to get noticed, one is old and
the other is new. The old tactic is one first used last year:
hiring people to wear sandwich boards peddling the brand. The
walking billboards are being placed at bars and restaurants where
younger drinkers congregate.
</P>
<P>
   The new tactic is the Web site, which tries to fuel ``a retro
mystique'' for Rheingold among the post-baby-boom consumers, said
Marshall Karp, president and chief executive at Compelling Content.
There are pages offering beer and New York trivia quizzes, the
lyrics to the original Rheingold jingle and a glimpse at the 1958
edition of a popular previous promotion, the annual vote to anoint
``Miss Rheingold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you market a beer that has been off the market 20
years?'' Karp asked. ``You make it relevant to today's beer drinker
with humor and irreverence, giving the history of the brand in a
fun way.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the campaign, with an estimated budget of $1 million to
$2 million, seems to have made only one faux pas. In a commercial
that sells a make-believe fragrance named Whisper ``for the
sensitive man in these sensitive times,'' the announcer interrupts
at one point to declare: ``Excuse me, excuse me. I just couldn't
let this go on. Real men don't wear pansy cologne.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot is the second recent ad aimed at younger men that can
be deemed vaguely menacing; a print ad for Wendy's International
carries the headline ``This is a burger town, pretty boy.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, who you calling pansy, beer belly?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
