<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1612 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUTH-VIOLENCE-(TRIMS     05-10 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-VIOLENCE-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNS BARELY MENTIONED AT YOUTH VIOLENCE `SUMMIT' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Colo., Calif.)  (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sarah Brady, a leading crusader against guns, found
common ground with Robert Ricker, a lobbyist for gun makers. Steve
Case, head of America On Line, and Doug Lowenstein, who represents
the trade association for video-game makers, agreed to try to
prevent children from buying violent video games on the Internet
that they are barred from buying in stores.
</P>
<P>
   And Eric Heydenberk, a 12-year-old from Quakertown, Pa., said he
was creating a Web page to tell other kids how to handle being
bullied. (He also slipped a copy of the latest CD from his jazz
band to the president.)
</P>
<P>
   Lots of small moments emerged from President Clinton's
three-hour ``summit'' Monday on youth and violence, as did a pledge
by the administration to campaign against violence. But one
immediate result of the talkathon, at which 50 people spoke and
which the press was barred from viewing, was to defuse blame for
the school massacre in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was exactly the kind of session I had hoped for, where
everyone was talking about the problems and the opportunities,''
Clinton told reporters later in the Rose Garden. ``No one was
pointing the finger of blame.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a big relief to Ricker, the lobbyist for the American
Shooting Sports Council. He said the atmosphere was constructive,
even friendly, and that no one put heat on the gun industry or on
anyone else in particular for what they all agreed was a vastly
complex societal problem. Because of the summit, he said afterward,
``I don't think the focus will be on guns.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems a safe assumption. So many factors were identified _
the Internet, movies, parental responsibility, domestic violence,
lack of religious faith, a coarsening of the culture _ that guns
were lost in the shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton said that the White House was undertaking
a national campaign against youth violence modeled on previous
campaigns to reduce teen pregnancy and find jobs for people on
welfare. ``It will come forward, we hope, with very specific
suggestions about what parents can do, what schools can do, what
community groups can do, what the media can do, what gun
manufacturers can do, what all of us can do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was impressed with such murky results. Pheniece
Jones, a 16-year-old who was part of the crew from U.S. Kids TV,
which did not film the event but listened to the adult chatter
afterward, said: ``It seemed like ordinary stuff that people say
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   What would she tell her friends? ``That I met Andrew Shue and he
was really nice,'' she said, referring to the former star of
Melrose Place.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not stop the adults from patting themselves on the
back for what they said was a conciliatory session _ what Gary
Bauer, a Republican candidate for president who was not invited,
called ``a feel-good forum, lots of talk and not much action,'' in
sum, ``a perfect Clinton administration event.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, who has been criticized for going soft on
Hollywood _ particularly as he prepares for a $1.5 million Beverly
Hills fund-raiser later this week hosted by David Geffen, the
Hollywood mogul _ did offer a mild rebuke to the entertainment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot pretend that there is no impact on our culture and
our children that is adverse if there is too much violence coming
out of what they see and experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said parents could ``turn off the television'' if they didn't
like what their children were watching. He said they should monitor
what their children are doing on the Internet and refuse to buy
products that glorify violence.
</P>
<P>
   He did not ask the entertainment industry to stop making such
products, only that they not dangle them in front of youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to ask people who produce things to consider the
consequences of them, whether it's a violent movie, a CD, a video
game,'' the president said. ``If they are made, they at least
should not be marketed to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, said he did not want the movies singled out and said he
supported a study by the U.S. Surgeon General to figure out ``the
why'' of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also believe that church and home and school are the three
places where children learn what is right and what is wrong, and
that's where they build a strong moral shield,'' Valenti said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With an eye toward gun-control legislation that the Senate is to
take up Tuesday, Clinton noted that the gun makers had endorsed
some of his ``common-sense'' proposals. They include: raising the
age to 21 from 18 for owning a handgun; requiring background checks
of people who buy guns at gun shows; banning juveniles convicted of
violent felonies from ever owning a gun; prosecuting parents if
they let their children use a gun for a crime; and expanding the
government's gun-tracing program.
</P>
<P>
   There was no mention of the two administration proposals that
the gun makers resolutely oppose _ limiting handgun purchases to
one a month and reinstituting the three-day waiting period for
buying a gun that expired Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Brady, whose husband, James, was shot during the 1981
assassination attempt against President Reagan, said she wanted to
``commend'' the gun makers for ``coming to the table'' and
``opening a dialogue that has not been there in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Across town, the National Rifle Association reacted with some
irritation to the summit, to which its top officials had not been
invited. Standing with the rifle association was another lobbyist
for the gun industry who had been invited to the summit but
boycotted it.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbyist, Robert Delfay, president of the National Shooting
Sports Foundation, said he boycotted the event because the White
House had submitted its legislation to Congress on Friday, before
giving the foundation a chance to shape it. He also said he wanted
to express solidarity with the rifle association.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne LaPierre, executive vice president of the NRA, said he was
miffed that he had not been invited because his organization
teaches gun safety. The real problem, he said, is that no one is
enforcing the laws that are already on the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk about the culture of violence for the next 10
years,'' he said. ``Unless you start prosecution, you're never
going to cut to the culture of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Baker, the NRA's chief lobbyist, said that ultimately he
expected little to come of the legislation on Capitol Hill. ``At
the end of the day, I see little or nothing passing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the proposals have already been rejected by Congress, he
noted. As for any anti-gun momentum spurred by the Littleton
shootings, he said: ``I don't think any of the proposals, whether
they come from us or from the White House, are responsive in any
way or would have had any effect on what happened at Littleton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
