<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-10 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: PLO Offices Ordered Closed
</P>
<P>
   The police served closure orders against three offices in Orient
House, the Palestine Liberation Organization headquarters in East
Jerusalem, but the action was delayed pending a petition to the
Supreme Court by Israeli peace advocates. Palestinians called the
order an election ploy by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyhau, who
has made Jerusalem a centerpiece of his campaign. Faisal Husseini,
the top PLO official in East Jerusalem, warned that a forcible
closure could set off riots.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan: Journalist Case Pressed
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Punjab state told the Lahore High Court that they
do not know the whereabouts of Najam Sethi, editor of The Friday
Times, although his wife says 2 Punjab police officers were among
10 men who took him from their home on Saturday. A government
spokesman has said Sethi was suspected of links to India's
intelligence agency; his wife says he is being punished for
speaking out against the government. The court gave the government
two days to say where Sethi is being detained.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: East Timor Clashes
</P>
<P>
   Supporters and opponents of independence for East Timor fought
for a second day in the capital city of Dili and officials said
four people had been killed. With the streets empty of pedestrians,
riot policemen circulated in trucks and shots could be heard from
the central market, the University of East Timor and a cemetery. A
referendum on independence is scheduled for Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam: 77 Accused of Corruption
</P>
<P>
   A major corruption trial with 77 defendants, including 18 bank
officials, opened in Ho Chi Minh City, drawing hundreds of
spectators. The case involves a charge of collusion by private
companies to acquire huge bank loans with exaggerated collateral.
It carries a possible death penalty for some defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: Looted Artworks Returned
</P>
<P>
   Under military escort, 61 sandstone statues and friezes looted
by the Khmer Rouge have been returned for safekeeping to
authorities at Siem Reap, the site of the huge temple complex of
Angkor. The looted pieces, some dating from the 10th century, were
recovered from Anlong Veng, the last stronghold of guerrilla
holdouts from the Communist insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Bomb Suspect Remanded
</P>
<P>
   A 22-year-old man accused of killing three people and wounding
more than 100 in three London nail bombings last month was ordered
held in custody by a London court. David Copeland, an unemployed
subway engineer, was arrested a week ago and charged with the three
attacks, the first in a black neighborhood, the second in an Asian
one and the last in a gay pub in which the three people died.
Copeland is not known to be a member of any of the racist groups
that claimed responsibility for the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: A Suit Over Viagra
</P>
<P>
   A decision by the National Health Service to curb the
prescribing by its doctors of the impotence drug Viagra was
challenged in England's High Court by Pfizer Ltd. as ``legally
indefensible.'' The drug company, which makes Viagra, said it was
considering suing the government for damages in lost business.
Health Secretary Frank Dobson took the action in September, saying
unrestricted prescribing would be a ``serious drain'' on the
service's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Sinn Fein's Choices
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein has picked its chief negotiator, Martin McGuinness and
another top party official, Bairbre de Brun, as its nominees for
the party's two positions in the executive of the new Northern
Ireland Assembly. The province's largest party, the Ulster
Unionists, are refusing to let Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
IRA, take its seats unless there is a start to guerrilla
disarmament. The Ulster Unionist leader, David Trimble, and Sinn
Fein's head, Gerry Adams, met in Belfast but remained deadlocked on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Yeltsin Charges
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Leaders of Russia's moderate Yabloko Party told members
to support one of the five impeachment charges against President
Boris N. Yeltsin: that he exceeded his authority by waging a
disastrous war against rebels in Chechnya. The impeachment debate
begins in the lower house on Wednesday; Yabloko's 46 members often
hold the balance of power, but it is unclear whether the votes
exist to impeach Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: A Terror Group Surrender
</P>
<P>
   One of the last members of the Red Army Faction terrorist group
of the 1970s and 80s has turned herself in, the Federal
Prosecutor's Office in Karlsruhe said. Barbara Meyer appeared
before the Federal Supreme Court and is being held pending trial.
The prosecutor's office said she had been living in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: Justice Minister Quits
</P>
<P>
   Minister of Justice Parmenio Cuellar has resigned, saying
reforms of the judicial system backed by the government will
contribute to human rights violations. Minister of the Interior
Nestor Martinez favors leaving untouched many features of special
``faceless'' courts that protect judges, lawyers and witnesses by
allowing them to testify anonymously behind two-way mirrors. That
system is supposed to be dismantled by June 30, but Martinez, who
takes over the Justice portfolio, favors laws that would allow many
of the most contentious practices to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Senator Hurt by Gunfire
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Sen. Hector Sanchez Lopez, a former candidate for
governor who continues to protest what he calls fraud in elections
last August in southern Oaxaca state, was wounded during a
confrontation with a crowd of governing party activists in a Oaxaca
village. Sanchez blamed the governing party leaders in Oaxaca for
the attack, a contention the state attorney general, from the
governing party, called infantile.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Paraguay Plea Rejected
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge rejected a Paraguayan request for the arrest of
Gen. Lino Oviedo, a retired former army chief who is suspected of
masterminding the assassination of Vice President Luis Maria Argana
almost two months ago. The judge said the Paraguayan warrant was
incomplete, lacking charges and the amount of jail time the general
could face. Oviedo has held political asylum in Argentina since he
and his family fled to Buenos Aires on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ANGOLA AND ZAMBIA: MEETINGS PLANNED
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to ease growing tensions between Angola and Zambia,
defense and security ministers from both countries have agreed to
meet in Swaziland this week for several days of talks. For months
Angola has been accusing Zambia of allowing the Angolan rebel group
Unita to resupply via Zambia. But Zambia denies such cooperation,
saying the accusations emanate from its refusal to allow Angolan
troops to use Zambian territory to attack the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
