<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1617 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-10 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV PULLOUT OFFER NOT ENOUGH, US SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As cracks appeared to surface in the NATO alliance
because of the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia announced Monday that it was withdrawing half of its
armed forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   US officials branded the pullout a ``half-measure'' that did not
comply with NATO demands for full withdrawal and other conditions
for a cease-fire. NATO remained on the defensive for Friday's
embassy bombing, with President Clinton apologizing for what he
called a ``tragic mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the air campaign would continue
until Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic met its terms. About
40,000 Yugoslav troops, police, and special forces are believed to
be stationed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the partial Yugoslav withdrawal and the
mistaken embassy bombing threatened to cause divisions within NATO
about how the war should continue.
</P>
<P>
   The German government was noticeably less hostile to the
overtures from Yugoslavia than Washington and London, and there was
unusually harsh criticism of NATO by the British opposition. The
German government's official spokesman said Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder would study the announcement from Belgrade before
commenting on it.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder called for a ``full and thorough'' investigation into
the embassy bombing, while a government spokesman in Berlin said
NATO's explanation so far is ``not satisfactory.'' Italy, which has
been more dubious of the war all along, repeated Schroeder's call,
saying it was vital for NATO's credibility that there be an
investigation that publicly explains what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the Chinese Embassy was a political and public
relations disaster for Clinton, who has had a tempestuous
relationship with China throughout his presidency. After two days
of protests by thousands of students who hurled rocks and other
debris at the US Embassy in Beijing, the demonstrations eased up
Monday, but US Ambassador James Sasser and aides remained inside
for security reasons, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Clinton sought to placate Beijing with his apology but
at the same time he called for continued shelling of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize. I regret this. But it's very important to
remember that this was an isolated, tragic event,'' Clinton said
about the embassy bombing. By comparison, he told a White House
audience, ``the ethnic cleansing of Kosovo, which has led to the
killing of thousands of people and the relocation of hundreds of
thousands, is a deliberate and systematic crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Chinese journalists were killed and 20 other people were
wounded in the attack, Chinese officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing of the embassy occurred because NATO planners,
acting on information from the CIA and other agencies, used an
outdated map of Belgrade that showed the old Chinese Embassy in a
different location, according to Defense Secretary William S.
Cohen. He said the maps did not include the new embassy that opened
in the last few years adjacent to the building NATO had intended to
target.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of systems failed'' to catch such an error, Cohen
said at a Pentagon briefing. Cohen said it was ``not a human or
mechanical error. It was an institutional error.'' He defended
NATO's bombing record, saying a dozen strikes out of 4,036 bombing
targets have resulted in civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he had seen no evidence that Milosevic had begun
pulling forces from Kosovo. ``Simply saying he is going to withdraw
part of his forces is completely insufficient,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said, ``If there ever
was a definition of a half measure, that is it.'' Officials also
noted that the Yugoslav statement made no provision for the return
of ethnic Albanian refugees, a key NATO demand.
</P>
<P>
   Some Western diplomats suggested the German circumspection
stemmed more from Schroeder's visit this week to China, and his
planned visit with Russian Balkans envoy Viktor S. Chernomyrdin,
than any real break from the European consensus that NATO cannot
let up in its war until Milosevic gives in. In protest, Beijing
trimmed Schroeder's planned four-day visit to a single day. A
Chinese-European Union trade summit this week was also canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that while Schroeder's statements were
understandable given his travel schedule, the remarks of German
Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping were more indicative of German
government opinion. Responding to the Yugoslav Army's announcement
of troops being withdrawn, Scharping said changing NATO's approach
``on the basis of a propaganda maneuver would be an act of gross
recklessness.''
</P>
<P>
   In the British House of Commons, there was unusually frank
criticism of NATO by Michael Howard, the opposition Conservative
Party's shadow foreign secretary. Howard called the embassy bombing
``an act of gross incompetence'' and said NATO's strategy appeared
to be ``made up as it goes along.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Newspaper Society in London, however, Prime
Minister Tony Blair said: ``There have been civilian deaths in
Belgrade, yes. But how does it compare to 1.5 million people driven
from their homes? One hundred thousand men aged 15 to 55 missing?
The systematic rape? The mass graves? The executions? People forced
to bury their dead, and then murdered and thrown in on top?''
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO diplomats said they believed the timing of the
announcement by the Yugoslav Army was aimed at stirring up
dissension among the European allies.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav Army ``statement suggests they're pulling out
because they've finished mopping up the KLA,'' said one senior NATO
diplomat, referring to the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army. ``But the
KLA is actually in better shape than it was a month ago, so that
doesn't explain the statement. Milosevic is sowing the seeds of
dissension, pure and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Monday:
</P>
<P>
   --NATO carried out daylight bombings on several towns in central
and western Serbia, killing four civilians and smashing a factory
in one 20-minute bombardment, Yugoslav media reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanjug news agency said seven missiles slammed into the
Serb-populated town of Kosovo Polje, site of the 1389 battle in
which the Serbs lost Kosovo to the Ottoman Turks. Tanjug said one
person was killed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the independent Beta news agency said NATO jets
struck a neighborhood of Kosovo's capital, Pristina, as well as the
city's airport _ a frequent target.
</P>
<P>
   --Yugoslavia began presenting its case to the World Court in The
Hague that NATO's bombing campaign is ``a crime against peace and
also the crime of genocide.'' NATO officials dismissed the suit as
hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   --The United Nations reported that 15,000 refugees crossed the
Kosovo border into Albania over the weekend, bringing the estimated
number of refugees and displaced people to more than 745,000.
</P>
<P>
   --The European Union tightened sanctions against Yugoslavia,
freezing funds held within the union by people close to Milosevic
and banning the export of goods to Yugoslavia that could help
Belgrade repair facilities damaged by the NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kranish reported from Washington, Cullen from London. Wire service
material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
