</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OPENS DIALOGUE OVER YOUTH VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w, e and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Careful not to blame youth violence on any one
cause, President Clinton opened a national conversation with an
eclectic group of leaders Monday on how to prevent another tragedy
like last month's student massacre in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The most substantive result of the three-hour White House
session was the launch of a national campaign and nonprofit
foundation aimed at curbing youth violence. But just as important,
the president said, was the sense from the meeting that gunmakers,
the media, and community political and religious leaders came
together committed to help parents raise healthier children.
</P>
<P>
   The president also challenged the entertainment industry to be
sensitive to and take responsibility for what he said was a
``coarsening of the culture'' and a movement away from creating a
positive image of American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot pretend that there is no impact on our culture and
our children that is adverse if there is too much violence coming
out of what they see and experience,'' Clinton said in the Rose
Garden after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so we have to ask people who produce things to consider
the consequences of them, whether it's a violent movie, a CD, a
video game. If they are made, they at least should not be marketed
to children,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents of CBS Television and ABC/Disney attended the
meeting, which was closed to the news media, as did the head of
America On-Line and the Recording Industry Association of America.
In all, 60 people strategized around a large, rectangular table in
the White House East Room, including singer Gloria Estefan, poet
Maya Angelou, and the Rev. Eugene Rivers of Boston. First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Vice President Al Gore and his wife,
Tipper, participated, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president attempted today to get out front on an issue
that needed some kind of presidential response in the aftermath of
the Littleton affair,'' Rivers said after the meeting. ``But
ultimately the initiative will be led by grass-roots activists who
don't confuse White House sessions with building a real-world
antiviolence movement that focuses on prevention, intervention, and
zero tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Five children opened the session with ``powerful stories of
their own experiences,'' said Bruce Reed, the White House domestic
policy adviser. Gore called it a wide-ranging discussion, as
panelists noted how everything from domestic violence to the
quality of after-school care, from the Internet to the availability
of guns impacts the behavior of young people.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the meeting some had expected to be an opportunity to
bash the gun lobby turned into one of considerable presidential
praise for two gun-trade groups _ the American Shooting Sports
Council and the National Shooting Sports Foundation Inc. _ that in
recent days tentatively endorsed what Clinton called ``common sense
measures'' to strengthen federal gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are proposals to raise the age to 21 from 18 for
legally possessing a handgun; require background checks for buyers
at gun shows; ban violent juveniles from ever buying a gun; expand
gun tracing nationally; and make parents legally liable for
allowing youngsters access to guns later used in crime.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, the largest lobby of gun owners,
was not invited to send its president, actor Charlton Heston, to
Monday's White House meeting. Wayne LaPierre, the NRA's executive
director, said Clinton was afraid Heston would expose the
``complete collapse'' of the Justice Department's enforcement of
federal firearms laws during the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of dealing with (prosecutions), what we see is the
president now dusting off every tired old gun-control bill that's
been around his administration for the last six years ... tired old
schemes that have no real impact on this criminal culture of
violence in this country,'' LaPierre said. Monday the NRA began a
national advertising campaign aimed at affirming its support for
unfettered gun ownership for law-abiding Americans.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre was joined at a news conference by Robert Delfay,
executive director of the National Shooting Sports Foundation, who
turned down an invitation to the strategy session because the White
House was ``trying to drive a wedge between the industry and the
National Rifle Association.'' Such a wedge, he said, ``does not
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is expected to begin debate Tuesday on a juvenile
crime bill that once was aimed at making violent juveniles stand
trial as adults but now is expected to become a vehicle for a
number of gun-control amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Clinton said he has instructed Dr. David Satcher, the US
surgeon general, to prepare a report on youth violence that would
review existing research and particularly assess the impact of the
Internet and video games on youth behavior. The idea came from,
among others, Democratic Representative Edward J. Markey of
Massachuetts, who was also instrumental in legislation that makes
the V-Chip _ a device for allowing adults to block objectionable
programming _ mandatory in new television sets next year.
</P>
<P>
   A survey released Monday by the Kaiser Family Foundation, a
California-based research group, showed 80 percent of parents said
they had heard of the TV ratings now in use, but only 39 percent of
them said they had seen an explanation of them. Seventy-seven
percent said they would block shows they don't want their children
to watch if their television sets were equipped with such
technology, while 20 percent said they would not.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that during the meeting, Gore praised ABC, CBS, and
most cable networks for rating children's programs and ``chided''
NBC for not taking part in the effort. Reed also said there were
``encouraging signs'' from the entertainment industry that it was
trying to ``galvanize efforts'' on the violence issue.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, the film industry's longtime Washington lobbyist,
said, ``An increasing number of creative people in Hollywood are
willing to examine the issue of gratuitous'' violence. But, he
added, ``I do not know of a single piece of research that shows
somebody looked at Quake or Doom or looked at a movie and then
grabbed a Tec-DC9 and then went out and blew somebody's head off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
