<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1624 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHANTOM-STARS-SPI &LR;      05-10 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHANTOM-STARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR LIVES FOREVER AFFECTED BY THE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For Samuel L. Jackson, the urge welled after he saw
``Star Wars'' in 1977. Teenager Natalie Portman had not seen a
single scene of the saga until opportunity knocked.
</P>
<P>
   Liam Neeson never envisioned a future in lightsabers but now he
wields a pretty green stick. There was no way Jake Lloyd, all of 10
years old, could say no to the chance of a lifetime: flying a space
fighter around the ol' Naboo-hood.
</P>
<P>
   Four actors. Four paths. They converged when the Force beckoned.
Now the quartet are members of George Lucas' exclusive club,
appearing in ``Star Wars: Episode One _ The Phantom Menace,'' which
hits more than 3,500 movie screens across the country May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Each actor, in his or her own way, is bracing for the
unavoidable tide of public recognition. Jackson is pumped about
getting a toy action figure in his likeness; Portman is
concentrating on advanced placement tests; Neeson, who is media
shy, would rather be out for trout; and Jake? Well, he and his
family already had to move once. That was after local kids started
camping in their front yard after Jake's mug appeared in the
movie's early trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were insane,'' Jake recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, spending time in the Big Apple with the big stars before
the big day is like witnessing lives in calm _ and not so calm _
contemplation before a storm.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel L. Jackson
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador of cool strolls into a room and tells how he got
the phat Kangol beret with the words P-h-a-n-t-o-m M-e-n-a-c-e
printed on it. ``I got friends in high places,'' chortles Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Best-known for his role as the Bible-quoting hitman in ``Pulp
Fiction,'' Jackson plays Mace Windu, a member of the Jedi Council.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the late '70s, Jackson said he saw ``Star Wars'' and
decided, ``I should have been in it, and if they make another one I
needed to be in that one.'' The reason for his passion was
adventure; he saw the original flick as being like a ``'70s Errol
Flynn swashbuckling'' tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took 22 years to make it happen,'' Jackson said of his Jedi
mission, now accomplished. ``But we got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   His ``Phantom'' time is limited, although the buzz is there is a
place for Mace in the next installment. Until then, Jackson does
have a deal in hand: his own Mace Windu action figure. ``Looks
good, too,'' he jokes.
</P>
<P>
   His presence in the film brings a second prominent African
American actor _ Billy Dee Williams in the original trilogy was the
first _ to Lucas' universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `Where the brothers at?' (Are they) on their own
planet and just have not stopped by yet?'' Jackson says with a
guffaw, adding ``Does that mean there's a Colt 45 (beer)
commercial?''
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Portman
</P>
<P>
   The girl is smart. The girl is pretty. The girl has two worlds
on a string _ Earth and planet Naboo.
</P>
<P>
   In the first world, Portman does plays on Broadway and is
preparing to go to an Ivy League college. (She's keeping mum on
which one.)
</P>
<P>
   In the second world, she wears wonderfully ornate costumes,
displays strength and compassion and is known as Queen Amidala of
Planet Naboo.
</P>
<P>
   No matter which planet you find her on, she is going places.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this role is so wonderful because young girls don't
have that kind of role model in their life, or often reflected in
film,'' the vibrant 17-year-old high school senior says, smiling.
``Girls are losing a lot of confidence in themselves as the years
go on. They become much more worried about their looks rather than
their intelligence, and their personality and their kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   Portman's previous credits include the movie ``Beautiful Girls''
and Broadway's production of ``The Diary of Anne Frank.'' She had
not seen any of the ``Star Wars'' movies until Lucas offered her
the part. In the movie, her character, which has pivotal roles in
the next two films, must try and save Naboo from destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Portman said she enjoyed working with Lucas _ ``he's a genius''
_ and was amazed to see the beauty of the ornate regal outfits she
wore on the big screen. On the set, the crew made light fun of the
headdresses, including one that looked like a mushroom. ``We named
it `The Armadillo,' '' she laughs.
</P>
<P>
   As she waits for Lucas to finish the next script, she has more
acting gigs lined up, as well as school. This week and next, she
has advanced-placement tests in French, calculus, government,
macroeconomics and biology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hate to go through life not knowing more,'' she says.
``Also, I've been acting for over five years. By the time I finish
college, it will be 10 years. I might be ready to move on by that
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Liam Neeson
</P>
<P>
   He'd rather be fishing. Upstate New York. Maybe Connecticut. Fly
rod in hand. Until then, Neeson will settle for a lightsaber on
Tatooine.
</P>
<P>
   Neeson plays Qui-Gon Jinn, a Jedi knight who takes Anakin
Skywalker under his wing.
</P>
<P>
   Neeson said he got into acting by good fortune. He had dropped
out of university in Belfast and was working on a forklift when he
called up a local theater that happened to be looking for someone
tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``What height are ye?'' a woman at the theater asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six-foot-four,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you be here next Thursday?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   He showed up. And the rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Neeson is standing tall in his profession, having been
nominated for an Oscar for his portrayal of Oskar Schindler in the
acclaimed film ``Schindler's List.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to the ``Phantom Menace'' project after hearing that
Lucas planned to emerge from his ``mini-retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not really for `Star Wars,' it was for George Lucas. He
was always on my little wish list from `American Graffiti' days,''
Neeson said softly, tugging on the sleeve of his casual black sport
coat. ``He offered me the part. There was no script. It was a leap
of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeson said he could identify with the serial's story line
because of the tradition of rich, mythic storytelling in his native
Ireland. ``King Arthur was as real to me as the strange man living
five doors up, ye know?'' said Neeson, whose first big-screen
credit was ``Excalibur.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother totally believes in fairies and goblins. She
could talk about those things the way you talk about the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The well-toned actor said he does not miss the physical demands
of the ``Phantom Menace'' shoot, for which he had to do extra
push-ups just to stay in saber-fighting shape. Now, with the crush
of media building, he is looking to run away _ in his green
Converse Chuck Taylors _ to a river.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want to go out and catch a 22-inch trout with my new dry
fly. It's called the Qui-Gon,'' he said, a smile breaking across
his face. ``It's the master Jedi of dry flies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake Lloyd
</P>
<P>
   See Jake spin in the chair. Spin, Jake. Spin.
</P>
<P>
   Feel Jake throw a fed-up glance. Ouch, Jake. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Hear Jake tell a joke. Talk, Jake. Talk.
</P>
<P>
   I have a dog, Jake says. Charlie is his name. ``He's a Shitzu.''
</P>
<P>
   (A pause.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You might have to shorten that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone cracks up.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why Portman and Neeson call Lloyd ``a sprite''
and expound on his energy. The 10-year-old is Grand Coulee Dam
breached.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, Lloyd plays Anakin Skywalker, who will grow up to
become Darth Vader. ``Whoa, Darth Vader rules,'' he says, spinning
again in a green chair.
</P>
<P>
   Jake has been acting half of his life. He is very excited to be
involved with the same director who catapulted another young ``Star
Wars'' actor to the big screen decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I haven't seen Mark Hamill in any other stuff,'' Jake
huffs, as he holds back a giggle. ``Either that or I'm not allowed
to see it!''
</P>
<P>
   Jake is saving up his movie money to buy a car, a nice home and
to go to college _ ``That's pretty much all I want'' _ but he can't
touch the moola, he says, until he is 18.
</P>
<P>
   He loves okra and black-eyed peas, the Stray Cats, and the baby
in the TV cartoon ``Family Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and he hates to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank goodness (``The Phantom Menace'') is finally coming
out,'' he says ``Four years is a long while. For a kid, it's like
eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   But even fun times can turn serious. When people started camping
out in front of Lloyd's California home, his family decided it was
time to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not need that,'' said Jake's dad, Bill, adding that
other factors also played into the family's decision to go. (Jake's
sister, Madison, 7, also has a small role in the movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Jake Lloyd says he has fond memories of Lucas. ``Amazing
director. Nicest guy. He's the biggest, oldest kid I ever met _
well, besides my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   But wait! Tell me what happened to you and Lucas at the Chinese
restaurant?
</P>
<P>
   ``They had one of those spinning things in the middle of the
table,'' Lloyd begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I stopped it, everything spun off and a lot of it got on
George ...''
</P>
<P>
   Uh oh!
</P>
<P>
   ``... he just started laughing!''
</P>
<P>
   Phew!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
