<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     05-10 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DARK SUITS, DARK DRESSES AND GLOWING WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police vans, with blinking lights, blocked East 87th
Street from Park Avenue to Madison Avenue, but every so often a
long black limousine was allowed through the barricades. On the
shaded sidewalk, men in dark suits and women in dark dresses waited
in a slow-moving line to enter the Park Avenue Synagogue. Some of
the 1,500 mourners had arrived as much as two hours before the 11
a.m. funeral Monday for Leon Hess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for a policeman's funeral,'' a police officer was
saying, ``I've never seen a street shut off like this.''
</P>
<P>
   As a man of quiet dignity, Leon Hess would probably have been
embarrassed by all the attention, but deep down, he surely would
have enjoyed it. As he had basking in his Jets owner's box at
Giants Stadium during the closing minutes of the playoff victory
over the Jacksonville Jaguars last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved the fans, even the ones who had reviled him,''
Wellington Mara, the Giants' co-owner, would say in his eulogy.
``But now those same fans stood and cheered him. He gave them the
thumbs-up sign and said, `This is thrilling.' A provident God had
given him a sweet thrill before He took him from us.''
</P>
<P>
   But before Hess owned the Jets, he had built the Amerada Hess
Corp. into a worldwide oil business. And along with several Jets
coaches and players as well as a few National Football League club
owners, oil executives had come from Africa, South America and
Europe to sit in the synagogue's pews.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kean, the former governor of New Jersey, remembered Hess'
reaction to Hurricane Hugo leveling much of St. Croix in the Virgin
Islands in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon told me about the terrible damage to his oil refinery,''
Kean said, ``but then he told me there was even a worse loss, that
every school there had been destroyed and he said, `It's more
important that we rebuild the schools.' And he paid to rebuild
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of Newark told how Hess had
rebuilt other schools in the Caribbean that had been flattened by
another hurricane, and how Hess would phone him at Christmastime to
donate funds to help feed and buy presents for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon Hess loved people,'' McCarrick said. ``He never took them
for granted. And when the Jets weren't winning, it's not that he
was disappointed for himself, but for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gutman, the Jets' president, remembered how Hess tested
the strength of the Hess toy trucks by standing on them. The day in
1993 when the Jets were hoping to woo Reggie White during his visit
as a free agent, Hess set a toy truck in front of the 300-pound
defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon had Reggie take his coat off, then he said, `It's your
turn, Reggie,''' Gutman recalled. ``Reggie stood on it. The truck
is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   Those toy trucks, now a collector's item, were the symbol of
Hess' success in the oil business. His brother-in-law, Warren
Wilentz, remembered driving him to Newport News, Va., shortly after
World War II to inspect a Liberty ship that the federal government
no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leon was a dreamer and he wanted to own a tanker,'' Wilentz
said. ``When we looked at that Liberty ship, I saw a dilapidated
piece of steel, but he saw his dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Hess' grandchildren, Betsy Williams and Peter Friedland,
spoke fondly of him. So did his daughters, Connie Williams and
Marlene Zirin, and then his son, John, now the chief executive
officer of Amerada Hess, remembered how ``my father at first hauled
coal, but the 100-pound bags of coal were too heavy, so he went
into the fuel-oil business'' when fuel oil was 4 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a special love for the Jets,'' John Hess said. ``Please
know he will evaluate this season from another place.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on sunny East 87th Street now, pallbearers slid the
flag-draped coffin into the hearse, Norma Hess and the family
leaned into long black limousines for the ride to the New Jersey
cemetery, and familiar faces emerged from the synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells, the Jets' football major domo, and two of the
Jets coaches that Hess dismissed, Rich Kotite and Joe Walton.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Namath, along with Super Bowl III teammates Winston Hill,
John Schmitt, Dave Herman and Ralph Baker. Marty Lyons, Bruce
Harper, Richard Caster and Ken Schroy from the Jets of two decades
ago. Vinny Testaverde, Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet from the
reigning Eastern Division champions.
</P>
<P>
   And Dennis Byrd, a slight limp the only trace of his paralysis
from a 1993 helmet-to-helmet collision.
</P>
<P>
   `` Hess visited me in the hospital every night I was there,''
the former defensive end said. ``He taught me the values of
dedication, teamwork and loyalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Among all the dark suits and dark dresses was an older man in
shirt- sleeves, Saul Miller, who happened to be in the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a distributor of smoked fish,'' he said. ``I knew Hess in
passing from a friend of mine. He was a nice man. I'm trying to
find out where the Hess family will be sitting shiva. I want to
send over some bagels and lox.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, Leon Hess would have enjoyed that, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
