<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CASSATT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO ARTIST PORTRAIT LEAVES A LASTING IMPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a business where depictions of strong, independent women lean
heavily on the assumption that they must also be slightly wacko _
see ``Ally McBeal,'' ``Felicity,'' ``Sports Night,'' etc. _ it's
refreshing and fun to find a female character who doesn't define
her self-worth by how she gets along with a man. Or with her
neuroses, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Mary Cassatt is not appearing in a regular series right
now. All the more reason to check her out Tuesday night if you have
access to HBO. She's on in the second of six profiles of great
artists. These ``Artists' Specials,'' aimed at young viewers but
perfectly suitable for anyone interested in an uncomplicated,
well-intentioned story, follow the path of HBO's ``Composers'
Specials'' and ``Inventors' Specials.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them have been keepers, but ``Mary Cassatt: American
Impressionist'' is worth a visit. It is the second in the artists'
series, coming after last month's ``Degas and the Dancer.'' It airs
again Saturday m., and May 19, May 23 and May 28.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Brenneman, who may have had the best female role ever handed
out by the testosterone-drenched cop show, ``NYPD Blue,'' plays
Cassatt with an individualistic spark that's reminiscent of her
spunky ``Blue'' character, Janice Licalsi. It's probably closer,
however, to the recurring Faye Moskowitz role she has been playing
on ``Frasier'' lately: an arty, independent woman devoted to her
family.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Cassatt was exactly that, and Brenneman's portrayal is
attractive and eminently convincing, especially when she tells her
niece, ``There's nothing wrong with being a single, independent
woman. You can be someone in your own right.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers of network TV series claim to be delivering this
message all the time, but it usually gets lost as comedy writers go
for the easy (and demeaning) sex joke and drama writers opt for the
standard woman-in-peril scenario. ``Mary Cassatt'' offers no such
clutter. Brenneman plays the American artist as an outspoken,
uncompromising woman who sees no shame in being far from home and
unattached at a time when the mission of ``marrying well'' is
uppermost in the minds of women who shared Cassatt's privileged
19th-century upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   Though inspired by actual events, the story involves a fictional
encounter between Cassatt and her mentor, the Impressionist painter
Edgar Degas (Thomas Jay Ryan), arranged by Cassatt's 14-year-old
niece, Katherine (Charlotte Sullivan). Katherine, herself smitten
with the son of her aunt's maid, hopes to ignite a spark of romance
in what she perceives to be the dull Parisian existence of her
eccentric aunt, whom she initially considers to be ``a rigid old
maid with no prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   While the American Cassatt and the Frenchman Degas would remain
friends and collaborators, the romance Katherine hopes for never
materializes. As Cassatt says in the film, her paintings are her
children, and far more important to her than being ``a pendant on
some man's arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Cassatt's individualistic tendencies rub off on
Katherine, helped in part when Louisa May Alcott pays a visit and
announces: ``No girl could be my friend if she refused to climb a
tree, and no boy could be my friend until I'd beaten him in a
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, the presence of Katherine and her siblings in
Cassatt's well-ordered world provides inspiration that surprises
and delights the artist.
</P>
<P>
   On its surface, ``Mary Cassatt: American Impressionist'' is a
well-crafted tale about the riches that accrue to people who treat
each other with mutual respect, no matter their ages. Underneath,
it's a deft treatise on the sources of creativity, and it leaves a
lasting impression.
</P>
<P>
   Odds 'n' ends
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of strong women, fans of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
won't want to miss Tuesday night's episode. Buffy (Sarah Michelle
Gellar) marries Angel (David Boreneaz). But only in her dreams. ...
And now on to Fine whines. The one-hour series finale of ``The
Nanny'' airs Wednesday. Hard to believe Fran Fine (Fran Drescher)
has been getting away with it for six seasons. Seems like 12. ...
The verdict on Monica Lewinsky's ``Saturday Night Live'' appearance
last weekend: She wasn't bad. Pretty good, actually. Certainly good
enough to secure a summer internship at NBC. ... Youth be served:
ABC will air a one-hour special on Teen People magazine's 21
hottest stars under 21. The date? The 21st, of course, at 8 p.m.
Among the profilees are Britney Spears, Brandy, Mya, Aaliyah, LeAnn
Rimes, Kirsten Dunst and three of the four hotties of ``Dawson's
Creek'': Michelle Williams, Joshua Jackson and Katie Holmes. ...
Reason to celebrate: The WB's ``Unhappily Ever After,'' possibly
the most heinous series on TV, airs its 100th _ and last _ episode
on May 23. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
