<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-CARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION STUDY FINDS SATISFACTION WITH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abortion, one of the most commonly performed, and apparently
safest, surgical procedures, also has a high rate of patient
satisfaction, according to a survey released Monday that gave
patients a rare chance to rate the quality of abortion care.
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, by the Picker Institute, a Boston-based
nonprofit group that analyzes patient experiences, most women were
pleased with the care they received from abortion providers. The
study was funded by the Kaiser Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers interviewed women nationwide about waiting time,
pain control, and confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty percent of the 2,215 women surveyed rated their overall
care as ``excellent.'' Another third said their care was ``very
good'' or ``good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It confirms what we have been hearing from our patients: that
the quality of care is very important, and that they are
satisfied,'' said Pam Nourse, spokeswoman for Planned Parenthood
League of Massachusetts, which was among 12 abortion clinics whose
patients were surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the missing link in the story of abortion in
America,'' said Dr. David Grimes, former chief of abortion
surveillance for the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   The safety of the surgical procedure, Grimes said, has helped to
make legal abortion a public-health success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mainstream medicine now. I was born in the 1940s and
women were known to die of abortion complications in the US back
then,'' Grimes said. ``Today, the risk of dying from legal abortion
is less than dying from a shot of penicillin.'' For mothers, the
death rate is less than .001 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Phillip Stubblefield, chairman of the Boston Medical
Center's Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology, said the Picker
report is important because abortion patients are often young
women, and thus ``it may be their first serious contact with
medical providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Picker study is about quality of care, access to
abortion was found to be the biggest issue facing those seeking the
procedure. From 1982 to 1996, the most recent period for which data
are available, the number of abortion providers declined in the
United States by 30 percent. Clinics specializing in abortion
perform about 70 percent of all of the procedures. Hospitals
provide only about 7 percent of them. Almost 1.4 million abortions
are performed annually in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Saporta, executive director of the National Abortion
Federation, said state legislatures are passing onerous laws that
serve only to restrict the ability of clinics to operate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the kinds of things that do not add to the quality of
patient care, but just aim at increasing cost and making it
difficult for a clinic to stay open.''
</P>
<P>
   The Picker Institute president, Susan Edgman-Levitan, said the
study was a challenge to design because of the stigma attached to
abortion. Women, for example, were concerned that participating in
the survey might compromise their personal safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never heard that from any other patients we've
interviewed. People who have heart surgeries don't worry about
other people finding out that they had that procedure,''
Edgman-Levitan said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report found a high quality of satisfaction with
the care the women received, 21 percent wanted more privacy in the
recovery room out of a fear of being recognized by others.
</P>
<P>
   Pain control was rated as adequate by 91 percent of the women,
but one in five reported feeling more pain than they had expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if 100 percent said they were reasonably
comfortable,'' said Stubblefield, who added that his goal is to
avoid using general anesthesia, while still keeping women
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``General anesthesia is actually more dangerous than a
first-trimester abortion,'' Stubblefield said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
