<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIAN-TESTS-COX     05-10 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIAN-TESTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refugees have health tested in U.S.
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chronic heart problems and the heartache of war and loss are
some of the health conditions found among the first two waves of
ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo at Fort Dix, N.J., where they
are staying before resettling in American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ten refugees were admitted to New Jersey's Burlington Memorial
Hospital, said Lisa Swenarski, a spokeswoman for the Department of
Health and Human Services, which is coordinating the federal
government's Kosovo refugee operation.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people admitted had chronic heart or lung problems
that had worsened because they had no medication while fleeing from
their Kosovo homes and while staying in primitive refugee camps in
neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
   One young woman was admitted to the hospital's psychiatric ward.
She ``had witnessed her father and other family members being
killed,'' Swenarski said.
</P>
<P>
   Swenarski, normally a press liaison with the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta, is among many federal workers
temporarily reassigned to the Fort Dix effort, dubbed Operation
Provide Refuge. President Clinton has vowed to take in 20,000
ethnic Albanian residents of Kosovo who have fled the Yugoslav
province after Serb threats and attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees will be given months of federal medical and housing
assistance and will be eligible to stay in the United States if
they choose.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires all refugees to undergo a thorough physical
work-up, including blood work and chest X-rays. They are being
checked for contagious diseases, such as tuberculosis,
sexually-transmitted diseases and HIV. No positive cases of these
diseases have been reported. If found, those three diseases can be
grounds for the INS not to admit refugees; however, a waiver can be
granted when the person receives treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the crowded, squalid conditions in refugee camps
along the Macedonian and Albanian borders, numerous cases of lice
and scabies were anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're fairly healthy, and if they do need treatment for
ulcers or lice, we can take care of that right here with the
pharmacy,'' said Dr. Susan Cookson, who heads the CDC's Migration
Health Assessment Office.
</P>
<P>
   Since Wednesday, 859 refugees have been received at Fort Dix,
and another plane load of 422 was scheduled to arrive Monday
afternoon. The base has capacity to handle 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
