<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0413 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-2TAK     05-10 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL HOPEFULS WOOING HIGH-TECHNOLOGY EXECUTIVES, AND VICE
VERSA 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore makes a point in his Seattle
visits of stopping at Internet companies like Amazon.com, the
on-line commerce pioneer. Other presidential hopefuls, including
Sen. John McCain, Rep. John Kasich and former Sen. Bill Bradley,
have recently toured Microsoft's campus here.
</P>
<P>
   So far Gov. George Bush of Texas has not come near either
Seattle or San Francisco's Silicon Valley. But that did not stop a
group of high-technology executives from taking out a newspaper
advertisement in The San Jose Mercury News last month, calling Bush
one of the ``visionary leaders who understand the New Economy'' and
urging him to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   The dance is on between presidential candidates and
high-technology executives, who were once regarded as bit players
in campaign finance and whose industry in turn famously prided
itself on its libertarian streak and almost dismissive attitude
toward whatever was happening in Washington, D.C. Facing a host of
tax and regulatory issues, and with the landmark Microsoft
antitrust case serving as a powerful reminder that federal
officials can still sway the competitive landscape, many industry
executives are clearly deciding that it pays to have friends in the
White House and Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who has long sought to position himself as the
administration's champion of high technology and the Internet, has
extensive contacts in the industry and pulled in roughly $400,000
last month at a Silicon Valley fund-raiser given by John Doerr, a
founder of Technology Network, widely known as Technet, the prime
lobbying and fund-raising organization of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's competitor for the Democratic nomination, Bradley,
who spent a year as a visiting professor at Stanford University in
which he nursed his own Silicon Valley contacts, has also done
well, taking in about $1 million at a large San Francisco
fund-raiser last month that was well-populated with industry
executives.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, though pledged to stay in Texas until the end of the
legislative session this spring, is planning a big San Francisco
Bay Area fund-raiser for late June. Among those who signed the
recent pro-Bush newspaper advertisement, which praised the
Republican Bush for ``creating an environment that stresses
personal responsibility over government intervention, and
innovation over regulation,'' were James Barksdale, founder of
Netscape; Bob Herbold, chief operating officer of Microsoft Corp.;
Jeff Henley, chief financial officer of Oracle Corp., and Steve
Behm, a vice president of Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   It is still early in the campaign cycle, but it is already
certain that computer-industry donations will be a bigger factor in
the 2000 elections than they have been in previous elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless high-tech people unplug their telephones, sign off
E-mail and leave the country in the next 18 months, they're going
to give more than they've ever given before,'' said Larry Makinson,
executive director of the Center for Responsive Politics, a
nonpartisan research group that tracks campaign finances. ``They're
certainly being hit up like never before.''
</P>
<P>
   High-technology-industry contributions to 1998 congressional
campaigns totaled about $8.1 million, more than twice as much as in
the 1994 campaigns. Even as industry contributions will continue to
grow in 2000, they probably still will be well below the dollars
spent by other industries, like energy and banking, that have had
large lobbying and campaign-donation operations in place for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, whose total campaign contributions in 1998, $1
million, were more than triple its 1996 contributions, according to
the Center for Responsive Politics, is planning to have a major
presence in the 2000 campaign. (The contributions include
individual giving by company employees, political action committee
donations and so-called ``soft money,'' which is given to the
political parties rather than the candidates.)
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman, Greg Shaw, said the company acknowledged
it was ``a little slow in recognizing the importance of being a
more visible and more active participant in Washington,'' but now
was intent on ``sharing its views and experience'' with policy
leaders there.
</P>
<P>
   For the presidential aspirants, the booming industry is not just
an obvious source of money. It is also the creator of technology
that the candidates are intent on understanding, since it could be
vital to their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The number of American households with Internet access has
doubled to nearly 44 million since the last presidential election,
according to Forrester Research Inc., a company that monitors
technology trends. Candidates are already trying to use the World
Wide Web to attract voters, with sites that offer video clips,
questionnaires and invitations for visitors to ``get involved'' by
volunteering to work for the campaign, donating money or at least
signing up for regular E-mail updates.
</P>
<P>
   For the high-technology executives, there is a growing array of
reasons to want good friends in Congress or the White House. They
have already won legislation creating a moratorium on taxes for
Internet commerce, special visas for skilled foreign workers and an
extension of tax credits for research and development, though they
have had only minor success so far in measures to limit lawsuits
for problems related to the year 2000 computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, while the more established interests in the relatively
young computer industry, like Microsoft and America Online, are
getting increasingly involved in the political process, many newer
Internet companies and their top executives do not show significant
signs of doing so, even as their stock prices have climbed so high
that their market value has eclipsed that of huge companies in
other industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're Amazon.com,'' said Wade Randlett, Democratic
political director of Technet, the industry group, ``you're a new
company and you're trying to grow at 50 percent a quarter and your
competitors are trying to kill you _ that just doesn't allow you to
devote a lot of time to anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Amazon.com, Bill Curry, said the company had
recently designated a person on the legal staff to monitor
public-policy issues related to the Internet, and was evaluating
whether Amazon.com needed to do a better job of establishing
contact with public officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to avoid the mistake of being so focused on building a
business that some day we find out we need relationships in
Washington and we don't have any,'' Curry said.
</P>
<P>
   Calculating the precise impact the high-technology industry is
having on the 2000 campaign is difficult. The most recent filings
with the Federal Election Commission, for instance, show
contributions by individuals through March 31 and do not reflect
big fund-raisers held by both Gore and Bradley in the Bay Area last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The commission reports show Gore with about $83,000 in direct
contributions from executives at high-technology companies, but
they do not show the roughly $400,000 he pulled in at the
fund-raiser given by Doerr, a leading industry venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Many computer companies, which had minimal presence in
Washington in past years, have set up political action committees
for corporate giving, which are expected to make major
contributions to candidates or to the national parties as the
campaign heats up.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while many computer companies applaud the federal
lawsuit against Microsoft, in which a ruling is expected this
summer, and thus may have a reason to reward Gore, the case is also
a powerful reminder that the federal government has the potential
to wield enormous power in shaping the industry, all the more
reason for computer executives to take an interest in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   As Microsoft has become far more active in both making campaign
contributions and deploying lobbyists, and tried to fend off a
lawsuit pushed by a Democratic administration, there is no question
that the Republican Party has benefited.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the company's total contributions last year
went to Republicans. In 1992, just 20 percent of the company's
donations went to that party.
</P>
<P>
   And Republican presidential candidates, including McCain and
Kasich, have traveled to Microsoft recently to meet with top
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives said that the company was ``steadfastly
bipartisan'' and that increases on the Republican side were
attributable to the party's having taken control of Congress in
1994. Across the industry in general, many executives are not
particularly partisan, meaning that either party could make
inroads.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything else, Silicon Valley is on the 50-yard-line
of the political spectrum,'' said Randlett of Technet. ``It's
strongly free-market, free trade, pro-economic growth. And it's
pro-choice, pro-public education and pro-environment, with the same
if not greater fervor than the belief in free-market philosophy.
Whichever candidate is most centrist is going to do best here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
