<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-CONFERENCE-COX     05-10 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CONFERENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conference for technology-related business owners wraps up
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ Short of sticking ``.com'' at the end of his
company's name, software billionaire Jim Goodnight didn't stand a
chance at Monday's Internet-crazy technology conference.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Cary, N.C.-based SAS Institute Inc.
forecast that the nation's largest privately held software producer
would ring up sales of $1 billion this year. The 14.8 percent gain
over 1998 seemed shabby by Internet standards, Goodnight
acknowledged. SAS makes analysis and management software systems
that can run on a variety of platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want a really great company, you want one on the Web
and losing millions of dollars,'' he said. ``Then you've got a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The laughter died down, but the Internet frenzy only gained
momentum at the Upside Southeast Technology Conference, a gathering
of gung-ho startups, technology powerhouses and ventures
capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth annual conference, which attracted more than 500
people, ends today at Duke University's Fuqua School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   In a tribute to soaring internet stock prices and explosive
growth in electronic commerce, entrepreneurs, investment bankers
and academics predicted a bonanza for companies tied to Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Doubling every 100 days, Internet traffic is forecast to reach
more than 50 percent of U.S. households by 2003, compared with 28
percent today. Forrester Research forecasts that Internet commerce,
valued at $7.8 billion last year, will soar to $1.4 trillion over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running a business without a connection to the Internet will
be like trying to run a business without a telephone,'' said
Georgia Tech telecom professor John Limb, one of several Atlantans
attending the Durham, N.C., conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the hype phase of the Internet right now,'' he said.
``We are going to enter the quiet era in four or five years, if not
sooner, when people do not talk about the Internet because it is
just part of doing business.'' A panel of experts resisted the
suggestion that the Internet bubble might soon burst, especially if
the rapid-fire succession of initial public offerings (including a
half dozen or more in the next two weeks) drains investor demand.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Moran, chief executive of Durham-based KOZ inc., a
supplier of e-commerce and other Web services, said he wasn't
worried that companies are pouring billions of dollars into
Internet ventures, including many that aren't yet profitable.
</P>
<P>
   He said companies are investing in a ``cyber infrastructure,''
which he compared to the turn-of-the-century construction of
transcontinental railroad tracks by investors who had to sell bonds
to finance the projects. Just as rail service transformed
transformed America's transportation, so will the Internet reshape
business, Moran said.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that profits will increase as companies which are
currently expanding rapidly to capture market share on the Internet
eventually slow their growth and focus on the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Yobie Benjamin, a global Internet and e-commerce strategist for
Ernst &AMP; Young, tried to make financial sense of the high stock
valuations of historically unprofitable companies. He suggested
that such companies be valued by a combination of traditional
variables, such as revenues and assets, and the potential for
companies to excel in innovation, flexibility and execution.
</P>
<P>
   The method is helpful both in justifying existing stock prices
and predicting future gains, Benjamin said. But in one of the
conference's few sobering remarks, he added, ``I cannot predict how
(the method) will work in a bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
