u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUGOVA-NYT &LR;      05-10 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUGOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXILED ALBANIAN LEADER SUPPORTS NATO POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Dismissing Yugoslavia's assertion Monday that it would
withdraw some of its forces from Kosovo as ``unverifiable,'' the
moderate Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova made his clearest statement
yet that he fully supports NATO's position in the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is true, OK, but first we have to verify it,'' Rugova
said in an interview with reporters Monday in Rome. He referred to
the overture by President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, which
has been rejected by American and NATO leaders as inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am asking for is, first, the installment of an
intervention force there, NATO and Russian, that can check the
withdrawal of Serbian forces and begin letting refugees back in,''
Rugova said. ``Belgrade has to accept that first.''
</P>
<P>
   Rugova is an Albanian intellectual who was long the voice of
passive resistance to Serbian control of its Kosovo province, where
90 percent of the prewar population was Albanian. But he has been
something of an enigma since the NATO bombing campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war, he was a respected voice of moderate opposition
to Milosevic's policies. When the bombing began he remained in
Kosovo, and statements attributed to him by the Yugoslav news media
led NATO to declare him a hostage under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   His hard-line separatist rivals in the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army were less sympathetic, though, and called him a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova left for Italy last week with his wife and children. He
had until Monday been reserved about the circumstances under which
he had remained in his house in the Kosovo capital, Pristina, now a
decimated city under Yugoslav control.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, surrounded and at times overshadowed by Italian
politicians and Catholic lay workers who helped secure his release
from Yugoslavia, he seemed meek and reticent in his new exile in
Rome, a hostage not to Serbian hostility but to European
hospitality. At a meeting in the Vatican on Monday, Rugova, a
Muslim, bent and gratefully kissed the pope's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said that Yugoslav efforts to paint him as a willing
collaborator with Yugoslavia who opposed the bombing campaign were
``false and propaganda.'' He also said he endorsed the NATO
conditions for a halt in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   And while he again declined to speak specifically about the
conditions under which he had lived for the last six weeks he spent
in Pristina, he made it clearer that he had been under considerable
pressure not to reveal his true feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his position that Yugoslavia must accept NATO
conditions before the bombing can be ended, he said: ``I said all
that in my house, but there were no journalists there except
Serbian journalists. My friends in the West know me, but you have
to understand the conditions in Pristina. I was there with my
family. I ask for a little bit of human understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that rebel leaders had also deliberately misrepresented
his position. ``What they are saying about me is stupid and
propaganda _ it's not serious,'' he said, ``and it's tragic today
to talk like that at a time when millions of Kosovars are in
exile.''
</P>
<P>
   Rugova said he would nevertheless seek to unite the squabbling
Albanian factions. ``Despite all that, I will try to bring those
boys in Tirana together and do something to get us organized to
focus on rebuilding a political structure in Kosovo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova, who views himself as the eventual spokesman for Kosovo
Albanian interests if and when negotiations with the Yugoslav
government begin, repeatedly said that he did not want to discuss
the pressure he was under in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear that in other ways, he was yearning to talk
about his ordeal. Discussing his plans to go to Paris and London to
meet with European leaders, he referred to the recent weeks in
Pristina, with only his immediate family around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back there, I was alone,'' he said. ``I was alone with
animals. They came close to my house _ cats, cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came because they needed to be near a human being.'' He
added softly, ``Pristina is a ghost town _ it's unbelievable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
