u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLEANSING-BOS &LR;      05-10 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLEANSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US OFFERS DOCUMENTARY EVIDENCE OF KOSOVO `CLEANSING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With attention riveted on the possibility of a
rupture in big-power relations over the Chinese embassy bombing,
the US State Department Monday put forward its first attempt to
document Serb atrocities in Kosovo, which Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said had made the Yugoslav bombing necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which officials said went to press before last
Friday's embassy bombing and ``has nothing to do with the Chinese
situation,'' listed slightly more than 3,000 alleged executions of
Kosovar Albanians by Serbs. About 10 percent of the reported
incidents were based on the accounts of single witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000 figure compares with 800,000 killed in ethnic
slaughter in Rwanda in 1994 and about 1.5 million slain in Cambodia
in the late 1970s. The 700,000 refugees who so far have fled Kosovo
compares with about 2 million who fled a similar war in neighboring
Bosnia, where organized rape took place on a greater scale than
anything yet described in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO ``has done everything it can to avoid civilian
casualties'' and regrets the embassy bombing, Albright said,
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's ``military campaign is
directed first and foremost at civilian targets'' _ an assertion
she said was proven by the report.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador David Scheffer, the lead US official on war crimes
issues, said ``what has occurred in Kosovo, with the possible
exception of Rwanda in 1994 and Cambodia in 1975, is truly
unprecedented with respect to the degree and ferocity and the short
time span with which an assault on a civilian population has taken
place. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The important point,'' Scheffer said, ``is: Is the
political-military response to the human rights crisis and the
humanitarian crisis warranted?'. . . What this report recounts is
the scale and intensity of the crime and the need for strong action
to oppose it.''
</P>
<P>
   In later questioning, State Department spokesman James Rubin
sharply defended Scheffer's assertion, asserting that the Kosovo
persecutions were unrivaled for the speed with which so many
refugees had been put to flight. He said that ``this is just the
beginning of the process of learning how many people died,'' and
revived a claim made early in the war, but not heard recently, that
100,000 men are ``missing.''
</P>
<P>
   US and NATO officials have suggested the men could be either
dead or in concentration camps, but have produced no evidence or
witness accounts so far of deaths or detentions on that scale. The
largest suspected detention camp listed in the report Monday
reportedly contains 5,000 ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the ranks of officialdom, there is growing concern at
the way the United States and NATO are invoking the plight of the
refugees and demonizing Serbs in general and Milosevic in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we make one of these major mistakes, we say `Oh,
those poor refugees,' '' said Uri Ra'anan, director of Boston
University's Institute for the Study of Conflict, Ideology and
Policy. ``Each time, we say the bombing will continue, possibly at
an accelerated rate, and then we throw in, `and look at those
refugees.' How many times are we going to do this before the public
gets wise to the fact that this is all going very badly?''
</P>
<P>
   Ra'anan said the use of the refugees to justify policy is
blocking Congress and the media from attempting unsentimental
appraisals of how the campaign against Milosevic's forces is going,
and whether the assumptions on which the assault on Yugoslavia was
launched remain valid. He particularly bristled at assertions by
defenders of the policy equating events in Kosovo with the
genocides in Rwanda and Cambodia, or suggesting a similarity to the
Nazi Holocaust in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are using this know it is absurd nonsense,'' he
said of the analogy.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Nye, dean of Harvard's Kennedy School of Government and
assistant secretary of defense earlier in the Clinton
administration, said a danger of making absolutist accusations
against Milosevic and the Serbs is that such demonization could
make it hard for NATO nations to accept a resolution of the
conflict that falls short of displacing the Serb leader and
militarily defeating his forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is not Hitler,'' Nye said. ``Milosevic has done some
very bad things; the Serbs have done some very bad things,'' but
they are only worse by degrees than other forces in the region
which did not suffer armed attacks from NATO or the United States.
He noted specifically that the US said little about the
Croat-Muslim struggle that decimated the historic and beautiful
city of Mostar, and nothing about ethnic cleansing committed by
Croats against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Ra'anan also cautioned that using the plight of the Kosovar
Albanians and refugees to justify use of force dramatically changes
the definition of NATO as an alliance to defend its own members and
friendly sovereign allies.
</P>
<P>
   Displacement of Albanians was occurring mainly within Kosovo
until the bombing started, he said, ``and if the US can intervene
on behalf of the ethnic Albanians'' in this way, ``couldn't the
Russians use these same arguments to rationalize intervening in
behalf of ethnic Russians in Latvia and Estonia? We have created a
terrible precedent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
