<HEADLINE>
EMERGENCY SPENDING REQUEST INCLUDES JET LEASES FOR GENERALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An urgent request from the Air Force is buried in
the multibillion-dollar emergency bills that will finance NATO's
air war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Smart bombs? F-16 fighters?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. The Air Force wants to lease Gulfstream executive
business jets to ferry four-star generals around the world. The
cost could run to half a billion dollars over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The aging 707s that transport nine of the nation's top military
commanders simply won't do, the brass complains. They want the
top-of-the-line Gulfstream V. The planes can fly eight passengers
non-stop for 7,500 miles, wrapping them in sweet silence and
comfort, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force already has two Gulfstream Vs for the very highest
government officials. Moguls from the movies and Microsoft fly
them. Why not the military's most powerful commanders, men like
Gen. Wesley Clark, now running NATO's air war?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a hot issue,'' said a congressional staff member
working on the Senate's still-evolving emergency bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to look like you're buying the CINCs executive
jets,'' he said, referring to the military's nine unified and
regional commanders-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   So the Pentagon and the Senate Appropriations Committee
chairman, Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, worked out a deal that would
let the Air Force lease six Gulfstreams for the commanders,
congressional staff members said.
</P>
<P>
   The new fleet would give them ``the capability to travel within
the full length of their theaters or to Washington, D.C., without
an en route stopover,'' the Air Force said in a fact sheet
submitted to Congress two weeks ago to underscore the commanders'
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the nine commanders, Clark, is actually based
overseas. The other regional and unified commanders work in
Virginia, Illinois, Colorado, Nebraska, Hawaii and Florida, where
three of them have headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But with the United States playing the role of the world's sole
superpower, their responsibilities are global, the Pentagon
contends.
</P>
<P>
   Those who support the request _ none of whom would be quoted by
name _ say leasing conceivably could be cheaper than maintaining
the Boeing 707s. And the Gulfstreams cost less than the planes some
of the commanders originally sought: a fleet of Boeing 767s, which
run upwards of $100 million apiece. One new Gulfstream was included
in this year's Pentagon budget.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Gulfstream V can only carry a small contingent.
So the Air Force says it might also go for two Gulfstreams and four
specially equipped 737-700s, which carry at least 126 passengers in
their commercial configuration.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's emergency spending bill includes a measure aiding
Central American hurricane victims, which is where the leasing
arrangement actually originated. It goes to conference Tuesday with
the $13 billion measure passed by the House last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Gulfstream measure includes only the legal authority to sign
a lease _ no money. It doesn't mention the money at all.
</P>
<P>
   But the leasing deal, if carried out, could cost $476 million or
more over 10 years, according to Air Force documents and
congressional staff members.
</P>
<P>
   It would actually cost less to buy each of the nine commanders
his very own personal Gulfstream V _ $333 million. But then it
would look like Congress was buying the commanders the jets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
