<SLUG> BC-SCI-DRUG-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FDA CHIEF DEFENDS FAST-TRACK SYSTEM FOR DRUG APPROVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKVILLE, Md. _ When the Food and Drug Administration was
forced to ban five prescription drugs in a recent one-year period,
critics said the agency had compromised patient safety as it
hurried new medicines to market. Monday, the agency's new
commissioner responded, making public an internal review that found
the agency's emphasis on speedy drug approvals was not to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has the standard been maintained at a high level?'' Dr. Jane
Henney, FDA commissioner, asked during a briefing with reporters at
the agency's headquarters. ``The answer to that is yes. Adverse
events are no greater now than when the system was slow.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, commissioned by Ms. Henney when she assumed control
over the agency six months ago, took a wide-ranging look at the
risks posed by products the FDA approves, and how the health care
system copes with those risks. With many new drugs and medical
devices coming into the market, the report concluded, government
and private industry must work together to develop a ``new
framework'' for reducing risk that will draw doctors, hospitals,
pharmacists and patients into a dialogue about drug safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``In calling for a broader drug safety debate, this is a step
forward,'' said Thomas Moore, a health policy fellow at George
Washington University Medical Center and a frequent critic of the
FDA. ``Saving lives and preventing injuries is going to have to
involve doctors and patients and medical groups. It isn't just a
simple matter of blaming the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   But agency officials are sensitive to being blamed, particularly
in light of the ban on the five prescription drugs, including the
painkiller Duract, the hypertension drug Posicor and the
antihistamine Seldane, during the 12-month period that began in
September 1997. Critics, including Moore, have said those drugs
should never have been approved.
</P>
<P>
   The report issued Monday is one of two new studies, both
conducted by current and former FDA managers, to examine whether
the withdrawal of those drugs was the direct result of the
Prescription Drug User Fee Act, a 1992 law that enabled the agency
to speed drug reviews by hiring additional reviewers with fees from
the pharmaceutical industry.
</P>
<P>
   The other, led by Dr. Michael Friedman, acting FDA commissioner
until Ms. Henney took over, will be made public Tuesday and
published in this week's Journal of the American Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, the average time for approval of a new drug
has dropped to 12 months from about 30 months. In addition, the FDA
report said, the agency has sharply increased the number of new
medicines it approves each year to an average of 97 from an average
of 70. Although the arm of the agency that approves medical devices
does not receive money through the user fee act, it too has dropped
its review time, to 12 months in 1998 from 27 months in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   With respect to drugs, the study commissioned by Ms. Henney
found that over the past 20 years, the FDA had consistently
withdrawn 1 percent to 3.5 percent of all the new compounds it
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the five drugs that were pulled from pharmacy shelves
from September 1997 to September 1998 were reviewed prior to
adoption of the 1992 law, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   And, the authors found, unexpected serious reactions to new
drugs are occurring less frequently today than in the past.
Nonetheless, the report recommended that the agency develop units
to track problems with drugs after approval.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings did not quiet the agency's critics, among them
Dr. Sidney Wolfe, director of Public Citizen's Health Research
Group, an advocacy organization in Washington, who questioned
whether the agency was ``disregarding the views of its own
physicians'' who objected to the marketing of certain drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said he conducted a recent survey of the agency's 172
medical officers; 53 responded, he said, and of those, 19
identified a total of 27 drugs that were approved over their
objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly applaud the idea that more attention has to be
paid once a drug gets on the market,'' he said. ``But to say, as
FDA does, that you can assume that all those drugs that are on the
market should be there, is just a reckless statement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
