<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS FOR NATIONAL CAMPAIGN AGAINST YOUTH VIOLENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to halt the spasm of school shootings,
President Clinton opened a national campaign against youth violence
Monday by challenging all Americans to do more to purge gory images
and easy access to weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The White House hosted a three-hour East Room strategy session
that brought 60 artists, parents, students, religious leaders,
police officers, gun manufacturers and gun control advocates
together for the first time to discuss ways to curtail violence by
youths.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton convened the conference after the April 20 Columbine
High School massacre in Littleton, Colo., in which two teen-agers
killed 13 people and themselves. It was the latest in a series of
school shootings that experts blame on a variety of ills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that there is more for us to do at home and at school,
in Hollywood and the heartland and here in Washington. Every
parent, every teacher, every leader has something more to do,''
Clinton said as Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and
Tipper Gore joined him in the Rose Garden after the session.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady announced the formation of a nonprofit
organization that would continue the national campaign, using as a
model the administration's efforts to combat teen-age pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will come forward, we hope, with very specific suggestions
about what parents can do, what schools can do, what community
groups can do, what the media can do, what gun manufacturers can
do, what all of us can do,'' Hillary Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president urged parents to turn off the television when they
see programming they don't like and to keep an eye on computer use
and to refuse to buy products that glorify violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If no one consumes these products, people will stop producing
them. They will not build it if you don't come,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He also encouraged the entertainment industry to join the cause,
saying its ``wholehearted participation'' was needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot pretend that there is no impact on our culture and
our children that is adverse if there is too much violence coming
out of what they see and experience,'' Clinton said. ``We have to
ask people who produce things to consider the consequences of them
_ whether it's a violent movie, a CD, a video game. If they are
made, they at least should not be marketed to children.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Clinton again called on Congress to pass legislation
raising the legal age to purchase weapons from 18 to 21. He also
has called on manufacturers to install child-proof locks on weapons
and wants to extend the instant background-check system to weapons
sold at gun shows. Earlier, a group of gun manufacturers and
pro-gun groups endorsed portions of Clinton's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Initial worries by entertainment and gun advocates that the
meeting would turn into a finger-pointing session proved unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very productive meeting. There was absolutely
no finger pointing, no bashing that went on,'' said Bob Ricker,
executive director of the American Schooling Council, an
association of gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Rifle Association, which was not invited to the
White House, held a competing new conference to accuse Clinton of
failing to enforce gun laws. ``We have the tools to get at this
culture of violence and don't do it,'' said Wayne LaPierre, NRA
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition also criticized the session, renewing
its call for a school prayer amendment and tax cuts that it says
would allow parents to spend more time at home. It ran
advertisements on its ideas in Iowa and New Hampshire, two key
presidential election states, to coincide with the White House
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the session drew a cross section of the nation's opinion
leaders, ranging from poet Maya Angelou to Steve Case, the
president of America On-line. The heads of ABC, which is a part of
Disney, and CBS also were on hand as were four religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here as a parent. I got invited because, I guess, of my
career, but I am here as a concerned parent. Everyone is concerned.
Everyone is shocked. I think we all want to be a part of the
solution,'' said singer Gloria Estefan. ``I think it would be
horrible if our children saw all these things being discussed and
nothing really came of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Estefan said she also opposed censorship. ``To me music has
always been a mirror image of what youth is feeling and I think it
would be ludicrous to try to censor that because this is a good way
for us to look at how these kids are feeling. This is a tool for
parents to sit down and have a conversation about what's going
on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
