<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOYS-EMOTIONS-COX     05-10 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-EMOTIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Rescuing boys from `gender straitjacket'
 &HT;    (EDS: Also moved to E (Entertainment) category.)
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Young boys would prefer to express their emotions
with tears and hugs, if only we'd let them without calling them
sissies or mama's boys. They tell psychologist William Pollack they
wish they could talk about deep or difficult feelings without being
ridiculed, the way girls can.
</P>
<P>
   `` 'I guess guys can't do those things that normal people do,'''
Pollack recalls one teen-age boy's telling him. As long as we
embarrass boys out of showing such feelings as pain, fear,
dependence or sadness, he says we can expect some of them to emote
through guns and pipe bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack's paperback book describes the consequences of teaching
boys at a young age that the world is not a safe place for males
with vulnerable feelings and offers some ways to make it safer, one
boy at a time. The Harvard Medical School researcher's book is Real
Boys: Rescuing Our Sons from the Myths of Boyhood ($13.95, Henry
Holt).
</P>
<P>
   The ``Boy Code,'' as Pollack calls it, requires real boys and
real men ``to be competitive, be a big wheel, be a sturdy oak. They
should take everything with a stiff upper lip, and the worst
possible thing would be for them to ask for help or admit they
can't achieve all this on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder they never ask for directions when they grow up and
drive cars, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Placed in society's ``gender straitjacket,'' Pollack says boys
are compelled to look tough even as they feel afraid and alone.
They notice the contradiction, of course, but they're ashamed of
that vulnerability. Real boys don't feel that way, they've learned,
so something must be wrong with them.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the only alternatives seem to be either repressing all
emotions or expressing them violently, the way a ``real man''
would.
</P>
<P>
   ``Littleton is the tip of an iceberg, and the iceberg is boys,''
Pollack says of the Colorado school massacre last month. His
opinions were in sudden demand after that, with television
appearances on Oprah the next day and at a town meeting in
Littleton the next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the warning signs?'' people asked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What signs do you mean?'' he asked them back. ``The signs that
someone is likely to kill somebody or the signs of boys who are
developing along the lines of becoming depressed and hurt, some of
whom will go to that point?''
</P>
<P>
   Boys are at least four times more likely than girls to commit
suicide, Pollack writes, and nearly 10 times as likely to be
diagnosed with a serious emotional disorder, usually attention
deficit disorder. From ages 8 through 12, they have more and deeper
cases of clinical depression. But girls' depression is easier to
diagnose, with more classic symptoms of sadness, while boys'
depression often surfaces as patterns of anger, misbehavior or
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does a boy have to grow up feeling ashamed of who he is
and confused about what it means to be a real boy or a real man?''
Pollack says. ``Why does he have to marry and not be able to talk
to his wife about his feelings? Why, after that first argument with
his wife, does he have to get drunk? And after the fifth, have an
affair? And after 15 years of marriage, have a divorce? And after
the second divorce, why does he have to have a midlife crisis,
which is really a depression?''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack answers his questions with the word ``shame,'' a term
psychologists use because ``dissed'' doesn't look good in
professional journals. They don't mean the remorse people feel
because of something they did, but the shame they feel because of
how others acted toward them.
</P>
<P>
   If you're snubbed by an old friend who didn't recognize you, you
might feel shame. If the old friend was only pretending not to
recognize you, he might feel remorse. He might act differently the
next time he sees an old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``But shame doesn't lead to correcting behavior,'' Pollack says.
``Shame leads to enactment or withdrawal. Some boys will go as far
as hurting or killing somebody else not to be shamed.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not suggesting that parents encourage their boys to break
out of this gender straitjacket by sobbing on the basketball court
or hugging the best friend who helped them do homework. He'd like
to see society change to accept vulnerable emotions from males, but
he knows it won't happen tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Pollack says parents, teachers and coaches can
take steps to help.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing is creating what he calls ``shame-free
zones,'' where boys can express their natural emotions. Parents do
that by making boys comfortable talking about their anger or
sadness in the basketball game or their warm gratitude for the
schoolwork help.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers should be made to feel comfortable hugging and cuddling
their sons without the fear of turning them into wimps, Pollack
says. And fathers should be comfortable that roughhousing with
their sons won't turn them into violent outlaws and hugging them
afterward won't make them soft. ``It turns out, the research shows
boys who do that have fewer temper tantrums.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools must recognize that young boys who don't like sitting
still for long stretches ``are not being bad, or poor students,''
he says. ``They're being normal boys, and we should not shame them,
punish them or medicate them out of who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches need to give boys the constructive outlet of competitive
play, he says, and not the middle-aged memories of being told they
played like girls. The most important thing they can teach is how
to lose without the world falling apart. ``Men don't learn that,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   So grown-up boys don't know how to cope with life's losses, and
they feel like talking about their disappointment or frustration
will only make them losers again. ``And we're just accepting
that,'' Pollack says, ``because we assume that's the way boys
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
