<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CASSATT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARY CASSATT': A DELIGHTFUL FAMILY DRAMA
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Broadcast notes are at the end of the review. Time, channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Cassatt did not really stand in her Paris studio in 1878,
pause in her work on a painting she planned to show at the Salon
and tell her teen-age niece, ``There's more to life than marriage,
my girl.'' But it would have been nice if she had. That indulgent
fantasy is at the heart of ``Mary Cassatt: American
Impressionist,'' a thoroughly charming episode in the occasional
series of HBO family dramas called ``The Artists' Specials.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the Composers' Specials and the Inventors' Specials in
previous seasons, here children help great creators arrive at their
best work. Apparently Leonardo da Vinci and Albert Einstein would
have been nowhere without the young friends who quizzed and
inspired them. The idea is handled with such glee and fidelity to
the creators' work (if not to history) that the specials are bound
to please both children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Brenneman (better known from ``NYPD Blue'' and a current
guest stint on ``Frasier'') is appealingly down to earth as
Cassatt. The paintings she works on are exact copies of the
artist's; the beautifully designed production is so full of
references to her work that it resembles a Cassatt come to life. So
what if the story takes liberties with the chronology of her career
and makes itself accessible through modern attitudes and language?
It is an engaging, lively tale that turns out to be a subtle lesson
in art, independence and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   The child-heroine is Cassatt's 14-year-old niece, Katherine, who
begins the drama with the timeless line, ``I will never, ever
forgive my parents.'' The last thing she wants is to be away from
her friends in Philadelphia on a vacation with her parents and
younger brother and sister to visit the aunt she calls an ``old
maid.'' And at first Aunt Mary is not happy to have three children
and a puppy scampering around her studio. But in the course of this
hourlong story, the children provide her with all sorts of
practical help.
</P>
<P>
   One day the youngest child, Elsie, is watching her aunt work.
``Why are you using all dark colors?'' Elsie asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because that's the traditional style &UR; , &LR;  and the Salon is very
traditional,'' Cassatt sighs. (She is working on ``The Musical
Party,'' one of her more conventional paintings.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I like bright colors,'' says Elsie, who happens to be sitting
in a bright blue chair, dressed exactly like the child in Cassatt's
vivid ``Little Girl in a Blue Armchair.'' ``So do I,'' the aunt
says, setting aside her old canvas and starting on what we soon see
as that completed, recognizable painting.
</P>
<P>
   If Cassatt learns fast, Katherine does not. Standing outside a
gallery window, looking at a canvas of a Degas ballet dancer, she
complains, ``You can't make out the faces, they're all blurry.''
Aunt Mary rolls her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes it so remarkable!'' she says, and explains a
little about Impressionism.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine does have a flair for romance, though. She has a
flirtation with Gilbert, the son of Cassatt's maid. And all three
children play matchmaker, arranging for Aunt Mary to meet her idol,
Degas. Fantasies go only so far, even in this fiction; Degas does
not become Uncle Edgar. He does become Cassatt's friend and
artistic colleague.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Cassatt's brother and his family did pay a crucial
visit to her in Paris, but that happened in 1880, after she had
already met Degas and exhibited with the Impressionists.
</P>
<P>
   And Cassatt's parents were living with her at the time. She may
have had a rebellious streak, but she remained a respectable lady
from Philadelphia, properly chaperoned.
</P>
<P>
   None of that would have made as good a story. Only the most
churlish historical stickler would be able to resist this tale's
inspired bits of creative license. One day Louisa May Alcott comes
to tea and asks Katherine, ``What do you want to do with your
life?'' (In fact, Louisa's sister May, the inspiration for Amy in
``Little Women,'' was a friend of Cassatt's when both lived in
Paris, so it's not that much of a stretch.)
</P>
<P>
   The Artists' Specials are not to be confused with HBO's
heavy-handed ``Dear America'' series, which focuses on girls in
historical settings and proves that playing games with history is
not enough to make a lively series. ``Mary Cassatt'' is a delight
because it is first of all an endearing story about how Katherine
and her independent-minded aunt come to understand and love each
other.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE ARTISTS' SPECIALS'
</P>
<P>
   Mary Cassatt: American Impressionist
</P>
<P>
   7 p.m. Tuesday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Created by David Devine and Richard Mozer; produced and directed
by Mozer; produced by David Devine; written by Heather Conkie.
</P>
<P>
   With: Amy Brenneman (Mary Cassatt), Thomas Jay Ryan (Edgar
Degas), Charlotte Sullivan (Katherine Cassatt), Jonathan Koensgen
(Robert Cassatt), Emma Isherwood (Elsie Cassatt) and Noah Shebib
(Gilbert).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
