<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     05-10 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS FIND ELBOW ROOM WITH DUDLEY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ How many Knicks fans thought they'd ever look for Chris
Dudley to come to the rescue?
</P>
<P>
   But with the Knicks facing a succession of Armageddon-type games
against a suddenly desperate Miami, including Monday night's Game 2
of this opening-round playoff series here, Dudley's sharp elbows
and knees have assumed a prominent role. Depending on how you look
at his salary _ $7.5 million this season, then $7.1 million, $6.2
million and $6.2 million _ Dudley is either the rich man's Charles
Oakley or simply a rich man.
</P>
<P>
   As the Knicks have gone from a team relying solely on strong-arm
tactics to a more transition-ready team, the 6-foot-11-inch,
260-pound Dudley is the last vestige of the team's black-and-blue
era. He stands as a reminder to the Heat _ and anyone else _ that
for all the talk about ``new Knicks,'' there is bruising muscle at
the end of the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   With Oakley gone, Dudley has becomes more than a rebounder, but
someone counted on to shake things up, create some chaos and, in
this Miami series, try to push Miami's Alonzo Mourning beyond his
breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say protect, but I definitely expect to be inside
and a physical force on the boards, defending the post,'' Dudley
said. ``These games with Miami _ you know how physical they can
get. They can be wars. I enjoy that. I expect to be in there mixing
it up.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of Dudley's tenure with the Knicks, his problem has
been fitting in, or at least finding a role. Last month, as the
Knicks began to jell, Dudley found his niche. He started in place
of Patrick Ewing in a crucial game against Charlotte, and bumped
and banged Hornets center Elden Campbell into 3-of-14 shooting.
Dudley scored 7 points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our second unit is a high energy group,'' Dudley said. ``With
Marcus, Latrell, Chris and myself, we try to keep the intensity
level up. Especially coming off the bench, I don't have to worry
about the fouls. I can really make things happen, especially if the
tempo is a little slow. I just try to mix it up get the intensity
going. Pick up the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of his 12-season career in the National Basketball
Association, the Knicks' 34-year-old backup center has been
perceived as precisely that, an overpaid backup, even when he was
starting with the Nets and Portland. When he signed a huge contract
with the Nets, fans scratched their heads; when he got a larger
contract with Phoenix, they scratched their heads again. When the
Knicks picked him up in a trade with Portland, the common wisdom
was that Dudley was one more big body in a big-body offense. Then
last season, Ewing shattered his wrist, Dudley started 22 games in
his place, and it seemed the acquisition had paid off.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 4 of last season's Knicks-Heat playoff series, Dudley
was so physically tough in defending against Mourning, he proved
instrumental in lifting the Knicks to the victory. When Dudley
fouled out late in the fourth quarter, the Garden crowd gave him an
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   This season has been more uneven for Dudley, who has alternated
between not playing to starting to playing a minimum number of
minutes as the Knicks struggled to find a groove.
</P>
<P>
   In March, during a game against the Lakers, Dudley provoked
Shaquille O'Neal into a push that that cost him a $3,500 fine.
Dudley was fined $2,500 for throwing the ball at O'Neal in
retaliation. On April 25, in a game in Miami that the Knicks
desperately needed, Dudley was torched for 27 points by Mourning.
But at the moment of truth, Van Gundy put Dudley on Mourning for
Miami's final possession. He bodied Mourning, pushed him just out
of his range and forced him to put up an awkward shot as the Knicks
by 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally its been a little up and down but it ended on a
real good note,'' he said. ``At the end of the year I was playing a
lot. And the stretch when we were 21-21 and we had to win six out
of the last eight or five out of the last eight, that probably is
when I felt I played some of my best games. I started a lot of
those games and really think I helped us to get over that hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Knicks, Monday night's game notwithstanding, have become
a team within a team _ more agile and athletic on the surface, but
still full of elbows and knees.
</P>
<P>
   In this bizarre season, Dudley is beginning to feel appreciated
for his ``skills.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have felt that,'' he said. ``It's fun to contribute, for
people to expect me to get things going, keep things going. It is
reward to be part of that, I felt that in Portland and New Jersey.
It feels good to feel that here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
