<SLUG> BC-DEAD-BILLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS OF UNPOPULAR TEXAS BILLS ARE DEAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When it comes to moving unpopular bills through
the legislative process, ``never say die'' is an unwritten law
among House members.
</P>
<P>
   But with the arrival of Monday's deadline for House bills to
pass House committees, one could almost hear the faint, final gasps
of hundreds of unsuccessful measures _ some old, some new _ echoing
through the Capitol halls.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these faltering bills could be revived as amendments to
viable legislation before the session ends May 31. Other concepts
may survive through similar Senate versions that are still
breathing. However, most of the bills left pending in House
committees are simply dead.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Among the dead and dying ideas are a lower sales tax rate,
approval for state-run casinos, a ban of hog-dogging and the option
for juries to sentence a murderer to life without parole. Also
languishing in House committees were proposals to repeal the
anti-sodomy law, ban same-sex marriages and gay adoptions, mandate
parental consent for a minor's abortion and require premarital AIDS
testing.
</P>
<P>
   A measure making it possible to execute 16-year-old murderers
(the minimum age now is 17) appears dead as well, as does a bill to
end executions of the mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   Other early victims of the clock were bills to wrest control of
the Alamo from the Daughters of the Texas Revolution; to declare
Austin as a capital district subject to direct legislative control;
and to require turkey hunters to use shotguns (rifles are allowed
in most parts of the state).
</P>
<P>
   Also dead were bills to ban use of cellular phones while driving
and to totally rewrite the Texas Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is designed to kill bills, not pass bills, which
is probably pretty good,'' said Rep. Rob Junell, D-San Angelo. The
influential chairman of the House Appropriations Committee is among
members with many dead bills on file.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bills that really should pass really do. Those that should
die, die. And there's some kind of never-never land in between
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, about 4,000 bills were filed in the House this
session and 1,800 in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, here is a rundown of some of the House bills that
likely won't make it into law:
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 343, by Rep. Arlene Wohlgemuth, R-Burleson, to
require parental ``consent'' for a minor's abortion. (A bill
requiring parental ``notification'' is still alive.)
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 383, by Rep. Warren Chisum, R-Pampa, preventing the
state from recognizing same-sex marriages performed in other
states.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 475, by Rep. Glen Maxey, D-Austin, prohibiting
employment discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 3069, by Rep. Juan Hinojosa, D-McAllen, barring
execution of the mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 1389, by Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston, making it
illegal to conduct a fight between a dog and a hog, a popular East
Texas sport.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 337, by Rep. Debra Danburg, D-Houston, repealing
the Texas Penal Code provision that makes sodomy a crime.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 11, by Rep. Tony Goolsby, R-Dallas, would require
turkey hunters to use only shotguns, not other firearms.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 607, by Rep. Talmadge Heflin, R-Houston, would
lower the state sales tax from the current 6.25 percent to 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 1525, by Wilson, would place the Alamo in San
Antonio under Texas Parks and Wildlife Department jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 3077, accompanied by a proposed constitutional
amendment, both by Wilson, would declare Austin to be a ``capital
district,'' subject to hands-on legislative managing.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 350, by Wohlgemuth, would create ``covenant
marriages,'' requiring couples to sign a prenuptial agreements that
would demand extra efforts before divorcing.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 717, by Chisum, would mandate premarital testing
for HIV.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 41, by Rep. Jim Pitts, R-Waxahachie, would change
the penal code to say that no person younger than 16 could be
executed. The code currently sets the lowest age for execution at
17.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Bill 77 by Rep. Pete Gallego, D-Alpine, would eliminate
the possibility of parole for those sentenced to life in prison.
Inmates serving life currently are eligible for parole after
serving 40 calendar years.
</P>
<P>
   _ House Joint Resolution 86, a proposed constitutional amendment
by Wilson, would authorize state-operated casinos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
