<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDOMIR-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS BUSINESS: NEW OWNER AND STADIUM FOR JETS?
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Naturally, the next owner of the Jets will want a new stadium.
It would be the only way to justify a price tag that will probably
exceed $500 million. The late owner Leon Hess never agitated for a
new stadium or squawked that he had a less-than-grand deal at
Giants Stadium, where revenues are split among the Jets, the Giants
and the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Hess was the antithesis of the modern team owner, who plays
cities against each other to win the stadium lottery. If the Jets
were ever displeased with their lease, you never heard it publicly
from Hess or Steve Gutman, the team president. Their typical
response was that the lease was solid through 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Even after meeting with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in January, Hess
never told the news media about the plans he was given for a
stadium on the West Side of Manhattan. Hess, who was planning to
show the city's plans to National Football League officials, was
too ill to schedule a subsequent meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that the Jets need a new stadium to be competitive,
but it would not hurt, especially by 2009 when even more teams will
be in new homes. In the Bill Parcells era, the Jets have shown the
ability to spend what is necessary on players. But as recently as
1996, the Jets were receiving $2 million a year from a special
league fund set up for fiscally needy teams.
</P>
<P>
   So it is difficult to imagine a new owner, whether it might be
Donald Trump or Charles Dolan, the chairman of Cablevision, gladly
paying $500 million without the cash flow afforded by a new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, whose name has been bandied about as a possible owner,
pulled out of consideration Monday. ``I want to make it known that
I am not part of any group, nor will I ever be part of any group,
that attempts to purchase any equity in the Jets,'' the coach said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Al Lerner, who will start life as the new Cleveland
Browns owner in a new stadium, a new Jets owner will need foresight
to look beyond the Jets' occupation of Giants Stadium through 2008
to a new stadium packed with steeply priced luxury suites and club
seats, plus a cushy naming-rights deal.
</P>
<P>
   What separates the wealthiest NFL teams from the remaining
wealthy teams is the stadium deal. Teams that own their stadiums,
like the Washington Redskins, or those with leases that route
nearly every cent to their bottom lines, like the Browns, emerge as
the league's most valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the difference in stadium revenues in 1998 between the
Jets at 23-year-old Giants Stadium and the Redskins at two-year-old
Jack Kent Cooke Stadium:
</P>
<P>
   The Jets kept about $18.3 million from gate receipts, after
paying rent (about $3.2 million) and the visiting teams' shares
($11.1 million). The Jets received $1.14 million from concessions,
$1.13 million from luxury suites, $900,000 from stadium advertising
and $831,193 from parking.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins performed somewhat better. Their $5.7 million rent
payment went from Corporate Pocket A to Corporate Pocket B.
Estimates of 1998 revenues pegged luxury suite and club-seat fees
at $29.9 million, advertising at $3.8 million, concessions at $2.7
million and parking at $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how juicy the Redskins' situation looks _ the
prospective owner, Daniel Snyder, still has about $160 million in
stadium debt to pay _ the Jets will get nothing to compare for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   When Jack Kent Cooke died in April 1997, it took 17 months for
his estate to put the team on the market. But the estate, hamstrung
partly by litigation with Cooke's former wife, did not decide to
sell its largest assets, like the Redskins, until the summer of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   If there are no major obstacles, the Jets' sale should move
faster, especially if Hess' will directs that the team be sold
before other assets or directs it to negotiate with a particular
buyer.
</P>
<P>
   DUVAL AND WOODS, ONE-ON-ONE: Snaring the rights to the
prime-time, $1.5 million Tiger Woods-David Duval exhibition on
Monday, Aug. 2, was crucial for ABC Sports. The network was
approached by the International Management Group six weeks ago,
about the time Howard Katz became the president of ABC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make a statement about the new ABC Sports,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ABC wants to call attention to itself and show that it will
be more active in the sports-rights game. ``We think people will
talk about this in the days before the match and in the days
after,'' Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   But ABC nearly did not get the match. Barry Frank, the senior
corporate vice president of IMG, said that he approached
pay-per-view distributors before calling on the broadcast networks.
He said he was uncertain whether a network would pre-empt
prime-time programming. ``But ABC stepped up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For various reasons, CBS, NBC and Fox passed on the program's
concept or the price. ``We didn't want it in prime time and didn't
think it had a place on our golf schedule,'' said Ed Markey, a
spokesman for NBC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, NBC and Fox would have incurred heavier costs than ABC to
pre-empt programming. Katz said his bosses did not resist the
rights fee or the cost of replacing one Monday night's prime-time
reruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were excited about it from the start,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
