<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET EXECUTIVES WILL DOMINATE BANKBOS-MERGER ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp.
agreed in March to combine into the nation's eighth-largest bank,
their chief executives went to great lengths to describe their
blockbuster transaction as a merger of equals _ despite the fact
that Fleet was technically acquiring its smaller rival.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, as the two companies announced a second round of key
appointments that again puts many Fleet managers at the top ranks,
the idea of a merger of equals for New England's two largest banks
had all but withered away. Now the rhetoric from Fleet and
BankBoston is about plucking the best parts of each company and
planting them in a new corporate framework.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new appointments, Fleet executives are in charge of
retail and commercial operations at the combined bank, reflecting
Fleet's particular strengths.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston executives are in charge of international banking,
investment banking, and large-scale corporate banking _ areas where
the nation's oldest bank, with Latin American operations, San
Francisco investment bank Robertson Stephens, and an A-list of
corporate clients, has considerable experience.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fleet executives have around 30 of the new top spots
while their BankBoston counterparts have around 25. Overall, Fleet
now has around 60 percent of the top positions. That weighting
suggests that Fleet is deepening its control of the new bank _ but
not excessively dominating it.
</P>
<P>
   When the two companies first announced their $16 billion deal,
they spoke insistently of a merger of equals, and Gifford took
umbrage at words like ``acquisition'' and ``takeover.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the outset, Fleet moved quickly to put its imprimatur
on the transaction, naming its own managers to most of the very top
positions and placing its chief executive, Terrence Murray, in the
highest spot. Industry analysts, eyeing the two banks' radically
different lines of businesses, spoke of the new company as a
hybrid, not as a union of evenly matched entities.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the latest appointments, Murray said he now
preferred to call the Fleet-BankBoston combination a ``strategic
alliance,'' rather than a merger of equals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're integrating the best of both companies,'' Murray said
Monday by telephone from Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gifford, when asked if he would call the deal a
merger of equals, asked rhetorically, ``What is equal?'' He
continued later: ``This is a merger of our two companies and the
organizational chart reflects that.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of equal vs. dominant is not just semantic. Banking
analysts say the recent appointments and the philosophy behind them
are crucial to success at the new company, which will have more
than $160 billion in assets after divestiture. Executives
disoriented by organizational changes or left in limbo for too long
can torpedo cost-cutting and revenue-building plans by
misunderstanding how the new company fits together. Problems at the
top filter down throughout the organization, causing insecurity
among lower-rank staffers and chaos. In a rapidly consolidating
financial world, neither investors nor consumers are kind to banks
that mangle their mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an early and `deep' announcement that sets your whole
infrastructure in place and gets many questions answered,'' said
Sally P. Davis, a banking analyst at Goldman, Sachs Inc.
</P>
<P>
   While industry analysts said Monday they were encouraged by what
they viewed as signs of cooperation between the two very different
banks, Fleet and BankBoston still must prove they can assemble a
powerhouse institution out of disparate parts. Both banks have
swallowed major competitors in recent years but face a strong
challenge in creating a new culture out of their different
corporate approaches. Fleet is generally viewed as aggressive and
hard-nosed, while BankBoston is seen as more sensitive to community
issues.
</P>
<P>
   As previously announced, BankBoston chief executive Chad
Gifford, who is the new company's number two until Murray retires
at the end of 2001, oversees most of the new bank's business lines
and day-to-day operations. Murray, who has said he will turn over
the reins to Gifford after retiring, handles strategy, technology,
finance, and staffing issues.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Higgins, now Fleet's president and chief operating
officer, will oversee retail and commercial banking, reporting to
Gifford. His counterpart at BankBoston, Henrique Meirelles,
overseas global banking and financial services.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, known as a ruthless bottom-line manager, will oversee a
cost-cutting drive designed to trim $600 million from the new
company, which will have nearly $3 billion in income next year, its
first year of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet chief financial officer Eugene McQuade retains his
position after the merger, and reports to Murray.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise appointment, Bradford Warner, in charge of
BankBoston's New England consumer bank and domestic private bank,
will oversee investment services at the new company. But Fleet
executives dominate the individual investment groups under Warner,
including mutual funds, private banking, and Fleet's Quick &AMP; Reilly
discount brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Snowden, head of BankBoston's highly regarded community
banking network, retains her position in the new bank, reporting to
Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   Another rising star is Fleet's Anne Finucane. Now in charge of
corporate communications, marketing, and advertising, she gains
additional duties at the new bank, including government relations,
public policy, and internal communications. Finucane, a close
Murray ally who in an unusual move will report directly to Gifford,
is seen as a key figure in helping the two companies create a new
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hogan, now BankBoston's head of wholesale, or large
corporate, banking, will oversee institutional and investment
banking, reporting to Meirelles. Leo Breitman, now head of Fleet's
commercial banking group, will oversee middle-market commercial
banking, reporting to Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's chief investment officer, Thomas O'Neill, will continue
in that role, but his BankBoston counterpart, Ned Riley, will not
join the new company, Gifford said. Although not included in
Monday's announcements, Fleet's chief economist, Nicholas Perna,
will have the top slot when a new round of appointments is made in
coming weeks. His BankBoston counterpart, Wayne Ayers, may leave
the combined company, sources familiar with the matter said.
</P>
<P>
   David Eyles, who handles risk management at Fleet, will continue
in that role at the new bank, with his BankBoston counterpart, John
Mastromarino, reporting to him. BankBoston's technology chief,
Joseph Smialowski, will head up technology when his Fleet
counterpart, Michael Zucchini, retires later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the line-up, Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Cleary Inc.
said: ``They each truly picked their best people.''
</P>
<P>
   But the selection process was fraught with quarrel and tension,
and decisions were announced several weeks later than expected.
Several key executives from both banks, including BankBoston
corporate affairs chief Ira Jackson and Fleet Bank of Massachusetts
president John Hamill, agreed during the negotiations to step
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Murray and Gifford wrangled over the appointments for weeks in
five one-on-one sessions, arguing over three points: whether the
investment bank should be part of the global or the corporate
banking unit; whether cash management should be part of commercial
or institutional operations; and whether leasing should be under
commercial finance or somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   While those debates might sound esoteric, they lie at the heart
of the new company's ability to function. Messily structured
business lines can doom the new bank on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``These charts are not really important to the outside world,
but they are terribly important to the inside world,'' explained
Nancy Bush of Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. ``Until these announcements were
made, you don't know who your boss is going to be, and life
virtually comes to a halt.''
</P>
<P>
   The two banks, which expect to gain regulatory approval for
their merger in the fourth quarter and will eliminate 5,000
positions, will now focus on cost-cutting and revenue-enhancing
plans. Those tasks, likely to be painful and difficult, must be
done well for the new bank to avoid becoming a takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say so-called mergers of equals rarely work since
they obscure who is in the driver's seat and competitive edges off
strong franchises.
</P>
<P>
   But with Fleet-BankBoston now clear about who is in control and
which parts of each bank will survive, the new company has dropped
the mergers of equal line in favor of one reflecting differences
betweeen the two banks.
</P>
<P>
   Said Murray: ``This reflects the core strengths of each
company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
