u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-TARGETS-BO     05-10 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-TARGETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELECTING TARGETS A   COMPLEX, UNCERTAIN PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three days after US pilots bombed the Chinese Embassy, thinking
it was a Yugoslav weapons agency, the reason seems to be a case of
the left hand not knowing what the right hand was doing.
</P>
<P>
   The key mistake was that the maps of Belgrade on which the US
targeteers relied _ drawn up in 1992, but reexamined as recently as
last year _ did not show that the embassy had moved to its current
location.
</P>
<P>
   A senior intelligence official, briefing reporters at the
Pentagon Monday, said that, to prevent such mishaps in the future,
the State Department will now be ``forwarding, more routinely,
information about embassies'' and their changes of address.
</P>
<P>
   So is the State Department to blame for not telling the Pentagon
that the Chinese Embassy had moved?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily. Until very recently, Yugoslavia was not a
country that the Pentagon had planned on bombing. No US military
command had a ``target list'' for Belgrade _ as the Strategic Air
Command once had for cities in the Soviet Union and the Warsaw Pact
(Yugoslavia was never a member).
</P>
<P>
   The US charge and his diplomatic staff in Belgrade would
probably have known the location of the Chinese embassy. The CIA
station chief would have certainly known. But it would not have
been an automatic procedure to pass along this bit of intelligence
to Air Force targeteers. Nor would it have been standard procedure
for the Air Force targeteers to ask.
</P>
<P>
   The senior intelligence official said analysts have gone back
over the archive of data, to see if anything was overlooked. ``We
have not found any reports to the data base that the Chinese
Embassy had moved,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   This ``data base'' is the vast file of information gathered,
processed, and put together by a variety of Western _ primarily US
_ intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force's National Reconaissance Office operates the fleet
of spy satellites, snapping and transmitting photographs as they
spin.
</P>
<P>
   The National Imagery and Mapping Agency turns these photos into
maps.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Intelligence Agency, a branch of the Air Force in
Arlington, Va., identifies certain buildings and other objects on
these maps as targets. Key targets would include military
headquarters, barracks, command-control centers, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   This process of identifying targets is aided by the National
Security Agency, which intercepts electronic transmissions, phone
lines, and other methods of communication.
</P>
<P>
   As targets are identified, special analysts at the Air
Intelligence Agency try to infer the structure of the targets and
what kinds of weapons would be needed to destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   This information is passed along to NATO's Combined Air
Operations Center in Italy, which assigns munitions to planes and
planes to targets.
</P>
<P>
   But all this, apparently, was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   John Pike, a private weapons and intelligence specialist at the
Federation of American Scientists, said: ``I've looked at enough
overhead photographs of rooftops to see you've still got to have
someone with a notebook or a camera, walking around, knocking the
pavement.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, partly because of strained relations between
the United States and Yugoslavia, partly because Belgrade was not
considered a logical target of US bombing anyway, there may not
have been enough people knocking the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can imagine last summer, someone figuring Belgrade might be
a target at some point,'' Pike said. ``I can imagine someone
saying, `How many guys can we send to do walking tours without the
security police getting suspicious?' Maybe enough to look at things
we were going to hit _ but maybe not looking at all the things we
didn't want to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior intelligence official at the Pentagon Monday seemed
to support Pike's imaginings. ``Nobody was going out looking for
the Chinese embassy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
