<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV16-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDING STUDENTS TO GO OVERSEAS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn., N.Y., Maine)   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The number of U.S. college students going overseas for part of
their undergraduate work is rising, and has been rising for some
years. At Carleton College in Northfield, Minn., where the director
of off-campus study says courses overseas are ``part of the
undergraduate experience, part of conversation at dinner,'' 310
students joined foreign study programs in 1997-98; this was 17
percent of a student body of 1,858.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation at Carleton is not typical. Nationwide, the
total of almost 100,000 students who participated in overseas
programs in 1996-97 represented about 1 percent of the 8.7 million
students enrolled in colleges granting bachelor's degrees The
increase continued steady _ 10,206, or 11 percent, in 1996-97, the
most recent available figures.
</P>
<P>
   These statistics worry the president of the organization that
gathers them, the Institute of International Education in New York,
a major nonprofit organization that works for international student
exchanges and manages many such programs. The president, Allen E.
Goodman, says that the glass is not half full but half empty.
</P>
<P>
   He says students need to study overseas to prepare to work and
compete in the world market. The country's commerce and
international relations, he maintains, will depend heavily on how
familiar graduates are with the world, its languages, history and
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman sees a number of trends converging: a decrease in the
study of foreign languages in high school, the evidently small
number of students _ 5 or 10 percent _ who arrive at college with
passports, and the popularity of English-speaking countries for
overseas study: a quarter of enrollments are in England, Ireland
and Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   But the oncoming steamroller he sees is the Internet. ``English
is the language of the Internet,'' he said, ``and this makes people
think they are closer than they are.'' They think, he said, that
because they have communicated with someone in the Middle East that
they know about the Middle East, but they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman and the Institute for International Education are
starting several projects to encourage students to go overseas as
undergraduates. In cooperation with the State Department, he is
working on a ``let's get a passport'' project for high school
students. Information on getting application forms from the
Internet will be provided. ``If they have passports,'' he said,
``they will figure out how to use them.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that by the time a student is a college sophomore,
getting a birth certificate from home may be complicated. He has
persuaded the University of California at Los Angeles to add a
question about passport possession to its national survey of
college freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Iseminger, the director of off-campus study at Carleton,
said that the overseas programs her college sponsored cost no more
than on-campus enrollment, except that students must pay to travel
to foreign countries instead of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   At Colby College in Waterville, Maine, where semesters overseas
are also a major attraction, the head of off-campus study,
Professor Jon Weiss, said that a student's cost for a semester
overseas in one of the Colby's own programs is the same as the
regular comprehensive fee at home. This includes air fare to the
overseas site, Salamanca, Spain; Dijon, France, or London.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said some of these subsidized the others: the round-trip
fare to Spain recently, for example, was $900, more than twice the
fare to London.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said that in the new effort he would also be seeking
channels for money for students who cannot manage the cost:
churches, community centers, corporations. Figures gathered by
William W. Hoffa for a new book, ``Study Abroad, a Parent's
Guide,'' show that at private colleges where financial aid packages
may be applied to study overseas, participation by nonwhite
students increases.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Spring is the time students begin looking at programs for a year
hence, particularly checking the ones conducted by their own
colleges, although the junior year is no longer the only chance for
study overseas. Half of the enrollments are by juniors, 16 percent
by seniors and 12 percent by sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   At Colby, a college of 1,760, about 57 percent of juniors spend
a semester overseas, but the college also has 67 to 70 students who
start college overseas. By graduation, Weiss said, 70 percent of
the class has had an ``abroad experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many colleges, Colby charges a fee to students who sign up
for programs sponsored by other schools; its fee is $1,000,
measured against the $29,000 comprehensive fee. Nationwide, about
two-thirds select their own school's programs, or those directed by
a consortium to which their college belongs.
</P>
<P>
   There are two main reference works for overseas courses, both
large, heavy paperback books: ``Peterson's Study Abroad 1999,'' a
guide to 1,700 semester and year-abroad courses, and ``Academic
Year Abroad 1999-2000,'' edited by Sara J. Steen and published by
the Institute of International Education, covering 2,700 programs.
Most colleges have these in the library. They can also be bought
from bookstores or directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academic Year Abroad,'' is available from the Institute of
International Education, 809 United Nations Plaza, New York, NY
10017; (800) 445-0443. The publisher sells it for $42.95, plus $6
for shipping. For ``Study Abroad,'' contact Peterson's, 202
Carnegie Center, P.O. Box 2123, Princeton, NJ 08543; (800)
338-3282. This sells for $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   Neither organization evaluated the specific programs it lists.
Many decisions are based on whether the student's college will
provide credit for a course; both books have caveats on this issue
along with information on passports, health, getting around,
identification cards and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa's ``Parent's Guide'' is a valuable smaller book that
breaks the issue down into useful bites. It covers everything from
selecting a course to the child's safety. The historical survey and
statistics of all sorts clarify the questions to be asked before
decisions are made.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa and Goodman do not always agree, but are in harmony when
it comes to the Internet. ``Telecommunications can interfere with
students' cultural adjustment,'' Hoffa said. ``Sometimes in cases
of homesickness, a call to Mom or an e-mail to a friend allows the
students to avoid the need to adjust to the local environment.
Until that umbilical cord is cut, there is no rebirth.''
</P>
<P>
   His book, which came out a year ago, is not in bookstores. The
publisher, the Association of International Educators, 1875
Connecticut Ave., N.W., Suite 1000, Washington, DC 20009, sells it
for $15 plus $5 shipping.
</P>
<P>
   High school students too go abroad. One resource for organized
programs is the Advisory List of the Council on Standards for
International Educational Travel, which will appear in its
1999-2000 edition this summer. It offers evaluations, but only of
programs that ask for it and pay a fee.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the programs focus on bringing students into the
United States. Copies are $15, domestic postage included, from
CSIET, 212 Henry St., Alexandria, VA 22314; (703) 739-9050.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
