<SLUG> BC-INMATE-AWARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    And the Grimmy goes to...a convict?
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Miami Valley's outstanding adult literacy
student of 1999 won't be able to pick up his Grimmy Award in person
at today's fourth annual ceremonies because he has a prior
commitment _ in the Montgomery County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Project READ, the local literacy umbrella group, is honoring Hal
Trevor Lutz for improving his reading from a fourth-grade to a
seventh-grade level just since October.
</P>
<P>
   The Grimmy Award, named after a character in the Mother Goose &AMP;
Grimm comic strip, honors students and tutors in adult basic
educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   Lutz, 35, is the first jail inmate to receive a Grimmy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will not be able to make it (to the ceremony),'' said jail
spokeswoman Sanita Branch. ``Federal prisoners don't leave our
facility without the accompaniment of federal agents, and I doubt
they'd be interested in taking him to accept an award, no matter
how highly they may think of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lutz is awaiting sentencing by U.S. District Judge Walter H.
Rice after pleading guilty to a count of conspiracy to distribute
cocaine, which carries a maximum penalty of 10 years to life in
prison and a fine of $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   He has been in jail since February 1998, when Drug Enforcement
Agency officials arrested him on charges of running drugs and money
from Chicago to Dayton as part of a cocaine ring. Agents found 39
kilograms of cocaine and $314,000 in cash in Lutz's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Ten other people were charged with being part of the conspiracy.
In all, nearly $1.3 million in cash and more than 85 pounds of
cocaine were seized in connection with the drug ring, the largest
such seizure ever in southeastern Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest was a turning point for Lutz, who has a wife and two
sons in his home state of California, according to his tutor,
Americorps member Anne Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says in his (acceptance) speech he didn't hit rock bottom,
but he got a wakeup call,'' said Banerjee, who was to accept the
award on Lutz's behalf today.
</P>
<P>
   Lutz was willing to be interviewed, but his attorney's
permission could not be secured in time to arrange an interview in
jail on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Banerjee said Lutz's progress has been ``just phenomenal. He's
gone from stumbling over words to reading pretty fluently. This is
a guy who never touched a book. Now he just devours books _ I give
him one and he's done in two days and wants another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Karla Hibbert-Jones, executive director of Project READ, said
literacy officials had some qualms about honoring Lutz because they
didn't want to give the impression that people with literacy
problems tend to be criminals. Criminals do, however, tend to be
uneducated _ 75 percent of Ohio prisoners lack a high school
diploma or its equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   But Lutz ``truly stood out in terms of what he accomplished
academically,'' Hibbert-Jones said. ``He clearly was the
outstanding (student), in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   A family member will take custody of the award until Lutz is
released.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably won't let him keep it in jail,'' Hibbert-Jones
said, ``because it could be used as a weapon. It's a big glass
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lutz, who quit school after sixth grade, hopes to get his
General Educational Development high school equivalency diploma
and, eventually, a degree in culinary arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have a long time to get his GED,'' Hibbert-Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beyerlein writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
