<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1701 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-2TAKES-N     05-10 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY BOMBING IMPEDES DEALS ON KOSOVO AND CHINA TRADE STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-CHINA, KOSOVO-SASSER, KOSOVO-CHINA-TRADE) 
(rm) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade
threatens to drag out a diplomatic solution in Kosovo and to sour
an already-troubled relationship with China, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although administration officials were confident at first that
the crisis would soon blow over, they now see signs that the
Chinese government will delay a U.N. Security Council resolution
requiring an international security force in Kosovo, a senior
administration official said. That resolution is at the heart of a
proposed diplomatic settlement to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than vetoing such a resolution outright, the Chinese
signaled Monday that they would try to obstruct the
administration's diplomatic strategy by demanding that NATO halt
its bombing against Yugoslavia before the Security Council could
consider any other action on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations on Monday, the Chinese ambassador, Qin
Huasun, said that suspending the air strikes was an essential
precondition to any discussion by the Security Council on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything short of that is impossible for the U.N. Security
Council to discuss any plan to solve the problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing may also imperil negotiations over the entry of
China into the World Trade Organization. Anti-Western officials in
Beijing are using the embassy bombing to make their case against
economic concessions that Prime Minister Zhu Rongji offered during
his trip to Washington last month.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Chinese would benefit from entry into the trade
organization, the Clinton administration has based much of its
strategy for improved relations with China on extending economic
ties. But just as anti-Americanism is riding high in Beijing,
anti-Chinese anger is simmering on Capitol Hill among those who
believe that Washington as been too lax on security and should not
be abetting China's grand entry onto the world economic stage..
</P>
<P>
   A deal with the Chinese on their entry into the trade group
needed to be accomplished in the next few months when Congress
would be most amenable, officials said Monday. But the events of
the last few days have jeopardized the administration's hope for a
speedy timetable.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, concerned that the Chinese continue to refuse
his explanation that the bombing was a mistake, apologized for the
third time Monday. He sent a letter to the Chinese president, Jiang
Zemin, Sunday and publicly expressed regrets Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say to the Chinese people and to the leaders of
China, I apologize. I regret this,'' Clinton said in remarks before
a ceremony on youth and violence at the White House, after China
demanded that the United States apologize.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, used the
crisis over the air strike to pile more pressure on the
administration by announcing a partial withdrawal of his forces
from Kosovo. The announcement did not state how many of his
estimated nearly 50,000 troops in Kosovo would be removed.
</P>
<P>
   There were differences in tone in the reaction of various
Clinton officials. The secretary of state, Madeleine Albright,
dismissed the announcement as a ``half-measure.'' Clinton said,
``I'm encouraged by any good word.'' But he insisted, like other
NATO officials who were cautious in their reaction, that other
terms must be met to reach a settlement. ``I think that the
conditions that we set out are the minimal ones to make this
work,'' the president added.
</P>
<P>
   As the administration worked at holding its Kosovo policy
together, the Russian envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, arrived in
Beijing to talk to Chinese officials about Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who is looked upon by the administration as one of
the best hopes for pushing a diplomatic solution with Milosevic,
changed his travel plans after the embassy strike and headed for
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they assumed that because
the Russians were eager to play a predominant role in finding a
solution in Kosovo, Chernomyrdin would encourage the Chinese to be
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the image of senior officials of two anti-NATO
countries, China and Russia, meeting over Kosovo, the place where
NATO's future hangs in the balance, was a little unsettling for
administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the officials said, they were confident
Chernomyrdin would ask the Chinese not to block a Security Council
resolution on the international security force.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Russians, the United Nations is an important venue,
and it's important for them to argue back home that they've brought
this issue back to the United Nations and out of the hands of
NATO,'' a Russia expert in the administration said. ``I think their
position to the Chinese is going to be: `Don't screw up the
possibility of a Security Council resolution. Let's try and get it
closer to our terms.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council became a pivotal part of the solution
in Kosovo last week when the seven richest industrial countries and
Russia agreed in Germany to a set of principles that would end the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Among the principles was an international security force for
which Russia and the seven countries said they would seek to get a
U.N. mandate.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO accidentally bombed the Chinese embassy in Belgrade,
the strategy for a Security Council mandate was put in jeopardy
because of China's veto power. Beijing illustrated how it could use
that veto earlier this year when it vetoed the continuation of a
U.N. force patrolling in Macedonia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said during the
weekend that he believed the Chinese would not exercise their veto
on the international force.
</P>
<P>
   Berger argued that the Chinese have been against the NATO
bombing since its start. ``Vetoing the force would put them in the
position of wanting to prolong the bombing and being against
peace,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   But others in the administration were not so sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping to get the ball rolling in New York at the
United Nations this week but that has all been put off,'' said a
State Department official. ``The question is how far has this set
us back and for how long. Whether the Chinese will calm down in a
week or two is not at all clear.'
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council met for two hours Monday to discuss the
bombing of the embassy but came to no conclusion on a Chinese draft
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese wanted the council to adopt a statement condemning
the bombing as a ``blatant encroachment on the sovereignty of a UN
member state.'' It asked NATO to ensure that ``all individuals
responsible for the incident be brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was supported by Russia and Namibia and opposed by
five NATO members of the Council: the United States, Britain,
France, Canada and the Netherlands. All council statements, formal
or informal, require the agreement of all 15 members of the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the issue of Kosovo, the White House was faced with
repairing damage to the foundation of its relationship with
Beijing, one that Clinton has tried to cultivate as a legacy of his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Some administration officials took heart from the fact that the
policy of engagement and the two summit meetings by the two leaders
in the past two years meant that there was some depth from which to
work. But others said they were concerned that the anti-Americanism
unleashed by the embassy bombing portended for great difficulties
in restoring a semblance of trust.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on the embassy also occurred at a trying time in
China's domestic politics _ when unemployment is soaring, the
conservatives are challenging the modernizers and the 10th
anniversary of the killings of hundreds of protesters in Tiananmen
Square looms next month.
</P>
<P>
   China's suspension of high-level military ties, and talks over
arms control, international security and human rights in protest of
the bombing meant that contacts between Washington and Beijing were
at their lowest since 1995 when relations plummeted over Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The suspended meetings covered issues that the Clinton
Administration cares greatly about: accusations that China has
provided nuclear weapons or missile technology to Pakistan and
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   To show its pique, China called off a visit by the Boston
Symphony Orchestra and curtailed a visit by the German Chancellor,
Gerhard Schroeder. In another sign of irritation, when the White
House suggested that Clinton would like to call Zemin to express
his condolences, the Chinese said they would prefer that Clinton
send a letter.
</P>
<P>
   The president said in the letter that he looked forward to
speaking to him ``when he is ready,'' the White House spokesman,
Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
