<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIMA SAYS MEDICATION LED HIM TO LIE IN POLICE BRUTALITY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: 2nd take is scheduled to move within 30 minutes.) 
(nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abner Louima endured a grueling day of
cross-examination Monday by defense lawyers, who hammered away at
lies he had admitted to telling and conflicts in his various
accounts of his alleged beating and torture by four police officers
in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Louima, a 32-year-old Haitian immigrant, calmly responded by
attributing some of the conflicts to a memory clouded by medication
in the days after he was injured, and said it was ``my choice'' to
follow a supporter's advice to falsely tell a grand jury that one
officer said, ``This is Giuliani time,'' during the alleged
assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I give evidence before the grand jury, I was under
medication and my memory, it wasn't clear like it is now,'' Louima
said.
</P>
<P>
   Answering a lawyer representing one of the officers, who had
demanded to know ``why your testimony is different today than it
was when you testified for the grand jury,'' Louima said, ``Now I
am not really worried too much about my health.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Louima suffered injuries to his rectum and
bladder after he was beaten and tortured after his arrest in a
street melee in 1997. Referring to those injuries, Louima said of
his answers at this trial: ``I don't have to carry a colostomy bag,
like I was thinking maybe I have to carry for the rest of my life.
I am more peaceful now. I have a better chance to think.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, responded sarcastically, ``You
were peaceful enough to commit perjury in the grand jury, weren't
you?''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange came as Kornberg, who represents Officer Justin A.
Volpe, cited several falsehoods and a series of inconsistencies in
the accounts Louima gave to state and federal grand juries and
investigators and to the media in the months after he was
reportedly brutalized.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe and three other officers are on trial in the racially
charged case in federal court in Brooklyn. The four officers,
charged with violating Louima's civil rights, are white; Louima is
black.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the officers are accused of beating Louima in a police
car after his arrest; Volpe and another officer are charged with
torturing him in a restroom at the 70th Precinct stationhouse.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of relentless questioning, Kornberg did not ask Louima
to respond to Kornberg's most explosive suggestion in the trial:
that Louima's injuries were not the result of Volpe ramming a stick
into his rectum, as the prosecution says, but by a consensual sex
act with another man before Louima encountered the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg later declined to say why he had not asked Louima about
this. But there was no doubt that Louima would have denied the
suggestion, and Kornberg has already indicated, in his opening
arguments to the jury last week, that he intended to support the
suggestion through testimony by medical experts who would tell the
jury that a sex act was consistent was Louima's injuries.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
