</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLORADO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITINGS PROMPTED WARNINGS FROM LITTLETON TEACHER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Mich.)   (jw) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Columbine High School officials said Monday that the
English teacher of Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris had warned their
parents one month before the shootings about the violent nature of
their sons' writings.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Klebold's school compositions, which included descriptions
of a killing, were brought to the attention of his mother, Susan
Klebold, and of his school guidance counselor, said Marilyn
Saltzman, a spokeswoman for the Jefferson County Public Schools.
The high school senior dismissed the writing as ``just a story'' in
conversations with his counselor, whom Ms. Saltzman declined to
identify.
</P>
<P>
   An essay in which Eric Harris portrayed himself as a shotgun
shell prompted the same teacher to have a similar talk with his
father, Wayne Harris. Once the teacher learned that Harris was a
retired Air Force officer and that his son hoped to enlist in the
military, she concluded that the essay was consistent with his
future career aspirations, Ms. Saltzman said.
</P>
<P>
   A student in the class, Kevin Hofstra, recalled recently that
Eric Harris wrote about ``some strange stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One assignment was to write about an inanimate object,''
Hofstra said. ``Most people would choose a bicycle or something. He
chooses a shotgun shell and writes about his relationship with the
barrel. He often wrote about shotguns.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest video to come from the school also had elements of
foreboding. The syndicated program ``Inside Edition'' broadcast a
two-year-old video, intended to be humorous, that shows students
wearing black trench coats and carrying guns as they move through
the school's hallways. As four students walk away from Columbine,
the school explodes in orange flashes.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold did not appear in the film, which
was partly edited by Brooks Brown, a classmate who knew the pair
well. In a coincidence, another editor of the film, a 1997
Columbine graduate, is the son of Dwayne Fuselier, the lead FBI
investigator in the killings. An FBI spokesman has said that the
agency has full confidence in Fuselier, a 51-year-old psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   School officials have declined to allow interviews with the
teen-agers' English teacher or with their film teacher.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the shootings, the family of Isaiah Shoels, the
only black victim in the killings at the high school in Littleton,
Colo., has hired Geoffrey Fieger, the Michigan lawyer who won the
Jenny Jones talk show case last Friday and who was until last fall
Dr. Jack Kevorkian's lawyer. Fieger has said he may sue Jefferson
County Public Schools for negligence. Michael Shoels, Isaiah's
father, has accused a Columbine dean of ignoring a complaint he
made in early April that his son had received racist death threats
from the trench coat mafia, a school clique that included Eric
Harris and Dylan Klebold and that was noted for long black trench
coats.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three weeks since the killings in Littleton, about 80
investigators are working on the case, evaluating about 10,000
pieces of evidence, 1,800 tips and 1,300 interviews.
</P>
<P>
   In the only arrest so far, Mark Manes, a 22-year-old neighbor of
the gunmen was formally charged Monday with providing a minor with
the handgun used in the shootings. According to the police, Manes
supplied one of the boys on Jan. 23 with a Tec-DC9 assault pistol.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for clues and confederates of the two gunmen,
investigators have also submitted a friend of the pair to a lie
detector test and have scoured the park areas of Eric Harris'
neighborhood for the remains of old pipe bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks Brown, a neighbor of the Harrises, has said that the pair
used to set off bombs in the neighborhood. Employees at a Blackjack
Pizza delivery outlet, where the young gunmen worked, have said
that on one occasion in the past year Eric Harris displayed a pipe
bomb to co-workers at the store. He was on juvenile probation at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   New evidence has emerged that, in the minutes before their
attack on Columbine, the gunmen used timers to set off two
diversionary bombs, one four miles away, the other two miles away.
The goal apparently was to confuse and delay police and fire
workers responding to emergency calls from the high school.
</P>
<P>
   Each bomb, disguised in a backpack, was based on two 16-ounce
camp-stove-size propane tanks. Passers-by have said that one of the
bombs sent up two successive fireballs, each 40 feet high and seven
feet in diameter. The gunmen had less luck with a 25-pound propane
bomb in the school kitchen. Judging by a pattern of bullet holes in
the kitchen wall and from a security videotape recovered from the
cafeteria, investigators believe that, when this bomb failed to
detonate, the frustrated attackers repeatedly shot at the propane
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Still shocked by the attack, Columbine students and their
families received several morale boosters in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, in an event closed to the news media and
billed ``Columbine Surprise Party,'' players from two of Denver's
professional teams, the Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos and the
Colorado Rockies baseball team, mingled with 1,500 Columbine
students and family members at a nearby high school, signing
autographs and eating pizza.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Shania Twain, a country singer who was in Denver for
a concert, visited the five Columbine students who remained
hospitalized. On May 20, the one-month anniversary of the killings,
President Clinton is scheduled to visit, the White House announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, dozens of volunteers started dismantling a shrine
covering the size of a football field in a park adjoining Columbine
High School. On Sunday, for the second time, votive candles sparked
a fire, which consumed a canopy tent, floral bouquets, scraps of
poetry and stuffed teddy bears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1713 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-2TAKE     05-10 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO ISOLATE YUGOSLAVIA, NATO PLANS TO OPEN TWO NEW FRONTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-DIPLO) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO's air commanders plan to open two new
fronts in the bombing campaign against Yugoslavia, launching
strikes from Turkey and Hungary in an effort to surround Yugoslavia
militarily and further isolate it politically, according to allied
officials.
</P>
<P>
   So far, NATO's attacks have been launched from bases in Western
Europe, the United States and from aircraft carriers in the
Adriatic. But now air war commanders plan to attack from the east,
using air bases in western Turkey, and at the same time station
warplanes in Hungary that would strike Yugoslavia from the north.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to increase the political pressure on the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, and help NATO warplanes counter
Serbia's battered, but still resilient, air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to make Yugoslavia a picture of isolation,'' said
a senior allied officer. ``The optics of the map will show that he
is surrounded, and the air defense systems he has left will be
spread very thin.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said, for example, that Yugoslavia had about 40
SA-6 and SA-3 surface-to-air missile batteries before the war and
that fewer than half were still operational.
</P>
<P>
   The SA-6, which is highly mobile, is the more capable of the
systems. And the Serbs have been moving the SA-6 batteries to both
conceal them and position them along the allies' expected attack
routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be more difficult for them if we attack along multiple
axes,'' said Brig Gen. Jean-Patrick Gaviard, a senior French
officer at NATO's air command center at Vincenza, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the SA-6s are in the south, we can come from the north,
Gaviard said. ``If they are in the center, we can come from the
south. If they only have about 10 SA-6s it will be more difficult
for them if we come from each side.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening up a new front in the air war will also help the
alliance cope with air traffic congestion over Yugoslavia. NATO
planners have done extensive planning to minimize the risk of a
collision by allied warplanes.
</P>
<P>
   And it gives NATO new bases for the hundreds of additional
planes the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, has requested.
</P>
<P>
   Though arrangements are still being completed, the basic
elements of the plan are clear. NATO plans to deploy U.S. F-15E
planes and F-16CJ fighters at air bases in western Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the F-15Es is to bomb ground targets. F-16CJs
equipped with HARM anti-radiation missiles are used to strike enemy
air defenses. Turkey, which has actively supported the air campaign
against Yugoslavia, is expected to formally approve the
arrangement, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary has agreed to a similar deployment of U.S. warplanes. It
is allowing 24 FA-18 attack planes and three A-10s to be stationed
on its territory for use against targets in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   American KC-135 refueling tankers are already based at Budapest,
and the Hungarian government has also agreed to let NATO warplanes
use its air space.
</P>
<P>
   Bases, however, are just part of the problem. To enable its
warplanes in Turkey and Hungary to reach their targets, NATO has
asked Bulgaria and Romania for permission to fly over their
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Turkey and Hungary, they are not NATO members. Both,
however, are said to have agreed. Still, considerable coordination,
including agreement on flight paths, is required.
</P>
<P>
   As a former member of the Warsaw Pact, Bulgaria also has many of
the same type of Soviet-made radars as Yugoslavia, and NATO needs
to make sure that the Bulgarian radars are not attacked by mistake.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There have already been three cases in which HARM missiles have
accidentally struck Bulgaria, allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   During the air war over Yugoslavia, NATO warplanes have fired
the HARMs, which home in on enemy radar beams, at Serbian
surface-to-air missile batteries. When the Serbs quickly turned
their radars off, the HARM missiles apparently picked up radar
emissions in Bulgaria and attacked targets there.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a repeat of these episode, technical adjustment to the
Bulgarian radars might be made. NATO might also persuade Bulgaria
to turn off the radars while allied warplanes are flying nearby or
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   NATO air patrols would then assume the responsibility of
protecting Bulgaria against Yugoslav air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A major advantage of the new arrangement, allied officials said,
is that it will help NATO accommodate the new planes Clark has
requested.
</P>
<P>
   When Clark reviewed his options for reinforcement, allied
officials said, he had three options, code-named ``Baby Bear,''
``Mama Bear'' and ``Papa Bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark picked ``Papa Bear,'' the largest option. It will bring
the number of NATO planes to over 1,100 and has sparked an urgent
search for new airfields.
</P>
<P>
   Searching for places where U.S. planes might be based, the Air
Force has sent teams to about 10 countries, including Turkey,
Poland, the Czech Republic and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   The teams are considering a number of factors, including
billeting space for Air Force crews, fuel and maintenance
capabilities, ramp space for the planes and the layout of the
airfields.
</P>
<P>
   Launching attack missions from Turkey and Hungary will also help
the alliance better foil Serb efforts to anticipate the direction
of NATO's attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Serb air defenses have been degraded by weeks of attack. Even
though NATO has flown more than 4,000 bombing missions, only two of
its planes have been shot down by Yugoslav forces: a ``stealth''
F-117 and a F-16 plane.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes also are no longer restricted to operating at
15,000 feet above ground. Some pilots have the flexibility to go
considerable lower, particularly to identify targets.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Yugoslav air defenses remain a worry for pilots. The
Yugoslav Air Defense Force is regarded as one of the most
professional elements of the Serbian military. Unlike the Iraqis,
for example, the Yugoslav force trained for years to counter a
large NATO air attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav military has also polished its tactics by
monitoring NATO air operations for years during the conflict in
Bosnia. And it is adept at hiding in hills and villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to honor it,'' said Maj. Mark Russell, the commander
of the detachment of ABCCC command and control planes here,
referring to the air defense threat.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav air defense capabilities were outlined recently by Gen.
Salko Begic, the Air Force chief for the Muslim-Croat federation in
Bosnia and a former classmate of the Serbian generals now
commanding Yugoslavia's air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the Yugoslav air defense, he said, is to create a
killing zone below 10,000 feet, using anti-aircraft artillery,
SA-7s and Swedish Bofors air defense missiles, which are very
portable.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs also had SA-3 and SA-6 surface-to-air missile
batteries, which, he said, draw on a network of more than 100
radars. The network also involves observers, including Serbian
agents who monitor NATO aircraft as they take off from bases in
Europe. It is tied together by underground communications lines and
fiber-optic cable.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's goal has been to break the network into pieces so that it
cannot function as an integrated system. Without access to
information from radars throughout the country, the utility of
individual surface-to-missile batteries would be seriously
degraded.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Steve Keim, the commander of the Marine Corps
``Prowler'' EA-6B electronic warfare planes at Aviano, said NATO
was making progress in thwarting the Yugoslav air defenses, but
that it was a complex mission.
</P>
<P>
   The Prowlers' mission is to protect NATO strike aircraft by
locating and jamming Yugoslavia's early warning and targeting radar
systems or by firing HARM missiles at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no one thing we can take out that will stop their
systems,'' Keim said. ``If we try to jam an emitter in the south,
there may be a northern one than can relay the information through
a communications link and land line. They are fighting on their own
turf and know where to hide.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the air defense forces have used all of their
ingenuity to survive. The SAM batteries hide during the day. When
they attack at night, they sometimes turn their radars on for 20
seconds and then quickly shut them down to elude attack by HARM
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a long range game,'' said Lt. Col. Steven Searcy, who
commands a squadron of F-16CJ planes, which are equipped with HARM
missiles. ``We've been picking away at him and making dents in his
defenses. Now we are starting to see holes. But it will take us a
long time to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaviard, the French commander, said that the Serbs have been
moving some SA-6s near Belgrade to fill in holes in their air
defense caused by attacks on the SA-3s.
</P>
<P>
   The SA-6s, however, can be loaded on a truck in minutes and
shifted to other regions where the Serbs are expecting an attack.
Attacking from multiple directions, he said, would make the allies'
task that much easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is very mobile and the Serbs are being clever and
flexible,'' said Gaviard. ``But if we are more flexible we will win
the war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
