<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOMERUNS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: THE FIRM OF BELL, BELL &AMP; BELLE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those fans who are waiting for Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa
to reprise their home run show, here is another race to watch while
they wait. Can Jay Bell and David Bell hit more home runs combined
than Albert Belle?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's combined,'' David Bell said when he was asked the
question, wanting to make sure the inquirer had not lost his mind.
Then he laughed. ``I have no idea,'' he said. Then he laughed some
more.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell was at Yankee Stadium this past weekend playing
second base for the Seattle Mariners. He did not add to his home
run total, leaving him with the same nine he had when he arrived.
But Jay Bell, playing against the Mets in Arizona during the
weekend, slugged his 10th and 11th home runs, giving him a share of
the major-league lead.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about combined. The Bells individually are ahead of
Belle, who had hit six for Baltimore. But the Bells, David and Jay,
need that headstart because Albert has a tendency to erupt in a
home run barrage in the latter part of the season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the All-Star Game break last season, Belle had 18 home runs
in 86 games. After the break, he swatted 31 in 76 games for a total
of 49. Jay ended the season with 20 home runs, one short of his
career high for a season. David left New York on Sunday only one
short of his career high of 10, which he reached last season with
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   David was reluctant to talk about his seemingly new penchant for
hitting home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying really not to think about it,'' he said. ``First of
all, you can't hit them when you're thinking about them, at least I
can't. It's not my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay and David are not related. David is the son of Buddy Bell,
who hit as many as 20 home runs only once in his 18-year career.
Gus Bell, Buddy's father and David's grandfather, once hit 30 in a
season. Jay is the first in his family to play major-league
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Their careers, however, are related. Both played their
minor-league years in the Cleveland organization, and both
struggled in their early experience in the majors. The Indians
traded Jay to Pittsburgh in 1989 after he had batted .216 and .218
the previous two seasons. David played professionally for eight
years before spending a full season in the majors last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gained a lot of confidence over the last year,'' said
David, at 26 seven years younger than Jay. ``Before last year, I
never really got an opportunity to play any significant amount of
time. Last year was important because it allowed me to believe I
could play in the big leagues every day. And it carried over to
this season. I finally can take a deep breath and relax and go out
and play and know I'm probably going to be in there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But if they are to outslug Belle, the Bells cannot afford to
relax too much. Marshall McDougall, on the other hand, can rest his
case for the future on only one day's worth of exploits. He is the
college player who hit six home runs _ in succession _ in a single
game Sunday. Nothing McGwire or Sosa will do this season is likely
to overshadow the Florida State player's feat at the University of
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it ``pretty crazy,'' McDougall said that once he hit
three, ``we already had the game in hand so I just kept trying to
hit more and improve on my day.'' His day was a good month for most
major-league hitters.
</P>
<P>
   After producing a mere single in his first time at-bat, he
lashed a bases-empty home run in the second inning, a three-run
shot in the fourth, a bases-empty homer in the sixth, a three-run
blow in the seventh, a grand slam in the eighth and a three-run
drive in the ninth. As he trotted around the bases with No. 6,
McDougall said: ``I was just looking over at the bench. They were
going crazy. I was laughing at them because they were as excited as
I was.''
</P>
<P>
   A 6-foot-1-inch, right-handed-hitting infielder, McDougall said
he hit only nine home runs last year as a sophomore at Santa Fe
Community College in Gainesville, Fla. ``This year I worked out a
little,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   McDougall, who hit three home runs in a game against Miami
earlier in the season and has 23 for the season, said he hopes his
flurry of home runs will gain him greater recognition for the major
leagues' amateur draft next month. ``I'd love to play professional
baseball,'' he said. ``I would like to leave here this year if the
opportunity arises.''
</P>
<P>
   McDougall had the chance to turn professional two years ago. The
New York Yankees drafted him in the 37th round but did not sign
him. ``They didn't want to offer as much as I wanted, so they
didn't even come up with an offer,'' McDougall said, adding that he
wanted about $100,000 to sign. ``The scout said it would be in my
best interest to go back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   So he went back, and now he has broken the National Collegiate
Athletic Association's one-game records for home runs and runs
batted in (16).
</P>
<P>
   Jim LaFountain, who had set the RBI record with 14 for
Louisville in 1976, went on to play two years in the low minor
leagues. Henry Rochelle, whose five home runs for Campbell in 1985
had been the record, never played professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a good sign,'' McDougall said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
