<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1717 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBC-INTERNET-ART-750&AMP;     05-10 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-INTERNET-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV-NET DEALS: ONE MAY FLOP, THE OTHER FLIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as one betrothal of a television network and an Internet
company was on the verge of breaking off Monday, another engagement
was being announced.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed combination of some assets of USA Networks, the
family of cable networks, with Lycos, the Internet portal, is about
to be abandoned, said people close to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NBC said Monday that it had agreed to merge some of
its Internet assets with Xoom, a publicly traded electronic
community that emphasizes direct marketing. The combined entity,
worth $3.9 billion based on Xoom's market value, will operate under
the name Snap.com and would be the seventh most- visited site on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force behind both developments is the stock market,
which values Internet businesses far more than enterprises in any
other industry. USA ran afoul of investors because it proposed
combining Lycos, a pure Internet company, with USA's Home Shopping
Network and Ticketmaster units, along with their associated Web
sites. Never mind that the company would have had revenue of $1.5
billion _ 30 times that of Lycos alone.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' stock fell on the news of the deal last February. And
CMGI, the largest holder of Lycos stock, said it would vote against
the acquisition. In recent weeks, executives of both Lycos and USA
concluded that it was far from certain that a majority of
shareholders would vote for the deal, people close to the deal
said. They added that since USA was not willing to raise its bid,
the two companies would agree to go their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lycos and USA just couldn't sell the deal to the Street, no
matter how they repackaged it,'' said one executive with knowledge
of the transaction. The deal's imminent demise was first reported
Monday by The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's deal, meanwhile, is specifically designed to create a
company exclusively involved in the Internet. It will operate under
the name NBC Internet, or NBCi. NBC hopes that the shares of NBCi,
independent of the network's parent, General Electric Co., will
ascend to the lofty levels of other big Internet portals. If so, it
will be able to trade those shares in acquiring other Internet
companies at prices that would be unthinkable if GE actually had to
pay cash.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were as favorable to the NBC deal as they were
scornful of the USA-Lycos transaction. News of the potential demise
of the deal with USA bolstered Lycos shares by $15.75, to $105.25.
In contrast, shares of Xoom jumped by $6.75, to $81.86 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC has a lot of marquee value and the power to promote
Internet properties,'' said Alan Braverman, an analyst with
Nationsbanc Montgomery securities. ``Xoom will help them capitalize
on what they have. But it's not enough.'' Braverman said that NBCi
would need to use its new public stock as currency in acquisitions
to get a bigger audience. Indeed, he said that a newly single Lycos
could make an attractive partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC would have loved to do a deal with Lycos before,'' he
said. ``Maybe they can again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rogers, the president of NBC cable, declined to say if NBC
would be interested in a deal with Lycos. But he said the company's
top goal in planning future acquisitions would be to build a
service for people with high-speed Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will contribute to NBCi its interest in Snap, the Internet
portal that it bought a portion of from CNet last year. It will
also contribute NBC.Com, the site about its television shows; NBC
Interactive Neighborhood, a site that links NBC's affiliates;
Videoseeker, a site that plays video clips over the Internet; and
10 percent of CNBC.Com, a personal finance site scheduled to begin
in June. NBC will also contribute $370 million in cash, payable
over four years, in the form of the note.
</P>
<P>
   In return, NBC will control 49.9 percent of the new company. By
keeping its ownership below 50 percent, the losses of the company
do not have to be incorporated into General Electric's income
statement. NBC has the right to convert the note into an additional
3 percent stake in NBCi, which presumably would be useful were the
company ever to make a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The current holders of Xoom shares will receive a 34 percent
stake in the new company. And CNet will end up with a 13 percent
stake.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will not include the MSNBC cable and Internet news service
in the new company. MSNBC is a joint venture with Microsoft Corp.,
and its Internet site is filled with links to Microsoft's MSN
portal, a direct competitor to Snap.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The deal shows just how far Internet valuations have risen since
last June when NBC announced its investment in Snap. NBC agreed to
pay $5.9 million for 19.9 percent of Snap and has a three-year
option to buy a further 40.1 percent of the service for $32
million. On Monday, NBC executives said that Snap was valued in the
deal as equal to Xoom, which has a market value of $1.3 billion,
giving NBC a paper return of 2,000 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that return is a result of the sharp increase in
audience Snap has experienced, in part because of the promotion it
receives on NBC. In March, it was the 11th most popular site,
visited at least once by 15.8 percent of the Internet users. Xoom
was the 12th most popular site, reaching 15.7 percent of the
audience. The combination would be the seventh most-visited site,
reaching 29 percent of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Xoom was started by Chris Kitze, a 39-year-old entrepreneur who
has started and sold four companies so far.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, Xoom resembles other Internet communities like
Geocities, which agreed to be bought by Yahoo, in that it offers
free home pages, message boards, chat rooms and so on. But Xoom was
built from the ground up to be a direct marketing vehicle,
gathering data about its users' interests in order to sell them
merchandise. Xoom members are regularly barraged with e-mail
offering electronics items like scanners.
</P>
<P>
   Xoom's direct marketing focus is very much in keeping with NBC's
broader strategy. The network has been emphasizing programming in
which it can sell related merchandise, as it did selling compact
disks and videos related to its miniseries, ``The '60s.'' NBC also
invested in Value Vision, a small cable shopping channel.
</P>
<P>
   NBC said that Robert Wright, NBC's president, would be chairman
of NBCi's board. Kitze would be its president and chief executive.
Halsey Minor, CNet's chairman who has also been the acting chief
executive of Snap, would have no role in the new company.
Similarly, Laurent Massa, Xoom's president and chief executive,
will leave the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
