r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAILBAG-SFCHRON &LR;      05-10 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAILBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Making IRA Tax Less Painful
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I invested in a traditional Individual Retirement
Account through my credit union for quite a while when I was
working. Now I have retired and am about to reach age 701/2, after
which I am required to start taking distributions from the IRA. I
really would prefer to keep the money in my IRA. But because I
can't, would there be some alternate strategy that wouldn't require
me to pay taxes?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Nope.
</P>
<P>
   You will have to withdraw at least some of the money from your
IRA each year, based on the life expectancy tables provided by the
Internal Revenue Service. In your case, the minimum required
withdrawal in the first year will be about 6 percent of the IRA's
assets. And you will have to pay taxes on your withdrawals.
</P>
<P>
   However, you might consider rolling over the money in your
present IRA to a Roth IRA. You still must pay taxes on the money
you roll over. But no matter what your age, you never will be
legally required to withdraw money from the Roth. And once the
money is in a Roth, your earnings will accumulate tax free, not
just tax deferred as with your present IRA.
</P>
<P>
   IRS spokesman Jesse Weller points out that if your present IRA
is large, you may not want to roll it over all at once.
</P>
<P>
   If you do, you might get pushed into a higher tax bracket for
the year in which you make the rollover. The spike in your income
also might affect your eligibility for Social Security benefits
that year and your right to claim certain tax credits. It might
even push your income to a level where you must grapple with the
outrageously complicated alternative minimum tax rules. I wouldn't
wish that on anyone.
</P>
<P>
   You probably should talk strategy with a financial planner or
tax consultant before you make your move.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds on the Net
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there an Internet site where I can enter a Series EE bond
serial number and find out the current value of the bond?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the U.S. Treasury Web site at  &LR; www.publicdebt.treas.gov.
 &LR; Click on the link for ``Savings Bond Wizard.'' Then follow the
prompts to download the necessary software to your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   You can use Savings Bond Wizard not only to determine bond
values, but also to maintain a detailed inventory of your bond
holdings _ assuming you have more than one.
</P>
<P>
   It's an attractive, easy-to-use program. I would use it myself
if only I owned a savings bond.
</P>
<P>
   Taxing Proposition
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a former manager with United Parcel Service and hold
several hundred shares of the privately held company's stock. UPS
recently informed me that it wants to exercise its option to buy
back 10 percent of my holdings. This bothers me because my stock
represents the bulk of the money that my wife and I have saved, and
now we are faced with paying a capital gains tax on the shares that
UPS wants to buy. Is there some way to defer this tax, such as
putting the money in an IRA?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Putting the money in an IRA won't help. You still must
pay taxes on your capital gain.
</P>
<P>
   But if the company will cooperate, you can take advantage of a
legal provision that applies only to privately held stock. You can
elect to receive the money in annual installments, and pay taxes
each year only on the portion of the capital gains you receive in
that year.
</P>
<P>
   You don't cite specific figures, but let's suppose the company
wants to buy $50,000 worth of your stock and that those shares cost
you $10,000. You could take the money in five annual installments
of $10,000 each, of which $8,000 per year would be taxable.
</P>
<P>
   The installment method makes sense if it keeps you from moving
into a higher tax bracket. That's the plus side.
</P>
<P>
   The minus side is that you won't be able to reinvest the full
proceeds from the stock sale until the five-year period _ or
whatever you and the company agree upon _ has elapsed. You at least
might ask the company to keep the undistributed funds in an
interest-bearing account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
