<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTS-INTERNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTSJONES OFFERS ALTERNATIVE FROM MAINSTREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Tim Morris, an associate professor and graduate adviser in
English at UT-Arlington, found the perfect venue for his musings
about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't in the glossy pages of some monthly sports magazine,
nor was it in the pages of a baseball periodical.
</P>
<P>
   Morris writes a column called Outside Baseball for SportsJones
(www.sportsjones.com), a collection of sports-related essays from
contributors who tackle topics usually not addressed by the
mainstream sports media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to provide something progressive and alternative,''
said Royce Webb of Nashville, Tenn., creator of the 1-year-old
site.
</P>
<P>
   This week's edition features an article on brutality in schools
and whether ``jocks'' created the conditions for the deadly
shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. Past
editions have examined topics such as flaws in the Bowl
Championship Series and reasons why Americans can't embrace soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said his Outside Baseball commentaries are recollections
of ``sitting in the stands from a fan's perspective, of listening
to baseball on radio or TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The editorial content at SportsJones is the kind of
thought-provoking efforts one would expect if Mother Jones or
Atlantic Monthly magazines had sports sections. SportsJones is, in
fact, the only sports site listed by the Arts and Letters Daily, a
portal for online literature. Online readers will consider
SportsJones a knockoff of Salon.com.
</P>
<P>
   The site isn't strictly for sports eggheads. One of the more
interesting features is Celeb-Jock Yearbook, where users win a
T-shirt if they correctly identify a sports personality in an old
yearbook photo.
</P>
<P>
   SportsJones was launched in June by Webb and some of his
friends. Knowing that producing a print magazine would be cost
prohibitive, Webb turned to the Web, specifically a friend who
owned PCI Media, a Web-hosting company.
</P>
<P>
   While SportsJones looks at controversial topics and tries to
stray from the traditional approaches, it does not attempt shock
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try not to be something that wants to hit you between the
eyes every week,'' said Webb, who once was a sports columnist for
the Daily Iowan. ``We just want to bring up different ways to see
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   SportsJones plans changes to its presentation beginning Monday.
The site won't get a major redesign, but instead have functions for
increased interactivity for feedback, chats, newsletters and e-mail
subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're standing on the steps yelling at people,''
Webb said. ``We want a little more mixing and mingling.''
 &LR; subheds:Bytes CBS expansion: CBS SportsLine has expanded its reach
to professional football with the two-year contract to produce the
official site for the NFL's European developmental league
(www.nfleurope.com). CBS SportsLine also entered the professional
wrestling ring, announcing that it will produce and host
WrestleLine (www.wrestleline.com). The site has extensive content
on wrestling's most popular promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Industry news: Speaking of tag teams, ESPN.com is joining forces
with careerexperience.com to produce an online sports careers
service ... CNNSI.com's NBA playoff section includes the standard
latest news, live scoreboard, schedules, playoff stats and roster
and a free fantasy game ... Former NBA stars Isiah Thomas and Bill
Walton are scheduled to join MSNBCSports.com for its NBA playoff
coverage. The site also has a Race for the Rings page that
highlights this year's top players.
</P>
<P>
   Live bowling: Frame-by-frame coverage of the Omaha Open, the
Professional Women's Bowling Association finals, is available on
the league's Web site (www.pwba.com) beginning at 7 p.m. tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Chat highlights: Former baseball great Pete Rose is the
scheduled guest at 8 p.m. tomorrow on CBS SportsLine. ... PGA Tour
member Phil Mickelson is on TalkCity (www.talkcity.com) at 7 p.m.
tomorrow ... NBA legend Oscar Robertson is scheduled to chat live
at noon today on NBA.com.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
