<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1725 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRACKING-SFCHRON &LR;      05-10 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACKING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Tracking Stock Can Unleash a Unit's Value
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In school you learned that the whole is equal to the sum of its
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Forget what you learned! The folks on Wall Street insist that
sometimes it can be more than that _ much more.
</P>
<P>
   That's the logic behind an ingenious financial instrument called
tracking stock, which is becoming increasingly popular in today's
highly speculative market.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stocks are designed to unleash the market potential of
promising subsidiaries whose value might not be fully reflected in
the price of a parent company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   They work much like spin-offs, except that the assets are not
actually spun off. They are retained within the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  According to Lehman Brothers, there are more than three dozen
tracking stocks on the market. Three companies have issued tracking
stock this year, and three more have issues pending.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pending issues is the first ever for the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Quantum Corp., the Milpitas manufacturer of computer storage
devices, plans to create separate stocks for its draggy, cyclical
disk-drive business and its glamorous, fast-growing digital tape
storage business.
</P>
<P>
   Quantum's current shareholders will get one share of the storage
business and one-half share of the disk-drive business for every
Quantum share they own. After that, the shares of the two
operations will trade separately on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Clemmer, Quantum's CFO, observes that Quantum's two
basic businesses appeal to different types of investors. He says he
hopes the offering will ``give us the ability to better link up
with the objectives of investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stock _ so named because it tracks a subsidiary's
financial progress _ has one great advantage over spin-offs, notes
Barbara Byrne, a Lehman Brothers investment banker who has handled
several tracking-stock deals.
</P>
<P>
   She points out that because the subsidiary remains part of the
parent company, it can draw on the parent's credit standing. If
spun off and left on its own, it might not be able to borrow as
easily or cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stock was pioneered in the 1980s by General Motors,
which created separate shares for its Electronic Data Systems and
Hughes Electronics subsidiaries, both of which were regarded as
more glamorous than the company's stodgy automotive business.
</P>
<P>
   EDS, which has since become an independent company, has
increased more than tenfold in value since it began trading in
October 1984. Hughes, first traded in November 1985, has nearly
tripled. The stock representing GM's automotive business has
slightly more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stock has taken on new popularity in recent years.
Companies and their investment bankers have been alert to any
gimmick that will allow them to capitalize on the latest market
trends _ and in today's market, gimmicks rule.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with Internet or bioscience subsidiaries, for example,
are taking advantage of the stock market's frenzy for those
industries by creating tracking stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Shrewd investors might be able to take advantage of this trend
by purchasing shares in companies that fit that profile in hopes
that the companies will parcel out tracking stock to their existing
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The one hitch in that strategy _ and it is a big one _ is that
companies don't necessarily issue tracking stock to existing
shareholders. Sometimes they do _ as in the case of Quantum _ but
other times they simply sell new stock to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Ziff-Davis, the New York publishing company,
recently created a separate stock to track the value of its ZDNet
subsidiary, which focuses on information for Internet users. It
kept the bulk of the stock for itself and issued the rest to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet accounted for a piddling 5 percent of Ziff-Davis' $1.1
billion in revenues last year, so Ziff-Davis wasn't viewed on Wall
Street as a significant Internet play.
</P>
<P>
   As Tim O'Brien, chief financial officer of Ziff-Davis, puts it:
``We felt we were at a disadvantage. We wanted to create an
Internet stock with a great enough value to use in buying other
Internet stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, Ziff-Davis issued 71 million shares of ZDNet
tracking stock, offering 10 million shares to the public at $19 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, ZDNet stock had soared to $36, and it
closed yesterday at $31.06.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet's total market capitalization of $2.2 billion now dwarfs
the $1.4 billion value of the remaining Ziff-Davis operations.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, this appears to be an extremely successful
issue. But it is impossible to say for certain, because we will
never know what would have happened to Ziff-Davis' stock price if
the company had stood pat and not issued tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   ZDNet technically remains part of Ziff-Davis, and its
shareholders are entitled to vote at the Ziff-Davis annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But ZDNet's financial results now are reported separately from
those of the parent company. And if ZDNet were ever sold or
liquidated, ZDNet shareholders would receive the proceeds. (At the
moment, of course, Ziff-Davis itself is ZDNet's largest
shareholder.)
</P>
<P>
   Another company planning to issue tracking stock is Donaldson
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, the investment banker and broker. It will have
one stock tracking DLJ Direct, its online brokerage, and another
representing its traditional brokerage and investment-banking
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Internet brokers such as Charles Schwab, E-Trade and Ameritrade
have enjoyed enormous run-ups in the stock market over the past
year, and DLJ obviously wants a piece of that action.
</P>
<P>
   The DLJ issue has a couple of unusual features.
</P>
<P>
   Holders of DLJ Direct will legally be considered holders of not
just the subsidiary, but also Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. However,
holders of DLJ Direct will not have voting rights ``except in
certain limited circumstances,'' according to the company's
prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, DLJ Direct holders will be paid off in full
if the parent company sells the online brokerage's assets.
</P>
<P>
   A DLJ spokeswoman declined to discuss details of the pending
issue because ``we're in registration.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stock faces a potential threat from the Clinton
administration. In effect, says a U.S. Treasury official, it allows
taxpayers to spin off assets without paying tax, even in cases
where a spin-off would have been subject to tax.
</P>
<P>
   In its latest budget proposal, the administration calls for a
corporate tax on future tracking stock, levied when the stock is
issued. The amount to be taxed would be the difference between the
value of the stock at that time and the original cost of the assets
represented by the stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Congress has yet to act on the
administration proposal. If it were to do exactly as the Democratic
administration wants _ never a sure bet _ ``that would be the end''
of tracking stock, says Lehman Brothers' Byrne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
