<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Apple Stays the Course With Software Strategy
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Apple Computer yesterday announced the most powerful lineup of
laptop computers anywhere; a deal with Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. to
carry iMacs; and a speech-recognition program for the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   But what the computer-maker repeated from a year ago may have
been just as significant: It is sticking with its operating
software plan _ the core of its computer systems _ after years of
``strategy du jour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope our software strategy sounds boring to you,'' Apple
interim chief executive Steve Jobs told the company's annual
Worldwide Developers Conference in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're staying with our plan and not surprising you with the
strategy of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's ever been a better time to be a Mac
developer,'' Jobs told a standing-room-only crowd of 4,000 that
included executives and engineers from firms that make Mac
software. Mac developers attend the week's conference to hear about
Apple's road map for the future, so they can tailor software
accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Flanked by imposing black-and-white murals of John Lennon and
Yoko Ono, and Nobel Prize-winning physicist Richard Feynman, Jobs
introduced the PowerBook G3 portable computers, which clock in at a
fast 333 and 400 megahertz.
</P>
<P>
   The svelte models are 20 percent thinner and almost two pounds
lighter than their predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   The top model, priced at $3,500, comes with a DVD player and
batteries that last up to five hours.
</P>
<P>
   The laptops weigh 5.9 pounds, compared &LR;   &LR; with 7.7 for the IBM
ThinkPad.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to reach more consumers, Apple will sell its
fruit-colored, Space Age iMacs at Sears, the largest U.S.
department store company, starting Memorial Day weekend. About 825
Sears locations also will sell add-on devices for the iMac, such as
printers and disk drives. CompUSA Inc., the largest domestic
computer retailer, is the only national chain that now offers the
iMac.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In addition, software maker Dragon Systems of Newton, Mass.,
is creating Macintosh products based on Dragon NaturallySpeaking,
the top-selling retail speech-recognition software. It lets users
speak into a microphone attached to the computer, which converts
their words into text on screen and allows them to give voice
commands, such as ``Print file.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jobs spent the bulk of his two-hour presentation at the
conference laying out the computer-maker's operating system
software plans. The operating system essentially acts as a
computer's central nervous system. Apple's current OS can't keep up
with the industrial-strength demands of corporate users. Apple is
in the process of melding elements of the original Mac OS with
those of Rhapsody, the more advanced technology developed by Next
Software, which Apple acquired in December 1996 for $400 million.
The merged software will be called Mac OS X, which Jobs calls the
most significant upgrade to the Macintosh operating system since
the computer's introduction in 1984. Mac OS X, due in early 2000,
would allow users to run several functions at once, prevent system
shutdowns when an application fails and perform networking tasks
faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two problems with changing your mind: You never get
anything done and you frustrate developers,'' a relaxed Jobs said
later in an interview, between bites of a rice cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple had been zigging and zagging, like so much of the
industry, and we decided to stick with a plan and implement it
well,'' he said. ``What's important is that we want Apple to be the
center of innovation and we want it to be run as efficiently as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobs said he was ``pleased,'' but not surprised by Apple's
remarkable turnaround from just two years ago. The Cupertino
company has logged six straight profitable quarters and is riding
the crest of strong sales of the iMac and Power Mac G3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling pretty good now,'' Jobs said. ``I don't have a
problem with (the title of interim CEO). We'll keep things moving
along.''
</P>
<P>
   He even joked that ``ER'' star Noah Wylie _ who will portray
Jobs in the cable TV movie ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' _ could
step in as permanent CEO. ``Maybe we should hire him,'' Jobs said.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs' buoyant disposition about the company he co-founded two
decades ago was echoed by developers yesterday in the corridors of
the San Jose Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very encouraging step after years of strategy du jour
from Apple,'' said Jack Putnam, project manager at Newer Technology
in Wichita, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Charlesworth, who runs a prepress publishing company in
Sydney, Australia, said she is relieved by Apple's ``newfound focus
on consolidation and snazzy products'' after years of indecision.
</P>
<P>
   Although conferences took on a somber tone during the company's
financial struggles, this year's get-together was upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is up 40 percent from last year, to 2,514, and about
3,100 applications have been announced for the iMac since its May
1998 introduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple's return to health is more than even I, a Mac addict,
could have dreamed,'' said John Knoll, visual effects supervisor
for ``Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace'' and a Macintosh
developer. ``I was hoping the iMacs and G3 tower machines would
help Apple limp back, but the company is charging back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
