r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-EX-BOXER-TOLEDO-T     05-10 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-EX-BOXER-TOLEDO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SWINGING SUCCESS: FROM PUNCHES TO PUTTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A 40-foot birdie putt trickled into the hole,
triggering an upraised right fist from Esteban Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   His former calling card exposed, a fan seated behind the green
made the connection and bellowed, ``Hey, that's the boxer!''
Outwardly, Toledo smiled when he heard the response. Inside, he
winced.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the paradox with Toledo, the only participant at the GTE
Byron Nelson Classic with more career victories as a professional
boxer (12) than Top 10 finishes as a PGA Tour golfer (3).
</P>
<P>
   Part of him wants to embrace the fact he has fought his way to
the champagne-and-caviar circuit from a dirt-floor shack with no
indoor plumbing in Mexicali, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Another part wishes people would overlook his past and give him
credit for what he has become: a player who has collected more than
$500,000 at tour events in the past 17 months and could contend
this week at the Four Seasons Resort and Club.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's latest top-10 effort, after all, came nine days ago at
the Shell Houston Open, where he finished 10th and won $53,571. If
anything, Toledo figures he's on a roll as he returns to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he expects gallery members to notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what I do, I'm still `The Boxer.' People look at me
different from the other players. Sometimes I get a little bit
tired of that,'' said Toledo, 36. ``I don't want to get attention
from that. I want to get attention because I'm playing good golf. I
want to earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Within moments of uttering his heartfelt desire, Toledo
dismissed it as a pipe dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will ever go away,'' Toledo said of
outsiders' fascination with his humble background and his 12-1
record as a lightweight on undercard bouts in Las Vegas and Los
Angeles. ``Probably, it shouldn't. Boxing is always going to be in
my mind. There's no question I was born to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a better boxer than I am a golfer. I have that killer
instinct. I won't give up on anything. That's the mentality I've
carried from boxing into golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Toledo's strong will touches all aspects of his life,
including romance. His wife, Colleen, turned him down five times
before agreeing to their first date. Now, they have two children:
Nicholas, 9, and a newborn daughter, Eden Faline.
</P>
<P>
   Without so much as one golf lesson, Toledo has carved out a
career in a sport he treated with little more than a casual
interest until he turned 21. Using a 7-iron he retrieved from a
creek and balls he scrounged from a driving range, Toledo began
daily practice sessions on a dirt field after a botched
appendectomy (doctors had to operate twice to correct the problem)
left him vulnerable to body blows and ended his boxing career.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, he said, considered him crazy for investing so much
time struggling to break 100 at the town's only country club. Yet
despite long hours spent cultivating ``everything except
marijuana'' on the family farm in a region marked by abject
poverty, Toledo began making incremental progress.
</P>
<P>
   By 1986, his fourth year as a golfer, he turned professional.
Toledo received his first PGA Tour card in 1994 but failed to
maintain it, earning just $66,049 and finishing 176th on the season
money list. He returned in 1998, this time to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, Toledo's $327,244 in earnings last season seemed
like a king's ransom to someone who was teased in elementary school
because he was the only boy in the class without shoes. At the
time, Toledo was 5 and his father had just died of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The family's youngest child made himself a promise: No matter
how hard he needed to work, he would carve out a better life for
his children. And he has. Toledo heads into the Nelson ranked 92nd
on the season money list with $187,453, and is ahead of his
career-best 1998 earnings pace.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Booker, one of Toledo's closest friends on the PGA Tour,
said the former fighter's drive separates him from most peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a big heart. That's what most people lack,'' said
Booker, who has known Toledo since both began competing in 1990 on
what is now the Nike Tour. ``In life, you can achieve anything you
want if you're willing to go through the highs and lows that it
takes to get there. That's where he stands out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Esteban has had a lot of obstacles in his path, enough to make
most people quit. But he's made it over the walls and he's still
going.''
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't forgotten about those from similar backgrounds.
Toledo frequently volunteers to conduct clinics for inner-city
youths. During practice rounds, he'll occasionally pick someone
from the gallery to pinch hit a drive or approach shot.
</P>
<P>
   Booker said Toledo ``probably is the nicest, most approachable
guy out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo is also a contender. Just not in the sport he envisioned
when he began mapping out his athletic career.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both sports, you really have to discipline yourself,''
Toledo said. ``The way I grew up, learning to do without things, I
think that made me hungrier and more disciplined than some other
guys. I think that helped me succeed in both. I know it's made me
appreciate what I have now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet given the choice, Toledo would trade his berth in this
week's 156-player field for a chance to fight for a boxing title.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went back again, I'd leave golf and stick with boxing,''
Toledo said. ``In boxing, you only have to beat one other guy.
Here, it's 155.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
