<HEADER>
A1732 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LACROSSE-DEATH-NYT &LR;      05-10 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LACROSSE-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BALL STRIKES A CHEST LIGHTLY, A YOUNG LIFE IS SUDDENLY LOST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELDEN, N.Y. _ Eric Sopracasa, a 21-year-old University of
Massachusetts lacrosse player, was participating in a routine
practice last Wednesday, during the last week of the Minutemen's
season. During one drill, he was struck on the chest by the ball,
not an uncommon occurrence for a defensive player. The ball was not
going particularly fast and seemed more like a pass than a shot,
said some of the people at practice that day.
</P>
<P>
   But Sopracasa, a fourth-year junior from Long Island, had been
struck in exactly the wrong spot at exactly the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   He collapsed and stopped breathing; his heart stopped beating.
After being revived briefly, he died that afternoon at Cooley
Dickinson Hospital in Northampton, Mass. An autopsy performed last
week did not list Sopracasa's cause of death, noting that it was
apparently accidental. But even though an underlying cause will not
be ruled out until the results of toxicological and other tests
come back next week, Sopracasa's family and school officials
believe he might have died from sudden cardiac arrest after a blunt
blow to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a freak, freak accident,'' said Frank Smith, who
was Sopracasa's closest friend and his roommate for two years.
``When I got to the hospital and they told me that Eric had died,
the doctor told me there is only a one-in-10-million chance of this
happening. So why did it happen to my best friend? It's
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sudden cardiac arrest is a rare killer of young athletes that is
nonetheless responsible for deaths in Little League baseball,
softball, hockey, football, karate and lacrosse, according to the
National Center for Catastrophic Sports Injury Research at the
University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   After an emotional memorial service at St. Margaret of Scotland
Roman Catholic Church here, Sopracasa, a former all-America
lacrosse player at Sachem High School, was buried Monday near his
family's Farmingville home. The funeral was attended by his family,
more than a hundred friends and all of his teammates from UMass.
</P>
<P>
   Sopracasa's teammates voted last week not to play the season's
final game, which was scheduled for last Saturday at Brown, so that
the entire team could take a bus from Massachusetts to Long Island
to attend his wake and funeral. Many of them still struggled Monday
to fully understand just how this happened to someone who was so
young and who appeared to be so healthy.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Ira S. Nash, a cardiologist at the Mount Sinai
Medical Center in New York, there exists only a fraction of a
second when a sudden blow to the chest can cause the heart to go
into ventricular dysrhythmia and eventually stop beating
altogether. This quivering of the heart is called commotio cordis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is thought to happen is a blow to the chest, at a very
precise moment, is equivalent to giving the heart an electric
shock,'' Nash said. ``That mechanical impulse throws the heart out
of its rhythm. But the timing has to be just right for this grave
disturbance to occur. What happens next is the heart can stop
pumping blood altogether, causing the victim to collapse
immediately. It is important to point out that this is not the same
as a real trauma to the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a risk involved in all athletic activities, Nash said,
but these rare occurrences should not cause parents to keep their
children from participating in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite uncommon,'' Nash added. ``You're probably at a
greater risk in your mom's car on the way to a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The victims are usually young people, and ones who frequently
have thin or narrow chests, said Dr. Barry Maron of the
cardiovascular research division of the Minneapolis Heart
Foundation. He has analyzed other fatal chest injuries in baseball,
soccer and lacrosse.
</P>
<P>
   Maron gave four conditions for commotio cordis to occur: a blow
over the heart, relatively light and at just the right moment in
the heartbeat cycle, and to an individual with a thin or narrow
chest.
</P>
<P>
   Sopracasa fit into that category. He was listed at 5 feet 8
inches and 170 pounds, probably generous numbers according to
several of his teammates. But it was his rather small size that
endeared him to those who played with him. He was considered too
small by many college recruiters, but he made up for his lack of
physical bulk with an uncommon fire and dogged determination.
</P>
<P>
   An expert in fatal chest blows, Maron and his colleagues studied
25 athletes, ranging in age from 3 to 19, killed by a blunt blow to
the chest. They published their findings in the New England Journal
of Medicine in August 1995. Sixteen deaths resulted from baseballs
hitting the chest, one from a lacrosse ball, four by hockey pucks,
one by a karate kick, one by a football helmet and the other two by
softballs. Before learning of Sopracasa's death, Dr. Frederick
Mueller of the National Center for Catastrophic Sports Injury
Research had never heard of a college athlete dying after a blow to
the chest.
</P>
<P>
   A lacrosse ball, which is made of hard rubber and weighs five
ounces, can reach speeds of 80 miles an hour when it is shot.
</P>
<P>
   Of chest padding and whether it could prevent commotio cordis,
Maron said: ``Common sense would say that additional padding over
the heart may do some good. But that needs to be proved through
research. And that hasn't been done as this is all relatively
new.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Waxer, who was Sopracasa's defensive partner two years ago,
said: ``This whole thing is hard for me to understand. I've been
hit in the same spot at least a hundred times. We're defensemen, so
we always get hit by the ball. It kind of goes with the territory.
But why did Eric die? I just don't get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
