<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AQUAFINE-ANNIVERSARY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WATER, AQUAFINE'S A BIG FISH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARITA, Calif. _ It started with chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, Aquafine Corp. got its start in a tiny downtown
Los Angeles office designing air purification systems for
industrial chicken farms.
</P>
<P>
   When antibiotics became a common ingredient in chicken feed,
company founder Louis Veloz changed the company's focus to water
purification through the use of ultraviolet light.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a good move.
</P>
<P>
   Sustained by strong demand and product diversification, the
multimillion-dollar company based in Valencia in northern Los
Angeles County will throw its 50th anniversary party this Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive Roberta Veloz said the company's success and
longevity have not come as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought it was going to be successful,'' she said.
``It has a lot of potential just because of the environmental
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Veloz, the daughter-in-law of Aquafine's founder, began working
at the company in 1980 and purchased it outright in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to her heavy investment in infrastructure,
Aquafine now has a &UR;  &LR; strong presence in the water purification
industry. Its products supply clean water for drinking and
semiconductor production, and its major customers include the
Coca-Cola Co., Anheuser-Busch Cos., Bristol-Myers Squibb and
Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has a growing international role. It opened an
office in the Netherlands last year, and officials say 35 percent
of company sales are now overseas.
</P>
<P>
   President Michael Murphy said revenues have grown almost 200
percent since 1994, bringing the private company into the ``$15
million to $25 million'' range.
</P>
<P>
   And there's more to come, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be a $50 million company in the next five
years,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's signature technology _ the use of ultraviolet
light to neutralize microorganisms and reduce organics _ has driven
much of Aquafine's growth.
</P>
<P>
   UV systems have become a standard part of semiconductor
production, a booming industry in which even trace contaminants in
a water supply can hurt the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Aquafine equipment is also used for beverage and pharmaceutical
production, shrimp farms, aquariums and building cooling systems.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said future growth will be fueled by innovation,
including developing chlorine-reduction technology and the
introduction of ``turn-key'' systems that integrate several
Aquafine systems into one compact unit.
</P>
<P>
   Veloz said the growing popularity of nonchemical water treatment
methods will also boost demand for UV systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the alternative to chemical disinfection,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But rapid growth has presented one major problem: how to fit
more work space into already-cramped facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The company owns one building and leases three others in the
Valencia Industrial Center. But President Murphy estimated the
company's current space _ about 40,000 square feet total _ is about
half what it needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's equipment that we frankly don't have room to put in
right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Long-time employee Wayne Schulze said he welcomes the change
from a smaller, family company to an international corporation. Now
a sales administrator with international responsibilities, Schulze
said he began working at the company in 1985 as an assembler making
$5 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things had stayed the same,'' said Schulze, who now makes
far more and is earning a bachelor's degree with the company's
financial assistance, ``I wouldn't be where I am today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
