u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-TRIMS     05-10 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BELGRADE-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE MOURN EMBASSY VICTIMS, AND ASK QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-CHINA) 
(nk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ They had laid her out in her best clothes
and wound a long silk chiffon scarf around her neck and draped it
down the length of her body. But the fine clothes could not hide
the stitches that closed an ugly gash on the forehead, nor the
black bruising that the bomb blast had inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu Ying, just short of her 28th birthday, died on Friday in the
NATO bombing attack on the Chinese embassy here. She had been
asleep in bed with her husband, Xu Xinghu, 31, upstairs in the
building when the bombs hit close to midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Monday they were in their coffins beside each other in a small
chapel at the New Cemetery. Xu was in a gray suit, white shirt and
tie, his face bruised and his spiky black hair standing on end. In
the quiet calm of the chapel, the violence of their deaths was
shockingly apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Beside them lay Shao Yunhuan, dressed in a pale turquoise
trouser suit, her face and hands blackened and bruised and her
frail body lying unevenly, her limbs wrenched in an unnatural
position.
</P>
<P>
   Xu was the Belgrade correspondent for The Guangming Daily, where
Ms. Zhu had also worked, in the advertising department. Ms. Shao
worked for the official New China news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The explosions that killed them came with such force that they
shook buildings miles away. The bombs, which NATO said it had fired
at the wrong target, landed in the sleeping quarters of the
embassy. They set fire to the building and demolished whole floors.
</P>
<P>
   One official survived by chance. ``Just two meters away from me,
the whole floor opened up,'' the official said. ``Those poor people
who were killed were sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 100 Chinese mourners _ family members, journalists and
embassy workers _ gathered for a short ceremony here at noon
Monday, before the bodies were cremated.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zhu's father, Zhu Fulai, a specialist on Japan, stood at the
head of his daughter's coffin, bowing to each group of mourners as
they filed past. He was alone, he said in an interview, because his
wife had collapsed when she heard of their daughter's death and was
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   No relatives stood at Ms. Shao's coffin. Her husband, an embassy
employee, was in the intensive care unit in Central Hospital,
unaware of his wife's death. He was blinded in the bombing and is
to be flown to Beijing for an operation as soon as his condition is
stable, colleagues said. Friends who have visited him said that he
was conscious but that no one had told him the news because of his
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Four other victims remain in the intensive care unit, including
the military attache, Ren Baokai, who was pulled from the wreckage
eight hours after the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Mourners, dressed in black, wore white paper carnations in their
buttonholes at the ceremony. As they passed, they smoothed the long
white ribbons of paper, crossed with Chinese calligraphy, that
decorated the wreaths of flowers. They bowed from the waist at each
coffin, many with tears streaming down their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian and Chinese officials attended the ceremony and were
quick to push their political message after the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a serious violation of international charters and the
sovereignty of China,'' said Sun Yuxi, a spokesman for the Foreign
Ministry who arrived from Beijing after the bombing. ``NATO should
take full responsibility for this act that caused three deaths and
wounded 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun said the bombing had been deliberate because three missiles
had struck the building. ``I visited the site yesterday,'' he said,
``and from the bombing I think the embassy was clearly targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three dead, he said, ``We are taking them home as
heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president of the Serbian government, Milovan Bojic,
criticized NATO, saying: ``They are not choosing their targets.
Their main aim is to destroy our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade Mayor Vojslav Mihailovic said, ``I appeal to all people
who create and can influence policy making in the world to prevent
further killings.''
</P>
<P>
   One diplomat said NATO made the embassy a target on purpose, not
least because such a mistake could have been so easily avoided.
``The American military attache was often coming to the embassy,''
the diplomat said. ``They were surely some CIA people in the
embassy here, and they had to have had the correct information.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The deputy editor in chief of The Guangming Daily, Chai
Huisheng, remembered Xu as one the paper's best correspondents.
``He was an ordinary guy,'' the editor said. ``Open, jokey. But he
really worked. Since the air strikes began, he wrote every day, and
there was huge interest in his articles.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zhu, had been popular at the paper, he said, adding, ``She
was always a joyful, happy person.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Zhu said he had not seen his daughter since the summer of 1997,
because his work had taken him to Japan and she had come to
Belgrade. Looking stern and troubled behind thick glasses, he sat
on a hotel sofa afterward and wondered aloud about the tragedy. He
said he had not followed the reactions that his daughter's death
had stirred. But he did wonder what NATO commanders and President
Clinton were thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Clinton always calls for human rights, and I agree
with him,'' Zhu said. ``But why does he not care for the rights of
my daughter? I want the president to understand that people, both
American and Chinese, all just want to live peacefully and
quietly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
