<HEADLINE>
AMY FISHER IS FREED AFTER 6 YEARS IN PRISON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)   (jw) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Amy Fisher was released from state prison
Monday morning, ending nearly seven years behind bars for the
shooting of Mary Jo Buttafuoco.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher flew to Long Island with her mother, who had fought
long for her release, and went into seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing dark glasses to shield her eyes from the bright morning
sun and the television news cameras, Ms. Fisher, who is 24, emerged
from the State Correctional Facility at Albion shortly before 9
a.m. and embraced her mother, Rose Fisher, who led her to a waiting
car. They were taken to a nearby airport, where they boarded a
privately chartered plane for the return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy is thrilled and very happy to be back with her mom,'' said
Ms. Fisher's lawyer, Bruce Barket, who helped usher her through the
crowd of waiting reporters and into the car. ``All she wants is to
spend the next few days with her mom and start getting used to life
outside a prison.''
</P>
<P>
   The final clearance for Ms. Fisher's release came last week when
the New York State Parole Board voted 2-1 to grant her parole. The
board acted several days after Judge Ira Wexner of Nassau County
Court reduced Ms. Fisher's sentence from a maximum of 15 years to a
maximum of 10 years, making her immediately eligible for parole.
Wexner acted after finding that Ms. Fisher was not appropriately
represented in 1992 by her first lawyer, Eric Naiburg.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Buttafuoco made an emotional appearance at the resentencing
hearing, telling Wexner that she had forgiven Ms. Fisher and asking
him to press for Ms. Fisher's release from jail. Ms. Fisher
tearfully told Mrs. Buttafuoco she was sorry for shooting her and
said she accepted total responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fisher was 16 and a senior at John F. Kennedy High School in
Merrick when she began an affair with Mrs. Buttafuoco's husband,
Joey, an auto-body repairman. She was 17 when she went to the
Buttafuoco home in Massapequa on May 19, 1992, rang the bell, and
shot Mrs. Buttafuoco in the face when she answered the door. The
.25 caliber bullet is still lodged in Mrs. Buttafuoco's neck.
</P>
<P>
   Joey and Mary Jo Buttafuoco now live in a suburb of Los Angeles,
where he has been the host of a radio talk show. They moved from
Long Island after Buttafuoco served six months in the Nassau County
jail after pleading guilty to having sex with Ms. Fisher when she
was a minor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
