<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-NEXTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT IS ACQUIRING 4 PERCENT STAKE IN NEXTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Demonstrating that its ambitions are not tethered to the wired
world, Microsoft Corp. said Monday that it had agreed to pay $600
million in cash for about 4 percent of Nextel Communications Inc.,
a big national provider of wireless communications.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's deal appeared to be Microsoft's biggest move yet into
the fast-growing wireless communications market. As part of the
deal, Microsoft, the No. 1 personal computer software company, will
help Nextel deliver data services, including electronic mail and
date books to wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Nextel will use software developed by Microsoft as a
framework for delivering an even broader range of Internet-based
services to its wireless users.
</P>
<P>
   Coming less than a week after Microsoft announced a $5 billion
pact with AT&AMP;T Corp. to use Microsoft software in some of AT&AMP;T's
cable television systems, Monday's deal highlighted Microsoft's
hunger to expand beyond the PC industry. Even as AT&AMP;T moves to use
cable systems to deliver integrated packages of voice, video and
data communications, new technologies are facilitating the delivery
of services more advanced than phone calls and without wires.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft wants to move its Windows operating system into both
environments and into others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft and Nextel will deliver the next generation of
wireless services to enable people everywhere to stay in touch with
the information they need, regardless of location,'' Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman, said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ozburn, general manager of Nextel's online unit, said in an
interview, ``Whereas yesterday, if you walked away from your PC,
you would have no ability to touch the power of the Internet. When
we launch Nextel Online, wherever you are, you will be able to
access those Internet tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Nextel's network, which uses wireless frequencies that were once
used largely for dispatching trucks, covers about 70 percent of the
U.S. population. But Nextel plans to offer the service in only six,
undisclosed markets this year. Using phones made by Motorola Inc.,
one of Nextel's primary backers, the company plans to offer the new
services throughout its system next year.
</P>
<P>
   For Nextel, Monday's deal came less than a week after it emerged
from abortive negotiations to be acquired by MCI Worldcom Inc., the
No. 2 long-distance carrier, which does not have a significant
wireless operation.
</P>
<P>
   Those two companies walked away from weeks of negotiations after
MCI Worldcom refused to pay Nextel what it wanted. Nextel's
discussions with Microsoft, however, had been developing for at
least that long. Some executives in the wireless phone business and
on Wall Street speculated Monday that Nextel's growing confidence
that it would get a cash infusion from Microsoft stiffened the
company's backbone in its talks with MCI Worldcom.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel is growing fast, but is not generating free cash flow
because it must record large interest charges on its almost $10
billion in debt and because it is spending about $1.9 billion a
year to expand its network.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to refinance some of its own debt and perhaps to improve
its cash position, Nextel is planning a new $1.2 billion bond
offering, according to some executives on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel declined to comment on its financing plans.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of the telecommunications and computing worlds
took yet another step Monday as Lucent Technologies Inc., North
America's biggest maker of telephone equipment, announced that it
had developed a new technology that could reduce from five to one
the number of microchips needed in a phone that uses Internet
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucent technology could make Internet phones cheaper and
easier to manufacture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
