<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ADDS FORMER WHIP TO HIS CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, seeking to add political
firepower to his campaign for the Democratic presidential
nomination, has enlisted former Rep. Tony Coelho of California as a
top strategist, several Gore advisers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers said Gore was turning to Coelho, a former House
majority whip who became an investment banker in New York, out of a
sense that his campaign was lacking direction and had been
diminished by favorable publicity about his rival, former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Coelho have had a series of meetings to discuss his
role, and met here as recently as this weekend, Gore advisers said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Gore's advisers said that they were not certain of
Coelho's title, that it might not have been worked out, but that he
would play a central strategic role in the campaign. It was not
clear how that would affect Gore's campaign manager, Craig Smith, a
former White House political director.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman, would not confirm Coelho's role
with the campaign. Lehane said only, ``I can't comment at this time
beyond the fact that they're obviously friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho did not return calls to his Washington office on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He and Gore first knew each other when they served together in
the House. More recently, the vice president and Coelho have worked
together on issues for the disabled. Coelho had epilepsy and has
long been a spokesman for people dealing with epilepsy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Coelho was a rising star in the Democratic Party
and was known as one of the party's most prodigious fund-raisers.
But he abruptly resigned his House seat in 1989 after accusations
of financial impropriety in his personal investments. No charges
were ever brought against him.
</P>
<P>
   Coelho re-emerged in the political spotlight in the summer of
1994, when President Clinton brought him to the Democratic National
Committee as a senior strategist dispatched to help save the
party's sagging fortunes in the elections that November.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two months before the election, Coelho told USA Today
that 1994 would be ``a normal, off-year election'' and not as
devastating as many Democrats feared. It was devastating, with
Republicans re-taking the House for the first time in half a
century. Once again, he returned to investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   One Gore adviser recalled Coelho's role in 1994 and questioned
what he could do for the vice president. ``He's an extremely smart,
capable guy,'' the adviser said. ``But the last time he was brought
in to whip something into shape he didn't last very long. I'm not
sure he knows how to wield that whip.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers insisted that they were not worried about
accusations surrounding Coelho's resignation from the House after
nearly a decade, even though Gore himself had been buffeted by
questions about his fund-raising in the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic strategist who supports Gore said Coelho was ``a
piker by today's standards'' in terms of the accusations that
swirled around him. The strategist added, ``And that was years and
years and years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps another sign of Gore's potential weakness, the
Republican National Committee said Monday that it had told its
research department to devote half its time to scrutinizing
Bradley's record.
</P>
<P>
   David Israelite, the party's director of political and
governmental affairs, noted in a memorandum to the Republican
national chairman, Jim Nicholson, that Gore's poll ratings had
slumped and that Bradley's were improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on this most recent confirmation of what our earlier
research has indicated, I have directed our research department to
shift its focus to Bill Bradley a full 50 percent of the time,''
Israelite wrote. ``We will continue to monitor the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clifford May, a Republican Party spokesman, said, ``We think
that at this point there are two candidates for the Democratic
nomination and the voting public deserves to know as much as
possible about both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lehane, Gore's spokesman, attacked the memorandum as a ploy
to make Gore appear vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their strategy is pretty obvious,'' he said. ``If they pretend
like they're attacking our opponents, by implication it's intended
to show that we have been weakened by their attacks on us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
