<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRUISING TO CHARLESTON
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to take my mother, who is 80, on a tour of
plantations in the South, by bus or barge. She has mentioned
visiting Charleston and thereabouts. Any suggestions? _ Kathleen
Sullivan, Manhasset, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. A number of companies, like the Delta Queen Steamboat Co.,
(800) 215-0805, and Riverbarge Excursions, (888) 456-2206, offer
plantation cruises on the Mississippi River. There is no such great
river meandering through the Southeast, of course, but there is the
Intracoastal Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The Nantucket Clipper is a 100-passenger ship that makes several
seven-night tours of the antebellum South i March, April and
November, between Jacksonville, Fla., and Charleston, S.C., calling
at Savannah, Ga., among other places. On Oct. 19, the vessel is
also scheduled to depart on an 11-night Colonial America and Civil
War cruise from Washington to Jacksonville, also calling at
Charleston and Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   There is time for touring on your own at the ports of call, or
optional excursions can be booked at extra cost, according to
Elizabeth McQuinn, a spokeswoman for Clipper Lines.
</P>
<P>
   At Charleston, for example, a three-and-a-half-hour outing to
Middleton Place, an 18th-century plantation with landscaped gardens
on the Ashley River, costs $46. A three-hour Historic Charleston
tour, including the 1803 Joseph Manigault House, costs $33. Similar
tours are offered in Beaufort, S.C., Savannah and other ports.
</P>
<P>
   The prices for the antebellum cruise are $1,950 to $3,490 a
person; the Civil War cruise costs $2,900 to $5,000. For more
information, contact Clipper Lines, 7711 Bonhomme Ave., St. Louis,
MO 63105; (800) 325-0100, fax (314) 727-6576;
www.clippercruise.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you go to Charleston directly, Charleston Tours offers
several tours of the area, using 15- and 25-passenger buses. These
range from a 90-minute city tour for $15 to an ``all-day
adventure'' combining the city tour and a trip to Boone Hall, a
plantation with gardens, slave cabins and an Avenue of the Oaks,
for $45. Jane Kiser, the owner, said she also arranges custom
tours.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Charleston Tours at 545 Savannah Highway, Charleston, SC
29407; (843) 571-0049, fax (843) 571-6248;
www.charleston.net/com/charlestontours/tours.htm.
</P>
<P>
   There are no true preserved plantations around Savannah, but
there are plenty of historic sites. The Savannah Convention and
Visitors Bureau, (877) 728-2662, and its Web site, www.savcvb.com,
can lead you to about three dozen tour operators.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is the River Street Riverboat Co., (800) 786-6404,
which uses two paddlewheelers for 60- and 90-minute narrated tours,
some with meals and entertainment (including gospel music), for
$13.95 and up. It offers occasional special tours in conjunction
with the Georgia Historical Society, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   By land, Gray Line Historic Landmark Tours, (912) 234-8687,
offers daily bus tours to museum and private homes in the city and
low country for $16 and up. Arrangements can be made for a private
guide and a car, as well, said Betsy Clapcott, director of sales
and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL TO EUROPE BY SHIP
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to explore France and the British Isles on foot.
Since I've grown wary of air travel, can I take a ship across the
Atlantic from Montreal or Boston? _ Hillary Smith, Peacham, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A. Most trans-Atlantic crossings these days are out of Florida
or New York, the latter mainly on the Queen Elizabeth II. I could
find only one ocean liner calling at Boston from Europe. But you
can leave nearly any week from Montreal on one of two
passenger-carrying freighters operated by Canada Maritime,
according to Kerry Touloumis of Travltips, freighter cruise
specialists in Flushing, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The ships, the Canmar Pride and the Canmar Honour, are
40,881-ton vessels built last year. Each has double and single
cabins, which are carpeted and air-conditioned, and have a
refrigerator and a sitting area, as well as private bath with
shower. Each also has a passenger lounge with television and VCR.
Passengers dine with the officers on Western and Indian cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   The ships leave Montreal on Sunday and are due in Thamesport,
Kent, England, a week later. On the return trips, they leave
England on Monday and stop in Antwerp, Belgium, and Le Havre,
France, before returning to Montreal. The cost is $1,740 one way,
$3,165 round trip.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Travltips at P.O. Box 580188, Flushing, NY 11358; (800)
872-8584; www.travltips.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to return in luxury and the timing is right, the
Seabourn Pride, a Cunard line ship, leaves London on Sept. 5 for a
14-day cruise to Scotland, Iceland and Newfoundland, arriving in
Boston on Sept. 19. The cost is from $11,550 a person, double
occupancy. Information and reservations: (800) 528-6273;
www.seabourn.com.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER SKIING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. For my husband's 50th birthday, we would like to plan a ski
trip for July. Are there choices for summer skiing other than
Portillo, Chile? _ Susan Zimmer, New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Portillo, where the U.S. ski team has trained, is but one of
more than a dozen ski resorts in Chile, including several _ La
Parva, El Colorado and Valle Nevado _ close to Santiago. And across
the border in Argentina are another dozen. The main centers for
skiing in Argentina are around Mendoza in the northwest (including
Valle de Las Lenas) and around Bariloche, farther south, in the
Lakes District.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is to head for the South Pacific, New
Zealand specifically. There are a number of ski areas, but the most
popular, according to Anna Synnott of the New Zealand Tourism
Board, are those on the South island, near Queenstown. These
include The Remarkables and Coronet Peak.
</P>
<P>
   Holidaze Ski Tours, 810 Belmar Plaza, Belmar, N.J. 07719, (800)
526-2827, www.holidaze.com, offers Southern Hemisphere ski trips.
Bob McErlean, the owner, said his most popular trip to New Zealand
was five nights in Queenstown. Including air fare from Los Angeles,
a Milford Sound cruise and transfers, it is $1,325 each, double
occupancy. Four days of lift tickets is $87 more.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also books summer ski trips to Chile and Argentina.
In Chile, seven nights at Valle Nevado, including air fare from
Miami, breakfast and dinner daily and lift tickets, start at
$1,716, a person double occupancy. Holidaze has similar trips to
Bariloche or Las Lenas in Argentina, with prices from $1,716.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
