<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-ALITALIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALITALIA TO BE THIRD PARTNER FOR NORTHWEST AND KLM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alitalia said Monday it intended to join Northwest
Airlines and KLM Royal Dutch Airlines in a broad partnership that
would combine their services over the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The three airlines said they would sell seats on one another's
flights, coordinate schedules and pricing, integrate their
frequent-flier programs, share facilities and combine marketing,
advertising and some back-office tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest and KLM have jointly operated in this way since 1993.
Their link helped usher in a wave of international airline
alliances that has picked up momentum recently.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's announcement, which was made by representatives of the
three airlines at a news conference in Manhattan, had been expected
in the wake of an aviation treaty between the United States and
Italy completed in November.
</P>
<P>
   Under that open-skies accord, Italian and American carriers are
free to fly back and forth between the two countries without
restrictions on where and how often they can land. In exchange,
Washington agreed that Alitalia would be granted immunity from
antitrust laws if it entered into an alliance with a domestic
carrier. The three airlines involved in this tie-in must still
apply to the Department of Transportation for approval, but that is
seen as a formality.
</P>
<P>
   Alitalia has struggled financially in recent years, but its
Milan, Italy, airport hub is considered one of the most promising
in Europe because it has much room for expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Alitalia previously entered into a partnership with KLM and also
has an agreement with Continental Airlines, which in turn is allied
with Northwest. Later this year, the four airlines are expected to
announce a broader international alliance called Wings. It will
compete with the Star Alliance, which includes United Airlines and
Lufthansa, and One World, which is anchored by American Airlines
and British Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Separately Monday, American and Japan Airlines began selling
seats on each other's flights in Asia and North America. The
arrangement allows American to expand its network into Asia while
giving Japan Airlines greater reach in North and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Candace Browning, an aviation analyst with Merrill Lynch in New
York, said the Northwest-KLM partnership had proved to be one of
the most profitable alliances. Northwest now handles KLM's North
American sales, which allowed the Dutch carrier to lay off several
hundred employees in the United States. KLM in turn handles sales
for Northwest in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the two airlines struggled for years to make the partnership
work, a challenge that they are expected to again face with
Alitalia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
