<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-VAUGHN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vaughn trying hard not to 'stink'
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Greg Vaughn promised anybody who would listen all
through his darkest days of April, ``I won't stink it up forever.''
</P>
<P>
   So, are better days ahead? Is the odor gone?
</P>
<P>
   Going into tonight's opener of a two-game series against the
Milwaukee Brewers, Vaughn has hit three home runs and driven in
four runs the past two games as the Cincinnati Reds try to put
something together.
</P>
<P>
   They've won one in a row. Big deal? Well, they haven't won three
in a row all season and only three times have won two in a row in
their first 29 games.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of it had to do with the inability of their $5.75
million left fielder to put anything together after he hit 50 home
runs and drove in 119 runs for the San Diego Padres _ then became
the first player to hit 50 homers in a season and get traded at the
end of that season.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, though, dropped a tidbit on the media multitude in front
of his locker Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fast starter, never have been,'' he said. ``Somebody
pulled my numbers the other day from April of last year and told me
I was only one home run and one RBI off my pace from last year. You
know, you still have to play the game. I'm not a moper or pouter .
. . there are a lot of other important things in the game in
addition to home runs and RBI and that's what I try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Vaughn only hit five home runs in April last year. He had
four this April. And actually, he had only 12 RBIs last April. This
April he had 13.
</P>
<P>
   In May, June and July he scorched everything _ 12, 10 and 11
homers, 32, 24 and 23 RBIs. He tailed off in August and September
to a combined 12 homers and 28 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and Sammy Sosa are good friends and we talked at length
this weekend,'' Vaughn said. ``We told each other, 'It's going to
be all right for both of us. I looked at the schedule, man, and we
have a lot of baseball left. I'm sitting around banging my head
against the wall and I still have 115 games to play.' And Sammy
said, 'Look at me. Our numbers are just about the same.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he took a different, more relaxed course after his
chat with Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (hitting coach) Denis Menke before Sunday's game, 'I'm
going to see how easy I can hit the ball hard. I feel I've been
overswinging and my head's been pulling off the ball, trying to
make things happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Vaughn and Barry Larkin suffering the April blues, the club
lounged in last place in the National League Central, but
Cincinnati has won four of its last six games and captured five of
the last six series and while the Reds remain last, they are only 4
games off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Reds continue to get offensive punch from an
unexpected source, a source that surprised Chicago Cubs manager Jim
Riggleman. Second baseman Pokey Reese, who begins tonight's game
with a seven-game hitting streak, went 7 for 11 in three games
against the Cubs, lifting his batting average to .326.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'd say Reese is the most improved player I've seen
this year,'' Riggleman said. ``He was an automatic out last year,
but he looks to me as if he knows what he is doing with the bat
this year. And he is doing it from the difficult No. 8 spot,
batting in front of the pitcher where you don't many good pitches
to hit.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
