<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NBC Plans New Net Company
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Attempting to take its ``Must See TV'' might to cyberspace, the NBC
television network yesterday said it is partnering with two leading
Internet companies to create a consumer-friendly Web portal.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will form a separate, publicly held Internet entity called
NBC Internet. NBCi, as the firm will be known, will incorporate
content from two San Francisco firms: Xoom.com, an online community
center, and Snap.com, a joint venture between NBC and Cnet that
provides news and searching.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies are hoping to create a broad,
general-interest site that will attract millions of users by
leveraging NBC's brand-name with Snap.com's rich content and
searching, and Xoom.com's e-commerce expertise.
</P>
<P>
   NBCi will be headed by Chris Kitze, the chairman of Xoom.com,
and will be headquartered in San Francisco. Kitze said NBCi will
have about 300 employees, mostly in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The site will operate under the Snap.com name and will have Web
searching capabilities, e-mail, e-commerce, online chat and NBC
content, such as video from ``Saturday Night Live,'' the companies
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBC's Internet strategy is to take their viewers and turn them
into users,'' said Lawrence Marcus, who follows Internet stocks for
BancBoston Robertson Stephens in San Francisco. ``They are driving
eyeballs from TV _ which is the most pervasive, powerful and
persuasive media there is _ online, where they can perform
transactions and get additional information, courtesy of NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the ``Must See TV'' viewership was a main factor in
Xoom.com's decision to merge its site with NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have a TV partner who could drive significant
amounts of viewers to the Web site,'' said Kitze. ``We believe at
the end of the day, the winners on the Internet are the ones that
have real brands. There are billions of dollars of brand equity
tied up in the NBC brand. I think it's safe to say you'll see a big
peacock on our site.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal does not include MSNBC, the 50-50 joint venture between
NBC and Microsoft Corp. However, Snap.com will continue to give
MSNBC ``premium positioning'' on the new site, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   NBCi will spend $380 million to advertise on NBC TV over the
next four years and will buy another $500 million in advertising
over the following six years.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, which owns NBC, will own about half of NBCi.
Xoom.com will own 34 percent and Cnet and Snap.com option holders
will own a 13 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Xoom.com zoomed $6.75 to $81.88. Cnet, which is based
in San Francisco, rose $22.44 to $136.20. GE shares fell $1.20 to
$108.75.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers placed the value of the new company between
$3.5 billion and $4 billion _ far less than other major Internet
portals such as Yahoo, which has a market value of $31 billion.
However, analysts said Wall Street's ``dot com'' frenzy would most
likely propel NBCi's value far beyond its initial worth, giving its
backers the leverage to do additional mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination will be worth considerably more than these
properties are worth as they stand alone,'' said Ryan Jacob, a
portfolio manager for the Internet Fund, which owns shares of
Xoom.com.
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies such as Yahoo and Excite are in a race to
build one-stop-shopping sites for Web surfers. These sites offer
news and other content, plus the ability to buy products, send
e-mail and chat. The more the sites offer, the more ``eyeballs'' or
users they attract. That translates into advertising dollars for
the site's operators, who can command more money for a highly
trafficked site.
</P>
<P>
   Kitze said NBCi would be the seventh-largest site on the
Internet and would be available within three to four months.
</P>
<P>
   Both Xoom.com and Snap.com are among the top 20 most visited
sites on the Web. Xoom.com, which has 7.5 million members, is an
online community offering free services such as home page building,
chat rooms, message boards and online greeting cards. It also does
direct e-commerce _ a service like direct mail, which targets an
individual user with products and services relevant to their
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Snap.com, which is 60 percent owned by NBC and 40 percent by
Cnet, is an Internet portal that provides news and other content,
as well as searching.
</P>
<P>
   The content of those sites will be fused with NBC's current
online assets, which include NBC.com, Videoseeker.com and CNBC.com,
in which NBC owns a 10 percent stake. NBC's other sites include
localized community guides, video clips from its shows and movie
trailers. The CNBC.com site will be launched later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To users, this means that they will only have to go to one
place _ Snap.com _ on the Web to search, chat with users of like
interest, e-mail ... and purchase products,'' said Marty Yudkovitz,
president of NBC Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   If the merged entity passes regulatory hurdles, NBCi will begin
trading publicly &UR;  &LR; within three to four months, Kitze said. Xoom's
stock would close and NBCi would be traded under a new ticker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
