</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Why Chevron Wants to Buy Rival Texaco
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Rebecca Smith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
A merger between Chevron and Texaco, the subject of heated rumors,
would create a company so huge that it could boost profits $1
billion a year simply by trimming expenses a modest 2.5 percent,
analysts said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest way to accomplish that feat would be to eliminate
duplicative functions. ``Do you really need two sets of oil
geologists for the Gulf of Mexico for instance,'' asked oil stock
analyst Edward Maran of A.G. Edwards in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And since Wall Street values oil companies at roughly 20 times
their earnings, stockholders would be rewarded with a $20 billion
windfall reflected through a higher stock valuation for the merged
company.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts said that may be the driving force behind the
rumored Chevron-Texaco deal as well the recent British
Petroleum-Amoco-Arco merger and Exxon-Mobil deal.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers said Texaco and Chevron have one other big
reason to merge: familiarity with each other's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two companies have known each other longer than any
other oil companies,'' said Fadel Gheit, oil analyst for Fahnestock
&AMP; Co. in New York. ``They know each other's operations and culture
and strengths and weaknesses. This deal makes better sense to me
than the other deals.''
</P>
<P>
   The two companies have been involved in a joint venture, Caltex,
since 1936, refining and marketing oil products cooperatively in
Asia, the Mideast and Africa. All told, the Caltex partnership
operates in 60 countries from its headquarters in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The two firms have joined forces on many other projects, as
well, including an alliance formed last year to jointly market
marine fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators certainly would look closely at the deal to make sure
the combined company didn't increase their control of the fuel
marketplace, a huge chunk of which is gasoline stations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said antitrust problems are pithy since Texaco
surrendered control of many service stations and refineries to a
new partnership with Royal Dutch Shell, called Equilon Enterprises,
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Though they still look like they did, Texaco stations in the
West and Midwest now are operated by Equilon. Texaco has a 44
percent stake in the company and Shell has the remaining 56 percent
interest since its piece of the pie was worth more.
</P>
<P>
   A separate partnership controls Texaco's refineries and service
stations in the East and Gulf States. Motiva Enterprises was
created last year by the pooling of the refining and marketing
assets of Texaco, Shell and Saudi Aramco.
</P>
<P>
   Though these alliances have given Texaco some of the benefits of
a merger without having to actually go through a merger, it could
be a big stumbling block to a deal with Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts already are poring over market share numbers,
trying to ascertain what the impacts of a merger might be on the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   If Chevron now stepped into Texaco's boots, it might be judged
too large and powerful by antitrust regulators at the Federal Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, the partnering of Chevron, Texaco and Shell would
put 43 percent of all branded outlets in the hands of these
affiliates, far ahead of Mobil-Exxon at 12 percent market share and
Arco at 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with 25 percent share for Chevron, Texaco and
Shell in the Gulf states, the next-highest area of concentration
posed by a Chevron-Texaco merger.
</P>
<P>
   The solution proposed by one analyst is that Shell and Texaco
swap out their holdings in such a way that Texaco would divest its
holdings where Chevron is strong _ to allay antitrust concerns _
and would pick up Shell assets where Chevron is weak.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, that would mean the Chevron-Texaco market share
would drop from 43 percent to 17 percent and Shell's would rise to
26 percent. In the Gulf States, the shedding of Texaco assets would
give Chevron-Texaco a 14 market share and give Shell a 12 percent
market share, according to numbers compiled from federal statistics
by CIBC Oppenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of regulators should be to eliminate some of the
overlap between these companies,'' said Fahnestock's Gheit. ``But
that can be done and if this doesn't go through, I'd be
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, neither company was commenting on the merger
rumor yesterday, which appears to have been revived over the
weekend by a story appearing in Sunday editions of the Sunday Times
in London.
</P>
<P>
   With most of America's integrated oil companies apparently
``spoken for'' further merger activity will move down to the next
tier of oil companies, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The next names on the list: Conoco Inc., Phillips Petroleum Co.
and USX Marathon Oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
