</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Online Insurer InsWeb Gets the Ball Rolling for an  Initial
Offering 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
InsWeb is going public.
</P>
<P>
   As anticipated in a July 3 Street Smarts column, the Redwood
City e-commerce startup has filed documents with the Securities and
Exchange Commission saying it intends to sell shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The number of shares, time frame and suggested price range for
the offering were not disclosed in the initial filing. Goldman
Sachs _ which is the lead underwriter for TheStreet.com offering _
will be the lead manager on the InsWeb deal.
</P>
<P>
   Co-managers of the insurance site's IPO are BancBoston Robertson
Stephens; Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette; and E-Offering, the online
underwriter launched by E-Trade and Sanford Robertson, co-founder
of Robertson Stephens. InsWeb executives and their bankers were
unable to comment because of quiet-period restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   InsWeb is a financial services concern that was started by
insurance executives _ as opposed to techies _ who believed that
their rather staid and conservative industry was ripe for the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   InsWeb was founded by chief executive Hussein Enan, a 30-year
underwriting industry veteran who scrapped his retirement plans
after hanging around the house watching his son surf the Net. Enan
cobbled together a group of major insurance companies to experiment
and invest in a Web site that would attempt to make buying
insurance easier and less costly for all involved.
</P>
<P>
   InsWeb doesn't sell insurance _ which some Web purists argue is
a shortcoming _ but instead is a matchmaker. It allows consumers to
compare insurance rates online from companies that have
prequalified them for a policy. The site aims to simplify the
process and tries to cut down the amount of time it takes to get a
quote from an insurer.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the business model clearly identifies how InsWeb
can make money. Insurance customers aren't charged anything.
Instead, revenues are collected from the insurance companies listed
on the site.
</P>
<P>
   InsWeb offers life, health and auto policies with more than 30
carriers, including such heavyweights as AIG, the Hartford, John
Hancock, State Farm, Mutual of Omaha, CNA and Nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   What makes InsWeb even more interesting is that two major
insurers are big shareholders. Insurance Information Exchange,
which is an affiliate of CNA, owns about 19 percent, and Nationwide
holds about an 11 percent stake. The two largest shareholders are
Enan and Softbank _ the Japanese venture capital group _ each
holding roughly 20 percent shares.
</P>
<P>
   Softbank has invested about $100 million in InsWeb during two
rounds of financing, which places a pre-IPO value on InsWeb of
about $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   An early stage investor was Sequoia Capital, the Menlo Park
venture capital company known for investing in such high-tech
superstars as Cisco, Apple and Oracle. However, Sequoia did not
show up in the filing as a shareholder with holdings of 5 percent
or more.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the insurance market is massive _ U.S insurance
customers spend nearly $700 billion a year _ InsWeb is the rare
Internet offering that could show profits sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MATTHEWS FUND &LR; : Wow. I guess it's fair to say that Chronicle
readers are bullish on Japan. After last week's item on the
launching of the Matthews Japan Fund, Street Smarts' voice and
electronic mailboxes were inundated with queries about how to
invest in the fledgling offshore fund. Here's the skinny: The fund
has yet to be assigned a ticker symbol. But you may invest in the
no-load fund, which was launched April 15, via discount brokerages
such as Charles Schwab and Fidelity Investments. These outlets are
not supposed to charge any additional fees for taking your order.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions about the fund, would like a prospectus or
would like to invest directly, you may do so by calling Matthews
International at (415) 788-6036. Of course, Street Smarts is
passing this information on as a courtesy and doesn't endorse this
or any fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
