<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1763 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-DALE-NYT &LR;      05-10 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWIN DALE JR., 75, REPORTER, AND AN EXPERT IN ECONOMICS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Edwin L. Dale Jr., a former economics reporter in
the Washington bureau of The New York Times who later explained the
intricacies of supply-side economics as a budget spokesman in the
Reagan administration, died Monday at the Washington Hospice.
</P>
<P>
   He was 75 and was visiting in Washington when he died. He had
homes in Delray Beach, Fla., and Osterville, Mass., on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was lung cancer, said his wife, Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   Dale worked for the Times from 1955 to 1976. In his journalistic
work, economists often found him as knowledgeable as they were. For
example, Dale was credited by economists with being one of the
first to establish that the roots of inflation lay as much in the
service sector as in the pricing of goods. He came to this insight
in the 1950s and helped bring it to public awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Laitin, a spokesman for government agencies including the
treasury department, said, ``One budget director commented to me
after an interview that this man Dale was qualified to be budget
director.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Volcker, the economist, said, ``It was pretty wild and
woolly when I was chairman of the Federal Reserve, and he was a
voice of calm, common sense during that period.''
</P>
<P>
   Volcker said that when Dale became the spokesman for David
Stockman, director of the Office of Management and Budget under
President Ronald Reagan, ``I thought that was a waste of a good
journalist, going to the budget bureau.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale was born in Philadelphia and went to Yale University, where
he was managing editor of The Yale Daily News and graduated in
1944, in time to serve as a naval officer in the Pacific in World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   His first newspaper job was with The Worcester (Mass.) Evening
Gazette in 1947 and he was an economics reporter for The New York
Herald Tribune before joining the Times.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Dale assisted on an important scoop on the escalation
of the war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Karnow, in his 1983 book ``Vietnam: A History,'' wrote
that Rep. William Moorhead of Pennsylvania held a party at his home
in Washington that was attended by Dale and Townsend Hoopes, the
under secretary of the Air Force. Hoopes, Karnow said, had turned
against the war and ``hinted to Dale that a faction of the Pentagon
was forming to resist a troop buildup in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting on Dale's hint, the Times was able to report on March 10
that President Lyndon B. Johnson was considering a Pentagon request
to call up 206,000 more men at a time when the administration was
proclaiming that Communist forces had been crippled by losses
suffered in their recent Tet offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Dale was the author of ``Conservatives in Power'' (1960,
Doubleday) and the principal author of ``The People's Budget''
(1995, Regency). He was co-editor, with his Times colleague Richard
E. Mooney, of ``Inflation and Recession?'' (1958, Doubleday).
</P>
<P>
   Dale was married to Mary Todd Hastings from 1950 until her death
in 1983. In addition to Mrs. Dale, he is survived by a
stepdaughter, Rosalind C. Dujardin of Bermuda; a stepson, Daniel C.
Cross of Washington, and six step-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
