<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- May 10, 1999 -- SCI-BEETLES-FIRE, 5-10 --
Researchers are studying the biology of the beetles that flock to
smoke and fire and promptly move to plant their eggs in the damaged
terrain. Recent studies show that the beetles have highly sensitive
detectors in their antennas and thorax, indicated by the red
arrows, which sense smoke. Researchers hope that by understand the
way beetles' can detect smoke, a new generation of fire alarms can
be developed. (Dr. Helmut Schmitz/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
