<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DIVISIVE POLITICS IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial on Tuesday, May 11: &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Next week's election in Israel will help determine the course of
the peace negotiations with Palestinians and Israel's Arab
neighbors. No less important, however, is the election's likely
impact on achieving peace among Israelis themselves. At a time when
Israelis have generally embraced conciliation with old enemies, it
is startling that the nation is more fragmented than ever on ethnic
and sectarian lines. Could the last curse bestowed by the 20th
century be for Jews to split into feuding tribal divisions, like so
many other countries? To help avoid that fate, Israelis can use the
campaign to reinforce the values of tolerance and inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   A hotly contested election campaign always underscores the
bitterness of any country's divisions. In the current campaign,
politicians representing Jews from Asia, Africa and the Middle East
are feuding with politicians representing Russians over who will
control the Interior Ministry, and the patronage t commands.
Religious Jews are fighting with non-observant Jews over which
customs the government should protect or promote. Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, who is behind in the polls, portrays himself as
the tribune of Israel's ethnic ``outsiders,'' mainly the Oriental
and religious subgroups. Ehud Barak, the Labor candidate, has
dubbed his coalition ``One Israel,'' but recently one of his
supporters created a furor by referring to some Jews as
``riffraff.''
</P>
<P>
   It is dismaying to think that American consultants to both
parties may be encouraging Israeli politicians to exploit their
divisions rather than heal them. But on another level, the
squabbling among subgroups represents a certain healthy maturing of
Israeli democracy. It would be impossible and unwise in any
representative government to avoid or suppress debate over the
benefits of government. The fact that Israelis are now fighting
over these things may also reflect a new consensus that security
issues are less urgent than they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Israel can nevertheless take some steps to minimize sectarian
and ethnic infighting. The current parliamentary system, in which
the prime minister is elected by one ballot and members of
parliament are elected in a separate vote, seems to exacerbate the
problem and is already being reconsidered. At present, Israelis may
vote for Netanyahu, Barak or other candidates on the overriding
economic or political issues and then exercise their narrow
self-interests by voting for a splinter group for parliament. As a
result, at least 32 parties are fielding candidates for parliament,
and it seems likely that 20 or so parties will be elected in a
parliament with only 120 members. Neither Barak nor Netanyahu, the
front-runners for prime minister, is expected to command more than
a quarter of the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Founded after World War II in fulfillment of the dream of
Zionists, who were largely secular European Jews, Israel fragmented
into factions almost from the beginning. It could not have happened
otherwise, as waves of immigrants from the Mediterranean, Russia
and Africa sought refuge, bringing many of their own religious and
folk beliefs. Though Israel is a democracy with an established
religion, it can find positive values in its diversity.
</P>
<P>
   But for such a system to work, no one form of Judaism should
dictate to others, and Jews must learn to be sensitive to those of
different backgrounds. Israel may have some distance to go on that
score. A recent poll showed that only 56 percent of Israelis
believe that equality of rights existed in their country. An
election that understandably underscores the divisions of society
can nonetheless clear the way for a new civic identity of
inclusiveness and respect for pluralism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
