<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0496 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1781 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LA     05-10 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-COLBASE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY HAS IDEAS ABOUT STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cal State Northridge plays its home games in one of the worst
college baseball facilities in the country.
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a significant movement by the university to
raise funds for the construction of a new stadium. Maybe the
athletic department should know who to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy, an All-American shortstop at CSUN who got a
$650,000 signing bonus after he was drafted in the first round by
the St. Louis Cardinals in 1997, said the athletic department
hasn't called him since he went pro.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he would give a portion of his bonus for a new
stadium _ if he knew Matadors head coach Mike Batesole would reap
the benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to give something to that school and have
(Batesole) not be around,'' Kennedy said. ``I owe him the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who is a starting middle infielder at Triple-A Memphis,
said his alma mater doesn't appreciate baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``How hard is it to build a nice stadium there?'' he said.
``Look at the Valley, how many kids play baseball. I guess (CSUN)
doesn't understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Batesole, who is finishing his fourth season as the head coach
and looking to sign a new contract, said he hasn't asked Kennedy
about giving back to the program that developed Kennedy into a
potential major-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said Batesole ``knows where I stand.'' He wouldn't mind
helping out financially for a new stadium ``if coach Batesole was
to be there in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Munson and the draft:On June 2, Eric Munson will be a lottery
winner. His income-tax bracket will be elevated after one 10-minute
phone call.
</P>
<P>
   Munson, USC's All-American catcher, is projected to be among the
first five picks in major-league baseball's amateur draft. Before
the season, he was rated Baseball America as the No. 1 college
player available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about it,'' he said the day before his return
to the Trojans' lineup earlier this month after he sat five weeks
with a broken hand. ``(The teams) know what I can do. Obviously
it's a big deal, but I'm not going to worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Munson's draft approach indicates two things: (a) He went
through this kind of anticipation before, in 1996. He was a senior
at San Diego's Mt. Carmel High and was drafted in the second round
by the Atlanta Braves. And (b) he has nothing to prove to the
scouts who have watched him play the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   A broken hand doesn't matter much when you're talking about a
guy who should be in the major leagues in two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   Munson will probably get a signing bonus of at least $2 million
from the team that drafts him. Considering he's a catcher, he might
get more because of the scarcity of young good players at his
position.
</P>
<P>
   But this is what Munson says he does care about: getting the
Trojans back to the College World Series. USC, the defending
national champion, will definitely get a bid to the NCAA playoffs,
which expanded from 48 teams to 64 in the offseason. The No. 23
Trojans (31-22) are in a battle to host a first-round regional.
</P>
<P>
   After missing 21 games with the injury, Munson returned to the
starting lineup as the designated hitter against UCLA on May 2. He
went 0 for 2 with a sacrifice fly. Two days later he had two hits,
including a double, and two runs scored in a nonconference win over
San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Munson) needs some time to go back to being him,'' USC head
coach Mike Gillespie said after the UCLA game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Torresmania: CSUN signed Yucaipa High left-hander John Torres
to a letter of intent. Torres, who is 7-2 with a 1.60 ERA,
resembles Fernando Valenzuela, according to CSUN pitching coach
Jamie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call him ``Little Fernando'' because he's got that pudgy
body,'' Nelson said, ``but we'll work that off.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Around the horn: UCLA's 3-2 win over USC on May 1 ended a
significant streak: The Bruins won for the first time in 404 games
when scoring three runs or less. . . . Pepperdine's Dane Sardinha,
a sophomore catcher, and Jay Gehrke, a junior reliever, have been
added to Baseball America's ``College Player of the Year watch.''
Sardinha leads the Waves in batting average and Gehrke leads the
nation in saves. . . . CSUN lost its exclusive hold on the NCAA
record for home runs in a game. Alabama slugged 13 homers in a 30-4
rout of Alabama-Birmingham, tying the Matadors' mark set against
Fresno State in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
