<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-TRADE-56     05-10 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-TRADE-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDES FEAR CLINTON'S CHINA DEAL HAS BECOME COLLATERAL DAMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Mont.)   (jw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the days just before NATO mistakenly bombed the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, administration officials were already
voicing fears that they might have missed their moment to strike a
political deal to get China into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Such a deal has been the centerpiece of President Clinton's
much-debated effort to build a ``web of engagement'' with Beijing.
Now the hopes of patching it together in a few months are fading,
and White House officials doubt that they will have the political
opportunity to get it through Congress after that.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing has clearly fueled the nationalist sentiments that
were forcing Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, China's leading economic
reformer, to pull back some of the concessions he offered a month
ago.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, creates a backlash here. Members of Congress who
were wavering about whether to support the deal that Clinton nearly
had in hand seem virtually certain to reject any accord with lesser
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   But that is only the beginning of the problem. The images of
Chinese tossing bricks at the U.S. Embassy may harden the views of
powerful figures including Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority
leader, who argue that the United States should not aid China's
efforts to seek prestige through membership in the group that sets
the rules of world trade.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has said he opposes China's entry because of Beijing's
alleged espionage efforts and human rights abuses. For its part,
the AFL-CIO has vowed to oppose the deal for fear that American
jobs will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the bombing of the Chinese Embassy, it was very
optimistic for the administration to think they could get this
together before the summer,'' said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., who
has been leading the effort in the Senate to get China into the
trade group and whose constituents export farm products to Asia.
Now, he said, ``It's much harder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But to a great extent,'' he said, ``this is now in the hands
of the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   Baucus is among many inside and outside the administration who
are critical of Clinton's decision to walk away from the
market-opening concessions that Zhu offered last month in
everything from agriculture to foreign ownership of cellular phone
concerns. Had a deal been initialed then, Baucus argues, it would
probably be far less vulnerable now.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell, some Clinton aides say, whether the
president himself harbors second thoughts about not having closed
an agreement while Zhu was here.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, Clinton castigated a few of his advisers after
Zhu's visit, saying that while the president was focused on Kosovo,
his aides should have been finding ways to quickly close the
negotiating gap.
</P>
<P>
   That outburst led to a last-minute effort to rescue a deal.
Clinton called Zhu in New York on April 13, offering to send
negotiators to Beijing immediately to finish up the talks. They
arrived days after Zhu's return but ran into obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese negotiators, under attack at home for giving so much
away, floated suggestions that the 14-page list of Chinese
concessions that the administration published during Zhu's visit
was no longer on the table. The American team returned home
empty-handed. In the aftermath of the Belgrade bombing, it is
unclear whether they will return to Beijing next week as scheduled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The best face that administration officials could put on events
Monday was that the well-coordinated protests on the streets of
Beijing might amount to a means for the Chinese to vent their
anger, first at the bombing and second at the widespread sense in
China that the economic concessions demanded for membership in the
trade group were part of some grander plan to check China's
economic rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're hoping,'' one official said, ``is that the
anti-American protests run their course and Zhu can proceed with
his reforms.'' In that case, the reforms would include the kind of
opening of markets that entry into the trade group would require.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a chancy bet. And if it turns out that the embassy
bombing was a turning point _ that the deal within Clinton's grasp
a month ago has become part of the collateral damage of the Kosovo
conflict _ then the effects could be serious and lasting. For the
deal was less about trade than about global strategy, accommodating
China's rising economic power to a world system in which Beijing
still feels treated as an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case where they probably could have gotten it
through Congress,'' said Nicholas Lardy, a scholar at the Brookings
Institution. ``Whether they could get the same deal right now is
highly uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lardy noted that while China suspended various talks with
the United States on Monday, it did not withdraw from the trade
talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
