<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1794 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOMS-DOUBLE-UP-LADN     05-10 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMS-DOUBLE-UP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMS' FIESTA TAKES NO SIESTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Latina mothers across Southern California got a
chance to double dip from the well of pampering by celebrating
Mother's Day on Sunday and again Monday, when it is observed in
Mexico and other Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
   In Arleta, 15 moms gathered at Rosalba Ramirez's house with
their young children to enjoy each other's company, good food and
one of the biggest holidays in their native countries, a day after
the American version.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers with that background get to celebrate it twice,'' said
Norma Ramirez, who has been organizing (italics) Dia de las Madres
(end italics) for eight years. ``You get to make some phone calls
to your own mother in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Alva, 37, has two sons at Canterbury Elementary School,
the common denominator among many of the mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use this opportunity to teach our kids about both
celebrations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To make the holiday happen, the mothers had to work hard: A trio
of them slaved over a hot stove making (italics) mole (end
italics), the traditional chocolate-based dish. The heart-shaped
corsages they all wore they made for each other.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all about companionship and keeping one holiday alive
as another overshadows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get into the spirit of friendship and love,'' said
Norma Ramirez, 41. ``It's really hard to do it like you used to do
it in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Fate dictated that the American celebration of Mother's Day took
place this year a day before May 10, the traditional day of
observation in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Acuna, a Chicano studies professor at California State
University, Northridge, said the (italics) Dia de las Madres (end
italics) is just one of a string of Mexican holidays that fall in
May, including Cinco de Mayo and Labor Day, which is celebrated May
1.
</P>
<P>
   Partly it's a response to warming spring weather. Flowers, as in
the United States, are a Mother's Day staple in Mexico. Missing
from the American celebration, though, are the serenades children
have played for their mothers. No. 1 on the request list is ``Las
Mananitas,'' ``The Morning Serenades,'' Acuna said.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Pamiagua, 17, said her mother, also named Maria, accepted
the flowers her children gave her Sunday but was waiting for this
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's like a big thing,'' the younger Maria said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the two Mother's Days were rolled into one because of
their proximity. Santa Rosa Church in San Fernando usually holds a
special Mass for the Latino celebration but held it on Sunday this
year, said Terry Vinson, who edits the church bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody came with roses for their mothers,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0500 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1795 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAS-WWII-WORTH-IT?-IN     05-10 1220
