<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY CHARGED IN FLORIDA; ARRAIGNMENT IN 2 WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry's unfolding legal situation advanced to the
next level Monday when he was officially charged with possession of
cocaine and with soliciting prostitution, according to Pam Bondi,
the assistant state attorney in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who was arrested in Tampa on April 14 on the charges
of possessing three-tenths of a gram of cocaine and soliciting
prostitution from an undercover police officer, will be arraigned
on May 26.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old outfielder/designated hitter was in Tampa
working out at the Yankees' minor-league facility at the time he
was arrested. Strawberry has said that the cocaine was not his and
that he was joking with the female officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We officially filed criminal charges on him today,'' Bondi
said. ``Evidently, there were rumors going around that we were
going to drop the charges against him, and that's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Bondi said that if Strawberry pleads not guilty, the case will
go to trial. The solicitation charge is a second-degree misdemeanor
and carries a maximum sentence of 60 days in the county jail. The
cocaine possession charge is a third-degree felony and is
punishable by up to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   While it is possible that Strawberry's lawyer could try to reach
a plea bargain agreement before the arraignment date, Bondi
declined to discuss the likelihood of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ficarrotta, Strawberry's lawyer, did not return a
telephone call left Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who is on administrative leave from baseball and is
forbidden to work out with the Yankees or their minor-league teams
until his situation is resolved, was suspended for 60 days in 1995
after he tested positive for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   This development further complicates Strawberry's chances of
returning to play this season because, regardless of his plea, it
increases the lengthy span that he has been away from the Yankees
and from playing baseball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
