</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIMA SAYS MEDICATION LED HIM TO LIE IN POLICE BRUTALITY CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to add what medication Louima was taking, and
4th graf to conform; SUBS 8th graf, Volpe and ..., to CORRECT, all
four officers are charged with beating Louima in police car, Volpe
and one other charged with assault in station house; Raises names
of all defendants higher; Combines takes.) 
 (nk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Abner Louima endured a grueling day of
cross-examination Monday by defense lawyers, who hammered away at
lies he had admitted to telling and conflicts in his various
accounts of his alleged beating and torture by four police officers
in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Louima, a 32-year-old Haitian immigrant, calmly responded by
attributing some of the conflicts to a memory clouded by medication
in the days after he was injured, and said it was ``my choice'' to
follow a supporter's advice to falsely tell a grand jury that one
officer said, ``This is Giuliani time,'' during the alleged
assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time I give evidence before the grand jury, I was under
medication and my memory, it wasn't clear like it is now,'' Louima
said. Louima said he did not remember what the medication was, but
a defense lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, said records showed it was
Tylenol with codeine.
</P>
<P>
   Answering Kornberg, who had demanded to know ``why your
testimony is different today than it was when you testified for the
grand jury,'' Louima said, ``Now I am not really worried too much
about my health.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Louima suffered injuries to his rectum and
bladder after he was beaten and tortured after his arrest in a
street melee in 1997. Referring to those injuries, Louima said of
his answers at this trial: ``I don't have to carry a colostomy bag,
like I was thinking maybe I have to carry for the rest of my life.
I am more peaceful now. I have a better chance to think.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg responded sarcastically, ``You were peaceful enough to
commit perjury in the grand jury, weren't you?''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange came as Kornberg, who represents Officer Justin
Volpe, cited several falsehoods and a series of inconsistencies in
the accounts Louima gave to state and federal grand juries and
investigators and to the media in the months after he was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe and three other officers are on trial in the racially
charged case in federal court in Brooklyn. The four officers are
charged with violating Louima's civil rights by beating him in a
police car; Volpe and another officer are also accused of torturing
him at the 70th Precinct station house in the Flatbush section of
Brooklyn. The officers are white; Louima is black.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers cited several contradictions by Louima, such
as whether a second officer had restrained him in the restroom
while Volpe attacked him, whether Volpe or another officer put him
in a cell after the attack and how many officers allegedly kicked
him in the groin in the restroom.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of relentless questioning, Kornberg did not ask Louima
to respond to Kornberg's most explosive suggestion in the trial:
that Louima's injuries were not the result of Volpe ramming a stick
into his rectum, as the prosecution says, but by a consensual sex
act with another man before Louima encountered the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg later declined to say why he had not asked Louima about
this. But there was no doubt that Louima would have denied the
suggestion, and Kornberg has already indicated, in his opening
arguments to the jury last week, that he intended to support the
suggestion through testimony by medical experts who would tell the
jury that a sex act was consistent was Louima's injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The other two officers on trial, Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder,
are charged with taking part with Volpe and Schwarz in beating
Louima in the police car. A fifth defendant, Sgt. Michael Bellomo,
is accused of trying to cover up the alleged beating in the police
car. All five defendants say the charges against them are untrue.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Kornberg and the other lawyers opted to focus largely
on discrepancies in Louima's accounts of the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the most inflammatory statement, Louima said one of the
officers had told him, ``This is Giuliani time! It's not Dinkins
time.'' Louima retracted that statement, which he had made to
reporters and to a state grand jury, after federal prosecutors took
over the case and presented it to a federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In the start of his testimony last week, Louima said the
brother-in-law of a nurse at Coney Island Hospital, where Louima
was being treated for his injuries, had advised him to make the
statement. Louima testified that the man told him, ``I must say it
to get the mayor's attention and also to get the attention of the
people responsible for justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by another defense lawyer, Stephen C. Worth,
Louima acknowledged Monday that he had given more than one version
of that false statement.
</P>
<P>
   In a hospital news conference several days after he was
reportedly attacked, Louima said that an officer had made the
``Giuliani time'' remark in the station house restroom as he was
being tortured. But when he falsely reported that statement to a
grand jury at about the same time, Louima said an officer had made
the statement earlier, when he was being arrested in the
disturbance on a street outside a nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put it in a different place, in the bathroom rather than
on the street?'' asked Worth, who represents Officer Charles
Schwarz, charged with holding Louima down while Volpe shoved the
stick into his rectum and then his mouth in the station house
restroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Louima replied.
</P>
<P>
   But Louima refused to agree with Worth that the idea for the
``Giuliani time'' statement had come not from the nurse's
brother-in-law, but from lawyers who represented Louima at the
outset of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Worth said that those lawyers, who were replaced, had possibly
gotten the idea from the Rev. Al Sharpton.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, sir,'' Louima responded.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Louima might face prosecution for his admitted
lies to the grand jury, a prosecutor, Loretta Lynch, declined to
comment. But it seems highly unlikely that the federal prosecutors
who have painted Louima as suffering grievously from what they have
called a depraved and traumatic assault would prosecute him for
perjury.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the only moment of drama in an otherwise long day of thrust
and parry by the defense lawyers and Louima, Worth asked if Louima
could identify Schwarz as the man who prosecutors say drove Louima
to the police station after his arrest and then held him down,
handcuffed, in the station's restroom while Volpe tormented him.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the witness box, Louima scrutinized the table where
all the defendants and nearly a dozen lawyers sat and said of
Schwarz, ``It looks like the driver, but I'm not sure.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first day of testimony last Thursday, Louima identified
Volpe as the man who tortured him in the station house restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Often Louima said he did not remember answers he had given in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you can just say I don't remember every time you
don't want to give an unpleasant answer?'' Worth said.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-examination of Louima is due to continue Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
