<HEADER>
A1813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNT-RANCH-2TAKES-NYT     05-10 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNT-RANCH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARANTEED-KILL RANCHES THRIVE, BUT OPPONENTS WANT THEM BANNED
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DEBRA WEST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleven years ago, having given up on venison farming, Jerry
Contento found a new and lucrative use for his sprawling property
in Homer, N.Y. He imported some big-game animals, fenced in nearly
300 acres and opened a ranch where, for a fee, hunters can shoot
Russian boar, Rocky Mountain elk, American buffalo or any of a
dozen species of exotic deer and sheep.
</P>
<P>
   He never dreamed how good business would be. Contento's ranch,
Cold Brook Hunts, is booked solid this year, and weekends are
reserved well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters are lured by a guaranteed kill, an abundance of well-fed
animals to choose from, a year-round open season and the
opportunity to use a gun, bow and arrow or a spear. Amenities
include an on-site butcher, a walk-in freezer and hunts that can be
tailored to most any skill level (easy for people who use
wheelchairs, challenging for those who prefer several days of
stalking).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like sending them on a golf outing,'' said Contento,
40. ``You can hunt hard all day, but in a controlled environment,
where you can take a break and have a nice lunch. It's time spent
out in the country. It's a vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Animal-rights advocates have a less genteel description of it:
they call it ``canned hunting'' and say it is more slaughter than
hunt because the properties are fenced and the animals have no
chance to escape. They say that animals hunted on ranches are tame,
that they are bred and raised in captivity, fed on a regular basis
and have lost their instinct to flee humans.
</P>
<P>
   The animal-rights advocates, outraged by what they perceive as
cruelty to animals, have stepped up their efforts to pass state and
national legislation that would ban canned hunting. Last month, the
American Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals began
broadcasting a graphic advertisement in New York depicting a
Corsican ram, repeatedly shot in the rump with arrows, quivering
and bleeding with no place to run. The footage was taken by an
undercover investigator at a hunting ranch in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen hunting ranch owners in New York and Pennsylvania
did not return repeated calls, and those who agreed to be
interviewed declined to allow a reporter to witness a hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven states, including New Jersey and Connecticut, have banned
canned hunting. In April, after months of debate, the Oregon
Department of Fish and Wildlife adopted a regulation banning canned
hunting. The regulation will effectively put the state's only
exotic hunting preserve, the 2,200-acre Clover Creek Ranch, out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, where the practice is relatively new (Contento, who
opened his hunting ranch in Cortland County in central New York in
1988, claims to be the first), hunting ranches are not regulated by
the state.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Conservation, which
oversees hunting, regulates only indigenous or endangered animals
and migratory birds, said Patrick Martin, a wildlife biologist.
</P>
<P>
   And the state Department of Agriculture and Markets has
jurisdiction over farm animals and tests for diseases on all
animals brought into state, but does not keep track of which
animals go to hunting preserves, said Pete Gregg, a department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Federal legislation that would ban ranch hunting on properties
smaller than 1,000 acres has also been introduced, but it has a
slim chance of passage, said Wayne Pacelle, a senior vice president
for the Humane Society of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, Texas is the major impediment,'' Pacelle said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas had 637 hunting ranches in 1995, the last time a survey
was taken, said Ike C. Sugg, executive director of the Exotic
Wildlife Association, an industry group.
</P>
<P>
   Ranch hunting in Texas is a tradition that dates from the 1930s
and is an estimated $100 million-a-year business.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0508 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUNT-RANCH-NYT     05-10 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNT-RANCH-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: $100 million-a-year business.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In New York, a bill that would prohibit hunting non-native
species on ranches that are 10 acres or less and would prohibit
shooting caged, tied or hobbled animals, was passed by the state
Assembly in March. It is expected to be voted on this month in the
state Senate. The bill would make hunting on small ranches a
misdemeanor under the state's environmental conservation law,
punishable with a fine of up to $2,500 and a year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who are promoting the legislation do not know whether
there are actually any hunting ranches in New York state small
enough to be affected by the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original draft was an out-and-out prohibition on canned
hunts,'' said Lisa B. Weisberg, vice president for governmental
affairs for the ASPCA. The legislation was drafted six years ago,
but efforts of the National Rifle Association, the property rights
movement and sportsmen's groups have whittled it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see now is legislation that's been through two dozen
drafts,'' Ms. Weisberg said. ``This is the best we could get.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the ASPCA and Humane Society estimate that there
are four or five big-game hunting ranches in New York, but there is
no way to know for sure. Contento, who advertises at the Web site
www.spinners.com/lopinto/issue2/coldbrook/html, says he thinks most
former venison farmers in the state have converted to ranch
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   One reason ranch hunting has grown in popularity is that the
hunting can take place all year long. Hunting in the wild is
restricted to short seasons so that animals are not disturbed when
they are mating or bearing young. For example, in New York deer can
be hunted only in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Pacelle of the Humane Society attributes the growth in ranch
hunting to a quest for stuffed animal trophies that hunters like to
display.
</P>
<P>
   But Donald E. Todd, a taxidermist in Carmel, in Putnam County,
has a roomful of trophy animals that people hired him to stuff and
then for one reason or another left behind. Among the orphans are
two Russian boars, two Spanish goats and a Corsican ram that people
paid good money to hunt on game ranches in Pennsylvania and New
Hampshire, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, by the time I'm finished stuffing them, the wife
has decided she doesn't want it in the house,'' Todd said. ``It's
funny, because they go to so much trouble. Some of them know
exactly what they want, how they want the head facing, where they
want it looking. They already know where they are going to hang
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Fiduccia, a writer and producer of cable television
programs on hunting and fishing, has hunted twice at the Lucky Star
Ranch, a hunting preserve in the Chaumont, N.Y., north of
Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   The first time, he took a 200-pound fallow deer; the second, a
500-pound European red stag, and neither time was easy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, it's not a walk in the park,'' Fiduccia said,
describing his hunt for the red stag. ``We were there four days. I
saw something on the second day, and it was moving too quickly to
get. On the fourth morning at the crack of dawn, I used my black
powder firearm and took him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize how big an acre is, let alone 2,700
acres. You don't hunt on a ranch because it's easier. When you want
to hunt an exotic animal, there's no other option.''
</P>
<P>
   David J. Miller, 36, a landscaper from Newburgh, began hunting
when he was 18. He has killed a grizzly bear in Alaska, a black
bear in Maine and an assortment of big-game animals in several
states in between.
</P>
<P>
   He visited a 500-acre hunting ranch in Vermont where hunters can
shoot a razorback boar and pay by the pound (but they pay nothing
if they do not kill anything), and then he vowed never to hunt on
enclosed property again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on a regular hunt, you know you're going after
wild game,'' Miller said. ``In a preserve, you know everything is
fenced in. It's challenging, but it's like hunting in a shoe box.
There's a fence around it that's maybe 10 or 12 feet high. Once I
passed through the gate, it felt like going into Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   But the experience is largely determined by the size of the
property, said the Baron Josef von Kerckerinck, the owner of the
Lucky Star Ranch. Kerckerinck is from Germany, where deer have
traditionally been hunted in private parks. He imported European
fallow deer in 1978 and started venison farming. Four years ago, he
switched to hunting and since then has expanded his fenced preserve
from 700 acres to 2,700 acres. He keeps four species of deer, about
300 deer in all.
</P>
<P>
   He bristled at charges of cruelty by animal rights advocates:
``I believe the animals killed by a hunter's bullet dies a more
humane death than an animal killed in a slaughterhouse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0509 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      05-10 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ And we thought the Lakers were the
dysfunctional family of the Western Conference playoffs, the team
of petulance and petty jealousy, of potential unrealized.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of stealing Game 1 on the Lakers' home court, the
Rockets face the second game of the best-of-five series having
stolen Los Angeles' script.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were cast as the wise old men, too seasoned to crack
under postseason pressure, much less bicker and lay blame after one
defeat. But they lost Game 1 by a point Sunday, and forward Scottie
Pippen stunned his coach and teammates by pointing fingers around
the locker room instead of at his own slip and turnover in the last
eight seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We win together and lose together,'' Rockets center Hakeem
Olajuwon said. ``Nobody can blame anybody else. It's our loss. We
had the opportunity to win. We didn't win. Now, we have to stick
together. Nobody is going to point fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen apparently didn't get the memo. He pointed in several
directions but mostly at Charles Barkley's decision to foul
Shaquille O'Neal with 28.4 seconds left and the Rockets holding a
two-point lead. O'Neal sank one of two free throws, and the Lakers
scored the decisive points on their next possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that foul we gave Shaq was a very smart play,''
Pippen said Sunday. ``You'd have thought that somebody might have
told somebody that you don't want to do that with a two-point lead
and 28 seconds left.''
</P>
<P>
   Told of Pippen's postgame comments, Olajuwon was aghast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that? Scottie?'' Olajuwon said. ``If you want to point
fingers, you have to start with yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Under that ``cloud,'' as Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
described it, the Rockets on Monday began preparations for Game 2.
But rebounding from a crushing defeat had become an increasingly
difficult challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets more than believed they gave away a Game 1 victory
on the road, a win that would have given them the home-court
advantage and tested the Lakers' chemistry, which is still
potentially fragile. On top of that, they now had to carry the
burden of Pippen's postgame analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a frustrating night last night,'' Barkley said. ``I
stayed in the room all night just disappointed, because everybody
is going to talk about how well Glen Rice played, how well Shaq and
everybody played. If we would have taken care of our business, we
would have won the game. We gave that game away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably easier to come back from a loss like that
because we know we played well. We're not going to point fingers at
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminded, however, that Pippen already had, Barkley would not be
drawn into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, whatever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed further on the subject, he reiterated, ``You heard me.
Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   While not changing his stance Monday, Pippen did say he hadn't
intended to blame Barkley for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't criticizing anyone,'' Pippen said. ``It wasn't a real
smart move at that time. We should have made them work. Once we
fouled, we gave them the two-for-one advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't criticizing or pointing fingers at anybody. We lost
the game together as a team. Everybody felt like they played
poorly. It wasn't any individual. It was a team loss. We have to
play better as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Signed to help the Rockets tap into his six-championship
experience _ a motivation that seemed somewhat ironic after his
first playoff game with them _ Pippen maintained the team's
maturity would help it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Experience) is great,'' he said. ``When you realize somebody
has to lose yesterday, we happened to be caught in that position.
We feel like we're going to win a game here. That was our mission
coming here _ to try to split and steal the home-court advantage.
We allowed one to get away from us. We have to move on. We're
mature enough to realize the game is behind us, and we have to
concentrate on the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of positives. Our game plan worked to
perfection. We have to go out and put it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich expressed similar sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to accentuate the positive,'' he said. ``Everybody
forgets about the positive. Everybody starts talking about this one
little play and that little play. We did a lot of good things. I
talked about this before the game, the emotional ups and downs and
how we have to stay together and understand not to let the clouds
get us off track. It's not a desperate situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to playing so well and losing, however, can go
either way. Reminding that Olajuwon was unstoppable early and
Barkley late, or that the rookie backcourt of Michael Dickerson and
Cuttino Mobley had solid games, might inspire confidence. Or the
wasting of such performances could increase the frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets seemed willing to blame that frustration for
Pippen's postgame comments. The last time Pippen vented, wondering
aloud why the Rockets signed him after a game in Phoenix, he and
the team played well in the games that followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't take that stuff personally,'' guard Brent Price said
of Pippen's critique. ``The thing is for us to focus on beating the
other team and sticking together through the rough stuff.
Obviously, we're at a rough point when you play well, you have a
game plan in place, and it works (and you still lose). Other than
that one stretch in the second quarter, we controlled that game and
had it in our hands and let it slip away. Now, we're at that rough
point; we have to stick together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, however, the frustration was still hanging around the
day after.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an opportunity,'' Olajuwon said. ``Once it is lost, it
can never be regained. We had that game. Until you play the whole
series, you never know how big it was _ unless we win the game
tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
