u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT     05-10 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT RESPONDS WITH DEFENSE AND ACCURACY TO EVEN SERIES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Touche. The Miami Heat took back its turf and mended its
confidence Monday night, answering an embarrassing performance in
the opener of this series with an emphatic 83-73 victory over the
Knicks at Miami Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat evened the three-of-five-game series at 1-1, after
having lost Game 1 by 20 points on Saturday, and will try to
maintain its success at Madison Square Garden on Wednesday night in
Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, which led the entire game, put on a performance more
reflective of its regular season. It closed off the open shots that
had been offered to Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell in Game 1,
and made the big baskets when it had to in order to hold off a late
rush by the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell and Houston combined to shoot 8 for 22 for 27 points,
while Patrick Ewing scored a team-high 16 points. The Heat was led
by Alonzo Mourning's 26 points. The Knicks, who trailed by as many
as 14 in the third quarter, were down by 63-55, entering the fourth
quarter. They had pulled off comebacks at this arena before,
including one from 20 points down two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they were down by 13 with under three minutes left in
the game. Not flustered, they pushed onward against the odds and
were able to cut the Heat's lead to 78-70 with 2 minutes 4 seconds
remaining on a driving layup from a relatively quiet Sprewell.
Unlike in Game 1, the Heat responded when Dan Majerle nailed a
3-pointer with 1:46 to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat shot 50.8 percent to the Knicks' 39.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This was exactly the turn of events Knicks' Coach Jeff Van Gundy
dreaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural NBA thing is to lose tonight, come in to the
locker room and say, `We're happy with the split,''' Van Gundy said
before the game. ``I've never understood that. You come down here
to win Game 1. And whatever the result is, you move on to Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're at this point of the year, and you're having to warn
people, it's not going to get through anyway. You hope your team is
mature enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was as it had been in Game 1 from the start. The Heat
led, 46-35, at the half, had the hot hand in hitting 53.3 percent
from the field and played on the edge defensively to hold the
Knicks to 40 percent. Two days earlier, the Knicks held a 48-31
halftime lead and shot 58 percent, while the Heat hovered at 32
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The steam was still coming out the Heat's ears when Miami came
out of the half, and it built a 14-point lead midway through the
third quarter. The Knicks had to either get it together or give in
to the Heat's bully tactics.
</P>
<P>
   So they pushed back. With Ewing playing gallantly but hobbling,
with the Knicks' guards nearly invisible, the Knicks went to Larry
Johnson. And he scored 7 consecutive points, including a 3-pointer
when Terry Porter inexplicably left him on the wing with 3:07 left
in the third to cap a 12-5 run as the Knicks pulled to 57-50. The
Knicks absorbed a jumper from Porter but maintained their inspired
play.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ward hit a 3-pointer, which was followed up by Houston
finally shaking Majerle for a jumper. The Knicks were clapping
their hands and pumping their fists when they cut the Heat's lead
to 59-55 with a minute left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat edged back out to a 63-55 lead entering the fourth
quarter. This was as it was supposed to be _ a tight, intense
battle.
</P>
<P>
   This was not like Game 1 at all. The ease with which shots
opened up for the Knicks in Game 1 closed as Majerle harassed
Houston, and Coach Pat Riley's attack dog, Keith Askins, put a few
doubts into Sprewell's thoughts about driving to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   The fluid motion of the Knicks' up-tempo offense in Game 1 came
to a grinding halt in the first half. Instead of making their first
five shots, they missed four of their first five and were 5 for 14
at one point in the first quarter. Instead of the Knicks watching
the Heat misfire, Mourning's 17 first-half points were complemented
by 9 from Jamal Mashburn and 7 from Clarence Weatherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Knicks were not converting the Heat's misses into
easy transition baskets. Suddenly, the Heat was awake and back to
defend any time the Knicks tried.
</P>
<P>
   To amplify the difference between Monday night's start and
Saturday's game, the Knicks watched as Sprewell and Houston
combined to shoot 2 for 11 in the first half. They began 11 for 16
in Game 1. The ball movement that opened up the Knicks in Game 1
vanished. The Knicks had just 1 assist in the first quarter and 5
in the first half, while the Heat totaled 13.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case so often this year, once the guards were
shut down, all offense flowed through Ewing. There was no other
choice. Although his Achilles' tendon was sore and aching _ which
was apparent as Mourning ducked around him for dunks _ Ewing was
the only thing going for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Two days ago, there were cries of, Who needs Ewing? Can't he
just rebound, block shots and disappear into the background? Not
when no one else can get off a shot. Ewing scored 11 first-half
points on a 5-for-10 effort. The rest of the team went 7 for 23.
What a reversal by the Heat. This time, the Knicks were overwhelmed
by the Heat's intensity and taken aback by the onslaught of Heat
offense. In the second quarter, during a span of 1:41, the Knicks
picked up five fouls in a row.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
