<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-POWERBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE INTRODUCES NEW POWERBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ A resurgent Apple Computer introduced a new,
lighter Powerbook Monday that the company maintained would permit
it to retain its performance lead over the larger Intel-based
computing world.
</P>
<P>
   The company's co-founder and interim chief executive, Steven
Jobs, announced two new models at the company's annual development
conference, which began here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The machines, which are priced at $2,499 and $3,499, are both
built around a PowerPC microprocessor that employs the advanced
copper-based chip technology developed by IBM Corp., which
significantly reduces the power requirements and thus increases
battery life.
</P>
<P>
   The new machines, which have 333-megahertz and 400-megahertz
processors, are about 20 percent thinner than Apple's current line
of G3 Powerbooks. However, at 5.9 pounds they are still heavier
than the ultralight Windows-compatible notebooks, typically around
four pounds or less, from companies like Sony, Toshiba, Sharp and
IBM.
</P>
<P>
   On the retail computing front, Jobs said the iMac consumer line
of computers would soon be carried by more than 800 Sears, Roebuck
stores. That will give Apple a distribution channel into the
no-computer consumer world, which it needs following a decision
last month by the Best Buy chain to stop carrying the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs was also vague about the announcement date of the company's
long-rumored ``consumer portable,'' with which Apple is planning to
duplicate the company's iMac strategy in the low-end retail
computing arena. While Apple's sales have increased significantly
in the last year, it is still under pressure from the Intel world,
where prices of Intel's own processors and those of competitors
like Advanced Micro Devices have continued to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, pricing pressure did not appear to be a
concern. Jobs at one point in a two-hour presentation told the
audience of 2,500 Apple developers that the company had beaten the
current leader in the Intel world, Dell Computer, on maintaining
minimum inventories in the last three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple has become the most operations-efficient computer
company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the morning session was devoted to the company's
software strategy, and Jobs said that for the first time in years
the company now had a consistent message.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to introduce an enhanced version of its
Sherlock Internet search technology later this year. The software
will enable Macintosh users to query multiple shopping sites or to
gather other kinds of information.
</P>
<P>
   Apple announced that it was shipping a new update to its
operating system, version 8.6, and Jobs demonstrated two future
versions, one code-named Sonata and another that will be released
as Mac OS X sometime early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the features of Mac OS X, including a new windowing
system dubbed Quartz and some new interface features, are
reminiscent of Jobs' Next software, which received high technical
marks but failed in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence that Apple has made significant progress in wooing
software developers, Jobs said that Dragon Systems Inc., publisher
of a popular speech recognition system, would once again produce a
version for the Macintosh. Janet Baker, the company's chief
executive, said the company would release its software for the
Macintosh early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs went to some lengths Monday to thank the developers for
standing by the company during several rough years. He said that
the new Apple Computer had shaken off the software doldrums and
noted that in the last year since the introduction of the iMac,
software companies had announced some 3,100 new applications for
the Macintosh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
