<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-KELLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLER LOSES BID TO GET BACK ON U.S. SOCCER TEAM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Debbie Keller, the No. 2 scorer on the United States women's
soccer team last year, lost an arbitration decision Monday in which
she sought reinstatement to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Keller, 23, had contended that she was excluded by the national
team in its preparations for the Women's World Cup because she had
filed a sexual harassment suit last year against Anson Dorrance,
the women's soccer coach at the University of North Carolina and a
former coach of the women's national team.
</P>
<P>
   After hearings in Chicago last week, however, three lawyers
representing the American Arbitration Association ruled Monday that
the United States soccer federation had committed no wrongdoing in
not selecting Keller to participate in the six-month training camp
that began in January in preparation for next month's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The federation maintained that she was not invited to the camp
for soccer-related reasons, not for retaliatory reasons. The
20-woman roster will be named next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this matter behind us, our players, coaches and
administrative staff can continue to focus on the most important
task at hand, which is winning the 1999 Women's World Cup,'' said
Hank Steinbrecher, secretary-general of the federation.
</P>
<P>
   Keller was invited to the camp for a week in March after scoring
14 goals for the team last year. She filed the suit against
Dorrance last August in federal court in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was unprecedented by the coaching staff, not to invite
the No. 2 scorer from the team to the residency camp, not to offer
her even a chance to get on the World Cup team,'' said Dane
Butswinkas, a Washington lawyer who represented Keller at the
arbitration hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit had caused tension among national team players, a
number of whom, like Keller, played for Dorrance at North Carolina
and who remain fiercely loyal to their former coach. Tracy Ducar, a
backup goalie with the national team and a North Carolina
assistant, was also a defendant in the Federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Tony DiCicco, now the head coach of the national team, formerly
served as an assistant to Dorrance on the national team. In a
letter he wrote Keller last fall, DiCicco praised her intelligence
and said she played with a strong sense of purpose, but said he was
concerned that she had reached ``close to your full potential.'' He
also said there were ``chemistry issues,'' mentioning the lawsuit
and ``underlying issues with other players on the team.'' He did
not name those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Butswinkas declined to say whether Keller would continue her
effort to regain a spot on the team. Her options include an appeal
of Monday's ruling and seeking relief under federal
antidiscrimination statutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
