<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0514 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAFTAN-FASHION-700&AMP;AD     05-10 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAFTAN-FASHION-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SIXTH SENSE FOR THE NEW YIELDS SOMETHING OLD: THE CAFTAN   (jw) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just because Muriel Brandolini lives in an elegant
brownstone in the East 80s and is married to an Italian banker _
``a scion,'' Vogue called him _ is no reason to think that she has
everything. Before Mrs. Brandolini became a much-in-demand
decorator, she was a fashion stylist, and before that she was a
Vietnamese immigrant selling sheets at Descamps in Manhattan. Plain
old, run-of-the-mill cotton is to the former Muriel Phan-van-Thiet
what a radish was to Scarlett O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God, there's no messing around with her,'' said Marian
McEvoy, the editor in chief of Elle Decor. ``She's iron-willed _
and funny.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Mrs. Brandolini's equally audacious decorating style,
which favors eccentric combinations of European and Far Eastern
furnishings all surrounded by yards of lurid Indian pastel prints,
it might be called Upper East Side Souk. ``It's sort of violent,
actually,'' said Andrea Botta, a friend and client.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, while in India to finesse the details of her
second collection of home fabrics, Mrs. Brandolini had a bright
idea. She was in a textile factory in Jaipur, poring over the
tissue-thin voiles _ rajah pinks, wading-pool blues _ when it
occurred to her that they would make great caftans. ``I loved the
fabrics so much I wanted to wear them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Caftans are hardly new. They've been around, at least in
Christian times, since the dawn of the Byzantine era, when
fashionable Romans took up the ankle-length Persian style. They're
loose-fitting garments generally made of semi-transparent fabric,
like cotton voile, and they have a long and glamorous association
with the world's chic watering holes, from Palm Beach to Marrakech,
wherever the jet set has landed.
</P>
<P>
   Such, in brief, is the story of how an East Side decorator took
an idea and ran with it _ straight to Neiman Marcus and Barneys New
York, which will have her vivid block-print caftans on sale in
early June for $265. (Because caftans are traditionally sheer, Mrs.
Brandolini has also designed loose floor-length coats in
contrasting prints).
</P>
<P>
   The funny part is, the people in Jaipur initially tried to put
her off, saying they couldn't possibly produce samples in the week
or so before she left.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brandolini smiled at the memory. ``I said, `No, you don't
understand,' '' she recalled. `` `They have to be in stores in
June. I want them now, now, now!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since her days as a stylist for Italian Vogue and other
farsighted magazines, Mrs. Brandolini, the daughter of a Vietnamese
lawyer and a French-Venezuelan pianist, has demonstrated a sixth
sense for the new. ``She's always been at the top of the crest of
the wave,'' said Carlos Souza, Valentino's longtime press aide in
Rome. But now her timing seems all the more perfect.
</P>
<P>
   At the Paris haute couture collections in January, Oscar de la
Renta showed a creamy white caftan of pashmina cashmere for Balmain
that was embroidered with Indian paisley. Next to some of the more
overblown concoctions of the week, that simple caftan looked
utterly modern. ``Although it was very, very expensive, it sold
well,'' de la Renta said. About eight women, mostly from the
designer's American retinue, ordered it (at $15,000).
</P>
<P>
   ``The caftan is a very luxurious way of dressing when you're at
home and relaxing with friends,'' de la Renta said, adding that he
has always included a couple of styles in his own collections, and
that although stores seldom order them, they are among the top
sellers at trunk shows.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Sotheby's plans to auction caftans worn by the
American heiress Barbara Hutton in her home in Tangier. They were
made for her in traditional Moroccan silks by the French houses of
Lanvin and Givenchy. ``I think part of their appeal is the
arts-and-crafts look that is coming back, and that we want to look
less uniform,'' said Tiffany Dubin, the director of Sotheby's
fashion sales. ``That's Muriel's style.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's maybe a little bit of a 1970s thing,'' said Judy
Collinson, Barneys general merchandising manager. ``It's all
related to lounging and luxury.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, some of the enduring fashion images of the late 1960s
are of Yves Saint Laurent lounging in white Moroccan caftans in his
home in Marrakech. The intimation that there was little under that
gauzy shroud was part of its erotic appeal. And who among the
glamorous and jet-propelled didn't wear one? Babe Paley, Mirella
Agnelli, Chessy Rayner, Mica Ertegun. Diana Vreeland, the high
priestess of fashion, wore them like nothing. ``It was Diana who
introduced me to the caftan life,'' de la Renta said. ``Every
collection I would make one for her, so she had a lot of my
caftans.''
</P>
<P>
   Boaz Mazor, executive at large for Oscar de la Renta, recalled
an evening at Mrs. Vreeland's apartment when she came out in a
white caftan over a red leotard. ``You could see all of her,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brandolini, who is 39, had to look no further for
inspiration than her own chic mother-in-law, Cristiana Brandolini,
a legendary beauty and a sister of Gianni Agnelli, the Fiat tycoon.
``Her style of living has refined my eye _ just to watch and live
with her in her surroundings,'' Mrs. Brandolini said one morning
last week as her 3-year-old daughter, Filippa, played next to her.
(She also has a son, Brando, who is 6.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' she said, ``Cristiana has a greenhouse in the
countryside where all the furniture is slipcovered in blue-jean
fabric. Who would think of that?'' Mrs. Brandolini laughed. ``And
she wears caftans all the time. In Venice, at Palazzo Brandolini,
she wears them with maybe flat shoes and just some beads. She's
superchic.''
</P>
<P>
   From her home in Switzerland, Countess Brandolini said by phone,
``It's such an easy thing to wear.'' She sounded a little bemused
at the attention being paid to something that is, after all, almost
an anti-fashion garment. ``You can wear a caftan at home or to the
beach or, in the winter, with a sweater. I think it's a good moment
to wear it again because it's more modern to have your own style.''
</P>
<P>
   In her town house, with its flea-market lamps, Venetian shades,
and chaotic mix of pattern and color, Muriel Brandolini projects
some of the bravura for which she is known as a decorator, a flair
that has won her young clients like Christopher and Pia Getty and
Ms. Getty's sister and brother-in-law Marie-Chantal and Crown
Prince Pavlos of Greece, for whom Mrs. Brandolini recently
completed a sleek apartment in mostly navy, brown and cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muriel's style is a bit orgasmic,'' Botta, her first client,
said with a laugh. ``When she starts running, she runs.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if people found it hard to say no to her, Mrs.
Brandolini thought for a minute, as if the question were a
criticism. Then she flicked aside a strand of hair and said, ``My
husband would say I don't take no for an answer.'' Yet even she
seemed to marvel at the way she seized on her naive caftans and got
them swiftly under the noses of buyers, all in a matter of weeks
after returning from India.
</P>
<P>
   With four decorating projects in the works and plans to expand
her line of fabrics, with pillows and possibly table linens, Mrs.
Brandolini won't guess whether she will design more clothes in the
future except to say it's all part of a piece _ and maybe, who
knows, it might lead to a range of products sold together in
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Flipping through a stack of the fabrics which had inspired her
caftans, she said, with obvious understatement, ``It's beautiful in
abundance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
