<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LAS VEGAS, SHOPPING, TOO, CAN BE A HIGH-STAKES PASTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS, Nev. _ It's easy to drop a bundle in Las Vegas
without ever hitting the slot machines or the baccarat table. The
other high-stakes game in town is shopping. Although the Fashion
Show Mall has been around since 1981 with stores like Neiman Marcus
adding glamour to the usual mall mix, the ante has been raised
recently by high-fashion boutiques that have opened in the new
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Like hard-core gamblers who rarely take time to sleep, serious
shoppers can spend their money from 10 a.m. to midnight, 365 days a
year.
</P>
<P>
   A woman staying at Bellagio or Caesars Palace _ the two hotels
with the greatest number of shops _ could buy designer sportswear,
evening dresses, lingerie, shoes, handbags and real jewels without
ever leaving her hotel. A man's choices are more limited.
</P>
<P>
   The concentration at the seven-month-old Bellagio is on high-end
shops like Fred Leighton, Giorgio Armani, Chanel, Prada and
Tiffany's, while Caesars caters to nickel bettors as well as high
rollers, with shops ranging from Guess to Versace and Louis
Vuitton.
</P>
<P>
   How well the merchants are doing is questionable. Andrew
Hagopian, the director of retail stores at Bellagio, said the
hotel's stores were off to a better-than-expected start. But on a
recent weekend, the only ones that seemed busy were Chanel,
Tiffany's and Prada.
</P>
<P>
   At Caesars Palace, there were crowds walking through the
shopping area but few people in most of the boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   Via Bellagio, as the main shopping arcade in the Bellagio is
called, has a glass ceiling inspired by the Galleria in Milan,
potted palm trees and Italianate mosaic-tile floors. Sunlight
streams down during the day, creating the feeling of being in an
elegant European city. Each leased boutique has its own distinctive
decor, so regular shoppers feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Chow's sleek design is a highlight of Armani's spacious
store. Hermes features warm woods (and currently, for $2,025, a
man's bicycle in black with a tan leather seat). Prada has the pale
celadon walls and cutout figures in the window that have become its
signatures (and this spring's mirror-decorated clothes).
</P>
<P>
   The black and beige Gucci shop carries only accessories, mainly
bags; clothing is sold at the larger store in Caesars Palace.
Tiffany's looks like Tiffany's and offers china, glassware and
silver as well as jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Bellagio also runs several shops of its own, including Bellagio
Collections, with women's clothing by designers like Donna Karan,
Calvin Klein and Richard Tyler; a lingerie store that carries La
Perla and Fernando Sanchez, and a shoe store with Andrea Pfister,
Robert Clergerie and Stuart Weitzman.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a men's store named D. Fine with Italian-made
clothing and accessories ranging from Brioni suits to $450 handmade
shirts to $20,000 crocodile sport jackets.
</P>
<P>
   No crocodile jackets have been sold yet, but six ostrich jackets
at $13,000 have been snapped up, the store said. To paraphrase
Cindy Adams, only in Las Vegas, kids, only in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Forum Shops at Caesars meander under a ceiling that changes
from day to night skies as strollers pass Roman statuary, marble
columns, a gurgling fountain with Neptune reigning over winged
horses, and the occasional simulated volcanic eruption.
</P>
<P>
   Among the shops are Coach, Christian Dior Accessories, Escada,
Shaun Stein (which carries Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, Jean Paul Gaultier and
Moschino), Ferragamo, Fendi, Hugo Boss and Victoria's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   The newest hotel in town is the Venetian, which opened earlier
this month with its re-creation of the Piazza San Marco and
miniature Grand Canal and a roster of more than 50 shops scheduled
to open later, including Ann Taylor, Sephora, Jimmy Choo and Banana
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Still under construction is the Paris Hotel, with copies of the
Eiffel Tower and the Arc de Triomphe in front and, no doubt, more
shops.
</P>
<P>
   The Fashion Show Mall, with 140 small shops and five large
anchors, attracts more local people than tourists. ``We're quite
sedate, like a normal mall,'' said Terri Monsour, the general
manager of the mall's Neiman Marcus store. ``We have travertine
marble but no volcanos and no roller coasters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
