<HEADLINE>
NEW ENERGY FOR A NEW YORK BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (With HSBC-REPUBLIC) 
(mk) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ HSBC Holdings PLC's agreement to buy Republic New
York Corp. may mean that one of New York's slowest-moving consumer
banks gets a much-needed shot in the arm.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition also means that a significant number of Republic
employees are likely to be laid off, although the bank said Monday
that it was too early to say how many layoffs there will be.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Republic said it would eliminate about 560 jobs, or
nearly 10 percent of its 5,800-member work force. The bank said
that 384 of those job cuts would be layoffs. Analysts said Monday
that more layoffs were likely as the two banks consolidated
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer banking has been something of an orphan at Republic, a
bank best known for inhabiting more exotic financial realms like
securities and currency trading and international private banking.
Because Republic's consumer business has not been nearly as
profitable as competitors' consumer units, HSBC is likely to beef
up Republic's recent efforts to sell higher-fee products at the
branches _ moves that might come as a shock to Republic's 800,000
customers in New York state who have grown accustomed to such
things as no-fee automated teller machines. HSBC declined to
comment on its fee plans.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Republic has the eighth-largest consumer banking
business in New York state, with about $13.6 billion in deposits
statewide, according to Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, the research firm.
Most of Republic's 109 branches are concentrated in New York City's
five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   HSBC, which recently renamed its American subsidiary from Marine
Midland Bank to HSBC Bank USA and employs 9,500 people here, is the
fifth-largest consumer bank in New York state, with some $21.3
billion in deposits. Most of its 405 branches are in upstate New
York, in areas like Rochester and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the banks would rank No. 3 in New York state in terms
of deposits, behind Chase Manhattan and Citigroup, according to
Keefe, Bruyette. In New York City, the combined bank would be the
fourth largest in terms of deposits and the third largest in
branches.
</P>
<P>
   Although the combined bank's 149 New York City branches seem
like an impressive number, ranking behind Chase's 363 and
Citigroup's 162, the bank would lag far behind in deposits. Chase
has $78.45 billion worth of deposits in New York City, Citigroup
has $34.25 billion, and a combination of HSBC and Republic would
have $17.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it's cutting edge,'' said Marni Pont O'Doherty,
a Keefe, Bruyette analyst, referring to Republic's consumer
operation. ``Republic has run it in a sort of stodgy fashion, and
HSBC will probably be able to add some dynamism.''
</P>
<P>
   HSBC has one of banking's best-regarded management teams. Its
expected overhaul of Republic's New York City consumer-banking
business is likely to include greater lending, more aggressive
marketing and higher fees.
</P>
<P>
   Republic once advertised its low fees and has not joined New
York banks like Citigroup and Chase Manhattan in the rush to charge
for services like the use of automated teller machines. But Ms.
O'Doherty and other analysts noted that other banks offered better
bargains on low-fee checking accounts and that Republic no longer
used low fees as part of its marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their metropolitan New York retail strategy was one of
acquiring old-line savings banks, which they haven't transformed,''
said Gerard Cassidy, an analyst with Tucker Cleary Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Republic once tried to foster a sense of homey service
in its consumer business, including piano players and free
doughnuts in branches _ quaint touches that have disappeared in
recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
