<HEADER>
A1824 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOTERRORISM-COX     05-10 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTERRORISM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida `inviting' for bioterrorism attack, experts warn
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Imagine hearing a day after shopping at
the mall that terrorists have exposed 9,000 shoppers to deadly
anthrax using the mall's air conditioning system.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, 855 shoppers are dead. Another 4,950 are
hospitalized. FBI agents close the mall indefinitely, bankrupting
scores of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   This devastating attack, so simple in its execution, is just one
scenario military experts have developed using computer models.
</P>
<P>
   The inclination is to call it far-fetched. But because
biological weapons are remarkably cheap, easy to make and easy to
use, it could happen. In fact, the state's assistant health officer
calls an attack in Florida ``likely'' within the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're an invitation for a bioterrorism event, no question,''
Dr. Leslie Beitsch said Friday in Tampa at the first
state-sponsored conference on the medical response to bioterrorism
and weapons of mass destruction. Bioterrorism means the use of
toxins and microbiological agents, such as anthrax bacterium, to
destroy people, plants or animals in order to achieve political
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is more attractive to terrorists than other states,
Beitsch said, because of its proximity to Cuba, which is considered
a safe haven for terrorists; porous borders that allow an influx of
undocumented migrant workers; a semi-tropical climate good for
breeding mosquitoes that can transmit disease; and numerous tourist
attractions, such as Walt Disney World, that would make it possible
to harm many people at once.
</P>
<P>
   And government statistics show the number of terrorist incidents
directed at Americans is at an all-time high, said Bernard
Schechterman, a University of Miami professor and coauthor of the
recently published Annual Editions: Violence and Terrorism, 99/00.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the government is taking threats to use biological
and chemical weapons more seriously than ever: President Clinton
proposes spending more than $1 billion next year, most of it for
research. The U.S. Department of Health and Human Services would
get $230 million, a 46 percent increase over spending this year, to
improve surveillance, stockpile medicine, develop treatments and
get hospitals and public health workers ready to work together.
</P>
<P>
   That means money for Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast.
Rescue workers are receiving awareness training. Palm Beach County
Fire Rescue recently received a $250,000 grant from the Justice
Department to buy special equipment to protect rescue workers and
decontaminate victims of biological or chemical attacks.
</P>
<P>
   And if the state receives a $2.5 million grant, it would upgrade
the health department's West Palm Beach laboratory so technicians
can detect some germs more quickly, improving survival odds for
local victims. Some grant money also would pay for computer systems
to speed up communications with county health departments and
private physicians, Beitsch said.
</P>
<P>
   But last week's two-day conference in Tampa indicates local
planning for bioterrorism has barely begun, particularly in rural
counties that don't get much federal money. Palm Beach and Martin
County officials say they've educated some health and rescue
workers, but they're still trying to get others especially hospital
administrators and emergency room staff to discuss how to deal with
something many people consider too remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have those capabilities right now,'' said Al
Sierra, a Palm Beach County Fire Rescue officer. While rescue
workers and the county's two trauma hospitals have trained for mass
casualty events, such as hurricanes or plane crashes, Sierra said
there's been no planning for dealing with hundreds, maybe
thousands, of victims from biological or chemical attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't all sat at the table to do a biological exercise,''
said Valerie Gryniuk, director of the Martin County Health
Department. ``This (conference) is designed to bring greater
awareness because you need to know where your community is with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, when a speaker asked how many hospital
administrators were among some 200 people at the conference, no one
raised a hand. One Veterans Administration hospital official did
attend, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I have never been able to get (through) to
hospital administrators,'' said Dr. L. W. Stringer, an emergency
medical services director in Winston-Salem, N.C., who heads the
East Coast's federal special operations response team. With
hospitals' tight budgets and a national shortage of nurses, ``it's
going to be a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The root of the problem: Biological weapons can be more deadly
because they can infect their victims and lie dormant for days or
months before causing health problems. So perpetrators can escape
quietly. Victims can infect others. And if the weapon is
genetically engineered, it could be resistant to normal treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Smallpox is the most worrisome threat. The highly contagious
virus lies silent for more than a week before causing pustules to
appear all over its victim's body and can last for a month. It
kills one in four adults and four of five young children.
</P>
<P>
   People are no longer routinely vaccinated against smallpox
because public health workers eradicated it worldwide in 1979. As a
result, many doctors have never seen a smallpox patient.
</P>
<P>
   Only the United States and Russia are known to have the virus,
but health experts say if those stocks were obtained and used by a
terrorist, one incident could infect 40 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax is considered the other big threat: Forty thousand
clusters of the bacteria can fit on the head of a pin. Though
infected people can't spread it, it is fatal unless treated
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people should be going paranoid,'' Gryniuk said.
``They need to be aware, they need to take threats seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Local health workers already have seen hoaxes. Last month, a
Lake Worth law firm received a package containing a white powder
that police worried might be anthrax. The FBI said lab tests showed
the powder isn't anthrax, but have not determined what it is.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, a Stuart doctor's office received a package
thought to contain Ebola virus, a highly contagious virus that
causes massive internal bleeding. It turned out to be a false
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Only one successful U.S. bioterrorist attack has been
documented: In 1984, the Rajneeshees cult used bacteria to poison
10 restaurants' salad bars in the Oregon town of The Dalles to
reduce voter turnout for an election. At least 750 people got sick.
A string of non-biological terrorist attacks in the '90s the World
Trade Center bombing, a nerve gas attack in Tokyo's subway and the
Oklahoma City bombing have made government officials jittery and
spurred increases in federal spending. In 1994, Congress made it
illegal to unlawfully possess biological or chemical agents that
could be used as weapons of mass destruction and to make threats to
use such weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Planners are particularly concerned about how unprepared the
nation's hospitals are.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County hospitals already are overwhelmed during the
tourism season, and county officials have been discussing how to
divert less sick patients to less crowded hospitals. But diversion
policies may not work in a biological attack because historically
more than half of an attack's victims arrive on their own and are
contaminated, Stringer said.
</P>
<P>
   He criticized hospital administrators for not addressing
inadequacies in decontamination facilities, controlling how many
patients move from one hospital room to the next, supplies of drugs
like atropine, and staff training.
</P>
<P>
   Inexperienced emergency room staff will face unique problems:
How will they get hundreds of victims to disrobe en masse in a
parking lot? How will they quarantine these witnesses to a crime
and preserve their clothing, considered evidence?
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County is trying to prevent hospitals from being
overwhelmed: Last month, county commissioners approved spending
$68,000 for supplies and equipment for two mobile hospitals. The
units can provide full hospital care to hundreds of patients for
six to 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But even with awareness, equipment and planning, rescue workers
are sure they won't be able to anticipate everything. ``Preparation
for something like that is always something you need to improve
upon,'' said Mike Arena, a Palm Beach County Fire Rescue battalion
chief.
</P>
<P>
   Sanjay Bhatt writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
