A1829 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-BODYARMOR-COX     05-10 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-BODYARMOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    K-9 officers get bullet-proof vests
 &HT;    By Sonja Isger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ After five years pounding a beat for the
Boynton Beach (Fla.) Police Department, Officer Sado got his first
police-issue, bullet-proof vest Monday morning. It's a custom-job,
leaving plenty of room for his legs _ all four of them.
</P>
<P>
   Sado, two other Boynton Beach police dogs and all 16 of the Palm
Beach County sheriff's K-9 unit have been fitted for the $350
special vests courtesy of a canine-loving chiropractor and his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Gary and Raelynn Gagliardi say their heartstrings _ and their
purse strings _ were tugged after they heard about Solo, a police
dog killed in the line of duty in New Jersey. After Solo's death,
the local humane society raised money to buy a vest for the rest of
the department's four-legged unit.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, dog lovers like the Gagliardis have stepped forward
in communities nationwide, hoping to pay for doggie vests that
departments either can't afford or find too embarrassing to ask the
public to pay for. The Gagliardis' bill to suit up 19 dogs topped
$5,600.
</P>
<P>
   Sado has worked for years unscathed. But at least two police
dogs in Palm Beach County have died. Smokey, with Boynton Beach's
K-9 Unit, was shot in 1981 while pursuing a criminal. Cello, who
worked for Delray Beach police, died in 1984 from internal injuries
he suffered when he caught two hubcap thieves.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, police dog deaths hit an all-time high of at least
eight, said Russell Hess, executive director of the U.S. Police
Canine Association. This year, the association says two dogs have
died.
</P>
<P>
   Solo, a 3-year-old German shepherd working for the Asbury Park,
N.J., police, was brought in to break a 12-hour standoff between
police and a gunman holed up in an apartment. Solo went in and
within minutes, the dog responsible for the capture of 19 criminals
was fatally shot.
</P>
<P>
   Though a vest wouldn't have saved him (he was shot in the head),
his death spurred the local humane society to provide vests for
every police dog in the state. Since then, pet lovers from coast to
coast have picked up the cause, Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   Dog vests have been around for a few years, but only now has
technology made them truly feasible, said Sgt. Bob Anderson, who
heads the sheriff's K-9 unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first ones were quite heavy and the dogs might not have
been able to perform with the weight and heat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vests Sado and Kazan sported Monday weigh a couple of pounds
at most. They're also color-coordinated to their handlers' uniforms
_ Boynton's wear black; the sheriff's wear Army green.
</P>
<P>
   But they did take some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he first put it on, it was kind of like a body cast,''
Sado's handler, Boynton Officer Rich O'Connor said. ``Take a step,
stop, take a step, stop.''
</P>
<P>
   After three or four go-rounds, Sado stopped nipping at his getup
and got to work.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said he's thankful for the peace of mind the
Velcro-fitted vest gives him, and the protection it provides his
7-year-old German shepherd partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you go into a wooded area in pursuit of a criminal
and you are protected, but they're not,'' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell 'em everything's going to be OK,'' added sheriff's
Deputy Chris Soares, who works with Kazan, a 3-year-old German
shepherd. ``But they are out there to protect officers. Having a
vest gives them a better chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the dogs have vests, Gagliardi has begun campaigning
for another cause: replacing the makeshift metal and plywood
back-seat cages the sheriff's dogs travel in with aluminium crates.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Isger writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
