<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BUDDY-DIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER NFL STAR DIAL THROWN FOR LOSS OVER PENSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ED ASHER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A federal appellate court has vacated an order
allowing Texas football legend Buddy Dial to recover full benefits
from the National Football League's disability plan.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, U.S. District Judge Vanessa Gilmore of Houston
ordered reinstatement of all disability funds for the former Rice
University, Pittsburgh Steelers and Dallas Cowboys receiver,
totally disabled by football injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But in a ruling released Monday, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in New Orleans vacated Gilmore's order and remanded the
case back to her ``to render judgment in favor of'' the NFL and
Dial's ex-wife, Janice Marye.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a defeat for Buddy, but it's not the end of the world,''
said Dial's attorney, Tom Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   He said he may ask for a new hearing before the appellate court,
or he may try to take the case to state court.
</P>
<P>
   Dial, 62, sued the NFL's disability plan in 1996 after its
administrator decided in 1994 that Dial's ex-wife _ divorced from
him since 1979 _ was entitled to 50 percent of his $4,000-a-month
disability income.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore ruled that the NFL-players union agreement that led to
creation of the disability plan in 1993 had been misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Marye's being awarded half of Dial's retirement income upon
their divorce had no bearing on the then-nonexistent disability
income, Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``NFL's interpretation,'' she said, ``suggests that any other
separate property that comes into existence after the parties are
divorced and is later discovered would be subject to equal
division.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the 5th Circuit said the NFL's disability plan
administrators correctly interpreted the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the NFL and Marye could not be reached for comment
late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Dial was an All-America end for Rice in 1958 and played
professionally for Pittsburgh and then Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   He was declared permanently disabled because of his
football-related injuries after the plan was initiated in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He is among a handful of players who receive complete NFL
disability pensions as a result of playing football.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
