<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEEN AS NEXT HOT DIET PILL, XENICAL RAISES CONCERNS
</P>
<P>
   Although orlistat, a diet pill approved for sale in the United
States two weeks ago and marketed under the brand name Xenical, is
available only by prescription, it is being made easily available.
</P>
<P>
   Some promoters are already treating the new drug as the next
magic potion for fighting obesity, and some health care
professionals and advocates for the obese worry that many Americans
will start popping Xenical without giving adequate consideration to
the costs, benefits and side effects.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON AND TEXACO SEEN IN TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, the nation's third-biggest oil company, and Texaco, the
fourth largest, have had preliminary talks about a possible deal, a
person close to one of the companies said, but no agreement is
imminent. Still, many analysts and industry consultants said that
any deal would be difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   SANGSTAT MEDICAL SHARES RISE 23 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Sangstat Medical, a biotechnology company in
California, gained 23 percent after Abbott Laboratories agreed to
distribute the company's generic versions of cyclosporine, a drug
that helps prevent organ rejection in transplant patients, in the
United States. Shares of Sangstat rose $2.75, to $14.5625.
</P>
<P>
   HOPES FADE FOR CHINA TRADE PACT
</P>
<P>
   In the days before NATO mistakenly bombed the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, administration officials voiced fears that
they had already missed their moment last month to strike a
political deal to get China into the World Trade Organization. Now
the hopes of patching together that deal in the next few months are
quickly fading.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT TO BUY 4 PERCENT STAKE IN NEXTEL
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft agreed to pay $600 million to buy 4 percent of Nextel
Communications, a national provider of wireless communications.
</P>
<P>
   A PACKAGING DISPUTE FOR PERFUMES
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein's fragrance Eternity smells nothing like Ralph
Lauren's Romance, but Calvin Klein contends that the bottle for
Romance is too similar to the one for its perfume and could confuse
consumers. So it sued. A federal judge rejected an injunction that
had sought to stop Ralph Lauren from selling or advertising
Romance, but the suit is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   FDA BACKS QUICK DRUG APPROVAL
</P>
<P>
   When the Food and Drug Administration was forced to ban five
prescription drugs in a recent one-year period, critics said the
agency had compromised patient safety as it hurried new medicines
to market. The agency's new commissioner has responded, making
public an internal review that found the emphasis on speedy drug
approvals is not to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ALITALIA TO JOIN NORTHWEST ALLIANCE
</P>
<P>
   Alitalia said that it intended to join Northwest Airlines and
KLM Royal Dutch Airlines in a broad partnership that would combine
their services over the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER STILL SEEN AS WINNER IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   Years of mismanagement and neglect have left Brazilian soccer in
disarray, but foreign and Brazilian investment firms increasingly
see opportunities to transform Brazilian soccer into a moneymaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
