<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-SCENE-435&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIMA IS QUESTIONED IN DETAIL BUT NOT ABOUT SEX 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Unrelenting and indignant, defense lawyers Monday dug
into the smallest details of Abner Louima's allegations of abuse
and torture by New York City police officers.
</P>
<P>
   They asked him to recall precisely where he was punched, to
describe every snippet of conversation, to recount to the minute
how long he stood in a particular spot. One defense lawyer asked
Louima if he was somehow being coached in his answers by a
courtroom spectator.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one inflammatory topic defense lawyers have
studiously avoided in their continuing cross-examination of Louima:
Of the hundreds of questions they have posed so far, not one has
been about sex.
</P>
<P>
   The silence on this subject is noteworthy. Last week, during
opening arguments in federal court in Brooklyn, a lawyer for the
officer accused of driving a stick into Louima's rectum suggested
that Louima's extensive internal injuries were caused by consensual
gay sex.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Marvyn M. Kornberg, told jurors that a trace of
Louima's feces _ found in the police precinct bathroom where the
alleged assault occurred _ contained ``the DNA of another male.''
He also said Louima's injuries were ``not consistent'' with
``nonconsensual insertion'' _ an argument that prompted prosecutors
to ask Louima about his wife and children, presumably to deflect
the idea that he had had sex with a man.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, though, Kornberg ended more than four hours of
questioning without asking Louima about his sex life. Kornberg
declined to discuss why he had not raised the subject, but others
involved in the defense of his client, Officer Justin A. Volpe,
said Monday that the silence was a calculated tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an answer to that, but I'm not prepared to give it,''
Les Levine, a private investigator for Kornberg, said when asked
why Louima had not been questioned about his sexual habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an oversight,'' said Robert Volpe, Officer Volpe's
father. ``You're at the beginning of the movie,'' he said with a
wink. ``Let the movie play.''
</P>
<P>
   But a lawyer for another of the five police officers charged
with violating Louima's civil rights said it was too risky to raise
the subject with Louima. No doubt, Louima would have denied the
contention, said the lawyer, who did not want to be identified. And
in the absence of contradictory testimony, such questions might be
perceived by jurors to be a cheap shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no profit in it,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe Tardieu, a lawyer who attended Monday's testimony as a
spectator, put it more bluntly: ``You run the risk now of having
the jury hate the defendant.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Consequently, defense lawyers focused on safer subjects Monday,
such as Louima's admission that he lied _ in public and before
grand juries _ when he said that one officer told him during the
alleged assault, ``It's Giuliani time.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers also reminded jurors that the ``dream team'' of
Johnnie L. Cochran Jr., Barry Scheck and Peter J. Neufeld _ which
represented O.J. Simpson _ is representing Louima in his civil suit
against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, the hours of cross-examination produced more
yawns than drama. Treating the defense lawyers with extreme
caution, Louima answered questions as if they entered his brain on
a time delay. After even the simplest questions, Louima would sit
silent and still for several seconds, his eyes searching the
ceiling. Finally, just as his questioner seemed about to lose
patience, Louima would offer a quiet reply, most often a simple
``Yes, sir'' or ``No, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, he asked the defense lawyers to repeat questions,
or he asked them to show him documents to refresh his recollection
or he said he did not understand what they were asking.
</P>
<P>
   In basketball terms, Louima pursued a slow-paced half-court game
while defense lawyers tried to run the floor, peppering him rapid
fire with questions. In this regard, Louima was the clear victor
Monday, and at times his implacable, respectful manner appeared to
get on the nerves of his interrogators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes or no?'' Kornberg asked several times in evident
exasperation at Louima's deliberate responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you let him finish the answer?'' Judge Eugene H.
Nickerson told Kornberg more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen C. Worth, a lawyer for Officer Charles Schwarz, became
so aggressive and loud that Nickerson sternly admonished him,
``Keep it down.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how strenuous the questioning, Louima remained as
unflappable as a diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't he being intentionally forgetful to avoid damaging
answers, he was asked. ``If I remember, I say what I remember,'' he
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't his civil lawyers coach him on how to avoid answering
questions?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that they tell me is tell the truth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't he provoke police officers by fighting and cursing at
them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' he said, his voice steady as ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
