<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KLEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART KLEIN, 66, TV CRITIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stewart Klein, a music, film and theater critic for WYNY-TV in
New York since 1967, died on Sunday at his home in Fort Lee, N.J.
He was 66.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was colon cancer, his wife, Barbara, said.
</P>
<P>
   Klein won three local Emmy awards for his work, including one
for a memorable review in 1978, in which he skewered ``Sebastian,''
a film that had been made entirely in Latin, by reciting his review
in Latin. Like the film, his review carried subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Osgood, the anchor of ``CBS News Sunday Morning,'' said
Klein's special quality lay in being ``very down to earth and at
the same time very well read.'' When the two worked together at ABC
Radio in the early 1960s, Klein introduced him to the writing of
A.J. Liebling and I.F. Stone, Osgood said, ``to give me some sense
of what journalism was really about.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein was widely considered the dean of the critics on New York
television stations, although at the start of his career he
confided to a fellow critic, Judith Crist, that he had no idea how
to review a film. He became, she said on Monday, ``the ultimate
critic.''
</P>
<P>
   Born and reared in Philadelphia and a graduate of Temple
University, Klein came to New York as a radio reporter in 1961. He
was at WNEW-AM when its sister station WNEW-TV decided to start a
10 p.m. news broadcast, and he was on the original team. He
remained as the station later became a Fox affiliate; it is now
WYNY. He also did theater and movie reviews for ``Good Day New
York,'' the station's morning news program, and ``Fox 5 Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein, an enthusiastic fan of both jazz and Latin music, met his
wife of 16 years at the jazz club Michael's Pub in Manhattan, where
she was a lighting designer who sat down at his table one evening
to chat. She and their son Matthew survive him, as do three
children from a previous marriage, Marjorie Klein of New York;
Joseph, of Miami Beach, and Joann Cueva of Danbury, Conn., and two
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Although some critics on television confined themselves to
reviewing high-profile Broadway productions, Klein often reviewed
Off Broadway shows and sometimes foreign films. And if he really
disliked a movie, he enjoyed giving it a curt review, said Bob
O'Brien, a WYNY reporter who worked with Klein for 31 years. He
recalled that Klein reviewed the expensive 1987 flop ``Ishtar''
with these words: ```Ishtar.' Stinkar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0531 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GRAND-JURY-NYT &LR;      05-10 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GRAND-JURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE TO TEST CHANGES TO EASE BURDEN OF GRAND JURY DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In an attempt to make service on grand juries less
burdensome, New York state court officials said on Monday that they
would set up experiments in six counties around the state to try
out different ways of reducing the length of a grand jury's term.
</P>
<P>
   While the officials did not offer many concrete details of how
the experiments would work, the announcement was the court system's
first response to a lengthy report, also released on Monday, from a
panel of lawyers, judges and other legal experts on how to improve
the grand jury system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should minimize the time that jurors should have to
serve,'' said Chief Judge Judith S. Kaye, who created the panel in
December 1997 to consider ways of making service on grand juries
less onerous. The effort to rethink grand juries followed a series
of successful initiatives by Judge Kaye to improve the lot of New
Yorkers called to sit on conventional juries, which are known
formally as petit juries.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike service on conventional juries, where people are screened
to sit on a single trial, those called for grand juries hear
evidence on dozens of criminal cases and vote on whether defendants
should be indicted. The statewide average for service on a trial
jury is 2 days; grand jurors serve an average of 12 days, state
court officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, grand jurors in Brooklyn and Queens serve for
a month, meeting all day every weekday. In some rural counties, a
grand jury meets one day a week for three or even four months.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the states around the country have eliminated most
grand juries because of the cost, the inconvenience for the jurors
and the difficulty of assembling witnesses. They rely instead on
hearings and other forms of judicial review.
</P>
<P>
   The New York state constitution requires, however, that
prosecution of a felony be sanctioned through an indictment by a
grand jury. So Judge Kaye asked the panel to research ways of
enhancing the existing system in New York and improving the
experience of individuals who find themselves on a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems wise to do what we could do to make the existing
system a better one for everyone,'' Judge Kaye said at a news
conference during which the report was released and the experiments
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, which was led by Stephen E. Kaufman, a prominent
defense lawyer, proposed several steps, including the creation of
pilot programs in several counties, upstate and downstate, large
and small, to test different strategies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the panel proposed creating two kinds of grand
juries. One would consider only relatively minor, uncomplicated
cases that take a day or less to present to jurors; it should be
possible to control the maximum term of such a grand jury, the
panel said. A second kind of grand jury would examine only the more
complex cases, the type that can take two or three days to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   The six counties selected for the pilot program are Albany,
Kings (Brooklyn), Monroe, Onondaga, Saratoga and Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   The panel created by Judge Kaye also proposed increasing the pay
for some grand jurors, who now receive $40 a day. It suggested an
increase to $60 a day for each day of service between 11 and 20
days, and $80 a day for service beyond 20 days. Judge Kaye endorsed
the increase, but she also noted that the proposal would require
approval of the State Legislature.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-10-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990510.0532 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1987 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-BELCHER-LADN     05-10 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BELCHER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHER'S BLOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tim Belcher walked off the mound after giving up a
run in a recent game and yelled an expletive that could be heard
clearly all the way up to the press box.
</P>
<P>
   Signed to a two-year, $10.2 million contract to be the Anaheim
Angels' No. 2 starter, Belcher, 37, has been cursing a lot lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim Belcher competes,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said.
``He's a little bit of a perfectionist. That's what makes him so
good.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also what's driving Belcher crazy these days.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-year veteran, Belcher was supposed to give the Angels
innings _ he's one of only four pitchers to throw 200 or more
innings every year since 1991 (excluding strike-shortened 1994 and
'95).
</P>
<P>
   Yet this season, he's made it out of the sixth inning only once
and gotten out of the fifth only twice in seven starts. He's 1-3
with a staff-worst 9.89 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   So what's wrong? Has a pitcher who won 42 games in the past
three seasons with the weak-hitting Kansas City Royals lost it? The
Angels say no; he just needs a little time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not concerned,'' Collins said. ``He's a veteran guy,
he's been through this before. You could say maybe he's off to a
slow start, because his health is good and he's throwing well. He's
just making mistakes. As long as he feels good, he's going to pitch
his way out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of Belcher's worst games came when the offense gave him a
big hand. In Toronto on April 22, Belcher took a 7-2 lead into the
fifth inning and couldn't get three more outs. He gave up four in
the inning and the Angels eventually lost 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   At home against the same Blue Jays on April 28, Belcher took a
10-0 lead into the fifth and again couldn't get the victory. He
gave up six in the inning before Collins took him out. The Angels
eventually won that one 12-10.
</P>
<P>
   In four of his seven starts, Belcher took the mound for the
fifth but had to leave before getting out of the inning. His
fifth-inning ERA is 40.50, while his ERA in the first four innings
is 4.82.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, though, says the problem isn't the fifth inning. Though
he hasn't given up nearly as many runs in innings 1-4, he says
those innings aren't much different than the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The misconception is that I'm throwing `four brilliant
innings,' '' he said. ``They're not so brlliant. The first time
through the order I might be able to get away with some things that
you're not able to get away with the second and third time through
the order. I think that's what's happening more than anything. I
just need to make better pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   When Belcher is missing with his pitches, he's missing right
down the middle. He's working with pitching coach Dick Pole and
bullpen coach Joe Coleman to correct the problem, but that's all he
can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not searching for any major flaw,'' Belcher said. ``I'm
not going to make any major changes. You get into trouble doing
that kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody knows why (Belcher is struggling),''
Collins said. ``You look at film and see what feels good and what
doesn't. Sometimes you just keep working. There's no easy fix. You
just grind your way through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, whose next start is Friday at home against Tampa Bay,
says he will pitch every game with the same idea that has helped
him win 137 major-league games, including one this year in which he
gave up just two runs and four hits in seven innings against
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't approach it any differently,'' he said. ``Every start,
every game I have the idea of throwing a shutout. If I give up one,
I try not to give up two. If that goes by the board, I try to give
up less than the other guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
