<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DWI-BILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas House votes to lower DWI limit
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Aiming to improve the state's dismal drunken
driving record, the Texas House on Monday voted to lower the legal
intoxication threshold to a blood alcohol level of .08 from the
current .10.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already approved the change, and Gov. George W.
Bush is expected to sign it into law. Texas would join more than a
dozen other states that have lowered their legal limits to .08.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Senate Bill 114, authored by Sen. Mario Gallegos
Jr., D-Houston, argue that it will save the lives of hundreds of
Texans. In 1997, Texas led the nation in alcohol-related traffic
deaths, with 1,748. Of those, 379 involved drivers with blood
alcohol levels of under .10.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government estimates that a 170-pound person could
have four drinks in one hour without hitting the .08 threshold. The
same person could have five drinks without breaking the .10 limit.
A 137-pound person could have three drinks in an hour as opposed to
four.
</P>
<P>
   The alcoholic beverage industry and other opponents contend that
the .08 limit will net social drinkers, and that studies focusing
solely on the effect of lowering the threshold are inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The .08 campaign is not effective because it's not targeting
the right people,'' American Beverage Institute spokesman John
Doyle said last month. ``More needs to be done on drunk driving,
not on drinking and driving.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Scott Hochberg, who shepherded Gallegos' bill through
the House, pointed to a National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration survey that concluded drunken driving deaths
declined in five of seven states that only lowered the limit. The
National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism has found that
alcohol can hamper steering ability at a level of .035, and impairs
vision at between .03 and .05.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you want your child to get on a school bus if the driver
had just had four shots of whiskey in an hour on an empty
stomach?'' asked Hochberg, D-Houston. ``And yet you're doing that
when you put your child on the road in a car when there are other
drivers who have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the social drinker. It is not a glass of wine with
dinner. It is a significant amount of alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   No lawmaker rose to oppose lowering the limit, and the bill
passed on a voice vote. The House rejected two amendments by Rep.
Harold Dutton, D-Houston, which would have lowered the limit to
zero and .05.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has urged states to adopt the .08 limit, and by
lowering its threshold Texas will be eligible for about $12 million
in federal highway grant money.
</P>
<P>
   But Hochberg didn't mention the highway money during the floor
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't the right thing to do, I don't think we should
have done it for the money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most Texans favor lowering the legal threshold _ even though
many of them are skeptical that the change will reduce the number
of alcohol-related accidents, according to a recent Texas Poll.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-seven percent of those who responded to the telephone
survey said they support lowering the limit to .08. But only a
third of the 1,003 people polled believe the change will make the
roads safer.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
