<SLUG> BC-SANGSTAT-DRUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANGSTAT SHARES SOAR ON NEWS OF ABBOTT DISTRIBUTION DEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Shares in the Sangstat Medical Corp. gained 23
percent Monday after Abbott Laboratories Inc. agreed to distribute
the company's generic versions of a drug that helps prevent organ
rejection in transplant patients in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sangstat, a biotechnology company based in Menlo Park, Calif.,
received approval from the Food and Drug Administration in November
for Sangcya, its liquid form of the anti-rejection drug
cyclosporine. But shares of Sangstat have declined from a high of
$32.125 in January because of concerns that Novartis A.G., the
Swiss pharmaceuticals giant that invented cyclosporine, would be
able to block Sangcya sales through patent litigation and superior
marketing muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Sangstat shares rose $2.75, to $14.5625, in Nasdaq trading.
Abbott fell 37.5 cents, to $46.50, on the New York Stock Exchange.
The American depository receipts of Novartis fell 62.5 cents, to
$76.375.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very intelligent move for Sangstat,'' said
Sergio Traversa, an analyst with Mehta Partners. ``The old story is
alive again.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, based in Abbott Park, Ill., will co-promote and
distribute Sangcya and cyclosporine capsules, which Sangstat said
it expected to introduce next year. Abbott will buy $14 million of
Sangstat stock, give up-front and milestone payments and make a
long-term loan to Sangstat. The companies did not disclose the
amount of the payments and loan. Abbott now makes and markets
products that aid in the care of transplant patients.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining Abbott as a marketing partner should increase confidence
in Sangstat's ability to compete with Novartis. Sangstat had
already reached a deal to have Abbott make Sangcya, but there had
been speculation that either Novartis, through its generic unit,
Geneva, or Abbott itself would introduce a generic cyclosporine
capsule. Novartis sued Sangstat for patent infringement earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it takes away a lot of the worries that have flowed
from rumors for the last three months,'' Philippe Pouletty,
Sangstat's chairman, said in a telephone interview. ``It shows that
Sangstat and Abbott can compete very effectively with Novartis. On
the legal side it doesn't change the fact that they have filed a
suit, but it tells investors that maybe the lawsuit from Novartis
is not very serious, which we have said all along.''
</P>
<P>
   Traversa said that investors were less concerned by the lawsuit
then by the potential competition for the capsules.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclosporine has approximately $1.35 billion in global sales and
more than $500 million in sales in the United States, but the
liquid form is less than 5 percent of that, he said. By pairing
with Abbott, Sangstat ``has almost exclusivity, because no one
else, except for Novartis, of course, has the ability to
manufacture cyclosporine in quantity,'' he said. ``Until the
capsule is on the market, we won't see big sales.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
