A2001 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-COURT-NYT &LR;      05-10 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN WINS CLOSE FIGHT TO PUT ALLY ON HIGH COURT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Ending one of the most contentious battles of
Gov. Christie Whitman's six years in office, the
Republican-controlled state Senate on Monday narrowly approved
Whitman's nominee for the state Supreme Court, Attorney General
Peter Verniero.
</P>
<P>
   Brushing aside complaints that Verniero is too inexperienced to
serve on the high court and was too slow to investigate complaints
of racial profiling by state troopers, Republicans delivered just
enough votes _ 21 _ to insure a majority of the 40-member Senate.
Three Republicans broke ranks and opposed the confirmation, joining
all 15 Democratic senators who were present.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, which came after a weekend of intense lobbying of six
undecided Republicans, was a hard-fought victory for Whitman. With
Verniero's confirmation she has now appointed three of the court's
seven justices, putting a decidedly more conservative imprint on a
court that had developed a national reputation for judicial
activism. And because of impending retirements, she will have the
opportunity to appoint even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate's confirmation of Peter Verniero will insure that
the court will continue to function as one of the greatest courts
in the nation,'' Whitman said in a statement Monday night.
``Notwithstanding the bitter partisan debate that seems to have
defined far too much of the discussion on this nomination, I have
full confidence that Peter Verniero will be a unifying force for
justice in New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats condemned the vote as a display of brute political
power by Republicans who ignored the New Jersey Bar Association's
determination that Verniero was not qualified for the state Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Richard J. Codey said legislators would
ultimately weaken the court if they began appointing justices based
on political loyalty rather than credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes loyalty demands too much,'' Codey said.
</P>
<P>
   The intense debate over Verniero's qualifications, which has
dominated the state's political agenda for the last two months,
also focused attention on the Whitman administration's handling of
allegations that the state police discriminated against black and
Hispanic drivers by stopping them disproportionately, a practice
known as racial profiling. Despite mounting evidence of the
practice, Whitman and Verniero only acknowledged in recent weeks
that racial profiling had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   At public hearings last week, Verniero refused to accept blame
for the discrimination by some troopers, insisting instead that he
deserved credit for releasing the first official state document to
admit the existence of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference that followed the confirmation vote
Monday night, he dismissed the notion that he might atone for his
belated response to the racial profiling issue by becoming a
champion for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already been a champion for civil rights as attorney
general,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats, and some Republicans, suspect that the issue
may later hurt Whitman as she runs for the U.S. Senate in 2000,
especially in minority districts, where she has never enjoyed
strong support.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Reginald Jackson, leader of the Black Ministers'
Council of New Jersey, said he considered the confirmation vote a
slap in the face and urged black voters to remember it the next
time candidates ask for their support. ``The minority community in
this state has to recognize that unless people in power feel they
have some price to pay for things like this, things will just
continue to go on as they are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero, 40, has devoted more than half his life to working for
Republican Party causes but has never served as a judge or tried a
case before a jury. He has spent six years as Whitman's chief of
staff, chief counsel and attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The final Senate tally was one vote short because a Democratic
senator, Wynona Lipman of Newark, died over the weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
