<HEADER>
A2003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-CUTBACKS-COX     05-10 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-CUTBACKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Compaq takes step to streamline delivery in its battle with Dell
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a major effort to simplify a strategy that
straddles two opposing business models, Compaq Computer Corp.
dramatically pared the number of companies that distribute its
business computers to four from 39, the company announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which was expected, is the first major change since
Compaq's board forced Chief Executive Eckhard Pfeiffer to resign
April 18 and was viewed with approval by investors. Compaq stock
closed up $1.50 at $26.25 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that partnering with four major companies, each of
which operates from Compaq's 280-acre Houston headquarters, makes
Compaq more efficient, gives it better control of its inventory and
may shore up its ability to compete on prices with Round Rock-based
Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The four distributors will be responsible for supplying Compaq's
large network of resellers, companies that sell directly to
Compaq's business customers and install computers they purchase.
Large retailers that sell Compaq PCs, such as CompUSA, are not
expected to be affected by Monday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Kay of International Data Corp., an industry research
company near Boston, said Compaq no longer will have to keep 39
distributors supplied with a full selection of its portable,
desktop and server computers for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made good sense, even from the sheer economies of it,'' he
said. ``In each location they had to have a full set of products.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, said Steve Dube of Wasserstein Perella Securities in
New York, Compaq's announcement is a welcome signal that the No. 1
computer maker is no longer waffling on its commitment to the
``channel,'' a network of partners that sell and install its
machines to corporate and business accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, after backing and filling for two years, they've
accepted the fact that the channel was, is and will be important in
the future,'' Dube said.
</P>
<P>
   The four distributors are Ingram Micro Inc., Tech Data Corp.,
Merisel Inc. and Inacom Corp. Each will be responsible for
maintaining its own inventories as they market and sell Compaq
products.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq predicted that the move will simplify product shipment,
improve forecasting of demand for PCs and reduce transportation
costs. Analysts cited poor forecasting when Compaq surprised Wall
Street a month ago with the warning that first-quarter earnings
would be less than half what investors expected.
</P>
<P>
   That surprise, which caused Compaq's stock price to plunge, was
seen as a contributing factor in the ouster of Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``By streamlining our logistics, Compaq is making the business
less complex, more manageable, and more profitable for the reseller
community, which remains a key advantage of Compaq over pure direct
competitors,'' Compaq Senior Vice President Peter Blackmore said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   While it remains the top PC maker in the United States and
worldwide, Compaq has struggled for months to find the right
response to the challenge from Dell Computer Corp. Dell, which
early on recognized the Internet's potential to connect with
customers, focused on the World Wide Web and telephone sales to
avoid retailers and third-party distributors and sell directly to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Dell was not seen as a serious threat to big
companies such as Compaq. Watching Dell in their rear-view mirrors,
competitors argued that there were limits to how far direct sales
could penetrate the mainstream markets of consumers, small
businesses and large corporate accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But Dell has consistently grown in market share while achieving
the highest profits among the major PC companies.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing directly with customers and building each PC to order
enabled Dell to charge lower prices and offer new technology faster
than Compaq, IBM Corp. and Hewlett-Packard Co., the other members
of the top tier of companies. At the same time, Dell avoided a
build-up of unsold PCs, which lose value daily as component costs
decline and new technology becomes available at a steady pace.
</P>
<P>
   Like Compaq, IBM and H-P have copied some aspects of Dell's
direct sales model.
</P>
<P>
   Dube said he believes Compaq may reduce Dell's advantage by
concentrating on only four distributors, and that IBM and H-P may
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will ratchet up competition for Dell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst warned the move to streamline its distribution
system carries risks for Compaq if it angers other distributors who
once accounted for a significant amount of business. ``They are
potentially going to alienate a number of partners that are going
to be forced to deal with these . . . master distributors,'' said
Robert Anastasi of Robertson Humphrey, an Atlanta securities firm.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
