<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE IT OR NOT, TUINEI'S DEATH FURTHER MARS COWBOYS' IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To a world already accustomed to tsk-tsking about Jerry Jones
and the Cowboys, nothing in today's toxicology report will likely
come as a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Jones. Cowboys. Drugs. Headlines.
</P>
<P>
   To the rest of the world, it won't matter that the Mark Tuinei
we knew wasn't about heroin or designer drugs. It won't matter that
a lot of us will remember Tuinei not for his death, but for the way
he seemed to embrace his life.
</P>
<P>
   It won't even matter that Tui had retired and, hence, his
behavior was incapable of affecting anything that happened to the
Cowboys on the field.
</P>
<P>
   To be accurate, Tuinei wasn't even a Jones-era Cowboy. He was
signed as a free agent during Tom Landry's watch, for what that's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   But you watch. Owner Jones will be blamed. The world will
tsk-tsk. And the Cowboys' proud image will take another blow to the
gut.
</P>
<P>
   Crass as those reactions seem, none of them would be out of
line.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei was family. He still socialized with current Cowboys. He
worked out at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   However unfair the notion, notoriety is a two-edged sword.
Tuinei rose to football prominence as a member of the Cowboys. Now,
even in death, he can't hide from their spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Retired or active, the Cowboys are deemed to be public figures.
Very public figures. And when a public figure, at age 39, whether
he be a Cowboy or a councilman or a columnist, is found dead in his
driveway, the cameras and notepads are going to be asking why.
</P>
<P>
   This was not some spare lineman who passed through camp on his
way to NFL anonymity. This was a guy with three Super Bowl rings
and two Pro Bowl appearances whose retirement papers still bore
fresh ink.
</P>
<P>
   The media truly liked Mark Tuinei, who smiled and seemed bemused
by our daily intrusions. But that should not exempt him from the
same scrutiny that a Leon Lett, a Michael Irvin or a Deion Sanders
would certainly have to endure.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, on the marred surface, Tuinei's death impacts neither the
on-field product nor the Cowboys' depth chart. But there's a topic
for a lengthy debate.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei's death will further soil the franchise's image. A
Cowboys team with image problems will eventually scare away a
Pepsi, a Nike or a long line of corporate underwriters. And without
the sponsor money, Owner Jones would have to rein in the signing
bonuses and salary-cap shufflings.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones wasn't worried about image, why did he fire Barry
Switzer? Why did he pass on Randy Moss?
</P>
<P>
   Jones, of course, had undertaken a mission of restoring the
luster to the Cowboys' silver star. He declared the team's most
popular hangout off-limits and fired a spare blocker who defied the
ban. He made a public show of fining and disciplining Switzer after
Coach Boomer was nabbed at the airport with a gun.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones, the maverick and wildcatter, has never himself set
any Mother Teresa example. The horses _ and the limos _ were
already out of the barn.
</P>
<P>
   Jones. Cowboys. Drugs. Headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin. Lett. Tuinei?
</P>
<P>
   To the rest of the world, right or wrong, this is the same story
with just another chapter.
</P>
<P>
   This can't be good for Lett, for whom Owner Jones seemed to be
expecting some sort of clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Nicky Sualua, who says he was with Tuinei on the fatal night, is
a backup fullback on the active roster. A third party, alleged to
be with Sualua and Tuinei last week, performs work for the Cowboys'
video department.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys. Headlines. And this time, a tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   You were about to say something, Owner Jones?
</P>
<P>
   After yesterday's TV reports, today's toxicology results are not
expected to include any pleasant news.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew Tuinei will tell you that they are surprised.
Tui's life, as we knew it, wasn't about heroin or late-night drives
for designer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Kind and gracious, Mark Tuinei deserves to rest in peace.
</P>
<P>
   But he was a Dallas Cowboy. The spotlight follows, even until
the end.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
