<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-10 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2017 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1ST     05-10 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS FIND ELBOW ROOM WITH DUDLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS throughout to UPDATE with Monday's Heat win; with
BKN-KNICKS-HEAT.) 
 (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In the wake of a 10-point loss Monday night, the Knicks'
locker room was an interesting dichotomy of perspectives regarding
what the loss really meant. The scorers _ Latrell Sprewell, Allan
Houston, Marcus Camby _ were talking about intensity and needing to
be more aggressive. The point guard, Charlie Ward, was talking
about patience and trust.
</P>
<P>
   This was the aftermath of Game 2, a winnable game the Knicks had
lost to the Miami Heat, 83-73. Now they go back to New York, the
best-of-five-game series tied at a game each, and on the surface
the Knicks' mission was accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, we wanted to at least get one and we did that,''
Sprewell said. ``If you had told me before it started we were going
to get one down here, I wouldn't turn that down. I'd much rather be
going home 1-1 than 0-2. We got the one, we have the chance to
finish it at home. We just need to take care of that first game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat, with visions of a humiliating sweep clearly before
them, came out Monday night at a blistering pace, attacked the
Knicks' middle, drove the ball at every opportunity and put the
Knicks on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   The smooth coordination of Saturday's game, with Sprewell,
Houston and Larry Johnson playing like a tight, well-rehearsed
trio, gave way to a succession of solos that seemed disconnected
from the theme. They were a combined 14 of 35 shooting _ Johnson
made six of 13 shots, Houston four of 13 and Sprewell four of nine.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday the Knicks routed the Heat and played as if they had
figured out the world. Last night they looked like a team at the
beginning of a transition.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell said there was nothing to be alarmed about.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the nature of this game,'' he said. ``You're going
to have nights when you come in and everything's perfect, other
nights when you can't seem to do anything right, and there's some
stuff in between there. You just have to get a feel for what's
going on and make adjustments as you go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell added: ``I'm not going to say we didn't come out ready
to play. I thought we were ready, they just got off to a better
start. We didn't shoot the ball as well as we did in Game 1; they
shot a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby, who scored 5 points in 16 minutes, said the difference
was distribution. ``In the first half we only had five assists and
ended up with 11 for the game. We definitely have to pass the ball
more.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Camby's second playoff game _ a far cry from the first
on Saturday, when he played so fluidly. ``I didn't think it was any
different,'' he said. ``It was just as intense. We just weren't
playing unselfish ball. On Saturday the ball was swinging, guys
were getting high percentage shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately there were no Knick answers. Not Muscle. Not Finesse.
And whatever hope there was provided by Patrick Ewing _ no new
light shed there. Ewing scored 9 points in the first half, and
finished with 16.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive juggernaut unleashed on Saturday _ Houston, Camby
and Sprewell _ was derailed for the evening. For at least a day,
things were back to normal. Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy all but
predicted this loss for the last two days. Predicted that the Heat
wouldn't shoot as terribly as they did on Saturday and the Knicks
might not play as well, or at last with the same degree of
intensity as they did on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They cut it to seven, then to four, but never could get lower
that eight down the stretch. The Heat, showing neither fear nor
respect of the middle, drove the ball relentlessly. They left it up
to the Knicks point guard _ Ward and Childs _ to beat them. They
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   No. This loss isn't the end of the series. The Knicks got what
they wanted, a split on the road. But there still is no resolution
about style of play. In fact the loss is likely to stir dialogue
anew regarding whether the Knicks are on the right path. Sprewell
and Houston, so lethal on Saturday, when they scored 44 points
between them, scored 27 on Monday and turned the ball over 10
times.
</P>
<P>
   Houston said the Knicks' problem was lack of aggressiveness.
``They just came out a lot harder than we did, and they played a
lot more aggressively than we did,'' he said. ``We've got to get
that aggressiveness back.''
</P>
<P>
   In Wards's view, the Knicks' aggressiveness was not the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play well, we play together,'' he said. ``When we
don't play well we go back to individual basketball, trying to do
it by ourselves. We have scorers _ that's a scorer's mentality, but
it's all about patience. Passing is about trust; when we don't play
well, we go back to individual basketball, trying to do it by
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Between Saturday and last night, the Knicks were like two teams
in one _ one fluid, agile, graceful and the other uncohesive,
individual and lacking any semblance of muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The question raised Monday night is do the Knicks have enough
offense? If not, do they have enough muscle?
</P>
</TEXT>
